r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      06-04 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAPPLING WITH A LEGACY
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The topic for the column became ob vious Wednesday morning,
sitting in the third row at Trinity Episcopal Cathedral, watching
working men and woman walk slowly past the casket of Barry
Goldwater, some of them stopping, some of them reaching out to
touch the flag-covered coffin, gently, the way a par ent touches a
sleeping child.
</P>
<P>
   Any hack worth his weight could see it. The thing to write about
on the day of the funeral of this completely original American man.
. .was a former world-class wrestler from Poland.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, a man only lies in state if he stood for
something.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater stood for fairness, for indi vidual rights, for
liberty, for all that things Roman Wroclawski seeks, but so far has
been denied.
</P>
<P>
   His time is running out. He may soon be deported.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Goldwater wasn't one to stand on ceremony _ even a big
public funeral _ when a regular guy was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Wroclawski came to the United States about four years ago on a
visitor's visa, bringing with him his wife and two chil dren. He
had been the world Greco-Ro man champion in 1982. Afterwards,
combining his fame in Poland with new-found worldliness, Wroclawski
wrote a book critical of his country.
</P>
<P>
   It got him accused of treason.
</P>
<P>
   As his lawyer, Marshall Whitehead de scribes it, ``Roman rose
above the masses. He was decorated by the pope himself. He was a
world champion. He had tasted freedom and he decided to ex press
himself about it. That made him some powerful enemies. They're just
waiting for him back there, unless we al low him to remain. But
instead of wel coming him, our government is trying to throw him
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republic's Bob Petrie has written several articles about
Wroclawski's case. But they've washed over like a sand cas tle by
wave upon wave of Goldwater cov erage.
</P>
<P>
   The senator wouldn't have liked that.
</P>
<P>
   Wroclawski works here as a wrestling coach. Earlier this year,
was supposed to appear before an immigration judge at a political
asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer at the time, former Arizona Gov. Raul Castro, got a
letter notifying him of the hearing. But it was lost and Wroclawski
wasn't told about the court date. Because he didn't show up, the
judge ordered him to be deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the government's rules and regulations,''
Whitehead said. ``But I'm afraid they're looking only at proce
dures and not at substance. This wasn't Roman's fault. To send this
family back without even a hearing seems to go against everything
we stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's lawyers argue that the wrestling coach _ who
doesn't speak English well _ is responsible for his law yer's
mistakes and should be shipped back to Poland.
</P>
<P>
   It could happen June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, however, Whitehead was told he'll have a
chance to argue be fore immigration Judge Dean LeVay on
Wroclawski's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   An ``emergency hearing'' is scheduled for Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge decides to reopen Wro clawski's case, he and his
family can stay in the country and fight for asylum. If not,
they'll have to leave. All of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What rubs me the wrong way about this,'' Whitehead said,
``what should rub ALL of us the wrong way about this, is that the
man didn't have a chance to pres ent his case. As it is, we're
punishing him for the mistake of an attorney. That's can't be
right. That isn't what this country is about. All we're asking for
is a fair shake. That's why generations of immi grants like the
Wroclawski's have come here.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also why the story of the foreign wrestler should be told
on this day. Not just because Wroclawski needs help. Not just
because it's right. But because I read in the paper this week about
the head of another family who left Poland in search of a better
life in America. This man was called ``Big Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Goldwater's grandfather. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 0028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
