<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-REDWINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS STAY ALIVE WITH A 3-2 OVERTIME VICTORY OVER RED WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He wanted one more playoff game, No. 191 in a career
evenly split between excellence and endurance. Guy Carbonneau, the
captain of the 1993 Stanley Cup Montreal Canadiens, showed in one
frenetic sequence why he won the Selke trophy as best defensive
forward in that championship year.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old's hustle also kept the Dallas Stars alive in the
Western Conference finals, as he scored the tying goal at the end
of regulation and the Stars came back to win, 3-2, in overtime
against the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Just 1 minute 25 seconds from elimination, Carbonneau dived to
the ice, saved and centered the puck, only to scramble to his feet
and get it right back from Sergei Zubov. He was nearly at a right
angle from Red Wing goalie Chris Osgood when he feigned and fired
the shot from that almost impossible angle.
</P>
<P>
   His riser somehow wedged into the foot-wide space between
Osgood's head and the left pipe to catch the front corner of the
net, and the 16,928 fans went wild. The Stars had a new life in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to score,'' Carbonneau said. ``I just wanted
to get it in front of the net where our guys were.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just 46 seconds into overtime, Jamie Langenbrunner, who was 6
when Carbonneau played his first National Hockey League game,
slapped a shot from just inside the red line, about 70 feet from
the goal, underneath an all alone and unexpecting Osgood.
Langenbrunner's shot knuckled, bounced twice on the ice, hit
Osgood's stick, rolled over and slid slowly into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit my stick and curved up,'' Osgood said. ``I knew it was
in as soon as it got past me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanenbrunner said he was trying to dump the puck for a line
change at the end of his shift. ``We just want to shoot at him at
all angles,'' he said, ``and I unloaded one on him.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a Game 6, in Detroit, as the Stars cut the Red
Wing' series lead to three games to two. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played a lot of these games,'' Carbonneau said, ``and I
know enough that no one wants to end their season right now. We
have plenty of time to play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series that had not experienced a single lead change, Igor
Larionov changed that with 16:20 left in the second period by
whistling a goal past Stars' goaltender Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas outshot Detroit, 14-6, in the first period, and the Stars
were the first to score in a series where whoever put the first
points on the board went on to win. They scored with 8:53 left by
doing what they failed to do in Game 4 _ winning a faceoff.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau was quickest on the draw and found Craig Ludwig on
the point. Ludwig launched a missile dead on at Osgood, who managed
to knock it down with his knee pad. But Stars forward Mike Keane
was there to easily bury the rebound past the prone Osgood.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of nursing the 1-0 lead with its focus on hard
checking, Dallas relaxed with 32 seconds left in the period and
allowed a careless goal. Larry Murphy's shot deflected off Tomas
Holmstrom in front of the net. Holmstrom, Stars defenseman Craig
Muni and Belfour crashed into each other and the puck skipped over
the helpless Belfour. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
