A3357 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-CARBONNEAU-     06-04 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-CARBONNEAU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD GUY GIVES LIFE TO STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars remain alive because there's still life in
Guy Carbonneau's 38-year-old legs.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps because when you're playing in your 190th playoff
game, when you're in the postseason for the 19th time, when you've
been to the Stanley Cup Finals three times and hoisted the Cup
twice, you know it's truly not over until the final horn sounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was Carbonneau's impossible, incredible, hustling, amazing
goal when all seemed lost that sent Game 5 of the Western
Conference finals into overtime last night.
</P>
<P>
   Without that goal, Jamie Langenbrunner doesn't score in the
first minute of overtime and the Stars don't defeat the Detroit Red
Wings, 3-2, at Reunion Arena. Without Carbonneau's goal, the Stars
aren't packing for a return trip to Motown for Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to let your teammates down,'' said Carbonneau,
who also assisted on the Stars' first goal by winning a faceoff in
the Red Wings' end. ``We've had a great season, and nobody wanted
it to be over tonight. That's what keeps you going. Instead of
playing golf together, we still want to play hockey together.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what gave Carbonneau the energy to make the play of the
night, and perhaps the series.
</P>
<P>
   There was less than two minutes left when Carbonneau found
himself on his rear end in the corner behind the Detroit goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went down behind the net, and fell down a little bit,''
Carbonneau said.
</P>
<P>
   Down, like the rest of the Stars who were on the verge of
elimination.
</P>
<P>
   Down, but not done.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau poked his stick and hit the puck, knocking it away
from a Red Wings player and keeping it alive. Even though he was in
his 27th shift and his 16th minute _ virtually the same as a
youngster like the 22-year-old Langenbrunner _ he quickly scrambled
to his feet and headed for the front of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   The puck skittered past with a Red Wings player in hot pursuit,
but Carbonneau dived headlong, poking it out to Sergei Zubov at the
blue line.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Carbonneau got up. Zubov passed the puck to him, and
Carbonneau turned and fired. The puck deflected off the stick of
Red Wings defenseman Nicklas Lidstrom and beat goalie Chris Osgood
high to the glove side, just sneaking the puck inside the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   The goal tied the score with 1:25 left in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great effort by him,'' Langenbrunner said. ``That
gave us a big boost.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner praised his teammate with a big smile. Carbonneau,
the stoic French-Canadian, merely shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were desperate,'' Carbonneau said. ``We kept working hard,
and trying for a break. We just got it at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Break'' might be the right word. Osgood called it a lucky
goal, and Carbonneau didn't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to score,'' he said. ``I was trying to hit it
where someone could get a rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   But when you're playing in you're 190th playoff game, when you
know what it takes to win a Stanley Cup, and when your legs
suddenly feel about 10 years younger, you tend to make your own
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the type of player those things happen to,'' defenseman
Darryl Sydor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
