<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILCARE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA SENIORS SUE NURSING-HOME OPERATORS ANDOTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, they believed it was a renegade family of nursing-home
operators that swindled them out of their security.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a group of Valley seniors saysa multibillion-dollar
Japanese company is as much at fault as the Vernon Will family.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four seniors filed a lawsuit Tuesday in Maricopa County
``Superior Court against companies believed to be subsidiaries of
Nomura Securities Co., Japan's biggest brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that Nomura Asset Capital Corp., Nomura Holding
America Inc. and Nomura Securities Co. helped Will and his company,
Camelot Campus of Care, to commit acts of fraud and racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   Will is president and director of WilCare Corp., which filed for
reorganization last year.
</P>
<P>
   The suit asks for at least $2 million in damages as well as
requiring the seniors' claims to be addressed before Nomura's
liens.
</P>
<P>
   The seniors say the suit can help recoup their losses after
WilCare, the company that sold them guarantees of lifetime housing,
filed for bankruptcy reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   After WilCare filed, residents learned that their deposits,
which ranged from $41,000 to $88,000, were gone. The residents had
been told the money was refundable and held in reserve, but Will,
WilCare president, said they had been depleted to keep the company
going.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Camelot Campus of Care in Peoria and Park Regency
Village in Chandler worried about being penniless and homeless.
</P>
<P>
   They grew even more worried when they heard that Will and his
family had been in legal and financial hot water before: filing for
bankruptcy reorganization for as many as nine nursing homes in
California; three revocations of nursing-home licenses; and
indictments on Medicare fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Woods, the state Attorney General, also had Will in his
gun sights as well. Will, his son, Douglas, and Joseph Ganzenhuber
were indicted by a state grand jury in November on 35 counts,
including fraud and racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   The three pleaded innocent and are awaiting trial. Ivan Mathew,
Will's attorney, has not seen the suit and declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as WilCare's bankruptcy case unfolded, creditors'
attorneys learned of a deal between Vernon Will and Nomura Asset
Capital Corp. that transferred property worth $17.4 million and the
residents' deposits to a new corporation owned wholly by Will.
</P>
<P>
   The new corporation couldn't be touched by any of WilCare's
creditors, including the residents, the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Nomura required Camelot to pay the new
company $29,000 a month extra. The move drained cash out of the
existing company for Vernon Will's benefit, said Robert Kinas, one
of the lawyers for the residents.
</P>
<P>
   Nomura knew that the residents' deposits were being siphoned
away, Kinas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it make them responsible to the lifetime residents for
the harm that they have caused them? Our answer is certainly `yes,'
'' Kinas said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lorenzen, representing Nomura, said his client would
have never conspired with Will to defraud the residents.
</P>
<P>
   In applying for a $13 million loan from Nomura, Will's company
never revealed the deposits. The deposits were not transferred to
the new company, Lorenzen said. &QL; 
The Camelot and Park Regency complexes now are managed by a
court-appointed trustee, who is working to sell both places. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
