A3360 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-JDPOWERS-LADN     06-04 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-JDPOWERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORDS, HONDAS, TOYOTAS LEAD IN CONSUMER RANKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When it comes to quality, Fords, Hondas and
Toyotas are tops with consumers, according to a widely watched J.D.
Power and Associates analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Those three companies placed the most models in Power's annual
Initial Quality Study, released Wednesday, which tracks the number
of problems owners of new vehicles experience within the first
three months of purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The study was introduced in 1987 and, as usual, Asian and
European manufacturers placed more models on the list than domestic
manufacturers. But domestic manufacturers are building better cars
now, said George Owens, the study's product director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quality as a whole continues to improve and while a gap still
exists, domestic automakers seem to be working hard to close it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study ranked the best model in each class and the top two
finishers and ties.
</P>
<P>
   Cracking the study for the first time, Chrysler nameplates swept
the important midsize car categories. The redesigned Concorde was
named best premium midsize car and the Cirrus best entry midsize
car.
</P>
<P>
   Most new models typically encounter break-in problems but
Chrysler apparently avoided this pitfall with the Concorde, the
L.A.-based market research firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Power said the Concorde's performance was especially noteworthy
because the car's designers relied heavily on virtual design and
very little physical mock-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Ford and Honda products made the list while Toyota
accounted for six. Five General Motors models were ranked and
Nissan placed four. Chrysler and BMW had three each.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's Lexus LS400 received the award as the best premium
luxury car and the top score in the survey. It's the fifth time in
the past six years the model won best in class.
</P>
<P>
   This year, J.D. Power made major changes in the study, which
means the findings cannot be compared directly to previous year's
results. The number of potential problem areas consumers were asked
to address was expanded to 135 from 89, and included features such
as air bags and anti-lock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the industry average per 100 problems hit 176 this
year, nearly double the 1997 results. This was expected to happen,
Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to pick up on anything that could be a possible issue
for consumers. When we started 10 years ago, some of these things
were just on the drawing board as dreams and now they are on the
most standard of vehicles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 58,117 owners of 1998 vehicles bought in November,
December or January participated in the study.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
