u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-NYT &LR;      06-04 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ WIN GAME 1 IN OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ There were almost too many things on Utah's
side. Ten days' rest. Home-court advantage. And Michael Jordan
wagging his tongue more from exhaustion than spite.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone, John Stockton and the Jazz extras were more
comfortable than confident going into Game 1 of the National
Basketball Association finals. But they eventually found their
range from the perimeter and, more important, they found Jordan on
the defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   The combination added up to an 88-85 victory in overtime and a
1-0 lead in the four-of-seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton dominated the overtime. After he fed Malone for a
driving layup to open the period, he then scored Utah's last 7
points.
</P>
<P>
   A tough fallaway jumper by a triple-teamed Jordan pulled the
Bulls within 84-82, but Stockton responded with 9.3 seconds left,
hitting a runner in the lane while tightly covered by Steve Kerr.
Toni Kukoc's long 3-pointer put the Bulls within a point with 5.4
seconds to go, but there was Stockton again, closing the scoring
with two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to inbound the ball the length of the court because they
were out of time outs, the Bulls managed to get an open 3-pointer
by Scottie Pippen as time expired, but it wasn't close.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to topple a champion with one punch, but the
Jazz staggered the Bulls enough to make Game 2 a major concern for
Jordan's club. The teams meet again here Friday night before the
series shifts to Chicago for Games 3, 4 and 5 beginning Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Longley tied the game, 79-79, with 14.3 seconds left in
regulation, hitting a tough lean-in jumper after Jordan was forced
to pass the ball. The play climaxed a wild final five minutes of
regulation in which the Bulls came back from a 7-point deficit to
tie the game on a Pippen 3-pointer with 2 minutes 34 seconds left.
Pippen's shot, which made the score 75-75, silenced the building.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone, after suffering through one of the worst shooting
nights of his career, hit two consecutive jumpers to put the Jazz
on top, 79-75, but the Bulls would not wilt. Pippen made two free
throws with 51.8 seconds left in regulation and Longley's shot
forced the Jazz to call time out and set up a potential
game-winning play. After a non-shooting foul by the Bulls, Bryon
Russell inbounded the ball with 7.3 seconds left and Stockton's
jumper bounced high off the rim, forcing the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Utah went from a mediocre first half _ after which it led, 45-40
_ into a productive third quarter. Jordan was his usual awesome
self, scoring 33 points. Employing up-and-under moves in the post
and picturesque step-back jump shots from the perimeter, he had 20
points by halftime and made the Jazz work on defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone (21 points, 13 rebounds) and especially Stockton (24
points on 9-of-12 shooting, 8 assists) were too much. Solid play
off Utah's bench from Howard Eisley, Shandon Anderson and Chris
Morris nearly led to the Jazz blowing the game open in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls caught their breath and came back on the shoulders
of you-know-who.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz had not played in 10 days since knocking out the Los
Angeles Lakers in four straight games in the Western Confeence
finals. If the Bulls looked fatigued early, Utah was unpolished and
rusty.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was atrocious from the field. Perhaps he was feeling the
strain of last season's finals, in which he missed several crucial
free throws to help the Bulls win in six games. Maybe the taped and
misshapen middle finger on his shooting hand was bothering him more
than he let on before the series began.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, his marksmanship prevented Utah from ever pulling
away from Chicago. He missed 13 of his first 17 shots. With 6
minutes 59 seconds left in the game, the Bulls trailed by only
69-65 and could finally see daylight in this Utah dungeon.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz had forged an 8-point lead at the end of the third
quarter, but could never put the Bulls away. Jordan and Pippen
seemed to have prepared a plan: keep it close and see what happens
down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's 67-59 lead after three quarters was a direct result of
Chicago's inept offensive play. Toni Kukoc was only 2 of 9 from the
floor through three quarters, and the Bulls had shot only 43
percent as a team up to that point.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman was expected to start for the Bulls, but the club
announced before the game that he had suffered torn ligaments in
his right thumb during Game 7 of the Indiana series. Instead, Kukoc
got the nod and the Bulls suffered physically for it.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was getting position inside, nearly setting up a pup tent
in the middle of paint. But he missed often, hitting only 4 of 14
shots before the fourth period.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls Coach Phil Jackson went to his bench after the third
quarter, hoping to give Jordan the rest he needed to take care of
business in the final minutes. It worked for a while _ Scott
Burrell, Jud Buechler and Steve Kerr did a good job of preventing
the Jazz from taking over the game _ but eventually Utah wore
Chicago down.
</P>
<P>
   While Malone struggled from the field, Stockton more than
shouldered the scoring responsibility. He had 13 points at
halftime, dropping in jump shots from 15 to 18 feet out and also
making some improbable runners in the lane with hands in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's Bryon Russell also made his shots, filling the lanes on
the fast break or spotting up around the 3-point arc. Russell,
Morris and Shandon Anderson threw the Bulls off their game by
pushing the ball up the court in transition in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It worked until Jordan caught fire. For all the talk about his
having one foot on the court and the other on the ninth hole of a
retirement-community golf course, he was dazzling once more.
</P>
<P>
   Splitting double teams with ease and grace, he kept going to the
up-and-under move. First, he would use a pump fake and then step
between two defenders until he was inches from the rim for a layup.
</P>
<P>
   When he grew bored with those tactics, he simply stepped back
and fired off one foot while leaving his defender flailing at air.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the court, Malone and the rim were not
getting along. He kept missing so often that the Jazz crowd seemed
to want someone else to shoot the ball. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
