<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-WINGS-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS SURPRISE RED WINGS, 3-2, IN OVERTIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Hold last call, the Stars are thinking about ordering
up another round.
</P>
<P>
   With the season about to close on the Stars last night, Guy
Carbonneau scored with 1:25 remaining to tie the score in
regulation and Jamie Langenbrunner fluttered in an 80-foot shot 46
seconds into overtime to win it, 3-2, and push this best-of-seven
Western Conference finals to Game 6 tomorrow in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars still trail 3-2 in the series but appear to have new
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live to fight again another day,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Few people in the capacity crowd of 16,928 at Reunion Arena or
in the national television audience on ESPN believed it was
possible. The Red Wings had held a 2-1 lead since the 3:40 mark of
the second period, and it appeared that nothing the Stars could do
would break that stranglehold. In fact, Game 5 had the same look as
the two losses that came before it for the Stars. They had
dominated statistically, but found a way to trail on the
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars outshot the Red Wings 14-6 in the first period and
even scored the first goal _ a refreshing change after they had
trailed by four goals in Game 3 and two goals in Game 4 before
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Mike Keane pushed the marker across on a perfect
play set up by the Stars' Montreal Mafia. Three former Canadiens
players were involved as Carbonneau won the faceoff back, Craig
Ludwig put a shot on goal and Keane shoveled in the rebound with a
backhand for a 1-0 lead at the 14:16 mark of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Stars made that one glitch, the Red Wings jumped
all over it. Ludwig took a needless retaliation penalty, and Tomas
Holmstrom cashed in with a power-play goal _ an ugly bouncing puck
that was originally shot by Wings defenseman Larry Murphy and
ricocheted off bodies, gloves and Holmstrom's stick until it
trickled past Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating,'' center Mike Modano said. ``We felt we
were playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustration hit its peak at the 3:40 mark of the second period
as Wings center Igor Larionov, who had been dormant for the series,
threw a 40-foot shot from the left wing that inexplicable slid past
Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one I'd like to have back,'' the Stars goalie said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   So would Stars fans, who mockingly cheered Belfour minutes later
for making a save on a 70-footer. They didn't know how prophetic
they would be.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour turned up his intensity and helped carry the Stars
through a depressing second period. But even with that and a
revived Stars attack in the third period, it appeared the season
was over.
</P>
<P>
   The lasting image came seven minutes into the third period when
Modano had a Darryl Sydor rebound on his stick and the right side
of the net wide open. He fired the shot two feet to the right, and
it appeared the Stars would get no luck in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been one I remembered all summer,'' Modano
said.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes later, Langenbrunner continued his scoreless curse
in the playoffs when his redirected shot skittered past Osgood and
off the right post.
</P>
<P>
   But then the game swung on an amazing play by Carbonneau with
the Stars trying to get Belfour off the ice with under 1:30
remaining. Carbonneau drove hard into the offensive zone and dove
to the ice to prevent the Red Wings' Murphy from getting possession
of the puck. Carbonneau then jumped up to deflect a puck away from
Red Wings defenseman Nick Lidstrom to Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov
at the point.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov held the puck, Carbonneau recovered his composure and
stood up in the right circle. Zubov sent a pass to Carbonneau, and
Carbonneau whistled a shot that luckily deflected off the stick of
Lidstrom past Osgood to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I don't know what I was doing,''
Carbonneau said. ``I just wanted to keep the puck alive.''
</P>
<P>
   That made Langenbrunner's goal almost anticlimactic. Two shifts
into the overtime, the Stars' scoring line had survived a Red Wings
rush and was looking to get off the ice. Langenbrunner took a pass
from Mike Modano and instead of just dumping in off the end boards,
he sent a fluttering shot at Osgood, who previously had surrendered
long-distance goals in the playoffs to Al MacInnis of the St. Louis
Blues and Jeremy Roenick of the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood tried to play the puck with the inside of his stick, but
instead deflected it behind him and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about putting it on him,'' Modano said. ``He's
good at handling the puck, but he doesn't seem to like the low
ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally caught a break.''
</P>
<P>
   And pushed closing time at least one game further into the
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
