r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-WINGS-OSGOOD-TEX     06-04 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-WINGS-OSGOOD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIZARRE GOAL HAS OSGOOD SEEING RED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He had explained this goal before. Another game,
another player, another time, maybe, but it was the same goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't see it at first,'' Osgood said of Jamie
Lagenbrunner's game-winning goal that came 46 seconds into
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It curved, hit the inside of my stick,'' Osgood continued. ``I
knew when it hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner had been heading to his bench for a shift change,
overtime had just begun and his legs were fresh. He decided to
launch a final shot.
</P>
<P>
   He was standing at center ice where the Star turns from green to
gold when he released.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched the other games, and we've seen what kind of goals
can go in,'' Lagenbrunner said.
</P>
<P>
   The puck was bouncing, from its side to flat to back on its
side, changing trajectory a couple of times. The puck looked to be
heading wide, said Stars players after looking at the replay.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood said he just wanted to tip Langenbrunner's bouncing puck
to a corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just curved and hit the inside of my stick,'' Osgood said
again.
</P>
<P>
   The curved stick turned the puck just enough that it trickled
inside the post. The red lamp lighting just 42 seconds into
overtime of Game 5, allowing the Stars to stave off elimination for
at least another game with a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely feel lucky,'' Langenbrunner said. ``You don't
count on any of those going in like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the luck that the Stars said Osgood has had with him all
series. It was the luck that finally went the Stars way in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got two lucky bounces tonight,'' Osgood said of
Langenbrunner's overtime goal and Guy Carbonneau's tying goal with
1 minute, 25 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   So he walked away once again shrugging his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood's last trip from Reunion Arena had ended similarly, a
funny bouncing goal in Game 2 providing a Stars margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   He had taken this same walk on that night, offered the same
explanation and had just as few answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never do anything the easy way I guess,'' Osgood said.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed last time when he said it. This time he didn't laugh.
The series just got a little tighter, he knows that. The pressure
on him just got a little more, he knows that too. There is also a
bit of history here.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood has a problem with letting goals that seemed destined for
anywhere but the back of the net end up just there.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix center Jeremy Roenick slipped a blue-line shot past him
in that playoff series. Blues defenseman Al MacInnis released a
shot at center ice that found a way past Osgood in that playoff
series.
</P>
<P>
   And now add Langenbrunner to that list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' Osgood said, a word-for-word repeat of his
post-Game 2 thoughts. ``It's not something that I wanted to happen.
I'm going to go home and be'' angry.
</P>
<P>
   He was angry because he had played well, even if his teammates
behind him hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   The supposed weak link heading into the playoffs had been
especially strong in the third period when the Stars were pressing
the attack, and the Wings seemed to be just waiting for the final
buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris played well enough to keep us in there,'' Wings winger
Brent Gilchrist said. ``Too bad we couldn't hang on, and that's
what we were doing _ hanging on.''
</P>
<P>
   Osgood was hanging on too, and then came the shot from center
ice. The bouncing, juggling puck that hit his stuck just a little
funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' Osgood said again, the words sounding all too
familiar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
