<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros </SLUG>
 sider-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Settled in as Astro, Alou candidate for team triple crown
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN DIEGO _ Say this for Moises Alou: He knows how to make an
impression.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he needed to earn any brownie points with his new
Astros teammates. His reputation for clutch hitting preceded him.
</P>
<P>
   But it's pretty easy to earn acceptance on a new team when you
lead the club in hitting, home runs and RBIs. Alou may be the new
guy, but over the first two months of the season, this has been his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I wasn't as happy as I am now,'' said Alou,
whom the Astros acquired in a trade with the Florida Marlins during
the offseason. ``I wasn't used to being in Houston and playing with
these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot to get adjusted to playing with a new team. At
the same time, I never felt like a new guy, because I was proven. I
didn't have to show anyone what kind of player I was.''
</P>
<P>
   But just in case anyone had forgotten, Alou has been dropping
reminders in ballparks throughout the league with his red-hot start
at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Wednesday night's game against the Padres, Alou had hit
safely in 20 of his last 23 games with a whopping .432 (35-for-81)
batting average during that stretch. The streak has consisted of
more than just a hit here and there. Alou produced multiple hits in
12 of the 23 games and delivered three hits on three occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I was driving in enough runs early in the
season, but I feel like I'm doing much better now,'' said Alou, who
is hitting .349 with 11 homers and 49 RBIs. ``I'm getting a lot of
two-out hits, which is something I feel like I'm supposed to do. It
also helps to be on a club like ours where there are so many
weapons in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lineup is as good as any in the league. I had some tough
stretches in Montreal because it's tough when the other team says,
`We're not going to let Alou beat us.' But here, our lineup is so
good, there are a lot of guys who they don't want to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou, the National League's Player of the Week for the period
ending this past Sunday, is a notorious fast starter. He's a career
.335 hitter in April with a .285 average for May. Alou exceeded his
expectations this May, when he hit .327.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only had one bad start in my career,'' he said. ``I've
had a lot of good Aprils and some good Mays, but this is the best
May I've ever had. I'm happy with that because I think it shows
that I'm improving and maturing as a ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know myself, and I know I can also get very cold at the
plate. But if it happens, I know I won't panic, because that's
something that's always been a part of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros third baseman Sean Berry played with Alou for four years
in Montreal, so seeing Alou on a tear is nothing new for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mo gets hot, he can carry you,'' Berry said. ``When he's
hot like this and seeing the ball, it doesn't matter where they're
pitching him; he's going to hit it. He's just so aggressive. He's
not up there looking for a walk. He's looking to do some damage.
I've seen him get it going like this a lot of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou doesn't like hitting cleanup; he prefers hitting fifth or
sixth. But he no doubt earned some points with manager Larry
Dierker when he asked to be inserted into the No. 4 spot in the
lineup _ the place no one has seemed to want over the past few
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't hit fourth a lot, but I felt like me hitting fourth
would make our lineup and our team better,'' Alou said. ``I would
prefer to hit lower in the order, but that might not be what's best
for the team. I thought we would be better with me hitting fourth,
so I asked (Dierker), and he decided to give it try. I think it's
worked out well.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said for the trade that brought Alou to Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
