<HEADLINE>
HARDER STARS WORKED, THE LUCKIER THEY GOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The easy and obvious thing is to write off last night's
rub-your-eyes climax to the Stars' 3-2 overtime heart-stopper
against the Red Wings to pure luck.
</P>
<P>
   Who could argue, really?
</P>
<P>
   A deflection off a Detroit defenseman's stick ties the score at
2 with 85 seconds left in regulation, then 46 seconds into
overtime, a no-prayer, throw-it-in shot to set up a shift change
takes a crazy bounce and winds up in the Wings' net.
</P>
<P>
   Instant Stars mob scene at the Detroit blue line. Cue the
fireworks. Bedlam and euphoria reign at deliriously stunned Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   But to give all the credit to a four-leaf clover or somebody's
lucky horseshoe wouldn't paint a picture of how hard the Stars
worked for this, how important it was, how desperate they'd become.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted this season to end,'' sighed 38-year-old center
Guy Carbonneau, who had yanked the Stars' season from the precipice
with his improbable goal with the clock ticking down in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   And so this Western Conference finals series is headed back to
Detroit for a Game 6 that surprises almost no one and shocks
everybody, because the defending Stanley Cup champion Wings had
this one in the bag and let it get away.
</P>
<P>
   That could be an interesting development for a team whose
players were so cocky at their skate-around yesterday, they spent
most of the time chatting with Detroit reporters about their
``next'' series, all but forgetting that they still must beat the
Stars one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win Game 5 to bring it back,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said of the series that had all but slipped away, ``and I'll bet
five minutes after we we're back in the dressing room. our guys
were already focusing on the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't waste any energy, positive or negative, on this
emotional state. You can only think about playing the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotional was the only way to feel when Carbonneau, spinning,
checking, skating with a demonic energy no 38-year-old should
possess, found himself with the puck on his stick 15 feet from the
Wings' goal.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't waste any time, cutting loose with a low sizzler that
hit defenseman Nicklas Lidstrom's stick and came off the ice like a
rising line drive. It found space just under goalie Chris Osgood's
glove and the Stars, who had trailed 2-1 since early in the second
period, took a deep, satisfying breath for the first time in more
than 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to create a chance,'' Carbonneau said. ``You're
desperate in that situation. I was just trying to shoot it at the
net.''
</P>
<P>
   Luck? Sure. The same kind that the Wings had on their first
goal, when Tomas Holdstrom _ or was it Stars defenseman Craig Muni?
_ got a piece of Larry Murphy's shot and tipped it past Eddie
Belfour just before the end of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   That erased a 1-0 Stars lead built when a charging Mike Keane
chipped in a rebound off Craig Ludwig's point-blank shot with 5:44
remaining in the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   Then, early in the second period, Belfour, who was brilliant
otherwise, coughed up the softest of goals, flat missing Igor
Larionov's unobstructed, routine shot from 25 feet out. How soft
was it? Like a mother's good night kiss and it almost sent the
Stars off to dreamland for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played by best yet, and I'm looking forward to that
on Friday,'' Belfour said. ``I haven't been good and lucky at the
same time in this series. I'm due.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Stars emerged for the final period, Hitchcock
gathered his troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt after the second period that we're trying too hard to
hit a home run,'' he said. ``We just said, `Look, stay tight with
our game plan. If it takes the last shift of the game to tie it up,
so be it.'''
</P>
<P>
   It almost did.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was the same for overtime. Play tight defense, check
hard, wait for the right opportunity. Don't do anything rash.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't a home run swing Jamie Langenbrunner took when he
came charging across the center line and cut loose with a shot that
came bouncing in on Osgood. It just turned out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were definitely looking to (shift) change,'' Langenbrunner
conceded. ``We were going to keep (the shifts) short and hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But on this night, luck and the Stars' work ethic joined hands
at 777 Sports Street. Osgood reached out to corral the crazily
bouncing puck with his stick. It took another odd hop, caromed off
the heel of the stick, and nestled oh so sweetly into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those last two goals,'' Hitchcock said, wiping sweat off his
forehead. ``Those were the breaks we needed. We live to play
another day.''
</P>
<P>
   OK. Maybe they did lucky.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it's about time. Now, they need to stay that way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
