<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: WILL LEWINSKY'S LAWYERS SEEK TO CHART NEW COURSE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 9th thru 12th grafs for insert containg remarks by Ginsburg
on Wednesday night) (See also LEWINSKY-LAWYERS) 
(sw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky's new team of lawyers has inherited
a legal strategy built on two seemingly irreconcilable goals. The
aim was to head off an indictment of their client, without putting
her in a position of becoming the witness who threatened to topple
a president.
</P>
<P>
   The unappealing set of possible options _ to become either
history's next John Dean or its next Susan McDougal _ has been
guided almost exclusively by the protective instincts of Ms.
Lewinsky's parents. Divorced and not always of one voice, Ms.
Lewinsky's father and mother have struggled since the outset of the
inquiry nearly five months ago to spare their daughter from either
the pain of an indictment or the agony of a protracted impeachment
proceeding where she would become the president's accuser-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   It was on that tightrope that William Ginsburg, a close friend
of Ms. Lewinsky's father, walked for the last four months, wobbling
between the president and the prosecutor as he sought to steer
clear of either an impeachment effort or an indictment, and
ultimately falling off this week.
</P>
<P>
   Like any good criminal lawyers, the new legal team, Plato
Cacheris and Jacob Stein, are moving quickly to see if there may be
room for a deal that averts an indictment. The pair spent a good
part of Wednesday meeting with two other lawyers who have been
working on the case, familiarizing themselves with the history of
the inquiry in preparation for a possible new round of talks with
the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sign that the two defense lawyers may be tacking to a
different wind when, moments after they were appointed on Tuesday,
their first decision was to pay a private courtesy call to the
independent counsel's office. Lawyers said they wanted to announce
their appointment to the prosecutors before they would learn about
it on the news.
</P>
<P>
   The two defense lawyers, according to participants at the
meeting, did not explicitly hold out the prospect of a new deal.
But it was clear that they understood from decades of experience
that by simply setting an initial tone of courtesy and
conciliation, they had begun to build a new reservoir of goodwill
that could be useful as the process moves along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The landscape changed yesterday,'' said one lawyer in Starr's
office. ``This was an honorable thing to do. It didn't surprise any
of us at all because these are two experienced and
independent-minded lawyers who are looking after the best interests
of their client.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not a statement that one of Starr's lawyers would ever
have made about Ginsburg, who alienated prosecutors days into the
inquiry when he kept them waiting by a telephone for hours,
neglecting to return a call as the investigation began to become
public. Prosecutors would later complain that Ginsburg, a
California specialist in civil malpractice cases, had little
understanding of how a criminal inquiry worked.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg, speaking to reporters on Wednesday night in Los
Angeles said he had told Ms. Lewinsky and her family 7 to 10 days
ago that he wanted to stop representing her.
</P>
<P>
   ``My strategy his a wall,'' he said. ``It no longer was
working.''
</P>
<P>
   That was partly due, he said, to ``my strained relationship with
Ken Starr.'' He added: ``My aggressive, outgoing strategy had lost
its effectiveness. It was time for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   In another contrast to Ginsburg, who seemed to revel in his ties
to the Lewinsky family, the two new lawyers are able to offer an
arms-length and dispassionate expertise that associates of Starr
say could lead to a serious new round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Any new thaw in the frosty relations between prosecutors and Ms.
Lewinsky's lawyers does not bode well for the White House, which as
a political matter had an ally in Ginsburg. Not only did he
regularly criticize Starr, but he also occasionally would make
statements undermining Ms. Lewinsky, statements that could prove
useful to the White House were she to ever testify against the
president.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides on Wednesday would not comment on the new
legal team or about any future agreement between Ms. Lewinsky and
the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains far from clear whether a deal with the
prosecutors can be reached as long as Ms. Lewinsky holds to a
strategy of not wanting to be seen as injuring the president.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's bind is in no small part of her own making. What
has made her lawyers' job so difficult is that prosecutors have
seen two faces of her.
</P>
<P>
   One, on the tapes recorded by her one-time confidante, Linda
Tripp, presents the picture of a young woman acknowledging she will
lie under oath to protect the president, urging Ms. Tripp to lie
and describing steps that may have been taken to conceal evidence
subpoenaed by the lawyers in the Paula Jones sexual harassment
lawsuit, according to people who have heard the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The other, presented by Ginsburg in a series of proposals on the
testimony his client would be willing to offer prosecutors, shows
Ms. Lewinsky as acknowledging that she had sex with the president
but not being urged by anyone to lie about it, according to lawyers
familiar with the proffers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the proposals were rejected because prosecutors
apparently came to believe the Linda Tripp tapes. As a result, the
investigators have spent months attempting to corroborate every
important and mundane detail mentioned on them. The process will
enable them to exert enormous pressure on Ms. Lewinsky to
ultimately acknowledge what she said on the tapes in a criminal
settlement or, failing that, to use the corroborative evidence as
the backbone for an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Her new lawyers made clear on Wednesday that, while talks may
resume soon, they are prepared to fight an indictment if no
agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an absolute misimpression to think that we were only
brought in to cut a deal,'' one of them said. ``We know how to try
a case just as well as to settle one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
