<HEADLINE>
UCLA FRESHMAN BENEFITS FROM SUNNY SKIES, REGULAR WORKOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shakedia Jones couldn't wait to leave Illinois for
a warmer climate after high school.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA freshman sprinter, training for a full season for the
first time, has emerged as a contender for a national title in the
100 and 200 at the NCAA Championships in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Jones made her presence in stunning fashion at the USC-UCLA dual
meet last month, clocking 11.11 and 22.84 seconds in the 100 and
200 to produce the Nos. 2 and 3 all-time junior marks.
</P>
<P>
   In the 100, Jones crushed her high school best of 11.74. In the
200, Jones took off a whopping eight-tenths of a second off her
high school best of 23.62 to set a national dual-meet record. Jones
also ran a leg on the Bruins' 400-meter relay that timed 43.49 for
another national dual-meet and Pacific-10 Conference record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got to a university and practiced seriously with good
weather, I thought I would improve a little bit each year,'' Jones
said. ``I thought it would be a four-year thing. I didn't think my
times would improve drastically.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones won a record 15 Illinois State titles at Waukegan High,
located in a suburb of Chicago, and did not lose a race in four
years. She captured the 100 and 200 all four years as well as the
400 her junior season. Jones also won six indoor titles.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the 1996 and 1997 Junior Olympic 200 champion, came to
UCLA with respectable credentials, but her development this season
has taken her to another level. In the 100, Jones ranks third in
UCLA history behind Gail Devers, the 1992 and 1996 Olympic gold
medalist, and world-record holder Florence Griffith-Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I am amazed because she has been hitting those
times in practice,'' UCLA women's coach Jeannette Boldon said. ``I
am surprised she has run so fast so soon. I thought those were
times we would see next year.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jones, her arrival to Los Angeles couldn't come sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to stay close to home,'' said Jones, who picked
UCLA over Georgia and Florida. ``Warm weather was my main
criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois outdoor season ran only seven weeks from April to
the May. Jones, who typically got a late start on track while
playing on the basketball team, also was forced to practice indoors
for much of the track season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was so unpredictable,'' Jones said. ``In June, it
would be 30 degrees and snowing. We would be wearing our tights and
turtlenecks and everything we had on outside. Even though I didn't
expect so much rain here, the sun is the aspect I love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had serious practice five or six days a week,'' Jones
added. ``Once I got over that I was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Her breakthrough at the UCLA-USC meet, though, was unexpected by
Jones _ and USC's Torri Edwards, the 1996 Pac-10 champion in the
100 and 200. Jones knocked off Edwards in both sprints, pushing the
USC junior to a school-record 11.11 in the 100 and a personal-best
22.88 in the 200. Jones proved her victories were no fluke, turning
back Edwards to win the 100 in the Pac-10 championships at Stanford
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get out and stay strong because she comes on at
the end,'' Edwards said about Jones. ``She's a completely different
sprinter than she was at the beginning of the year. I can't believe
the improvement she has made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
