<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3382 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-3fran-HNS &LR;      06-04 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3 </SLUG>
 fran-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blinebury
</P>
<P>
   So far, series foundation is made of bricks
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ It was a game for the ages. Stone, I think.
</P>
<P>
   The opening match of the NBA Finals resembled basketball the way
a leggy supermodel resembles a porcupine.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't ballet or poetry. It was construction work with bad
grammar.
</P>
<P>
   Grunting, straining, heavy lifting and bricks. Tons of bricks.
Enough to build a skyscraper. Or a very tall monument to
ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   You know what they say in sports: Somebody has to lose.
Eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen shoots 7-for-19, Michael Jordan 13-for-29, Toni
Kukoc 4-for-12, and those are the three big guns in the Chicago
attack. It's a wonder they didn't take a couple of toes off with
that kind of errant aim.
</P>
<P>
   So it was the Bulls who ultimately went down 88-85 in overtime,
perhaps only because the clock ran out before the Jazz could put up
a few more misses.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone shoots 9-for-25, Jeff Hornacek 2-for-10, Greg Foster
1-for-5. And the Jazz is the team with a 1-0 lead in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure wasn't pretty,'' said Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is a pig in lipstick. But after waiting nearly 1{ weeks
for the Finals to finally begin and having so much extra time to
think about the tremendous opportunity before them, this Utah bunch
was willing to cuddle up to just about anything.
</P>
<P>
   You had the Jazz shooting 44 percent as a team. You had the
Bulls shooting 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So what was the problem? Did the Bulls have too little rest
after going the distance in their seven-game war with Indiana in
the Eastern Conference finals? Or did the Jazz have too much rest
after sweeping the Lakers in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe a little of both,'' said Jazz guard John Stockton. ``I
know they had to be very tired after what they went through, and
I'll tell you, sitting around for 10 days and trying to keep
yourself sharp physically and mentally is almost impossible. You
have to do whatever you can.''
</P>
<P>
   In Stockton's case, as usual, he did everything he could and
rescued the Jazz when the night was on the verge of slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Stockton who has been bothered by a bad back
since way back in the first round of the playoffs against the
Rockets and has spent almost as much time on the bench as on the
floor through the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was when the Jazz needed him, when Malone was
struggling, when his team was teetering. He scored 24 points, dealt
eight assists and was the bullet in the Jazz gun that finally shot
down the Bulls in the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   After a Hornacek steal from Pippen, Stockton barreled the length
of the floor and converted a layup and a three-point play that
briefly gave Utah breathing room at 84-79.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls came back. The Bulls always come back. And as the
clock ticked down inside 10 seconds, it was Stockton again with the
ball and the game in his hands as he skittered down the lane. He
took off just inside the foul line and lofted an arching
nine-footer over the outstretched arm of Steve Kerr. It hit nothing
but the bottom of the net and the middle of the Bulls' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   There was a desperate trey by Kukoc that got it back to 86-85.
There were two more free throws by Stockton. There was a heave at
the buzzer by Pippen that didn't hit the rim.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that had drama. Just not much in the way of
artistry.
</P>
<P>
   How many times in the Finals do you see see Jordan get caught
holding the ball for a 24-second violation in the last minute of
overtime? How often do you see Jordan miss a driving shot on the
inside when the outcome is in doubt? His Airness scored 33 points
but looked earthbound.
</P>
<P>
   There were errors from Malone, the Mailman, who returned to the
big stage of the Finals and once again did his impersonation of
Cliff Clavin from Cheers or Newman from Seinfeld or some other
belovedly inept postal employee.
</P>
<P>
   Malone missed from the outside and from the inside. He missed
early, and he missed late. He missed 14 of the first 18 shots he
took in the game before finally roaring down the lane in the fourth
quarter for a pair of slam dunks and then dropping in a fadeaway
from 15 feet and a straight-up jumper from 19 in the last 1:42.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have good rhythm the whole night,'' Malone said.
``But they kept running my plays, and you have to remember that the
game lasts 48 minutes. In the playoffs, I'd like to win and hit all
my shots. But I don't care about the shooting percentage as long as
they go to me and I can hit the big ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Give the kid at the carnival enough tries, and he'll eventually
hit something.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz knows this. The team that wins Game 1 of the Finals has
won the title 80 percent of the time. Utah also knows something
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play better in the next game,'' said Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   It would sure be hard to play worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
