<SLUG> BC-BBC-ARIZONASTATE-LBST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU ADVANCES TO FINAL  
 MURPHY'S AMBITION FINALLY PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ It was a defining moment for a coach who has spent
the past four years stuck between a Brock and a hard place _ his
own fierce ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after his team beat Long Beach State, 14-4, Wednesday,
Arizona State Coach Pat Murphy paused and sighed, inhaling the
moment that had just befallen him.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are advancing to the College World Series
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through so much to get to this point,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy longed for this. He wants success for the players he
believes have given so much. And he has struggled living in the
shadow of the late Jim Brock, who brought the Sun Devils so much,
including two national championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not done,'' said pitcher Richy Leon, who allowed three
runs and eight hits in six innings. ``We know we still have a task
at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Sun Devils' post-game enthusiasm was tempered. The
players shook hands, but there was minimal celebrating. Maybe they
just wanted to get out of the 39-degree (wind chill) conditions.
</P>
<P>
   This is ASU's first trip to the championship since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils will meet either Louisiana State or Southern
California for the title. The Tigers would advance by beating the
Trojans today. USC must beat LSU on back-to-back days.
</P>
<P>
   A Sun Devils-Trojans confrontation would pair college baseball's
two greatest powers. Only USC has appeared in more finals (13) and
won more titles (11) than ASU (nine finals, five titles).
</P>
<P>
   ``A cold night in Omaha turned out to be an even colder and
drearier night for Long Beach State,'' 49ers Coach Dave Snow said.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive thing about ASU is the ease at which it has
advanced through this tournament, outscoring opponents, 34-16.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, it's surprising this team arrived in Omaha in maroon
and gold instead of black and blue.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils grueling schedule resulted in several beatings.
Six straight losses in mid-March. Midweek road games against powers
such as Oklahoma. Three straight losses at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   There were questions. Could this team survive without the the
power hitters of other big-name programs? Would the pitching hold
up? Was Murphy's tough schedule the way to go?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, yes and yes.
</P>
<P>
   Their postseason has been defined by unlikely heros _ Greg
Halvorson, Dustin Delucchi _ gutsy efforts _ Mikel Moreno, Rudy
Arguelles _ and an ace, Ryan Mills, who has not let thoughts of a
professional career get in the way of dominating performances.
</P>
<P>
   It also has been defined by a coach who is enjoying the fruits
of his labor. A coach who often operates on instinct, even when it
is not necessarily a popular decision. A coach whose tough
scheduling looked like a bad idea at times, but in the end proved
to be the right choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought I was blowing smoke, but I knew that
type of schedule would help us,'' Murphy said. ``I knew it was
going to make us better.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon, often the forgotten pitcher in ASU's rotation, did exactly
what Murphy wanted Wednesday, and once again, Leon did it his way:
not with blazing 95 mph fastballs, but with off-speed pitches and
wise decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game, the ESPN guys were giggling and saying, `Look
at this guy's numbers,' but you never judge Richy by his numbers,''
Murphy said. ``You just look at what he's done in the big games,
what he did in the regionals, what he did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon gave up his first hit in the third and his first run in the
fourth, a home run by catcher Bryan Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ASU jumped out to an early lead and not surprisingly, it was
Moreno, a walking spark plug, who got things going with a home run.
</P>
<P>
   It was all ASU from there. The Sun Devils scored four runs in
the second, two in the third and had a 7-0 lead after three
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State freshman Jeff Leuenberger lasted just 2 innings
after allowing seven runs (five earned) and seven hits.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Kramer picked up the save after allowing just one run and
three hits in three innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils got home runs from Moreno, Willie Bloomquist and
Andrew Beinbrink.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomquist demonstrated why he belongs at the top of the order.
He was 5 for 6 with four RBIs and three runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't feel like I was swinging that bat that well,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Delucchi and shortstop Michael Collins had three-hit games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the class of the bracket,'' said Snow, whose team was
eliminated from the tournament. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
