<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3386 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--Malone-Jazz-HNS &LR;      06-04 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--Malone-Jazz-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Malone able to avoid a painful replay
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ The whole scene must have looked eerily familiar
to Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Game 1 of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Chicago Bulls, the defending world champions.
</P>
<P>
   Malone and the Jazz in the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   And Malone couldn't find his game.
</P>
<P>
   Try as he might, Malone couldn't hit a basket, as jumper after
jumper clanged off the rim. The ``Mailman'' wasn't delivering when
the Jazz needed him.
</P>
<P>
   But when it counted most, Malone finally located his touch,
dropping in a pair of jumpers in the final minutes of regulation,
then opening the overtime period with a layup to help spark the
Jazz to an 88-85 victory Wednesday night at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   Malone must have been sweating, though.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was just last year that he stood at the free-throw
line with a chance to put the Jazz ahead late in Game 1 of the
Finals. Malone, just named the league's Most Valuable Player,
clanked both _ and then watched Michael Jordan nail a last-second
jumper for a two-point victory.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Malone, who missed 16 of his 25 shots, was able to
come through.
</P>
<P>
   Malone scored 10 of his 21 points and grabbed six of his
game-high 14 rebounds in the fourth quarter and overtime. He knew
it was just a matter of time before his shots started dropping.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I tried to do was stay within the offense,'' Malone said.
``That's something we've been doing all year long. I've had a lot
of games where I didn't start out shooting the basketball well,
throughout the playoffs. But Jeff Hornacek kept telling me that
it's a 48-minute game _ he didn't mention the overtime _ and that I
should keep shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that the whole night that I took maybe three tough
shots. All the rest were within the offense. And if they're there
on Friday, I'll take those shots. It's just part of it. I didn't
shoot the basketball like I wanted to, but other guys came through
and we were able to get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, and in one of those alternate-reality types of
situations, it was Jordan who made a crucial mistake in the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   With less than two minutes to play and the Bulls trailing by two
points, Jordan was caught with the ball in his hands and the
24-second shot clock winding down. Unsure what to do, Jordan hung
on to the ball too long. Turnover, Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, however, was making his move.
</P>
<P>
   After draining a 15-foot jumper with 1:42 left, Malone came back
with a 19-footer with 57 seconds remaining to give the Jazz a
four-point lead. The Bulls forced overtime, but Malone got the Jazz
started with a power layup and Utah never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Just what John Stockton, who fed Malone on all three baskets,
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around that guy a long time, and even when he has
rough starts, he comes through,'' Stockton said. ``In fact, he hit
two huge shots for us down the stretch in regulation when we seemed
to be just kind of going through the motions and kind of lost out
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a couple of big shots _ that's the type of player he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone shrugged off the late heroics, feeling he did nothing
different than when he was missing the shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those (the late baskets) were in the offense,'' Malone said.
``My main thing throughout these playoffs has been to try and stay
within the offense. Down the stretch, we ran the same plays. I had
those shots early on but wasn't hitting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But down the stretch, we ran those plays, and they're really
not designed for me to pass it. I was wide-open, and I was able to
get some good looks at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I would have felt bad if we would have lost the ballgame
and I didn't shoot the ball really well. But down the stretch, you
can't be afraid to take the next shot.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the Jazz rolled up 62 wins during the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll still go to Karl Malone,'' said coach Jerry Sloan. ``I
kept thinking he had a couple of low shots there, as we got a
little bit of a lead at the end of the ballgame. He missed a
couple, (and) they (the Bulls) got back into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of it _ you have to keep working to do it. We've
gone to him so many times, and we'll do it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
