<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3389 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-CASSTEVENS-ARIZST     06-04 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-CASSTEVENS-ARIZST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS' BELIEF IN SELVES BECOMES INFECTIOUS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ With his team in the College World Series, Pat
Murphy has a lot on his mind. During the last practice, the Arizona
State coach sat in the dugout, staring off into the distance, deep
in thought. He looked as if he were searching for an answer, which
in fact, he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's Gilligan's first name?'' Murphy asked.
</P>
<P>
   A trivia buff, Murphy couldn't remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collins will know,'' the coach said, brightening. To prove it,
he put the question to his shortstop. ``Hey, Collins, what was
Gilligan's name. On ``Gilligan's Islan''d?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie,'' Mike Collins replied.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was correct, of course, which should come as no
surprise. Whether the game is TV trivia or baseball, the Sun Devils
seem to have all the answers.
</P>
<P>
   In Omaha, this team that back in March was only four games above
.500 has been unstumpable, and unstoppable. Florida State couldn't
beat the Sun Devils. No. 1-ranked Miami couldn't either. Long Beach
State never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   On a breezy, October-like night, with the wind chill in the 30s,
the Long Beach coach stood on the dugout steps and watched his team
quickly fall behind 5-0 . . .7-0 . . .8-0 . . . With his gray
moustache and receding chin, Dave Snow resembles the cowboy actor
Slim Pickens, who uttered the immortal line in ``Blazing Saddles,''
``What in the wide, wide world of sports is goin' on here?''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what's going on. ASU is playing its best baseball of the
season. Solid pitching. Good fielding. Great hitting. The Sun
Devils think they're the '27 Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   When you're playing well, baseball is a simple game. See the
ball. Hit the ball. That's what they did again Wednesday night,
slapping out 18 hits, including three homers, to bury Long Beach,
14-4, and advance to the national championship game for the first
time in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Can they win it all?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, why not?
</P>
<P>
   Half of winning is believing you can win, and right now these
kids, who have won six in a row, believe that center-field sign in
Rosenblatt Stadium is meant for them. ``College World Series,'' the
message reads. ``Where Dreams Come True.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting is as contagious as the measles. And the entire ASU team
is infected. In three games, the Sun Devils have scored 34 runs.
With each run, each win, their confidence has grown.
</P>
<P>
   Can they do it?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got a group of winners,'' Murphy said, ``you've
got a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Go down the lineup. You can take your pick of winners. Leadoff
man Willie Bloomquist collected five hits, including a home run.
The All-America second baseman scored ASU's 12th run when he raced
home after a wild pitch _ Long Beach had six, a Series record and
slid headfirst across the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Mikel Moreno led off the scoring with a solo home run, Andrew
Beinbrink knocked one out. Left fielder Dustin Delucchi collected
three hits. So did Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Richy Leon gave the Sun Devils six strong innings as
a starter. This year the senior has played second base and
shortstop and stepped in as the designated hitter. Leon is ASU's
utility man, which means he does everything except repair phone
lines. In games Leon has started, the Sun Devils are 10-1.
</P>
<P>
   Although destiny is a cliche in sports, you have to wonder if
maybe this is meant to be ASU's year. The Sun Devils' three
opponents committed 10 errors. One of them led to Long Beach's
undoing when the 49ers shortstop dropped a routine pop-up in the
second inning and two ASU runs scored. The Sun Devils sent nine
batters to the plate in that inning.
</P>
<P>
   Now ASU faces its toughest test. It must wait. The Sun Devils
don't pay until Saturday. They will face either Southern California
or Louisiana State, the two-time defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   Can ASU win it?
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``We said all along we didn't come here just to show up,''
Murphy said. ``I said it so many times I believe it now.''
</P>
<P>
   So do his players.
</P>
<P>
   What a story. What a year. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
