<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3390 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-nbafinals-HNS &LR;      06-04 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-nba </SLUG>
 finals-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Malone, Stockton 
leave Bulls in rare 
spot after opener
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The Utah Jazz's dynamic duo of Karl Malone and
John Stockton has put the Chicago Bulls in a predicament they
haven't seen since 1991 _ down 1-0 in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Malone shook off a subpar showing for most of the game to make
numerous key plays late, then Stockton converted a crucial
three-point play and the clinching, running, 10-foot jumper with
9.3 seconds left as the Jazz took a hard-fought 88-85 overtime
victory over the Bulls in Game 1 at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the Los Angeles Lakers won Game 1 in '91, then got
swept in the next four, have the Bulls fallen behind in their five
marches to NBA titles during the past seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   If their dynasty is to continue, it will do so in
come-from-behind fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have asked for a better game or a better
opportunity to win one on their home floor,'' Chicago coach Phil
Jackson said. ``We sort of feel like we let one slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   It was apparent the Bulls felt they had wasted a silver-bullet
effort out of their arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, when the exhausting, thrilling opener was done, the
Jazz thought it had taken a major step toward proving the Bulls'
dynasty is, indeed, crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   If Utah had any doubts it can get this job done, the Jazz erased
them Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Or did it? Judging from Utah's analysis of the performance,
maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an awfully good win for us,'' said Jazz coach Jerry
Sloan. ``I didn't know if we were going to be able to hold them off
because we had a terrible time trying to score in a stretch or two.
And we had a terrible time trying to guard them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fortunate. I don't have anything to jump up and down
about after that. I think we had to have a little bit of luck to
win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Stockton: ``We're going to have to execute a lot better to
beat this team on Friday (in Game 2).''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but a whole lot of execution in crucial moments should
have given some positive vibrations to the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the way the Jazz survived the lid-lifter was
reminiscent of another battle-toughened team's mode of operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watch the Bulls, they've won a lot of games through the
years just like this,'' Malone said. ``When the playoffs come, you
just want to win. You don't care how or if it's by one point or a
whole bunch of points.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz had precious little room for error in Game 1,
particularly in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz scored the first five points of the extra period, then
fell back on two clutch defensive stands to seal the win.
</P>
<P>
   Up 84-82 with under two minutes to go in the overtime, Utah
forced a shot-clock violation with 1:18 to go when Michael Jordan,
who had 33 points, let the 24-second clock expire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mental lapse,'' Jordan said. ``I never really noticed
the clock. Nobody really noticed the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jackson said: ``We had no one in front of Michael to tell him
the clock was running down.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a human error, the kind nobody expects from Jordan. It
was one of 15 Chicago turnovers, which led to 21 Utah points, many
of them of the fast-break variety. Utah had 21 fast-break points to
six for the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   After the Chicago shot-clock snafu, Stockton turned the ball
over because of Steve Kerr's deflection, then Chris Morris tipped
the ball away from Luc Longley on Chicago's end and Bryon Russell
recovered in time to call a timeout with 28.4 seconds left. That
set up Stockton's heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Though Toni Kukoc hit a 3-pointer with 5.4 seconds left,
Stockton nailed two free throws with 3.5 showing and Pippen's
3-pointer at the buzzer was long.
</P>
<P>
   It was a scintillating end to a great Finals game.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks started when it was tied at 75. Malone had missed
16 of 22 shots to that point. But he first nailed a 16-footer over
Longley, then, after a Jordan miss, stepped out to 20 feet and
swished a jumper for a 79-75 Jazz lead with 55.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't over. After Pippen made two free throws, Malone
passed out of the double-team to Bryon Russell, who missed a
3-pointer with 36 seconds showing.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls had plenty of time to set up a tying play. Two in
fact. First Jordan missed, but Pippen rebounded with 23.6 seconds
left and called timeout before falling out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan found Longley on the left side of the paint and the big
Australian's 8-foot push shot banged off the glass and through the
net, tying the score with 14.3 ticks to go.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago had a foul to give and took it with 7.3 left and
Stockton's desperation 20-footer hit off the back iron as the
buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   Overtime took on a Jazz tint quickly as Malone scored on a
layup. Then Jeff Hornacek tipped the ball away from Pippen and
Stockton converted a three-point play with 3:23 to go for an 84-79
Utah lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was the Jazz's defense that saved it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Malone must have been having a flashback. Midway
through the fourth quarter, Malone was looking at a 4-for-17
shooting ledger, bringing back the horrid memories of the Finals
from last June, when he was a disappointment, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   They say postal workers have trouble with canines. This Mailman
obviously was allergic to these so-called underdogs, which the
Bulls fashioned themselves as when the series began.
</P>
<P>
   But the doldrums didn't last all night.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz endured a miserable stretch when it went 5:20 without
scoring in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   During that entire drought, Utah lost exactly four points off
its lead, which stood at 69-65 for what seemed like an eternity as
both defenses dug in.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Malone snapped to life. After a Steve Kerr miss, the Jazz
got a fast break that ended as Jazz breaks often do _ with Stockton
feeding Malone for a slam.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, after Jordan made just one of two free throws,
Malone drove an alarmingly wide-open lane for a dunk with 4:41 left
for a 73-66 Utah lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls had one push left. After an exchange of points, Jordan
hit consecutive midrange jumpers and, after Malone missed, Pippen
rebounded and then fired in a 3-pointer with 2:36 left to tie the
score at 75.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls had put themselves in precisely the kind of
opportunistic situation they'd hoped for going into Game 1. Now the
question was whether they could finish it.
</P>
<P>
   They came up just short.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
