<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO_DESIGNATED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DH STANDS AT CROSSROADS  
 25-YEAR-OLD RULE TO SPREAD TO NL OR VANISH, SOME SAY 
</HEADLINE>
 HITTER-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The purists have been shaking their heads in disgust for more
than 25 years. The designated hitter, they say, simply is not
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they love to point out, the very first item in the
official baseball rule book states, ``Baseball is a game between
two teams of nine players each . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Add a DH and you're looking at 10 players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I like the National League style, where you earn
what you get,'' San Diego outfielder Tony Gwynn said. ``If you ask
me now, I like the game without the DH. But I might be nearing a
stage of my career where I could have a DH job waiting for me soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, though, I hate it. I think it's a better brand of
baseball without the DH.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks will be in Oakland this weekend, getting their
first taste of the DH, introduced into the American League in 1973.
It immediately became one of the most significant and controversial
changes the game has seen.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Yankees' Ron Blomberg first hit in place of the
pitcher, the debate has raged between those who love it and those
who loathe it.
</P>
<P>
   As baseball nears the next century, it's becoming increasingly
evident that something is going to happen to either eliminate the
designated hitter from the AL or adopt it in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming belief is that the DH may die in the next few
years. Of course, strong opposition will come from the players
union, which must give its approval though collective bargaining
for a change that drastic.
</P>
<P>
   The union's argument against killing the DH is that a dozen or
so high-salaried players will be eliminated from the game. Players
such as Edgar Martinez, Paul Molitor and Harold Baines, none of
whom possesses great defensive skills, could be forced into
retirement or significantly reduced roles.
</P>
<P>
   One possible remedy that has been mentioned is allowing rosters
to expand from 25 to 26, a move that could appease the union and
bring about the elimination of the DH.
</P>
<P>
   The other side, as Gwynn pointed out, is that baseball is a game
in which a player should be required to earn what he gets, and
playing the field in order to get your at-bats was required of the
game for the first century.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what they do, I wish the game had the same rules in
both leagues,'' Gwynn said. ``The fact that one league has one set
and the other another is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Many baseball fans prefer watching a Molitor or Baines continue
playing late into his 30s or early 40s. And it's doubtful a Dave
Winfield or Carl Yastrzemski would have reached 3,000 hits without
the benefit of the DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at where most DHs bat, and it's in the (No.) 3, 4 or
5 spots in the order,'' said Colorado Manager Don Baylor, a former
MVP and one of the finest designated hitters toward the end of his
playing career. ``You're talking about some great hitters who have
added a lot to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Some will argue that if a player can hit, a manager will find a
spot for him in the field, no matter how poor his defensive skills.
</P>
<P>
   Like most everyday players who are asked to make the adjustment
to the DH, Baylor fought the move in the beginning when he was with
the California Angels.
</P>
<P>
   He said he resisted ``until (Coach) Dave Garcia pulled me aside
and asked me to put myself in the manager's spot. We had Joe Rudi
and myself as left fielders. Garcia asked me who I'd rather have in
left if I was the manager. From that point on, I never fought it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another argument made by the purists says there is less managing
in the AL, where taking a pitcher out of a game requires no
juggling of the lineup in order to make double-switches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree,'' said former Texas and Boston Manager Kevin
Kennedy, who was reared in the NL style in the Dodgers system.
``Sometimes it's harder to decide when to make a pitching move in
the AL. In the NL, if you're down three runs in the fifth and the
pitcher is due up, the decision is almost made for you. You
pinch-hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The DH was instituted on an experimental basis at a time when
the AL was lagging behind the more powerful NL in the early 1970s
in attendance and glamour.
</P>
<P>
   American League owners voted 8-4 to approve the DH while the NL
vetoed the idea, which was first attempted in the Triple-A American
Association in 1969. Then-Commissioner Bowie Kuhn pushed strongly
for the DH, believing sagging offenses could use the boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the designated hitter has killed the game or the
sport,'' said Geronimo Berroa, who in the past three years has
emerged as one of the top DHs. ``For players like me and Molitor
and Baines, it's been great and I think fans haven't minded seeing
the extra offense. Whether it stays, who knows?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
