<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TINKER, EVERS, CHANCE AND DIET OF WORMS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Team sports involve trust and combinations:
Johnny Unitas to Raymond Berry. Joe Montana to Jerry Rice. Tinker
to Evers to Chance.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, it was Utah's John Stockton and Karl Malone
versus Chicago's Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when Malone found himself mired in a wretched
9-for-25 shooting slump, Stockton implored the Mailman to ``shoot,
shoot, shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   After eight possessions without either team scoring, and Utah
leading by 69-65, Stockton finally waved his hand and effectively
said, let's get back to basics: pick and roll. Stockton found
Malone, and the Mailman dunked it down. Three possessions later
Stockton and Malone collaborated on back-to-back plays.
</P>
<P>
   On one, Malone hit a 15-foot jumper, and the next time he took a
pass from Stockton and knocked down a 19-foot jumper to give Utah a
79-75 lead with 56.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   On Chicago's three previous possessions, Jordan had hit a
17-foot jumper and a 20-foot jumper and then Pippen had tied the
score with a 24-foot 3-pointer. And so it went, back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   Tinker. Evers. Chance.
</P>
<P>
   In the moment of truth, with the game on the line, Chicago
trailing by 2 points, Jordan once again took the ball and took the
drive and drew the double team. But this time instead of hitting
Pippen, he found a wide-open Luc Longley, who hit a short shot to
send the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Overtime belonged to Stockton. He had the first basket, then
made a steal, scored, drew a foul by Jordan and completed a 3-point
play. This effectively catapulted Utah to a victory in what may
well be the most important game of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's victory in Game 1 may have eased, at least temporarily,
the insecurities of a city that is desperately pulling for its team
to win its first championship. The yearnings were evident earlier
in the day, on a gorgeous afternoon in a city known for its
laid-back veneer.
</P>
<P>
   Fans converged on the downtown Gallivan Center, where a variety
of booths had been set up for their participation.
</P>
<P>
   By 2 o'clock the audience had grown to 150. This was the moment
of truth: they had come to watch five fans vie for the right to win
two pairs of tickets to Game 1 on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a promotion by KFAN radio, fans were asked what they
would do, how far they would go, how desperate they were to win
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Postma took out a jar containing 15 goldfish that he
planned to devour. ``I just figured that 15 is the number of
playoff games we have to win to win the championships,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Just before he went up to do his thing, Postma said, ``I'll eat
the first 11, then the last four I'm going to chew up, like the
Jazz are going to chew up Chicago tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   As he gulped, fans chanted, ``Blair, Blair, Blair,'' then
``U-tah, U-tah.''
</P>
<P>
   There is clearly a marriage in Salt Lake City, a confluence of
purpose surrounding basketball: fans are as desperate to win
championship tickets as the players, especially Malone and
Stockton, are to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   The sense in Salt Lake City, if you go by what you hear and
read, is one of supreme confidence that 1998, finally, is Utah's
year:
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think we've got them where we want them,'' Postma
said of the Bulls before swallowing the goldfish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The final contestant of the day was a man known only as Dale; no
one expected him to top Postma. Until he announced was going to eat
a Dennis Rodman sandwich, and produced two slices of white bread
with worms in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   There were shrieks from those at the front, howls of disgust
from those in the back. But everyone applauded wildly for Dale,
even as they averted their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   So Postma and Dale were hands-down winners. They sat next to
each other last night, rooting with 19,000 others as Utah stopped
the Bulls, &QC; 88-85, perhaps the beginning of the end of Chicago's
dynasty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
