<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-ROCKIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS SUFFER NIGHTMARE OF FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
Rockies 3, Diamondbacks 2 
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Diamondbacks left fielder David Dellucci said he
probably will dream about it, but there will be no way to change
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Back, back, back . . . he reached up for the ball hit by
Colorado's Vinny Castilla, felt something make contact with his
glove . . .
</P>
<P>
   He looked in it and nothing was there. The ball had hit the
yellow line on top of the fence and bounced over for a two-run home
run, giving the Rockies a come-from-behind 3-2 victory with nobody
out in the bottom of the ninth Wednesday night at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   The home run on a 1-1 curveball from right-handed closer Gregg
Olson was Castilla's sixth in six games against the Diamondbacks
this season and his 22nd overall, and helped the Rockies (25-34)
avoid the embarrassment of a third straight loss at home to the
expansion Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The shot came with Larry Walker at third base as the result of a
leadoff double and a stolen base. In the top of the ninth, Walker
had saved what could have been a big insurance run for Arizona when
he threw Dellucci out at the plate after catching a fly ball to
right field by Karim Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks (19-40) still can win the four-game series with
a victory today at 5:05 p.m. They move on to the Bay area on Friday
to begin a three-game interleague series with the Oakland
Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Willie Blair started for the Diamondbacks and
pitched his best game of the season. He gave up only a
second-inning run on six hits through eight innings before Olson
(1-3) took over in the ninth in an attempt to earn his eighth save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough one,'' Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter
said. ``Willie pitched as well as you can pitch, especially here.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair had thrown 93 pitches and probably could have at least
started the ninth, but Showalter decided to go with Olson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been the first time Willie had gone into the
ninth,'' Showalter said. ``Oly has been pitching as well as anybody
other than maybe Russ Springer out of the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair dueled Rockies right-hander Pedro Astacio throughout the
game, which started when the temperature was 49, 35 degrees colder
than Tuesday night's temperature at game time.
</P>
<P>
   Blair had a 2-1 lead as the result of Travis Lee's two-out, solo
homer in the sixth inning, his 10th of the year. Astacio, who beat
the Diamondbacks on April 2 at Bank One Ballpark, scattered six
hits and struck out nine in 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing, but that stuff happens,'' Blair said. ``I
knew that I pitched well and gave us a chance to win the ballgame.
I was able to throw all of my pitches for strikes most of the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was surprised to be lifted after eight innings,
Blair said, ``Yes and no. Oly's been throwing so well lately, that
it would seem to be the logical thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the top of the ninth against left-hander Chuck
McElroy, Dellucci doubled to right-center, his fourth in two games.
He advanced to third on a single to left by Jay Bell but was held
because the ball was hit too shallow.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia then lofted a medium-deep fly to Walker in and third base
coach Brian Butterfield sent Dellucci. Walker's throw was there in
plenty of time, and catcher Jeff Reed made a sweeping tag on
Dellucci, who slid headfirst, for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That throw turned the momentum back in their direction,''
Showalter said. ``Larry's arguably the best right fielder in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   As if Walker's heart wasn't charged up enough, he led off the
ninth with a drive to left-center between Dellucci and Devon White
and outraced Dellucci's throw to second. Olson and the Diamondbacks
didn't even pay attention when Walker took off for third and made
it easily.
</P>
<P>
   Then Castilla connected on the 1-1 curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing deep, but I didn't think it was going to go
out,'' Dellucci said. ``I didn't think it was even going to reach
the fence. But it kept floating and floating . . . the next thing
you know . . . I put my glove up and I hit something, but I don't
know if it was the ball or what. I'll probably dream about it.''
</P>
<P>
   TV replays showed a fan reaching for the ball with a glove, but
it didn't appear that the fan had an impact on the play because the
ball had already bounced on top of the fence. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
