<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN DEFECTORS ARE STRUGGLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez made his major league debut for
the New York Yankees on Wednesday night. He's the latest Cuban
defector to make the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has been that most of the Cubans to arrive in the
big leagues recently have been major disappointments. Hernandez's
half-brother, Livan Hernandez, was the National League Championship
Series and World Series MVP last year but has done little this
season to distinguish himself.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for leading American League Rookie of the Year
candidate Rolando Arrojo in Tampa Bay and New York Mets shortstop
Rey Ordonez, the recent Cubans to make it the majors could almost
all be branded busts.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Osvaldo Fernandez, Oakland's Ariel Prieto and
Rene Arocha haven't come close to living up to the advance billing
each received.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the new Cubans had too much to live up to. The Cuban big
leaguers of the 1950s and '60s set a high standard for the island
nation of 11 million. Minnie Minoso, Luis Tiant, Tony Perez and
Camilo Pascual were All-Star-caliber players whose talents bordered
on the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban-Americans of the 1980s, the first generation of Cubans
either born or raised in the United States, continued the standard
set by the previous group.
</P>
<P>
   A list that includes Rafael Palmeiro, Jose Canseco, Alex
Fernandez, Fernando Vina and Jorge Fabregas did little to diminish
the belief that Cubans were great players.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Orlando Hernandez will take his shot at entering the elite
group of Cuban players. Recent history is not on his side, but that
shouldn't matter to the pitcher considered the greatest from Cuba
since Tiant. &QL; 
 &QL; 
They're serious &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs are no longer just hoping to be in a divisional
race this summer. The Cubs are actually making the kind of moves
that show they're dead serious about making a run at their first
playoff appearance in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   By sending third baseman Kevin Orie to Triple-A Iowa last week
and warning catcher Scott Servais to start hitting or else, Cubs
President Andy McPhail sent word that being lovable losers is not
acceptable in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping Orie, considered the best third baseman in franchise
history since Ron Santo, definitely sent a shock through the
clubhouse. Of course, with a .181 batting average, Orie couldn't
make much of an argument to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all accountable, myself, the coaches and the players,''
Manager Jim Riggleman said. ``The bottom of the lineup has got to
pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Servais, who was batting .227 with 11 RBIs in 132
at-bats entering Wednesday, has been told to pick it up or face
losing regular playing time to back up Sandy Martinez, who is
batting .298 with six RBIs in 47 at-bats. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oh, Brother &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's four-time Cy Young Award winning pitcher Greg Maddux
showed exactly why he is considered a fierce competitor during a
game against Montreal last week.
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves clinging to a 1-0 lead, Expos reliever Mike
Maddux (Greg's older brother) came in to face Eddie Perez to start
the eighth. Perez fell behind 1-2 in the count before slamming a
homer over the left-field fence, helping the Braves to a 2-0 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for the pitch,'' Perez said. ``Greg told me
about his brother. He said, `Get ready for the sinker.' And he
threw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux said, ``He's my brother. I love him. I want him to
do well. But I'm trying to win, you know? I was glad Eddie hit a
home run, sad my brother gave it up. (It) turned out to be a big
run.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rarified air, kind of &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's Jim Thome is attempting to enter a select group that
includes only Babe Ruth and Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Wednesday, Thome's 36 walks and 59 strikeouts were good
enough to rank second in the American League in each category,
trailing the leader by three and one, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a player led the league in those two categories in
the same season was 1958 when Mantle tied with the Washington
Senators' Jim Lemon in strikeouts and led in walks. Before Mantle,
only Ruth had accomplished the feat, leading the league in both
categories in 1923, '24, '27 and '28.
</P>
<P>
   The most amazing aspect of this? Thome was batting .322 entering
Wednesday's game. No player has ever hit above .320 and led the
league in strikeouts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
