<SLUG> BC-BBO-FANTASYBASEBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A SLUMP? DON'T BE TOO QUICK TO PANIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF CADE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Run silent, run deep.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, and it's almost always impossible to predict or
explain, somehow your fine collection of players seems to come to a
dead stop. No one hits, runs or scores, and all the pitchers are
getting creamed. The team sinks faster than the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, is this just a two-week malaise or are you in a
free fall that will wreck your entire year? Will your team correct
itself or do you need to intervene and make a few deals?
</P>
<P>
   One thing to keep in mind is that there are still 100 games to
play.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox Manager Jerry Manual sort of summed it up recently.
``When do we say, `This is enough at-bats, this is enough starts?'
But we're still in the month of May and we still have to keep
things in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   No sense unloading a player who is going badly and then watch
him rebound for another team. Some players you just have to ride
out.
</P>
<P>
   That takes in all the trade rumors, too. If you have Randy
Johnson, Hideo Nomo, Rafael Palmeiro, John Olerud, Roberto Alomar
or Carlos Baerga, you just have to bear it.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, baseball insiders usually are wrong more often than
they are right. They are on TV every night and they have to come up
with juicy tidbits, even if they aren't quite on the button. In
short, most trade rumors don't come to fruition, simply because,
for one thing, most teams are not the Marlins. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Speaking of rumors &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays are shopping a pitcher for the Cardinals' Delino
DeShields. The Jays are talking to the right team. The Cardinals
have three starters disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs denied a three-way deal that had them getting Todd
Hundley, the Mets getting Carlos Perez and the Expos getting Brant
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Hamilton of the Padres is targeted by Seattle and St. Louis
for Randy Johnson and Royce Clayton, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The entire Hideo Nomo situation is baffling. He is coming off
surgery. You'd think both sides could cool it, give him the summer
to regain arm strength and then go from there. The Dodgers, taking
a hard line, first with Mike Piazza and now with Nomo, gave up any
trade leverage. Chances are, Nomo will go through waivers, he'll be
assigned to Triple-A, refuse to go and then become a free agent.
What would be something is if the Dodgers pull the trigger on a
deal to get Johnson and the Mariners get the players they want from
LA _ and sign Nomo. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Take note &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rod Beck, who despite losing the zip on his fastball, had been
doing the job as the Cubs' closer until last week, when, admittedly
overused, he blew two straight saves and had to be taken out last
Saturday. To Beck's credit, he was used five straight days.
</P>
<P>
   Just a bit to the north, the Brewers have decided to go to
bullpen by committee after Doug Jones blew his trillionth save _
oh, all right, he's blown seven in 18 chances. Chad Fox is expected
to return to the roster in about three weeks. If his arm stays
healthy, he could win the closer job. Expect the Brewers to be
cautious with him, just the same.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett will get a chance to play center field full time
for the Astros while rookie Richard Hidalgo mends a separated
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Griesinger, the Tigers' No. 1 pick in '96, will get a
chance to win a spot in the rotation. His Triple-A record isn't so
hot, but he had a 2.91 ERA in 10 starts at Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to leadoff, Reds outfielder Reggie Sanders has
become a new man. He is hitting .357, with a .502 on-base
percentage. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
