<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-INTE     06-04 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-INTERLEAGUE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS TAKE THEIR SHOW TO INTERLEAGUE PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a season full of firsts, the Diamondbacks will step into the
world of interleague play for the first time this weekend when they
travel to Oakland to play a three-game series against the
Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the Anaheim Angels will visit Bank One Ballpark for
the Diamondbacks' first home interleague series.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second season of interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   The reviews on the first season appear to be mixed, primarily
because of some travel difficulties and resistance from purists.
</P>
<P>
   Interleague play will be a new experience for the Diamondbacks'
Buck Showalter, who last managed in 1995. Since he came from the
American League with the New York Yankees, this might be an easier
transition for him than it would for others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' he said. ``I think it has some
real merits. The fans get to see the players from the other
leagues, which is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy geographically, matching up teams from the West and
the East and so on, but I do think our fans in Arizona would like
to see the (Boston) Red Sox and the (Baltimore) Orioles. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And that other team. The one that wears pinstripes. The, uh,
Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Showalter said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll have to sit down after this season and
re-examine it, how to make things better with the scheduling end of
it,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was messed up, man,'' San Francisco Giants Manager Dusty
Baker said. ``Two games here, two games there. And what happens
when you end up tied for a playoff spot with a team that might not
have played the same amount of games against the same teams as you?
I don't know if they should keep it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Baker's pitchers, veteran right-hander Orel Hershiser, is
never short on opinions. He has played in both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should make a decision on it, period, and stick with it.
None of this straddling-the-fence thing every two or three years,''
Hershiser said. ``If they're going to keep it, I think there
certainly has to be a better way than what they have now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of sitting down and taking the time and going
through it, step by step. I'd love to see something in place for
like a minimum of 10 years. It's all about leadership, having a
plan. I've never seen a $10 billion industry fly by the seat of its
pants like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn, the San Diego Padres' perennial All-Star outfielder,
said if interleague play is based solely on geographical ties, his
club falls way short.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no geographic interleague rival like the Dodgers would
and the Giants would,'' he said. ``The Diamondbacks are kind of in
the same category. The Rockies, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, you probably would have everybody playing
everybody, kind of like the NFL does, but I don't know . . . having
the leagues separate makes things interesting at World Series time.
That's what has made our game unique.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that it was enjoyable playing against the Seattle
Mariners. The teams share the same spring-training facility in
Peoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edgar (Martinez), A Rod (Alex Rodriguez), Grif (Ken Griffey
Jr.). It's fun to play against them and fun for the fans, I'm sure,
to watch,'' Gwynn said. ``And I would kind of like to play in
Yankee Stadium and Fenway Park just once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there is the question of the (designated hitter). I DH'd
once or twice last year, but I really didn't like it. You get more
of a full experience playing in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it (interleague play) stay? I honestly don't think so.
Mainly because of the travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks shortstop Jay Bell was with the Kansas City Royals
last season, and said the fans' response to games against the St.
Louis Cardinals ``was tremendous. You would hope that kind of
excitement can continue all around baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a different style. The National League probably
relies more on pitching and defense and the American League relies
more on the home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they should do is do the reverse of what they're doing
now. Use the DH in National League parks and not use it in the
American League parks. In general, the National League teams
probably have the advantage because the American League pitchers
don't normally hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The second season of interleague play is sure to manufacture its
share of memorable moments, but will it be enough for it to
continue?  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
