<HEADER>
A3411 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BICKLEY_NBAFINALS     06-04 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BICKLEY_NBAFINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTAH APPEARS READY TO TAKE ULTIMATE STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ They're ready now. Ready to take the final
step. Ready to win the big prize.
</P>
<P>
   After 53 minutes of chaos, after a man consumed a sandwich
stuffed with live worms just to win a pair of tickets, after Karl
Malone hosted his own Brickyard 400, the Utah Jazz took a huge step
toward the maturity of champions. A huge step toward the finish
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz escaped its own blunders, overcame its jitters and won
a basketball game that could've effectively ended its season. And
now, the Jazz is ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good win for us,'' Jazz Coach Jerry Sloan said. ``I didn't
know whether we'd be able to hold them off.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Scottie Pippen slammed his gum to the floor in
disgust. The Bulls have done this so many times, refusing to lose
when they're destined for defeat. Like Wednesday, a night when the
Jazz squandered every opportunity to put the game away, handing
Michael Jordan the showcase of overtime, simply begging for
heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Jazz lost, a championship trophy might have slipped
through its fingers. But it didn't. And now the Bulls can add the
strain of overtime to their aching legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't ask for a better game, a better opportunity to
win on their court,'' Bulls Coach Phil Jackson said. ``We let one
slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson can take partial credit for that, committing a tactical
blunder that sealed the outcome. On the decisive play of overtime _
following a timeout _ he assigned Steve Kerr to guard John
Stockton. The mismatch was exploited, Stockton scored on a drive to
the hoop, and the Jazz had the cushion it needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted that kind of situation,'' Jackson said. ``Steve
stayed in front of him. It was a tough enough shot. I'll live with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He may die with it, too. Surely, Malone won't gag on his jumper
like he did for the first 46 minutes. The Jazz now knows its bench
is superior and is giddy with its breakthrough performance. And it
realize the Bulls are on their heels, a team that committed rare
mistakes in overtime, including a 24-second violation when Jordan
had the ball.
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame Jordan, who authored another fabulous game and
may have found renewed serenity with a new hobby. Jordan has begun
playing the piano in his hotel, taking lessons from NBC's Ahmad
Rashad.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls now are relying on Luc Longley, an injured Dennis
Rodman and the immortal Dickey Simpkins to handle Malone. All three
performed well on Wednesday, but the odds of that continuing are
not good. They are also relying too much on Jordan and Pippen to
carry the offense, and pretty soon, the well is going to run dry.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, they haven't beaten the Jazz in three tries this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's neat to win a game when I don't play the way I expect to
play,'' Malone said. ``In the past, when I didn't have a great
game, we'd lose. That's changed, and it's neat to see when you're
trying to win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   If not a passing of the torch, this series is an amazing
contrast in organizations. On Wednesday, Jazz owner Larry Miller
said he is determined to extend the contracts of his three
cornerstones _ Malone, Stockton and Coach Jerry Sloan. But in
Chicago, a dynasty will be dismantled before its time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael isn't coming back,'' Ron Harper told ``Newsweek''
magazine. ``There's too much bad blood here for anybody to want to
do this again.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't worry about Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf suddenly
finding a conscience, which bodes well for everyone who wants to
see Pippen in a Suns jersey next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Pippen gets a five-year deal for a lot of money, he should
take it,'' Reinsdorf told a national publication.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a wonder the Bulls can even perform with all the daily
chaos swirling through their lives. Now they have to find a way to
recover and win a game in Utah, find a way to beat a team that's
convinced its time has come.
</P>
<P>
   Or the run is over. And the real chaos will begin. &QL;  &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
