<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3417 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-JA-ZZ-AZR &LR;      06-04 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-JA-ZZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKTON TAKES CENTER COURT AS JAZZ TOP BULLS  
 JORDAN GAFFE NEAR END OF OT DOOMS DEFENDING CHAMPIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Utah's John Stockton may not be as renowned as
Chicago's Michael Jordan for making great plays in critical
situations, but he hasn't been on the NBA's biggest stage as often,
either.
</P>
<P>
   It was Stockton, not Jordan, who made the clutch plays down the
stretch in Game 1 of the NBA Finals on Wednesday night, lifting the
Jazz to an 88-85 overtime victory and a 1-0 lead in the
best-of-seven championship series.
</P>
<P>
   And Stockton's timing couldn't have been better, as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the Finals a big question was how rusty the Jazz
would be after sitting idle for 10 days after their sweep of the
Los Angeles Lakers in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, most of the rust settled in Karl Malone's airway.
The Jazz star struggled with his shot most of the night before
finally hitting a couple of big shots in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Malone wound up with 21 points on 9-of-25 shooting. But Stockton
hit 9 of 12 shots and handed out eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, meanwhile, were concerned with rest more than rust.
They just came off a grueling seven-game series with Indiana and
had to win an intense Game 7 to advance. The last thing the Bulls
wanted was an overtime game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious we had our chances. . .that shot by John Stockton
kind of extinguished our hopes,'' said Chicago Coach Phil Jackson.
``Except for fatigue being a factor at the end of the game, I
thought we played fairly well. Malone had a tough night shooting,
but Stockton picked him up tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan finished with 33 points on 13-of-29 shooting, but he made
a critical error with 1:18 remaining in the overtime and the Jazz
leading by two points. Jordan lost track of the 24-second shot
clock and it expired, turning over the ball to Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intensity level is so high, I think we felt like we had
more time on the clock,'' said Chicago's Scottie Pippen. ``I think
he just lost track.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan agreed it was a mental lapse, but not necessarily his
own. He said Pippen was confused about the play that was supposed
to be run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie didn't know what the play was, so we had to start it
over again,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton made them pay, hitting a running 10-footer off a
classic Utah pick-and-roll set with 9.3 seconds to play in overtime
that gave the Jazz a four-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Chicago's Toni Kukoc connected on a three-point shot with
5.1 seconds on the clock, trimming the Utah lead to a point,
Stockton made a pair of free throws to push it back to three.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, without a timeout remaining to move the ball to
halfcourt, had to go the length of the floor with a pass that
Jordan tipped to Luc Longley. He shoveled it to Pippen, who got a
three-point attempt off at the final buzzer. But the shot was long.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton said the 10-day layoff probably had a negative effect
on the Jazz .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a long time to sit there and wonder and think about
the series when last year we were just thrust into it,'' he said.
``Sometimes thinking too much can hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz almost let the game slip away after leading by eight at
the start of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With a make-shift Chicago lineup of Kukoc, Dennis Rodman, Steve
Kerr, Scott Burrell and Jud Buechler on the court, the Jazz went
cold. After Bryon Russell hit a leaning 16-footer early in the
final quarter, the Jazz went 5:17 without scoring, turning over the
ball four times and missing six straight shots. The Bulls chipped
away, and when Jordan returned he briefly took over. He hit a
17-foot jumper with 3:47 to go in regulation to cut the Jazz lead
to five, then following it with a 19-foot jumper. When Pippen hit a
three-pointer with 2:34 to go, the score was tied.
</P>
<P>
   But Chicago could never seize the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Malone finally came alive at that moment, hitting back-to-back
jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still going to go to Karl Malone,'' said Utah Coach
Jerry Sloan. ``We're not going to quit going to him in those
situations. He missed a couple. That's part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls got a pair of free throws from Pippen, then a driving
shot from Longley off Jordan's assist with 14 seconds to go in
regulation that tied the score. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
