<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3423 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-JOHNSON-AZ     06-04 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-JOHNSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CARD JOHNSON HAS CANCER  
 GIANTS DOCTORS DIS COVER TREATABLE CHEST TUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Born into a rodeo family in Haskell, Okla., a town so small that
it has just one store, LeShon Johnson never had anything handed to
him except a good pair of work gloves.
</P>
<P>
   But he's now facing the biggest chore of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the former Cardinal running back who signed this spring
with the New York Giants, has lymphoma, the Giants announced
Wednesday. The 27-year-old Johnson and his doctors should decide
this week how to treat the cancer, which was discovered after a
routine chest X-ray revealed a tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctors tell me we have a good chance to cure this,'' said
Johnson in a statement released by the Giants. ``My family and I
believe that with the help of the doctors and with the strength of
our faith in God, we will get through this, and I will be back on
the field in 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   That's questionable, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of us are thinking that's a priority,'' said
Giants Coach Jim Fassel, the Cardinals' offensive coordinator in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson experienced no symptoms and participated fully in a
minicamp last month, Fassel said. The Giants required players to
have chest X-rays as part of their physicals before the minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   A mass was found in Johnson's chest, and tests later confirmed
the cancer, which is believed to be non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prognosis for these types of tumors is good,'' team
internist Allan Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had a similar X-ray taken last spring while with the
Cardinals, and it showed no abnormalities. The medical staffs from
the two teams have been in contact for several weeks, and the
Cardinals have forwarded Johnson's medical records to the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prayers are with he and his family,'' said Bob Ferguson,
Cardinals vice president for player personnel. ``He's faced
challenges all his life, and I'm sure he'll do everything possible
to overcome this.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who married just a few weeks ago, played with the
Cardinals in 1996 and 1997 after being released by the Green Bay
Packers. In 1996, he set a Cardinals record by rushing for 214
yards in a victory over New Orleans. He scored on consecutive runs
of 56 and 70 yards.
</P>
<P>
   He had a 66-yard run the following week but eventually lost his
starting job. Last season, he rushed only 23 times for 81 yards and
signed with the Giants this spring as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who is deeply religious, was popular with his Cardinals
teammates. He was shy and humble, and teammates teased him about
his love of country music, bull riding and the large pickup truck
he drove.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson started riding bulls when he was 8 and later became an
accomplished football player. After two years at Northeastern
Oklahoma A&AMP;M Junior College, he transferred to Northern Illinois,
where he led the nation in rushing his senior year, gaining 1,976
yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers drafted Johnson in the third round in 1994, and he
suffered a torn anterior cruciate ligament at the end of that
season. Green Bay waived him the following season.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1996 season, Johnson underwent excimer laser surgery
on both eyes, which improved his vision immensely. His running
style, however, never changed. At 207 pounds, Johnson isn't big by
NFL standards, but he preferred to run over people rather than
elude them.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has yet to prove he can be successful with that style,
but he would like another chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``LeShon asked the doctor many times (about playing in 1998),''
Fassel said, ``and the doctor said, `we'll talk about that when we
lay out a whole scenario of what we are going to do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had missed the last three days of the Giants' voluntary
practice, and Fassel told the team Wednesday of Johnson's illness.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kent Graham, who like Johnson moved from the
Cardinals to the Giants this spring, has known about Johnson's
condition for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got everybody upset,'' he said, ``but it's encouraging
because it's the type that can be treated.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
