u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-ECKERSLEY-     06-04 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ECKERSLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORE SHOULDER CONCERNS ECKERSLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Red Sox reliever Dennis Eckersley, who pitched two
innings Sunday for only the second time in his last 120 appearances
dating to the start of the 1996 season, was unable to pitch
Wednesday night because of discomfort in the back of his right
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley was clearly worried after the game. ``I got hot, ready
to go,'' he said, referring to his warm-ups in the bullpen, when he
was preparing to pitch the seventh inning against the Orioles.
``But then I felt (discomfort). I just didn't find it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley said he first felt discomfort Monday morning, the day
after he went two innings against the Yankees. Eckersley, who
averaged 15 pitches an appearance last season as the Cardinals'
closer, threw 26 pitches against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   That's a total he's exceeded only four times in the last three
years, including a 35-pitch outing against the Indians April 18,
the most pitches he has thrown in that span.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just have to see how it feels tomorrow,'' said Eckersley,
who had been pitching better of late, going un-scored upon in six
of his last eight appearances, though he has seldom been used in
critical situations.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Jim Corsi, his close friend, said Eckersley's shoulder
had felt better when he played catch the last couple of days. What
concerns Corsi is the location of the discomfort, in the back of
Eck's shoulder. Eckersley plans to be examined Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
