</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-JOHNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ONE NIGHT, JOHNS A STANDOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He shares the locker room with Cal Ripken and Robbie
Alomar and others who regularly command attention from the
assembled media. Perhaps that's why Baltimore Orioles lefthander
Doug Johns, who began last season pitching in Italy, seemed
perplexed to see reporters in front of him Wednesday night _
despite the fact that he held the Red Sox hitless for five innings
and wound up allowing just four hits in 7 1/3 innings of a 3-0
victory Wednesday night at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The journeyman pitched like an All-Star against one of the
American League's best hitting clubs, striking out four and walking
one, as he raised his record to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Three of his strikeouts came in the first four innings. He got
Mo Vaughn swinging in the second and Darren Lewis and John Valentin
looking in the fourth; Valentin was then ejected after arguing
balls and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug Johns pitched a great game against a very tough lineup,''
said Orioles manager Ray Miller. ``He got (Nomar) Garciaparra out
with two pitches the first two times up. That's pitching, because
even if you give up a hit, at least the guy hasn't seen your whole
arsenal the first time up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox saw much of Johns's arsenal Wednesday night and were
unable to counter until Damon Buford singled to left to open the
sixth. But Johns didn't falter. He got Lou Merloni to force Buford
at second, then retired Jason Varitek on a fly and Lewis on a
grounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going at them, and fortunately, we got them to hit the
ball where we had guys who made great plays,'' said Johns. ``The
game was close and I just tried to keep guys off base. With this
ballpark, one bad pitch and it can be a close game.''
</P>
<P>
   Johns, 31, was signed by the Orioles as a free agent last June
30 and was assigned to Triple A after being released by the Kansas
City Royals. He had signed a minor league contract with Kansas City
after playing in Parma, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over there for a couple of weeks and had a great
time,'' he said. ``(Baseball) is definitely not as big there as it
is here. I went with a team that played in the European Cup in
Holland. I never actually played with a team in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had always been a one-dimensional pitcher, right over the
top,'' said Miller. ``He got righthanders out but he had trouble
with lefties. But (pitching coach) Mike Flanagan, being a Cy Young
winner, a great lefthanded pitcher, worked with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johns has had a most eventful career. After playing in the
minors from 1990-95, he got his first major league stint with
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   His major league debut came on July 8, 1995, when he started the
opener of a doubleheader against Toronto. He was ejected in the
fourth inning after throwing a pitch behind Toronto's John Olerud,
a retaliation after Oakland's Mark McGwire was hit on the helmet by
David Cone. For his show of solidarity, Johns was optioned to
Triple A Edmonton following the game.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night marked Johns's fourth start since he came off
the disabled list, where he had been placed with insomnia, of all
things. He began his Orioles career with a start against Anaheim
April 21 but gave up three runs on seven hits in four innings and
was later moved to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he took the mound Wednesday night with a 2.08 earned run
average since being activated and continued his success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
