A3437 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-HERNANDEZ     06-04 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-HERNANDEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ ELEVATES YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Another poignant scene from the inevitable ``El
Duque'' Hernandez TV movie was staged here Wednesday night: The
Cuban defector doffed his cap for the American national anthem,
then puzzled the Tampa Bay Devil Rays with a Luis Tiant-like range
of deceptive deliveries in his major league debut.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez's life has been playing out in improbable acts
ever since he and seven others slammed into the Bahamas in a
20-foot boat over Christmas. Wednesday night he replaced David
Cone, who missed a turn because a Jack Russell terrier named
Veronica bit him on his pitching hand Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With Cuban flags fluttering from the Yankee Stadium upper deck
and fans chanting, ``El Duque'' and ``libertad,'' in the
right-field bleachers, Hernandez came out wearing No. 26 _ the
number he wore while pitching 10 seasons for Havana's famous
Industriales under the banner of Cuban Communism.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said he cried while warming up in the bullpen. Then he
was all high leg kicks and multiple arm angles, allowing five hits
and striking out seven in seven uneventful innings of a 7-1 Yankee
win. Fred McGriff bombed a high sidearm fastball over the
right-field fence in the fourth, but for the most part, El Duque _
28 going on 32 _ was scarcely nicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I be nervous?'' he said earlier in the day while
munching room-service pasta at the Hilton in Fort Lee, N.J. ``I've
pitched when it was packed at Estadio Latinoamericano'' in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I wasn't nervous,'' he said afterward. ``But I realized
the responsibility I had, taking the place of David Cone.''
</P>
<P>
   Five months ago, Hernandez, the older half-brother of Marlins
righthander Livan Hernandez, was banned from Cuban baseball and
living in the back of his in-laws' sweltering cinder-block home. He
played third base and managed a neighborhood team that played
before a scattering of cows at Lenin Park. He earned $8.75 a month
as a physical therapist at Havana Psychiatric Hospital. After
landing in the Bahamas, he took up residency in Costa Rica, signed
a $6.6 million contract with the Yankees, went 6-0 with Triple A
Columbus, then ascended to the major leagues two months ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   His arrival here was terrible news for the Red Sox and the rest
of the American League East. Among other things, it demonstrated
the strength of a Yankee rotation whose weakest link is currently
Andy Pettitte. The Yanks are so deep that Joe Torre announced
before the game that he was planning to send El Duque back to
Columbus immediately regardless of how he pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``His future is tonight,'' said Torre. Later, though, the
manager gave himself some wiggle room in case he got a call from
George Steinbrenner, who watched the game from Tampa. ``I don't
anticipate he'll start here in five days,'' said Torre. ``But if
somebody else wants to make the call, I'll write his name in.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Havana, which lives under a perpetual news
blackout, there was no mention Wednesday of Hernandez's debut in
Granma, the Communist Party newspaper. The country was abuzz
nonetheless, according to people who spoke by phone, as word
traveled across the Florida straits via Miami radio and the vast
Cuban exile community in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he was supposed to start a day earlier, but they put
it off,'' said Ricardo Calderon, 52, sitting in Havana's Central
Park, where dozens of men gather each day to argue about baseball.
Chino Rodriguez pulled out a weathered Miami Herald clipping of El
Duque donning his Yankee togs for the first time. ``This is a big
moment for all Cubans,'' he said. ``These are the New York
Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven people who set off with Hernandez from Cuba's
northern coast, five remain in Costa Rica. Alberto Hernandez, the
former star catcher, is working in an auto repair shop along with
El Duque's cousin, Joel Pedroso. The boat captain and his wife had
a falling out with Hernandez and are living somewhere in the
capital. Osmany Lorenzo, El Duque's best friend, is working as a
bartender.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez used to get around Havana hitching rides in Lorenzo's
beat-up Lada sedan, and the two lived off Lorenzo's mastery of the
black market.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in San Jose, Lorenzo said of El Duque, ``After so much
work, after so much pain, he's finally living his dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
