<HEADER>
A3439 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-BOS &LR;      06-04 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ HAVE A LITTLE BIT EXTRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SALT LAKE CITY _ The Utah Jazz took the first step Wednesday
night in a once futile but now apparently viable effort to dethrone
Michael Jordan's Bulls. They almost slipped.
</P>
<P>
   They blew a couple of late leads in regulation. They got a
nightmarish shooting game from their leading scorer. But they
nevertheless survived in overtime, taking a tense 88-85 victory in
Game 1 of the best-of-seven NBA Finals before a jubilant crowd at
the Delta Center. Game 2 is here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Utah has won 11 of 12 playoff games since falling behind the
Rockets, 2-1, in the first round. The Bulls, meanwhile, dropped
their fourth consecutive road playoff game, having gone 0-3 in
Indiana in the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, which beat Utah in six games last year for its second
straight NBA title and fifth in seven years, got 33 points from
Jordan, but he hoisted 29 shots to get them. He also was whistled
for a costly 24-second violation in overtime when he clearly had
lost track of the shot clock. ``It was a mental thing and I never
really noticed the clock and no one noticed the clock,'' Jordan
said. ``We made a lot of mental mistakes down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen added 21 points but was long on a 3-pointer that
would have forced a second overtime. The Bulls left the building
feeling they let one slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't ask for a better opportunity,'' said coach Phil
Jackson. ``We had our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Jordan, ``When you're on the road and have a chance to
win, that's all you want. But we never capitalized.''
</P>
<P>
   No, they didn't. They didn't make the plays when the plays
needed to be made, which they usually do. This time Utah did. The
estimable John Stockton led the Jazz with 24 and bailed them out in
OT, scoring 7 of Utah's 9 points and assisting on the other 2. Karl
Malone was 9 for 25, made only two jump shots all night, and said,
``I didn't have a good rhythm.'' He sure didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was rusty. The Jazz had not played in 10 days, and that
was one of many subplots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten days is a very long time,'' Stockton said. ``I'm not
claiming I was rusty or anyone else was, but it's a long time to
sit back and think about the next series. Sometimes thinking too
much can hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Another subplot was Dennis Rodman's sore right thumb, which was
taped and clearly bothered him. He still collected 10 rebounds in
40 minutes and made some key defensive plays. ``I thought Dennis
played exceptionally well, given his situation,'' said Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The Utah bench, an undeniable strength, came through again,
outscoring Chicago's reserves, 22-8.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had trouble on offense, as evidenced by the 79-79
score at the end of regulation. (Good defense was there, too, but
so were a lot of missed open shots.) Many of Malone's misses were
shots he routinely makes and likely will make in Game 2 if he gets
the same looks. Jordan, who was 13 for 29, saw several spin out.
The Jazz, who led the NBA in field goal shooting, shot 45 percent.
The Bulls shot 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Utah was in control most of the night, although it never had a
lead larger than 8 points. (The Bulls' largest lead was 4 points,
and they never led after the first quarter.) The Jazz led by 7 with
4:28 left, only to see the Bulls rip off 7 straight points in 72
seconds, 4 by Jordan and a huge trey by Pippen. Utah led by 4 with
55.7 seconds left (after Malone's two jump shots) but saw that
disappear on two Pippen free throws and a Luc Longley lean-in with
14.3 seconds left, tying the game.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, on a pick-and-roll with Stockton, broke the ice in OT,
the first of 5 straight Utah points. The other 3 came from
Stockton, who took it coast to coast after a Pippen turnover and
was fouled. The freebie made it 84-79. The Bulls got within 2
(84-82) on 3 Jordan points (he missed a free throw in there), but
Stockton killed them again with a floater in the lane over Steve
Kerr with 9.3 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   End of game? Not quite. Toni Kukoc dropped a big 3 out of an
inbounds play to make it 86-85. Stockton was deliberately fouled
with 3.5 seconds left, making both shots. The Bulls, out of
timeouts, went for the post-pattern trey. Pippen got a look and a
shot, but it wasn't close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
