</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE OLD BIRDS ARE AN ENDANGERED SPECIES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They won 98 games and the American League East last
year, then padded their payroll to a historic $74 million, just to
make sure they'd do it again. They came into this season with more
veteran stars than the combined rosters of the Utah Jazz and
Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   And then they lost 25 of 35, including nine straight, to fall to
the bottom of baseball's Social Register Division _ a whopping 15
games behind the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   We got our first look at the Baltimore Orioles Wednesday night,
and they beat the Olde Towne Team, 3-0, on the strength of Doug
Johns's strong 7 1/3 innings of four-hit ball. A 31-year-old
journeyman lefthander, Johns has been on the disabled list with
insomnia. Oriole coach Mike Flanagan said they got him out of it by
pitching him in Yankee Stadium (``the city that never sleeps'') and
the Kingdome (``Sleepless in Seattle''). It must have worked.
</P>
<P>
   Shutout pitching is not what we expected from the reeling O's.
We expected to see Robbie Alomar and Brady Anderson dogging it,
refusing to run out ground balls. We expected to see a clubhouse of
guys demanding to be traded and/or calling their bankers on cell
phones.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Orioles looked very much like most teams that come
through here, only older. With such notables as Cal Ripken, Harold
Baines, Joe Carter, B.J. Surhoff, Rafael Palmeiro, and Jesse
Orosco, the Oriole lineup some days resembles a Supreme Court team
photo.
</P>
<P>
   They are scuffling. But they know it's folly to hang their heads
over a bad start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all right,'' said Anderson (.182). ``I have an idea
what's been going on. I've been told we're not in first place. The
Red Sox are in a better position than we are. They've earned it and
outplayed us all year long. But it hasn't been my experience that
panicking helps.''
</P>
<P>
   To a man, the Orioles offer injuries as the primary excuse for
their early-season swoon. It's partially legit. At this hour, three
of Baltimore's top four starters (ace Mike Mussina, Jimmy Key, and
Scott Kamieniecki) are on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Putting three starters on the shelf has wreaked havoc with
Baltimore's bullpen, and manager Ray Miller has been forced to use
a lot of rookies and Triple A talents. It hasn't been pretty. Going
into Wednesday night's game, the Baltimore staff ERA was 5.22.
</P>
<P>
   There's been some bad luck involved. Mussina's two trips to the
disabled list were caused by (1) a wart on his finger, and (2) a
line drive to the face. He's supposed to come back Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Down but not done, the Orioles object to the notion that they've
given up. Things got particularly ugly when they were swept in New
York and Anderson and Alomar made video highlights by failing to
run out ground balls. It looked like Miller was losing control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take care of that stuff, but I do it behind closed doors,''
said Miller. ``When things go bad, every little thing gets pointed
out, but the fans at home have been good to me and good to the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, the Yankees have played great, but take (Andy) Pettitte,
(Hideki) Irabu, and Bernie Williams out of their lineup for a month
and see how (expletive) good they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles are 28-30, 14 1/2 games behind the Yankees and six
behind the Red Sox in the hunt for the wild-card spot. They have
104 games remaining. And they are still working. There were no less
than 16 Orioles on the field Wednesday at 2:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work through this,'' said Ripken, who played in his
2,536th consecutive game. ``Every team goes through a time like
this in their season. We have talent on this club. The ability to
hit and play is all there. It's a matter of getting through it.
There's still two-thirds of a season left. Let's play it and see
what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Jimy Williams, Bret Saberhagen, and several of the Red
Sox, Ripken acknowledges the existence of the wild card.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not just one chance anymore,'' he said. ``Obviously,
the wild card is extra incentive. It keeps you optimistic. There's
two shots you can play for instead of one.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the beleaguered manager, looked around the room and
said, ``I wouldn't give up on us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
