A3453 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANDY-JOHNSON-SPI     06-04 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANDY-JOHNSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE FANS GREET JOHNSON WITH WARM RECEPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ There was a sense of relief Wednesday night among many
Mariner fans that Randy Johnson wasn't traded to the Los Angeles
Dodgers or any other team in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   A banner next to the bullpen mound summed up their sentiments:
``Welcome home Big Unit.'' Ushers removed the sign during the first
inning, and it never reappeared.
</P>
<P>
   But some fans believe that trading Johnson is the only way the
M's can pick up some relief pitching before the season gets away
from the defending AL West champions. And they wonder if Johnson
will pitch with the same heart and dedication for the Mariners if
he remains unhappy over his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not happy, then he should go,'' said Stacey Wilson of
Vancouver, Wash. ``If he's not happy, he's not going to play hard
for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, Stacey Mohagen, admitted that she felt the same, but
would support Johnson as long as he continues to pitch in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not right to be booed when you're forced to stay where
you're at,'' she said. ``You can't be upset with him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson noted that Johnson still makes $6 million playing in
Seattle this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's almost over the hill, so why pay millions of dollars for
him?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Season-ticket holder Mike Gallagher said he wasn't impressed by
Johnson's last two outings, in which Johnson picked up two wins _
and 25 strikeouts _ over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason he's pitching good is because he sees his
value going down,'' Gallagher said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Johnson was met with a polite ovation from the crowd
of 24,944 when he walked to the bullpen mound Wednesday night to
begin his warmups and then again when he was announced as the
starting pitcher. However, it was a far cry from the standing
ovation he received when taking the mound on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   For the players, having M's president Chuck Armstrong announce
that Johnson was no longer on the trading block brought a sense of
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could turn into something positive, really spur him on and
really inspire him,'' catcher Dan Wilson said. ``That's what we're
hoping for. There's been a lot on his mind, that's for sure, but
now there's a little bit of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Backup catcher John Marzano heard the news Tuesday just before
he sat down for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like I could finally eat my meal in peace,'' Marzano
said. ``You don't want to get rid of a guy like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson entered Wednesday night's game 13-5 against Anaheim in
23 career starts with a 2.69 ERA. He was 10-1 against the Angels
since June 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet I was hoping not to see him,'' said Angels manager
Terry Collins. ``I was hoping big time for a trade. But I told
everybody (in Anaheim) that we'll see him. Even if there was going
to be a trade, they would let him pitch against us one more time.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was the best news for season-ticket holders Jan and
Dick Kochel of Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy he's still here, because I think he can still
win,'' Dick Kochel said. ``I actually think we need him to stay
around to have a shot at the pennant. Everybody else is getting the
big bucks, why shouldn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   His wife added: ``I feel very loyal to the team and we give a
lot to the team by attending and supporting them every way we can.
I would love for him to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the ace of the starting rotation appears to be staying
with the club at least for the short term, Wilson and other players
said they hoped all the talk would turn to how the Mariners can get
back in the pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is important and every game is important now,''
Wilson said. ``We're in a position where we can catch the No. 1 and
2 teams in our division, and even though we haven't played the way
we wanted, we're not way out of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
