<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEDEVIL JOHNSON'S RETURN TO KINDOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners ushered in a new era Wednesday night _
Big Unit, A.D.
</P>
<P>
   Almost Dodger. After Dangling. Alone and be damned.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson made his reluctant return to the Kingdome after a
week of twisting in the trade winds, and it wasn't a happy
homecoming. He got beat by the Anaheim Angels 8-1, extending
Seattle's losing streak to three and causing a seemingly lost
season to dim a little more.
</P>
<P>
   Taking full advantage of all the hurt feelings, longtime Mariner
nemisis Chuck Finley posted his 17th career victory over Seattle in
24 outings, and Damon Mashore drove in the deciding run with a
seventh-inning home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do much,'' Mariner manager Lou Piniella said,
amazingly keeping his composure during difficult times. ``We need
to start winning ballgames. That's how you get momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange and uncomfortable setting, one witnessed by
24,944 fans. People half-heartedly applauded when Johnson's name
was announced on the public-address system a half-hour before game
time. They clapped tepidly when he walked to the bullpen to warm
up. They finally raised their level of appreciation a level higher
when he trudged to the dugout and his name was splashed on the
stadium big screen. Didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (5-4) went about his business in a cold, detached
manner, first setting down some stern ground rules. There would be
no eye contact with anything but the catcher's mitt. No exultant
gestures. No interviews the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   For six innings, his displeasure didn't show. The 6-foot-10
lefty locked himself in a terrific duel with Finley (6-2), each
pitcher permitting one run and five hits. Then it all came apart
like a moth-eaten sweater.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner ace crumbled in the seventh inning, serving up five
runs. The first came on the long ball by the light-hitting Mashore
leading off, one soaring out over the left field fence. It was
Mashore's second homer of the season. A one-out double was followed
by a hit batter, a walk, a run-scoring grounder and two singles.
Johnson was done.
</P>
<P>
   Before facing his last batter, the tallest and unhappiest
Mariner turned toward his dugout, as if asking out of this mess.
The last time he did something like that, in 1991, his manager
called him a quitter. Once relieved of his duties on this night, he
left the field with stoic look and a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella offered an explanation for all of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stiffened up in the seventh inning, but he gave us six good
innings,'' the manager said. ``It's nothing long-term. We started
to notice it in the sixth.''
</P>
<P>
   Through his agent before the game, Johnson had asked reporters
to limit their questions to performance, not trade possibilities.
As the game began, the Mariners announced that the pitcher
ultimately had decided not to deal with reporters for the remainder
of the season. He was dressed and gone when the media was allowed
in the clubhouse 10 minutes after the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, according to a witness, let his temper go and started
throwing things in the tunnel outside the dugout after leaving the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Before his mound meltdown, Johnson was efficient, more cutting
than overpowering. He got big outs when he needed them. Outs by
other means than his old standby, the strikeout. He finished with
five K's.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson allowed a lone run in the second inning when the Angels'
Justin Baughman bounced a no-out, infield hit to shortstop with the
bases loaded. Alex Rodriguez could only wait for the high hopper to
settle in his glove and fake a throw to first as Anaheim's Craig
Shipley crossed the plate. Johnson showed great resilience by
retiring the next three hitters and moving on.
</P>
<P>
   For five innings, Finley was even better. He raced through the
Mariner lineup twice, allowing just two harmless doubles by Edgar
Martinez in the fourth and Joey Cora in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners finally got something going against the Anaheim
pitcher in the sixth inning. David Segui singled up the middle and
Martinez followed with another double, slicing one off the right
field wall. Glenallen Hill's groundout plated Segui with the tying
run.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, however, struck out Cora with the bases loaded to end
the inning and send the Angels to their fourth consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have much to sort out. Players say they're trying
to get the clubhouse in order after the carnival atmosphere caused
by the Johnson dealings, or lack of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you dwell on the past and think of negative things, you're
going to go out and play poorly,'' reliever Paul Spoljaric said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has matched his loss total for 1997, will make his
next start Monday night in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
