<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS WANT TO TRIM COACH CANDIDATE LIST TO TWO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The man who barreled past Sonics president Wally
Walker on a street corner here knew the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, will you take my application?'' teased the man, obviously
a friend of Walker's. ``Betcha got a lot of those.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Walker jokingly replied, ``they're piling up.''
</P>
<P>
   But which pile are the applications falling into when it comes
to the Sonics' vacant head-coaching job? Although the predraft camp
here is a haven for just about every NBA coach and general manager,
it probably isn't where Walker will find George Karl's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   There are several plausible candidates on hand at the Moody
Bible Institute's Solheim Center, site of the predraft camp. Sonics
assistant coach Bob Weiss is here. So is Charlotte assistant Paul
Silas.
</P>
<P>
   However, one guy who is not present appears to be at the top of
Walker's list. Although Walker will not discuss individual
candidates, former Phoenix Suns coach Paul Westphal is considered
the frontrunner by two sources close to the situation.
</P>
<P>
   There are only six candidates Walker will consider: Westphal,
Silas, Weiss, former Indiana Pacers and San Antonio Spurs coach Bob
Hill, Chicago's Phil Jackson and apparently one other hopeful whose
name Walker will not disclose.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, though, is attempting to narrow his search to two in a
week. A new coach could be named as soon as 10 days from now.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal is definitely on the short list because Walker is
impressed by his success with the Suns. The next-strongest aspirant
could be Silas or Weiss, depending on how their interviews go.
</P>
<P>
   Silas is scheduled to formally meet with Walker Thursday. Weiss
will have his time a few days after.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, in the meantime, is gathering information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a casual background-checking mode,'' said Walker, who
is being approached by scores of advocates for certain hopefuls.
``A friend will say you should consider _ fill in the name _ for
these reasons. A lot of (information) I'm getting from people I
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Do not underestimate Walker's predetermined analysis of certain
candidates. Westphal's name has been thrown around the most since
Karl's ouster. The reasons are so viable that Westphal, a one-time
Sonics player, probably will be the last to interview late next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Westphal take the Suns to the 1993 NBA Finals, but
he also achieved success with a volatile superstar in Charles
Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Walker is looking to create a similar tonic in
Seattle. Appearances aside, Karl struggled at times with All-Star
guard Gary Payton's persona and sometimes poor leadership last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inexact part of (finding the next coach) is trying to find
the right guy who fits our team,'' Walker said. ``I'm still more
inclined to someone with experience. We're going to have a
contending team.''
</P>
<P>
   There are indications that the Sonics' next coach will come from
the free-agent pool. That all but eliminates Atlanta's Lenny
Wilkens from the mix. The perception is that Atlanta and Wilkens
were working on an amicable separation. Speculation is that Wilkens
would love to coach the Sonics again _ especially since he is
beloved by Seattle where he maintains a home.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilkens has several years left on his Atlanta contract and
needs permission from the Hawks to pursue other jobs. Atlanta
general manager Pete Babcock said he's heard the rumors _ but
nothing from Wilkens' mouth _ about the NBA's winningest coach
wanting to leave for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never said anything to me,'' Babcock said. ``Lenny and I
sat down just three days ago and talked about where we need to go
with the team. We made a commitment to him, and he made a
commitment to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker didn't totally rule out a Wilkens candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't asked permission of anybody yet,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Hill, who some feel is being hurt by his public
campaigning for the job, Jackson is perhaps the other longshot. The
Sonics are said to only be willing to wait on Jackson if he
indicates interest in the job. Otherwise, the Sonics would have to
wait until his Bulls contract expires July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who remains coy about the search, said finding a new
coach should not be a long process. He set a light deadline of
filling the vacancy by the June 24 NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   The target date seems to be the best thing going in Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
