<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME 1 MAKES UP IN DRAMA WHAT IS LOST IN AGED PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ As one of the more eagerly anticipated NBA
Finals _ step right up, kiddies, getcher last look at The Man
before he ascends to Valhalla _ Game 1 between the Utah Jazz and
Chicago Bulls was something less than divas with orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was more of a Middle-Aged-Man Festival, sponsored by
Rogaine and Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Even the pregame dialogue was less than compelling, both teams
scrambling for the low ground, desperate to be cast as underdogs to
accrue the mythical advantages of the trite us-against-the-world
dogma.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent contest rarely emerged from that rhetorical
basement. Rims took a heavy pounding from the brutal shotmaking,
defense was spotty, and aside from a couple episodes of
incandescence from Michael Jordan, the game was smeared with too
many moments of Clipper training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite all this desultory bang-and-clang, the Jazz and
Bulls never lacked for hand-wringing drama. After more than three
hours of inelegance, with no lead greater than eight points, the
Jazz won 87-85 in overtime, leaving the impression they might be
ready for another 10 days' rest before Game 2. (Certainly, anyone
in attendance at Delta Center who had ears is ready for several
days off, unless the NBA invokes a ban on contrived pregame audio
assaults.)
</P>
<P>
   You might have read that the comparative issue advancing this
championship rematch was the Jazz's rust versus the Bulls' lack of
rest. Turns out there was no competition between the liabilities _
both were overwhelming enough to smother the game.
</P>
<P>
   So it was a question of whose poor play would be less
consequential. The Jazz answered positively and perhaps in more
decisive ways than the game-long tautness of the score.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions came from so many directions that the Jazz
established they do indeed have the overall personnel advantage. In
particular, the Jazz reserves outscored their Chicago counterparts
22-8, with all but Antoine Carr hitting at least half their shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bench played really, really well,'' gushed Karl Malone,
whose poor shooting night made assistance mandatory. ``In the past
when I had a bad game, we lost. But we've matured. We still managed
to win, and it's really neat to see.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that was one of several points in the game that were
reverse images of what these teams had done in the past. The
dramatics of the fourth quarter and overtime were usually where the
Bulls excelled, and the multiple lineup combinations had been a
Chicago staple.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was the Jazz who had more smart guys doing the right
things more often, even if shots weren't falling.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most telltale sign of Bulls' vulnerability came in
the second quarter, when Chicago rested Jordan and trotted out
seldom-used reserves Dickey Simpkins, Randy Brown, Jud Buechler and
Steve Kerr in a bizarre lineup that veteran Bull-watchers swear
they had never seen.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup didn't exactly fail them, but it didn't allow any
exploitation of poor Jazz play. It also accentuated the absences of
two big forwards from the 1997 Finals, Brian Williams and Jason
Caffey, whose contributions weren't replaced this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some guys on the court who weren't particularly
comfortable from an offensive standpoint,'' said Scottie Pippen.
``They do a good job in practice moving the ball. But tonight they
didn't feel confident taking the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson, the sage of the bench who is nearing his personal
free agency, picked an odd time to conduct what he admitted was an
experiment with the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lineup I wanted to test,'' he said. ``It's early in the
series. You've got to figure out what's going to work. We're
willing to take some experimental time with it.''
</P>
<P>
   December against Denver is when most teams experiment. Trying it
in June is a fine way to end a dynasty. But it was no less a
stunner than when the Bulls, trailing 84-82 inside the final 30
seconds of overtime, committed a 24-second violation with Jordan as
the ball-holding culprit.
</P>
<P>
   This mistake was Michelangelo straying outside the lines on
paint by numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mental lapse,'' Jordan said. ``Scottie got confused
in terms of what the play was, so we had to start it back over
again. I never really noticed the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of mental mistakes down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   For the defending champs, it was hardly a characteristic game.
As Sonic fans can recall from the Laker series, the results of the
opener in a best-of-seven series are often indicative of little.
Or, in the lexicon of Gary Payton, ``It don't mean nothin'.''
</P>
<P>
   But this one meant something.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've watched Chicago, they're the champs,'' said Malone.
``This is the kind of game they usually win _ one or two points
down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle-Aged-Man festivals rarely are pretty, but they are the
events in which champions excel.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
