<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-VACCINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHERN CALIFORNIA FIRM TO CONDUCT LARGE-SCALE TRIALS OF
AIDS  VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABIN RUSSELL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bankrolled by private investors, a Bay Area
biotechnology company will begin the world's first large-scale
trials of an AIDS vaccine this month.
</P>
<P>
   South San Francisco-based VaxGen Inc., headed by legendary AIDS
pioneer Dr. Donald Francis, said it has received clearance from the
Food and Drug Administration to test its AIDSVAX vaccine on 5,000
American volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   The company also plans to test its vaccine soon on 2,500
volunteers in Thailand. Results should come to light in two to four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wanting to see this happen for the last five years,
so I am delighted,'' said Dr. Marcus Conant, a prominent San
Francisco AIDS physician.
</P>
<P>
   Testing will begin in Chicago, Denver, Los Angeles, Philadelphia
and St. Louis, but not in New York and San Francisco _ centers of
the AIDS epidemic where skepticism of Francis' vaccine runs deep.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen years after the emergence of AIDS, the planned test of
VaxGen's vaccine is generating cautious hope. But there is also
widespread skepticism that the immunizations will work.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many researchers are uncomfortable with the ethical
dilemma posed by the vaccine trials. One out of three volunteers
vaccinated will get a placebo, conferring absolutely no protection
against the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   The only way researchers will know that the vaccine is working
is if a percentage of the placebo group abandons safe sex practices
and becomes infected, while a comparable group of vaccinated
subjects also takes risks but remains virus-free.
</P>
<P>
   There is additional fear that the promise of a vaccine could
induce even some of the general population to cast aside sexual
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is evident that (current AIDS vaccines) have not yielded
antibodies that neutralize most natural strains of HIV,'' said Dr.
David Baltimore, chairman of the AIDS Vaccine Research Committee,
in a January article in the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, backers of the vaccine see the decision to go
forward as an historic step in the battle against the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a watershed event in the AIDS crisis,'' said Dr. Seth
Berkley, president of the International AIDS Vaccine Initiative, a
New York organization advocating aggressive testing of AIDS
vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it can cost more than $30 million to conduct such
a large clinical trial _ money the National Institutes of Health
was not willing to gamble on the VaxGen approach.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 potential AIDS vaccines have been tested in humans, but
until now none has inspired enough confidence to attempt the costly
large-scale trials needed to prove the vaccine works.
</P>
<P>
   Francis said he had no trouble, however, lining up private
investors willing to take a chance this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money hasn't been a problem,'' he said during a phone
interview from New York.
</P>
<P>
   The VaxGen vaccine is a genetically engineered protein almost
identical to one found on the surface of the AIDS virus. In theory,
the vaccine trains white blood cells to produce antibodies that
recognize and attack the same protein, killing the virus.
</P>
<P>
   An early version of the vaccine was safely tested on 1,200
humans. A new version, which is made from proteins found on two
different strains of the virus, has been tested on 120 humans, and
this is the one that will be used in the large-scale trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's driven us,'' said Francis, ``is the success we have had
in chimpanzees.'' Early versions of the vaccine protected chimps
that were deliberately infected with the AIDS virus. Human subjects
nevertheless have produced more protective antibodies after
vaccination than the chimps.
</P>
<P>
   But as scientists piece together the AIDS puzzle, there is a
mounting consensus that antibodies alone are not sufficient to stop
the virus. A second defense system, consisting of blood cells
programmed to kill other cells infected by the virus, may be
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nonsense,'' counters Francis. ``We know this vaccine is
more than sufficient to induce protection.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first federal scientists to warn of the danger of
AIDS in the early 1980s, Francis has made his mark as a maverick
not afraid to speak his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Francis has earned an enviable track record in battling various
diseases including smallpox, the Ebola virus and Hepatitis B.
</P>
<P>
   He said it is only a matter of time before his vaccine is tested
in New York and San Francisco, and up to 40 clinics in North
America should be participating by the end of the year. San
Francisco AIDS doctor Conant said the tests will be valuable even
if the VaxGen vaccine proves a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how these trials come out, (they) will get very
important answers to basic questions,'' he said. ``The skepticism
that is out there is based on speculation, rather than
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the trial, subjects must be uninfected people at
high risk for AIDS because they have more than one sexual partner
within a year. Doctors will be required to reinforce the safe sex
message each time test subjects get one of four shots and receive
up to 14 follow-up evaluations over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the 2,500 Thai volunteers are drug addicts at high
risk for AIDS, who will be counseled on the dangers of sharing
needles. The participants will not be given the clean needles often
provided in Western countries, through programs like San
Francisco's needle exchange program.
</P>
<P>
   Francis said that failure to practice safe sex, whether in a
vaccine trial or not, is part of the cold reality of AIDS. ``If
people were following all the rules we made on safe activity, we
wouldn't need a vaccine,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
