</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS BLAST CLINTON FOR RENEWING TRADE STATUS WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ President Clinton renewed China's favored nation
trade status Wednesday on the eve of the Tiananmen Square
massacre's ninth anniversary, provoking harsh criticism from
members of his own party who scolded him for ignoring human rights
abuses.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Another anniversary present for the regime,'' said Rep. Nancy
Pelosi, D-Calif., one of the fiercest adversaries of the
administration's China policy.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi called on Clinton to cancel plans to pay a ceremonial
visit to the plaza in the heart of Beijing during his trip to China
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such an action by you, the leader of the free world, would
desecrate the memory of the brave individuals who lost their lives
fighting for democratic reforms,'' Pelosi wrote in an open letter
to the president that she circulated last night to other members of
Congress for their signatures.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she defended Clinton against Republican
accusations that the president compromised national security when
he approved a deal that gave Beijing access to sophisticated
satellite technology. The Republican complaints spring from
Clinton's decision to allow a Southern California company run by a
major Democratic Party donor to do business with the Chinese
government _ against the wishes of the Justice Department _ earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never pulled any punches regarding Clinton,'' she said
in an interview. ``But for the Republican leadership to ...
question the president's patriotism is so hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, who has opposed such deals based on China's record of
selling weapons to Pakistan and Iran, nonetheless rejected the
suggestion that a campaign contribution would have played a role in
the decision. She noted that GOP leaders have consistently
supported such deals in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were part of the decision every step of the way. They
have supported the Clinton policy year in and year out _ do they
think we have no memory?''
</P>
<P>
   Heated debate over U.S. policy toward China is expected all
month leading up to Clinton's nine-day trip starting June 25. He is
the first American president to visit China since the bloody 1989
Tiananmen Square crackdown on pro-democracy protesters.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has shown little willingness to confront the Chinese
government over human rights, trade or weapons proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   At a Rose Garden ceremony with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Clinton cited the need for close relations with Beijing
amid an escalating nuclear arms race between India and Pakistan as
one reason not to erect trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to renew (trade relations) would be to sever our economic,
and to a large measure, our strategic relationship with China,
turning our back on a fourth of the world at a time when our
cooperation for world peace and security is especially important in
light of the recent event in south Asia,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright will meet with leaders from five nuclear powers
Thursday in Geneva to discuss the escalating arms race between
India and Pakistan. Clinton said China's participation in the
Geneva meeting was evidence of ``constructive Chinese leadership''
that will be ``essential to the long-term resolution of issues
involving south Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual fight over China trade is expected to be more intense
than usual this year in light of the revelations surrounding the
satellite technology and investigations into illegal campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Clinton is required to notify Congress of his intention
to extend China's trade status 30 days before it expires July 3.
Congress has 60 days after the expiration to object to the
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the current circumstances make it a very (close)
vote,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., added his
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not reward the Chinese Communist government for its
continuing political repression and tyranny,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the prospects of Congress repealing the
president's decision _ and then overriding a likely veto _ appeared
doubtful. Three senior Republicans _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich of
Georgia, Rep. Bill Archer of Texas and Rep. Philip Crane of
Illinois, wrote Clinton that China's trade benefits deserve
support.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate is certain to expose the deeply divided
sentiments in Washington over how to handle relations with the
world's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   An unusual coalition of conservatives, including members of the
religious right such as Gary Bauer of the Family Research Council,
and liberals like Pelosi, are banding together to pressure Clinton
into standing up to his Chinese hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi mocked Clinton's assertion that China is needed to
resolve the arms race in south Asia, noting that ``China has
provided Pakistan with technology critical to its development and
recent testing of nuclear weapons. Without that assistance,
Pakistan would not have had such a developed nuclear weapons
program.''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter addressed to Clinton distributed to her colleagues
Wednesday, Pelosi urged the president while in China to:
</P>
<P>
   -- Call for the unconditional release of a significant number of
political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   -- Encourage a meaningful dialogue with the Dalai Lama, the
spiritual leader of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   -- Encourage the Chinese to allow workers to form free trade
unions.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, she expressed disbelief at Clinton's assertion
that China is taking significant steps toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of state of denial is he in?'' she asked. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
