<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3634 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-CO     06-04 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Tobacco lobby blows smoke
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, June 7, 1998.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say that if you can remember the day you quit smoking,
you're still a candidate to resume. I quit so many years ago that I
forgot when, which is a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a search through some old articles I had written, I
came across the one that announced my separation from smoking. It
was written in June 1983, so it means I quit 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't accidental that I was looking for that column. I was
trying to find it to see how much cigarettes cost when I quit
because I wanted to make a point about it.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, who still smokes -- ``Just two or three a day,'' she
unwisely rationalizes -- had asked me to pick up a pack of
cigarettes for her the other day. It was the first pack I had
purchased since I quit.
</P>
<P>
   When the clerk asked $2.55 of me, I was astonished. When I quit
my pack-a-day habit, cigarettes cost half that much. Had the price
held all the years of my abstinence, I figure I have saved more
than $7,000. (And, likely, my life, since I had been puffing away
since I was about 14 years old _ when a pack sold for 17 cents.)
</P>
<P>
   But the cost of cigarettes, abetted by so-called sin taxes, has
risen considerably so I must have saved in excess of $10,000. (I
think I spent it all on a trip to Europe last summer.)
</P>
<P>
   Between medical reports, lawsuits and even more sin taxes, the
cigarette industry has been under siege and, not surprisingly, has
developed a siege mentality. Despite the discovery of secret
methodology to trap youths into smoking, and other nefarious
methods to promote their industry, the cigarette people appear to
lack remorse for what they have inflicted upon this nation.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of heaping huge additional taxes onto cigarette sales
is to dissuade people from buying cigarettes. If you can't convince
them they are under medical risk in buying and smoking cigarettes,
then drive them away from them economically. Make cigarettes too
costly to buy.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the best idea because a kid wanting to smoke is going
to find a way to get that money, but it is a venture in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette industry, already riled by truth, is striking
back, purchasing ads that contend the government spends its tax
income unwisely, and thus we should oppose the new cigarette taxes
because it's just going to fill a bunch of pork barrels somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to that, the cigarette people are lobbying us that
impairing the cigarette industry is going to put a lot of good
people out of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the coca-growing nations of South America have used that
approach as well. Their logic: if the coca industry is wiped out,
lots of South American farmers are going to be hungry.
</P>
<P>
   I guess the same could be said of the people who worked for the
Nazi war machine. They would have stopped invading countries and
slaughtering people but it would have put a lot of good Nazis out
of work.
</P>
<P>
   My role in life is to not be a missionary against smoking; to
each his own. But keep it out of my face because I learned my
lesson 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What worries me, and gets me to writing about the subject, is
the way the lobby representing Big Tobacco is trying to defend
itself by attacking government in a clever campaign that is certain
to impress some very naive Americans, a component of this
population which, unfortunately, is quite numerous.
</P>
<P>
   If all the tax money garnered from cigarette sales went to
cancer research _ and why don't they do that? _ the tobacco people
still would find some other approach to blow smoke in your face.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
