A3635 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN07-COX     06-04 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Swiss must account for Nazi gold
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nazi gold, more than 50 years after World War II and the
Holocaust ended, remains molten. It burns the conscience.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reports that a pending U.S. government report
will show that some $300 million in looted gold _ $2.6 billion in
today's money _ was washed through Swiss banks and was used to buy
critical war materiel from such other neutrals as Turkey, Spain,
Sweden and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the gold was looted from the central banks of conquered
nations. Much was stolen from Jews _ personal effects, wedding
rings, even gold fillings mined from the teeth of Holocaust
cadavers. More than $40 million in current dollars from Jewish
victims was desposited in just one account. The account is believed
to represent only a fraction of the thefts.
</P>
<P>
   Most neutrals have fulfilled to some degree their postwar
obligation to repay looted gold. Sweden, which had an
understandable case for defensive neutrality, was unhesitating. The
Swiss still balk, although Switzerland's own study commission says
the Swiss National Bank knowingly accepted billions in stolen Nazi
gold.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss culpability is no longer at serious issue. Swiss honor and
justice very much are.
</P>
<P>
   A financial accounting is the necessary means to a moral
accounting. The commerce the Swiss so agreeably serviced, and
profited from so richly, prolonged the war and the Holocaust.
Germany was able, for instance, to buy from Spain and Portugal
virtually all of the minerals it needed to produce machine tools
and armaments _ especially, the U.S. report says, armor-piercing
shells.
</P>
<P>
   It is futile to try to calculate by how much the war was
lengthened, but even if it was for only a few hours _ and it was
surely for very much longer than that _ thousands died in the
delay. More, the gold let the Nazis set aside resources for their
death camps and still fund the military. Fungibility for the
business of extermination.
</P>
<P>
   If the Swiss and other benefiting neutrals did not know at the
time all the horrors of the war, nor exactly the extent of the
Holocaust, they did know these things, for they were univerally
known: Nazi Germany was devasting unoffending nations, it was
working slave laborers to death and it was rounding up Jews with an
anti-Semitic fervor that could promise nothing better than a
wretched end, whatever that might be.
</P>
<P>
   Those would seem to be reasons enough _ wouldn't they? _ to
manage neutrality, not as a career opportunity, but with a
reluctance informed by revulsion. Instead, more often the Nazi gold
bought not just goods but souls.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it seems now that all this was a long time ago, but history
will be eternally downwind from the Holocaust and the other horrors
of that war, and the moral debris does not lessen but grows as
recent scholarship teaches us how often the Nazis backed off from
the righteous few who stood against the demands of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   In its time, Nazi gold tempted and persuaded. But history has
been, if you will, a kind of counter-alchemist. It has turned Nazi
gold into dross and has left the taint of base metal on the hands
it passed through.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
