 NEWS &AMP; FEATURES SUMMARY No 2452 - JUNE 4, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. JAMAICA'S SOCCER MIRACLE: THE LITTLE ISLAND THAT ROARED Until
only three years ago, soccer was barely known in Jamaica, played
mainly on dirt roads and gravel-covered squares in the poor
island's slums. Then came ``The Miracle.'' Rene Simoes, a Brazilian
coach with only a mixed record of success, took over the national
team. He scoured the island for talent, turned a grab-bag of
skilled but undisciplined players into a united team, and imbued
the entire island with a new spirit of optimism and belief in
itself. When Jamaica qualified for this summer's World Cup, it
became the least populous country to do so since World War II. From
Der Spiegel. 1,000 words. (English translation available.)
________________________________________________________________ 2.
THE INTERNATIONAL COMMUNITY CAN'T IGNORE THE CONTEMPT
</P>
<P>
   SHOWN BY INDIA AND PAKISTAN The recent nuclear tests in the
South Asian subcontinent have shaken the international community.
Their consequences are much more than just the start of a regional
nuclear-arms race. By Mikhail Gorbachev. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
HUMANKIND BATTLES FOR SCRABBLE SUPREMACY Sure, Deep Blue trounced
the world chess champion. But when it comes to a word game, two
hyperlexical men can outthink a computer, can't they? By John
Tierney. The New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
DON'T REPEAT BOSNIA, PRESS ON MILOSEVIC There are some eerie
similarities in the way Europe and the U.S. are reacting to
hostilities in Kosovo and the way they dithered as Bosnia was left
to stumble into a long, ferocious war. If NATO wants to avoid
repeating the tragic Bosnia story, members should do what they can
to help the new Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic send Slobodan
Milosevic packing. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
________________________________________________________ 5.
HIGH-TECH GHOST SHIP : AN UNMANNED BOAT PREPARES
</P>
<P>
   TO SAIL ITSELF AROUND THE WORLD A German-built sailboat is about
to set off on a remarkable voyage. Its planned route around the
world is daring enough. What is new, however, is that the ``crew''
will remain behind in Germany. The ``Relationship,'' designed by
eight professors, will be controlled by a computer that will raise
and lower sails, turn the rudder, and set its own course. Back in
Germany, ``mission control'' will keep an eye on things, thanks to
onboard video cameras and a satellite hookup, and interfere only in
case of emergency. The magnificent experiment begins with a
stopover at the World's Fair in Lisbon. Der Spiegel. 800 words.
(English translation available.) 6. DEMOCRACY : IS IT FOR EVERYONE?
The prestigious Council on Foreign Relations is offering this
important commentary on late 20th-century democracy as part of our
monthly World Leaders Forum. It is also available as a ``separate
buy.'' By Samuel P. Huntington. Council on Foreign Relations. 1,800
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
From PROSPECT (Not available in the U.K.)
</P>
<P>
   A. DEBATE : GOD AND SCIENCE : What are the odds in favour of the
existence of an ultimate creator? By Nicholas Beale and Colin
Howson. (Nicholas Beale is an adviser to the Church of England on
science and medicine. Colin Howson is professor of logic and
scientific method at the London School of Economics.) 4,000 words.
B. THE MISSING CHILDREN : Where on earth, in the history of the
novel, have all the children gone? Robert Winder wonders why great
literature, which is supposed to address universal truths, ignores
children, parenthood and family life. But this may be changing.
Writers no longer consider it beneath them to write about
parenthood. 4,000 words. C. THE BATTLE OF KOSOVO : Contrary to
popular belief, the conflict between Serbs and Albanians is not an
expression of ancient ethnic and religious hatreds. By Noel
Malcolm. 3,000 words. D. EUGENE DELACROIX : Two hundred years after
his birth, for what should we remember the French painter
Delacroix? By John Armstrong. 4,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
WHEN IT COMES TO EXERCISE : BETTER LATE THAN NEVER Researchers have
found that regular light-to-moderate activity has substantial
health benefits for older people, even those who have not been
exercising in the past. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News
Service. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
SUMMER LEARNING MADE EASY The kids may soon be on summer vacation
but that doesn't mean they have to stop learning. Kathy Peel looks
at various activities you can encourage to keep the learning
process going all year round. From Child magazine. 1,400 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
SAFEGUARDING YOUR SIGHT : YOUR EYES AND HOW TO PROTECT THEM Vision
problems can sneak up on you. Jacqueline Stenson looks at warning
signs of potential eye problems and what you can do about them.
From Family Circle. 1,400 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
