<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My sure-fire idea for the next movie blockbuster
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, work with me on this one. I have a great idea for a movie.
Just work with me . . . .
</P>
<P>
   What happens, see, is that you have this humongous space ship
from another galaxy that comes to orbit Earth and and sends
smaller, but still really big, ships over every major city in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Are you with me, so far? Good.
</P>
<P>
   After a few days, they blow the White House, Empire State
Building and some other well-known places to smithereens. We send
the Air Force after these ships and it doesn't do any good at all.
Our missiles just bounce off.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, an astronomer in California trying to look at
the ships actually spots something else.
</P>
<P>
   It's. . . Oh, no! It's a mile-wide asteroid ripping through the
heavens and heading straight toward earth.
</P>
<P>
   The scientist gets scared out of his gourd and starts driving
down a mountain to tell everyone his bad news.
</P>
<P>
   As he is driving, he is thrown off the road because of a sudden
and massive earthquake that shatters the Richter scale. He tumbles
down the side of the mountain and into a pit of molten lava formed
from the volcano that has erupted because of all the seismic
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Someone in California circulates a petition asking for a
constitutional amendment that the state can only suffer one
disaster at a time. Between aliens, earthquake and volcano, taxes
are going to be the worst disaster of all. The only people who sign
the petition have recently been hatched from pods left by another
alien intelligence that wants to take over the world. About the
same time off the East Coast, something very strange is happening.
Something is moving in the water.
</P>
<P>
   You guessed it, Godzilla. But this is not your daddy's Godzilla.
The old version had some trouble walking and, in fact, looked as if
he had a bad case of Godzilla chaffing. The new Godzilla can do
zero-to-60 in six seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, just as Godzilla decides to surface -- wouldn't you know
it -- the world's largest cruise ship, the Titanic II, which has
the King of the World on board, runs smack dab into the big lizard.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just water off a lizard's back. The ship snaps in
half and Celine Dion begins to sing.
</P>
<P>
   Above the cruise ship a hijacker takes over a 747 and terrorizes
the passengers, each of whom begin to have their lives flash before
their eyes. The hijacker, whose name is Gort, speaks in a foreign
language with words that sound something like, ``Klattu Berada,
Nickto.'' Nobody knows it, but the President of the United States
is on the plane with his entire family and probably his mistress
(you can never have too many disasters).
</P>
<P>
   But this is where the movie's action really heats up. You forgot
about that pesky asteroid didn't you?
</P>
<P>
   Picture this, just as the aliens are ready to fire their
Doomsday weapon that will vaporize every living being on earth, the
mile-wide asteroid makes a donut out of the aliens' mother ship.
All the little ships explode, too.
</P>
<P>
   But the asteroid doesn't stop. It keeps hurtling toward earth
and plunges into the Atlantic Ocean where it hits -- would you
believe it -- Godzilla as he is fleeing the smog in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A huge tidal wave sweeps across the ocean and is so big that it
reaches California and snuffs out the volcano which, miraculously,
has spewed just enough lava to fill in all the cracks left by the
aarthquake. The seawater also kills all the pod people.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the air the President of the United States risks his life
(remember, this is a movie) to beat up the hijacker and takes
control of the airplane himself. Sorry, I can't do anything about
the cruise ship. The Titanic always sinks.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the movie everyone left alive finds someone to
kiss for three minutes while the credits roll.
</P>
<P>
   If all that isn't enough, I've found a sure-fire way to get
people to get people into the theater. It's all in the name. We'll
just call it, ``Two Thumbs Up.''
</P>
<P>
   Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas) News
Messenger
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
