<HEADER>
A3692 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN04-COX     06-04 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Corpus Christi teaches lessons of life
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ My son is in the beehive of kindergartners at
Corpus Christi School. They buzz with so much energy and vitality,
the mornings I've visited the classroom, they crowd out any
thoughts of what might have come before them. So it's incongruous
to see the banners all over school this year: ``Corpus Christi
Celebrates 85 Years!''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Staley Callier, too, was once part of the youngest class at
Corpus Christi, a second-grader during that first school year of
1912-13. She's 93, but she can close her eyes and travel back to
the day she started, and how proud everybody was of their brand
spanking new school. ``Oh, it was so beautiful,'' she recalls, her
cornflower-blue eyes shining in a way that makes you see the little
girl who made the half-hour trek with her older brother and sister
from their home on Riverside Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody anticipated that first school year would bring the Great
Dayton Flood _ or any of the other challenges that would face the
school in its 85-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Callier remembers the days after the flood: ``The teacher
painted the children's names at each desk. When the teacher found
out the student was safe, the name was removed. The teacher
wouldn't take the name off until the child was safe.'' All of the
25 children in her class survived.
</P>
<P>
   The school faces different challenges today. Financial
struggles. Struggles to maintain its mission and strong academic
tradition while adapting to the neighborhood's changing
demographics. Long an anchor for the Five Oaks neighborhood, Corpus
Christi started out as a strictly Catholic, neighborhood school,
primarily serving the children of Eastern European immigrants.
Corpus Christi enrollment, which peaked at more than 600 in the
'60s, now hovers around 200.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time in Corpus Christi history, more
than half the student body is non-Catholic. ``Eighty-five years
later, we're different and we're the same,'' said Corpus Christi
pastor Jim Schutte. ``We're different because we're reaching out to
a whole different child today, mainly because of the differences in
the demographics of the neighborhood. Those are the challenges: How
do we live our mission statement, of sharing, living and teaching
the Catholic faith?''
</P>
<P>
   The Jane Staley of 1913 would find much that was unfamiliar in
the Corpus Christi of today. She would no doubt have been surprised
by the multi-cultural student body and the existence of Cor-Care,
the day-care center in the school's basement. She might have been
startled to see Principal Barbara Markus greet the children every
morning as crossing guard.
</P>
<P>
   Other things would have seemed more familiar, including some of
the family names. Second-, even third-generation families are
commonplace here. There is still the kindly parish priest _ Father
Schutte, a man who literally and figuratively gets down to the
kids' level. He has been witnessed on at least one occasion getting
down on his knees and joining students in the drinking fountain
line, and has been spotted on many occasions acting silly and
affectionate with them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1913, there was Father John Gallagher. ``He was very good to
the children,'' Callier recalls. There were also, as today,
committed teachers who know how to be strict yet compassionate.
``The nuns cared in a special way when they were the teachers, and
the caring of the teachers is still evident,'' said Jim Flynn,
Callier's nephew and business manager for Corpus Christi parish.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, discipline methods have changed since 1913. Kids
lived in terror of the words, ``Go to the cloakroom,'' Callier
recalls. She was careful not to get in the bad graces of Sister
Fostina, who was fair but stern if you misbehaved. ``There was a
bond between the nuns and the children,'' she recalls. ``We knew we
had to obey them and respect them, and we didn't have any
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody gets banished to the cloakroom these days, but you can
still find teachers of the stern-but-kindly variety. There is the
indomitable Sarahmarie Coleman, a Corpus tradition for 32 years.
The first-grade teacher is a rite of passage for kids who might be
at first intimidated by her booming voice and no-nonsense
discipline, but are won over by her zest for learning.
</P>
<P>
   Students greet visitors like properly trained French
schoolchildren: ``Bonjour, Madame McCarty.'' Mrs. Coleman ``expects
manners,'' just as the nuns who brought her up expected manners.
</P>
<P>
   With her commanding presence and voice _ part Barbara Jordan,
part Vanessa Redgrave _ Mrs. Coleman could have been born for the
stage. But the classroom is the only stage Mrs. Coleman craves.
``First grade is my favorite grade. You lay the foundation for
their life in school. You want to encourage positive habits and
make it interesting, and informative, so they will enjoy
learning.''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher who inspires the fear of God also inspires notes
like this: ``I love you for a teacher. God made you to teach us to
be kind.'' She praises as exuberantly as she reprimands.
``Outstanding!'' she exclaims, as the students practice sentences.
``You are on target! You are ready for second grade!''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Coleman is a family tradition for some of her students; she
taught the parents of two of her students and the uncles of another
first-grader, Jason Brandell.
</P>
<P>
   Jason's mother, Sue Brandell, said the family postponed a move
to Washington Twp. partly because she wanted her younger son to
have Mrs. Coleman for a teacher. ``She has a wonderful sense of
discipline, but she still makes it fun for the kids,'' Brandell
says. ``She is a disciplinarian, but that only helps the children
to be better people, and more responsible, as they go through
life.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other lessons in life. This year, sixth-grade teacher
Carmen Coggburn coordinated the annual ``Buckets of Love'' program,
three barrels and 30 buckets of clothing and toys to be sent to an
orphanage in Monrovia, Liberia. It's part of their religious
education, Coggburn explains, ``giving and helping the less
fortunate. That's why we do it during the season of Lent.''
</P>
<P>
   Today is the last day of school, and my son's last day of
kindergarten. His teacher, Joan Eifert _ a woman of saintly
patience and stalwart eardrums _ will now enjoy some richly
deserved quiet and rest. And maybe, if I visited Alec's classroom
tomorrow, I could sense the presence of other children, hear other
voices.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I could hear Jane Staley, 8 years old again, no longer a
widow and sole survivor among the nine children of James and
Catherine Staley. She certainly can hear all those voices from
1913, see all those earnest young faces. ``We were raised from the
ground up at Corpus Christi,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What a foundation it proved to be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
