<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMN: Who has the right to repent?
</P>
<P>
   By Rowland Nethaway
</P>
<P>
   c 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Some African-Americans want an official apology
for slavery. Others seek reparation payments. A Waco city council
member wants a public plaque to denounce an 82-year-old lynching.
</P>
<P>
   While these requests are being debated or ignored, a group of
white citizens in Tulsa, Okla., publicly repented for a 1921 race
riot.
</P>
<P>
   On the 77th anniversary of a race riot that claimed up to 300
lives and destroyed 35 blocks of Tulsa's prosperous black business
district, the Rev. Glenn Shaffer and other whites repented for the
riot and sought forgiveness from African-Americans who gathered to
watch the ``assembly of repentance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Shaffer and other white ministers led a gathering of whites
in asking forgiveness for something they did not do.
</P>
<P>
   Black ministers led a smaller group of blacks in pardoning the
whites.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, not everyone in Tulsa thought the idea of
repenting for the riot was a worthwhile undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't repent,'' Phillip Rhees was quoted in an Associated
Press story. ``I didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhees was just 8 when the race riot erupted on May 21, 1921,
after word spread that a black man had assaulted a white elevator
operator, a woman who later declined to press charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it hadn't happened,'' Rhees told the reporter. ``I wish
a lot of things didn't happen, but I don't take responsibility for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The 84-year-old Tulsa native said his family sheltered blacks in
their home during the riot.
</P>
<P>
   That's always the sticking point. For the most part, people not
directly involved in some historical outrage seldom feel the need
to repent for something they didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   Out of a population of more than 500,000, only a few hundred
people, both white and black, bothered to turn out to the
``assembly of repentance'' in Tulsa's once-thriving Greenwood
district.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary of Tulsa's race riot was marked by the city for
the first time two years ago, according to the AP story. A black
state representative issued an apology to survivors and victims'
families.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is a Waco native and president of the local National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, council member
Lawrence Johnson said he had never heard of the 1916 lynching of a
young black man convicted of the rape and murder of a white woman
until he visited the National Civil Rights Museum in Memphis two
years ago. There he saw a photo of the burned and disfigured man
hanging from a tree on the lawn of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were indications that city officials were watching it
happen and did nothing to stop it,'' Johnson said. ``I thought it
was time we did something to purge that incident, to gain a sense
of atonement.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Johnson, it's unlikely that many Waco natives ever heard of
the 82-year-old incident that became a campaign issue in the
NAACP's push to pass federal anti-lynching legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Lynchings were barbaric and outrageous, but unfortunately they
were not that unusual in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Even the staunchest critics of the 1916 lynching did not
question the guilt of the young black man sentenced to hang for his
crimes. The barbarity of the lawless mob shocked the nation. The
young man was dragged from the courtroom, beaten, hanged, burned
and disfigured for souvenirs by the more bloodthirsty of the 15,000
onlookers. His corpse was dragged triumphantly through city
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Although the passage of time clouds apologies, acknowledgments
and pleas of forgiveness, 101-year-old Mabel Little, who lost most
of her community in the Tulsa race riot, forgave the whites who
repented for something they did not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless you wonderful people,'' said Mrs. Little. ``I'm the
happiest person in the world today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: RNethaol.com
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-03-98 1522E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
