<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3695 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-GRAULICH05-COX     06-04 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-GRAULICH05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baby daze leaves mom-to-be with mind-that-was
 &HT;    By Heather Graulich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm here at my desk at work, a perfectly useful place for a
pregnant woman to be . . . until I hit the eighth-month mark about
three weeks ago. That's when my brain left me.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose my brain hinted that it needed a break a few months
back. There were all the rooms I walked into, only to find myself
wondering why I was in them. (If I was in the kitchen, I could
answer ``Ice cream!'' and be satisfied, even if I later remembered
the unwashed dishes.)
</P>
<P>
   There were the motor skills _ both fine and gross _ that
departed, the ones I yearned for while teetering in the shower,
trying to shave my legs. (As if anyone was paying attention to my
legs, hidden in the shadow of my dirigible belly.)
</P>
<P>
   Work, though, became the biggest challenge. I tried to think of
clever stories to write. The process went something like this:
``Hmmm . . . all those problems in Indonesia . . . Indonesia's near
Malaysia . . . my mother-in-law lived in Malaysia . . . she just
sent us those adorable baby shoes . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``When do babies start wearing shoes?''
</P>
<P>
   But then one day my brain completely vanished, right there in
the Publix check-out aisle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Left or right?'' asked the helpful bag boy, his hands poised
on my loaded shopping cart.
</P>
<P>
   I blinked at him. The car! He wanted to know where I'd parked
the car. Good question. Outside? Yes, definitely outside. But
where?
</P>
<P>
   ``Left,'' I announced, with confidence I did not really possess.
I thought of suggesting we look for a beige Camry, until I realized
that would be like saying, ``Look for a brown UPS truck.''
</P>
<P>
   But there, parked right out front, was my car. I had forgotten
not only where I'd parked it, but that I had scored a maternity
coup: an unoccupied ``stork parking'' spot for pregnant women. (It
had been a triumphant moment. How many times, on my way to the
parking lot boonies, had I waddled past some skinny man getting
into his stork-parked car? Of course, once inside the store I
forgot my triumph and was soon overwhelmed by too many kinds of
cheese.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few weeks, the baby daze got worse. Where the
brain goes, apparently, the will to move follows. This is when you
find yourself glued to the couch and an episode of Love Boat, circa
Gopher and the gang.
</P>
<P>
   I had become a human paperweight.
</P>
<P>
   The Book explains all of this. ``What to Expect When You're
Expecting,'' the pregnant woman's operating manual, warns of ``a
feeling you're not quite together. You're a scatterbrain, you
forget things, drop things'' starting in the fourth month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's caused,'' the manual states, ``by the hormonal changes
wrought by pregnancy.''
</P>
<P>
   But with my baby's birth just days away, I think I've learned a
more important reason for the memory lapses: A mother's brain needs
a hiatus before her child arrives. It must reprogram some of its
adult, self-centric wiring. Mine, I think, ditched a whole lobe's
worth of thoughts on nuclear testing in India, the last episode of
Seinfeld and whether to boost my 401K contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has room for lullabies.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Samuel Graulich was born May 28.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Graulich writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
