<HEADER>
A3696 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN05-COX     06-04 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Column
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have heard you can get old shredded dollars from the U.S.
Treasury. I'd love to get some to use in a direct mail campaign.
Who do I contact? _ Michelle W.
</P>
<P>
   A: Small bags of shredded bills may be purchased from the Bureau
of Engraving and Printing in D.C.,at (202) 874-2999.
</P>
<P>
   However, any use involving commercial enterprise must be
approved by Uncle Sam. Send a letter outlining your intended use of
the shreds to Tom Rogers, Chief, Department of Treasury, Bureau of
Engraving and Printing, Office of Currency Standards, 14th and C
Streets, SW, Washington, D.C. 20228.
</P>
<P>
   You will be sent the department's guidelines. The shredded money
purchase is made at certain Federal Reserve Banks. Permitted uses
include recycling (roof shingles or insulation) and as novelties
(pens, neckties, etc.).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to get tickets to the Olympics in Salt Lake City. How
do I go about this and when? _ Anne Douglas
</P>
<P>
   A: Tickets for Utah's Winter Olympics are not on sale yet.
Policies and information will be available in 2000. Want to check
in periodically for more information? Try the games' Web site at
www.slc2002.org or call (801) 322-2002. (See the pattern?)
</P>
<P>
   The XIX Olympic Winter Games will be Feb. 8-24, 2002. An
estimated 3,500 athletes and officials will participate in seven
sports in 68 medal events.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to purchase an Al Hirschfeld cartoon. Do you
know where? _ David Morris
</P>
<P>
   A: The Margo Feiden Galleries Ltd. in New York. Call (212)
677-5330 to buy an original (beginning at $3,000) or a lithograph
(beginning at $650).
</P>
<P>
   You may have seen his work on a letter. In 1991 Hirschfeld's
drawings of famous comedians were made into postage stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis-born artist hides his daughter's name, Nina, in
every cartoon. Where does this famous Nina reside? Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter and I are having an argument. I say that Kentucky
Fried Chicken was for sale in Austin, Texas as early as 1953. Am I
right?
</P>
<P>
   Also my cherrywood dining chairs have some wax buildup. I used
Murphy's Oil Soap but no dice. What will remove it without harming
the finish? _ C.M.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: Try a solvent like toluol to lift grease, wax and glue.
Experiment on a hidden area to see how the finish reacts. You may
have to strip and refinish the furniture. The Austin History Center
staff says The Colonel first appears in the 1961Austin telephone
directory. Good resource because the people at Kentucky Fried had
no idea! The first KFC franchise was located in Salt Lake City in
1952.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a gazebo in our back yard and every summer bumblebees
descend on the area. They do not seem to do anything except fly
around and chase each other.
</P>
<P>
   It is getting increasingly difficult to ignore them _ they buzz
very close and we are afraid of them. They may take over the entire
yard even though there is no hive. Can you help us?
</P>
<P>
   _William &AMP; Jeanne Lummus
</P>
<P>
   A: Good news. These are carpenter bees, not bumblebees, says
John Fick, apiary inspector at Texas A&AMP;M.Carpenter bees are
solitary and do not nest in a hive like bumblebees.
</P>
<P>
   You are besieged by male carpenter bees looking for a female _
not very successfully, it seems. Males cannot sting but there is
little you can do to discourage them from returning. Still want a
bee-ectomy? Call local bee and wasp guru Al Kinser at 477-9025.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just noticed recently that Mary Higgins Clark had a No. 1
best seller in fiction and in paperback fiction at the same time,
according to The New York Times Best Seller list. Has anyone had
more than two No. 1 sellers at a time?
</P>
<P>
   _J.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: Prolific authors such as Clark often have a hardback novel
hit the stands as the previously published hardback is released in
paperback. Thus the simultaneous ``firsts'' on the list. According
to Peter Breen, managing editor of Book Publishing Report other
such authors have been John Grisham and Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need to to know how to reach Bernard Hill _ he played the
captain in ``Titanic.'' He is a friend from way back and we have
some important information for him. I have exhausted my sources _
even those in England.
</P>
<P>
   _I. Watson
</P>
<P>
   A: Hill is represented by Susan Smith &AMP; Associates, 121 N. San
Vicente Blvd., Beverly Hills, Calif. 90211.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter is a Peace Corps volunteer in public health
stationed in Sofara, Mali, West Africa. She is working with a
biology teacher who has no visual materials (body systems,
diagrams, models, etc.), no up-to-date textbooks and no microscope.
Surely one of your readers has an outdated microscope or some
textbooks or visual aids to assist this teacher.
</P>
<P>
   We will be glad to bring such donations to this school.
</P>
<P>
   _Paul Angenend
</P>
<P>
   A: Terrific way to help a teacher! Call Angenend at 453-8686 to
donate. His ``Mali Express'' leaves this month!
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have an old, baby push cart bought in England many years
ago and need to replace the tires. It has spoke wheels, about seven
inches in diameter, and hard rubber tires. Where might we find
replacements?
</P>
<P>
   _C.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: New metal wheels with spokes and tires are in stock at Breed
&AMP; Co., 718 W. 29th St. If you want to keep the original wheels and
just re-tire them, talk to the folks at A to Z Tire and Battery,
</P>
<P>
   6401 S. First. They stock (or can order) tires like the Carlisle
line (used on utility carts, wheel barrows and go-carts).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to know what the law is in Texas about loans
that a husband borrowed from a bank without the wife's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Is the wife still responsible for the payments if the husband
does not pay? Also, does it apply to credit card purchases that he
made on his individual cards? I am new and confused in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A: L.H. Very possibly. Welcome to Texas, a community property
state. A spouse is at risk for the debts incurred by a marital
partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot be assured you won't be held liable _ even if you
did not sign for the account or the loan,'' says attorney Sara E.
Saltmarsh, board certified in family law. In Texas, ``each spouse
has the duty to support the other, and the nature of the debt may
determine responsibility in a court's view,'' adds Saltmarsh.
Sounds like you and your spouse might benefit from a course or two
at Consumer Credit Counseling Service (447-0711).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I believe my great-grandfather served in the Confederate
Army. Can you tell me how to reach the Daughters of the
Confederacy?
</P>
<P>
   _K. Boyd
</P>
<P>
   A: The group's Albert Sidney Johnston Chapter meets monthly at
Camp Mabry, except for a summer recess. Call chapter registrar Lana
Henley (258-7904) for details.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please help us settle a bet. What year did the Space Mountain
ride open at Disneyland? My husband swears it was in the early
1970s and I say it was 1977 or 1978.
</P>
<P>
   _Ronda W.
</P>
<P>
   A: May 4, 1977. You win. This terrifying ride (really want to
hitch your stomach to a roller coaster in the dark?) is a hit with
children. The most popular ride in the park? Pirates of the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I get an appraisal locally of what might be a
valuable antique book? It is a leather-bound volume titled ``The
Conquest of Granada,'' by Washington Irving, Hudson Edition,
illustrated, G.P. Putnam's Sons. Inside the front cover it states,
``entered according to Act of Congress, in the year 1850, by
Washington Irving.'' It appears Irving wrote this book in 1829
while serving as an ambassador in Spain. I thought it strange the
book was not entered into the Library of Congress until 21 years
later.
</P>
<P>
   _Amy S. Harper
</P>
<P>
   A: You need the services of an appraiser like Pat Hart
(478-2101) at Hart of Austin Books, 1009 W. Sixth St., in the Whit
Hanks shops. Written appraisals for everything from Texana to
children's books are in her purview.
</P>
<P>
   You will be in good company. The Westbank Libraryasks Hart for
assistance when old tomes are donated. pshot/Update/Uproar
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while I happen on an I nternet site that delivers. For
those of you travel ing to foreign lands this summer, take a look
at http://babelfish. altavista.digital.com where translations
(English to French, German, Spanish, Portuguese or Italian and
back) are a click away.
</P>
