A3698 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAUX-PSYCHOLOGIST05-C     06-04 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAUX-PSYCHOLOGIST05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida school therapist faces felony charges
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   School therapist Linda Werner passed herself off as a clinical
psychologist and collected $200-an-hour fees as an expert witness
in Palm Beach County's court system _ even though she was never
licensed.
</P>
<P>
   Now Werner, 47, is charged with defrauding Blue Cross/Blue
Shield of Florida and may face federal prosecution on Medicare
fraud allegations. She also could be prosecuted for lying about her
qualifications under oath in court cases and on her Blue Cross/Blue
Shield provider application, according to the Florida Department of
Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts police arrested Werner at her home in the Cape Cod
village of Sandwich at 6:30 a.m. Wednesday, June 3, on a warrant
charging her with grand theft, organized scheme to defraud, and
filing false and fraudulent insurance claims. Each is a
second-degree felony punishable by up to 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The charges are based on bills for 20 patients totaling $33,739
that Werner and her partner, Larry Mack, submitted to Blue
Cross/Blue Shield between April 1996 and March 1997, according to
the arrest warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Werner waived extradition and was released in the custody of her
attorney, George Otto, who's also her husband. She has 10 days to
turn herself in to the Palm Beach County Jail, an investigator
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Werner nor Otto could be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, a licensed marriage and family therapist on Palm Beach
Lakes Boulevard, is still under investigation, a department
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Mack is not guilty of any intentional wrongdoing
whatsoever,'' said Michael Dubiner, his attorney. Dubiner told
investigators Mack didn't know Werner wasn't a licensed
psychologist _ or that she'd lost even her school license _ until
he read it in The Palm Beach Post in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Werner has a doctorate in psychology but never went through the
state testing and licensing procedure for psychologists. Her school
license, issued in 1985, was limited to dealing with students'
learning problems. The state Department of Business and
Professional Regulation forced her to give that up in 1996,
charging she had violated it by testifying in a custody case and
arranging a personal relationship between two patients.
</P>
<P>
   Werner was a favorite of local divorce lawyers. They paid her to
do psychological evaluations of adults and children _ something she
couldn't do, legally _ and testify to their mental and emotional
states.
</P>
<P>
   Werner said under oath in 1994 that she was a ``licensed
clinical psychologist'' who had testified as an expert in at least
250 cases and been appointed by judges 30 to 40 times. Judges
relied on her testimony to decide whether parents were capable of
raising children and how marital assets should be divided.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County requires court-appointed mental health experts
to provide their license numbers, but they don't have to submit
copies of the licenses or other proof.
</P>
<P>
   Werner listed herself as a clinical psychologist when she
applied for a Blue Cross/Blue Shield health care provider number in
1991, according to the arrest warrant. Mack didn't have a Blue
Cross/Blue Shield number so all insurance claims were filed under
Werner's name and number, a common practice in professional
offices.
</P>
<P>
   The two continued filing claims even after Werner lost her
school psychology license in April 1996. Of the $33,739 billed, the
agency paid $10,395 before learning that she had no license of any
kind, but only $6,000 is included in the state charges. The rest
was Medicare money and will be dealt with by federal investigators,
said Ron Poindexter, director of the state insurance fraud
division.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations against Werner aren't that unusual, Poindexter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another type of medical billing fraud, which is
rampant in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
