<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ OK, I have a great idea for a movie. Just work
with me on this one . . . . If all that isn't enough, I've found a
sure-fire way to get people to get people into the theater. It's
all in the name. We'll just call it, ``Two Thumbs Up.'' (Latham,
Marshall News Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ Grass consumes every non-working, non-sleeping
minute of my meager life. I dream of water sprinklers, cinch bugs
and root rot. I pray for rain each night, leave my car windows
down, curse meteorologists for giving me false hope of rain, and
come back to the rent house at dark-thirty covered with mud and
grass clippings, soaked to the skin, and stinking to high heaven.
To paraphrase Descartes, I stink, therefore I am. (Borders,
Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Some African-Americans want an
official apology for slavery. Others seek reparation payments. A
Waco city council member wants a public plaque to denounce an
82-year-old lynching. While these requests are being debated or
ignored, a group of white citizens in Tulsa, Okla., publicly
repented for a 1921 race riot. As might be expected, not everyone
in Tulsa thought the idea of repenting for the riot was a
worthwhile undertaking. ``I can't repent,'' Phillip Rhees was
quoted in an Associated Press story. ``I didn't do it.'' (Nethaway,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ There are banners all over my
son's school this year: ``Corpus Christi Celebrates 85 Years!'' The
school faces challenges today. Financial struggles. Struggles to
maintain its mission and strong academic tradition while adapting
to the neighborhood's changing demographics. (McCarty, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
