<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, June 4, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LAREDO-PROBE (Laredo, Texas) _ A massive federal investigation
here has focused on at least 142 people, including the Webb County
district attorney, a former state district judge and investigators
from the district attorney's office. The probe focuses on what
happened to criminal charges against 128 people over the nine years
that Joe Rubio has been district attorney here. By DANE SCHILLER
and CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   SALVATION-ARMY-PARTNERS (San Francisco) _ The Salvation Army has
decided to sever its contracts with San Francisco to provide social
services to elderly, ill and aged San Franciscans because of a
dispute over the city's domestic partners law. By RACHEL GORDON and
TYCHE HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOV (San Francisco) _ Voters who had a hard time telling
the difference among the three Democratic governor's candidates
should have no such trouble in the race between Attorney General
Dan Lungren and Lt. Gov. Gray Davis. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-POLITICS (San Francisco) _ Political consultants are
scratching their heads, trying to figure out how millionaire
businessman Al Checchi could plow an unprecedented sum of nearly
$40 million into winning the Democratic gubernatorial nomination
and come out with only 13 percent of the vote. By ERIN McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   BILINGUAL-EDUCATION (San Francisco) _ California's third epic
legal battle in five years over an initiative fraught with
widespread social implications is under way in the wake of voter
approval Proposition 227 that scraps most of the state's bilingual
education programs. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   MEDALS-OF-HONOR (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ Nearly 100 winners of
the Congressional Medal of Honor are meeting here for the four-day
Medal of Honor Society annual convention. They are a vanishing
breed of old-fashioned war heroes. There are fewer living
recipients _ 163 _ of the prestigious award than at any time since
the society was formed in the early 1950s. By BRENDAN LYONS.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (San Francisco) _ The once fledgling grass-roots gun
control campaign is blossoming into a bona fide statewide movement,
say gun control advocates bolstered by the sweeping success of
ballot measures in three East Bay cities. By KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   RFK-REMEMBERED (Washington) _ In 1968, Robert F. Kennedy had an
agenda _ end the Vietnam War and heal its wounds, get rid of racial
strife, try to halt the standoff with Cuba and the Cold War with
the Soviet Union. But he did not know how to get the power to
achieve that, nor how he could beat President Lyndon Johnson. An
inside look at Kennedy's decision to run. By WARREN ROGERS. (For
release Sunday, June 7)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-EXHIBIT (San Francisco) _ A polemical photo exhibit,
``Human Rights and the Drug War,'' views federal drug policy
prescribing mandatory minimum sentences, even for first offenders,
through the lens of the Bill of Rights and the United Nations
declaration on human rights and finds it abhorrent. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   DOG-MAGAZINE (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Bark is an erstwhile
newsletter for dog lovers that is on the verge of going national as
a tabloid newspaper. Bark editor Claudia Kawczynska and creative
director Cameron Woo describe Bark as a hip alternative to glossy
mainstream magazines such as Dog Fancy and Dog World. By DAVID
ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   HERBAL-SUPPLEMENT (Austin, Texas) _ After receiving more than
1,400 ephedrine-related complaints from citizens across the state,
the Texas Department of Health is considering classifying the
stimulant as a dangerous drug and requiring a prescription for most
products containing it. By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN-CLIMBER (Albany, N.Y. ) _ Douglas Gerhardt is getting
ready for his 1998 vacation that he'll spending trying to climb
Mount Elbrus, at 18,481 feet the highest point in Europe. By JANE
GOTTLIEB.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-PARTIES (Houston) _ It's June and time to plan your
summer party. A fashion guide on party favors, party clothes, pool
parties, and, of course, food. By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WINE-COLUMN (Undated) _ When it comes to single malts, try the
Islay and Bowmore ``Cask Strength'' Single Malt. The Bowmore costs
$50, but it's a serious whiskey, and it would make a goof Father's
Day gift. By MICHAEL LONSFORD.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It was a full house that
witnessed the installation of Sister Patrick Curran as executive
director of the half-century-old Tenderloin institution. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Oakland, Calif.) _ The people of Oakland want to be
somebody. That, more than anything else, explains why almost 60
percent of Oakland voters on Tuesday chose Jerry Brown as their new
mayor. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
<P>
   RFK-ASSESSED (San Francisco) _ With Robert Kennedy's
assassination, the rest of this century's history was written in
blood and sorrow. The place where peace and hope, freedom and
reconciliation died _ the Ambassador Hotel _ is still there, a
reminder of the great American tragedy that occurred there 30 Junes
ago and has devastated the destiny of the American people. By
HALTON ADLER MANN.
</P>
