<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3809 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-COX &UR; $ADV     06-04 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
   $ADV07  COMMENTARY: BRING IN THE RED TEAM
 &HT;     For release Sunday, June 7.
 &HT;     By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's no secret nowadays that a chunk of the $27
billion to be spent this year on our vast intelligence empire will
pay for an order of humble pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my responsibility to stand up and tell the American
people that we didn't get it right,'' George Tenet, the nation's
spy chief, said of his team's failure to predict that India would
muscle its way into the nuclear club. At a closed hearing, Tenet
told the Senate Intelligence Committee that he would try to do
better.
</P>
<P>
   One way to start is to have some of the folks who deal with the
region, home to a fifth of the world's people, bookmark the Times
of India newspaper on their Internet browsers. It's a free ride on
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Had they done so last month, they would have noted that India's
fiercely nationalistic Bharatiya Janata Party had sent loads of
clear signals in plain English of plans to put nukes in their
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   As retired admiral David Jeremiah sees it, the failure came
because ``both the intelligence and policy communities had an
underlying mind set'' that the people who took over in New Delhi in
March ``would behave as we behave.'' As director of Central
Intelligence, Tenet brought Jeremiah in to write a classified
report on what had gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   So far as an outsider can tell, the sole flaw in Jeremiah's
analysis of the CIA's failed analysis was his use of the past
tense: The mind set he cited has yet to change.
</P>
<P>
   Take the briefing that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
gave before leaving for Geneva and a Big Five powwow on the nuclear
expansion issue. She ignored the only country that has so far
actively stepped in to mediate the crisis: Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Even as she spoke, Iran's Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi was in
New Delhi meeting with India's Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee
and telling reporters that ``we believe in a nuclear weapons-free
zone in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Islamabad, where he had met with Pakistani leaders,
Kharrazi sang a different tune, praising Pakistan's ``Islamic
bomb'' and suggesting that ``the development of a nuclear bomb by a
Muslim country can act as a deterrent for Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Iran, these themes fail to strike a happy chord in
official Washington, which holds that the Iranian mullahs are up to
no good when it comes to nukes and that, in any event, they have no
business trying to mediate matters in their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing Jeremiah's secret report, Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb.,
a key member of the intelligence panel, said we need new laws ``so
that there is regular `red team' independent analysis done. Such
teams, as Kerrey would have it, would ensure ``that the people who
are collecting, who are processing, and who are analyzing and
disseminating intelligence have outside review.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad idea. But so long as they are at it, let them begin by
analyzing the flawed foreign policy priorities of a distracted
president and the mind set of a secretary of state loath to
exchange her personal popularity by speaking honestly about the
world as it really exists and not as she wishes it would.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
