<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-COX &UR;      06-04 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-COX </SLUG>
    
 &HT;     TIANANMEN DEMONSTRATION GOES PEACEFULLY _ 1,000 MILES AWAY IN
HONG KONG
 &HT;     By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Shielding their candles from a punishing rain,
thousands of demonstrators held the first vigil on Chinese soil
Thursday night for their countrymen mowed down in the Tiananmen
Square democracy movement nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony dramatized by thunder and lightening amid the
sweet, sad tones of traditional Chinese music, a crowd that
organizers estimated to number 40,000 carried off a peaceful rally
in Victoria Park. Pro-democracy activists laid wreaths in memory of
the victims.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first memorial to the Tiananmen victims since Hong
Kong was restored to Chinese rule last summer, and thus the first
such event ever to take place in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our responsibility to continue what has not been
finished,'' said exiled Chinese dissident Wei Jingsheng, who spoke
to demonstrators over a videotape from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the democratic movement on the mainland is suppressed in a
cruel way, then it will be very hard to maintain democracy in Hong
Kong,'' Wei said. ``On the other hand, if Hong Kong can maintain
democracy here, this will be important to the democratization of
China.''
</P>
<P>
   A second dissident recently released from prison into U.S.
exile, the Tiananmen student leader Wang Dan, talked to the crowd
on an open telephone line. He thanked them for braving the lousy
weather, and expressed hopes he one day will be permitted to join
demonstrators back in his homeland to mark the June 4 massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's annual remembrance here drew 55,000 mourners, but
organizers guessed in advance that today's more temperate political
atmosphere would pull down the numbers. Just before the Hong Kong
handover last year, people here were intent on letting China's
leaders know the change in regime would not cow them into quieting
their calls for democracy and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the crowd Thursday was of respectable size for the
conditions, and it was the only protest permitted anywhere in
China. There had been no threat of disorder by the group that has
staged annual peaceful memorials since the 1989 crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   In Tiananmen Square in Beijing, there was no overt observance of
the bloody attack China's army staged the night of June 3-4, 1989,
to end a weeks-long, student-led demonstration for democracy and
against corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly Chinese tourists flew kites and ogled monuments on a
sunny, warm day, and a crowd of yellow-hatted retirees stood
through a lecture on the history of the square that has been a
central landmark to generations of Chinese. The lecturer left the
events of 1989 out of his recitation.
</P>
<P>
   The only unusual event was the appearance of a wheelchair-bound
protester and his brother, farmers from Fujian Province in the
southeast, whose complaint was unrelated to the 1989 events that
remain an open political wound. Police quickly hauled both men off
the square, stifling their effort to draw attention to claims that
local officials abused power in the personal injury case that left
the man crippled.
</P>
<P>
   Others dared not show up to demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups report police as usual stepped up
surveillance of dissidents and their families in days leading up to
the anniversary, detaining some and putting guards at the homes of
others.
</P>
<P>
   Tighter controls were reportedly placed over Zhao Ziyang, the
78-year-old former Communist Party general secretary who remains
under house arrest nine years after expressing sympathy for the
students who gathered thousands of demonstrators to the square.
</P>
<P>
   The human rights group Amnesty International reported Thursday
that at least 250 people remain in prison for their participation
in the democracy movement, out of more than 2,000 political
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   One of the boldest efforts to be heard has come from Bao Tong,
the assistant to Zhao Ziyang in 1989, who only in recent days
finally was released from prison. He had been held on charges of
leaking state secrets and counter-revolutionary incitement.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews, including one published here Thursday
in the South China Morning Post, Bao has come out strongly for
democratic political reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest lesson (from June 4) is that our power must have
limits and supervision by the people,'' Bao said in the interview.
``If we do not establish controls, then such a thing could happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary was especially sensitive this year, as
authorities wondered whether increasingly troubling unemployment
problems might translate into political protest. Another sore point
is the coming visit by U.S. President Bill Clinton, who has been
under fire at home for agreeing to have his official welcome
ceremony at Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers Asia correspondent Joseph Albright contributed
to this story from Beijing.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
