<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUN TACKLES A NEW MISSION FOR THE NEEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although the place was packed, there were no
mayors, supervisors, city department heads or well-heeled
representatives from the Office of Protocol. Seeing as it was a
pretty strong Catholic crowd, there were plenty of priests, nuns
and brown-robed Franciscan friars in attendance, but no bishops.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it was a typical gathering in the dining room at
the St. Anthony Foundation: About 175 just-folks singing, hugging,
praying and gnoshing _ and everyone there was ``family.''
</P>
<P>
   All had come to witness the installation of Sister Patrick
Curran as executive director of the half-century-old institution in
San Francisco's Tenderloin neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   A Sister of Mercy who took her vows the year men first walked on
the moon, Curran has a long career in health care and
administration. As its vice president and chief operating officer,
she spent the last 14 years running Mercy Retirement and Care
Center in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Already, though, she has learned the lay of the new land. Of the
tight-knit, hard-working San Francisco neighborhood in which most
St. Anthony services operate, Curran said: ``Do not fool with the
Tenderloin community.''
</P>
<P>
   That remark won the no-nonsense nun a raucous round of applause.
Yet, in nearly the same breath, she reminded all present that their
new executive director is first and foremost a woman of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel blessed to be here,'' she said. ``This is very holy
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   While most San Francisco Bay-area residents know of St.
Anthony's through its legendary dining room for the poor _ 2,000
meals are served each day _ the foundation is considerably more
than a soup kitchen next door to St. Boniface Church. With an
annual budget of $13 million, St. Anthony's oversees more than a
dozen programs, including a free medical clinic, drug and alcohol
rehabilitation programs, housing for elderly women, clothing and
furniture distribution and employment.
</P>
<P>
   Like most social service agencies in the United States, St.
Anthony's biggest challenge these days is keeping up with the
increasing number of people made poor, homeless and desperate by
state and federal welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The faces of the poor have changed so much since I was a young
nun in Harlem,'' Curran said after the ceremony. ``Then, it was
almost always men. Yesterday, we had an 8-month-old baby in here.
Earlier this week, a typical family came in. They can pay their
rent, but, by the end of the month, there's no money for food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their son is 11. You could tell he was embarrassed to have to
be here. I sat down and talked with him and tried to make him feel
a little more comfortable. With the numbers of people we have
coming, we can never lose the personalism that St. Anthony's has
always offered. We can never stop looking each person in the eyes
and seeing the individual.''
</P>
<P>
   In his opening comments, the Rev. Floyd Lotito touched on that
``personalism'' _ and its two-way benefits. All priests and nuns in
the Franciscan order, he said, have been charged by their superiors
to rediscover the spirit that moved their founder, St. Francis of
Assisi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each should share as far as they are able, the life, history,
and hope of the poor and marginalized of our society, in order to
be evangelized by them,'' Lotito said.
</P>
<P>
   The mission isn't to teach the poor, he said, but ``to allow
them to preach the gospel to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Patrick Curran could not agree more. Back in the early
1800s, the Irish founder of her order, Catherine McAuley, advised
her pioneering nuns: ``Welcome everyone _ and make them a
comforting cup of tea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that fits right in here at St. Anthony's,'' Curran
said.
</P>
<P>
   As if to demonstrate that the St. Anthony family expects
Curran's ``cup of tea'' to be decidedly 21st century, a man from
the maintenance staff walked up, congratulated the nun and gave her
a sharp military salute.
</P>
<P>
   She saluted back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
