<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SOMEBODY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The people of Oakland want to be somebody.
That, more than anything else, explains why almost 60 percent of
Oakland voters on Tuesday chose Jerry Brown as their new mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund G. ``Jerry'' Brown Jr. is somebody, a former California
governor, a former presidential candidate, a former boyfriend of
pop singer Linda Ronstadt, a former helper to Mother Teresa.
</P>
<P>
   Oaklanders, who have never had anyone like him lead them, are
tired of living in the shadow of San Francisco and envious of
Silicon Valley's booming high-tech economy.
</P>
<P>
   They are starved for positive recognition. They cringed when _
pre-Jerry Brown _ the national news media turned a glaring
spotlight on their humble town. The attention was usually negative,
with ``menacing'' as the adjective affixed to the Black Panthers,
the Hell's Angels, the Oakland Raiders and even the Rolls Royce
funeral cortege of a notorious drug dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor-elect Jerry Brown promises to bring a positive national
and international spin to a city that hungers for validation.
</P>
<P>
   Debbra Schwartz, speaking amid the din of Brown's victory party,
said: ``When a national figure like Jerry Brown comes here and
says, `Hey, this place is OK,' then it's not a loss for us. Oakland
gets a lot of bad press from San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to sit around here and say things are hopeless,
horrible. But when someone who's been around like Jerry Brown has
comes here and says, `It's not so terrible; let's do something,'
then it helps our national image.''
</P>
<P>
   David Hilliard had similar feelings. A founder of the Black
Panther Party in the 1960s and an early supporter of Brown, he
said, ``With Jerry as our mayor, Oakland will be a focal point of
national and international importance. He brings our city into an
international community, because we live in a global era.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Johnson, an Oakland resident and truck driver, said,
``Jerry Brown gives Oakland national exposure. People are looking
at Oakland in a different light than before.''
</P>
<P>
   That Brown is white doesn't bother Hilliard or Johnson, who are
African Americans in a city with an African-American population of
about 40 percent and Asian-American and Latino populations of about
15 percent each. It's a city where race is always a factor, despite
protests to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about black or white,'' Johnson said. ``Jerry knows
more CEOs than the other candidates. He has connections. We have
had black people on the school board and on the City Council. We
can't blame whites. It's not about race. It's about getting the
best person to run the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard says Brown has historical connections to the
African-American community. And, in a back-to-the-future twist,
Hilliard sees Brown's victory in Oakland as a continuum of the
Black Panther Party's programs of the 1960s and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very progressive victory for Oakland,'' Hilliard
said. ``Our politics have always been class politics. It was never
about race.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jerry puts the right people in place, it will be the most
important transition for the city since the Black Panther Party. He
echoes our agenda of addressing joblessness and crime. I haven't
seen this sort of electricity of race and class and participation
in politics since Bobby Seale ran for mayor in 1973. Jerry will
bring all sorts of experiences to get the community participating.
Jerry will bring the races together. He will heal the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that happens awaits the passage of time. Meanwhile,
before he takes office in January, Brown will try to change the
city charter to strengthen the mayor's office, a highly divisive
issue in the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
