<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3839 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RFK-ASSESSED-2TAKES-$     06-04 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RFK-ASSESSED-2TAKES-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THUMB UP, RFK DECIDED TO SEEK THE PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 7)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN ROGERS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Sen. Robert F. Kennedy was trying to make up
his mind about anything of moment, he took on a look of pain and
anguish.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to sweat more and to lower his head and stare off into
space and twist his hands a lot. He was never a fashion plate, but
at such times he seemed to grow more ungroomed, and too consumed by
thought to notice.
</P>
<P>
   He was that way in January 1968, when Look magazine photographer
Stanley Tretick and I, as Look Washington editor, were hanging out
with him, practically day and night. He was wrestling with a
decision on whether to oppose incumbent Lyndon B. Johnson in the
1968 Democratic presidential primaries. His head told him it would
be folly, but his heart said do it.
</P>
<P>
   All of us watching him up close understood the struggle. Tretick
and I were closer than most because we had a deal with him, to
cover him ``from the inside out,'' as Theodore White had done in
1960 for his book, ``The Making of a President.''
</P>
<P>
   The arguments against running were overwhelming. Even though
Vietnam War casualties and protests had severely undercut Johnson's
earlier popularity, he still had the power of incumbency. And
everybody knew he could be a formidable no-quarter, no-prisoners
campaigner. He had scornfully, humiliatingly rejected Kennedy's
suggestion to pick him as his vice-presidential nominee in 1968,
and any idea of another confrontation was chilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``O-oh-oh, what he would do to me!'' Kennedy said once,
grimacing, almost to himself, as he responded to the umpteenth
question about whether he would run.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed, but said nothing more. He had an agenda _ end the
war and heal its wounds, work more imaginatively to be rid of
racial strife, try to halt the standoff with Cuba and the Cold War
with the Soviet Union, resolve to boost early education,
reinvigorate the war on poverty, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not know how to get the power to achieve that. And,
despite all the pressures from liberal well-wishers, he did not see
how he could beat Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Tretick and I flew into Rochester, N.Y., with him and Ethel
Kennedy in January 1968.
</P>
<P>
   He was making duty rounds as New York's junior senator, a Polish
American breakfast here, an Italian American supper there. But, as
he had since he toured the country campaigning on behalf of
Democratic candidates in 1966, he was testing the waters for a
possible run at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Just as we landed, a raging blizzard set in, and all aircraft
were grounded. It took three hours to feel our way to Syracuse in
the blinding blanket of snow. We had a wonderful time, talking some
shop but mostly just talking.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and his wife had had dinner the night before with Harold
MacMillan, the former British prime minister. To my great surprise,
because I knew Kennedy had a tin ear and could sing only one song
(``Jingle Bells''), he beautifully mimicked MacMillan's upper-class
accent, phrasing and cadence in repeating stories he had told at
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen,'' he said, suddenly serious. ``You guys keep saying I
have to run, I have to run. Well, it is not just me I would be
deciding for. If I announce, people would come running to the
campaign. They would quit jobs they love and leave their families
to work in the campaign. There would be divorces, and some people
would meet and get married. Hundreds, thousands of good people
would be affected. It isn't just me. It's a lot of people. And they
would never be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   As the months went by and we kept gnawing at him, he took on a
deeper look of distress. He did not budge even when Minnesota Sen.
Eugene J. McCarthy got in to challenge Johnson and attracted a
whole flock of liberal activists away from Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   He was gathering a team, though, just in case. By this time, I
was pretty convinced he would run. Look assigned Tretick and me to
do the story. But I could not get a definite yes or no out of him,
even for my own background and guidance, and the deadline for the
story was bearing down.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote two stories. One said he had decided to run and
explained why, in a grand display of punditry, and the other
confidently detailed why he did not run.
</P>
<P>
   That left the problem of the ``sell line'' to go with Tretick's
splendid portrait of Kennedy on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   It was major, because the cover was printed two weeks ahead of
the rest of the magazine, and there was no time left. After much
thrashing about, I came up with a one-size-fits-all: ``Bobby
Kennedy: How He Made Up His Mind about 1968.''
</P>
<P>
   We rolled the cover with that. But we could not get a commitment
from him until McCarthy won a surprising 45 percent of the vote
against Johnson in the New Hampshire primary, a prelude to
president's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   I called Kennedy early the next morning and he said he would let
me know the following day at Saratoga Springs, N.Y., where he was
giving a speech. We held the presses at Look, the first time we had
ever done that in the magazine's history, at a cost of $25,000 per
day.
</P>
<P>
   At Saratoga Springs, as Kennedy entered the hotel where he was
to speak, I fought my way through a mob of reporters and
photographers to his side. I did not want to tip my hand, and so I
shouted, ``Is it up or down?''
</P>
<P>
   He looked puzzled a second and then made a thumbs-up gesture. I
raced to a telephone and told the Look printer in Chicago to go
with the ``go'' story. It was as close to a scoop as I could get.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy formally announced his candidacy March 16 in the Senate
Caucus Room, the same place from which his brother John began his
quest for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Kennedy marched in the St. Patrick's Day parades
in Boston and New York, and we all set out on the whirlwind, 81-day
campaign that ended in that hotel kitchen in Los Angeles the night
he won the California primary and seemed certain to get the
nomination and probably the election.
</P>
<P>
   When the shots were fired, I came up behind Sirhan Sirhan. I got
him under one leg and, with others, wrestled with him for the gun.
There were too many big, strong people in that melee and I
disengaged and went to Kennedy. Mrs. Kennedy was bending over him.
I saw the wound, in the mastoid area just behind his ear. I knew
then that all the hopes and dreams would vanish.
</P>
<P>
   And as Mrs. Kennedy, security man Bill Barry, campaign worker
Fred Dutton and I took him to the hospital in the ambulance, I
thought of what he had said once on the campaign trail, scolding
aides for being over-protective of him in crowds:
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people don't want to hurt me. They just want to touch me
and feel part of something. But, if there is somebody out there who
means me harm, I don't want to dwell on it. I can't live like that,
in fear that something might happen to me. And I won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy died at the age of 42 just 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People have asked many times since whether he was always as
dour, demanding and humorless as they remember him.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect, it makes me laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Dour and demanding at times, OK. But humorless? Not hardly. He
never went out of his way to make you laugh, and he despised foul
language and dirty jokes and always walked away from them. But he
could crack us up, and he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, Kennedy emulated Harry Truman's triumphant
whistlestopping of 1948 by riding a train dubbed ``The Wabash
Cannonball'' for a spell. Ethel Kennedy joined us and, when we
stopped at Warren G. Harding's hometown of Marion, she saw me
interviewing people in the crowd and waved.
</P>
<P>
   Back aboard, Kennedy was looking out the rear at a German
television crew stranded on the tracks, glum and forlorn, as the
train gathered speed. Nobody could empathize like Kennedy. He
appeared genuinely distressed as he asked, ``Will they catch up
with us someplace?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't,'' I said, ``they don't belong in this business.
Besides. It's your fault they missed the train.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked aghast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' I said. ``You know that part in your set speech where
you say, `As George Bernard Shaw once said, ``Some men see things
as they are and ask why _ I see things that never were and ask why
not?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you left that out this time. Senator, I don't know what
those words mean to you, but to us they mean, `Run for the
train!'''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, at a stop outside a very small town where only a
few farmers, thumbs in the straps of their bib overalls, showed up,
he hurried through his speech to the climax and, voice rising
dramatically, declared, ``As George Bernard Shaw once said _ `Run
for the train!'''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's reputation as a sourpuss probably arose from innate
shyness as well as from the role he assigned himself in the Kennedy
clan. He was the family naysayer.
</P>
<P>
   He braved the limelight when he had to, but he never got over
his stage fright. He made hundreds of speeches, and yet his hands
never stopped trembling. He could sweat through a fresh shirt at a
single television appearance, and he usually did.
</P>
<P>
   The legendary TV host Jack Paar had Kennedy on his show many
times.
</P>
<P>
   They worked a routine whereby Kennedy would change to a clean
shirt after the show and leave the damp one behind. Paar would take
it home to his wife, who would wash and iron it and have it ready
for the next time.
</P>
<P>
   When Paar decided it was time to retire, he called Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do?'' Kennedy asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Paar mumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Kennedy said, ``you could always open a laundry.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Warren Rogers, who writes the syndicated ``White House Watch''
column, has written two books about Robert F. Kennedy, the latest,
``When I Think of Bobby, a Personal Memoir of the Kennedy Years.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
