<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUNTAIN-CLIMBER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG LAWYERS PLANS HIKE TO ONE OF EARTH'S HIGHEST HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GOTTLIEB  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Douglas Gerhardt spent minutes putting
on boots, a fleece jacket, wind pants, ropes and spiked iron shoe
plates called crampons, grabbed an ice ax and stepped outside. The
burglar alarm beeped.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife will kill me if I ruin the carpet,'' he said, taking
care with the crampons as he closed the sliding door, quelling the
alarm. Dressed in as much gear as an astronaut, he posed in a
grassy backyard outfitted with bird feeder, deck and barbecue
grill.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Gerhardt was a suburban commando. But at 18,000 feet in
the Caucasus Mountains of southwestern Russia, the layers will
prove useful _ no, essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says here: `More than 50 percent of those attempting to
climb (Mount) Elbrus turn back due to high altitude, wind and
cold,''' he said moments later, clad in jeans and an Oxford shirt
and reading the travel literature at his kitchen table.
</P>
<P>
   Gerhardt, 31, leaves July 19 for Mount Elbrus, at 18,481 feet
the highest point in Europe. He will join a group led by
Seattle-based REI Adventures to scale one of the world's Seven
Summits, so-named because they represent the highest points in each
continent.
</P>
<P>
   The climber, an attorney and lobbyist for the School
Administrators Association of New York State, is quick to emphasize
that Elbrus is not the people-eating Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian peak is a good 10,000 feet lower than the Asian
summit, and it is unlikely climbers will become afflicted by the
accumulation of fluids in lungs more common at higher elevations.
</P>
<P>
   Elbrus does not require the specialized ice climbing techniques
needed to scale Everest and Alaska's Mount McKinley, and also lacks
some their other extremes: cost and time among them. Permits for
Everest can run in the tens of thousands of dollars and like other
elite mountains, it demands months of work.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at a time of year when thousands of visitors will flock
to his own town for fun, Gerhardt is aware his summer place to be
is an unusual choice.
</P>
<P>
   His two-week vacation will cost more than $5,000, a good share
of it that will go to insulate his body against the elements. The
expense probably means no more trips this year, for himself or his
wife Pam, who isn't even going on this one. And, Elbrus is
certainly more dangerous than, say, Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there's a selfishness to the endeavor. I've only
been married a year and a half and my wife isn't coming along,''
conceded Gerhardt, who stands 5-feet-7-inches and weighs 161
pounds. ``But I see it as a risk, not as life threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   The group of six climbers will fly to Moscow before catching a
transfer flight to Mineralniye Vody, a town named for its mineral
waters. On the fourth and fifth day, climbers will take day hikes
at ever higher elevations, arriving at their final base camp and
then, one hopes, the summit.
</P>
<P>
   At 18,481 feet, Elbrus is a gentle-sloped volcano in the center
of the Caucasus range, near the Russian-Georgian border. Its jagged
peaks resemble the Swiss Alps, its terrain recommended for the most
physically fit.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures can range from 60 to minus 20. Mountain sickness is
a threat, along with unscheduled storms. The REI itinerary reserves
day eight for ``summit attempt,'' not simply ``summit,'' followed
the next day by another attempt and then a ``reserve'' day in case
the weather isn't amenable the first two times.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the up and down can take between nine and 15 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Though undoubtedly a risk taker, Gerhardt said he is not one to
be lured to the top if weather and his own physical limitations
suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Respect for the outdoors is a lesson he wishes more people would
heed. People twist ankles and they die doing what he is about to
do.
</P>
<P>
   But the drama is part of what drives him, Gerhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like my boss said about this trip, `You'll go higher than
anyone I know.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
