<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BOWMORE SCOTCH UNTAMED AND TERRIFIC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The North Sea roared and spit its cold, gray fury as I stood at
water's edge. The wind rocked me back on my heels, stinging my
face. My teeth chattered like shuffled dominoes despite the
overcoat, wool suit and cashmere sweater.
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't care; I was happy as a clam (albeit a stone-cold
one).
</P>
<P>
   I was standing on the beach, if you can call it that, in the
Orkney Islands, north of Scotland. It was November, and mister, it
was raw. In a moment I would join my group for a ``ceiligh,'' a
``musical evening,'' in the salon of the hotel in the seaport town
of Kirkwall. A small group of U.S. visitors was being entertained
by the Orkney Strathspey and Reel Society. This was a local group,
and the toe-tapping music was the real MacCoy.
</P>
<P>
   To my dying day I'll never forget that night: icy winds outside,
warm camaraderie inside.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention we were drinking some of the finest whisky in the
world?
</P>
<P>
   Single-malt scotch, of course. Several brands were on the
sideboard, and they were free-flowing. I sampled the ones from
Orkney first, and the Highland Park, especially, was memorable. But
my favorite scotches continue to be from the western Scottish
islands, specifically those from Islay.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with blended scotches, mind you, but the single
malts offer more complexity if less finesse. When you talk
single-malt scotches, you talk about their regions.
</P>
<P>
   Single-malt scotches come in varying styles, usually dictated by
their geography. In my tasting experience, going from Islay in the
west to the Highlands in the east, single-malt whiskies get
smoother, lighter, less peaty _ more ... civilized.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why I like the Islay (EYE-lah) malts so. At their
best, they're untamed, unforgiving, unrepentant _ and magnificent.
It's true that some of the Islays have been compromised to tame
that wild, peaty, smoky iodine streak, but others play that
pungency to the kilt _ er, hilt. If Mel Gibson had tippled a wee
dram in ``Braveheart'' before he went off to fight the British, you
know it would've been an Islay malt ...
</P>
<P>
   It's been awhile since I stood on that wind-scored shore and had
what was left of my hair blown south to the Azores. But one day _
soon _ I'm going back to Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   And I'll head west next time, west to Islay and maybe the isle
of Jura, and visit my favorite distilleries, such as Lagavulin and
Laphroaig.
</P>
<P>
   And I'll be stopping at Bowmore, too, which has just released a
couple of new single malts, one of which is sensational. It's a
``Cask Strength'' Islay malt _ 112 proof, can you believe? _ that
has power and complexity and enough iodine, heather, seaweed and
peat in a single sip to carve its initials on your taste buds for
life.
</P>
<P>
   There's no age for the Bowmore ``Cask Strength'' Single Malt
listed on the label, but it's roughly 15 years old. And the whisky
was aged in bourbon hogsheads, so there's no sherry-cask nuances to
butt in on the cornucopia of flavors already there.
</P>
<P>
   This is a serious whisky. And at a suggested price of $50 or so,
it's expensive.
</P>
<P>
   But Father's Day is in a couple of weeks, and since this Bowmore
``Cask Strength'' Single Malt is obviously a special-occasion
potable _ well, the connection seems obvious.
</P>
<P>
   There are other Bowmore scotches already in the market, however,
including the Bowmore ``Legend'' (eight years old), plus Bowmore
12-, 17-and 21-Year-Old. And there is a ``Cask Strength'' Bowmore
bottled by Cadenhead available, too, but it's pushing the
$100-a-bottle mark.
</P>
<P>
   So: If you happen to be in western Scotland ere long, and you
see a solitary fellow walking along the beach, stop and ask him
what's in that sterling flask in his hip pocket. If it's Bowmore
``Cask Strength'' Single Malt, well, I'll be happy to share.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the truth _ straight, no chaser ...
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Father's Day, here are a few more ideas for Dad on
his special day. There are several companies that specialize in
wine-related paraphernalia; these suggestions are from the Wine
Enthusiast catalog:
</P>
<P>
   Riedel makes wine glasses for every conceivable kind of wine,
and they come in three price categories, ranging from $8 or so a
stem to $70 a stem.
</P>
<P>
   If Dad is serious about his wine but has no practical place to
store it, consider a self-contained cooling unit such as EuroCave.
These start in the three-figure range and go up quickly, but they
do store your wine in a cooled, humidity-controlled unit, away from
light and vibration.
</P>
<P>
   If Dad likes an occasional post-prandial brandy, a crystal
decanter looks great and will keep his best cognac or armagnac
available at arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   Toss out that cheesy corkscrew and buy Dad a Screwpull, probably
the best cork-puller ever. The basic models (which work just fine,
thank you), start around $15, although there's a super-deluxe model
for about $130.
</P>
<P>
   Just starting out learning about wine? One of the best primers
is ``The Windows on the World Complete Wine Course'' (Sterling,
$24.99). It's that publishing rarity: informative AND fun.
</P>
<P>
   Other gift ideas: wine racks, wine-logo aprons for the dad who
likes to barbecue, small wine-cork bulletin boards and trivets and
wine coasters.
</P>
<P>
   To get a Wine Enthusiast catalog, call 800-356-8466 or write to
Box 39, Pleasantville, N.Y. 10570; the Web site is
www.wineenthusiast.com.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, make it easy on yourself: Just get Dad a bottle of his
favorite wine or maybe even two or three. It's his day, and the old
boy's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Michael Lonsford can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and question to
michael.lonsford(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
