<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-PARTIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO PLAN SUMMER PARTIES  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ June. You remember it well. School is out, shoes are
off, the swimming pool is open, and the Popsicle man cometh round
every afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As adults, however, life and entertaining are not always so
simple. Like children, we want to kick back and celebrate the
advent of summer, yet our sense of decorum tells us that is not as
easy as squeezing into cutoffs, popping the top on a cool one and
throwing a hunk of meat on the grill. Perhaps if we're camping out
_ but city, and even country, life today is a tad more civilized
than that hippie '70s version of backyard partying.
</P>
<P>
   Today's flaired pants may have Gucci labels, our capris may be
silk and even our paper plates are loaded with style. Why not take
advantage of the options available to entertain in a grand manner,
color-coordinating disposable paperware, your party favors and even
your summer fashions and accessories?
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it's your party and you can shine if you want to.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GARDEN PARTY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mackenzie-Childs, the Aurora, N.Y.-based company famed for
wildly decorative home accessories, china and painted furnishings,
also excels in patterned paperware pretty enough to grace tables at
a wedding reception.
</P>
<P>
   With coordinated plates, napkins and cups, Mackenzie-Childs
offers so many florals, stripes, checks, dots and garnishes that
your guests will not miss the kinds of china and crystal that need
to be washed by hand.
</P>
<P>
   For table decorations, arrange colorful English garden-variety
flowers in clear glass vases, clay pots or tin pails. For
inexpensive tablecloths, look in discount stores for colorful flat
bedsheets. Or sprinkle a table covered in a bright paper cloth with
paper flowers.
</P>
<P>
   A salad menu is perfect for this kind of party, with fresh
berries and cake for dessert and iced tea to drink.
</P>
<P>
   If you choose highly decorative paperware, do not make the
mistake of matching your hostess ensemble to the patterns in the
plates and napkins. Stick to clothing in bright or pastel solid
colors. Choose silk shantung and patent-leather sandals for shine,
and some of today's newly colorful cosmetics, including pink,
fuchsia and orange lipsticks and blue and green eyeshadows.
</P>
<P>
   Party favors might be Mackenzie-Childs cotton sock coin purses
or large sock shoulder bags, silk-flower-topped boxes of candies or
a tiny bottle of a fresh ``green'' fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COUNTRY SHINDIG &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summer is a fine time to show off a country home and garden, but
make entertaining easy on yourself with red, white and blue paper
products that are tasteful without overdoing your theme.
</P>
<P>
   Ideal Home Range offers combination red bandanna print and blue
check plates. Add coordinating prints and solids, with paper
napkins or cloth bandannas.
</P>
<P>
   Country-flavored party favors _ spiced pecans, chocolate chip
cookies, note pads, decorative magnets _ in blue-checked paper
totes. If it tends to be buggy in your area, light citronella
candles and add bug repellents and anti-itch agents to the goodie
bags.
</P>
<P>
   Pick flowers such as zinnias, marigolds, sunflowers, daylilies
and bachelor buttons, massing them in tin pails or watering cans
with herbs such as rosemary, basil and pennyroyal, all natural bug
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Make a scarecrow to point the way to your back yard, and if you
have a garden growing, allow guests to help with the harvest for
lunch or dinner. If your place is a haven for birds, station your
bird books on the table so city-slicker guests can identify the
various species.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the menu simple. Sun tea and wines. Grilled chicken or pork
chops, baked beans, cole slaw or green salad and jalapeno corn
bread. Shine with a dessert you prepare ahead _ pecan-covered ice
cream balls served with a choice of chocolate or butterscotch
toppings.
</P>
<P>
   What to wear? Jeans or a denim sundress are always appropriate
in the country, but white cottons and linens look and feel cooler.
You might want to shop for eyelet embroideries or a white knit,
long dress to wear with a pointelle sweater tied round the neck or
waist.
</P>
<P>
   If fire ants have infested your part of the country, do your
guests a favor and advise them ahead of time to wear socks and
tennis shoes and leave the sandals at home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
POOL PARTY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amscan's line of paperware includes almost-neon-colored
tableware and invitations to match in a pool party motif. Cover
your table in a whisk-away fuchsia plastic ``cloth'' or a bright
flat sheet.
</P>
<P>
   For novel table decorations, buy bright but inexpensive
flip-flops and sunglasses, and for party favors, fill colorful
paper totes with lip lubricant, one of the new combination sun- and
bug-proofing lotions, melt-proof candies and fun items such as
yo-yos and, if you dare, water guns.
</P>
<P>
   Pick your swimsuit to coordinate with the colors from Amscan's
pool-party papers _ blue, hot pink, green, yellow and orange _ but
make it floral, striped or polka-dotted. Pick a bright cover-up, a
pair of comfortable sandals and a hat for sun protection.
</P>
<P>
   If guests will be going directly from the pool to the table in
wet suits, drape chairs with bright terry beach towels.
</P>
<P>
   Hot dogs cooked on the grill, with pots of chili and sauerkraut
for toppers, make the simplest menu. Add a variety of chips and a
platter of raw vegetables, but skip the potato salad, which is
often difficult to maintain at a safe temperature in the outdoors.
For dessert, offer cupcakes with happy faces, M&AMP;M cookies and a
bowl of fresh fruit salad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WILD TIMES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contempo and Creative Papers offer animal print paperware to get
your summer party off to a roaring start. These animal prints work
well with solid brown or brown-striped cloths and flowers in
yellow, orange and red. For the most elegant table, set your paper
plates on an antique kuba cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical flowers, such as birds of paradise, and banana leaves
and palm fronds are easily arranged in plain vases or cans of water
hidden in baskets. Add African or Indian masks to the table and
dcor, and light citronella flares in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a menu that includes shish kebobs that guests assemble
and cook on their own. Ingredients might include three choices of
meat and six to eight vegetables and fruits, with a choice of
basting and dipping sauces, a cold rice or couscous dish, and a
green salad.
</P>
<P>
   Make your choice of clothing on the simply elegant side. While
the temptation might be to wear animal spots and stripes, resist
the urge. If you let your invitation spell out your tribal/safari
theme, allow your guests to show off their collections of animal
prints while you confine yourself to a beautifully bare, black
linen sundress or a figure-hugging neutral striped knit. Wear
sandals and treat yourself to a pedicure and bright polish.
</P>
<P>
   For party favors, look for decorative boxes and fill them with
chocolate-covered coffee beans or strings of ethnic beads.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
