<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-04 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN YEARS AND A NEW OUTLOOK LATER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten years ago, I stood on stage at the Boston Public Library and
looked out at a sea of faces. It was one of the best and yet one of
the worst afternoons of my life.
</P>
<P>
   I'd had a collection of columns published that year and the
Globe had been good enough to choose me as one of five speakers in
the 1988 Globe Book Fair. I'd attended two earlier talks, observing
Nicholas Daniloff and Edward Abbey as they signed their books and
chatted with readers. Neither one of them had quite filled the hall
so when I arrived for my talk 15 minutes early and found that the
library guards were already turning people away, my heart started
pounding in my chest.
</P>
<P>
   It was early in my career. Writing from home, I had no idea how
many people read my column or how anyone felt about it. My only
feedback from my editors at the Globe so far had been, ``No
complaints.'' I didn't hear from readers that often back then, and
 &UR; rras I pressed past groups of women trying to talk their way in, I
saw their presence as an antidote to my shaky self-esteem. I felt a
surge of triumph. ``This will show everyone,'' I thought. I'd no
longer be invisible. I'd arrived.
</P>
<P>
   They say pride goeth before a fall. In my case, it was
immediate.
</P>
<P>
   As I made my way backstage, someone official approached me. The
woman flashed a tight smile, then apologized. Sorry, there were no
books. They'd been ordered, but William Morrow, my publisher,
hadn't sent them. Hoping to make me feel better, I think, the woman
confided, ``We only asked for 30. It wouldn't have been enough
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Disbelief and shock welled up in me like oil gushing from an oil
well, and instinctively I tried to keep it from overflowing into
tears. I ran into the bathroom, where I tried to get control of my
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   At the very moment of my greatest success, I couldn't help but
feel that a vengeful power had deliberately cut me down to size.
I'd made the mistake of feeling important, dared to think I was
something out of the ordinary. Not only was my publisher
indifferent, but the bookstore hadn't been expecting many people to
come. Now I heard a voice from my childhood, saying, ``Serves you
right, big shot!!'' and I buried my face in my hands, trying not to
hear the laughter at my expense. How had I dared to picture myself
equal to the authors who'd appeared before me? I was a nobody, a
middle-aged suburban housewife whose column was buried in an
obscure section of the newspaper, and now I'd been properly humbled
and humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   How in the world was I going to set foot on stage?
</P>
<P>
   I swallowed to relieve the pressure in my throat. I splashed
cold water on my eyes and stared at my reddened face in the mirror.
Four hundred-plus people had come to hear me. That was solid. That
was real. Acknowledging that fact calmed me and released me from
the grip of my own contempt. Now I could experience my longing to
connect with women who knew me as I was, not as a celebrity with an
audience, but as a person in dialogue with friends. They hadn't
come to stare at some rising star, but to become part of an
informal network of women struggling with the same issues and
dreaming the same dreams. I'd spoken from the heart to all these
folks before and now they were ready to listen from the same deep
place.
</P>
<P>
   I took a deep breath and stepped back into my life.
</P>
<P>
   When I finally went on stage, I paused for a moment, gazing out
into the hall. I located various points of safety _ my two
daughters, my husband, my sister-in-law juggling my 4-month-old
nephew on her lap, my best friend Lynn _ until all the glowing eyes
in front of me dissolved into a single promise of encouragement and
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   That's how I found my voice.
</P>
<P>
   By some quirk of fate, I have given exactly 300 talks between
that afternoon and next Wednesday at 6 p.m. when I'll be on stage
at the Boston Public Library once again. Another book, another
speech, but this time the speaker has a different outlook.
</P>
<P>
   I'm grateful those books never arrived. I now see that my pain
was actually an affront to my ego, which at the moment was engaged
in taking over the reins from my soul. The real triumph of that day
was an inner one and it resulted in a decision to redirect my
energies into more meaningful directions. I have come to believe
that the most satisfying place to be in this society is not in a
starring role, but linked with others in a mutuality that helps
everyone reach their goals.
</P>
<P>
   I have a simple philosophy E.M. Forster would be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only connect!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Linda Weltner is a freelance writer whose column appears each week
in At Home. Her new book is called ``Family Puzzles: A Private Life
Made Public'' (Innisfree Press, $13.95).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
