<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENCE ME IN FOR PRIVACY, GOOD LOOKS, AND SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good fences make good neighbors, saith the bard, although the
motives for putting up a fence vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   Some fences _ stockade, Cyclone, chain-link topped by razor wire
_ say, ``Keep out!'' and are designed to keep undesirables (dogs,
cats and maybe even neighbors) out, and desirables in; a fence is a
good way to keep your pet pooch from wandering.
</P>
<P>
   Such fences are put up for privacy, although they do reflect a
fortress mentality and are not a nice thing to look at.
</P>
<P>
   But most fences are indeed, neighborly, set on the line simply
to divide the properties. Low (four feet or so) picket fences are
ideal for this purpose. And, for privacy without intimidation, a
four-foot picket topped by lattice will do nicely.
</P>
<P>
   These fences also provide a good background for growing plants
and shrubs. And your neigbhor can do the same.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman once prposed setting up a fence between his ewstate
and but neighbor didn't like the idea, even when she was informed
that this would be pickets topped by lattice; in other words, a
neighborly, friendly fence.
</P>
<P>
   But she relented, reluctantly, but was surprised and pleased
when it finally went in place. So it pays to discuss it with yur
neighbors. An added neighborly gesture, and stylish, too, is a
gate.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever you put up a boundary fence, it is a good idea to build
it a tad back from the line, and pay for all of it. Sharing a
boundary fence with your neighbor can get sticky over time. Even
though you and he are friends, your friendship will not apply if
someone buys his property and wants to tear down the nice fence and
put up a brick wall, and wants you to pay for part of it.
</P>
<P>
   There are an infinite number of styles out there. Cedar is the
preferred wood; in fact some fence companies do nothing but cedar,
disdaining anything more or less. Some companies recommend
pressure-treated wood. So you can compromise: use pressure-treated
posts and rails, and cedar pickets. The cedar will last
indefinitely if it is allowed to dry out between wettings.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing? At the risk of being politically incorrect, I venture
that women, it seems, dream of a nice, white picket fence, and that
means regular staining or painting and sanding and scraping and
cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Why not leave it alone, as a fence should be? Both woods _ cedar
and pressure-treated _ will weather nicely without decaying, and
absolutey no maintenance is needed. Even spruce, often used in
economy type stockade fences, weathers well.
</P>
<P>
   And, to repeat, any wood that gets wet but is able to dry out
between wettings, will last indefinitely. The biggest failure in
fences occur in the posts, if they are cedar and buried in the
ground. Other failures may occur due to the way the fence was
built. If pickets and other components are nailed to rails so that
water collects and stays in the joints, then decay will occur.
</P>
<P>
   Fences cost $10 and up per lineal foot; about half that if you
buy the materials (at any fence builder) and put it up yourself.
</P>
<P>
   A big aid to putting up a fence these days are Post Ups, a steel
stake 24, 30 and 36 inches long and topped by as steel box big
enough to hold a 4x4 post. Such shanks are cross-shaped and
relatively easy to drive into the ground by inserting a short 4x4
in the box and driving it with a sledge hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Secure the post and you're home free.
</P>
<P>
   You have to locate the posts fairly accurately, but they are
easy to drive, if you don't run into any stones. Sometimes the
driven stake will bypass a stone, although it might slope a little,
even twist, something you can avoid by redriving the stake.
</P>
<P>
   If you hit a rock, pull up the Post Up and see if you can dig up
the rock. Avoid driving the stake come hell or high water, trying
to break through the stone or circumvent it; it almost never works,
and you will end up with a stake that has a perfect U shape at its
point. The handyman has one such bent stake in his trophy case,
just like Alvin York's rifle gun when lightning hit it. Remember
the movie?
</P>
<P>
   Building your own fence not only saves money, but allows you to
make your own design, and just as important, allows a random
spacing of posts, which may be required, depending on how many
stones you hit or the lay of the land. However random you make the
posts, don't space them more than 10 feet apart; eight is better.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, if you build a fence up or down a slope, do not
slope the fence itself; it will look very strange. All posts should
be plumb (vertical, straight up and down) and each section of rails
between posts should be level, so you will have to step the fence,
setting one section level at one height, and the second also level
at a higher or lower height, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Fences designs are infinite. Examples:
</P>
<P>
   Pickets spaced half an inch on rails for air circulation and
some privacy. Use two or three rails, depending on the height of
the fence. You can buy pickets up to six feet long, with tops that
are square, fleur de lis, plain curved or Gothic. The curved tops
are better than square ones because they shed more water than
square tops. Or, put an rail on top of the square-topped pickets,
protecting them from water.
</P>
<P>
   Set 2x4 rails between posts with joist hangers.
</P>
<P>
   A design variation is a two-foot-high strip of pressure-treated
lattice on top of four-foot pickets, giving you six feet of good
looks and privacy. Six feet is usually the maximum height for a
fence. Check with your community for height limits and other
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are board-on-board fences, with a vertical 1x6 or 1x8
on one side, spaced six or seven inches by similar boards covering
the gap. This gives nearly total privacy but allows air
circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a woven fence will hit the spot. These are boards
woven along upright pieces. It will take more careful fastening to
keep the curved boards, which are under tension, from springing
back.
</P>
<P>
   Getting any fancier increases the cost, except for a picket
fence with a catenary curve or arc. Catenary is from the Latin word
katena, meaning chain. To achieve a catenary curve, suspend a chain
from two posts; it will hang naturally in a catenary curve. It will
be a natural curve whether you make it long and shallow or short
and steep. Once this curve is established, transfer it to the
pickets all in a row and cut them to match.
</P>
<P>
   A bonus for a solid fence is that it is a sound barrier, sort
of, by deflecting sounds up and away from the fence. A brick wall
would be better, but that is another story.
</P>
<P>
   Two more points:
</P>
<P>
   1. It is a tradition (no laws) for the builder to face the
smooth side toward his neighbor as a goodwill gesture. That is
nice, but thinking about it, the unsmooth side, with rails and
other structural members showing, is more interesting than the
smooth side.
</P>
<P>
   2. A long, straight fence looks nice, but may tend to lean over
after a few years. To avoid this, and to give the fence a
sculptured, architectural look, set the fence in a series of jigs
and jogs: Set one section straight and level; set another to turn
at right angles for one to two feet, then a straight line, and
another jog back to the original plane of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   This technique also helps you to make a jog aroud a tree that
sets smack in the middle of the fence line.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to paint it, don't. Instead, use a stain: a solid
color latex stain will give you a good white color; two coats are
neded, but no primer. All you have to worry about is cedar bleed.
</P>
<P>
   Or, better yet, use a semitransparent stain. One coat is needed
and you can recoat in four to five years without having to scrape
and stain. You can't get white in a semitransparent stain, but you
can get a pleasant light gray and other pastel and earth colors.
</P>
<P>
   Do fence me in!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
