<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIL-ORDER NURSERIES IN NORTHWEST EXPLORE NEW DIRECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The residential streets of Seattle and Portland, Ore., are alive
with front-yard rock gardens, Japanese maple groves, and clambering
clematis vines, signaling a population that can grow almost
anything. Long a national center for the wholesale shrub and tree
business, the Pacific Northwest now pulses with a new excitement.
Combining entrepreneurial spirit and ideal growing conditions, the
region has given birth to a crop of mail-order nurseries
specializing in rare and hard-to-find plants.
</P>
<P>
   With a group of fellow plant lovers, I recently criss-crossed
Washington state and Oregon on a Horticulture magazine tour of the
region's top nurseries. As plant fever tightened its grip, young
trees, shrubs, and perennials boarded along with their new owners,
filling every spare seat and many a lap.
</P>
<P>
   Because these nurseries are run by enthusiasts who started out
with large gardens and then went into business to support the
hobby, most have knockout display gardens that allowed us to see
mature specimens. The hot plants among importers and hybridizers
that will evenually be appearing in local garden centers included
epimediums, perennial geraniums, Asian jack-in-the-pulpits,
pulmonarias, and, most of all, hellebores in new colors. It seemed,
too, that breeders were more excited by colored foliage than
flowers. Everywhere we went, we saw old-fashioned flowers deemed
exciting because of foliage in new colors: feverfew and columbine
with chartreuse foliage; buttercups and cow parsnips with maroon
leaves; heuchera with three or four colors on a single leaf. Trees
and shrubs had greenery edged or flecked with white or yellow so
they looked as if they were in permanent bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Differences in climate, shipping costs (which average about 30
percent), and the stress plants undergo when mailed are all major
reasons why it's better to buy locally grown plants when possible.
But if you're an ``early adapter'' who likes to be the first with a
trendy plant, a horticulturalist looking for the unusual or
underappreciated, or a collector focusing on a certain genre, then
this nursery list is for you. Here is the best of the Northwest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Heirloom Old Garden Roses. &LR;  24062 N.E. Riverside Drive, St.
Paul, OR 97137; 503-538-1576; fax 503-538-5902; open daily. The
lush $5 catalog has color photos of many of the 700 varieties of
roses offered. Plants are propagated and shipped year-round.
</P>
<P>
   This 12-year-old rose nursery is one of the few that propagates
and sells rose varieties grown on their own roots. (Lowes Own Root
Roses, 6 Sheffield Road, Nashua, NH 03062, is another.) That's
important, says owner Louise Clements, because the technique keeps
roses free of a virus that affects many roses commercially grafted
onto diseased rootstock. Clements's customers say her roses are
longer lived and more vigorous. Fifteen hundred roses are on
display on her family's farm near Portland, which is well worth a
visit between May and August. Old-fashioned roses are prized for
fragrance and the lemon scented resin on old moss roses melds with
the clove fragrance of Rosa moschata and the myrrh of David Austin
roses as you wander through 3 acres of color and perfume.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Collector's Nursery. &LR;  16804 NE 102d Ave., Battle Ground, WA
98604; 360-574-3832; fax 360-571-8540; catalog $2; Ships spring and
fall.
</P>
<P>
   This nine-year-old home nursery is doing fantastic things. Bill
Janssen was a gem prospector before he switched to searching out
exotic plants. He breeds hostas. His wife Diana Reeck breeds
epimediums. She's an ex-hippy and amateur botanist who's gone to
Yunnan Province in southwest China twice to collect rare seeds.
He's an artist who has made the garden his palette. In their areas
of specialization _ woodland plants and dwarf conifers _ their
offerings are rare, exotic, and inexpensive. If you want to add
some scary-looking Asian jack-in-the-pulpits to your staid woodland
garden, this is the catalog to order. And the 2-acre home display
garden is a marvel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Russell Graham Nursery &LR; , 4030 Eagle Crest Road NW, Salem, OR
97304. Spring and fall catalogs $2. Shipping resumes in late
August.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne and Russell Graham _ he's a retired motor vehicle
department manager _ believe in low overhead and low tech. They
have a devoted following among gardeners looking for hard-to-find
woodland plants, field grown and shipped bare rooted. This is the
place for Cardiocrinum giganteum bulbs, English violas, primroses,
or woodland wildflowers at prices just short of amazing. If you
visit, you'll find a modest old frame house and barn, perennial
gardens, and bluebirds and tree swallows skimming over meadows
against a breathtaking view of Mount Hood. Write for visiting days.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gossler Farms Nursery &LR; , 1200 Weaver Road, Springfield, OR
97478-9691; 541-746-3922 for orders or questions 8 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Pacific Standard Time; fax 541-744-7924; catalog $2; shipping
season October to mid-December and February to April; visits by
appointment only.
</P>
<P>
   This family home business includes three homes, one each for
brothers Roger and Eric, and one for their mom, Marj, linked by an
exquisitely designed display garden of 5,000 plants.
</P>
<P>
   You'd have to look pretty hard to find a nurseryman as nice or
as knowledgeable as Roger Gossler, especially on his specialty,
ornamental trees and shrubs. If you call him up and he doesn't have
what you want, he says he'll try to suggest someone who does. He
grows everything he sells in his home garden before he markets it
to make sure it performs well, making this catalog small but
select. One of the plants he's currently testing is a mutant yellow
Boston ivy called Parthenocissus tricuspidata Fenway Park that
Arnold Arboretum horticulturalist Peter Del Tredici spotted growing
near the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Greer Gardens &LR; , 1280 Goodpasture Island Road, Eugene, OR
97401-1794; customer service, 541-686-8266; fax, 541-686-0910; to
order the $3 catalog with full-color photographs, 800-548-0111;
open seven days a week; shipping year-round.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This is the catalog to order if you like one-stop shopping
with color pictures, though with more than 3,000 trees, shrubs,
vines, perennials, orchids, bamboos, ornamental grasses, and bonsai
and rock garden plants offered, only a tiny percentage can be
pictured. This is a large traditional nursery that tries to offer
everything and uses subcontractors to grow much of its stock.
Still, within the soup-to-nuts framework, the areas of special
depth reflect owner Harold Greer's passions: rhododendrons (700!),
Japanese maples, magnolias. Favorite features are the discounted
``frugal-dendron'' and ``frugal azaleas'' listings. ``Breakfast at
Tiffany's on an Egg McMuffin Budget,'' the catalog calls them. The
3-acre display garden features many mature trees and is open to the
public year round.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Forestfarm &LR; , 990 Tetherow Road, Williams, OR 97544-9599;
orders, 541-846-7269; problems and fax orders, 541-846-6963;
catalog $4, ship air year round.
</P>
<P>
   This nursery is more like a cause than a business. While
everyone else is growing trendy hellebores, idealistic Ray and Peg
Prag try to grow useful plants that other nurseries disdain. Their
catalog is full of little horticulture lessons that make good
reading. Offerings are coded to tell you if a plant is useful for
basketweaving, dying, bee pollination, and all sorts of things you
wouldn't think of asking. The couple's emphasis is native plants
and they grow most of the thousands of types they offer in their
book-size catalog without using middle-man suppliers. The 30 young
employees are treated as a communal family and when we visited they
had a bonfire celebrating the end of winter, a European tradition
observed to honor interns from the Czech Republic, Hungary, and
France. Remotely located, they welcome visitors warmly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Siskiyou Rare Plant Nursery &LR; , 2825 Cummings Road, Medford, OR
97501; 541-772-6846 Tuesdays-Fridays 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; color
catalog $3 with spring and fall supplements; fax 541-772-4917;
e-mail:  &UR; srpn(AT)wa &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; ve.net &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   This home nursery, which also propagates most of its own plants,
has been a wellspring for rock gardeners and lovers of alpines. The
nearby Siskiyou Mountains were a source for many of the wild seeds
grown and distributed by the two postal employees who started the
business 35 years ago. In 1978 a California architect named
Baldasarre Mineo came for a visit and ended up buying the business.
The beautiful display garden covers 2 acres and includes a rock
garden by designer Josef Halda. The fall catalog, mailed out in
August, carries the country's largest selection of erythroniums and
anemones. Open to visitors the first and last Saturdays of March
through November or by appointment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Joy Creek Nursery. &LR;  20300 NW Watson Road, Scappoose, OR 07056.
503-543-7474. Catalog is $2 with a fall supplement. Open daily 9
a.m.-5 p.m., March through October.
</P>
<P>
   This six-year-old nursery is on the brink of going big-time. It
tries to carry a comprehensive listing of the best new perennials,
with a specialization in rock garden plants and unusual clematis
vines. The three owners wear different hats. Scott Christy is the
horticulturalist. Mike Smith is the businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Horn, who has a theater background, is in charge of
sales. The display gardens are delightful. The owners assumed they
were too far outside Portland to attract retail trade, but local
gardeners have sought them out and now the majority of their
business comes from that and landscaping, though their mail-order
business continues to double annually.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Heronswood Nursery Ltd. &LR;  7530 NE 288th St., Kingston, WA 98346;
360-297-4172; fax 360-297-8321. Web site,
 &UR; www.eskimo.com/ &UR; GFtilde &LR; mcalpin/ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; heron/heron.html &LR; . The catalog is $5 for two years. The nursery
ships mail orders Feb. 1-May 15 and mid-September to Nov. 1.
On-site visits by appointment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Although only 10 years old, this catalog carries the largest
offering of perennials in the country and has been immensely
influential. Heronswood is viewed by plant connoisseurs as the
Cadillac of catalogs, listing 2,800 species of plants. Dan Hinkley
travels the globe procuring plant seed from the wild, and since
many of the plants he then grows are unknown to the nursery trade
and the catalog has no pictures, each order arrives like a surprise
package. ``I want to get botany back into horticulture,'' said
Hinkley. But high-style design also has a place at Heronswood. A
faux Eygyptian ruin is one new addition to the 12 gardens that
surround his home with colored foliage and rare plants. Hinkley's
catalog prose is unique. Each spring he turns out 265 pages of
gonzo plant descriptions written in caffeine-fueled spurts between
4 and 6 a.m. (``Geranium endressii `Hot Pink': From a seedling that
originated here, perhaps more true to the nature of the species
itself, with weeks of zappy, zingy, I got steam-m-m heat, flowers
above somewhat felted leaves,'' goes one entry, warning, ``Not for
the meek.'')
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Northwest Gardeners' Resource Directory &LR;  by Stephanie
Feeney, available by mail for $22.95 from Cedarcroft Press, 59
Strawberry Point., Bellingham, WA 98226, offers updated
compilations of nurseries, plant sales, garden shows, and
horticultural organizations invaluable for any gardener visiting or
living in western Oregon, Washington state, or British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Horticulture Magazine Tours  &LR; information is available at
800-395-1901, or write Horticulture Garden Programs, 98 North
Washington St., Boston, MA 02114, or visit the Web site at
 &UR; www.hortmag.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
