<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF THE SCHOOL YEAR BRING OUT EMOTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not exactly something the Centers for Disease Control
documents, and it doesn't show up in emergency rooms, but anecdotal
evidence points to a little-known phenomenon that affects children
every year at about this time: As the end of school gets closer,
preschoolers become more accident prone, schoolage children become
more sickly.
</P>
<P>
   Children of all ages have a love-hate relationship with the end
of school. Even though there is joyful excitement ala ``No more
pencils, no more books, no more teachers' dirty looks,'' there is
also dread. Few children make it through the transition to summer
without feeling some sadness, confusion, or anger about the loss of
structure, routine, familiar faces, and familiar places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met a kid who isn't affected somehow, sooner or
later,'' says developmental psychologist Charles Flatter of the
University of Maryland. For many kids, the blip passes so quickly
parents don't even notice. But for others, loss and uncertainty
take a toll.
</P>
<P>
   Every June, preschool educational director Mary Ucci anticipates
a proliferation of scrapes and bruises. She reminds her staff at
the Child Study Center at Wellesley College to be more alert than
usual, not just to physical red flags but also to emotional ones.
``Because preschoolers are upset about change, they're emotionally
distracted,'' she says. ``They're not paying attention and they
fall down more.''
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Benton, principal of the Fiske Elementary School in
Lexington, sees more stomachaches, headaches, and minor ailments in
June, especially in first, second, and third grades. ``It's related
to the stress of transition,'' she says. ``I tell parents not to
keep a child home unless there's a fever.''
</P>
<P>
   Younger children tend to be transparent. Ucci recalls, ``Last
year, one 4-year-old sat on the swing and sobbed, `I'm not going to
see my Mary Ruth anymore.' It doesn't take a lot to figure out
what's going on there.'' (Mary Ruth was her teacher.)
</P>
<P>
   Preschoolers are just as likely to exhibit anger as they are
sadness, though, and that can take parents and teachers by
surprise. ``If you're not a seasoned teacher, it's pretty hard to
hear a 4-year-old tell you, `I don't like your long hair!' `I don't
like your big teeth!''' says Ucci, who says these outbursts are a
defense mechanism against the hurt and loss they're feeling.
``They're so angry and sad to leave that they have to find reasons
not to like it or you anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Struggling with such powerful feelings fuels regression. Ucci's
antidote is to offer soothing, simple activities. ``We go back to
basics, markers and papers, instead of collages,'' she says. At
home, she urges parents not to deny the feelings or try to talk a
child out of them. Offer support instead: ``Don't yell or
humiliate. Tie their shoes, pour the juice, and say, `I know you
will miss school, and we'll help you.'''
</P>
<P>
   With older children, Flatter says there are two mistakes parents
and teachers typically make.
</P>
<P>
   The first is to pay attention only to kids in marker years _
those leaving kindergarten or elementary or middle school. ``Kids
in every grade need help with closure. Just because they've done it
before doesn't make it easier,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Benton says first graders frequently have the hardest time.
``They're finally getting comfortable with the work and it dawns on
them it will be even harder in second grade,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth graders may be developmentally more vulnerable to sadness
than other children, especially if they will be leaving the school
in one more year, because they're able to sense what next year's
loss will be like, says developmental psychologist Amy
Susman-Stillman of the University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Flatter, whose area of speciality is school-age
children, says the end of the year gets harder as children get
older. ``Friendships are stronger and more significant. Even
separating for the summer can be a blow,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The second mistake parents make is to not connect the onset of
grumpy, oppositional behavior to loss.
</P>
<P>
   Flatter says for some kids, ``There's an emotional discomfort
that fuels a regression and makes them literally feel sick.''
That's what can lead to the kind of physical ailments Benton sees.
</P>
<P>
   For others, the loss will hit like a ton of schoolbooks sometime
in the first weeks of no-school. ``Without reason to look at a
calendar, they literally doesn't know what day it is,'' says
Flatter. There's a feeling of panic: ``How do I organize myself?
How do I give meaning to my time?''
</P>
<P>
   The more teachers provide rituals in the last weeks of school,
the easier the transition can be.
</P>
<P>
   At Fiske, children in every grade write a letter to the incoming
class. ``It provides closure and a chance to see their own
accomplishments,'' says Benton. Kids in all grades also participate
in a self-assessment, writing what was good and bad about the year.
Benton also urges teachers to keep routines and limit-setting in
place, including homework, down to the last week. ``Familiarity and
consistency count,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, once school ends, it is the lack of routine and the lack
of expectations that often gets kids of any age into trouble, says
Flatter. ``A kind of depression can set in,'' he says. The more you
set expectations around such things as bedtimes, TV, and morning
routines, and the more you include children in the planning of
activites, the better they'll do.
</P>
<P>
   Sure signs that a child is having difficulty include unusual
moodiness and oppositional behavior, unusual nastiness to a
sibling, and endless time in front of the TV or computer.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're tuned in and recognize this as a sign of the
sadness and loss your child is feeling, your child probably won't,
says Susman-Stillman. ``Especially not a boy. Even if they feel
sad, they won't admit it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Parents need to be proactive. ``Assume they are having a
reaction,'' Susman-Stillman says. ``Every child needs some
recognition of the change they are experiencing.'' But don't
approach it head-on with a direct question, as in, ``Do you think
you're missing/are going to miss school?'' A more oblique approach
works better: ``Even though most kids are glad school is over,
sometimes they miss their friends/a favorite teacher/a favorite
subject more than they expect to.'' That normalizes the experience
for a child and gives him permission to feel what he's feeling.
However, Susman-Stillman adds, it doesn't mean he will necessarily
share it with you.
</P>
<P>
   Provide the opportunity, nonetheless. She recommends a family
ritual, for instance, a dinner with relatives where each child
makes a short presentation about the school year.
</P>
<P>
   While older children may mope around in the first week or two
after school, preschoolers may be fine for two or three weeks,
then, out of the blue, something makes it concrete for them. ``They
realize, `Oh, no! I'm not going back there,' and sadness hits,''
says Ucci.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the time to talk about the future. ``Acknowledge the
feelings of the present first, which is the loss,'' she says. Pull
out the book of accomplishments that most preschoolers will have
made at the end of the year: ``Look at all you learned! Look at the
friends you made!'' Only then, she says, can you look forward: ``I
bet you'll make friends in kindergarten, too!''
</P>
<P>
   For children leaving a school, there is usually plenty of
ritual. The Fiske School has two months of activities for
graduating fifth graders, including a yearbook that Benton works on
with them. It's not unusual for feelings to surface in the course
of the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely loss and anxiety for all of them,'' she
says. ``The best thing you can do is get it out in the open.''
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Eighty percent of all kids stop playing organized
youth sports by the time they're 12. They burn out young because
they start so young and feel so much pressure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Child Caring appears every Thursday in At Home. Barbara F. Meltz
welcomes letters and comments and can be reached via e-mail at
meltz(AT)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
