<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY 103-YEAR-OLD COLLEAGUE HAS THE RIGHT ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when I think that, career-wise, the finish line is looming,
I find a story in the Denver Post about a 103-year-old newspaper
columnist. By that standard I've barely begun working.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Nix Leo of Howard, Kan., has been writing for newspapers
since she was a teenager. She now writes a column for the weekly
Elk County Citizen-Advance News, and another for the monthly
magazine Tallgrass Country. In her spare time she writes her church
newsletter. ``I find that the older I get, I am more aware of the
brightness of everything,'' she wrote recently. ``I look for
beauty, adventure, discovery, and push for increasing knowledge
that awakens me to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Bless her heart. That must be the kind of attitude it takes to
keep on doing this job until you're 103, which means that my own
career prospects are getting dimmer by the minute. Can I help it if
I'm drawn in a different direction? I used to wonder if I'd reach a
point when I'd run out of column ideas, but the older I get, the
more aware I am of how many people are taking leave of their
senses, and in public too, so that running out of ideas is
impossible, no matter how hard I try.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Ralph Lauren's suit against Polo, the magazine of the
US Polo Association. Apparently Lauren owns the word polo, or
thinks he does, and has taken umbrage at the magazine's use of it.
Polo, the publication, was recently redesigned, and Lauren claims
in his suit that it now focuses ``not on equestrian sports but on
sophisticated fashions and elegant lifestyles,'' which he considers
his turf.
</P>
<P>
   And whose image has Lauren been trading upon? If anybody has a
case here it would seem to be the polo-playing set, whose style
Lauren has been ripping off for years. The suit is incredibly
stupid, but the spectacle of a lot of rich people fighting over a
four-letter word is gratifying, in a way. Maybe they should change
the name of the centuries-old sport to ralph. (``I keep a string of
ralph ponies up at Hamilton ...'')
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of being incredibly stupid, who advised Monica Lewinsky
to pose in a swimsuit in the forthcoming July issue of Vanity Fair?
Actually the item, as reported in USA Today, didn't promise Monica
in a swimsuit but in a ``beach layout,'' which could mean just
about anything. Her public image can't get much worse than it is,
so I suppose the exposure can't hurt, especially since USA Today
reports that ``the raven-haired ex-intern looks fabulous in the
Herb Ritts shots.'' I can hardly wait for the issue to hit the
stands. Next up has to be Playboy's ``Girls of Clinton'' issue,
with Monica, Gennifer Flowers, Paula Jones et al.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Viagra, but what doesn't these days? I have
here the first, but certainly not the last, Viagra book, ``Viagra:
A Guide to the Phenomenal Potency-Promoting Drug.'' It's a curious
volume indeed. My favorite chapter? ``Evaluating Impotence,'' which
asks the reader to think of the problem as a game of Clue. No
kidding. The first step to determining the cause of sexual
dysfunction ``is to gather all the evidence,'' writes the author,
psychiatrist Susan C. Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn continues, a few paragraphs on, ``Certain clues would
lead us to consider Professor Plum the prime suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Plum is the probable culprit if dysfunction is brought
on by psychological factors. Colonel Mustard gets into the act a
few paragraphs later, when the cause is organic. And no, I'm not
making this up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viagra may reduce the need for some aspects of detective
work,'' Vaughn writes. This is something to be thankful for,
especially since the doctor suggests that one way to solve the
mystery is to ask your partner ``to stay awake all night and
monitor your manhood's whereabouts at all times.'' Maybe some
mysteries are better left unsolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
