<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SNOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRMAN CROCKER SNOW WRITES ABOUT THE EARLY DAYS OF FLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID MEHEGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOG BOOK &QC; 
A Pilot's Life &QC; 
By Crocker Snow &QC; 
Brassey's, 290 pp., illustrated, $29.95 &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crocker Snow is one of those people whose lifetimes coincide
with a particular historical epoch in such a way as to reveal it.
He saw his first airplane flight in 1910, was flying a biplane
himself in 1926, and managed to participate in virtually every
aspect of aeronautical development, military and civilian, from
that point until his retirement in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a prosperous Boston lawyer, Snow went to Harvard, but
dropped out of the law school to follow in the footsteps of his
older brothers, Bill and Kitchell (``Kick''), who were both
flying-mad. Bill flew air patrol in Europe during World War I,
while Kick's postwar civilian flying career ended tragically when
he was killed on takeoff from the new East Boston airfield in 1923.
Determined not to be restrained by that tragedy, Crocker Snow
persisted.
</P>
<P>
   He and a group of friends founded the Harvard Aeronautical
Society, an informal club that gave many of them their first taste
of buying, outfitting, and regularly flying planes. In 1928, Snow
and several friends went into business with Skyways Inc., a company
set up to sell planes, give lessons, and carry passengers. The
business petered out toward the end of the Depression, as did many
of the hundreds of small aircraft companies that blossomed in the
optimistic 1920s as software start-ups do today.
</P>
<P>
   In 1934, at the request of Governor Joseph Ely, Snow proposed a
code of aviation law that would rationalize the chaotic state of
relatively unregulated flying. Though the bill failed while James
Michael Curley was governor, a new version was enacted under the
Saltonstall administration in 1939. When the bill became law, Snow
was asked to run the state's new aeronautics commission.
</P>
<P>
   Snow returned to that job in 1946, but had, you might say, a few
adventures in between. In 1941, on the eve of war, Snow (as an
experienced Army Air Corps Reserve officer) was asked to help set
up ferry routes between North America and England by which aircraft
and supplies could be moved to Europe. He and his teammates flew
and charted routes from Presque Isle, Maine, to Goose Bay,
Labrador, then to Greenland, Iceland, and finally Prestwick,
England, setting up the fields and devising procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In 1943 he was named commander of a B-17 bomber group then
forming in Tennessee, but was transferred to a training job before
it went into action in Europe. In early 1944, he was assigned to
the Pacific theater and became commander of the 498th Bombing
Group. After service in the campaign against Japan, Snow came home
to resume a long career in the development of civil and commercial
aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Snow has a perky and brisk style, and his account of his career
is thick with details about particular planes, flights, and
anecdotes. Although his own life is in the foreground, and aviation
history in the background, what comes through most clearly are
these details _ how planes were made, what they were like to fly _
and a succession of hard-learned facts about flying itself. Even
the death of Snow's brother Kick is followed by the author's
observation that in the event of a total power loss right after
takeoff (which is what happened to Kick's plane), the best measure
is to try for a straight-ahead crash landing instead of attempting
a 180-degree turn without power. Kick would have known that, we're
told; the author suspects he had been afraid that his passengers
might drown in the harbor if he ditched. This sort of common-sense
resourcefulness, combined with a determination to move on to the
next challenge and adventure, makes this book a fascinating
account.
</P>
<P>
   Not much about Snow's deeper views and social world gets into
the book, but now and then we get a glimpse. He acknowledges that
``my own family lifestyle was hardly affected'' by the Depression.
He plays polo and seems to have had a fine time in those lean
years. He blames the New Deal, especially the National Recovery
Administration, for ruining the climate for companies like Skyways.
He allows that Roosevelt's ``Date of Infamy'' speech after Pearl
Harbor ``was just right for the occasion,'' while mentioning that
he had never voted for Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   It is always clear that nothing in Crocker Snow's life that he
wanted to do was closed to him. He had the contacts and the money,
or access to the money, to do what he wanted. And of course, unlike
the case with so many free spirits of his generation, his luck
held. Still, what he wanted to do was to be successful and useful
in war and peace, and he assuredly was. His is a fascinating
American story, all about restlessness on the ground, all about the
yen to take off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
