<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-04 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FOLLY OF CAMPAIGN-FINANCE `REFORM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF JACOBY 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They want to ban ``soft money.'' They want to control political
advertising by noncandidates. They speak appealingly of ``reform,''
of ``closing loopholes,'' of ``preventing special interests from
buying elections.'' They are, no doubt, sincere.
</P>
<P>
   But for all their good intentions, what the campaign-finance
crusaders demand will only make campaign finance more corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   US Representatives Christopher Shays and Martin Meehan are
getting lots of good press for their efforts to push through the
House of Representatives a law overhauling campaign spending rules.
Last fall, when the action was in the other chamber, it was
Senators John McCain and Russell Feingold who were getting the
applause. But McCain-Feingold and Shays-Meehan are not the first
campaign finance bills under the sun, and if the history of such
laws teaches anything, it is that they boomerang. With a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974 and 1976, Congress determined to deodorize federal
campaigns once and for all. Then as now, the talk was of halting
corruption and closing loopholes and reining in the power of money.
To those ends, the post-Watergate reformers decreed that individual
contributions would be held to just $1,000 per candidate per
election. Political action committees would be allowed to give
$5,000. A cap was placed on the total amount a donor could donate
to all candidates in any one year. What resulted from all this
cleaning up was the system that Shays and Meehan now say needs
cleaning up.
</P>
<P>
   Because politicians could no longer accept more than $1,000 from
any single donor, they were forced to fund-raise more obsessively
than ever. Because PACs could give five times as much as
individuals, PACs became five times as influential. Office-seekers,
desperate for cash, no longer had time to ``waste'' on mere $25 and
$50 donors. The superwealthy, blocked from freely donating to
candidates they liked, searched for a loophole through which they
could contribute liberally _ and found it in the parties'
unrestricted ``building funds'': soft money.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of dollars in politics didn't shrink after the
1970s-era changes _ it expanded. The new laws didn't make it easier
for challengers of modest means to get elected _ they made it
virtually impossible. And the power of special interests wasn't
curbed _ it was entrenched.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing will happen if Shays-Meehan becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   Congress can plug the soft money loophole. It can make it harder
for advocacy groups and unions to run TV and radio commercials. It
can make reporting requirements more intricate. In so doing, it may
well dissuade minor donors and political amateurs from getting
involved in campaigns at all.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing Congress does can stop those who have money to spend
on politics and the motivation to spend that money. When the stakes
are high enough, there are always means of funneling aid to
politicians. If not directly, then through a PAC. And if not a PAC,
then through independent TV spots. Or in-kind contributions. Or a
hired army of sign holders. Or a get-out-the-vote phone bank. Or
jobs for the politician's brother-in-law. Or a rented Goodyear
blimp flashing ``VOTE FOR THROTTLEBOTTOM,'' if that's what it
takes.
</P>
<P>
   No election ``reform'' is going to keep money out of campaigns.
No new law is going to suppress the ability of the wealthy and the
well-connected to buy access to office-holders. In political
participation as in everything else, there are inequalities.
Shays-Meehan cannot eliminate them, but it can make them worse.
</P>
<P>
   What is corrupting our politics is not money. It is a government
grown so powerful and intrusive that virtually anyone with
interests to safeguard feels the need to pay protection money to
politicians. With outlays of $1.8 trillion, Washington consumes
more than one-fifth of the wealth Americans produce each year.
There is virtually no activity or product that is safe from federal
interference. A line in the federal budget can destroy a company _
or treble its income. Change a phrase in the tax code, and scores
of workers lose their jobs. A thousand local enterprises rise or
fall on the decision of a committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Washington controls everything from mushroom standards to
computer exports to gallons-per-toilet-flush. Corporations, unions,
and interest groups know that the people in the White House and the
Capitol can do them great harm. Is it any surprise that they are
willing to pay so much to stay in their good graces?
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal last week reported on 144 individuals
who contributed $5.4 million in the last three years to the PAC of
Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader. ``I gave because I have an
interest in how he votes on maritime issues,'' one donor said. ``If
you give them money,'' said another, ``they return your calls.'' A
third: ``We saw it as a way of life in Washington.'' A fourth: ``We
thought it would be a chance to get the issue in front of Senator
Lott. We wanted to see it passed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Journal could have picked any other group of donors to
virtually any other federal politician. The quotes would have been
the same.
</P>
<P>
   The planted axiom of campaign finance ``reform'' is that it is
possible to devise a system in which men and women whose well-being
depends on political access won't spend great sums to purchase that
access. Such a system has never existed and never will. If Shays
and Meehan really want to get money out of politics, let them bend
their efforts to getting government out of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Jacoby is a columnist for the Boston Globe. His e-mail
address is jacoby(AT)globe.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
