<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3973 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DATING-RULES-SPI &LR;      06-04 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATING-RULES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO OPPOSING BOOKS FORM BATTLE LINES OVER DATING RULES  
 (WITH DATING-LIST) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TERESA TALERICO  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To call or not to call?
</P>
<P>
   Does the guy pay or do you go Dutch?
</P>
<P>
   Who makes the first move when your eyes meet?
</P>
<P>
   And what about sex on the first date?
</P>
<P>
   The best-seller lists have plenty of answers to these questions
and other dating advice for women these days. Guides to finding Mr.
Right have sprung up on bookstore shelves everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But many of these self-professed romance-guru authors give
conflicting insights into the male psyche.
</P>
<P>
   So who _ and what _ to believe?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rules'' by Ellen Fein and Sherrie Schneider (Mass Market
Paperback, 174 pages, $5.99), hit the shelves in 1995 and created a
stir (and a sequel last year) with its ultraconservative advice for
women.
</P>
<P>
   In April came a new book, ``What Men Want'' (Cliff Street Books,
192 pages, $19), written by three guys as a rebuttal to ``The
Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Gerstman, Christopher Pizzo and Rich Seldes _
respectively, a lawyer, accountant and doctor _ reveal what they
think single men are really after when looking for Ms. Right or Ms.
Right Now.
</P>
<P>
   The advice in these two books is often hilariously _ or sadly _
disparate. As different as Mars and Venus? Try a whole other
galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at how technology has advanced, the one thing that
hasn't advanced is the communication gap between men and women,''
said Gerstman, 30. ``All these books out there seem to widen it.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Rules,'' Fein and Schneider take a demure, 1950s
approach in their advice to women. Look pretty and brush up on your
current events, girls! Wear lipstick even when you jog. Never
approach him first. Don't call him. Let him pick movies and
restaurants. And even after you're an official couple, heavens to
Betsy, don't initiate sex.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa! Of course the guys had to strike back _ although it did
take the big lugs three years to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of ``What Men Want'' say they ``break the male code
of silence'' when it comes to dating, women and romance. The trio
reveal how a woman can read signs that show whether she's a ``good
for now girl'' or a woman with ``wife potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerstman and Pizzo were in Seattle last week for a taping of
KOMO-TV's ``Town Meeting'' scheduled to air on June 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to know a man's point of view, you come to a man
himself,'' Gerstman said. ``A lot of guys don't say the things they
really feel. We try to articulate them in ways a woman can
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerstman et al., advise women thusly:
</P>
<P>
   _ Playing hard to get, as ``The Rules'' advocates, is sure to
turn guys off. The trio calls it ``Machiavellian.''
</P>
<P>
   _ It's OK to approach men. It's cool to make the first move.
Guys are sometimes bashful little boys and scared of rejection.
</P>
<P>
   _ Men appreciate women who take initiative.
</P>
<P>
   _ You can call him first. For some guys, it's a relief.
</P>
<P>
   _ As for women initiating sex _ pretty please. Just don't act
like you're in a porn movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're throwing up the white flag here,'' Gerstman said. ``The
theory of (``The Rules'') is to make a man chase. But by making a
man chase, what he's in love with is the chase and not the woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is some practical advice in ``The Rules'': Don't
date a married man. Don't cling. Have your own life and
independence.
</P>
<P>
   And if the ``ugly truths'' listed in ``What Men Want'' are
indeed reality, perhaps it's no wonder the women of ``The Rules''
resort to forms of manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gerstman, Pizzo and Seldes, guys:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cheat on women they love.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use women for sex.
</P>
<P>
   _ Value a woman's looks over almost everything else.
</P>
<P>
   _ Are driven by their sex urge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Would never marry if they didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   The authors are unapologetic about these ``truths,'' which they
present as self-evident. And judging from the way the book ends,
there is no reason to change them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that brings us to No. 18 in ``The Rules'': Don't try
to change him.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make a single woman cry, ``Yikes, where's the
nearest convent?''
</P>
<P>
   But there is hope. ``The Rules'' and ``What Men Want'' do agree
on a few things:
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't open up too quickly with a new love interest _ as in
telling on the first date everything about your ex-boyfriends,
dysfunctional family or recovery from alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't have sex too soon _ unless you're just interested in a
casual fling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't pressure your partner.
</P>
<P>
   _ And above all, honesty still ranks high _ for both sexes _ no
matter what the current dating trends might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just be real,'' say Gerstman and his writing partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't lie,'' write Fein and Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   Phew. At least some things never go out of style.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
