<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3975 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUG-EXHIBIT-HNS &LR;      06-04 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-EXHIBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTO EXHIBIT FOCUSES ON PUNISHMENTS FOR DRUG OFFENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A polemical photo exhibit, ``Human Rights and
the Drug War,'' views federal drug policy prescribing mandatory
minimum sentences, even for first offenders, through the lens of
the Bill of Rights and the United Nations declaration on human
rights and finds it abhorrent.
</P>
<P>
   While the American drug policies are not as draconian as those
of some other countries _ Malaysia, Turkey, Saudi Arabia, Thailand,
for example _ where some drug offenses call for the death penalty,
the United States is a world leader in incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit features a ``POW wall'' with photos of 100 inmates
and their families, a memorial to people killed by law enforcement
in connection with drug offenses and sections on medical marijuana
and property confiscation.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers of the exhibit are invited to write their comments in a
notebook placed on a lectern in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The comments indicate that the exhibit packs a punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Nazi holocaust survivor, and I had no idea what is
going on right here in my own back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It warms the heart of an old head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock 'em up. Throw away the key. What a bunch of wasted tax
dollars and space. How about putting some books out somewhere?''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, in the Skylight Gallery of the San Francisco main
library, is shocking.
</P>
<P>
   Among those featured in the exhibit is James Geddes, 45, who is
six years into a 90-year sentence in an Oklahoma prison for
cultivating and possessing five marijuana plants. ``I honestly feel
that I have been kidnapped by the state of Oklahoma,'' Geddes says.
</P>
<P>
   John Avery, a 58-year-old paraplegic, is serving a 20-year
sentence in Kentucky following his 1994 conviction for growing
marijuana in an underground greenhouse. ``They basically killed my
whole family,'' Avery says.
</P>
<P>
   Geddes and Avery are among dozens of case studies on the effect
of mandatory minimum sentences for drug offenses detailed in the
photo exhibit that will be on display through June 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1424EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3977 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIRECTOR-RICHMAN-SPI &LR;      06-04 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTOR-RICHMAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DIRECTOR RICHMAN, BEING BEHIND A CAMERA FEELS RIGHT AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUAL NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle's Meg Richman has finally found her calling.
</P>
<P>
   After she went through an ``existential crisis'' while studying
visual art at the University of California/Berkeley grad school
because she kept veering off the traditional student painter's
path, a frustrated professor finally called her bluff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Couldn't you just make films?'' he cried.
</P>
<P>
   She says she had never even considered the option even though,
after ``putting text'' in her paintings and even ``installing audio
tapes in them so they became a kind of performance art,'' making
movies was a logical next step.
</P>
<P>
   Richman laughs as she sits, some years after her finding her
niche, in the Plaza Park Suites before a showing of the first
feature film she directed, ``Under Heaven,'' which is playing
tomorrow and Monday at the Seattle International Film Festival and
opens a regular run on June 19 at The Harvard Exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Heaven'' is a shot-in-Seattle contemporary retelling of
Henry James' novel, ``The Wings Of The Dove.'' It stars British
actress Joely Richardson, Canadian Molly Parker and Australian Aden
Young (``It wasn't a conscious choice to cast people from the
Colonies,'' Richman says) in a film that lushly shows off Seattle's
beauty as well as giving its three leads equally rich and diverse
roles.
</P>
<P>
   It's a risky gamble after Iain Softley's acclaimed period film
of ``The Wings Of The Dove,'' which won an Academy Award nomination
for Helena Bonham Carter. It has just exited theaters and will be
released this month on video.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been difficult and ultimately I have no idea whether it
will make a big difference, but it's been a bit of a trauma for my
film's production company,'' she concedes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Under Heaven'' has its own unique perspective on the tale,
which was also ``borrowed'' by Terrence Malick for his 1977 film,
``Days Of Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of Eleanor (Richardson) a lonely, dying heiress
who employs a poor young woman, Cynthia (Parker), to be her live-in
help. Cynthia schemes to get her lover, Buck (Young), hired on as
well. Telling Eleanor that Buck is her half-brother, she then
pushes the gullible, sweet-tempered man to flirt with Eleanor and
to bring a little passion into her sad life. Maybe, she thinks,
Ellie will marry Buck and they will be able to live a life of
luxury when the older woman finally dies.
</P>
<P>
   The director notes it ``was pretty easy'' to transfer James to
the current day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a fan of his work and there were obviously
certain conflicts that had to do with class and a kind of Victorian
repression that I had to figure out an equivalent for because
they're no longer applicable.''
</P>
<P>
   Richman has put her art background to good use in the look and
design of her movie. It features gardens from plush shoreline
homes, vistas of the Seattle cityscape, scenes in Gasworks Park and
the rich architecture of Pioneer Square.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one metaphor for Eleanor's blooming after falling for
Buck is her garden. Richman says she pored over books on
Pre-Raphaelite art to achieve the look. ``I wanted it to move from
a Seattle streets, Nan Goldin-type image back to the
Pre-Raphaelites. I wanted that kind of range.''
</P>
<P>
   For a first-time director, Richman was blessed with an ideal
cast. She admits she was a little nervous about directing Joely
Richardson, who is the daughter of Vanessa Redgrave and the late
director Tony Richardson. ``But Joely is such a down-to-earth
person and she has no snobbery in her. In all honesty, there were
moments I felt daunted, but Vanessa sometimes came round to visit
so the whole thing took on a very human scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting her dream cast took time. ``I went through an incredible
audition period for the film,'' says Richman. ``We had to have a
name actor for the role of Eleanor because we had to appease the
production company and their investment in the project. But we were
lucky because once the funding was in place, it never fell through.
It just took a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw every young, up-and-coming star in L.A. for the roles of
Buck and Cynthia. Molly and Aden were just so clearly the best. It
was kind of magical that I really got, in each case, the person I
wanted the most.''
</P>
<P>
   And she found directing to be naturally easy. ``I thought,
finally, after all these years, I'm doing the thing I was born to
do. But that said, I was prepared in a lot of different ways. I'd
taken acting courses, directing courses and done directing in the
theater. And I have that strong visual background as well as years
of writing. All the components meshed. The thing I was most
frightened of was camera movement and the impact camera movement
had on the narrative.''
</P>
<P>
   Richman's own family helped keep the short, 29-day shoot, in
perspective and on budget. ``They were very generous in donating
things,'' she laughs. ``It definitely made it easier to be
surrounded by friends and family in Seattle and to be making a
movie in my hometown. I felt bolstered by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the process of getting everything in place for ``Under
Heaven'' wasn't always easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things the legislature could do to make this city a
far more attractive place to shoot a film,'' she says. ``There are
other states where the tax breaks the permit situation are better,
but the people here are so wonderful and, of course, it's
unparalleled as far as its beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Richman has completed another script _ of the Somerset Maugham
novella _ ``Up At The Villa,'' which has been picked up by Sydney
Pollack's production company. It will star Kristin Scott Thomas and
Sean Penn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know if I'll get a credit because Belinda Haas
has re-written it,'' Richman says. ``We might share a credit but as
a writer, I've never had the desire to hang out on the set.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how plastic the medium is and it can change. I can
change it, my actors can make a suggestion and change their words
into something better. I'm happy for the change.''
</P>
<P>
   And has the film business changed toward women directors? ``As
more women work in the industry, I think it will change,'' she
says. ``But it makes no difference to me if I'm thought of as a
Seattle or woman director. I'll just go forward and do my work.
What does surprise me is that because a woman's sensibility, if
there is such a thing _ and I think there is _ and it's a
culturally different sensibility, is still regarded as suspect and
there's a failure to recognize it as legitimate, strong and a
powerful point-of-view.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The delicacy and subtlety of it can be perceived as
weakness,'' says Richman, and with a laugh she adds, ``And I find
that tremendously annoying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
