<HEADLINE>
`THE TRUMAN SHOW' IS SOMETHING TO SAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story is that when Paramount execs sat down to design the
marketing campaign for ``The Truman Show'' last year, they suddenly
realized they had a huge problem on their hands. They knew the
movie was special, but there was nothing to compare it with, and it
was basically a Jim Carrey movie that was not a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   After delaying its release twice, they decided to show it to the
movie press early _ in fact, an unheard of two months before its
release date. And the press went crazy for it. Several national
critics called it one of the best films they'd ever seen, and
Esquire magazine dubbed it ``the film of the decade.''
</P>
<P>
   As the word-of-mouth started to hum and the first rave reviews
began to appear in the slick magazines, the studio kicked in with a
barrage of pre-release television ads and a long theatrical
trailer, which collectively show every beat of the movie, including
the characters and mechanics of its surprise last act.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this campaign is that _ while it lets people
know what is in store for them _ it ruins the impact of the movie.
The maximum effectiveness of ``The Truman Show'' depends on not
knowing what's around the corner _ it doesn't even reveal its
premise until the film is half over! The element of surprise is
absolutely crucial to the wonderful experience the critics had two
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   So my heartfelt advice to Seattle moviegoers is that, difficult
as it may be, do whatever you can to avoid the the avalanche of TV
trailers, read no reviews (including the rest of this one), don't
talk to your friends about it and go see this remarkable movie with
as fresh and unsullied a perspective as you can.
</P>
<P>
   If you must know, however, the film tells the story of an
Everyman named Truman Burbank (Carrey), who lives in an ideal
little middle-America community on what seems to be an island off
the Florida coast: happily married, with a solid job, troubled only
by a certain wanderlust and a nagging fear of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, as we get to know his life, his personality and the
characters around him, certain oddities and incongruities begin to
pile up, and well into the movie's midsection we learn (at roughly
the same time Truman does) that it's all a sham, that he's the
unknowing subject of a bizarre, ``reality-based'' television show.
</P>
<P>
   He's actually an orphan picked for this honor at birth, his wife
and friends are all actors, his community is one vast television
studio with thousands of hidden cameras, and his fear of water has
been induced in him to keep him on his island set. It's ``The Real
World'' times 100, the ultimate paranoid delusion come to life!
</P>
<P>
   As he learns this unbelievable truth, his imperative becomes to
escape the false world and make his way to the outside and the one
person who early-on tried to tell him the truth (Natascha
McElhone). But since he's the star of the world's No. 1-rated TV
show, the behind-the-scene powers cannot afford to lose him _ plus
he's as instantly recognizable as Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Though not strictly speaking a comedy, Carrey is in no way fully
restrained and there's enough humor throughout for the film to
loosely qualify for the designation. And, to be sure, it's most
definitely a satire _ indeed, the wildest imaginable satire of
America's obsession with soap operas and reality TV.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than this. It achieves a genuine pathos as a
character piece: We really care about this guy and his plight. It
also turns its neatest trick in a magnificent last act, as Truman
goes one-on-one with his creator (Ed Harris, in the best
performance of his career), and the film becomes a devastating
religious parable.
</P>
<P>
   The exact meaning of this parable is not easy to put in a few
words, and it's also wide open to interpretation. But it's so
skillfully done that it's impossible for us not to identify with
Truman on this higher level: His situation in his world is our
situation in the cosmos. His argument with his TV-creator becomes
Man's argument with God.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey is likely to come out of this film as a much bigger star
and much more respected actor than he went in. But the truth is
that, good as he is, this is not really an actor's movie. Almost
any star would work in the part and it's not Carrey's movie at all.
It's a film that fits neatly in the groove of its director, Peter
Weir.
</P>
<P>
   In his 30-year-career, this Australian-turned-Hollywood
filmmaker has made his share of non-personal and genre films _
``Green Card,'' ``Dead Poets Society'' _ but his artistic heart has
been in a series of films that are fascinated by the mystery of
man's place in the cosmos, and willing to entertain almost any
metaphysical possibility.
</P>
<P>
   His best films _ ``Picnic at Hanging Rock,'' ``The Last Wave,''
``The Plumber,'' ``Witness,'' ``Gallipoli,'' ``The Mosquito Coast''
and ``Fearless''_ are obsessed with man's spiritual nature and the
world of hidden connections beyond our surface reality. He's the
closest thing Hollywood has ever had to a New Age director.
</P>
<P>
   His problem is that, except for ``Witness,'' the box office has
not supported his filmmaking quest. But with ``The Truman Show,''
he's cleverly sneaked his boldest expression right through the
studio system in the form of a Jim Carrey vehicle. And, unless I
miss my guess, it's going to pay off for him big time.
</P>
<P>
   The Truman Show. Directed by Peter Weir. Written by Andrew
Niccol. Cast: Jim Carrey, Laura Linney, Natascha McElhone, Ed
Harris. Paramount. 104 minutes. Rated PG for thematic elements.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
