<SLUG> BC-FILM-MURDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PERFECT MURDER' LACKS SUSPENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though ``A Perfect Murder'' gets by on the strength of
Michael Douglas' star power and its glossy, noirish production
design, it ends up being a fairly lame thriller that's not half as
suspenseful or riveting as it wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   It's a remake of the 1954 Alfred Hitchcock melodrama, ``Dial M
For Murder,'' and is based on Frederick Knott's adaptation of his
own 1952 West End and Broadway play. (There was also a 1981
TV-movie remake starring Christopher Plummer and Angie Dickinson.)
</P>
<P>
   But in this version, the very British setting has been moved to
upper-crust Manhattan, and Ray Milland's suave, aging-tennis player
villain has become a grim-faced Wall Street manipulator whose
financial world is crumbling all around him.
</P>
<P>
   When he discovers that his immensely wealthy-in-her-own-right
wife (Gwyneth Paltrow) is having an affair with an artist (Viggo
Mortensen) who she doesn't know is actually a fortune-hunting
ex-con, he conspires to bribe the lover into killing her.
</P>
<P>
   The husband then sets up the perfect murder, arranging for an
intruder to break into the house and attack the wife. But, of
course, it does not go as planned, and becomes only the prelude to
a complicated cat-and-mouse game between the three characters.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Dial M'' is not considered one of Hitchcock's great
works, the filmmakers have felt little compunction to be faithful
to it in any way except in spirit, and have made significant
changes to the premise, the characters and especially the last act.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes have not improved the piece, and _ like the
Hitchcock film _ it looses steam and falls apart. While his
direction is fluid and competent, Andrew Davis (``The Fugitive'')
simply doesn't have the master's flair and streak of originality.
</P>
<P>
   The weakest link in the production is Paltrow, especially when
compared to the original's Grace Kelly _ a tough act to follow. Her
character is poorly written, and she seems such a shallow, spoiled
ninny that she fails to be the sympathetic center she's supposed to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Considerable better is Douglas as the cold-blooded cad of
husband. He's both magnetic and believable. And after seeing him
play so many nice guys since his 1987 Oscar win for ``Wall
Street,'' it's also fun to have him play an even more evil version
of his Gordon Gekko character.
</P>
<P>
   Also fun is the film's production design, which goes less for a
Hitckcockian look and feel than for the gaudy, high melodrama style
of producer Ross Hunter and such over-produced kitsch classics of
the late '50s and early '60s as ``Midnight Lace,'' ``Portrait in
Black'' and ``Back Street.''
</P>
<P>
   A Perfect Murder. Directed by Andrew Davis. Screenplay by
Patrick Smith Kelly. Cast: Michael Douglas, Gwyneth Paltrow, Viggo
Mortensen. Warner Bros. 107 minutes. Rated R for violence and
sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
