<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE COPS PUT METTLE TO THE PEDAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four weeks ago, Paul Donahue went for a ride. On his 18-speed
trail bike. In Seattle, Washington. With his friends, Timmy
Connolly, Bob Sheridan and Conrad Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks later, they're still out riding. Last night, they
were in Providence. Tomorrow they'll finally be back home, in town,
right here at City Hall Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks. Seattle to Boston. A hundred and twenty miles a day.
No excuses. No sick days. No banging in with blue flu.
</P>
<P>
   Riding in the rain. In the sun. Riding through cool mountain air
in Montana as well as the congested South Side of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been great everywhere we've been,'' Donahue was
saying yesterday over a cell phone as he pedaled through
Connecticut. ``In Helena, Montana, we were met by the mayor of the
city and the governor of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helena is the capital. I think they have about 20 cops on the
force there. Imagine that.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Paul Donahue is: a cop. It's what he does for a
living and it's also why he's been on the road with the other three
for the past month: To draw some attention to an outfit called
C.O.P.S. _ Concerns of Police Survivors Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Seattle, they had a big deal put together for us when we
started the trip,'' Donahue was saying. ``Their Police Department
had the first bicycle patrol in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lost a motorycle cop there about three years ago. Guy got
killed on the job. His wife and children showed up to wish us well
when we left. They had a big crowd there. It was quite a send-off.
Really nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the way things tend to go these days cops only
get their names in the paper when they get killed, indicted, or
accused of behaving poorly. Why, just the other day a really
terrific state trooper had his name smeared across the TV screen
along with the front pages after he stopped and arrested one of
Louise Woodward's lawyers and charged her with drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   She then accused him of asking for sex in exchange for dropping
the charges, apparently convinced the public might believe the
trooper was blind. Yet, for a couple of news cycles, her cheap
insinuation became almost as big a story as the dumb things the
shabby lawyer allegedly told the trooper about her pathetic client.
</P>
<P>
   When police are caught acting like thieves with badges,
corrupting the system by ripping off drug dealers, and lying people
into jail, that is news. But that is far from the normal pattern of
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   There simply aren't many jobs in America where the wage-earners
had left for work with the knowledge _ often buried in the back of
the mind _ that they could lose their lives in the performance of
their tasks. No office offers the constant cycle of potential
danger found on the streets or highways _ rural as well as urban _
where it can all end in a single second.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue is 47. He's been on the job 19 years and is currently
assigned to Station 14 in Brighton. Connolly is 32 and works at the
police academy. Sheridan is 39 and is assigned to the motorcycle
unit. Bailey is an accomplished triathlete and has spent most of
the past month looking over his shoulder at the other three.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get up, do about 40 push-ups and then ride all day,''
Donahue pointed out. ``I have to tell you, this is a beautiful
country. It's unbelievable. The Rocky Mountains. The rivers. It's
incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the best part about America is the people. Everywhere
we've been the people have been fabulous to us. We've been staying
at places local police departments along the route hooked us up
with. Motels. Station houses. People's homes. It's been great.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night, they were guests of the great Buddy Cianci, the
marvelous mayor of Providence and the only chief executive of any
city in the country with his own pasta sauce. This morning _ if
Cianci does not steal their bikes _ they will travel the short
distance between Providence and Foxborough, kind of a day off
actually, prior to biking their way into Boston and a reception
Friday at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The awareness they hope to raise is almost as important as the
money people have contributed to C.O.P.S. Those funds have helped
more than 8,000 families since the organization was formed 14 years
ago to assist survivors; a rather cold, antiseptic word that means
the husbands, wives, sons, and daughters of police officers who
went to work one morning and never returned. And here we have four
guys, riding just for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-RAITT-BOS &LR;      06-04 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RAITT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVIS RAITT TO PLAY FOOTBALL IN IOWA _ AND GET HIS DEGREE AT BU
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some ways, his college days are already over and he is well
into his postgraduate career.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way Travis Raitt wanted it, of course. If the
6-foot-3-inch, 270-pound offensive lineman could have written his
own script, he would have kept the main act here, at Boston
University, where Raitt and his fellow Terriers would work their
way back into Division 1-AA national football contention.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt would have been going through this summer at BU preparing
for his final season at a school he chose four years ago because he
liked what it had to offer, both academically and athletically.
</P>
<P>
   But as anyone who has been around the Terrier program knows,
that's not the script that has been played out.
</P>
<P>
   At BU, football exists only in memory. That's been the case
because the school chose to drop the program last fall. And Raitt,
who had to choose between staying, getting a degree, and giving up
football or moving on, has taken the latter course, but with an
intriguing twist.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt is now a mercenary in the broadest sense of the word.
Starting last winter and spring and continuing through next fall,
he is attending classes at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   He also is playing football _ right now he is second-team center
and guard on the depth chart _ for the Hawkeyes, a situation that
is about a solar system away from the ``football'' atmosphere at BU
the past several months.
</P>
<P>
   But come December, Raitt will return to Boston as a student.
He'll pick up his degree in marketing from BU and either move into
the business world or, if luck stays with him, on to professional
football.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, what Raitt is doing is taking a year's fellowship in
college football at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing illegal about this. Not in the eyes of the
NCAA, which allows players from schools who drop football to
transfer and play at another university immediately without having
to sit out a season.
</P>
<P>
   For Raitt, it's an opportunity that wasn't there four years ago
when he came out of Miami Lakes, Fla., with only the service
academies, the Ivy League, and Division 1-AA schools interested in
him.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa? The Big Ten? Then it was fantasy land. Now it's months
away from being reality.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt says he's as excited as a freshman. ``It's just so
different than anything I've experienced before,'' he said
recently, sitting in the athletic offices at BU during a visit back
from Iowa. ``The Big Ten. All that tradition. Why, they had more
people at our spring game out there than saw us play all of last
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Raitt made it clear that he will return to BU because of his
friends and the value of the degree he will earn. Athletically,
however, the wounds of last season's administration decision remain
open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of fond memories here,'' he said. ``But I still
don't understand it. There's still a lot of anger in us. We gave a
commitment to this school to make it the best we could make it in
football. Now they don't even acknowledge that we were ever here,
or at least that's the way it seems to us. It just seems as if we
busted our butt for this school and they gave us nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   BU contended that its decision to scrap football was based on
lack of revenue, lack of interest, and lots of other things.
Regardless of the reasons, football, part of the BU tradition since
1884, is gone and not likely to come back, despite the sincere
efforts of some special-interest groups to make another go of it.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt says the demise of the program came as a shock to most of
his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing was frustrating because we felt there was
nothing that we could say or do that mattered,'' said Raitt.
</P>
<P>
   The reality was that if any Terrier wanted to play football this
season, it would have to be somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I was worried that no one would be interested in
me,'' said Raitt. ``But then the calls started to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Given carte blanche to go anywhere, talk to anyone, Raitt put
out feelers. He talked to people at Pittsburgh, Marshall, and
Youngstown State. He visited Arizona and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   He chose the Big Ten because it felt comfortable, just as BU had
felt four years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt makes it clear he is a short-timer at Iowa. ``I took
classes this spring and I'll take classes next fall,'' he said.
``I'll also come back in the summer and start working out to get
ready for the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Raitt's arrival at Iowa was met with enthusiasm, and he was
treated as a welcome gift handed to the Hawkeye coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a tremendous kid,'' said Iowa offensive line coach
Frank Verducci. ``When he came here, we felt he was the perfect fit
for us. He gives us what we needed _ depth on the offensive line.''
</P>
<P>
   Raitt worked as second- and first-team center and second-team
guard before a minor injury knocked him out of spring drills.
</P>
<P>
   Verducci says the depth chart is meaningless in terms of Raitt.
``He's more like the sixth man on the offensive line,'' Verducci
said. ``He's going to play. Play a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is all Travis Raitt wanted to do at BU.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
