<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-NEWFOUNDLAND-BOS &LR;      06-04 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-NEWFOUNDLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD-LUCK NEWFOUNDLAND HOPES OIL WILL PROVIDE ECONOMIC RECOVERY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HIBERNIA OIL PLATFORM, Off Newfoundland _ The Puma transport
helicopter, shuddering against icy wind blasts, settled on the
boxing-ring-sized landing pad perched a dizzying 300 feet above the
ocean swells.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers leaping onto the grillwork deck were clad in
rubber survival suits _ a cumbersome cross between scuba garb and
spacesuit _ that could mean the difference between survival and
quick death from hypothermia in the waters of the North Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   They are roughnecks, mudmen, geologists, drill technicians and
other toilers in the oil trade. All of them had come to punch in
for another three-week, 12-hours-a-day, seven-days-a-week shift on
the Hibernia platform 200 miles southeast of St. John's, smack in
the middle of ``Iceberg Alley'' where the treacherous ice mountains
sweep down from Greenland.
</P>
<P>
   Newfoundland, the notoriously hard-luck province where tens of
thousands of fishery workers were cast out of work when codfish
stocks collapsed five years ago, is today pinning its economic
hopes on undersea crude.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offshore oil fields are our sleeping tiger, and the tiger
is just starting to roar,'' said Chuck Furey, provincial minister
for industry.
</P>
<P>
   The colossal Hibernia rig _ rising 735 feet from the ocean floor
_ is half the height of the Empire State Building. More important,
it is the first success story of what could become the first great
oil boom of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``A real industry is starting to emerge, even if it's still in
its embryonic stage'' said Donald May, an economist at Memorial
University in St. John's. ``And that's something Newfoundland
desperately needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Other potentially huge oil fields have been identified beneath
the turbulent seas off Newfoundland. Only last week, Gulf Canada
began seismic exploration of deposits to the south of the province
that could dwarf Hibernia's projected 1 billion barrels of
recoverable oil.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, construction will soon begin on drilling rigs to be
located on the Terra Nova south of the Hibernia reservoirs. Another
offshore oil project, Husky Oil's White-rose fields, may start
pumping oil by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Hibernia platform, towed into position last June and
maneuvered into place atop a massive concrete pedestal anchored to
the sea bottom, is one of the most ambitious, expensive and
disputed engineering projects in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The dream dates back nearly two decades when petroleum
geologists first discovered two oil fields _ the Hibernia and
Avalon _ within the Jeanne d'Arc Basin on the northeast portion of
Newfoundland's Grand Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the platform took more than five years to
complete at a cost topping $4.2 billion. It was jeered across
Canada as an overpriced, government-subsidized ``mega-workfare''
project that would do little more than provide short-term
construction jobs in the impoverished province of 558,000 people,
where jobless rates run at more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last November 17, the jeers turned to wild cheers as
Hibernia came a gusher _ spewing forth more oil than the headiest
estimates had forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``So maybe we Newfoundlanders will have the last laugh, 'ey?''
said Sean Ryan, 35, an out-of-work fisherman turned oil roughneck
as he fitted a rock-chewing bit onto a drill shaft. ``So maybe
there's going to be some future for the old place after all.''
</P>
<P>
   The fiery plume of Hibernia's gas burn-off flare is visible for
miles around, and has become a well-known landmark for air crews
and seamen on the northern trans-Atlantic routes between Europe and
North America.
</P>
<P>
   Hibernia's production, now 50,000 barrels a day, is gradually
building to a peak of 135,000 barrels a day for the next 19 years.
Ten years from now, Newfoundland will be pumping 500,000 barrels a
day from this and other fields on the Grand Banks, or nearly half
of Canada's output of light oil, according to some projections.
</P>
<P>
   Other so-called gravity-based offshore platforms similar in
scale to the Hibernia rig are in operation around the world, mainly
in the North Sea fields off Scotland. But Hibernia is the first
platform ever constructed to confront the threat of icebergs with
an ultra-fortified design that contributed to the stupendous cost
of the project.
</P>
<P>
   The Hibernia fields lie generally in the middle of the ponderous
flow of icebergs shed from the western shores of Greenland.
Hundreds of ships, most famously the Titanic, have been sent to the
bottom of this region of the North Atlantic after a fatal encounter
with floating ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a danger never far from our minds,'' said Howard Granger,
radio operator and weather watcher aboard the rig. ```When they
come within 24 nautical miles of the platform, we start taking very
serious notice. When they come within six nautical miles, we
react.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction might mean dispatching one of the emergency vessels
bobbing on permanent standby around the platform to lasso a
medium-sized iceberg and towing it to a safer drift. Smaller bergs
are blasted off course with water cannons pumping 2,500 tons of
seawater per hour.
</P>
<P>
   If a true monster iceberg were to bear down on the oil platform,
however, there would be no choice but to abandon the rig and hope
that the enormous concrete base _ with its collar of
five-foot-thick ``teeth'' meant to absorb impacts that no other
structure is designed to absorb _ saves the day.
</P>
<P>
   In the radio room, with its satellite down-links, radar screens
and high tech communications gear, operators plot the precise
position and exact course of every piece of ice carried down to the
North Atlantic by the cold Labrador currents.
</P>
<P>
   The Hibernia field is jointly owned by Mobil Oil Canada, Chevron
Canada, Petro Canada, Murphy Oil, Norsk Hydro and the Canadian
government, which injected $1.8 billion into the project to keep it
alive during rough economic times in the mid-1990s. About 5,800
people were employed during construction, and about 650 have
secured fulltime jobs onshore and off.
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, there are 270 people living and working aboard
the platform, or a total of 540 in two shifts _ three weeks on,
three weeks off. They sleep in small, two-bed living quarters
similar to college dormitory rooms, and feast on sumptuous courses
of steak, Italian sausage, curries, fried fish, potatoes and salads
dished out in the cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Possession of alcohol or drugs is a firing offense. So is
fighting. There is a large, well-equipped gym where employees can
sweat off the pounds _ or pound out frustrations _ as well as cable
television, movie offerings, computer games and free telephone
calls home. Even bingo nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is good, and the work is hard enough that the three
weeks seem to fly by, and you're back with your family,'' said Pat
Druken, 42, who works with the ``mud,'' or lubricants used to cool
down drill bits and other sophisticated heavy equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the project has been dogged by occasional tragedy _ in
1982, an early-phase drilling rig, the Ocean Ranger, went down in a
heavy winter storm, taking all 84 hands to the bottom _ the worst
injury since the platform went up a year ago has been a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   The most frustrating part of the job, workers say, comes when a
shift ends but the fog is so deep or the weather so severe that
transport choppers cannot make the flight to carry them home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose Newfoundland wouldn't be Newfoundland without
godawful weather,'' said a drilling foreman, Wayne Walters. ``But
when your 21 days are done, and you find yourself waiting day after
day for that flight home to your wife and kids, it's hard to get
sentimental about sea fog.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
