<SLUG> BC-SALVATION-ARMY-PARTNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING OBJECTIONS TO DOMESTIC PARTNERS LAW, SALVATION ARMY CUTS
SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDEN and TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Salvation Army has decided to end its
contracts with San Francisco and shrink programs serving the
homeless, drug addicts and the aged because of a dispute over the
city's domestic partners law.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Richard Love, a spokesman for the Salvation Army, said
after 11 months of negotiation, the organization had told city
officials Wednesday it could not comply with the ordinance. It is
giving up $3.5 million in city contracts to serve the needy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be applying for those funds,'' Love said, ``but
we're not leaving the city of San Francisco. We've provided a
quality service here without discrimination for 118 years and we'll
continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the $3.5 million was a relatively small part of the $18
million budget for the organization's San Francisco operations. The
organization plans to reduce its services beginning Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic-partners ordinance, which took effect June 1, 1997,
requires companies that do business with the city to provide the
same benefits to their workers with unmarried partners as they do
to married couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disheartening, it really is, but you can't put a
price tag on discrimination,'' said Supervisor Leslie Katz,
co-author of the benefits ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies are challenging the ordinance in federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   Three Salvation Army programs, including meals for 1,700 senior
citizens, receive taxpayer dollars and will be reduced, though the
programs will not be closed.
</P>
<P>
   The Salvation Army objects to the domestic partners law on
religious grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army's belief system, grounded in traditional
interpretation of Scripture, does not perceive domestic partnership
arrangements as similar to the sanctity granted marriage
partners,'' read an editorial in New Frontier, a Salvation Army
publication.
</P>
<P>
   But the editorial goes on to say that the group provides
services to individuals regardless of race, religion, sexual
orientation or marital status.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first religious organization to find fault with
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the city and the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San
Francisco, which has affiliated agencies with city contracts,
fought the mandate. The two sides eventually reached an accord.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement allows employees of Catholic agencies _ or any
other organization doing business with the city _ to designate
someone in their household as eligible to receive
``spousal-equivalent benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   That could include a spouse, sibling, other relative or
unmarried partner. Citing church doctrine, the archdiocese has been
a vocal foe of sanctioning domestic-partner relations, gay and
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Katz said the Salvation Army had been offered a similar deal but
declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought early on we could use that language,'' said Love,
``but as it progressed, we realized it was important to speak with
one national voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Love said the Salvation Army had asked for a ``sole provider
exemption'' that allows a waiver to contractors providing a unique
good or service.
</P>
<P>
   Love said such waivers had been granted to Blue Cross,
Encyclopaedia Brittanica, the U.S. Tennis Association and the
Lawrence Hall of Science, and 300 other companies or organizations.
The city denied the Salvation Army's request, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
