</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASSACHUSETTS-CANDIDATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE DEMOCRATIC CANDIDATE FOR GOVERNOR WOULD LOWER AGE OF CONSENT
FOR ABORTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pushing the envelope on abortion rights and risking the wrath of
voters, the three candidates for the Democratic nomination for
governor said Wednesday they would lower the age requiring parental
consent for an abortion from 18 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' positions were revealed during a gubernatorial
forum held at The Boston Globe. The candidates were asked how they
would reconcile two laws: one setting the age of consent for sexual
relations in Massachusetts at 16, the other requiring women under
the age of 18 to get permission from a parent or judge to obtain an
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it must be reconciled,'' said Patricia McGovern, the
former state senator from Lawrence. ``I think 16 is the age and I
do believe in a judicial consent process for children, and they are
children, or children under that age.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Donnelly, a longtime opponent of abortion rights as a
member of Congress from Dorchester, agreed the age of consent
should be 16 both for sexual relations and abortion. When he
announced his candidacy for governor earlier this year, Donnelly
said he would uphold a woman's right to an abortion if he were
elected.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Harshbarger, the attorney general, said he, too, believed
the laws needed to be reconciled, though he hoped there would still
be ``a huge amount of parental consent involved and people would
think this decision through.''
</P>
<P>
   When a decision on abortion needs to be made, Harshbarger said,
it ought to be ``as easy as possible. The law should not be
directing additional barriers to these kinds of very difficult
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the issue of parental consent turns into an
election-year controversy may depend on the reaction of suburban
voters, said Lou DiNatale, a political analyst at the University of
Massachusetts-Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will suburban independents feel this is an appropriate
response to ensure the right to an abortion or will they think this
is encouraging inappropriate sexual behavior?'' asked DiNatale.
</P>
<P>
   And while the state's population favors abortion rights by a
60-40 ratio, he added, ``that's not the safe position for any of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Acting Governor Paul Cellucci also favors lowering
the age to 16 for requiring a young woman to get permission from a
parent or a judge for an abortion. For the last several years,
Cellucci has filed bills calling for the Legislature to do just
that.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph D. Malone, the Republican state treasurer, is the only
gubernatorial candidate against changing the law. ``I am
pro-choice,'' Malone said in a statement. ``However, I support
parental notification because there is definitely a role for
parental involvement. The law as it currently stands is
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for abortion rights were ecstatic Wednesday to hear of
the candidates' positions. On the flip side, antiabortion activists
expressed dismay, particularly with Donnelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that amazing, appalling,'' said Philip D. Moran,
president of the Pro-Life Legal Defense Fund. ``If a young woman
cannot go into the hospital and have her appendix removed without
her parents' consent, I don't see why she should be able to go in
and have an abortion. There is no logic to this.''
</P>
<P>
   But abortion-rights advocates said the need for permission often
causes a minor to go out of state for the procedure, or even to
obtain an illegal and unsafe abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't fair to kids to make them go to court or go out of
state to get a constitutionally protected medical service,'' said
Susan Webber, vice president for external affairs at the Planned
Parenthood League of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Congress is expected to debate a bill making it a
federal crime for any adult to take a minor across state lines to
evade parental consent laws to obtain an abortion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
