r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKIN-REVIEW-LADN     06-04 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LOOK AT SAME OLD SITUATIONS IN `SKIN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
Our rating: 3 Stars  
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; In ``Under the Skin,'' a young English woman
deals with the grief and resentment generated by her mother's death
by going on a self-destructive sex-and-drinking jag. Anyone could
tell her that this is only going to make a sad situation worse,
since we've seen where this path leads in dozens of previous
movies. But just like the protagonists of all those films, she's
not about to listen to warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The thing that saves ``Skin'' from the same old prurient/preachy
same-old is its fierce central performance by newcomer Samantha
Morton. Lacing recklessness with palpable vulnerability, Morton
makes the film's heroine, Iris, convincingly wanton yet touchingly
naive. A lot of the situations in the movie are old hat, but Morton
brings them to life through the pain of a troubled girl who's
experiencing them for the first time. And not having a uniformly
awful experience.
</P>
<P>
   The writer-director, Carine Adler, also makes her feature debut
with ``Skin.'' She's very arty _ big on colored lens filters, odd
camera angles and unnecessary slo-mo _ especially in what might
have otherwise been boldly graphic erotic sequences. She likes to
have Iris talk dirty on a voice-over track, telling us what Adler's
a bit too timid to show.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker has good insight into fractious relationships,
however, and more of the movie, fortunately, addresses that than
the supposedly shocking stuff. Iris has a fascinating push-pull,
for example, with her older, married-and-pregnant sister Rose
(Claire Rushbrook, of Mike Leigh's ``Secrets and Lies''). It's far
more interesting than any of her increasingly degrading encounters
with strange men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Skin'' suggests that a good hug and some traditional
domestic role-playing is all Iris needs to straighten out. Morton's
harrowing but fervid performance indicates, however, that it will
take more than that to truly tame this wild heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1448EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4033 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEALOUSY-REVIEW-LADN     06-04 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEALOUSY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JEALOUSY' KEEN ON HUMAN FOIBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Writer-director Noah Baumbach made a bit of indie
splash three years ago with his debut feature, ``Kicking and
Screaming,'' a deft look at a group of post-college slackers
wondering what to do with their lives other than alphabetize movies
at the neighborhood video store.
</P>
<P>
   With his new film, ``Mr. Jealousy,'' Baumbach revisits the same
kinds of characters (with many of the same actors from ``Kicking
and Screaming), only now these people are 10 years older, a little
bit wiser and, yes, still wondering what to do with themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Jealousy,'' though, is anything but aimless. Baumbach has
a keen eye for form and character, and even though some of his
dialogue can sound a little self-conscious at times, it is usually
interesting, revealing and, best of all, funny. And while some
filmmakers seem destined to keep making the same movie for the rest
of their lives (Ed Burns would be the most blatant example),
Baumbach here has altered the form and content enough to make you
want to keep an eye out for his next feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Jealousy'' could well be the nickname of the film's
protagonist, the appropriately named Lester Grimm (Eric Stoltz), a
man so consumed with his girlfriends' pasts that he can't relate to
them in the present. Lester is trying, though, particularly now
that he's met Ramona Ray (Annabella Sciorra), a sexy, smart and
impulsive woman who lives in the moment, but carries a lot of
history with her.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Ramona's history includes old boyfriend Dashiell (Chris
Eigeman), a successful writer who has been hailed by some as ``the
voice of his generation.'' This annoys Lester since his novel has
been stuck on page one for quite some time. One day, Lester spots
Dashiell on the street and follows him to his therapy group.
Consumed by jealousy _ and curiosity _ Lester joins the group,
using his best friend's name and problems as an alias.
</P>
<P>
   This sets up the movie's best scenes, with Dashiell and Lester
jousting in group therapy while the shrink (director Peter
Bogdanovich playing another wonderfully named character _ Dr. Poke)
referees. Baumbach also has crafted some interesting scenes between
Lester and best friend Vince (Carlos Jacott), whose impending
marriage seems to be driving an unspoken wedge between the two. The
detail, though subtle, is rich and revealing in character.
</P>
<P>
   The performances are uniformly fine, although we could have done
without much of the monotone, Joe Friday voice-over narration.
Sciorra is particularly good, having finally been given a
three-dimensional character to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Jealousy'' suggests that its title vice may not be
completely without merit since it forces us to confront our fears
and dreams and actually deal with them. It's a novel idea, apropos
for a film brimming with captivating notions about relationships
and life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1449EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
