<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4042 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIEST-MOLEST-BOS &LR;      06-04 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-MOLEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHDIOCESE ACKNOWLEDGES IT PAID MILLIONS TO SETTLE CLAIMS AGAINST
PRIEST ACCUSED OF MOLESTING CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA   AND WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite past promises of openness, the Archdiocese of Boston
reluctantly acknowledged Wednesday that it paid millions of dollars
to settle claims against the Rev. John J. Geoghan, a retired priest
accused of sexually molesting more than 50 children over three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   But in a tersely worded one-page statement, archdiocesan
officials still declined to admit responsibility for Geoghan's
behavior and did not apologize directly to his alleged victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Archdiocese of Boston is terribly saddened by episodes of
clergy sexual misconduct,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the archdiocese has quietly settled 12 lawsuits
pending against it and Geoghan, paying a total of between $2.5
million and $10 million, according to several of the priest's
victims.
</P>
<P>
   But some victims said they were bitter that they won't get to
confront Geoghan, 63, in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This still smells to me like the archdiocese is trying to make
this go away as quickly as possible,'' said one victim, who alleges
Geoghan fondled him at a church north of Boston in the mid-1960s.
The victim asked not to be identified; he worried that his comments
could violate the terms of his settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Boston church officials insist that their refusal to discuss the
settlement is in the best interest of the alleged victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to respect the rights of the people who have
been victimized,'' said John Walsh, a spokesman for the
archdiocese. ``We're just not going to go into any details.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh also would not say how many priests have been accused of
sexual misconduct or give the total amount paid to alleged victims
since Cardinal Bernard Law instituted a new policy on the issue
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Geoghan's victims said they decided to settle with
the archdiocese because they believed state law would make it
difficult to win large financial judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's charitable immunity law, verdicts against
religious and other charitable organizations in tort cases are
capped at $20,000 per plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the archdiocese's continued secrecy indicates the
Roman Catholic Church's inability to fully grasp the seriousness of
clergy sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever good intentions the archdiocese has in dealing with
this terrible problem are seriously undermined when they are not as
forthcoming as they could be,'' said the Rev. John Rother, a New
York priest who has studied the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 15 years, about 1,000 pedophile priests have been
identified nationally and the church has paid nearly $800 million
in settlements to alleged victims, according to experts who track
the problem. There are about 50,000 priests in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American bishops still view this as a public
relations problem that will pass &UR;  &LR; in time,'' said Jason Berry, a
Catholic in New Orleans who wrote ``Lead Us Not Into Temptation,''
a 1992 book on sexual abuse by the clergy. ``There is this
mentality of institutional defenses that seems to view the
messengers of bad news as culprits rather than trying to understand
why the news is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoghan still faces criminal investigations by Suffolk and
Middlesex County prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Archdiocese of Boston may have to defend itself
in Middlesex Superior Court in September. A plaintiff, Drew Fales,
46, a Maine carpenter, charges he was molested by the Rev. Robert
Barrett in 1967 and 1968 while Barrett was assigned to St. George's
Church in Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who lives in Waltham, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Geoghan case, Mitchell Garabedian, an attorney who
represents several of the victims who received settlements, said he
still has 12 other court cases pending against the retired priest
and the Boston Archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, church officials revealed that the settlements
to Geoghan's victims were paid from funds borrowed from the
archdiocese's internal insurance funds. Some of those loans have
already been reimbursed to the archdiocese by its commercial
insurance carrier, Walsh said, adding that the internal insurance
fund is separate from the operating fund.
</P>
<P>
   Ken McLean, who says he was sexually abused by Geoghan when the
priest was serving Blessed Sacrament Church in Saugus, says he is
bitter that no one from the archdiocese has ever offered an
apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't even acknowledge that this happened to us,'' said
McLean, who now lives in suburban Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Cardinal Law issued a blanket apology to all victims
of clergy sexual abuse in the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all my heart, I beg forgiveness of all who have been hurt
by such acts of abuse,'' Law wrote last November in the Pilot, the
archdiocese's weekly newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   After dramatic revelations against James R. Porter, a former
priest in Southeastern Massachusetts who pleaded guilty in 1993 to
molesting 28 children during the 1960s and 1970s, Law implemented
detailed and aggressive guidelines on clergy sexual abuse. They
call for priests who have been accused of sexual abuse to quickly
be temporarily removed from their posts.
</P>
<P>
   Boston attorney Roderick MacLeish Jr., who has represented many
victims of abuse by clergymen and been critical of the archdiocese
in the past, praised recent efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give them credit,'' MacLeish said. ``They are doing
a much better job.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they haven't publicly discussed the Geoghan case, church
officials insist they are not trying to downplay the problem or
evade responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not congratulating ourselves for this,'' Walsh said,
referring to the archdiocese's handling of clergy sexual abuse.
``We are not blase about this, and so when I say I think we have
done a lot, it doesn't take away from the fact that nothing will
suffice for those who have been truly victimized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
