A4081 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDALS-OF-HONOR-HNS &LR;      06-04 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDALS-OF-HONOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDAL OF HONOR WINNERS A DISAPPEARING BREED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRENDAN LYONS  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Charles A. MacGillivary wasn't thinking
of heroism when he singlehandedly wiped out three machine-gun
positions before he was struck by enemy fire that tore off his arm
above the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was splattered all to hell,'' said MacGillivary, now 81, as
he recounted the firefight, part of the World War II Battle of the
Bulge.
</P>
<P>
   He stuffed the stump of his arm in the snow to stem the bleeding
and waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I wasn't fighting for medals,'' he recalled. ``I
was fighting for my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the platoon sergeant, who was 27 at the time, was later
awarded the Medal of Honor, the nation's highest award for bravery.
</P>
<P>
   MacGillivary is one of nearly 100 Medal of Honor recipients
arriving in upstate New York city of Saratoga Springs this week for
the Medal of Honor Society annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   They are a vanishing breed of old-fashioned war heroes. There
are now fewer living recipients _ 163 _ of the prestigious award
than at any time since the society was formed in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers will probably continue to dwindle because, other
than peacekeeping missions and limited conflicts since the end of
the Vietnam War, there have been no drawn-out wars involving
American service personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the recipients are veterans of World War II, Korea and
Vietnam. Two soldiers were awarded the medal posthumously for
action in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   Smart bombs and other ``over-the-horizon'' weaponry, which can
be launched from ships that are hundreds of miles off shore, are
more prevalent in combat today than the massive ground forces that
battled for weeks straight in World War II, said Professor Daniel
Gibran of Tennessee State University, a leading expert on the Medal
of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some situations that will more readily lend
themselves to a display of courage,'' Gibran said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what can win a guy a Medal of Honor, if he's
3,000 miles away and pushing a button,'' MacGillivary said.
</P>
<P>
   But some military strategists point out that smart bombs will
never completely replace the need for muddy-booted grunts. The Gulf
War, which involved thousands of ground troops after Iraqi forces
were pounded from above, supports that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have `over-the-horizon' technology, but we've had those
for decades,'' said Lt. Col. Thomas Begines, a Department of
Defense spokesman. ``There will always be a need for muddy boots on
the ground. If you look at our missions around the world,
operations other than war ... there is a requirement for a physical
presence in most cases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1504EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
