<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4099 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET-     06-04 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
HITCH-MOVIES (Los Angeles) _ Perfection. It's not a word often
bandied about in Hollywood, so you can understand why filmmakers
have been reluctant to tread upon Hitchcock's hallowed legacy. But
since commerce _ not perfection _ remains the primary principle at
work with studios, we're starting to see a stream of remakes _
``Psycho,'' ``Rear Window,'' ``To Catch a Thief'' and
``Spellbound'' among them _ that approach Hitchcock's work from
every conceivable angle. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
WOMEN-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Maybe someday down the line, the Los
Angeles International Women's Film Festival will pick and match
films connected by a singular theme. This first time out, however,
the philosophy was simple and direct: Let's get something going. By
Bob McCarthy. 
. 
TRUMAN-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ A triumphant change of pace for Jim
Carrey and the finest realization of director Peter Weir's
inquisitive approach to filmmaking, ``The Truman Show'' is a marvel
of artful, intelligent entertainment. More, it's as complete a
movie as it can possibly be. 4 Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
PERFECT-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``A Perfect Murder'' is an imperfect
thriller, an eager-to-please movie that delivers a few tingles but
not nearly enough tension for its audience to willingly surrender
and suspend disbelief. 2{ Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
JEALOUSY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Indie writer-director Noah
Baumbach's followup to his successful debut feature ``Kicking and
Screaming'' is a keen character film about a guy whose fixation
with his girlfriends' pasts stamps him ``Mr. Jealousy.'' 3 Stars.
By Bob Strauss. 
. 
SKIN-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ In ``Under the Skin,'' a young English
woman deals with the grief and resentment generated by her mother's
death by going on a self-destructive sex-and-drinking jag. The
thing that saves ``Skin'' from the same-old prurient/preachy
same-old is its fierce central performance by newcomer Samantha
Morton. 3 Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
PENN-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Dan Penn has a few songs under his belt.
Nothing serious _ just some co-writes such as ``Dark End of the
Street,'' ``Cry Like a Baby'' and ``I'm Your Puppet.'' Yet he,
along with others in the tiny town of Muscle Shoals, Ala., invented
that enduring and beloved genre known as Southern soul. By Fred
Shuster. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ It was a ``warm, intense feeling'' the
first time guitarist Ian Cone of high-energy Home Grown heard
himself on the radio. Nowadays, Cone gets that buzz often since the
band's ska-powered summer hit, ``Surfer Girl,'' was added at
influential KROQ-FM. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ A list of thumbnail reviews of recent
CD releases. By Fred Shuster and Glenn Whipp. 
. 
GETTY-ART (Los Angeles) _ Although it fills only one small gallery,
a tiny, ornate 14-century prayer book at the J. Paul Getty Museum
is considered a ``blockbuster,'' no less a turning point in Western
art history than, say, a Cezanne landscape or a Picasso nude. By
Reed Johnson. 
. 
OSCAR-VIDEO (LoS Angeles) _ As a relatively small film coming out
during the holiday glut of movies, ``Oscar and Lucinda'' failed to
find much of an audience. But this screen adaptation of Peter
Carey's 1988 Booker Prize-winning novel is as brilliant as the
glass and water images that flow through it. By Rob Lowman. 
. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
