<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETTY-ART-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRAYER BOOK'S' LATEST CHAPTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; It measures only 3{ by 2{ inches, a work of art
so painstakingly crafted and minutely scaled that you suspect it
was made by an elf.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this tiny, illustrated prayer book was created in
14th-century France by Parisian master illuminator Jean Pucelle. An
artwork literally fit for royalty, it belonged to Jeanne d'Evreux,
reigning queen of France from 1324 to 1328, who probably used it on
special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Rendered in still-vivid reds, blues, lilacs, turquoises and
pinks, ``The Hours of Jeanne d'Evreux'' is both a lavish
glorification of the word of God, and a virtuoso artistic display.
</P>
<P>
   And although it fills only one small gallery of the rambling J.
Paul Getty Museum, Thomas Kren considers the book to be a
``blockbuster,'' no less a turning point in Western art history
than, say, a Cezanne landscape or a Picasso nude.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, it's like a private portable art gallery,'' says
the Getty's curator of manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ``Hours'' is a work several decades ahead of its
time. Pucelle's illustrations have a sculptural, three-dimensional
quality more characteristic of Renaissance art than of the flat,
decorative, more abstract style of Gothic-era painting.
</P>
<P>
   Those qualities made Kren pounce when ``Hours'' became available
from the Cloisters, the branch of the Metropolitan Museum of Art in
New York City devoted to medieval art. For the first time in its
history, the manuscript is being removed from its binder so that a
Swiss publisher can make a high-quality facsimile. In the meantime,
a selective sampling of its 209 folio pages will be shown at the
Getty through July 5 and next summer at the Met.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Gothic rulers, Jeanne d'Evreux was a pious woman who
reportedly prayed eight times a day, seven days a week. The prayer
book helped her stick to her schedule of devotions by specifying
certain prayers for certain times of day, as well as meditations on
the story of Christ and its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Two elaborate cycles of prayer services are devoted to the
Virgin Mary and to St. Louis (King Louis IX), Jeanne d'Evreux's
great-grandfather, who died in 1247 and was canonized in 1270. The
book depicts several scenes from the saint's life, including his
crusades to the Holy Land and his ministering to the needy. In one
striking image, he kneels at the bedside of a gaunt, sickly man to
feed him with his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   Other prayers mark seasonal feast days, with everyday images
drawn from peasant life. Beggars and musicians cavort with bishops
in scenes of medieval Paris, while gables, arches and other
architectural motifs embellish devout reflections on the Christmas
and Easter stories.
</P>
<P>
   But the manuscript is as famous for its exuberant whimsy as for
its somber piety. Studying Pucelle's intricate pages is like
perusing an elaborate computer Web site. Text, icons and
illustrations knot together in dense thickets of symbolic meaning.
The mischievous marginal drawings of half-beast, half-human
grotesqueries provide a comic counterpoint to the earnest saints
and dour true believers. You'll need one of the Getty's magnifying
glasses, thoughtfully provided, to catch every unexpected sight gag
and between-the-lines splash of irreverence. While Kren says ``a
great deal of scholarly ink has been spilled over what the
marginalia means,'' it's believed these drawings may have
illustrated medieval parables or folk sayings.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to say what such a book might cost today, but in
Pucelle's time apparently no expense was spared. The rich colors
and laborious artistry, not to mention the parchment itself, were
precious commodities in the 14th-century world.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kren says, to the Gothic mindset, money spent in the
service of God was money well spent. The depth of belief that's
evident in ``The Hours of Jeanne d'Evreux'' is, like the book
itself, no small thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
