<SLUG> BC-PENN-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROLIFIC PENN PAL FOR SOUTHERN SOUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Dan Penn has a few songs under his belt.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing serious _ just some co-writes such as ``Dark End of the
Street,'' ``You Left the Water Running,'' ``Out of Left Field,''
``It Tears Me Up,'' ``Do Right Woman,'' ``Cry Like a Baby'' and
``I'm Your Puppet'' _ enough to retire on.
</P>
<P>
   Penn, along with others in that most unlikely of tiny towns
called Muscle Shoals in rural Alabama, is partly responsible for
inventing that enduring and beloved genre known as Southern soul.
</P>
<P>
   A singer, songwriter and producer, Penn had led several r&AMP;b
groups around town in the early '60s when pal Chips Moman invited
him to visit American Sound Studio. Penn ended up producing the Box
Tops' blue-eyed soul smash, ``The Letter,'' and later helped out on
historic recording sessions by Joe Tex, Aretha Franklin, Duane
Allman and Wilson Pickett.
</P>
<P>
   Booker T. &AMP; the MG's guitarist Steve Cropper dubs Penn ``a rock
'n' roll genius. Dan bridged the gap between pure r&AMP;b and what
you'd call rock because his music has a lot of soul to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Author Peter Guralnick wrote that Penn was ``the secret hero''
of his thoroughly entertaining history of Southern r&AMP;b, ``Sweet
Soul Music.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn's boyhood friend and songwriting partner, Spooner Oldham,
played keyboards at many of the same classic soul sessions. In what
can only be considered an event, Oldham and Penn will open for Nick
Lowe at the El Rey Theatre in Los Angeles on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Spooner are still kind of like we was in the '60s,''
Penn said in his gentle Southern drawl this week from his Nashville
home. ``If you close your eyes, you might see younger guys singing
these songs, and you might even hear the clinkers. But at least
it's a stripped-down version. We've been playing these isolated
shows, just the two of us, and sometimes it goes over great if
you're in the right setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn and Oldham will perform the classic soul tunes they've
co-written as well as material they collaborated on for Penn's 1994
solo album, ``Do Right Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn is in the process of recording another solo album.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do the songs we wrote and the songs we wrote with other
people,'' Penn said. ``We have two sets we can do because of all
the songs we wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn said he hasn't known Lowe long. The erudite British singer
and songwriter called him when he was in Nashville a few years ago
and asked Penn and Oldham to open a show for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to turn him down, but this time he wanted me and Spooner
out in L.A., so I accepted,'' Penn said. ``He has a pretty good
band, and he's a great singer. He's smooth, man. I like his '40s
influence on the new record.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn said Lowe's low-key new album, ``Dig My Mood,'' reminded
him of a collection of songs from the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still funky, but the way he wrote the songs was kind of
strange and wonderful,'' Penn said. ``One of the reasons I took
this gig was I liked his record.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn believes there's still so much love for the soul recordings
he helped create in the '60s because there weren't many of them
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, if you look down the list of all the music we cut,
there's only a handful with that sound because it stopped around
1969,'' he explained. ``But there are a lot of reasons it holds up
today. It's that r&AMP;b with a country influence.''
</P>
<P>
   It was after the British Invasion that Penn and Moman turned out
``Dark End of the Street,'' one of Southern soul's golden moments
best covered by James Carr.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a break from a poker game while in Nashville, the two
hammered out the tune on a piano in about an hour and returned to
play another hand.
</P>
<P>
   It might be the best ``cheatin' song'' ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Penn recalled that he was knocked out the first time he heard
Elvis Presley's Sun records, but lost interest when Presley turned
his back on his roots.
</P>
<P>
   While he loved Ray Charles, Bobby ``Blue'' Bland and Aretha,
Chuck Berry didn't register on Penn's funk meter.
</P>
<P>
   And he never liked the Beatles in the beginning, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just held my nose when they came along,'' Penn recalled. ``I
said, `Give me some black records. What is this?' But I've realized
later that the Beatles were great. But my thing was black music.
These days, I try to take it all in. I enjoy lots of different
kinds of music.'' &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
