<HEADER>
A4129 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-VIDEO-LADN     06-04 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OSCAR AND LUCINDA' A MOVIE GEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The wonderful thing about the advent of the video
age is that overlooked film gems don't necessarily have to be
relegated to years of neglect before some critic-champion rescues
them. There are numerous classic films that failed in their first
theatrical release, only to be considered years later as essential
viewing for any serious film buff. Orson Welles' ``Citizen Kane''
is a notable example.
</P>
<P>
   Gillian Armstrong's ``Oscar and Lucinda'' is no ``Kane,'' but it
is one of the best films of 1997, landing on a number of critics'
top-10 lists. As a relatively small film coming out during the
holiday glut of movies, it failed to find much of an audience. But
for those who saw it, ``Oscar and Lucinda,'' which was adapted from
Peter Carey's 1988 Booker Prize-winning novel, is as brilliant as
the glass and water images that flow through it. This story of the
conflict between earthly pleasures and the contemplation of the
heavens is a delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole faith is a wager, Miss Leplastrier,'' Oscar, played
with risky panache by Ralph Fienes, tells Lucinda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bet _ it is all in Pascal and very wise it is, too _ that
there is a God. We bet our life on it. We calculate the odds, the
return, that we shall sit with the saints in paradise. Our anxiety
about our bet will wake us before dawn in a cold sweat. We are out
of bed and on our knees ... and God sees us, and sees us suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Oscar is telling this to Lucinda (the vibrant newcomer Cate
Blanchett) over a game of cards in her shipboard room as they sail
to Australia in the mid-1800s. It is a monologue that is as much
about God as it is about gambling, for they are both addicted to
wagering _ one an obsessive gambler, the other a compulsive one.
Oscar refuses to believe that a God who asks us to bet on his
existence finds other forms of betting a sin.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins with Oscar as a young boy who has just lost his
mother. His minister father's hard ways and strict Pentecostal
faith drive Oscar to gamble that God will show him the right path.
He does this by throwing a stone over his shoulder onto a rock
where he has written in chalk the names of various religions. When
the rock lands on the Church of England repeatedly, Oscar runs away
from home and is raised by a rival minister, eventually becoming an
Anglican priest. As a young man studying at Oxford, Oscar discovers
his love of gambling, betting on almost anything. He is incredibly
successful, but although he gives most of his money to the poor,
each winning pot drives him into a deeper moral dilemma until he
resolves to go to Australia as a missionary to escape the
temptation.
</P>
<P>
   It is aboard ship that he meets Lucinda, an Australian heiress
who is desperate to be liberated from the confines of the
male-dominated culture of that time. Lucinda is returning to Sydney
after buying equipment for a glassworks she has bought with her
inheritance. Oscar and Lucinda separate upon reaching Australia,
but are soon reunited by fate. Though recognizing each other as
soulmates _ the two play cards with more passion than most people
feel when they make love _ the pair are unable to get past the
confines of their Victorian emotional prisons to express their love
for each other. Oscar, in a wild gamble, attempts to break out by
wagering that he can transport a church made of glass (one of
Lucinda's improbable dreams) to the Australian outback safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are gamblers in the noble sense,'' Oscar tells her. ``We
believe all eternity awaits us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucinda agrees, but insists on betting her entire inheritance
against Oscar's future legacy. His mission is to transport the
glass church that she has built to a remote location in Northern
Australia by Good Friday, where he is to turn it over to the Rev.
Dennis Hasset (Ciaran Hinds). Hasset has been exiled to the Outback
for his association with the scandalous Lucinda.
</P>
<P>
   Though Oscar's trip through the outback yields numerous notable
scenes, the image of the glass church floating majestically down
the river past lush green banks is one of the most compelling
images in recent film memory. The church is a symbol, of course,
operating on one level as a physical monument to the
spiritual/worldly duality of our natures. But academic
considerations aside, it is an image that stays with you long after
the costliest Hollywood special effect has faded from your mind.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the joy of Armstrong's movie. Odd and quirky,
sumptuously photographed, with a wonderful score by Thomas Newman
(``The Horse Whisperer,'' ``Unstrung Heroes''), ``Oscar and
Lucinda'' is filmmaking at its finest.
</P>
<P>
   CHIMING IN ON `MIDNIGHT': Clint Eastwood's adaptation of
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' _ John Berendt's
best-selling book _ met with mixed reviews for good reasons. The
story is centered around a famous murder trial in Savannah, Ga.
Eastwood's attempt to capture the moral ambiguity of the scene
never coalesces. ``It's like `Gone With the Wind' on mescaline!''
says John Cusack, who plays the reporter-narrator, but too much of
the movie is disjointed. Video is probably the best way to watch
it, however. You can zip through the scenes that don't click and
take a break or two during the two-hour, 35-minute movie. It does
have some terrific acting, especially Kevin Spacey as Jim Williams,
the rich antiques dealer and semi-closeted homosexual. And there
are also some funny set pieces involving the town's eccentric
characters, particularly The Lady Chablis, a drag queen comedienne,
played by the Lady Chablis, of course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
