<HEADLINE>
FIRST AIRPLAY BRINGS HOME GROWN JOY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; It was a ``warm, intense feeling'' the first time
guitarist Ian Cone of high-energy Home Grown heard himself on the
radio.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Cone gets that buzz often since the band's ska-powered
summer hit, ``Surfer Girl,'' was added at influential KROQ-FM.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, the Huntington Beach quartet built a sturdy
following on the indie circuit after cross-country treks with
Orange County pals like Save Ferris.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I heard us on KROQ, I was pulling into the
driveway and it was amazing,'' Cone said. ``I just went crazy. I
felt satisfied, like we've finally done it. Our song was finally on
the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Grown, whose debut album ``Act Your Age'' (Outpost/Geffen)
was released this week, appears Sunday in a hometown show at the
Old World Hall in Huntington Beach. The band is known for
good-humored, lively gigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love to have fun,'' Cone said. ``We're not a violent band.
We're concerned about the crowd having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   The four musicians met in high school, launching the band in
guitar class. They began writing songs four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't very career-oriented,'' Cone admits. ``We were just
doing it for fun, playing parties and stuff. It was something we
always wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone agrees it's been a quick rise to a contract with Geffen and
airplay on KROQ.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with luck and timing,'' the guitarist said. ``And
being in the right place at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   ZOMBIE'S QUIET TIME: Rob Zombie, leader of the hard-hitting rock
outfit White Zombie, has been quiet lately _ too quiet.
</P>
<P>
   That changed Tuesday with the release of two albums on his own
label, Zombie A Go-Go Records. The discs are ``A-Haunting We Will
Go-Go'' by the Ghastly Ones and ``Head Shrinkin' Fun'' by the
Bomboras.
</P>
<P>
   Both local acts specialize in a trashy, surf-punk sound.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Zombie's own solo album is due later this summer,
followed by a tour with the Ghastly Ones as the opening act.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD AGAIN: Lucinda Williams' long-awaited new disc,
``Car Wheels on a Gravel Road,'' is due June 30. Produced by ex-E
Street Band pianist Roy Bittan, the album features cameos from
Steve Earle, Emmylou Harris and Charlie Sexton, and already is
being hailed as one of the top efforts of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
