<HEADLINE>
MOM'S CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday June 11)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of my friends _ both mothers of young children _ died of
breast cancer this past week, within days of each other.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote the obituary for one, and fielded phone calls for
details of the other's memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   Shar Kinloch, 43, was a nurse; Bryanna Latoof Green, 39, a
journalist.
</P>
<P>
   These women were resourceful. They fought their illnesses for
years with every weapon available to them: surgery, aggressive
chemotherapy, radiation, bone marrow transplants, holistic methods,
good nutrition, staunch optimism and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Their husbands and children surrounded them with strength and
love, as did myriad friends and coworkers.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps their biggest support came from each other. After
meeting during bone marrow treatments, they talked on the phone
almost daily, for hours. I imagine they shared fears not many of us
could relate to, and dark humor not many could muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know too much,'' Shar, the nurse, would tell me with her
mischievous grin. ``I'm in denial about being in denial.''
</P>
<P>
   Her ``cancer dance,'' as Shar called the five years spent trying
to defeat errant cells playing havoc with her body, was mostly done
to an upbeat Buffett tune or the rolling lick of a Stones guitar
solo.
</P>
<P>
   Up to a month ago, Shar was still making her ``laps around the
county,'' volunteering at her children's school and dropping in on
her second home _ the Lakeland Regional Medical Center neonatal
intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks before she died, on Mother's Day weekend, she
insisted on going to one of her favorite annual events _ the
Mayfaire by-the-Lake art festival _ with Duncan and her kids,
Caitlyn, 11, and Adam, 6.
</P>
<P>
   Although Shar was in a wheelchair and on oxygen, she told me she
wanted to walk up to a few of the exhibits so ``I don't look like
too much of a dweeb.''
</P>
<P>
   Shar laughed out loud a lot, especially at life's small ironies,
and would stop in the middle of the road if something caught her
eye. She was brash and irreverent and gentle and quirky. She said,
``Bi... cycle'' at the end of every phone conversation just because
it amused her.
</P>
<P>
   Bryanna Latoof Green and I were new moms together. We had our
sons within months of each other, and commiserated over
breastfeeding, colic and sleep deprivation with all the
obsessiveness of first-timers.
</P>
<P>
   A talented reporter and writer, Bryanna never shied away from
hard topics. She wrote about parents who had AIDS, women who were
stalked by their ex-boyfriends, plane crashes.
</P>
<P>
   A Louisiana native, she had all-night Mardi Gras parties at her
house most of the years she lived in Lakeland, steaming shrimp,
stirring jambalaya and stacking up muffaletta sandwiches to feed
hordes of festively dressed friends.
</P>
<P>
   Our sons were perpetual guests at each other's birthday parties
for five years. One of my favorite pictures is of the ``A-Team,''
Adam, Austin and another close friend, Alex, just past toddlerhood,
all wearing fake Groucho mustaches and glasses, with their arms
slung around each other's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   A fiercely protective mother, Bryanna was always on the lookout
for vicious dogs and salmonella poisoning. At one summer party, she
talked the host into whipping up another, special batch of homemade
ice cream for the kids just so she could be sure no one slipped raw
eggs into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Just over three years ago, Bryanna was diagnosed with breast
cancer late into her second pregnancy. She and Mark were relieved
when Joshua was born healthy and robust. One of the hardest parts
of her treatment was the mandatory isolation after a bone marrow
transplant, when she had to be away from her boys for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, she returned with Mark, Austin, 7, and Joshua, 3, to
New Orleans after achieving what we had all hoped was a lasting
remission. She wanted to live closer to her parents and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   I received the call that Bryanna had died while I was walking
out the door to see a Saturday matinee of ``Godzilla'' with my
husband and son. The disparity made me flush with guilt.
</P>
<P>
   After the Lakeland memorial service, Austin, Alex and Adam spent
the night together, running through Alex's house, eating pepperoni
pizza and watching old ``Tarzan'' movies. The A-Team, together
again. By midnight, they were asleep in a sprawling tangle of socks
and toys and blankets.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at Austin, one arm curled around his raggedy blue
stuffed bear he's had since birth, and here is what I thought: He
will be OK. Maybe not right away. Maybe not all the time.
</P>
<P>
   But these are brave kids _ Caitlyn Kinloch and Adam Kinloch and
Austin Green and Joshua Green. Kids full of courage and fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   They inherited it from their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a feature writer for The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
