<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL SWAN SONG OF RICH OUTSIDERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIN McCORMICK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lt. Gov. Gray Davis and state Treasurer Matt
Fong may be the ones celebrating campaign victories this week, but
the real history-makers in California's primary election are the
gold-plated losers.
</P>
<P>
   Never before have so many millionaire office-seekers pumped so
much of their own money into a primary election, only to suffer
dramatic defeats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest bomb in the history of American
politics,'' said Garry South, campaign manager for Davis, who won
the Democratic gubernatorial nomination in Tuesday's primary.
``Based on the amount of money spent here, this is the biggest
disaster ever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the more money they spent, the worse they did,''
said Tony Miller, a campaign-reform advocate who lost his bid for
the Democratic nomination for lieutenant governor. ``I think people
are really offended at people trying to buy elections. Political
pundits underestimate the intelligence of the voters. They're not
idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   Political consultants are scratching their heads trying to
figure out how millionaire Al Checchi could plow nearly $40 million
into his campaign for the Democratic gubernatorial nomination and
come out with only 13 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's going to be a lot of books written on Al
Checchi,'' said John Herrington, the former Republican Party state
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Another unsuccessful candidate, Rep. Jane Harman, spent more
than $11 million of her own money in the three-way Democratic race
for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Issa forked over $13 million in his race for the
Republican nomination for U.S. Senate. But it was Fong, a small
spender by comparison, who won the nomination to challenge
incumbent Sen. Barbara Boxer, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Californians were not the only ones who appeared to reject the
expensive television commercials and sophisticated campaign
strategies of the wealthy candidates.
</P>
<P>
   This year, big-spending candidates have been drummed out of a
number of races around the country, in favor of contenders with
more political experience.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Kentucky voters narrowly rejected multimillionaire
U.S. Senate candidate Charlie Owen after his infusion of personal
cash made the race the most expensive in that state's history. In
Illinois' March primary, voters rejected a gubernatorial candidate
and two congressional contenders who spent huge sums of their own
money.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts say the public's rejection of rich
outsiders shows a major shift in the mood of American voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amateur hour in politics is over,'' said Washington, D.C.,
pollster Mark Melman. ``I see this as a trend. The notion that
people want outsiders to come in and shake things up is no longer
true. People want experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political observers say voters are not as likely to rock the
boat as they were in the early 1990s, when the economy was not as
healthy. In the 1992 presidential race, for example, political
neophyte Ross Perot pumped millions of dollars of his own money
into an independent campaign that helped deny George Bush a second
term and prevented the winner, Bill Clinton, from getting a
plurality of votes.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, ``voters were so angry that they were
politically assassinating government insiders right and left,''
said Darry Sragow, campaign adviser to Checchi. ``But that is
obviously not the mood anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Checchi's accomplishments outside of politics may have
hurt the candidate the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people looked at a successful businessman, who had
accumulated a lot of personal wealth, with skepticism,'' he said.
``It appeared that voters put more value on candidates who had
worked their way through the rungs of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   But one political scientist said he did not believe that voters
rejected wealthy candidates simply because of their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some kind of voter backlash,'' said Paul Hendrie
of the Washington, D.C.-based Center for Responsive Politics, ``but
I don't think it proves that money doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, people with a lot of money who get into
politics don't have any experience running a campaign. That hurts
them,'' he said. ``Running a business is very different than the
rough-and-tumble world of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this election, the most ever spent in a California
primary was the $9 million raised by Democrat Kathleen Brown in her
1994 bid for governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1539EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4160 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLD-ENVIRO-COX &UR; 260&AMP;     06-04 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-ENVIRO-COX </SLUG>
   260&AMP;ADD  GLOBAL POLLS SHOW MANY FEEL
ENVIRONMENTAL LAWS TOO WEEK
 &HT;     Eds: Optional add can be used as a separate list or for a map.
 &HT;     By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A series of opinion polls in 30 countries show that
most people feel their countries' laws fail to adequately protect
the environment, the Canadian firm that commissioned the surveys
for multinational corporations and governments said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The results ranged from Greece, where 91 percent of respondents
agreed that environmental laws ``don't go far enough,'' to Finland,
where only 37 percent agreed with the statement.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, 59 percent of persons agreed with the
statement, a smaller share than in all but four other nations
polled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potency of the environmental issue is so great that we're
going to see major changes in many countries, and companies doing
business in those countries will have to anticipate those
changes,'' said Doug Miller, president of Environics International
Ltd. of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Miller also said in a telephone interview that he has been
invited to brief officials at the White House next week on the
polls, which were conducted by polling companies in each country.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Finland, Nigeria was the only country where fewer
than half of respondents (42 percent) did not agree with the
statement that national environmental laws don't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that debate over climate change in the last year
appears to underlie much of the environmental opinion, but in Asia
and southern Europe, people are concerned about health problems
growing out of pollution.
</P>
<P>
   He said it cost $1 million to commission the 30 polls and that
more than 35,000 people were interviewed, either in person or by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
