<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEALOUSY-FILM-REVIEW-     06-04 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEALOUSY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MR. JEALOUSY': THERAPY, AS A FRONT FOR SNOOPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
 (JT)  
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Noah Baumbach has described his second film, ``Mr. Jealousy''
(after the bright, witty ``Kicking and Screaming''), with reference
to the directorial pantheon, invoking filmmakers from Billy Wilder
to Francois Truffaut to Ernst Lubitsch as inspirations for his own
comic style. Without knowing that, it would be easier to cite the
two most imitated contemporary influences on independent comedies,
Woody Allen and ``Seinfeld'' (in that order). Articulate,
self-defeating romantics who discuss their troubles at coffee shops
are again on the loose, this time in the story of Lester Grimm
(Eric Stoltz) and his wild possessiveness about his girlfriend,
Ramona Ray (Annabella Sciorra). Since Ramona is the sort to explain
she's been home having a shampoo when her unwashed hair looks
suspiciously tousled, Lester has his hands full.
</P>
<P>
   In a film that flows less smoothly than ``Kicking and
Screaming,'' bogged down by overzealous narration and a story
that's slow to get rolling, the otherwise astute Baumbach gives
Lester the rival he deserves: Dashiell Frank, the literary
celebrity known as the voice of his generation. While Dashiell's
best-selling book is read on audiotape by Tom Cruise, Lester (who
also has literary ambitions) is a schoolteacher who isn't always
happy in his work. For instance, when he fills in as a Spanish
teacher without understanding so much as ``Si.''
</P>
<P>
   The story's central gambit has Lester joining Dashiell's group
therapy sessions (led by an amusingly donnish Peter Bogdanovich) so
he can find out more about Dashiell, Ramona's famous ex. Lester
pretends to be Vince, his own best friend, for secrecy's sake.
Lester also bristles whenever Dashiell confesses to sexual
exploits. ``How can you say at your age that you've never been
faithful to anyone?'' he exclaims. ``What kind of boyfriend  &UR; are &LR; 
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Though two appealing actors play Lester and Dashiell, the roles
are strikingly miscast. Chris Eigeman, the hilariously sulky,
nit-picking star of Whit Stillman's films and a major asset in
``Kicking and Screaming,'' plays the supposedly suave Dashiell. But
he's got Lester written all over him; Eigeman seems ready-made for
the nutty, fiendish jealousy of the title role. And Stoltz, while
credibly neurotic here, radiates the well-being and smooth
complacency that could have made Dashiell that much more galling.
The film, which is better written than staged, could have been
funnier if its actors weren't playing against type.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sciorra gives Ramona the right friskiness, though she is not
shown off to best advantage by the film's dowdily retro costumes or
its oddly somber look. Marianne Jean-Baptiste, who played the
daughter in ``Secrets and Lies,'' and Bridget Fonda are underused
in smallish roles. Also in the cast (as they were in ``Kicking and
Screaming'') are Carlos Jacott as the real Vince, who enjoys
Lester's tactfully censored versions of what the group therapy
patients have to say about him, and John Lehr as the most enjoyably
weird of Lester's friends. ``It's fun just to follow people
around,'' he assures the snoopy Lester. ``Anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   MR. JEALOUSY
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Mr. Jealousy'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity and
sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Noah Baumbach; director of photography,
Steven Bernstein; edited by J. Kathleen Gibson; music by Luna and
by Robert Een; produced by Joel Castleberg; released by Lions Gate
Releasing. Running time: 105 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Eric Stoltz (Lester Grimm), Annabella Sciorra (Ramona
Ray), Carlos Jacott (Vince), Chris Eigeman (Dashiell Frank),
Marianne Jean-Baptiste (Lucretia), Peter Bogdanovich (Dr. Poke),
Brian Kerwin (Stephen), John Lehr (Lint) and Bridget Fonda (Irene).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
