<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4226 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-04 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT ADDS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Of all the partisan squabbles between President
Clinton and the Republican-controlled Congress, the one that seems
at first blush the least earth-shaking is a dry technical argument
over how to count heads.
</P>
<P>
   The way the national census for the year 2000 is to be
conducted, however, could tilt the population numbers toward one
party or the other. Its impact will be felt in the redrawing of
congressional and legislative districts, affecting the makeup of
future congresses and state houses. It could also change the
regional distribution of federal funds, which is often based on
population.
</P>
<P>
   This is a very big deal indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The political fight over the census isn't really about which
method will produce the most precise count, as both sides like to
pretend. The census is often inaccurate anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It is about how to cook the books so that voters likely to be
Republican are overcounted and those likely to be Democrats
undercounted _ or vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials frequently base public policy decisions
affecting domestic concerns, such as heath care programs, on the
number of people who live in certain locations, belong to certain
ethnic groups or are otherwise statistically differentiated.
</P>
<P>
   The specific issue here is whether to supplement the traditional
method of physically counting bodies by knocking on doors and
mailing out questionnaires. The Census Bureau proposes to do the
physical count and to add a demographic technique called
statistical sampling. Using the technique, the figures actually
counted in 90 percent of the households in each census tract would
be adjusted, based on an extrapolation of those figures plus a
survey of 750,000 households nationwide. The technique, says the
bureau, would allow it to account for those people known to exist
who were not actually contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaigned on behalf of sampling in his weekend radio
address and at a Houston community roundtable talk this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau confessed after the 1990 head count that it
had missed 8.4 million people and double-counted 4.4 million
others. A substantial portion of those missing were minorities and
poor inner city families likely to vote Democratic. Some of those
who were counted twice were wealthy folks who owned two homes and
were likely to vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton raised the troubling problem of minority undercounting,
warning that ``having an accurate census is a big part of having a
strategy for racial reconciliation in America.'' He promised to
make the census a priority issue this year and predicted that with
modern statistical devices sampling would be virtually error-free.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans charge that the president and the Democrats
don't care about a correct count and are simply scheming to adjust
the figures in a way that could prompt massive redistricting. They
fear that such population shifting could potentially change the
partisan makeup of roughly two dozen House seats and return control
of that august body to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   GOP congressional leaders have threatened to block the
administration's planned introduction of sampling by denying
federal funds for the method during budget negotiations this fall.
They have also filed suit to stop it on the shaky ground that it is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   But the Constitution says that an ``actual enumeration'' must be
conducted every 10 years ``in such a manner as they (members of
Congress) shall by law direct.'' That wording would appear to allow
changes in the census process. Sampling is a well-recognized system
of counting used in political polling and other statistical
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   We Americans have always been curious about who we are and how
many of us there are. The first census in 1790 was ordered in the
first public law issued by Congress on June 1, 1789. It counted
slightly under 4 million inhabitants. This included approximately
700,000 men and women held in slavery. The most populous state was
Virginia, with 692,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 Census declared that we had ballooned to 248,709,873
people, before the discovery of the undercounting problem. Experts
predict that we will hit a population of 270 million citizens in
the 2000 census, a massive head-counting project.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense to supplement the old-fashioned system with an
advanced process that is widely accepted as accurate by
professional bureaucrats and the statistical and scientific
community. It would cut the cost of taking the census and make it
easier for the bureau to do its job properly.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are having a good time making fun of the concept
of counting people who haven't been eyeballed or otherwise directly
contacted, but they are living in the past.
</P>
<P>
   And their fears of the sudden emergence of hordes of Democratic
voters seem greatly exaggerated. In any case, if those voters are
out there they deserve to be counted.
</P>
<P>
   It is time census-taking entered the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1623EDT &QL; 
