<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, June 5. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congress opens inquiry into the
China satellite controversy. The House is expected to pass a
resolution asking the President to refuse to visit Tiananmen
Square. Plus hearing on illegal sales of body parts in China. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With: CHINA-ANNIVERSARY and CHINA-HONGKONG.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BANKS (Jakarta) _ Foreign banks agreed Thursday to
reschedule some $80 billion in corporate and bank debt that has
become one of the biggest barriers to Indonesia's recovery. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   SWISSBANKS-HOLOCAUST (Washington) _ Switzerland's three major
commercial banks have reportedly offered a settlement of hundreds
of millions of dollars to settle claims brought by Holocaust
victims and their survivors who charge the banks failed to return
their assets. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   AWESOME-CRUISESHIPS (Venice, Italy) _ The Grand Princess _ twice
the size of the Titanic and three times as costly _ sailed into
port and all but eclipsed the cupola of St. Mark's Cathedral. As
passengers spilled out to to inspect the canals of Venice, most of
Venice stared, awestruck, at the world's largest cruise ship. The
cruise industry, boosted first by the hit TV show ``The Love Boat''
and more recently by the movie ``Titanic,'' has calculated that
bigger ships provide economies of scale. And it thinks it can draw
in more passengers with ever more varied and baroque forms of
entertainment. A foreign journal by Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-RAILCRASH (Eschede, Germany) _ One day after a German
rail crash killed at least 93 people, the authorities pulled scores
of high-speed trains out of service Thursday, after discovering
traces of a broken carriage wheel and damage on the tracks that
might have contributed to Wednesday's disaster. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-U.N. (Geneva) _ The United States, Russia, China, Britain
and France called on India and Pakistan on Thursday to freeze their
nuclear weapons development programs and refrain from deploying
bombs on missiles. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
