<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILINGUAL-EDUCATION-H     06-04 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILINGUAL-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DRIVE BEGINS TO STOP ANTI-BILINGUAL EDUCATION MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's third epic legal battle in four
years over an initiative fraught with widespread social
implications is under way, this time against the anti-bilingual
education Proposition 227.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the initiative, which scraps most of the state's
bilingual education programs, filed suit in federal court Wednesday
seeking to invalidate it on constitutional grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 227 was approved by a broad margin, 61 percent to 39
percent, in Tuesday's primary election.
</P>
<P>
   The man who put Proposition 227 on the ballot, Ron K. Unz,
called the measure ``ironclad constitutional'' and predicted that
it would be used as a nationwide model.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reaction to approval of the ballot initiative recalls
the uproar that followed passage of Proposition 187 in 1994 and
Proposition 209 in 1996. Both initiatives faced lengthy court
battles and Proposition 187, dealing with immigrant rights, was
largely gutted.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 209, the measure that ended most public affirmative
action programs, survived court challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Unz said he believed ``the overwhelming majority of school
districts in California will be implementing our initiative at the
beginning of the school year.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he said he expected a quick settlement of the legal
issues, the history of such contentious issues suggests otherwise.
It took the courts more than a year to resolve debates over the
other two propositions.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the coalition of civil rights, parent, church and
ethnic organizations that filed the class-action lawsuit to block
Proposition 227 said they were entering unchartered legal
territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not arguing that there's a categorical entitlement to
bilingual education classes,'' said Ed Chen, an attorney for the
American Civil Liberties Union of Northern California. ``Our point
is that (Proposition 227) not only eliminates bilingual education,
it limits (English) immersion to one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody is saying that you can give these kids
the kind of literacy they need in one year.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Escobedo, a lawyer for Multicultural Education Training
and Advocacy Inc., said the case was unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first instance where extremely viable means of
providing equality of educational opportunity are being stripped
from the state and local school districts,'' Escobedo said.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action complaint argues that Proposition 227 is
invalid because it violates the Civil Rights Act of 1964, the
Educational Opportunity Act of 1974 and the equal protection clause
of the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   It discriminates against minorities on the basis of national
origin, the plaintiffs contend, because the law requires school
districts to take steps to take ``appropriate action to overcome
language barriers'' for non-English speakers.
</P>
<P>
   In their effort to squelch the initiative, the plaintiffs must
first convince U.S. District Judge Charles Legge that
implementation of Proposition 227 should be blocked pending
resolution of the legal issues it raises.
</P>
<P>
   Legge, who was appointed by President Ronald Reagan in 1984, is
regarded as one of the most conservative members of San Francisco's
federal bench. The case was assigned to Legge by lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 227 prescribes one year of ``sheltered English
immersion'' for children who are not proficient in English in place
of the array of bilingual programs now offered in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely unbelievable,'' said Veronica Chavez, a
teacher in charge at San Francisco's Buena Vista Alternative
school, which teaches students by immersion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we told any English-speaking parent that we could teach
their kids (Spanish) in a year, we'd be lying, but that's what
we're now telling Spanish-speaking parents,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit contends that sheltered English immersion would
subject children to an educational experiment, deny them access to
critical parts of the curriculum and virtually assure that they
will be low academic achievers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
