<HEADER>
A4261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROADWAY-TONYS-ART-3T     06-04 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-TONYS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNDAY'S TONY AWARDS: SINGING AND WINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Walter C. Miller scanned the tables in the center of
the gymnasiumlike rehearsal room on the ninth floor of Radio City
Music Hall, staring into the faces of the slouching technicians,
directors and production assistants who will put on this year's
Tony Awards telecast on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' he said. ``Rosie O'Donnell is not going to be a
traffic cop on this show. She is (italics)hosting(end italics) our
show. She is a personality, and we are going to let her personality
shine. Am I understood? She will shine.''
</P>
<P>
   On last year's telecast, the first with Ms. O'Donnell, the talk
show host and Broadway enthusiast as host and the first to be held
at the expansive music hall instead of a smaller Broadway house,
she drew more national attention and higher ratings to Broadway's
top awards event, the theater's answer to the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not gonna burden her with listing everybody's credits
and so on,'' said Miller, the show's longtime director and new
executive producer. ``This year, we're gonna let the announcer do
that. She is not a traffic cop. She's gonna be our warm and fuzzy
host.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1997-1998 Broadway season comes to an official close on
Sunday night when the 52d annual awards honoring artistic and
technical achievement on the Broadway stage are handed out during a
live television broadcast at Radio City Music Hall with Ms.
O'Donnell presiding.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems certain: she will not be a traffic cop.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Donnell will open the show in full diva fashion, joining
Betty Buckley, Jennifer Holliday, Patti LuPone and eight dancers
from ``Chicago'' in a belters' medley. Later in the program, there
will be elaborate production numbers from the four nominees for
best musical (the opening extravaganzas from ``Ragtime'' and ``The
Lion King,'' ``Into the Fire'' from ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' and
``I Will Never Leave You'' from ``Side Show'') and the three
nominees for best revival of a musical (``Willkommen,'' from
``Cabaret,'' ``Sit Down, John,'' from ``1776,'' and a medley from
``The Sound of Music).
</P>
<P>
   And at 10:56 p.m., give or take, after Nathan Lane has opened
the final envelope of the evening, either Garth Drabinsky, creative
director of Livent, the corporation behind ``Ragtime,'' or Peter
Schneider, president of Walt Disney Theatrical Productions, the
corporation behind ``Lion King,'' will almost certainly be standing
on the music hall stage issuing thanks.
</P>
<P>
   A short time before, when Alec Baldwin opens the envelope for
best play, it will be revealed whether one of the two favorites for
the award, ``Art,'' by Yasmina Reza, or ``The Beauty Queen of
Leenane,'' by Martin McDonagh, have taken the award.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns to influence the 750 Tony voters are not as extensive
_ or expensive _ as the ones waged over Oscars, though some of the
awards, like the best musical Tony, can mean a fortune to a
production. Last season's ``Titanic,'' struggling before it won the
Tony, has since become one of the biggest hits on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaigning for a Tony is more of a low-key thing,'' said one
Broadway professional, who declined to be named because it might
affect his own campaign. ``It's done in ads in the newspapers and
the trades, and during the endless round of cocktail parties and
minor awards presentations that follow the announcement of the
nominations.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is also a small assortment of tchotchkes that have
gone out to Tony voters: a CD from ``Cabaret,'' books from ``The
Lion King,'' assorted T-shirts and coffee mugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties have been bigger this year than before and they're
coming closer together,'' said Isabelle Stevenson, president of the
American Theater Wing, which presents the Antoinette Perry Awards
in association with the League of American Theaters and Producers.
``It never ends now. And while we used to have one big party after
the awards now, with all the big corporations and everything being
bigger, a lot of people want to have their own smaller party. It's
getting to be big business, which tends to curtail some of the
warmth of the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to the awards, nominees try to give Tony
voters a reason to vote for their show, a kind of theatrical spin.
Drabinsky, for instance, has accepted some earlier awards for
``Ragtime'' by talking about how the show is very American and
traditional.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Taymor, the acclaimed director of ``Lion King,'' has
accepted awards by praising Disney for using its corporate muscle
to bring daring, cutting-edge techniques to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few nods and grunts around the room as Miller spoke
to his troops (``the salty group that follows me around,'' he
called them). People scribbled into their notebooks. ``There is an
awful lot of good stuff on Broadway this season,'' Miller told
them. ``I don't know what we can do to mess it up but we're gonna
try not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the season that the awards cap is the most lucrative and
successful in Broadway history, despite a slump in its last days
that saw the closing of several shows. The season set records for
attendance (11.3 million) and box office grosses (more than $550
million) and keeping virtually every theater on Broadway lighted
during the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Producers and theater owners have also tried to capitalize on
the flush times by beginning to edge up the top ticket price, which
had been stuck at $75 for years. Some added $1 service charges to
renovate theaters. Livent put in a VIP section at its Ford Center
for the Performing Arts, and prices there are set to rise to $135.
``Cabaret'' and ``Rent'' are raising top prices to $80.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just money, of course. The season was an artistic
success, as well, creating one of the most competitive Tony
contests in years, with a battle in almost every category capped by
the titanic struggle for the best musical award between
``Ragtime,'' with 13 nominations, and ``The Lion King,'' with 11.
</P>
<P>
   It is deemed all but certain by theater professionals that the
Roundabout Theater's searing revival of ``Cabaret'' will win the
best musical revival award, and the Roundabout's revival of ``A
View From the Bridge,'' by Arthur Miller, is the solid favorite for
best revival of a play, over ``The Chairs,'' ``Ah Wilderness'' and
``The Diary of Anne Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really a very good season, and I've been around a
long time,'' Ms. Stevenson said. ``It's one of the fullest seasons
that I know of and what's really gratifying is that there are so
many straight plays and such an enormous amount of talent on
Broadway. I can tell you that the Tony nominating committee was
hard-pressed to limite their nominations to four in such categories
as best play and best male performance.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, not long ago straight plays were considered such an
endangered species on Broadway that the Broadway Initiative, among
other efforts, was created, in part, to subsidize them. Now
straight plays are being presented in profusion and with marked
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season was the year of the play,'' said Jed Bernstein,
the league's executive director. ``What producers discovered this
season is that it is possible to package and produce a play
profitably, whether it's through limited runs or star vehicles or
whatever. It's doable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the unusual breadth of the season has struck many.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use a department store analogy,'' Bernstein said. ``What you
hope for is to have really good stuff in every department, so you
can get all the potential customers into the store. This was a year
where that really seemed to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second year, the two-hour Tony broadcast on CBS, from 9
to 11 p.m., will be preceded by a one-hour PBS telecast produced by
WNET/Channel 13 called ``Broadway '98: Launching the Tony Awards.''
</P>
<P>
   During that hour, the awards will be presented for choreography,
musical score, musical book, orchestration, scenic design,
orchestration, lighting design, costume design, director of a play,
director of a musical and the annual award to a regional theater
company. This year, that award goes to the Denver Center Theater.
</P>
<P>
   During the CBS program, the acting Tonys will be presented,
along with the two most prestigious awards, for best play and best
musical. There will be plenty of time for production numbers,
celebrity presenters and effusive speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a veteran of many awards broadcasts, said he had decided
not to use the tactic of playing music to force loquacious winners
from the podium. Instead, he said, he will simply place a message
on the teleprompter (``Please wrap it up'') and hope for
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   This year's innovation will be a segment highlighting the
nominees for best play, which are often overshadowed by the musical
production numbers. Miller asked the writers of each of the
nominated plays _ Ms. Reza, McDonagh, David Henry Hwang for ``The
Golden Child'' and John Leguizamo for ``Freak'' _ to write a
45-second synopsis of their play to be performed by a member of its
cast, in costume, on a set designed to resemble the show's actual
Broadway set.
</P>
<P>
   All of the productions except ``Art'' agreed to take part. Late
last week, the producer of ``Art'' told Miller that Alda, who had
been asked to read the synopsis, would not take part and Ms. Reza
would not write one.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Baldwin, the award's presenter, will read a
synopsis of ``Art'' written by Miller's staff and then introduce a
trio of live readings by performers in the other shows, culminating
in Leguizamo's interpretation of his own play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that he's nominated this year,'' Miller said. ``He's
such a fast-talking, fast-thinking, high-energy performer. It going
to be a great burst of energy at the end of the segment. That guy
can tell his life story (italics)and(end italics) yours in 45
seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   An informal canvassing of more than two dozen theater
professionals _ an eclectic assortment of producers, theater
owners, performers and press agents _ revealed a widespread belief
that there are at least two all-but-sure winners: ``Cabaret'' for
best musical revival, and the show's star, Natasha Richardson, for
best actress in a musical. (The nominees competing with Ms.
Richardson are Marin Mazzie for ``Ragtime,'' Alice Ripley and Emily
Skinner for ``Side Show'' and Ms. Buckley for ``Triumph of Love.'')
</P>
<P>
   A sizable majority also believe that Alan Cumming, the
insinuating M.C. of ``Cabaret,'' will win the award for best actor
in a musical, although a minority favor Brian Stokes Mitchell's
star turn as Coalhouse Walker in ``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Sills' acclaimed performance as ``The Scarlet
Pimpernel'' is seen to be handicapped by that show's mediocre
reviews and box office struggles, while Peter Friedman's Tateh in
``Ragtime'' is seen to be overshadowed by Mitchell's performance in
the same show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mitchell and Friedman will split the `Ragtime' votes and
Cumming will skate to victory,'' one producer said.
</P>
<P>
   But another producer demurred: ``The M.C. role is traditionally
a supporting one, and Mitchell really commands the stage in
`Ragtime.' I think that when the voters look in their hearts,
they'll go with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony LaPaglia is the favorite to win best actor in a play for
``A View From the Bridge,'' though some think Alfred Molina will
win for ``Art,'' a box-office success that could use a Tony or two
to catapult future national tours.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Briers, nominated for ``The Chairs,'' is considered
highly unlikely to win. But more than one person suggested that
Leguizamo could be the night's biggest surprise by winning the
award.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long shot, but `Freak' has been a real phenomenon and
has brought a lot of people into a Broadway theater who have never
been in one before,'' one said of the young and Hispanic audience
attracted to the show. ``I think there is a real sentiment to give
the show something, and this is the most logical award.''
</P>
<P>
   A minority predict that Jane Alexander, returning to Broadway
this season after four years of leading the National Endowment for
the Arts, will win the best actress award for ``Honour.'' Most
others feel that the poorly received play will be overshadowed by
``Beauty Queen of Leenane'' and the award will go to Marie Mullen.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller voting block feels that Allison Janney, a favorite
among Tony voters, will win for her performance in ``A View from
the Bridge.'' Geraldine McEwan, nominated for ``The Chairs,'' is
considered a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of those asked said the best play contest is between
two favorites, with about two-thirds believing that ``Beauty
Queen'' will take the award (``It's been the biggest sensation on
Broadway since `Lion King' opened,'' said) and another third
favoring ``Art.'' (``A third of the voters are from the road and
they're going to want to have an audience-pleaser like `Art' to
bring a Tony into their towns,'' another said.)
</P>
<P>
   Both ``Freak,'' whose limited run ends next month, and ``The
Golden Child,'' which has already closed, were seen as outside
shots by only one predictor each.
</P>
<P>
   The general consensus seems to be that Terrence McNally will win
the award for writing the book of ``Ragtime,'' but that ``The Lion
King'' will take home most of the rest of the awards, including one
for Ms. Taymor's direction.
</P>
<P>
   The closest contest, if these people are correct, will come in
the best musical category. Of the 26 people who ventured a
prediction, most felt the race could easily go either way. But when
pressed for a choice, 15 felt that ``Ragtime'' would take the award
and 11 went with ``Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While `Ragtime' is a traditional Broadway musical with a great
book and great music and great performances, `Lion King' is more of
a spectacle,'' one producer said. ``A lot of people don't think
it's a Broadway musical, really. It's an adaptation of an animated
movie with puppets. I think they'll go with something more
traditional.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, another said. ``There's more than spectacle to `Lion
King,' '' he said. ``There is something joyous about it. `Ragtime'
is too earnest and plodding. Voters will go with joyous every
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
