</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARLIE-MOVIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHARLIE HOBOKEN': A MOB HIT MAN'S WEAPON: TALK, TALK AND MORE
TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end)  
 (JT)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Charlie Hoboken'' is a movie about a couple of hit men. Mostly
what it does is talk you to death _ slowly and painfully.
</P>
<P>
   Buried somewhere in all the talk, which mistakes the smart
alecky for the witty, is a tale of youth and risk-taking ambition
contrasted with conservative middle age, of self-centered egotism
that leads to loneliness contrasted with a generosity of spirit and
true love, and of father-son relationships.
</P>
<P>
   But for Thomas F. Mazziotti, a New Jersey insurance company
owner's son who wrote and directed this story of an insurance
company owner's son by day who is a mob hit man by night, talk _
not action _ is character. And the talk rapidly grows wearisome.
</P>
<P>
   Pickup lines like ``Do you know the word `fun' is in the word
`funeral.' So do you want to have some fun?'' have an effect as
deadening as any of the business carried out by Charlie Hoboken
(Ken Garito), the young moonlighting partner of a third-generation
assassin, Harry Cedars (Austin Pendleton). Little wonder that most
of the women that Charlie attracts to the candlelit abandoned
church where he lives don't come back after he insists on using the
astringent in his bathroom to clean their fingers and pores.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of ``Charlie Hoboken,'' Harry and Charlie have
carried out 30 successful hits in a year and a half for the Boss,
and Charlie is getting bored. An ambitious yuppie, he'd like to do
something different. Instead of shootings with a silenced pistol,
what about electrocutions, stabbings, poisons? What about working
on commissions rather than flat fees? And somewhere in the back of
his selfish mind is the idea of rising in the Boss's criminal
hierarchy, over Harry's dead body, if need be.
</P>
<P>
   Harry, a nerd who affects leather caps, rumpled tweeds and plaid
shirts that give him the appearance of a Woody Allen clone who
wandered into the wrong movie, is happy the way things are. He's so
colorless that ``America's Most Wanted'' canceled its segment on
him. When he comes home after the night's work to his wife, Angie
(Tovah Feldshuh with a ``Dead End'' dames accent), and she asks him
about work, he replies, ``Same old, same old.'' Angie would like
children, but Harry is not so sure, given the risks inherent in his
line of work. Anyway, Charlie is sort of like a son to him.
</P>
<P>
   But Charlie isn't much of a son to his father (George Morfogen)
or his stepmother (Anita Gillette).
</P>
<P>
   And he isn't good company.
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of comedy, ``Charlie Hoboken'' is more bleak than
black.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   CHARLIE HOBOKEN
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Thomas Mazziotti; director of
photography, Mike Slovis; edited by Thomas R. Rondinella; music by
Peter Lopez; production designer, Dina Goldman; produced by Linda
Crean; released by Northern Arts Entertainment. Running time: 85
minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Austin Pendleton (Harry Cedars), Ken Garito (Charlie
Hoboken), Tovah Feldshuh (Angie Cedars), Anita Gillette
(Stepmother) and George Morfogen (Father).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
