<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURNE-JONES-EXHIBIT-2     06-04 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNE-JONES-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LOVE WITH THE PAST AND A VISION OF PERFECT BEAUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The prolific Pre-Raphaelite painter and designer
Edward Burne-Jones (1833-1898) is an artist whom generations of
cognoscente have loved to hate, or at least ignore.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1870s and '80s, after two decades of relative obscurity,
Burne-Jones found himself considered England's greatest living
painter. and celebrated in France and Belgium, where his work
influenced Symbolism and he established ties with such like-minded
artists as Gustave Moreau, Pierre Puvis de Chavaunnes and Ferdinand
Khnopff.
</P>
<P>
   But even then, some contemporaries could sniffed at his
chivalric themes of Galahad, the Sleeping Beauty and Saint George,
and at his somnolent lovers and pensive sibyls. And numerous
complaints have echoed through the years.
</P>
<P>
   To some, his work has been regressive, inexcusably innocent or
too literary. Others have found his dense compositions were
overwrought and claustrophobic: too eminently Victorian. Still
others have labeled the enigmatic sensuousness of his handsome
androgynous figures decadent or morbid.
</P>
<P>
   Burne-Jones's reputation began to decline shortly before his
death. His style was superseded by Impressionism, which the
meticulous Burne-Jones found ``muzzy'' and unfinished, and by a
younger generation of artists who were awed by his achievements but
tended to look elsewhere for inspiration. (Still, it is hard to
imagine Aubrey Beardsley's unfurling line and languorous aloofness
without the precedent of Burne-Jones.)
</P>
<P>
   But, as the painter William Rothstein put it in his memoirs,
Burne-Jones's work may have ``certain weaknesses; but no man who
can draw and design so nobly and thereby impress his vision on the
world is to be swept aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, my suggestion for visitors to ``Edward Burne-Jones:
Victorian Artist-Dreamer,'' the lavish survey at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art: Whatever you think about his art, surrender to the
dream. You won't regret it.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which includes more than 170 works in several media,
is the most comprehensive survey of his work yet and the first in
this country. It has been organized by Laurence B. Kanter and Dita
Amory, curators of the Met's Robert L. Lehman collection, and
Stephen Wildman, curator of the Ruskin Library at Lancaster
University in England.
</P>
<P>
   Ignore the installation's oppressive color scheme, but give in
to the sometimes wooden paintings with their distinctive horizontal
proportions (all the better to depict reclining bodies), burnished
colors, dense-packed compositions and gilded frames.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy the radiant stained glass and the two books for which
Burne-Jones made ink-on-vellum covers as gifts to Frances Graham,
the daughter of a patron. Compare the firey portrait of Maria
Zambaco, with whom he had a passionate affair in the late 1860s, to
his portraits of Georgiana, his devoted wife, or Lady Frances
Balfour: whose soft gazes disguise inner strength.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, pore over his astounding tapestries, executed in
collaboration, as were his stained-glass commissions, with his
lifelong friend William Morris, and fabricated by the craftsmen at
Morris and Co. Burne-Jones benefited incalculably from Morris's
brilliance as a designer; and his researches into the crafts,
motifs and literature of the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
   Especially crucial was Morris's emphasis on assertive patterns
derived from nature; they seem to have infiltrated Burne-Jones's
art, affecting everything from his depictions of lush brocades to
his habit of reducing nature to easily distinguished bands of
repeating leaves, flowers or trees.
</P>
<P>
   Such devices give Burne-Jones's work a sense of artifice and
vitality that makes him the least naturalistic, and best, of the
Pre-Raphaelites.
</P>
<P>
   The tapestries are the visual high point of the show. Their
scale fits the scope of Burne-Jones's ambition, their materials
magnified his artifice further and in the process frequently
freshened up age-old conventions. Haloes are little more than
circles of fizzy white dots, for example.
</P>
<P>
   In the exhibition's penultimate gallery, which contains six
tapestries depicting the quest for the Holy Grail, the angels'
ornate vestments seem studded with real gems, so precise are the
woven highlights.
</P>
<P>
   By almost any standards, there's plenty that can be called weird
and retrograde about Burne-Jones's art: its fervent historicism,
its relentless busyness, its frequent sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   He borrowed from nearly every major Early and High Renaissance
artist, from Giotto to Michelangelo and, later in life, Titian.
Burne-Jones was ``an art historian's artist,'' as the catalog puts
it.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts may not always strike the eye as being esthetically
alive, as having ideas that might fuel contemporary art, as
exhibitions from the past often do.
</P>
<P>
   But this exhibition lays out an extraordinary career. It also
says much about Victorian England, its romantic love of the past
and its confidence in its own bright future. After all, Burne-Jones
was the first English artist to be given a memorial service at
Westminster Abbey.
</P>
<P>
   Burne-Jones was nonetheless a reclusive artist. He disliked
selling his paintings and even refused to exhibit them from 1870 to
1877. He avoided publicity, became more self-deprecating as his
fame increased, declined to explain the meaning of his images and
suffered paralyzing losses of confidence that resulted in paintings
and projects that were worked on for years or abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Burne-Jones had drawn incessantly since childhood. In 1856 at
22, he fled Oxford for London, driven by the desire to be an
artist. He was quickly swept up in the Gothic Revival, becoming a
protege of the critic John Ruskin, whose passionate writings on
Gothic art and architecture helped spark the revival.
</P>
<P>
   He also became a close friend of Dante Gabriel Rosetti, who
would provide most of his scant artistic training. And he fell in
with Rosetti's Pre-Raphaelites, who looked to the Italian
Primitives, wanted to unify art and poetry and viewed academic
training with a radical disdain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The young Burne-Jones was tailor-made for this milieu. In fact,
he and Morris, ultimately the founder of the English Arts and
Crafts movement, would breath new life into the Pre-Raphaelite
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Burne-Jones, like Morris, had loved the Middle Ages since
childhood, attracted, through poetry and Walter Scott's novels, to
its legends, romances and fairy tales. These stories provided
escape from a life that was itself a bit Gothic: Burne-Jones's
mother died within a week of his birth, and his father mourned for
years, taking his son on frequent visits to her grave.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder love, both lost and found, would be one of the
artist's consuming themes, or that his becalmed knights and ladies
convey intense if elusive states that include contemplation, grief,
reverie and, often, sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity of Burne-Jones's work is thoroughly accounted for
here, with the exception of his drawings, which are too few, and
the absence of certain Burne-Jones chestnuts, like the Tate's
``Golden Circle,'' which will be seen only on the European leg of
this exhibition's tour.
</P>
<P>
   But other important works are present, like the Met's hauntingly
beautiful ``Le Chant d'Amour'' finished in 1877 and exhibited in
1878 at the Grosvenor Gallery to great acclaim, and ``King Cophetua
and the Beggar Maid.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting, which established Burne-Jones's reputation in
Paris, is based on a Tennyson poem and features an elaborately
stepped, gold architectural setting that looks like a Cimabue
throne reinterpreted by Piero della Francesca.
</P>
<P>
   This work, like so many here, reflects Burne-Jones's ability not
merely to borrow from the past, but to mix and remix his sources
with astounding fluidity. For example, he blended classical and
Christian themes by adorning the story of Pygmalion with the
garments and architecture of the Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Finding of Medusa,'' an imposing body-color study for
his unrealized cycle of paintings based on the story of Perseus,
the recipe combines Michelangelo with Henry Fuseli to dramatic,
almost surreal effect.
</P>
<P>
   It is also important to realize that despite its involvement
with literature, Burne-Jones's work is not literary in the usual
sense. It does not give precedence to subject matter. Rather it
breaks narratives into a series of autonomous scenes that
communicate primarily through a combination of charged
psychological states expressed by his figures and the visual rigor
of contrasting forms, colors, patterns and degrees of spatial
depth.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Burne-Jones, working in the time before Freud and before
Fauvism, laid out the separate paths of much 20th-century art _ the
one toward expressions of raw emotion, the other toward pure form _
cranking them up to a new level, but kept them inextricably fused.
Maybe this accounts for the hothouse intensity of his work.
</P>
<P>
   Follow his confined spaces closed off by dense swatches of
repeating flowers, trees and bushes through Art Nouveau to their
logical conclusion, and you find Jackson Pollock. Follow his
withdrawn or anxious characters, and you find Francis Bacon. (But
let's not get carried away. Pursue the subject matter and stylized
realism to its logical conclusion, and you find N.C. Wyeth,
Maxfield Parrish and Norman Rockwell.)
</P>
<P>
   His work rife with once and future art styles, Burne-Jones
worked hard to keep everything up in the air. In fully mature works
like those from the ``Rose Briar'' series, based on the saga of
Sleeping Beauty, the reclining figures are surrounded by coil upon
coil of thorny, flowery briar, and nature is frequently pushed in
the direction of pure pattern.
</P>
<P>
   It is telling that Burne-Jones did not depict the final scene,
where Sleeping Beauty is awakened by the Prince's kiss. That would
have been too definite for an artist who summed up his work with
the following statement, displayed at the beginning of this odd and
moving exhibition: ``I mean by a picture, a beautiful romantic
dream of something that never was, never will be, in a light better
than any light that ever shone, in a land no one can define or
remember _ only desire.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``Edward Burne-Jones: Victorian Artist-Dreamer''
remains through Sept. 6 at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, Fifth
Avenue at 82d Street. It will travel to the Birmingham Museums and
Art Gallery, England (Oct. 17 through Jan. 7, 1999) and the Musee
d'Orsay, Paris (March 1 through June 6).(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
