<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-WOODY-DOWNSIZE-NYT (Hollywood) _ For 25 years, Woody
Allen has offered a remarkable outpouring of films using a tightly
knit production staff, veterans who considered themselves loyal
members of the Allen professional family. Not anymore. Quietly,
within the atmosphere of secrecy and control that marks Allen's
creative decision making, the team that helped fashion movies like
``Annie Hall,'' ``Manhattan'' and ``Hannah and Her Sisters'' has
largely broken up amid an intense effort to cut costs and overhaul
the management of his operation. Photo. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   CARREY-FILM-PROFILE-HNS (Undated) _ Jim Carrey has his best role
yet in ``The Truman Show,'' in which he realizes his whole life has
been a TV show, and everyone in it is an actor. By Louis Parks.
</P>
<P>
   DISCO-INTERVIEW-COX (New York) _ As a group of mostly
twentysomething and slightly older journalists debates the cultural
meaning of disco, director Whit Stillman shifts around in his
chair, grinning broadly.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-FRY-BOS (Undated) _ Spend time with Stephen Fry, and one
can almost envision what it might have been like in the company of
Oscar Wilde. By Renee Graham.
</P>
<P>
   GEEZERS-MOVIES-HNS (Undated) _ Michael Douglas and Gwyneth
Paltrow. Jack Nicholson and Helen Hunt. Warren Beatty and Halle
Berry. See the trend here? There's a spate of movies out now
featuring young women and old men. It's not new, but it seems to be
getting worse. What does it mean? We ask experts _ and a few
movie-goers. By Clifford Pugh.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-GIBBONS-COX _ For authors, landing a spot on Oprah's Book
Club is akin to winning a literary lottery. Last fall, North
Carolina writer Kaye Gibbons went from being a critically acclaimed
author to best selling celebrity. By Don O'Briant.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-BIOGRAPHIES-HNS (San Antonio) _ Pope John Paul II, who
turned 78 last week, will become the longest-reigning pope of the
20th century Sunday. He'll surpass Pope Pius XII, who headed the
Roman Catholic Church 19 years, seven months and seven days. Pope
John Paul II leads in another measure _ the number of major
biographies written about him (three). By Michael Parker.
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN-MONEY-MAVEN-NYT (Woodstock, N.Y.) _ ``Maxing Out: Why
Women Sabotage Their Financial Security'': Just by the subtitle,
you can tell that Colette Dowling is willing to court controversy.
By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-DIFRANCO-BOS (Undated) _ Ani DiFranco is a walking,
talking, guitar-strutting rebel, proud of her ``indie girl'' status
and her anti-corporate. By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   TIPTON-GENDER-NYT (New York) _ The hidden life of Billy Tipton,
a cross-dressing jazz musician. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-STEWART-BOS (Undated) _ Talk about having a full life. Rod
Stewart has five children by three women. He's made more than 20
albums, many of them bestsellers. He's in the Rock Hall of Fame.
And he owns several homes around the world, including one in Palm
Beach, Fla., from where he recently telephoned on a beautiful,
85-degree day. ``Life is good. It couldn't be better,'' said
Stewart, who plans to have a sixth child, the third one with his
wife, actress-model Rachel Hunter. Here's the biggest news for his
fans, though: Stewart, now 53, is rocking again. By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   SINATRA-MYTH-NYT (Undated) _ Monotheism doesn't suit the world
of popular music; that world has too many great performers. The
pleasure I have always taken in Frank Sinatra's best singing is
being tainted by the ``thou shalt have no other singer'' eulogies
and by the cultural studies, conferences and papers still to come.
By Margo Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GENERAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SLATE-MEDIA-NYT (Undated) _ A talk with Scott Shuger, who writes
about today's papers for Slate. By Lisa Napoli.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURIST-MEDIA-NYT (San Francisco) _ Peter Schwartz, a leading
futurist and chairman of the Global Business Network, says that the
world is witnessing ``the beginnings of a global economic boom on a
scale never experienced before,'' driven by waves of fundamental
technological change and free-market economics. Photo. By Steve
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   BLIND-SKYDIVER-HNS (San Antonio) _ Blind since birth, Robert
Dittman had no problems leaping from a plane flying at 10,000 feet.
``I just want to prove to people there are no limits, whether they
are disabled or not,'' Dittman said. By Loren Figueroa.
</P>
<P>
   TENN-VALEDICTORIAN-NYT (Memphis, Tenn.) _ Three years ago, Daira
Hodges was a 14-year-old honor student. But on May 9, 1995,
everything changed when an ex-boyfriend, also 14, dragged her into
a vacant classroom, choked her, stabbed her 21 times, and then went
to take an algebra test, leaving her for dead. But she regained
consciousness, survived and on Tuesday will graduate from East High
School as valedictorian of her class. This fall, she will begin
working toward a pre-med degree at Vanderbilt. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   VALEDICTORIAN-TEX (Kerrville, Texas) _ Tivy High School
valedictorian Josh Walther saw humor in calling on the two
lowest-ranking members of his class to replace him at the podium at
commencement exercises. ``Why should I have to do more work and
give a speech?'' he planned on saying. ``I wasn't the one slacking
the last four years.'' School officials stopped him from giving the
speech. By Zeke MacCormack.
</P>
<P>
   EMILY-POST-STAMP-NYT (Undated) _ In her 1923 classic book
``Etiquette,'' Emily Post observed that ``older people invariably
feel that the younger generation is speeding swiftly on the road to
perdition.'' And so it is with stamps. Last week, the first
domestic image ever to appear on a stamp was unveiled, heralding
Emily Post's ``Etiquette.'' The stamp _ a 1920s place-setting with
Lafayette Towle silver, a goblet and hand-painted Copeland Spode
China plate _ is elegant and extremely proper. But beneath that
white damask tablecloth lurks a radical shift in the design and
subject matter of the United States postage stamp, from America's
calling card to adhesive pop icon. By Patricia Leigh-Brown.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PASTRY-CHEF-NYT (Paris) _ Except for a few late-nighters
stumbling home, the Avenue des Champs-Elysees was eerily still. But
inside Laduree, a tea room, pastry shop and restaurant, everything
was astir. It was 6 in the morning, and Pierre Herme, the premier
pastry chef in Paris, was taking the first of many rounds through
the place. To the French, Herme has achieved the stature of the
legendary pastry chef Gaston Lenotre. And since last September he
has taken charge of one of Paris's most beloved tea salons and
pastry shops. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
