<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KURT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KURT AND COURTNEY': A DEMIMONDE IN THE PACIFIC NORTHWEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bleary, purple-faced, waving a fly swatter and his middle
finger, covered with tattoos and accompanied by a mean-tempered
dog, a man nicknamed El Duce lumbers over to Nick Broomfield
asking, ``Where's the booze?'' They have been introduced by a third
party identified as ``Divine Brown's pimp.''
</P>
<P>
   El Duce, whose night job is delivering ugly rants with a rock
band (the Mentors) while wearing an executioner's mask, claims to
have valuable information about Courtney Love's role in the death
of her husband. ``She offered me fifty grand to whack Kurt
Cobain,'' he says, talking tougher than he looks. He offers to
reveal more about this if Broomfield will buy him a beer.
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield, whose last two films were ``Heidi Fleiss: Hollywood
Madam'' and ``Fetishes,'' is the ingratiating, kink-loving,
deceptively mild-mannered British filmmaker whose favorite
interview question seems to be ``Really?'' His handling of El Duce
is typically low-keyed. ``People might think you're not the most
reliable witness,'' he remarks in a whopping understatement. People
might also think, upon hearing later of El Duce's death, that his
demise shouldn't necessarily give rise to conspiracy theories. As
seen in Broomfield's documentary ``Kurt and Courtney,'' he looks
quite capable of having accidentally wandered in front of a train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt and Courtney'' is a prime, colorful example of
Broomfield's offbeat investigative tactic: burrowing into scuzz.
Meandering almost casually into his material, Broomfield cruises
through the Pacific Northwest searching for something, anything,
that will give his film a raison d'etre. Even when he delays in
finding it, his eye for the sordid demimonde helps him to assemble
a memorable group portrait of grunge parasites with Nirvana
connections. Everyone here has either a grievance to settle or a
story to sell. Broomfield himself doesn't have either until he
happens onto an unexpected benefactress: Courtney Love.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Ms. Love's extraordinary efforts to suppress this
film backfired into helpful publicity (it became the hottest
after-hours ticket at Sundance after official screenings had to be
canceled for legal reasons), the film itself had evolved into a
kind of ``Courtney and Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Galvanized by Ms. Love's stonewalling, Broomfield began to make
her the focus of much speculation. Ms. Love's long trail of enemies
leads all the way back to her father, Hank Harrison, who freely
suggests she was capable of dispatching her husband and recalls
telling teen-age Courtney ``that she couldn't smoke dope, do
heroin, turn tricks or bring any of her weird heroin buddies around
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Broomfield why, in effect, blood isn't any thicker than
water here, Harrison describes his feelings about family by asking:
``You saw `The War of the Roses?'''
</P>
<P>
   Never one to pass up trivia, Broomfield begins the film with
revelations like the sound of 2-year-old Kurt singing (as preserved
by his devoted aunt), the fact that an early girlfriend found
living with him ``fun'' and the detail that he used to enjoy firing
a BB gun at the Washington State Lottery office across the street
from his home.
</P>
<P>
   Slight as some of this is, it piles up, and its cumulative
effect is to draw the viewer into the film's determined digging.
And eventually, as the array of minor figures becomes so sordid
that El Duce fits in easily, ``Kurt and Courtney'' becomes nearly
as absorbing for the viewer as this odyssey must have become for
Broomfield.
</P>
<P>
   From the dazed, scabby so-called friend who supplied Cobain with
a gun to Ms. Love's embittered ex-boyfriend (they met cute when she
threw a drink in his face) to the private detective who sees a
James M. Cain plot in Ms. Love's rise to glamorous widowhood, the
speakers here are united by suspicion and malaise. They define the
Cobain-Love aura that is this film's real subject, just as
Broomfield's film about Heidi Fleiss explored the world that made
Ms. Fleiss possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Minghella!'' Ms. Love is heard exclaiming sweetly to the
director of ``The English Patient'' on Oscar night, in the midst of
reinventing herself as glossy Hollywood royalty. Just when it looks
as if the film will never get closer to her than that, Broomfield,
who becomes an active part of his own films, barges onto the stage
at an American Civil Liberties Union dinner where Ms. Love is
speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Having included audiotapes of Ms. Love and Cobain threatening
writers in ``Kurt and Courtney,'' Broomfield denounces her publicly
and gives a final note of grandstanding to a film that otherwise
might have reached no real conclusion. Broomfield doesn't
ultimately prove, or even believe, that Cobain died under
incriminating circumstances. But he makes it wrenchingly clear why
the world in which he lived had become impossible to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt and Courtney'' was never a music documentary, but a
negligible sample of Cobain's music has been removed from the film
for legal reasons. Threats of lawsuits were also brought to bear
against the San Francisco theater that showed the film.
Broomfield's financial backing from Showtime was apparently
withdrawn because of external pressures. The film opens today at
Cinema Village. It is _ and is well worth _ a trip.
</P>
<P>
   Production notes:
</P>
<P>
   KURT AND COURTNEY
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Nick Broomfield; directors of photography, Joan
Churchill and Alex Vendor; edited by Mark Atkins; music by David
Bergeaud; produced by Tine Van Den Brande and Michael D'Acosta;
released by Roxie Releasing.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 95 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Kurt Cobain and Courtney Love.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
