<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: OLDIES VIA MAIL ORDER; MOVIE LOVERS VIDEO GUIDE; NEW
RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Old (but Gold) And Slapstick
</P>
<P>
   For a look at the month ahead in video, one person to consult is
Bob Helland of Asymmetrical Entertainment, a Brooklyn mail-order
company that previews coming releases in its monthly bulletin. June
looks moderately promising. While not particularly rich in big
feature films _ ``Amistad,'' ``Wag the Dog,'' ``Welcome to
Sarajevo'' and ``Wings of the Dove'' are among the better-know
titles scheduled _ the month has several older films that people
have been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   From Home Vision come ``Forever and a Day'' (1943), with a huge
British cast including Charles Laughton, Merle Oberon and Claude
Rains, and ``Spitfire'' (1942), Leslie Howard's last film before he
was killed when the plane he was aboard was shot down by the Nazis
in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   Helland also recommends ``The Slapstick Encyclopedia'' from
Kino. ``All good stuff that's never been out before, a lot of Fatty
Arbuckle and Buster Keaton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of June's old movies come in series. ``The best things are
the Universals,'' he said, a reference to three sets of old movies
_ literary adaptations, comedies and Westerns _ from Universal.
Perhaps the most awaited is ``All My Sons'' (1948). A television
version of the Arthur Miller play has been available on tape but
never the Irving Reis film starring Burt Lancaster and Edward G.
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is ``The Great Gatsby'' (1949), with Alan Ladd and
Betty Field as Daisy Buchanan, the earlier of two movies based on
the F. Scott Fitzgerald novel. ``It's not a great film, but Field
is really fine,'' Helland said.
</P>
<P>
   The most important comedy is ``The Major and the Minor'' (1942),
which starred Ginger Rogers and Ray Milland and was Billy Wilder's
first feature film, and there are two notable Westerns, ``Man in
the Shadow'' (1957) and ``Canyon Passage'' (1946).
</P>
<P>
   `` `Man in the Shadow' only because it has a long, offbeat
performance by Orson Welles,'' Helland said, ``and `Canyon Passage'
because there are a lot of Susan Hayward fans out and because of
the Hoagy Carmichael song `Ole Buttermilk Sky.''' Helland doesn't
have time to discuss all the releases with everybody, but he will
mail you the catalog. Information: (718) 237-6031.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting and Dicing
</P>
<P>
   Mail order catalogs are ordinarily drab or drabber, so it's a
pleasure, almost a shock, to open ``The Movie Lovers Video Guide''
from Facets Multimedia, a large Chicago distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with ``33 Directors to Watch'' (Arnaud Desplechin,
Mike Leigh, Emir Kusturica, Peter Greenaway), the catalog makes a
striking case for itself by shuffling thousands of Facets listings
into scores of categories: 50 silent masterpieces, 25 Shakespeare
plays on video, 100 best British television titles, 25 films about
the Holocaust, 100 cult classics, 100 best horror stories, 100
films that fell through the cracks (like ``Gas Food Lodging,''
``Danzon,'' ``Big Night'' and other acclaimed films that never
found large theatrical audiences), 25 great cultural documentaries,
25 best dance videos, 50 top theater adaptations, five best Samurai
epics. And so on. Information: (800) 331-6197.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   The End of Violence
</P>
<P>
   At the center of Wim Wenders' darkly paranoid film, the bullying
action-movie mogul Mike Max (Bill Pullman) watches his empire fly
off the tracks for reasons he doesn't understand. First, a 400-page
document about a top-secret government surveillance project lands
in his e-mail, source unknown. Next he is kidnapped and about to be
executed when his abductors are killed instead. Mike wakes up in a
flower bed tended by Chicano gardeners who keep him housed and fed
while he tries to figure out what has happened to him. That has to
do with a satellite communications expert named Ray (Gabriel
Byrne), who holes up in a hilltop observatory and monitors the
streets of Los Angeles on dozens of video screens.
</P>
<P>
   How these pieces connect make a story, Stephen Holden wrote in
The New York Times, that ``artfully crunches together more
intriguing speculation about technology, communications and the
effects of mass media than a hundred science-fiction fantasies.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997. MGM. $100.96. Laser disk, $39.98. 122 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Afterglow
</P>
<P>
   With the passion long drained from their marriage, the
middle-aged Phyllis (Julie Christie, in a performance that earned
her an Academy Award nomination) and Lucky (Nick Nolte), her
philandering husband, have settled into a workable understanding
with each other. Phyllis tolerates and even encourages Lucky's
affairs while he is patiently and supportively versed in the
moodiness that sends her to the doctor in search of physical
answers to her psychic anxieties. Allen Rudolph's film eventually
turns silly, but he ``writes and directs with obvious affection for
his characters and with a deep knowledge of whatever it is that
makes them tick'' (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1997. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. Laser disk, $34.95. 113
minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Scream 2
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back that blood-drenched gang from Wes Craven's slick,
funny 1996 slasher film about a pair of masked nutcases who slice
up much of the teen-age population of a leafy Midwestern town. This
time, the victims have moved on to Windsor College, but they're
just as dumb about setting themselves up to get their throats cut
or tossed off sorority house balconies. Sidney Prescott (Neve
Campbell) hangs in there once more as a plucky heroine. Gale
Weathers (Courteney Cox) has graduated from pushy television
reporter to best-selling author, but she's still relentlessly after
the story. And the ``Scream'' resident geeks, Randy and Dewey
(Jamie Kennedy and David Arquette), again offer up their bodies in
a film ``with so much tongue-in-cheek trickery that it virtually
escapes the horror genre, the one it so happily lampoons''
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1997. Dimension. $107.11. Laser disk, $39.99. 120 minutes.
Closed captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Big films like ``As Good as It Gets,'' ``Tomorrow Never Dies''
and ``Starship Troopers'' lead current best-renter lists. Here are
some top renters from Video Business magazine's list of smaller
films (those that played on no more than 475 theater screens).
</P>
<P>
   ULEE'S GOLD. A reclusive beekeeper (Peter Fonda) is forced by
the demands of family to journey beyond himself and raise two
granddaughters after his son lands in jail and their mother
disappears. 1997. Orion. $100.96. 111 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   THE ICE STORM. Watergate and marijuana are in the air in Ang
Lee's film, set at Thanksgiving time 1973, about suburban families
struggling with a malaise that strands them on shifting moral
ground. 1997. Fox. $104.16. 113 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSE OF YES. Marty (Josh Hamilton) takes his fiancee (Tori
Spelling) home to the stately family seat, where she encounters
Marty's spectacularly disturbed twin sister (and former lover),
Jackie-O (Parker Posey), who roams the mansion dressed and acting
like the former first lady. 1997. Miramax. $104.16. 90 minutes.
Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE COMPANY OF MEN. In Neil LaBute's gutsy first feature
film, a misogynous office worker named Chad (Aaron Eckhart) and a
like-minded friend (Matt Malloy) take out their resentments on a
deaf woman (Stacy Edwards). 1997. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 97
minutes. Closed captioned R.
</P>
<P>
   MRS. BROWN. Before Queen Victoria (Judi Dench) got back to work
as monarch after mourning Prince Albert, there was her relationship
with the horse groom John Brown (Billy Connolly). 1997. Miramax.
$104.16. 105 minutes. Closed captioned. PG. &QL; 
