<HEADER>
A4359 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-HABITAT-NAT     06-04 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-HABITAT-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        MIAMI REPS. JOIN TO HAMMER OUT HOMELESSNESS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark D. Preston  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 4 -- Rarely do Democrats and Republicans agree
how to solve homelessness, but this weekend three Miami House
members will cast aside partisan differences to attack the problem
head on.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with hammers and nails, GOP Reps. Lincoln Diaz-Balart and
Ileana Ros-Lehtinen will join Democratic Rep. Carrie Meek to build
a Habitat for Humanity home Saturday in Liberty City. A new 12-home
Habitat development will go up near 14 Habitat homes built with the
aid of former President Jimmy Carter in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The new homes will help address a lack of affordable housing in
Dade County, Diaz-Balart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an issue that transcends politics and partisanship,'' he
said. ``I think it is really important for (lawmakers) to work on a
bipartisan basis solving problems like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Miami lawmakers are joining their Washington colleagues in a
nationwide congressional blitz-building campaign dubbed ``The
Houses That Congress Built'' to coincide with the first day of
National Home Ownership Week.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Habitat) and others like it in Dade County are making the
American dream of home ownership a powerful reality for people who
otherwise wouldn't have a chance,'' Meek said.
</P>
<P>
   The representatives will work alongside local volunteers to
build a three-bedroom one-bathroom home for 49-year-old Mozell
Adams. The Eastern Credit Financial Union employee will share the
home with her 28-year-old daughter, Tonnika, and three
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Green, spokeswoman for the Greater Miami chapter of
Habitat, said the local affiliate will build 50 homes throughout
Dade this year, including 11 more in Liberty City. Since 1989, the
local Habitat chapter has built 250 homes in Dade.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 342 House members have pledged to build a Habitat
home in their congressional districts, including Rep. Jerry Lewis,
R-Calif. Lewis, chairman of the House Appropriations subcommittee
that focuses on housing issues, said he conceived the idea of
involving his House colleagues in a Habitat project while swimming
laps in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the great thing about this project is that it is kind
of a response that symbolizes all of our responsibilities to
govern,'' Lewis said. ``It takes us way beyond any partisan
consideration. That is what governing is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who has been involved with
Habitat since 1994, will dedicate the fifth Habitat home in his
suburban district north of Atlanta on Saturday. In all, Gingrich
has helped to build 10 Habitat homes across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker predicts as the program continues to grow, it will
become ``routine for elected leaders to return to help build homes
for needy Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the vision of our country that I believe in -- the
vision that (Alexis de) Tocqueville laid out in `Democracy in
America' -- where a citizen legislature comes home from Washington
to solve problems, rather than the other way around,'' Gingrich
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Kennedy, D-Mass., joined Lewis, Gingrich and 30 other
lawmakers to build the first two ``Houses That Congress Built'' in
the nation's capital last year. Kennedy said it is becoming more
important for traditional social programs to rely on nonprofit
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Congress reduces its financial commitment to affordable
housing, we must increasingly rely on volunteers and nonprofit
groups to fill the gap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat founder Millard Fuller will be in Nashville on Friday to
help Rep. Bob Clement, D-Tenn., and the local Habitat chapter try
to complete construction of a house in five hours and 30 minutes,
which would break the current record by 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller said lawmakers who volunteer with Habitat For Humanity
get a better understanding of how the poor live, and this knowledge
is important when it comes time for them to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``They become personally acquainted with these families,''
Fuller said. ``It is helpful to these policymakers to meet face to
face with these low-income families so that it will become a
personal matter with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The average Habitat home in the United States has three
bedrooms, one bath and costs $38,000. Families are selected by
their level of need, willingness to become partners in the program
and ability to repay the interest-free loan to build the house.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat has chapters in 59 countries and has built 65,000 homes
around the world since 1976.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
