<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES ON THE CALIFORNIA ART SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Left Their Art In San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   Even before the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art's $63 million
building was completed three years ago, the trustees had been
determined to fill it with world-class art, the kind that is not
only hard to find but hugely expensive. And over the past few
years, they have consistently bought works, either at auction, from
dealers or directly from artists, in ever larger numbers.
</P>
<P>
   This week, museum officials announced that several trustees have
given the institution 23 works by prominent 20th-century artists.
The gift, which includes works by Robert Rauschenberg, Piet
Mondrian, Marcel Duchamp, Louise Bourgeois, Robert Motherwell and
Barnett Newman, is valued at $40 million. One of the most important
portions of the gift is a group of 14 Rauschenbergs that have come
directly from the artist's collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is the single-largest commitment any museum
has made to a living artist,'' said David Ross, the peripatetic new
director of the museum, who assumed his post on Monday after seven
years as director of the Whitney Museum of American Art. ``I've had
a reasonable amount to do with this gift. Ever since I signed on
here, I started working. I disassociated myself from the Whitney in
March.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of the trustees responsible for the donation wish to
remain anonymous, one who doesn't mind being known is Phyllis
Wattis, a longtime philanthropist supporting cultural organizations
in the Bay Area, including the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Garrels, the museum's chief curator of painting and
sculpture, said the gifts helped fulfill a wish list drawn up some
time ago by the museum's curators. They not only wanted to fill
gaps in the collection, they also wanted to acquire the works of
certain artists in depth.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 Rauschenbergs substantially enlarge and diversify the
museum's holdings of the artist's work. They include paintings,
drawings, photography, sculpture and his mixed-media ``combines,''
a form he invented in the early 1950s. Especially noteworthy is the
artist's famous ``Erased de Kooning Drawing, 1953'' a predecessor
of conceptual art that the title accurately describes. It is an
original drawing that the Abstract Expressionist gave Rauschenberg
with the full knowledge of his intention.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Rauschenbergs are in the artist's retrospective that
opened at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum in New York City in
September and that will travel through Europe until February 1999.
They will arrive in San Francisco next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Mondrian is represented by a major work, ``Composition III
(White-Yellow),'' which the artist made from 1935-1942. The
painting was bought from the Pace Wildenstein Gallery in Manhattan
and had been in the respected collection belonging to Burton and
Emily Tremaine, who are Manhattan collectors.
</P>
<P>
   The museum acquired Duchamp's famous urinal, called
``Fountain.'' This edition of the 1917 work was made in 1964 for
Arturo Schwartz, an Italian scholar, dealer and collector, and is
the first of the artist's ``ready-mades,'' his term for
pre-existing objects that he designated as works of art, to join
the collection.
</P>
<P>
   An important Robert Motherwell is part of the gift. ``Elegy to
the Spanish Republic, No. 57,'' from 1957-1960, comes from one of
his best-known series, in which he explored the destruction of
Spanish democracy. It is a large painting, 84 inches by 109 inches,
with vertical bands and oval shapes in black and white. The museum
``gave Motherwell his first one-person museum show, in 1946,''
Garrels said. ``This painting has been on loan to us since 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   Another gift is ``Zim Zum I,'' a 1969 sculpture by the American
Abstract Expressionist Barnett Newman. It came from Annalee Newman,
his widow, and had been on long-term loan to the Tate Gallery in
London. It joins two Newman paintings in the San Francisco museum:
``Untitled (Number 3),'' a 1949 gift from Mrs. Newman, and
``Untitled,'' given to it in 1970 by Ms. Wattis.
</P>
<P>
   Works by other artists in the gift include a major 1960s
painting by Brice Marden, a Giocometti bust, a sculpture by Louise
Bourgeois, an Anselm Kiefer painting and a landscape by Wayne
Thiebaud.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Lore
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco isn't the only city on the West Coast with
passionate supporters of contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Peter and Eileen Norton, whose contemporary-art
collection numbers about 1,600 works, have just bought another
major collection, that of Karen and Clyde Beswick. The purchase
merges two of this country's largest private collections of
contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction cost the Nortons a reported $1.5 million and was
handled by Regen Projects, a West Hollywood gallery. It includes
about 700 works, primarily from the 1980s and 1990s, predominately
by Southern California artists.
</P>
<P>
   The Beswick collection had been tied up in court since March
1997, when Beswick was convicted of embezzling money from Brody
Smythe Direct, a Pasadena-based direct-mail company he founded. He
served 11 months in prison and is now in a halfway house in Los
Angeles. Mrs. Beswick sued her husband for divorce two years ago,
and proceeds from the sale of the art will go toward the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seized an unprecedented opportunity,'' Norton said. ``The
collection adds strength to strength.'' Besides increasing the
holdings of many artists the Nortons already had, the purchase adds
works by artists like Nan Goldin and Alexis Smith, which weren't in
their collection.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase, Norton said, is forcing him to focus on and cull
his holdings. Once he decides which works he doesn't want to keep,
he said, he plans to package works in groups by theme or similarity
and donate them to small institutions that have limited money for
buying contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long-term project,'' Norton said. ``Meanwhile, our
collection will continue to grow. We lend extensively to
institutions and have about three dozen works on loan right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
