<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIREMENT-SAVE-COX </SLUG>
     POLITICAL LEADERS SHOULD TRIM THEIR OWN
PENSIONS FIRST, SAY REFORMERS
 &HT;     With RETIREMENT.
 &HT;     By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton and Republican congressional
leaders tiptoed cautiously Thursday toward overhauling Social
Security, watchdog groups urged them to start by reforming their
own benefit programs.
</P>
<P>
   Opening a two-day summit on the politically supersensitive issue
of Social Security, the president joined with House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., to
voice concern about whether baby boomers will have enough cash for
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But private groups suggested that the leaders could demonstrate
their interest by trimming their own pensions, which far outpace
those of most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American public would appreciate a gesture of
leadership by example, to show they're serious about putting Social
Security on solid ground,'' said Gary Ruskin, director of the
Congressional Accountability Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a small but meaningful gesture,'' said Ruskin,
whose group is part of consumer activist Ralph Nader's network.
</P>
<P>
   The National Taxpayers Union joined in the call. ``Probably one
of the best ways to get Social Security reform rolling is using
Congress as a test case for reform,'' said the group's spokesman,
Pete Sepp. He called the congressional pension plan ``one of the
worst affronts'' to pension policy.
</P>
<P>
   Many veteran lawmakers have pension benefits that are twice as
generous as those offered private company executives, and all
members of Congress are eligible for far more generous benefits
than other federal workers.
</P>
<P>
   Former House speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, is currently receiving
$111,300 a year, while former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole,
R-Kan., is drawing $115,000. Former Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill,
continued to receive his pension even as he served prison time for
misuse of public funds. He is currently drawing $105,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Retired lawmakers also receive an annual cost-of-living
adjustment, almost unheard-of among private pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   Former presidents have much more lavish retirement packages,
including a pension that is equal to a current cabinet member's pay
(now $148,400), plus Secret Service protection, plus a limousine
and drivers, in addition to a government-paid office and funds for
the upkeep and staffing of their libraries.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief reform movement after the Republicans won control of
Congress in 1994, Gingrich and others promised to reduce the
congressional pensions. But the effort stalled and has all but
disappeared, amid published reports that Congress is planning to
give itself a pay increase this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., who took up the crusade to reform the
congressional pension program three years ago, has given up and
directed his energies elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate attempt to bring congressional pensions in line with
those paid other federal workers also failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pension reform has moved to the farthest back burner,'' said
Sepp. ``In times that are relatively prosperous, members of
Congress hope they can slide back. These issues don't produce the
same outrage when no one is feeling economic pain.''
</P>
<P>
   That could change rapidly if the economic picture changed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
