<HEADLINE>
CHASM SEPARATES CALIFORNIA GUBERNATORIAL CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Voters who had a hard time distinguishing
between California's three Democratic candidates for governor
should have no such trouble in the race between Attorney General
Dan Lungren and Lt. Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   A political chasm separates Lungren, the Republican, and Davis,
who defeated two rivals to become the Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a real contest of philosophies and ideas,'' said
Dave Puglia, Lungren's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is wasting no time in highlighting the distinctions on
such issues as abortion and education.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat had a strong showing in Tuesday's election,
garnering more votes than Lungren in the open primary. But
political analysts expect the general election race to be very
tight.
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco Examiner poll taken just before the primary
showed the two veteran politicians in a statistical dead heat. In a
hypothetical head-to-head matchup, 44 percent of voters backed
Davis, while 42 percent supported Lungren; 14 percent were
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very close _ within 4 or 5 points,''
predicted San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, who joined Davis at a
campaign stop Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues that differentiate Davis and Lungren:
</P>
<P>
   Education: Lungren proposes giving parents vouchers and allowing
parents and school districts more local control. Davis opposes
vouchers and wants to give mayors and state officials more power to
take over under-achieving schools.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion: Davis supports abortion rights. Lungren would seek to
end taxpayer-funded abortions and the late-term procedure called by
opponents ``partial-birth abortions,'' and to reinstate a state law
mandating parental consent for minors.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action: Lungren supported Proposition 209, which
ended affirmative action in public hiring and education, and says
improving elementary and secondary education and community colleges
is the only way for minority students to ``rise to the top.'' Davis
opposed Proposition 209, and would give the top 4 percent of
students in every school access to the University of California
system.
</P>
<P>
   Guns: Lungren voted for the Brady anti-gun bill when he was in
Congress, but opposed recent efforts to ban so-called Saturday
night specials. Davis backs a ban on assault weapons and Saturday
night specials, and recommends legislation to require child locks
on guns.
</P>
<P>
   Having secured the nominations of their parties, both candidates
are now duking it out for moderate voters. Their supporters are
stepping over one another to paint the opponent as an extremist.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson called
Davis ``the most vulnerable and liberal of the field, the former
chief of staff for Governor Moonbeam,'' referring to former Gov.
Jerry Brown.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Party Chairman Art Torres said voters in
November had a choice between ``a decorated Vietnam veteran and
perhaps the best governor-in-training California has ever
produced'' and Lungren, ``who opposes a woman's right to choice,
favors offshore oil drilling and supports the rights of convicted
criminals to own assault weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates share some similarities in their backgrounds.
Neither is wealthy. Both have held statewide office and have strong
support among party loyalists. Both champion tough-on-crime
positions and favor the death penalty. They are Catholics, though
Davis only became a regular church-goer again in recent years at
the urging of his wife.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
