<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AIR IS CLEARLY GETTING WORSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of the time, we take the air we breathe for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Unless we have asthma or emphysema or some other severe
respiratory disease, we usually don't even think about our air in
Texas, the heart of the great outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   But for the past few weeks, including Clean Air Week (May
24-30), a brown, ugly haze has hung in the Texas skies off and on,
burning our eyes, causing headaches and leaving people irritable
and lethargic.
</P>
<P>
   The smoky haze caused by brush fires burning out of control in
Central America and Mexico has a lot of people talking about air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   But we need to know that the ozone that moves in with hot and
humid sunny days each summer is an even greater health risk than
the fine particulate matter that has obscured the sun for the past
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Unhealthful levels of ozone the past couple of summers have
caused the Fort Worth-Dallas area to be classified as having a
``serious'' air quality problem _ just like Atlanta and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   We teach our children to play safely, avoid sunburn and insect
bites, learn to swim, and respect water and traffic rules, but the
American Lung Association says the air they breathe could be making
them sick.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone levels typically rise between May and October, when higher
temperatures and increased sunlight combine with stagnant
atmospheric conditions to ``cook'' hydrocarbon compounds and
nitrogen oxide emitted primarily by motor vehicles, power plants
and industry.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone is the most widespread air pollutant, affecting millions
of people nationwide, and it is expected to be around long after
the brush fires are finally extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Children are especially vulnerable to all forms of air pollution
because their airways are smaller and their respiratory defenses
are not fully formed. They spend lots of time outdoors, breathing
hard, primarily through the mouth, which has no way to filter the
air before it reaches the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   To help protect our kids, the Lung Association recommends
keeping track of air pollution levels and limiting the time they
spend outdoors in vigorous play when ozone levels are unhealthful.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a new consumer guide, ``Ozone Air Pollution and Our
Kids,'' is available free by calling the Lung Association at (800)
LUNG-USA.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor air pollution is impossible to avoid completely, but
there are ways we can make its overall impact less severe. The
American Association for Respiratory Care offers the following
tips:
</P>
<P>
   Avoid toxic fumes: If you work on your car in the garage, make
sure the garage door is completely open; don't allow exhaust fumes
to enter your house; dispose of chemically saturated rags in sealed
containers; replace lids on solvent containers securely; minimize
your use of strong chemicals in and around the home and garden; and
wear a mask to minimize inhalation of fumes.
</P>
<P>
   Stay updated on pollution reports: Be aware of ozone, mold and
pollen counts before going outside; wear a mask when mowing, raking
leaves or working in the garden; choose early morning for outside
exercise, and work to limit your exposure to irritants in the
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
