A4416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOGUCHI-ART-REVIEW-NY     06-04 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOGUCHI-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: WHAT SET NOGUCHI APART _ HE WAS APART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Ind., Japan)   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During the two decades before he died in 1988, at 84,
Isamu Noguchi spent half of each year at a studio in Mure, a
village on Shikoku, one of Japan's four main islands, making stone
sculptures. He liked materials that he thought matched the
character of the places he worked, so in the United States he tried
metals like aluminum, and in Italy he tried marble. In Japan he
favored basalt and granite (Swedish granite sometimes), partly
because for him they, like Japan, evoked nature, the earth, a
durable past.
</P>
<P>
   Pace Wildenstein's exhibition of a dozen of Noguchi's Mure works
from the 1980s must be the most peaceful spot in the city at the
moment, with the exception, maybe, of the garden at the Noguchi
Museum in Queens, where a big, shady Katsura tree is blooming among
the rocky sculptures and tinkling fountains.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't been to the museum in a while, and among other things
the visit helped clarify what's at Pace. A Mure sculpture has
lately been installed there: ``Beginnings'' consists of five
irregular andesite blocks in a circle. Noguchi had a way of making
a delicate order out of chaos. What he does with ``Beginnings'' is
what you see throughout the Pace show.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has also put up maquettes for Mure sculptures,
including a balsa wood and plaster version of ``Awakening'' at
Pace, which proves that Noguchi sometimes labored to achieve what
looks effortless in the event.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly I was struck by several granite table-top sculptures from
the 1960s and early '70s (``Planet in Transit,'' ``Mirage'') that
are clearly precursors to Pace works like ``Galaxy Calligraphy,''
as are the table-top models for parks and playgrounds he designed
from the 1930s on. They echo Giacometti's board games.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly they show how ambiguous and open-ended Noguchi
allowed his art to be. Their forms slip back and forth from
abstractions to landscapes in miniature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mountain Landscape (Bench)'' at Pace may be the best example
of this; even its title makes the point. An oblong basalt slab, the
bottom rough, the top partly cut and polished, it recalls a plain
and mesa. It also can suggest a log. You can't be sure any of this
was Noguchi's intent. Perhaps the allusions happened in the process
of turning the stone into a bench. Or maybe Noguchi, making a
sculpture of a landscape, realized he had also made a bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Noguchi Foundation, which runs the museum, is selling the
works at Pace to raise money, among other things, to help establish
a studio museum at Mure, where Noguchi, at his death, left 160
sculptures, finished and not. The Mure studio is akin to David
Smith's studio at Bolton Landing in upstate New York; like Smith,
Noguchi made a contained world for himself, a place peopled by his
sculptures, which he arranged and rearranged throughout the
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   I have no doubt that the Pace show only dimly summons up the
experience of Mure, but it is at least evocative. Two works in it
are fountains, one that he proposed for the Seagram Building in
1987, which consists of reddish-brown basalt boulders, each
six-sided and resting on stones, like thick tuna steaks on a
shallow bed of rice. Water gently flows from holes in the tops of
the boulders over the sides, pooling among the stones. The other
Pace fountain, made of Japanese granite, works on the same
slow-drip principle. The result is a low-level burble through the
room, very Zen.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember being more tempted to caress art. The
temptation is to touch the notches, circles, dips and cracks in the
stones, which sensuously sometimes imply bodies.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there's nonetheless a tough, astringent quality just
beneath the nuanced surfaces: a restless intensity to Noguchi's art
that may reflect his personal condition.
</P>
<P>
   His biography is familiar. Born in 1904 in Los Angeles, brought
up in Japan until he was 14, then sent to school in Indiana, he was
the son of a Japanese poet and an American writer. Noguchi's father
became a fierce Japanese nationalist, divorced himself from his
American family and started a new one in Japan _ like ``Madama
Butterfly'' in reverse, more or less.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Noguchi's relationship with his father, and so with
his Japanese identity, was vexed. The old line on him is that he
was a Japanese artist steeped in European modernism, or conversely
that he was an American who cribbed from Japan. But neither is
right. His art suggests a sense of displacement or alienation; it
is elusive. I imagine what he meant when he sometimes used the word
oasis to describe it was not that the art was serene as much as it
was apart from everything.
</P>
<P>
   After all, though he belonged to the generation of New York
School artists that included Willem de Kooning, Mark Rothko and
Smith and, like them, rose to success on the tide of postwar
American art, no one thinks of him in terms of the New York School.
His separateness has always defined him.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike de Kooning and the others, he maintained a commitment to
the notion of public art, which they mostly abandoned after the
30's. His lamps and furniture reflected his consistent desire to
engage the public. His later years were significantly devoted to
outdoor projects and to his museum in Long Island City, a public
space.
</P>
<P>
   His career, in this way, paralleled those of Europeans like Miro
and Leger and that of an expatriate like Calder, who also focused
increasingly on big public commissions after the war. Noguchi's
results, like theirs, were mixed. Sometimes his art turned icy,
corporate, precious.
</P>
<P>
   But it's amusing to recall that as a child he apprenticed to
Gutzon Borglum, who later did Mount Rushmore, the country's biggest
public sculpture. Borglum thought Noguchi was hopeless. Whatever
his shortcomings, Noguchi turned out to be the best sculptor of
public spaces the United States had in the modern era.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite work at Pace is a tall, rough piece of granite,
untitled, from 1983. It's a monolith on the scale of commemorative
statues of standing figures, but abstract. A circle is carved where
an eye might be. The top of the stone is rounded at a slant, like a
head, maybe, and the middle (the waist?) smoothed.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is between Rodin's ``Balzac'' and Brancusi's
``Kiss,'' if you can imagine it. Subtle discrete marks lead you
around and around the stone in an effort to make the whole come
together. Somehow Noguchi turns plain gray stone into something
rich and evocative.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's best to say he uncovered a richness that was there
but easily missed. ``There must be something in the stone, a
predisposition that permits the artist to imagine,'' he once
explained. Noguchi's great gift was to let us see with fresh eyes
what's before us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stones and Water,'' the exhibition of Isamu Noguchi's late
works from Mure, Japan, remains at the Pace Wildenstein Gallery, 32
E. 57th St., through June 26. The Isamu Noguchi Garden Museum, at
32-37 Vernon Boulevard, Long Island City, in Queens, is open 10
a.m. to 5 p.m. Wednesdays through Fridays and 11 a.m. to 6 p.m.
Saturdays and Sundays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
