<HEADLINE>
SUNDANCE CHANNEL: SUNDANCE OFFERS A WEEKLY FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Time, channel are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(js) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The photographer William Wegman dresses up his Weimaraners in
summer-camp clothes and sends them out to solve a mystery, Hardy
Boys style, in the funny parody, ``The Hardley Boys in Hardley
Gold.'' (``Hardly boys, they were girls and dogs,'' Wegman says in
his deadpan narrative.) That half-hour film is one of the quirky
treats appearing this Sunday when Sundance Channel finally arrives
in Manhattan in a big way. Devoted to independent film, Sundance
Channel (a spinoff of Robert Redford's Sundance Institute and Film
Festival) will be available on Time Warner Cable on a daylong
pay-per-view basis every Sunday, beginning with a free preview this
week.
</P>
<P>
   With its richly eclectic mix, Sundance Channel is a film lover's
fantasy. Sunday's highlights include ``Big Night,'' Stanley Tucci
and Campbell Scott's affecting comedy about two brothers and a
feast of Italian food, and ``The Portrait of a Lady,'' Jane
Campion's underrated, beautiful adaptation of Henry James' novel.
There is also ``Trees Lounge,'' a meandering, atmospheric character
piece written, directed by and starring Steve Buscemi as a man at
loose ends who hangs out in a local bar. Low-key and hauntingly
real, it is the quintessential Sundance movie.
</P>
<P>
   The Sundance Channel is available on Time Warner's Channel 60.
After this week's free preview, subsequent Sundays will cost $1.95
a day, less monthly or yearly.
</P>
</TEXT>
