<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTN: Managing editors, weekend editors, automotive editors,
business editors
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following automotive and features.
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmissions of these stories, please call 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING-COX (Atlanta) _ There are a lot of ways to test a
vehicle, but none is more fun than on a racetrack. Over Memorial
Day weekend, I did just that with a Dodge Neon at Lime Rock Park in
Connecticut. By Linda Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   MECHANIC-COX (Atlanta) _ With summer approaching and
temperatures climbing higher, more air-conditioning systems will
require servicing. As the price for R-12 -- or Freon, the most
common but now banned refrigerant -- continues to escalate, owners
of older vehicles with A/C systems that use this refrigerant will
become the prime targets for the retrofit hawkers. By Nora Carter.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-COX (Atlanta) _ Face it. Mainstream family sedans --
both domestics and imports -- don't get much glory. They're like
washing machines in the sense that they only get attention when
they're not working properly. But Honda set out to change that with
the '98 Accord, and it's paid off for the Japanese-based
manufacturer and buyers. Billed as the ``All-American'' because
it's built in Marysville, Ohio, with Japan supplying only 15
percent of its parts, this Accord really is new. By Russ DeVault.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-BOS (Undated) _ Where, I am asking no one in
particular, are the outside mirror controls? I have searched the
dash, scoured the console, examined the interior minutely, but I
can find nothing remotely resembling a remote mirror control. There
must be a control in here somewhere. Now, before you start sneering
at the ``spoiled'' auto writer, consider that this is a $66,500
automobile _ plus $700 delivery, a $3,000 guzzler charge, and, in
the tested car, $500 worth of optional aluminum wheels. By John R.
White.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ The best has just gotten
better. It's hard to imagine the king of the sport utilities
getting any better than it was, but that's what happened when
Toyota redesigned the Land Cruiser for 1998. By G. Chambers
Williams III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-AZR (Undated) _ Like flip sides of a coin, the new
Chrysler Concorde and redesigned Dodge Intrepid set out on
identical platforms with two different missions. The Concorde is
meant to evoke a classic style of grand-tour motoring, aimed at
mature drivers who might appreciate such things. The Intrepid is
the hotter ticket, aggressively wedge-shaped with a grille borrowed
from Dodge's main image machine, the Viper sports car. By Bob
Golfen.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-COLUMN-COX _ For many people, the most frustrating part of
vehicle ownership is getting quality service at a fair price.
Because most of us are not certified automotive technicians, when
we talk to our technician about vehicle repairs, it's not unlike
trying to feel knowledgeable about dealing in rocket science.
Normally, I feel confident about automotive topics, but a recent
experience proved that under some circumstances, I can be just as
lost at the repair shop as the next guy. By Don Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-MERCURY (Detroit) _ A look at the 1999 Mercury
Cougar. Cars as fashion appears to be in vogue. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
