<HEADLINE>
`GORILLA GAME' GUIDES INVESTORS ON HIGH-TECH STOCK HUNT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gorillas and monkeys, kings and serfs, tornado warnings and
terrain mapping _
</P>
<P>
   all could be elements of a new Jumanji game.
</P>
<P>
   But instead they are descriptive terms for a hot, bestselling
investment book, ``The Gorilla Game: An Investor's Guide to Picking
Winners in High Technology'' (HarperBusiness, 331 pages).
</P>
<P>
   The book is written by high-tech consultants Geoffrey Moore and
Tom Kippola and technology analyst Paul Johnson. The colorful
language for otherwise dry number-crunching started with Moore's
other bestsellers, ``Inside the Tornado'' and ``Crossing the
Chasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Interested readers should be alerted to another newly published
book with a similar title: ``Guerrilla Investing: Winning
Strategies for Beating the Wall Street Professionals'' (Longstreet,
326 pages, $24).
</P>
<P>
   That book, by Wall Street money manager Peter Siris, describes
guerrilla investing as ``a strategy that uses both the latest
technology and time-tested, common-sense techniques to allow the
amateur, against all odds, to win.''
</P>
<P>
   (''Guerrilla'' refers to a type of military force that operates
in small, speedy groups.)
</P>
<P>
   Buying stocks from companies you know well, talking to investor
relations departments and reading income statements are some of the
actions Siris recommends when picking individual stocks. Overall,
the book is a good primer for stock-buying and for beating the
professionals at their own game, with some description of Internet
investment tools.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, in their book on gorilla (as in the ape) investing,
Moore, Kippola and Johnson describe their investment strategy as
hyperselective. Indeed, out of about 8,000 public technology
companies, only around 100 fit into the criteria they've developed
from which to pick their ``gorilla'' investment with hypergrowth
potential.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the Gorilla Game, they note, is ``to help private
investors participate in the rewards of high-tech stock gains while
standing clear of the market's unnerving volatility.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds good so far. The high-tech market is known for its
heart-stopping leaps and losses, as those on Wall Street try to
figure out whether the latest technology development will end up on
Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly is gorilla investing? It's a form of growth
investing in which a single company (the gorilla) emerges from a
pack of companies and dominates a new technology. Gorilla companies
experience hypergrowth (which is when they are in the tornado) and
create new value chains, the authors write, ultimately beating the
overall market for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was a gorilla, as were Intel and Oracle. Potential
gorillas include software companies Vantive, Scopus and Clarify,
the authors predict.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the Gorilla Game can be described in a five-step
plan:
</P>
<P>
   _ Find markets that are moving into hypergrowth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy a number of stocks in that market that could turn into
gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   _ As the gorilla breaks away from the pack, sell off the rest of
the group.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hold the gorilla for the long term.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sell only when a new alternative technology threatens your
gorilla.
</P>
<P>
   Three chapters describe the rules of picking the gorilla
company. Another three gives past, present and future gorilla
company case studies. The final chapter discusses investing
specifically in Internet companies, which the authors nickname the
possible Mother of all Tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy seems sound, although most investors will find it's
a lot more work than they are willing to put into their financial
investments. Still, the book does not bog readers down with numbers
and charts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, using the imagery of gorillas, tornadoes, kings,
princes and the like, the book effectively describes its points in
a form that is easy to understand and analyze.
</P>
<P>
   The authors provide a Web page address and invite readers to
visit. They finish the book by wishing readers happy hunting.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
