<HEADLINE>
IRS, FBI SEIZE RECORDS FROM SOUTH TEXAS PROSECUTOR, STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER and CARMINA DANINI  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ A vast federal investigation unfolding here has
focused on at least 142 people, including the Webb County district
attorney, a former state district judge and investigators from the
district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators are trying to learn what happened to
criminal charges against 128 people over the nine years that Joe
Rubio has been district attorney in the South Texas city.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, agents from the FBI and Internal Revenue
Service have gone after the personal financial records of 14
people, including Rubio, his father and eight people who work in
Rubio's office.
</P>
<P>
   Those records include income tax returns, checkbooks, expense
accounts, payroll records and other documents, according to the
search warrant federal agents used to seize the items.
</P>
<P>
   Agents also are combing criminal files that are among the
truckload of documents and records seized Sunday when Rubio's
county courthouse office was raided.
</P>
<P>
   The search warrant sheds light on the scope and depth of the
federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Rubio and his father, Jose ``Pichino'' Rubio Sr.,
former state District Judge Ruben Garcia was among 14 people from
whom personal financial records were sought. No charges have been
filed against hte men.
</P>
<P>
   The search warrant lists 128 people who either have been
arrested by state authorities and charged with a crime or who could
be charged with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Emilio Davila, Joe Rubio's lawyer, said his client is the focus
of attention simply because he is in charge of the district
attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd have had the goods on anyone, you'd think they'd
have made arrests,'' Davila said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a matter of going in and picking up everything to see
if anything is wrong, it's improper,'' Davila said. ``It gives Webb
County a bad image irrespective of the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Guerrero, a spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney's office in
Houston, which is overseeing the investigation, declined to comment
on the search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the document is filed in the public record, we can comment
on it. If it is not, we cannot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents have repeatedly declined to comment on the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
