<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO STUDIOS CUTTING BACK  
 AS BUSY AS TRUMAN  
 A DELICATE TASK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Studio executives here cry ``wolf'' so often that
it's hard to believe them. They complain about the soaring costs of
films but pay millions of dollars and give elaborate perks to
actors whose movies keep failing. They grumble about the sameness
of films but produce movies that are often alike. They groan that
the marketplace is too crowded every weekend but keep churning out
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Now two of the most prolific studios, Walt Disney and Warner
Bros., say they are sharply curtailing production, largely because
of costs. Warner said it would reduce its output to about 20
pictures a year, down from an average of 28 over the last few
years. And Disney plans to release only 17 or 18 films next year;
several years ago the studio released as many as 35 movies a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every level, we'll be more selective,'' said Joe Roth, the
studio chief, whose boss, Michael Eisner, Disney's chairman, fully
endorses the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Roth added that the cut was intended to limit production costs
as well as development, marketing and overhead expenses. But the
reduced output will mostly be in Disney's adult films, not its
family movies or animated features.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Donald DeLine, president of Touchstone Pictures, the
Disney unit that makes grown-up films, said he would leave the
studio after 13 years. It was under DeLine that Touchstone made
adult movies, including ``Pretty Woman,'' ``Ransom,'' ``Sister
Act,'' ``Con Air'' and the coming ``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Disney family-film division _ responsible for ``George of
the Jungle'' and ``Flubber,'' among others _ is one of the studio's
more lucrative units, together with animation. ``Beauty and the
Beast'' and ``The Lion King,'' for example, have been huge profit
makers for Disney, not only because of their box-office power but
also because of spinoffs ranging from toys and merchandise to
Broadway shows. Live-action films are, by their nature, riskier.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's predecessor, Jeffrey Katzenberg, made numerous
high-concept comedies, but also gave the green light to adult
films, including ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' ``Dead Poets Society,''
``When a Man Loves a Woman'' and ``What's Love Got to Do With It.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth and DeLine have been working on several grown-up films.
These include ``Beloved,'' based on the novel by Toni Morrison and
directed by Jonathan Demme, and ``A Civil Action,'' directed by
Steven Zaillian and starring John Travolta and Robert Duvall.
</P>
<P>
   Roth acknowledged that more time and money would now be spent on
the Disney label, meaning family films. But he insisted that the
company would continue to make movies for grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to be forced to only make your best stuff,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some talent agents and top producers are not certain.
</P>
<P>
   As Busy As Truman
</P>
<P>
   Just a few hours before the glittering premiere of ``The Truman
Show'' in Los Angeles, Laura Linney was sitting nervously in her
room at the Four Seasons Hotel in Beverly Hills. ``It's scary, a
little intimidating,'' the New York-born stage and film actress
said. ``There's so much attention, so much interest in the film.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right.
</P>
<P>
   Few films in the summer season have arrived with the
anticipation of ``The Truman Show,'' a dark fantasy directed by
Peter Weir, written by Andrew Niccol and starring Jim Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey plays Truman Burbank, a slightly goofy man who lives in a
picture-postcard town and doesn't suspect that his entire life,
from the moment he was born, is a television show. His family, his
friends, everyone in his life is an actor, and it finally dawns on
Truman that his life is a fabrication.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Linney plays Truman's wife, a scary and manipulative woman
who controls him with an icy smile. The role was quite complicated,
Ms. Linney said, because she was actually playing an actress
playing a role on a television show.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were moments when I was unclear about the different
layers,'' Ms. Linney said. ``All of us came up with back stories,
elaborate histories of who we were. And my back story was that this
actress _ her name is Hannah Gill _ was profoundly powerful; she
rivaled Oprah in how much money she was making; she was a really
shrewd businesswoman who made millions and millions of dollars in
product placement on the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Linney laughed. ``She was also a failed child actress, one
of those little horrible kids who was in a million productions of
`Annie' but never actually played Annie,'' Ms. Linney said. ``She
went through some terrible years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Linney has not endured any such terrible years, and in fact,
at 34, has had a formidable career. She is appearing on Broadway in
``Honour,'' a play by Joanna Murray-Smith. She'll also be seen in
Armistead Maupin's ``More Tales of the City,'' starting Sunday on
Showtime. Last year she played opposite Clint Eastwood in
``Absolute Power'' and won strong notices as a prosecutor in
``Primal Fear'' opposite Richard Gere.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Linney lives in New York with her husband, David Adkins, an
actor she met while studying drama at the Juilliard School. The
daughter of Romulus Linney, the playwright, and Ann Perse, Ms.
Linney grew up in New York, went to Brown University and from
childhood yearned to be an actress.
</P>
<P>
   Her New York theater credits include roles in ``Hedda Gabler''
and the Broadway productions of ``Six Degrees of Separation'' and
``The Seagull'' and she starred in Philip Barry's comedy
``Holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Truman Show'' was her most complex role. Ms. Linney
said she learned an enormous amount from Weir, the filmmaker, as
well as Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most actors are a little timid, self-conscious,'' she said.
``Jim cuts through all that, and he has courage like I've never
seen. He'll try anything. His impulses are immediate. It was
amazing to be around.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Delicate Task
</P>
<P>
   The death of Phil Hartman this week was greeted with special
sorrow at Dreamworks.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the company had worked with the 49-year-old
comedian on ``Small Soldiers,'' a family film set to open on July
10, and were deeply fond of him. But in addition they viewed the
film as a potential summer sleeper and are now faced with delicate
questions about its advertising and trailers.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is about toy action figures who come to life and clash
in a miniwar that ensnares a suburban Ohio town. It tested strongly
before preview audiences, and Dreamworks executives had hoped it
would appeal to teen-agers as well as families, especially
considering Hartman's popularity during his eight-year run on
``Saturday Night Live'' and on the NBC show ``News Radio.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, which blends live action with computer-generated
imagery created by the Stan Winsten studio, Hartman plays a
suburban father whose son brings home one of the toy soldiers. He
is not the star, but part of an ensemble cast, including Kirsten
Dunst, Denis Leary and Jay Mohr. This will make it somewhat easier
for Dreamworks to alter the marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks executives are carefully examining how much or how
little to show of Hartman in the new trailers and newspaper
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   One change in a trailer had been made before Hartman's death. In
an early version shown in theaters, the Hartman character,
witnessing a fight among the soldiers, said, ``I think I'm having
an aneurysm.'' But the line was cut.
</P>
<P>
   Film studios about to release a movie with a starring actor who
has died have few options but to promote the film with that star.
Take the case of ``Almost Heroes,'' the comedy from Warner Bros.
that opened last weekend. It starred Matthew Perry and Chris
Farley, who died last year; the two shared star billing. Still, the
advertising for the comedy was limited, but this was largely
because the movie was poorly received by audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Spencer Tracy before the release of ``Guess Who's
Coming to Dinner'' and the death of James Dean before ``Giant'' had
no discernible impact on the success of those films, now considered
classics. They were promoted as if their stars were still alive.
</P>
<P>
   It's another problem entirely when a star dies in the middle of
making a movie. A bizarre Hollywood solution to that difficulty
came about when Jean Harlow died of kidney failure during the
making of the 1937 comedy ``Saratoga.'' She was 26. The film also
starred, among others, Clark Gable (as a bookie) and Lionel
Barrymore (as a horse breeder and Ms. Harlow's grandfather).
</P>
<P>
   The studio decided to use Ms. Harlow's stand-in, Mary Dees, in
many scenes. The effect was bizarre: Ms. Dees was seen with her
back to the camera, looking through binoculars or wearing a
wide-brimmed hat.
</P>
<P>
   According to David Stenn's ``Bombshell: The Life and Death of
Jean Harlow,'' (Doubleday, 1993) the film turned out to be Harlow's
most successful, grossing $3.3 million, more than any other movie
in 1937. Many reviewers actually called the Harlow performance the
best of her career, but The New York Times thought she ``was
patently not her tempestuous self.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
