<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4491 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-CARROLL-EXHIBIT     06-04 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-CARROLL-EXHIBIT-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A.K.A. LEWIS CARROLL': LOOKING GLASS REFLECTED A SHY VICTORIAN
DOOR
</HEADLINE>
   (js) 
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Could the mathematician who in 1867 published ``An
Elementary Treatise on Determinants With Their Application to
Simultaneous Linear Equations and Algebraical Geometry'' also be
the author of ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland''? To be sure. His
real name was Charles Lutwidge Dodgson (1832-1898), and under it he
functioned as an Oxford don who taught math, a cleric, a poet, a
pamphleteer, a deviser of games and puzzles, an ardent theatergoer
and a gifted amateur photographer.
</P>
<P>
   But the pseudonym Lewis Carroll, a Latinization of Charles
Lutwidge in reverse order, is the name that belongs to his most
brilliant achievement, the ``Alice'' stories.
</P>
<P>
   The show ``a k a Lewis Carroll'' at the Morgan Library marks the
100th anniversary of the death of this odd and intriguing polymath,
and it reflects a life of fascinating paradoxes. A Church of
England deacon and an eminently proper Victorian, he also took
adoring photographs of little girls and often fell in love with his
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   A writer of ``serious'' if schmaltzy Victorian verse, he was
also an ironist and nonsense rhymer who had fun with sober
institutions like Oxford and the British monarchy. A very private
person who kept Charles Lutwidge Dodgson and Lewis Carroll strictly
apart, he was also a tireless celebrity chaser who sought big names
to pose for his camera.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, assembled largely from the Morgan's own
collection by Anna Lou Ashby, curator of printed books, represents
a very respectable slice of Dodgsonia. It includes letters (he
wrote thousands), personal memorabilia like his microscope and
watch (a big silver timepiece that resembles the White Rabbit's),
first editions of his books, pamphlets and other literary
endeavors, original drawings by John Tenniel, the Punch cartoonist
who illustrated ``Alice'' and its sequel, ``Through the
Looking-Glass,'' photographs of Dodgson himself and those he took
of his very young friends.
</P>
<P>
   There is a load of associated ephemera, too: the childhood ring
and purse of Alice Liddell, for whom his Alice was named; parlor
games invented by Dodgson; toys, songs and records inspired by
``Alice''; parodies of his work by other authors; drawings and cels
for Disney's 1951 animation of ``Alice,'' and a book version of the
1933 Paramount movie ``Alice in Wonderland,'' starring Gary Cooper
as the White Knight, Cary Grant as the Mock Turtle and W.C. Fields
as Humpty Dumpty.
</P>
<P>
   If a few things have been left out, like nude photographs of
girls (he thought boys were ugly), pages from his voluminous
diaries and the original ``Alice'' manuscript (now in the British
Library), no matter. There is enough Dodgson/Carroll material here
to keep a viewer hopping. And those who want to know more can turn
to the redoubtable biography by Morton N. Cohen (Knopf, 1995), and
now a Vintage paperback.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The son of an accomplished parish curate and community leader,
Dodgson was the oldest and much adored boy in a family of 11
children. Seven were girls, a fact often cited in speculations
about his interest in prepubescent females. A clever, personable
young man, especially good with words and mathematics, he grew up
in his father's country parsonages, was sent to Rugby at 14,
entered Christ Church, one of Oxford University's most fashionable
colleges, at 19, and stayed on as a don until his death. He taught,
was active in college politics, had a social life and at 24 got
hooked on the popular Victorian vice of photography.
</P>
<P>
   He was good at this then very cumbersome process, so good that
sitters beat a path to his door. From photographing fellow
academics and churchmen, he went on to their children, and so met
Alice Liddell, the 4-year-old daughter of Henry George Liddell, the
newly appointed dean of Christ Church. She was to change his life.
A number of photographs of Alice with and without her two sisters
appear in the show; two of the most engaging were taken when she
was 7. In one she proudly sports a crown of flowers, in the other
she presents a grave profile as she presses her face against the
back of a chair.
</P>
<P>
   His most famous photo of this seductive child is included,
``Alice Liddell as Beggar Girl,'' taken at the same age in the
deanery garden. Barefoot and dressed in rags, like the child
prostitutes who frequented London streets, she cocks her head in a
challenging come-hither look, one foot drawn up and resting on a
ledge. There are two versions: one a carte de visite, the other a
larger presentation copy, hand colored and dressed up in a leather
case. Also on view are photos of several other young girls, among
them Xie Kitchin, the daughter of the headmaster of Winchester
College, and Julia Arnold, the niece of Matthew Arnold and later
the mother of Aldous Huxley.
</P>
<P>
   Famously, while boating on a summer day in 1862 with the Liddell
children and an adult friend, Dodgson concocted the tale of Alice
in Wonderland to amuse them, and wrote it down later at Alice
Liddell's insistence. Originally titled ``Alice's Adventures
Underground,'' it was published in 1866 as ``Alice's Adventures in
Wonderland'' and is possibly the world's most widely read
children's book, rendered into more than 70 languages, including
Swahili and Yiddish. (A lineup of translations, among them a 1923
version in Russian by Vladimir Nabokov who was later to write the
pedophiliac ``Lolita,'' fills a display case in the show.) Also on
view is a facsimile edition of the original manuscript, with
drawings by the author that include a giraffe-necked Alice.
</P>
<P>
   Not the least of this show's pleasures is the number of
illustrations, some original, some in proof form, by Tenniel
(1820-1914), who created the legendary images of Alice, the White
Rabbit, the Red Queen, the Duchess, the Cheshire Cat, the Mad
Hatter and the rest of the gloriously wacky Wonderland crew. (An
early review of the book called the illustrations ``square, grim
and uncouth.'') Although many other illustrators _ the work of
Arthur Rackham, Marie Laurencin and Barry Moser is shown here,
among others _ have had a crack at ``Alice'' over the years, the
Tenniel drawings have never been surpassed.
</P>
<P>
   If this show is made up of maybe too many ``bits and scraps''
(Dodgson's description of ``Alice''), it's still an enjoyable
tribute to the shy, unmarried don who somehow found the freedom to
let the child in him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``a k a Lewis Carroll'' remains at the Pierpont Morgan Library,
29 East 36th St., Manhattan, through Aug. 30
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
