<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPING-BEAUTY-BALLE     06-04 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPING-BEAUTY-BALLET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECTURM OF INTERPRETATIONS IN THREE `SLEEPING BEAUTIES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Sleeping Beauty,'' set to one of Tchaikovsky's most
sumptuous scores, is a standard against which performers may be
measured. It is also a ballet that is capable of a surprising
number of interpretations, as American Ballet Theater suggested in
well-danced performances on Monday night and Wednesday afternoon
and evening at the Metropolitan Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   A thread of otherworldliness ran through Susan Jaffe's
impressively sustained portrayal of Princess Aurora on Monday
night. Ms. Jaffe was an unusually shy Aurora in the first act,
dancing with a dreaming softness and delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   In the second-act Vision Scene, Ms. Jaffe's melancholy Aurora
gave full, calm measure to each step and gesture. She distilled all
that had come before in the third-act grand pas de deux, somehow
suggesting that this eager, triumphant princess would always be
haunted by her half-remembered years of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Tuttle was unconvincing as the young first-act princess
on Wednesday afternoon, in polished dancing without much heart. Her
Vision Scene was filled with softness, fluidity and unexpected
musical phrasing. She then became a queen, and a grand ballerina,
shifting between grandeur and melting love.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda McKerrow, Wednesday evening's Aurora, was an endearingly
coltish, spunky princess at the start and a wraith in her
delicately phrased Vision Scene. She embodied royal perfection in
the third act.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Manuel Carreno offered an elegantly danced performance as
the prince on Monday, but his remoteness and pedestrian acting made
a cypher of the character.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Roberts, the matinee Desire, wore his heart on his sleeve
throughout in stylish dancing filled with big, flowing mime and
polished partnering. Vladimir Malakhov's Desire, on Wednesday
night, was the idealized prince of 19th-century classicism in what
seemed like an exquisite drawing for a master painting.
</P>
<P>
   Only Christina Fagundes, at the matinee, brought the necessary
amplitude to the Lilac Fairy. Julie Kent added some charming bits
of emotional business on Monday. But Veronica Lynn was an
irritatingly well-behaved child as the evening Lilac Fairy.
</P>
<P>
   All three Carabosses were powerful, nuanced creations. On
Monday, Victor Barbee's evil fairy was a relatively young beauty.
Brian Reeder was a mocking, chill embodiment of evil as the
skirt-swirling matinee Carabosse. In the evening, Michael Owen
offered a complex portrait of a world-weary yet awesomely
commanding woman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
