<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIENDS-MUSIC-REVIEW-     06-04 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIENDS-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FRIENDS AND ENEMIES OF NEW MUSIC': DEPENDING A BIT TOO MUCH ON THE
PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's natural for composers to look to music's past
for inspiration. Too many creators in all fields, especially
younger ones, make the mistake of trying to come up with something
entirely and shockingly new.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a difference between drawing on models (and even
stealing ideas) from the past and simply evoking it. Such thoughts
were buzzing about on Wednesday night when the impishly titled
Friends and Enemies of New Music, a composer/performer collective,
presented its ninth anniversary concert at Weill Recital Hall.
Though the group has no fixed agenda, it seems to have attracted
mostly composers who still find potential in tonality as a musical
language. And more power to them, you might say.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the works performed, however, were not merely attentive,
but beholden to the past. For example, ``Three Silent Things,'' a
30-minute work for soprano, violin, viola, cello and piano,
composed by Daron Hagen in 1984, is curious music for a young man
to have written. A couple of the 10 texts he sets are unusual
choices, like the Adelaide Crapsey poem from which the title comes.
But most of the poets, like Walt Whitman and Robert Graves, have
been frequently turned to by American composers.
</P>
<P>
   The work begins with a Whitman text set to stern, proclamatory
music with hints of 12-tone complexity. Soon the piece shifts modes
and wistful tonality predominates. The composer deftly mixes spiky
rhythmic restlessness, jagged instrumental lines and crunchy
chords. But mostly the music recalls the lushly harmonic,
clear-textured styles of several mid-century conservative American
composers, and Hagen's own voice seems faint. Brenda Harris was the
sensitive soloist.
</P>
<P>
   Freshness and originality were similarly not the strong points
of ``The Husbands,'' a 1994 work by Tom Cipullo, for mezzo-soprano
(Mary Ann Hart) and baritone (Randall Scarlata), with flute, viola
and piano. But this work has surprises and finely wrought detail
that made it seem more individual. The text by William Carpenter
tells a mysterious tale of elderly ladies on a New England foliage
tour, who stop at a diner and meet, they believe, their deceased
husbands. The musical setting is richly harmonic, vocally
expansive, restless and often skillful. But Samuel Barber was more
modern.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s, David Del Tredici was in the vanguard of
university-trained American composers who re-embraced tonality in
striking ways. He was represented here by four songs from his cycle
``Gay Life,'' written in 1996, and there is clearly a vigorous
compositional mind at work. But it was hard to tell how
straightforwardly we were to take Del Tredici's ruminative, thickly
chromatic tonal writing. For example, in his setting of an excerpt
from Lorca's sensual ``Four Ballads in Yellow,'' Del Tredici's
music sounded like Richard Strauss as a cocktail pianist.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking song was the fitful, punchy setting of Allen
Ginsberg's ``Personals Ad.'' In the piano part, fanfarelike
outbursts collided with insistent, even desperate, descending
chromatic lines. John Kelly delivered the text in the style of a
raspy cabaret singer, and Del Tredici played the piano part
vividly.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of Ben Yarmolinsky's ``Amendments' was promising: to
set, with deadpan seriousness, amendments to the Constitution, the
Miranda warning and the presidential oath. But the music, with its
hymnal harmonies and oom-pah-pah dance riffs, did not have enough
profile to stand against these iconic texts, though the baritone
Ryan Allen brought an amusing, pontifical quality to his singing.
John Link's ``Whirligig'' for marimba, which had its New York
premiere, shifts constantly from undulant repetitive patterns to
bursts of stuttering chords. Thomas Kolor played it dynamically.
</P>
<P>
   The most original work was ``Dynaflow Drive Descant'' by Matthew
Guerrieri. Over a tape recording of Chopin's Fantasy-Impromptu as
performed in 1947 by the Harmonicats, a harmonica trio, a solo
flute makes edgy, jabbingly funny musical commentary. The
recording, played through a small boom box, became like some
weirdly familiar but disorienting accompaniment to the commanding
flute of Margaret Lancaster. And it was refreshing to have at least
one composer thumb his nose at music's past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
