<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-HONGKONG-400&AMP;AD     06-04 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HONGKONG-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HONG KONG, 40,000 COMMEMORATE VICTIMS OF TIANANMEN SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Nine years after the Chinese military suppressed
pro-democracy demonstrations in Tiananmen Square, China's newest
citizens gathered here by the tens of thousands Thursday evening
for a candlelight vigil to honor those who died on June 4, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first commemoration in Hong Kong of the killings
around the square since the former British colony reverted to
Chinese rule.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a rainstorm that cut short the ceremony and threatened
to turn Victoria Park into a flood plain, about 40,000 people
huddled under umbrellas that glowed softly with the light of
candles.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the hand-over, we really are fighting for democracy on
our own soil,'' said Cheung Man-kwong, a local pro-democracy
politician who led the crowd in chanting ``The people will not
forget!'' and ``We will fight to the end!''
</P>
<P>
   For Hong Kong, the rally marked the second powerful display of
democratic sentiment in two weeks. Late last month a record number
of people defied another torrential rainstorm to vote in
legislative elections. Cheung and other pro-democracy candidates
were swept to victory.
</P>
<P>
   As in past years, the rally's organizers laid wreaths and hung
placards around the soccer fields in this sprawling park to honor
the hundreds of protesters who were killed when Chinese soldiers
forced their way into Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to come, no matter what,'' said Andy Kan, a 45-year-old
real estate agent who flew from Vancouver to attend the rally.
``What happened in Tiananmen Square showed how important the fight
for democracy is.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Chan, a 29-year-old secretary who stood stoically in the
rain with her husband, Simon, said Hong Kong needed to show Beijing
its commitment to democracy. ``We can't forget the people who died
for freedom,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chan said she had doubted that the Hong Kong government
would allow the vigil, which has been held annually since 1990, to
continue after the hand-over. Still, she gave China little credit
for being tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are very clever,'' she said, ``They can't
suppress everything, with the whole world watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang Tai, 39, a chef at a retirement home, said he chose to
attend the vigil this year for the first time because Hong Kong was
now part of China. ``It's more meaningful this year because it will
show whether the Chinese government will allow any freedom here,''
he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although the crowd was smaller than last year's turnout of
55,000, the rally's organizers claimed victory, given the
forbidding weather. Attendance has waxed and waned since 1989, when
one million people marched through Hong Kong's central business
district to protest the Tiananmen Square massacre. But the rally
continues to attract a cross-section of Hong Kong people, from
students and families to business people, who come from work in
suits and ties.
</P>
<P>
   An emotional high point came when Wang Dan, a student leader of
the democracy movement who was jailed by Beijing and freed in
April, spoke to the crowd by telephone from New York, where he has
begun a life in exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope Hong Kong will be an important step in the future
democratization of China,'' Wang said, adding that he hoped to
visit the city soon.
</P>
<P>
   Wang also bantered with one of Hong Kong's most senior
pro-democracy politicians, Szeto Wah, who sounded like a concerned
uncle as he inquired about Wang's health, his studies and his
mother. As Wang signed off, a clap of thunder reverberated off the
high-rise apartments that surround Victoria Park.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fears that the government would muzzle anti-Chinese
protests after the hand-over, police were scarcely noticeable
Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Anson Chan, the chief secretary of the Hong Kong government,
said in an interview with a Japanese television network earlier
Thursday that the rally proved ``there is no change to the rights
and freedoms enjoyed by the Hong Kong people.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
