<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4509 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-VICTIMS-COX     06-04 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-VICTIMS-COX </SLUG>
   280&AMP;ADD  PANEL TO STUDY HOLOCAUST-ERA
ASSETS IN U.S. ADVANCES IN HOUSE
 &HT;     By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a search for ``retrospective justice,'' the
House Banking Committee voted Thursday to create a commission to
conduct research on Holocaust-era assets under U.S. government
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inquiries into the nature of evil and how to behave in the
face of it are not the normal stuff of congressional hearings,''
said Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, the panel's chairman. But the
commission's work is vital so that each generation can ``learn from
the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill approved Thursday would form a 19-member U.S. Holocaust
Assets Historical Commission that would study what happened to
gold, gems, cash and art works that came under control of the U.S.
government after Adolf Hitler came to power in Germany in 1933. The
panel would also review other public and private research on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   A final report would be submitted to President Clinton by Dec.
31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton strongly supports establishing the commission,
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat told the committee
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel ``will send a message that the United States
government is determined to address the fate of Holocaust assets
here at home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat has conducted extensive studies of how Swiss banks
helped Nazi Germany obtain currency for gold looted from Holocaust
victims and how nations neutral during World War II sold Germany
crucial war materiel.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Reuters reported that three major Swiss banks
have offered Jewish negotiators more than $1 billion to settle
claims for failing to return Holocaust-era assets.
</P>
<P>
   The offer came within the past few days from Union Bank of
Switzerland, Swiss Bank Corp and Credit Suisse, the report said. It
said negotiations were continuing.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat's most recent report, released this week, focuses on
how Nazi Germany used the looted gold to sustain its war effort.
</P>
<P>
   It complements a May 1997 on the Swiss banks ``by illuminating
the trade as well as the financing side of the equation,''
Eizenstat told the Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Using U.S. documents, including those captured from the Nazis, a
task force supervised by Eizenstat found that five neutral
countries fed the Nazi war effort by supplying Germany with its
major resources.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal and Spain, for example, provided Germany's wartime
supply of wolfram, a mineral used to produce tungsten, used in
steel alloy for weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden provided iron ore, also used to make weapons, and Turkey
sold Germany chromium, essential for building tanks and planes.
Argentina provided a base for smuggling. Finally, Sweden supplied
Germany with food and arms, Eizenstat said.
</P>
<P>
   These dealings took place perhaps due to fear of the Germans or
the desire to ``reap economic rewards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat noted the inconsistent actions of these nations. For
example, they all allowed thousands of Jews fleeing the Holocaust
to enter their country. The key to understanding these nations'
neutrality is understanding when it became clear that the Nazi
aggression was distinct from other European wars, Eizenstat said.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat's report also addresses the failure of these countries
to return the looted gold it acquired from Nazi Germany. Less than
$20 million of up to $240 million acquired by the wartime neutrals,
apart from Switzerland, was returned to the Tripartite Gold
Commission, which processes claims from the central banks of 15
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat also commended other efforts to explore Holocaust-era
issues, including hearings held in February on a bill introduced by
Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., that seeks to help Holocaust survivors
recover life insurance benefits denied to them after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
