<SLUG> BC-JUNKMAIL-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELIVER US: `JUNK MAIL' BELONGS IN DEAD-LETTER BOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED- It must be a small world after all, or at least the
part of it belonging to the world's mail carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, according to the Norwegian suspense film ``Junk
Mail,'' that mail carriers in Norway pull Newmans: They read other
people's letters and dump mail so they won't have to make
deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   Those revelations are slightly more interesting than the rest of
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Roy (Robert Skjaerstad) is a creepy, gloomy mail carrier who
emerges as the hero only because he is half a degree less creepy
and gloomy than everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Alienated from the rest of society, Roy spies on a young woman,
Line (Andrine Saether), then becomes involved with her when he
inadvertently stops her from committing suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Line is mixed up in something mysterious, involving stolen money
and a nasty thug, which puts Roy in danger.
</P>
<P>
   The more he runs from trouble, the further into it he gets.
However, perhaps that's not strange for a character who finds being
sent to the hospital in a coma rather enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junk Mail'' has all the trappings of an ordinary suspense
film. Halfway through, however, I began to suspect it was intended
by first-time Norwegian director Pal Sletaune to be a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the humor is as dry as an Arizona June at about 4 in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the post office gives Roy an award for refusing to
give up his mailbag when he's mugged by three junkies. In
actuality, Roy was trying his hardest to give up the bag, but the
strap kept getting caught on his jacket.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junk Mail'' does offer some sage advice: Don't move to Oslo,
or, if you do, handle your communications through e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junk Mail'' won an award at the Cannes Film Festival in 1997.
It's unclear why. But I don't think I'd like to see the competition
it beat.
</P>
<P>
   Unrated, ``Junk Mail'' contains an R-level of profanity and
nudity. In Norwegian with English subtitles. 2 stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
