   EDs: MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: A map-graphic placed on the Cox Server by the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution is still available for use.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR _ WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Thursday
denied independent counsel Kenneth Starr's request to decide
quickly whether President Clinton could claim attorney-client
privilege to block a key aide's testimony. The ruling means that
Starr's investigation is likely to take several more months to
complete. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO _ WASHINGTON _ Discussions of how to proceed on a
national tobacco bill dissolved into partisan wrangling Thursday,
with Democrats and Republicans accusing each other of using the
issue for political advantage. The rhetoric further darkened
already dim chances for the bill's passage. (Lipman, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   RETIREMENT _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, House Speaker Newt
Gingrich and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott agreed Thursday that
Social Security reform should be the first order of business in
Congress next year. (Sherman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RETIREMENT-SAVE _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and House
Speaker Newt Gingrich addressed concerns about whether Social
Security will be around for the baby boom generation at a
``summit'' Thursday. But some reform groups argued that reform
should begin in Congress and the White House, where retirement
benefits are excessive. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-PRAYER _ WASHINGTON _ The House votes on a constitutional
amendment that would guarantee the right to school prayer.
(Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-ENVIRO _ WASHINGTON _ More than 90 percent of people in
Greece and 87 percent in Argentinia think environmental laws in
their countries ``do not go far enough.'' In fact, majorities in
almost all of the world's most populous countries think
environmental protection is inadequate, according to a series of
polls released Thursday. Only in Finland and Nigeria did less than
half of poll respondents agree with the statement that
environmental laws ``don't go far enough.'' (Nesmith, Cox News
Service 400).
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-VICTIMS _ WASHINGTON _ A Senate subcommittee approved
a bill Thursday aimed at recovering assets belonging to Holocaust
victims as well as committing the United States to join research
efforts on the topic. Central to this issue is how other countries
will proceed, since at least five neutral countries during World
War II fed the Nazi war effort by supplying key materials to
Germany, according to an interagency task force report discussed
Thursday. (Abulhassan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   YORKTOWN _ WASHINGTON _ The National Geographic Society holds a
news conference to release photos and video footage of the U.S.S.
Yorktown, the aircraft carrier discovered May 19 more than three
miles under the surface of the Pacific Ocean. Speakers include
Robert Ballard, expedition leader and discoverer of the Titanic.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TOBFOES _ A family feud is under way among anti-tobacco forces,
pitting traditional groups like the Lung Association and the
American Cancer Society against newer groups like Campaign for a
Tobacco Free Society which seem to be in favor with the Clinton
administration. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PILOT-VIOLATIONS _ATLANTA _ Rudolf Duncan, the pilot of the
Cessna 172 Skyhawk that collided in mid-air with a Cessna
Citationjet over metro Atlanta on April 4 had been cited for
violation of FAA flight regulations four times in the past, and
twice had his license suspended. Records the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution obtained through an FOI request show that as
recently as 1994 his license was suspended for 60 days for flying
an airplane the FAA considered not airworthy. Duncan, and the five
occupants of the Citationjet, all lawyers, including the pilot, for
the firm that represents Cox Enterprises, were killed in the crash.
(Payne, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
