<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-DEPOTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS BLAST ADMINISTRATION OVER MILITARY DEPOT CONTRACTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican lawmakers threatened Thursday to stop
the Air Force from issuing contracts on work at two military depots
in California and Texas, citing a memo they said showed the Clinton
administration tried to manipulate the process.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Secretary F. Whitten Peters denied there was White
House pressure in the process and told the House National Security
Committee that his memo was written ``in haste'' and did not
reflect the ``nuances'' of conversations with President Clinton's
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   But the House committee chairman, Rep. Floyd Spence of South
Carolina, said the memo underscored a three-year White House effort
to manipulate the closing of McClellan Air Force Base in Sacramento
and Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio in exchange for political
support during the 1996 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``That memo appears to be the most recent _ and most public _
evidence of what many see as a consistent pattern of behavior on
the part of the administration to skew competition for depot
workloads in the aftermath of the 1995 Base Realignment and Closure
Commission's recommendation to reduce overhead and infrastructure
among Air Force depots by closing McClellan and Kelly air logistics
centers,'' Spence said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the three-year controversy also has doomed the prospect
of future rounds of base closings because lawmakers fear further
White House meddling.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the committee said they would join Spence in
writing legislation that would remove the Air Force from the
contract process at the installations in San Antonio and
Sacramento. Those installations are both destined for closure.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the Cold War, the military has moved to shutter
bases and turn over some repair and maintenance work to private
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ciro D. Rodriguez, D-Texas, called the effort a political
charade and accused the committee of disguising its true intent: to
snare more depot jobs for bases in congressional districts and
protect them from efforts to privatize maintenance work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it ironic, the comments I'm hearing,'' Rodriguez told
Republicans on the committee. ``You want to privatize welfare. You
want to privatize housing.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to depot work, Rodriguez said, committee
members were opposed to privatization that could ``impact jobs in
your back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said taking the contract system away from the Air
Force would invite further politicization of the process.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is currently seeking contracts for $200 million in
aircraft repair at McClellan and $660 million in aircraft engine
repair at Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Peters recused himself from the process following the release of
his April 26 memo to Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre. In that
memo, Peters said John Podesta, deputy White House chief of staff,
urged the Air Force to induce Lockheed Martin Corp. to compete for
the repair work at Sacramento and keep the workload at the base
when it closes and is turned over to the city in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing Corp. also is bidding on the work, and if successful,
would move half of the workload to Hill Air Force base near Ogden,
Utah, and move repair of the KC-135 tanker aircraft to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Hansen, R-Utah, said he was incensed at the White
House's attempt to steer the contract away from his base and
charged that such behavior was ``unethical and potentially
illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed also is bidding on the $660 million engine work at
Kelly. The company plans to move half of the workload to Tinker Air
Force Base outside Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Following release of the memo, Defense Secretary William Cohen
said a panel of outside advisers would review the contract process
for work at Kelly and McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   Two Air Force officials told the National Security Committee
Thursday that the process would be fair and free of political
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a shrinking violet,'' said Darlene Druyun, Air Force
deputy assistant secretary. ``The integrity of the process will be
pristine.''
</P>
<P>
   J.S. Gansler, a Defense Department undersecretary, said: ``The
competition will be fair and open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
