r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROES-MOVIES-AZR &LR;      06-04 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROES-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HEROES' A ZERO AS MEM ORY OF FARLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Those of us who were big fans of the big man maintain
many great memories of Chris Farley. ``Almost Heroes'' won't be one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   We can crack up just picturing Farley's wild romps through
``Saturday Night Live.'' We treasure those hilarious moments he
created in inadequate comedies, such as ``Beverly Hills Ninja'' and
``Black Sheep.'' We know ``Tommy Boy'' proved that when Farley had
a good story and solid support, he could be among the best, a guy
we loved and loved to laugh at.
</P>
<P>
   The rotund comedian, who died too young, left behind two final
gifts for his fans: ``Almost Heroes,'' in which he stars, and the
upcoming Norm MacDonald comedy, ``Dirty Work,'' in which he has a
small role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost Heroes'' is nothing great, but it does have some of
those great Farley moments. His fans have to take what they can get
now.
</P>
<P>
   Farley and Matthew Perry (``Friend's``) play two explorers in
1804 trying to beat the Lewis and Clark expedition across the
wilderness to the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Bartholomew Hunt (Farley) is a mountain man who looks like a man
mountain, while Leslie Edwards (Perry) is a fop who brings a tea
service into the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   With their crew of trusty idiots, Hunt and Edwards bumble
through encounters with a mad conquistador, wild animals and
not-so-wild Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this kind of overdone spoof is that you don't
get caught up in the story.
</P>
<P>
   There is no story that won't be sacrificed at the slightest
opportunity for a pratfall.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Almost Heroes,'' it's mosey down the trail, do
something silly, then mosey farther down the trail.
</P>
<P>
   How much you enjoy the movie depends entirely on whether you get
caught up in the collection of slapstick, sight gags and general
silliness.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Christopher Guest, ``Almost Heroes'' has
some great moments but more than its share of clunkers, too. It
hops down that trail of laughs with one foot tied behind its back.
</P>
<P>
   Guest has a flair for offbeat gags, but ``Almost Heroes'' is
nowhere nearly as funny as his inspired ``Waiting for Guffman.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that earlier film was tied together with a good story
and characters you could care about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost Heroes'' has Chris Farley.
</P>
<P>
   If this were just another of Farley's films, you'd think: OK,
he's getting better . . . a definite step up from ``Beverly Hills
Ninja.`` Sometime soon, he'll get cast in a movie worthy of his
comic talents.
</P>
<P>
   Too late.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG-13, ``Almost Heroes'' contains minor profanity and
nudity, and some risque humor.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the movie's comedy is pitched at the perfect
level for kids, the filmmakers should have cleaned it up. 2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKWHITE-COX     06-04 2171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKWHITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As minorities in opposite-race worlds, these two teens literally
stood out
 &HT;    By Bette Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--People do many things to stand out in a crowd. Joel
Bethea and Kelvin Lawrence simply went to high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep, I stood out,'' laughs Joel. ``Once my grandmother had to
pick me up at school, and she asked my mom how to find me. `It
isn't hard,' said my mom. `Just look for the white kid.'''
</P>
<P>
   Joel is one of two white students graduating this month from
Southwest DeKalb High.
</P>
<P>
   It's equally easy to spot Kelvin Lawrence, one of six black
students in his senior class at Pope High in east Cobb County.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my fabulous smile,'' he jokes.
</P>
<P>
   On June 13, both will celebrate their high school graduation.
They admit it wasn't always easy being a white face in a black
crowd or vice versa. But they didn't just survive their four years
of high school, they thrived.
</P>
<P>
   Joel helped edit the school newspaper and wrote a humor column
that, apparently, transcended racial lines. ``I heard a lot of,
`Hey, man, you're funny' comments from my fellow students,'' he
deadpans. He also showed athletic skill on the soccer field,
helping send his team to the playoffs this year. He enters Georgia
Tech in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin did so well academically at Pope that he earned a full
scholarship to Florida A&AMP;M University. A budding politician with
Democratic leanings, he threw himself into student government. This
year he served as class treasurer. He also played football, and his
fellow seniors liked him so much they voted him prom king.
</P>
<P>
   An academic decision
</P>
<P>
   For most students in public systems, address determines school
assignment. Not for Joel.
</P>
<P>
   In sixth grade he and about 60 other youngsters formed the
nucleus of DeKalb's first magnet class for gifted students. By
design, half the pupils were black.
</P>
<P>
   The group held together until the start of ninth grade, when all
but three of the white students left the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the other parents were saying, `It's OK for my
child to be in a mixed-racial classroom in sixth, seventh and
eighth grade, but now that he's getting into high school, this is
not OK,''' recalls Joel's father, Paul Bethea. ``At a meeting, a
parent actually said, `But who is he going to take to the prom?'
And I was thinking, `Goodness gracious, he's only in ninth
grade.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Betheas' chief concern was the school's academic excellence,
not its racial makeup. Ultimately, they chose Southwest because it
was closer to their Lithonia home than the other school that housed
the magnet program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't our motivation for him to go through a singular
racial experience, but to get a fine academic education at a school
where we could stay involved in PTA and other school activities,''
says Paul Bethea.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to send Joel to Southwest was made easier because
Wendy Bethea had graduated from predominantly black Bass High in
Atlanta in the 1970s. ``I knew it was possible to have a good
experience. I did,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   They knew they had made the right choice after Joel completed
ninth grade. ``The magnet program sent a card each year asking if
he wanted to transfer to another school. We told him it was his
choice. And every year he'd write, `No,' and send it back,'' Wendy
Bethea says.
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin had less choice in his school. He simply attended the one
to which he was assigned, mostly white Pope High.
</P>
<P>
   ``East Cobb was about all I knew,'' he says. ``My parents moved
there when I was 4 because my father's office was nearby. I grew up
with white kids.''
</P>
<P>
   His mom, Linda Lawrence, says she never worried about Kelvin
attending predominantly white schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's easygoing and people always like him,'' she says. ``Now
when I was in school, it was different. I went to an all-white
girls school (in Louisiana) and when I walked down the halls,
they'd say, `There goes one of them.' But that was back in the
'60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the neighborhood in which Kelvin grew up, his mom
says, ``I know he'll have more opportunities in life than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering high school
</P>
<P>
   Joel and Kelvin both attended opposite-race elementary and
middle schools. Still, they found high school, in the words of
Joel, ``a bit of a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing being a different fish in a small pond, but quite
another being a different fish in a big pond. In both cases, the
pond was more like an ocean; both Pope and Southwest DeKalb have
about 2,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember walking down the hall when everyone was in there,
and you felt self-conscious. You do stick out,'' Joel says. The
presence of his friends from the magnet program meant he didn't
feel like a complete outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Joel, Kelvin had a brush with racism long before high
school. ``It was at a day care center,'' he says. ``A kid would
say, `Don't play with him.' And one day they threw rocks at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering ninth grade, he says, he was prepared for the worst and
delighted when it didn't come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninth grade was easy because I was going to school with my
friends,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In his sophomore year, however, a few students did make race an
issue. Some of them began fighting after school, white kids vs.
black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone at school knew they were fighting. It was kind of
funny,'' he says. ``As soon as the last bell rang you'd hear people
saying, `Can you give me a ride to the fight?'''
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin stayed out of the fray, but Joel wasn't so lucky. In his
freshman year, a small group of what he calls ``juvenile
delinquents'' beat up him and his white friend Louis Belott.
</P>
<P>
   Bethea was left with scrapes and bruises. There was, however, a
happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazingly, it was a positive experience,'' Wendy Bethea says.
``Because other kids began helping him and named all the kids who
were involved. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers and students were so appalled and told him they
were so saddened by it, because they didn't feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the good times roll
</P>
<P>
   By the time they became juniors, Lawrence and Bethea had settled
in to their minority status at their respective high schools. They
even began to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   One recent night after work _ he works part-time at Smoothie
King near his home _ Kelvin and a few friends sat down to talk
about him and his relationships at school. Their jocular intimacy
and ability to make light of race were apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go downtown we always take him with us,'' teased Pope
senior Joe Daniel. The group laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' said Gregg Nelson, another Pope senior, ``he's
going to be a politician and maybe the first black president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an incredible friend and he's going to go far,'' says
Kerry Alexander, another Pope senior, who was Lawrence's date to
the prom. ``It's a running thing with his friends that he's going
to become the first black president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone loves him,'' says Joe. ``I've never been around
anyone who's had a problem with Kelvin. Even my parents, who were
raised pretty prejudiced, really like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin is so comfortable with his situation that even when he
realized a white girl he was dating was ``only using'' him to get
back at her parents, he shrugged it off. ``Just another life
experience,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Joel, too, became more comfortable with his status as a racial
minority. He whooped with laughter the day he received a letter
telling him he had been recommended for a college scholarship
reserved for African-Americans. ``An irony,'' he quips.
</P>
<P>
   He also admits to secretly enjoying when someone would ask him
where he went to school. ``I'd say Southwest DeKalb, and they'd go,
``'Scuse me. You go to which school?''' he says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   And no, he doesn't rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``With rap you've got to be really good at it,'' he notes.
``Otherwise people are going to laugh and say, `Look at that white
guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Commonalities
</P>
<P>
   Joel and Kelvin share traits that helped them thrive in
surroundings others would have found difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Each faced their years in a middle-class high school with an
open mind and a willingness to adapt to their environment. Their
opposite-race classmates admired them, both for their athletic
abilities and their brains. And each was voted ``most
intellectual'' by their fellow students.
</P>
<P>
   Both also enjoy making people laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, my sense of humor helped a lot,'' says Kelvin,
sitting with Joel after having their pictures taken for this
article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same here,'' says Joel. ``It loosens people up.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors helped too, they say. Joel cites his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just their general attitude,'' he says. ``It was like, `This
is normal. It's no big deal. It's an everyday thing.' It wasn't,
`Oh, you're so wonderful for putting up with this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing,'' Kelvin opines, ``the vast majority of people
I went to school with weren't from the South. I think coming from
the North, they had more open minds and fewer prejudices.''
</P>
<P>
   As for dating, both have gone out with girls of the opposite
race. Neither Joel's nor Kelvin's parents view this as a problem.
Says Paul Bethea, ``We haven't put any restrictions on him at all
in the dating department.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither has gone steady with an opposite-race girl, so far. ``I
would, but I just haven't found anyone I've wanted to go steady
with _ white or black,'' Kelvin says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't either,'' says Joel. ``But currently I'm in the
talking phase with a girl I like, and she's black.''
</P>
<P>
   The racial divide
</P>
<P>
   The two seniors share one high school experience that left them
somewhat unnerved: hearing classmates make off-putting racial
remarks in their presence.
</P>
<P>
   For Joel, the moment occurred during a casual conversation with
some black friends about college plans. A girl said she didn't want
to go to the University of Georgia if it meant she'd have a white
roommate. Realizing he was present, she quickly added, ``No
offense, Joel.''
</P>
<P>
   He bristles at such attitudes when they come from his
classmates. ``I've had a lot of them tell me, `You're the coolest
white guy I know.' Why can't I just be the coolest guy?'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In Kelvin's case, the incident also occurred during a group
conversation. ``Someone in the group said, `But Kelvin isn't black,
he's Kelvin.' And I thought, `That feels strange. I am black.'''
The comment disturbed him _ he took it to mean the student thought
he was all right, but not necessarily other blacks _ but he never
mentioned it.
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin struggles with the notion that although the white
students at Pope accept him, some still prejudge other blacks. He
takes that attitude personally, quoting Christ from the Bible: ``As
ye have done it unto one of the least of these my brethren, ye have
done it unto me.''
</P>
<P>
   More so than Kelvin, Joel talks about his classmates' general
attitude about race. ``I think a lot of them are distrustful,
uneasy, unaccustomed to being around white people,'' he says.
``They have misconceptions and preconceptions. That they're put
upon. That the school isn't as good because they're black. That
white people are given more. It's stronger in some people than
others.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he's stopped trying to change their minds. ``It's a
losing battle. It's something you can't do by debating them. It's
something they have to find out on their own. Occasionally, they've
tuned me out because I'm white and it's like, `What do you know?'''
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor Kelvin claim they've made a real difference in
bringing the races closer. But Kelvin's best friend, Pope senior
J.P. Fournier, who is white, disagrees. He says Kelvin has broken
stereotypes for Pope students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they get to know a single black person like Kelvin,
who's a good, decent person, a smart person, then they have the
opportunity to be more open to all black people,'' J.P. says.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bethea says even he has grown from his son's experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I went to a meeting at Southwest DeKalb with
all those black parents, I was uncomfortable. But that passed with
time. Joel's experience has proven to me that, if you give it a
chance, people really can become colorblind.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel's best friends are Alonzo Ward II, who is black, and Navin
Ravi Maharaj, an Indian from Trinidad. All are graduating from
Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo's father, Alonzo Ward, says: ``Their experience there,
well, it's just knocking down so many walls. We can only hope that
they will go out into the world and be beacons.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin and Joel do claim one thing, that they know how people
can begin to heal America's racial divide.
</P>
<P>
   Says Kelvin, ``Two words: hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel agrees: ``Give it a shot. Go over to the new neighbors.
Don't avoid them. Have a barbecue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And don't prejudge people you aren't familiar with,'' Kelvin
says. ``Make a conscious effort to get to know other people with an
open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
