<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4535 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRISONFORD-COX     06-04 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRISONFORD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An off-duty hero: `Six Days' delivers Harrison Ford lite
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 7: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York
</P>
<P>
   Outside on Central Park South, the scene is barely controlled
bedlam. Security sawhorses range all over the broad street, where
irate cabbies are sounding off at hundreds of cops locking things
down in preparation for a visit by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The whole world seems to be coming together just a few floors
beneath the window at the elegant Essex House hotel, yet Harrison
Ford is lost somewhere deep within his own thoughts, describing a
place even he's not sure actually exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's every man's fantasy to have a little house on the
beach,'' Ford says, his words spilling out as spontaneously as a
young boy startled from his treehouse. ``To have his airplane, to
have a simple life and not have to worry about responsibilities
and, uh, accoutrements.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Ford, footloose and fancy-free. If it's not exactly
what moviegoers have come to expect from an actor whose characters
tend to be as rock-solid as his box office numbers, well, give him
a break. In recent years, it seems like whenever Ford, 55, hasn't
had to rescue America from the clutches of an evil president
(``Clear and Present Danger''), he's actually had to be president
(``Air Force One'') and rescue America from the clutches of an evil
Russian terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder then that his latest role in the upcoming
romantic comedy ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' _ boozy, beach bumming,
barely-in-business pilot Quinn Harris _ is lighter than anything
Ford has played of late?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do something that was not a suit-and-tie job,''
Ford explained. ``Something where I didn't have to go around
containing the tension all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   You want uncontained tension? Try asking Ford about his ``Six
Days'' co-star Anne Heche. Here he is, star of the ``Star Wars''
and ``Indiana Jones'' series. Equally beloved by the folks who buy
and sell movie tickets; he's the National Association of Theatre
Owners' star of the century, after all, not some mere decade. Yet
for months, most of the ``Six Days'' talk in Hollywood and the
media has centered on Heche. Her growing acclaim for her supporting
performances (``Donnie Brasco,'' ``Wag the Dog'') seemed to reach
its zenith last year when she snagged the plum role of Robin
Monroe, the Type A-plus New York magazine editor who winds up
stranded on a desert island with Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of all that talk initially was on Heche's seemingly
unlimited future in films. But it quickly turned to questions about
her believability as an onscreen love interest when she publicly
confirmed in spring 1997 that she was a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a what?''
</P>
<P>
   Ford interrupts the carefully worded question, his own voice
low-pitched and vaguely ominous in tone.
</P>
<P>
   Um, a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   You know, she lives with Ellen DeGeneres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh!'' Ford smacks his forehead in an exaggerated gesture, as
if to suggest that he (or at least one of the two people in this
room) is a bit foolish. ``I thought you said thespian.''
</P>
<P>
   You get the point. It's not just that he doesn't care what Heche
does in her private life _ although clearly he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care a (expletive) about anybody's private life as
long as it doesn't make the working relationship difficult,'' Ford
says with unmistakable intensity.
</P>
<P>
   No, what really stands out about this seemingly unscripted
moment is the way it shows off Ford's comic gift. No matter how
many times he replays the scene between now and the movie's opening
next Friday, Ford doubtless will be totally convincing going from
downright alarming to disarmingly funny in a matter of seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has this sort of wonderful, natural comedic ability,'' says
``Six Days'' director Ivan Reitman, who knows from funny, having
directed everyone from Bill Murray (``Ghostbusters'') to Robin
Williams (``Fathers' Day.'') ``There's a sort of sardonic, grumpy
quality to him that he can turn into humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ford is at his sardonic, grumpy best in a scene where
Quinn removes a deadly snake that swims up Robin's shorts. She
frostily warns him against smiling about where his hand is, then
grudgingly tells him ``thanks'' for essentially saving her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not without skills,'' Ford snaps as he turns away from her
and slowly lets a devilishly charming and double entendre-packing
smile play across his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hilarious and charming and more real than he's ever been
on-screen,'' says Heche in the film's press kit. She suggests it
may not all be acting on Ford's part. ``I've kind of fallen in love
with working with him.''
</P>
<P>
   With enough marauding pirates and plane crash scenes to tempt a
little boy out of his treehouse, however, ``Six Days'' isn't all
romantic comedy. Reitman likens it to the circa-1940s
``character-based comedies'' rarely made now because ``you don't
have the movie stars you used to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Except maybe for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harrison Ford is a guy who holds his own with Humphrey Bogart,
Clark Gable, Spencer Tracy,'' said Reitman, who senses some irony
in Ford's popularity. ``Because he's been so successful and because
he does such populist movies, there's a tendency _ as with all
those great stars until about 50 years later _ to not appreciate
the really good work that's going on and the subtlety of what he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Heche saw Ford as ``larger than life,'' something he apparently
never noticed on the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a healthy disregard for me and my .I.I. whatever I
represent,'' Ford waved his hands in the air a bit helplessly as
his mouth twisted into a wry smile. ``She was actively needling,
and that was very appropriate to the (characters') relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, being larger than life does have its perks. Ford had
a say in everything from casting Heche to how the movie should end.
On the other hand, it all sounds like a lot of responsibility for
someone who says it's every man's fantasy to have none at all.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ford's home in Wyoming is awfully far away from any
beach, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right.'' Standing up for a goodbye handshake, Ford seems
unable to suppress a small grin. ``But I'm not far away from an
understanding of what the attraction would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
