</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPat40-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Look who's 40: Our biggest pop stars are hitting midlife.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Years after Prince wore his skin-tight yellow butt-less pants,
Madonna's crosses dangled over cleavage and bare midriff and
Michael Jackson's silver glove glistened as he did the moonwalk,
they are still very much in the public consciousness. Mainly
because they are bigger than their music. They're mega pop stars
with instantly identifiable images who've influenced hairstyles,
clothes, sounds and stage performances through their entire
careers.
</P>
<P>
   They became stars in the decade that pop went boom: the '80s.
Jackson's 1982 ``Thriller,'' which became the biggest-selling album
ever (48 million), created a new benchmark against which all other
performers were measured.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now the standards Madonna, Michael Jackson and Prince set
for themselves, and for this music business, they find themselves
up against,'' notes longtime Rolling Stone writer Anthony DeCurtis.
``They're trying to find a way to not be blockbusters and still
have a career in this business. Country and R&AMP;B seem to be more
tolerant of aging artists. Rock 'n' roll expects you to be 20 for
the rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning 40 is no longer the curse in the music business it once
was. After all, Mick Jagger, who once said he didn't want to be 40
playing ``Satisfaction'' in Vegas, is 54 and playing
``Satisfaction'' in Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these three people _ forces that they are _ are trying to
defy the rule and see what the next stage is,'' adds DeCurtis, 46,
``with, obviously, varying degrees of success. But there's not a
lot of models here. They are still pioneers.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Jackson, Madonna and the Artist who doesn't want to be
called Prince chart the course to where they go next, we thought
we'd note where they are:
</P>
<P>
   THE ARTIST
</P>
<P>
   (Prince Rogers Nelson) (Born June 7)
</P>
<P>
   -- Personal:
</P>
<P>
   After dating a harem of slinky women (Vanity, Apollonia, Kim
Basinger), he settled down with Mayte in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   -- His image:
</P>
<P>
   He's gone from a gender-bender with a name we could pronounce,
to a pretty regular-looking guy (albeit, in heels) who can spend an
hour with Oprah Winfrey. It's that name, then that symbol that
still distances him from the public.
</P>
<P>
   -- His music:
</P>
<P>
   He could stand to slow down production a bit. There was the
three-CD ``Emanci-
</P>
<P>
   pation'' last year. The three-CD ``Crystal Ball'' a few months
back. And another on the way this month. Still, this work is better
than the uninspired contract obligations he released during his
fight with Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   -- :His impact:
</P>
<P>
   He made funk rock 'n' roll. It sounds simple. But when it came
out of his malleable voice or one of the many instruments he
played, it was so compelling he made you see purple rain and doves
cry. D'Angelo, Tony Rich and Maxwell count him among their
influences. ``He showed me there were no boundaries musically,''
Rich says.
</P>
<P>
   MADONNA
</P>
<P>
   (Madonna Louise Veronica Ciccone) (Born Aug. 16)
</P>
<P>
   -- Personal:
</P>
<P>
   She's been divorced for nine years from actor Sean Penn. The
single mother gave birth to Lourdes Maria Ciccone Leon in October
1996.
</P>
<P>
   -- Her image:
</P>
<P>
   Ever changing as usual. But since motherhood the volume on
whatever image she chooses has toned down a lot. No more pointed
cone bras or dominatrix gear. Now it's long, simple hair and pretty
everyday-looking couture. What she says now is often more striking
than what she wears.
</P>
<P>
   -- Her music:
</P>
<P>
   It's ever changing as well. Reviewers widely hailed her latest
electronica-influenced ``Ray of Light'' CD as one of her best ever.
But at its essence, it's still very much the dance music that got
her out of her New York studio apartment and onstage singing her
first hit, ``Everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Her impact:
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, Madonna is a self-made woman. Drive personified.
She took so-so vocal skills, dance club moves and great club tracks
and became a pop star much bigger than her individual parts. Who
has she influenced? Isn't it obvious? Any dance diva since her 1983
debut, including Paula Abdul, Janet Jackson and the late Selena.
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL JOSEPH JACKSON
</P>
<P>
   (Born Aug. 29)
</P>
<P>
   -- Personal:
</P>
<P>
   After a 20-month marriage to Lisa Marie Presley, Jackson wed
nurse Debbie Rowe, the mother of their boy and girl, Prince and
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   -- His image:
</P>
<P>
   He needs more rehabilitating than he's done with his face. But
let's start there. When he started lightening his skin around 1987
_ for medical reasons or not _ he stripped away a sizable amount of
his core black audience. The overarching ambitions (``Call me King
of Pop'') widened the chasm as did the child molestation
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   -- His music:
</P>
<P>
   It's been all downhill since he split with Quincy Jones (``Off
the Wall,'' ``Thriller'') _ musically and sales wise. Where he was
once singing ``Rock With You,'' now he chirps, curses and talks his
way through gigantic productions such as ``Scream.''
</P>
<P>
   -- His impact:
</P>
<P>
   Since he was a preteen, he's been one of the world's best and
best-known entertainers. That's why he's still making a great
living performing _ outside the United States. ``No matter what
happens offstage, he's still the man when he's on it,'' says R&AMP;B
vocalist Usher, who along with Puff Daddy, considers Jackson a big
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
