<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4539 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAV-RANCHMAN-COX     06-04 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAV-RANCHMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He's rich and wacky and into the art of discovery
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 7: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amarillo, Texas _ He's been called ``Amarillo's version of
Picasso'' and ``a lunatic.'' He once brought a bucket of cow manure
to John Connally's bribery trial in Washington, and asked Pat Nixon
in a letter to donate her clothes to his Museum of Decadent Art.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years he has publicly stated that he wanted to legalize
insanity, and to ``encourage art for art's sake and use it to fight
back the ever-rising flood of philistinism.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also one of the richest men in west Texas, freely admitting
his membership in what locals call the Lucky Sperm Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy was rich, my momma was good-looking and my wife's
family owns a 200-square-mile ranch. So these are my toys,''
Stanley Marsh 3 (the third generation oil and gas heir considers
III too pretentious) says of the outdoor installations, such as
Cadillac Ranch, that he has either helped erect or commissioned.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Marsh's day is taken up with business, including
ownership of a local TV station. But his 12th floor headquarters in
downtown Amarillo is as unconventional as the owl-eyed,
mustachioed, 60-year-old Marsh. It's a kind of open-air artists'
collective; homemade spears are stacked against one wall, a blowup
of Howard Beale's ``Network'' screed against the inanity of TV
(``I'm mad as hell and I'm not going to take it anymore'') hangs
from another.
</P>
<P>
   The activities inside the floor's various offices are never
predictable: In one room this afternoon, a state senator held a
business meeting; Marsh had lent his own office to a magazine
writer, who was using it to interview a half-dozen local punks.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh's views on art are equally unconventional, especially when
he talks about how museums can pervert our notions of art and why
he prefers his art outdoors. Here's a typically Holden
Caulfield-esque sampling, spoken in Marsh's deliberate twang:
</P>
<P>
   ``Art museums make things precious,'' Marsh begins. ``When you
walk into one, there's the staff, the architecture, the rules of
parking, the hours it's opened. First, you walk by a guard, there
are cameras everywhere, then there's a docent trying to sign you up
as a member. Then you walk into a room, there's no smoking, no
breathing, no cursing allowed. Then you see an enormous gold and
bronze frame, it's huge, spotlit, while the rest of the room is lit
like the dark end of a church. Then next to the painting there's a
plaque that tells you it's by Peter Paul Rubens and that it was
donated by Mrs. Oglethorpe Peachtree Peachtree.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that by the time you look at the painting by Rubens, you're
so intimidated that all you can say is `It's a masterpiece!'
</P>
<P>
   ``If you took that Rubens and hung it under an expressway, or in
a filling station, or in the lobby of a movie house, or in the
grocery store over the cash register, people might say, `That's a
pretty nifty painting,' or `Those girls are too fat, and anybody
who'd spend that much time painting each leaf like that must not
have much else to do.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I happen to like Rubens. But unless you've gone to a
school where you were taught how to look at such things, the museum
destroys your ability to like it or not. Museums contain things
that are not necessarily art, but which are precious. They're
depositories _ treasures that rich people have made. There's no
reason a lot of things are there, except they're very valuable and
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was king, I would take the paintings and hang them
without labels that you could see right way. And I would hang them
where people could see them. A great place would be at the top of
an escalator in a mall. Then a certain number of people would
really have their socks knocked off, and the painting wouldn't end
up being cherished. To take all this stuff and hide it in museums
is insulting.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I make things that are hidden, but I'm not a very good
hider. They're hidden where most people can see them when they bump
into them _ you don't have to trek to the top of the Sierra Madres.
They see it where they don't expect it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an Easter egg hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
