<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4540 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAV-RANCHTOUR-COX     06-04 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAV-RANCHTOUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas has always set itself apart _ and this art is right up
there
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 7: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amarillo, Texas--Stanley Marsh 3 provides roadside sideshows.
The rest is up to you. ``After you see it, either you liked it or
you didn't,'' says Marsh. ``At least you're deciding.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're driving through the Texas Panhandle, here's a rundown
of what you can see:
</P>
<P>
   CADILLAC RANCH
</P>
<P>
   Best postcard in America. The authentic Caddys are arranged
chronologically by model year, from '49 to '63. They lean east at
the same slope as Egypt's great Pyramids _ a nice, New Agey touch
to an installation inspired by the horizon-to-horizon oceanscape
the plains here resemble.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was a dolphin idea,'' art conspirator Doug Michaels
has recalled of being shown the spot by Marsh in the late '70s.
``(We) were standing in a wheat field off Route 66 in the rain. And
you know how the wheat waves and ripples in the wind? Well,
suddenly we imagined a dolphin tail fin sticking up out of the
wheat. Then the dolphin tail fin became a Cadillac fin. That was
it. That was Cadillac Ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cadillacs were exhumed and reburied a couple miles west last
year _ it seemed like half the city stood on the plains to watch _
when nearby development threatened their seclusion. ``The girls
(the cars) didn't like the smell of the city,'' Marsh has
explained. ``They like the fragrance of cow manure and wheat and
new-broken sod.''
</P>
<P>
   The classic cars are now covered in graffiti, with some parts
stolen by souvenir hunters. That jibes with the site's
for-the-people credo (like other Marsh sites, you just walk up to
it and look), but also makes it feel more neo-hippie than it
should.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cadillac Ranch is one odd, oddly awesome thing to stand
out there among, on what seems like the edge of the world _ this
strange metal crop seemingly made in the image of modern man's
highest aspiration: cool wheels. Don't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   FLOATING MESA
</P>
<P>
   The riskiest payoff, but worth a look-see. The drive winds
through burnt, rolling, ravine-filled land just outside Amarillo _
the real West. Then, in the distance, sprout three big,
dictionary-definition mesas _ an even realer West.
</P>
<P>
   In a certain light _ probably best in early morning _ the mesa
on the far right can look a little peculiar. There's a band of sky
between the top and the rest, leaving the top to look as if it's
... floating?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a stranger, from a long way off, maybe you think
it's a cow patty in the sky. Or maybe a flying saucer,'' says
Marsh, who had 180 feet of 8-foot-tall fence painted the same color
as a light gray sky and erected around half the mesa.
</P>
<P>
   It can also look like 180 feet of 8-foot-tall painted fence
around a mesa. But it's such a nutty concept _ and such an
interesting drive _ it's worth checking out.
</P>
<P>
   OZYMANDIAS
</P>
<P>
   A weird winner. Two massive concrete legs severed above the
thigh, as if a larger warrior monument had been eroded by the wind,
rain and sun of millenniums. A sendup of the Shelley poem by the
same name that exults the impermanence of man-made monuments, it
was, says Marsh, ``Put up to make fun of myself. A monument to a
poem that makes fun of monuments.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in the middle of another wheat field, off a small
interchange several miles from Cadillac Ranch, this is the jokiest,
frankly funniest of Marsh's outdoor installations. It's fronted by
a replica of a Texas historic marker engraved with the site's
amusingly bogus story: that Shelley and his wife traveled across
Texas in the early 19th century and came across this statue, which
inspired him to write his famous poem. The rest of it _ including
its famous ``visage'' _ was destroyed by Lubbock high school
students after a football game with their archrivals in Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a camera: America's second-best postcard.
</P>
<P>
   GRAVE OF THE UNKNOWN PET
</P>
<P>
   A quick chuckle on Soncy Road, on the way to Ozymandias. My
Marsh-ordered tour guide (we traveled to the sites in a pink '59
Caddy) called it ``One of the small things not many people know
about.'' A 10-foot high wooden copy of the obelisk in the movie
``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' it is a monument to all those pets
who've been lost and never found. Marsh suggests you visit it on
the anniversary day your pet (``snake, cat, dog'') disappeared and
feed a ``biscuit or a sandwich'' to the prairie dogs that live in
the field surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNS
</P>
<P>
   They're everywhere: empy lots, beside highways, on country roads
outside of town. Marsh plunks a sign in the yard of anybody who
wants one, free of charge. There are now so many, they're virtually
the official state shrub.
</P>
<P>
   In some neighborhoods, a message is related Burma Shave-style _
in successive signs down the road _ philosophizing on the nature
of, say, art. Others are more haphazard. Marsh won't give specific
locations for signs. I'm reluctant, too, for the same reason: Half
the effect is coming upon them out of the blue. But you won't be
disappointed if you head down Soncy Road, near downtown _ they're
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Among the signs out there: ``IF I WERE YOU,'' ``WITHOUT A NET,''
``I WAS MADE THIS WAY,'' ``BRING BACK PUBLIC HANGING'' and ``LAUGH
AND THE WORLD LAUGHS WITH YOU _ CRY AND YOU CRY ALONE.''
</P>
<P>
   One read ``STEAL THIS SIGN.'' Until somebody did.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
