<HEADER>
A4541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ART-COX     06-04 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ART-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amarillo not the only place for odd art
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 7: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    (SUGGESTED TO USE WITH TRAVEL-RANCH-COX)
 &HT;    By Eileen M. Drennen and Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- Paradise Gardens, the 2-acre arts environment Howard Finster,
Georgia's most famous folk artist, carved out of a swamp in
Summerville. Open 10 a.m.-6 p.m. every day except Christmas and
Thanksgiving. $3; $2 for children under 12; free for under 3; $5 on
Sundays when Finster is on the premises; Tuesdays are donation day
(contribute what you can). 706-857-2926.
</P>
<P>
   -- Pasaquan, the fantastical wonderland that sprang from the
mind of self-taught artist Eddie Owens Martin, rises out of the
green rural landscape outside Buena Vista, Georgia like a dream.
You can get information on the Web,
www.shockoestudios.com/steom.htm. Open 10 a.m.-5 p.m.
Wednesdays-Saturdays; noon-5 p.m. Sundays. $5 adults, $3 seniors
and students with ID, free for children under 12. Information:
912-649-9444.
</P>
<P>
   -- W.C. Rice's Cross Garden, an eerie, phantasmal scene
painstakingly sown into the Prattville, Ala., landscape over the
past 20 years by William Carlton Rice, retired house painter and
self-described ``Jesus Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ROADSIDE ART INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Fun Along the Road: American Tourist Attractions''
(Bullfinch, $29.95) is a fun, strange trip. In the just-published
hardback, author John Margolies visits oddities from Monkey Jungle
south of Miami (where ``the monkeys are caged and the humans are
free'') to the Dinosaur Park, seven statues on a Rapid City, S.D.,
hillside created by the Works Progress Administration and now on
the National Register of Historic Places. Lacking in addresses and
other concrete facts, this is more a well-illustrated reverie than
a true guide.
</P>
<P>
   -- A helpful Web site is www.roadsideamerica.com, which handily
breaks the attractions out by state.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
