<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-RANCH-COX     06-04 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-RANCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Driven to act, a free-spirited Texan makes the Panhandle a place
to pause.
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 7: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amarillo, Texas --The Texas Panhandle is ``drive through''
country. If you're here, you're probably driving through on your
way somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The late, great Route 66 once drifted through these booming
flatlands, hoodwinking passers-by to brake for roadside rattlesnake
farms and oddball reptile museums. But the stop-and-start Route 66
has long been replaced by clear-the-runway U.S. 40. The highway's
offramps let you make a pit stop for gas and a Yoo-Hoo, then head
right back out, Amarillo already a tiny toy town in your rearview
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   And then, just as what passes for sprawl in Amarillo peters out
_ what the. ... ? Over there. If you're headed west, on the left.
In the middle of that wheat field.
</P>
<P>
   It ain't wheat. Ten vintage Cadillacs buried halfway into the
Panhandle hardpan nose first _ one plunked right behind the other,
as if the Texas twister gods had tossed them down there like a
series of big Fourth of July yard darts, their double row of tail
fins angled high and sharp and skyward.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Cadillac Ranch, a piece of roadside pop art now nearly
as much an icon to modern, car-propelled Texas as the Alamo was to
the wagon wheel state that preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   What's it doing there?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense to this,'' explains Stanley Marsh 3, a
60-year-old local millionaire and all-purpose eccentric who 20
years ago collaborated with a San Francisco designers collective
called the Ant Farm to create the Cadillac Ranch on his wife's
family's farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art,'' adds Marsh, ``is the enemy of common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense. But Marsh and his nonsensical works just might be
the salvation of Amarillo _ or at least the salvation of the
drive-through people just trying to get ... through the
relentlessly featureless stretch that unrolls between Dallas and
Tucumcari, on their way someplace they might actually want to be:
Santa Fe, Las Vegas, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us end up driving across the country at least once in
our lives, and that usually means driving through Texas _ which
often means driving through its Panhandle, of which Amarillo is the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   There're a number of uncommon sights to see on your way through
here: the Helium Museum (Amarillo is the nation's helium capital);
the heavily secured Pantex Plant (where every U.S. nuclear weapon
was once assembled, and where they're now being disassembled); the
Big Texan Steak Ranch and Motel (a monument to southwestern
overkill right off U.S. 40, where anyone who polishes off the
72-ounce steak dinner within an hour gets it free).
</P>
<P>
   But there's an even more extraordinary set of sights to break up
this endlessly ordinary terrain: Stanley Marsh's outdoor art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you whether it's art or not. I just like to make
things,'' says Marsh, whose first installment, in the early '70s,
was a huge backyard likeness of a pool table with pool balls. ``As
a boy, I liked to build treehouses and Christmas tree forts and
caves. I'm still making things. If you like them, that's fine. If
you don't, that's fine, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of Marsh's ``things'' is an offbeat break that can be
viewed in about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Cadillac Ranch, there's the Floating Mesa (a real
mesa whose top looks separated from the rest of it), Ozymandias (a
statue of two giant legs), the Grave of the Unknown Pet and more
than 700 traffic-sign look-alikes proclaiming slogans such as
``ROAD DOES NOT END'' and ``WHAT'S THE VILLAGE WITHOUT THE VILLAGE
IDIOTS'' that Marsh and his crew of prairie pranksters have erected
in yards all over town.
</P>
<P>
   If you're driving through, here's a rundown:
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac Ranch: Best postcard in America. The authentic Caddys
are arranged chronologically by model year, from '49 to '63. They
lean east at the same slope as Egypt's great Pyramids _ a nice, New
Agey touch to an installation inspired by the horizon-to-horizon
oceanscape the plains here resemble.
</P>
<P>
   ''To me, it was a dolphin idea,'' Ant Farmer Doug Michaels has
recalled of being shown the spot by Marsh in the late '70s. ``(We)
were standing in a wheat field off Route 66 in the rain. And you
know how the wheat waves and ripples in the wind? Well, suddenly we
imagined a dolphin tail fin sticking up out of the wheat. Then the
dolphin tail fin became a Cadillac fin. That was it. That was
Cadillac Ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cadillacs were exhumed and reburied a couple miles west last
year _ it seemed like half the city stood on the plains to watch _
when nearby development threatened their seclusion. ``The girls
(the cars) didn't like the smell of the city,'' Marsh has
explained. ``They like the fragrance of cow manure and wheat and
new-broken sod.''
</P>
<P>
   The classic cars are now covered in grafitti, with some parts
stolen by souvenier hunters. That jibes with the site's
for-the-people credo (like other Marsh sites, you just walk up to
it and look), but also makes it feel more neo-hippie than it
should.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cadillac Ranch is one odd, oddly awesome thing to stand
out there among, on what seems like the edge of the world _ this
strange metal crop seemingly made in the image of modern man's
highest aspiration: cool wheels. Don't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Floating Mesa: The riskiest payoff, but worth a look-see. The
drive winds through burnt, rolling, ravine-filled land just outside
Amarillo _ the real west. Then, in the distance, sprout three big,
dictionary-definition mesas _ an even realer west.
</P>
<P>
   In a certain light _ probably best in early morning _ the mesa
on the far right can look a little peculiar. There's a band of sky
between the top and the rest, leaving the top to look as if it's
... floating?
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're a stranger, from a long way off, maybe you think
it's a cow patty in the sky. Or maybe a flying saucer,'' says
Marsh, who had 180 feet of 8-foot-tall fence painted the same color
as a light gray sky and erected around half the mesa.
</P>
<P>
   It can also look like 180 feet of 8-foot-tall painted fence
around a mesa. But it's such a nutty concept _ and such an
interesting drive _ it's worth checking out.
</P>
<P>
   Ozymandias: A weird winner. Two massive concrete legs severed
above the thigh, as if a larger warrior monument had been eroded by
the wind, rain and sun of millennia. A sendup of the Shelley poem
of the same name that exults the impermanence of man-made
monuments, it was, says Marsh, ``Put up to make fun of myself. A
monument to a poem that makes fun of monuments.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in the middle of another wheat field, off a small
interchange several miles from Cadillac Ranch, this is the jokiest,
frankly-funniest of Marsh's outdoor installations. It's fronted by
a replica of a Texas historic marker engraved with the site's
amusingly bogus story: that Shelley and his wife traveled across
Texas in the early 19th century and came across this statue, which
inspired him to write his famous poem. The rest of it _ including
its famous ``visage'' _ was destroyed by Lubbock high school
students after a football game with their archrivals in Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a camera: America's second-best postcard.
</P>
<P>
   Grave of the Unknown Pet: A quick chuckle on Soncy Road, on the
way to Ozymandias. My Marsh-ordered tour guide (we travelled to the
sites in a pink '59 Caddy) called it, ''One of the small things not
many people know about.'' A 10-foot high wooden copy of the obelisk
in the movie ``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' it is a monument to all
those pets who've been lost and never found. Marsh suggests you
visit it on the anniversary day your pet (``snake, cat, dog'')
disappeared and feed a ``biscuit, or a sandwich'' to the prairie
dogs that live in the field surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   Signs: They're everywhere: empy lots, beside highways, on
country roads outside of town. Marsh plunks a sign in the yard of
anybody who wants one, free of charge. There are now so many,
they're virtually the official state shrub.
</P>
<P>
   In some neighborhoods, a message is related Burma Shave-style _
in successive signs down the road _ philosophizing on the nature
of, say, art. Others are more haphazard. Marsh won't give specific
locations for signs. I'm reluctant, too, for the same reason: Half
the effect is coming upon them out of the blue. But you won't be
disappointed if you head down Soncy Road, near downtown _ they're
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Among the signs out there: ''IF I WERE YOU,'' ''WITHOUT A NET,''
''I WAS MADE THIS WAY,'' ''BRING BACK PUBLIC HANGING'' and ''LAUGH
AND THE WORLD LAUGHS WITH YOU _ CRY AND YOU CRY ALONE.''
</P>
<P>
   One read ''STEAL THIS SIGN.'' Until somebody did.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
