<HEADER>
A4551 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-COITUM-COX     06-04 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-COITUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For the ages: Tale of lust, heartbreak after 40
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Post Coitum'' is a story of heedless passion that would
probably look clumsy, contrived and ickily politically correct if
it fell into Hollywood's hands. But French director Brigitte Rouan
brings flair, sophistication, heartbreak and sexual heat to this
tale of an older woman who hurls herself into a passionate affair
with a younger man.
</P>
<P>
   Diane (Rouan) is a very attractive fortysomething _ think Susan
Sarandon crossed with Maggie Smith _ with a loving husband, two
nice teenage sons and a big-time job as an editor with a powerful
Paris publisher. But when Francois, one of her most promising
novelists (Nils Tavernier), comes down with a bad case of writer's
block, she makes a house call and meets his twentysomething
roommate, Emilio (Boris Terral), who makes no secret of his
interest in her. ``I'm a lifetime ahead of you,'' she protests
before succumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, against her better judgment, she thinks she and Emilio
have a lifetime ahead of them, too. A lifetime together. After all,
she's risking everything she cares about for him. Which may be why
she isn't listening when he says he's really happy because they're
having such fun and ``I'm not in love with you.''
</P>
<P>
   As both filmmaker and actress, Rouan traces Diane's precipitous
fall with wrenching precision. And with a knowing sympathy as
Diane's ``happiness'' takes its toll, turning her life into a
chronicle of loss, abandonment and the constant lies that come with
the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as the movie's writer-director, she's generous to Emilio as
well. She makes it clear that he's not really using Diane. He has
no careerist agenda; he's an engineer who specializes in the Third
World, not an aspiring writer. And he's no himbo. Rather, he's much
like the inevitably much younger women in any given Hollywood
movie: not just physically desirable, but also funny, smart, aware,
sensitive and even a teeny bit dangerous in his self-assured
flirtatiousness. Emilio doesn't mean to destroy her life with their
fling, but at the same time, he has no idea how much she's willing
to risk in exchange for this intoxicating new sense of herself.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's full title, ``Post Coitum, Animal Triste,'' is taken
from the Roman poet Ovid: ``After sex, the animal is sad.'' Diane's
sadness is a spectacle of self-abasement and depression. And Rouan
plunges into her character's full-blown masochism with much the
same reckless courage that propels Diane into Emilio's embrace. A
raw, revealing tragicomedy of eros in which renewal is only a
breath away from rejection, ``Post Coitum'' offers truths as
inescapable as stretch marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Post Coitum''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brigitte Rouan. Directed by Rouan. Not rated, but there
are steamy sex scenes. In French with subtitles. Tara. One hour, 37
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Doomed passion, charted unsparingly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
