<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4552 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MURDER-COX     06-04 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MURDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dial R for remake: `Perfect Murder' lets viewers thrill to crime
in an opulent New York
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a dumpy detective stumbles through a slick Central Park
penthouse, he murmurs that old, familiar slogan, ``the rich are
different.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the prime selling point of ``A Perfect Murder.'' It's a
B-movie shot in the deep mahoganies of a Rembrandt painting, decked
out in Fifth Avenue fashions. Its thrills come equally from the
twisty plot (husband schemes to off his wealthy wife) and our
vicarious pleasure in prowling past the semi-recognizable paintings
and gleaming bathroom fixtures in the troubled couple's home.
</P>
<P>
   In Andrew Davis' glossy remake of ``Dial M for Murder'' (1954),
Michael Douglas plays the husband, Steven Taylor. He's a 1990s
variation of his Oscar-winning ``Wall Street'' character, a
business shark whose boom is going bust. Fast. It's a signature
Douglas role: scum-sucking sicko with caviar tastes, flawlessly
attired by Barney's of New York. Dariusz Wolski's cinematography
surrounds him with a feudal Manhattan still redolent of robber
barons (dig the firelit club where he plays poker with fat-cat
cronies).
</P>
<P>
   Steven's prize acquisition is his decades-younger wife, Emily
(Gwyneth Paltrow). The film's subliminal kicks include the notion
that someone as beautiful and young as Emily, with $100 million in
trust to boot, can still be unhappy. That's why we first see her in
the arms of David Shaw (Viggo Mortensen), the classic starving
artist with a libido as long as his hair.
</P>
<P>
   David isn't exactly what he seems, any more than Steven is the
tycoon he pretends to be. When the men meet, the husband encourages
the lover to ``cash out.'' In other words, kill Emily and make it
look like an accident. David will get half a million bucks for his
efforts, and Steven the rest of his wife's fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say things don't work out as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's second half involves the scheme's aftermath. The
stakes are raised considerably by the arrival of David Suchet as
the lead detective on the case. The movie could have benefited from
more of his piercing, intelligent presence.
</P>
<P>
   After consecutive bombs (``Steal Big, Steal Little'' and ``Chain
Reaction''), director Davis is back to craftsmanlike work, if not
up to his breakout hit ``The Fugitive.'' The film's burdensome
sense of dread saps life out of the slower scenes _ hey, this ain't
Bergman. One bit of foreshadowing involving a meat thermometer is
so ham-handed that you assume Davis will pull a fake-out and tweak
our expectations. Afraid not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Perfect Murder'' isn't. A plot machine, it's a little like
David Mamet's current mind-trip, ``The Spanish Prisoner.'' It puts
its attractive cast through a plot line that's twisty enough to
keep us guessing, but it's too pat and airless to be a total kick.
Still, it's a pleasant way to spend a summer evening. Plus, you
might get some interior decorating ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Perfect Murder''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michael Douglas. Directed by Andrew Davis. Rated R for
profanity, sex, murder and gore. One hour, 47 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Not perfect, but a B-movie given the A-list
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
