<HEADER>
A4553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-TRUMAN-COX     06-04 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TRUMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carrey's breakout ``show''
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a wonderful life for Truman Burbank (Jim Carrey), a
perpetually beaming insurance salesman whose impossibly picturesque
hometown, Seahaven, makes George Bailey's Bedford Falls look like,
well, Pottersville.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, none of it is real. Not Seahaven, which is
actually a huge sound stage. Not Truman's pert, pretty wife (Laura
Linney) or his salt-of-the-earth, have-a-brewski buddy (Noah
Emmerich). In fact, the only real thing in Truman's life is Truman
himself. He's the unwitting star of ``The Truman Show,'' the
world's most popular long-running TV series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' is also the name of Peter Weir's smart,
thoughtful and thoroughly entertaining comedy-drama that's already
stirring up comparisons to ``Forrest Gump'' (misguided) and talk of
Oscar nominations (not so misguided).
</P>
<P>
   Truman, the first baby ever to be adopted by a corporation,
initially has no idea that he's being watched 24-7 by some 5,000
hidden cameras, to say nothing of billions of ``Truman'' addicts
who gather at Truman-themed bars in their Truman T-shirts to watch
the dailiness of his daily life. He has no idea that his ``god'' is
an egomaniacal producer-director named Christof (Ed Harris), who
gets a special kick out of issuing commands like ``Cue the sun.''
Or that even his most personal traumas are scripted.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, his father's accidental death by drowning when
Truman was a boy accomplishes two things. First, it helps create
Truman's horror of water, thus keeping him Seahaven-bound, even
though he dreams of Fiji. Second, it gets rid of a cast member who
has become troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   But what would happen should Truman ever discover the truth?
That's the theme that gives Weir's film its exceptional resonance.
Andrew Niccol's script isn't perfect; it's too reminiscent of other
recent ``puzzle'' films such as ``The Game'' and ``The Spanish
Prisoner,'' and its payoff isn't as ingenious as its setup. Still,
``The Truman Show'' raises all sorts of intriguing questions.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, there's the frightening pervasiveness of
so-called ``real TV,'' already on view in everything from the Loud
family chronicles of the 1970s to the ``Real World'' soap operas of
the '90s. On the other, there's a deus ex media context, in that
Truman really is always being watched by a supposedly ``superior''
being who allows him certain freedom of choice while controlling
almost everything that happens around him. In a sense, Seahaven is
a high-tech equivalent of the Garden of Eden. But when this Adam
gains knowledge, the outcome is quite different.
</P>
<P>
   The entire movie is a dazzlingly executed conceit that plays
expertly on our sense of media manipulation, as both viewer and
victim. Weir's direction keeps things crisp, challenging and often
very funny. So does his gifted cast. And of that cast, no one is
more gifted than Carrey, who uses all his limber likability to
create an indelible character that couldn't be further from his
manic ``Dumb and Dumber'' persona. His Truman is both the essence
of homogenized, media-made humanity and the embodiment of human
fallibility and unpredictability. He's the one real thing in an
artificial world. How that world both shapes and fails him is
central to the movie and to Carrey's astute performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' may end up the victim of its own hype. It's
not the best movie of the decade, as some magazines have
proclaimed. It's not the Second Coming, even if Harris' character's
name does have messianic overtones. It's not even, in some crucial
emotional ways, ``It's a Wonderful Life.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's still a heck of a picture. Provocative, beautifully
crafted and endlessly intriguing, it's the sort of film Hollywood
stumbles into every once in a while, then gets scared about
releasing. But don't let the overcompensation, i.e., the hype, turn
you off to ``The Truman Show.'' Rather, turn on, tune in, drop by.
You won't be sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jim Carrey. Directed by Peter Weir. Rated PG for mild
language. One hour, 44 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Jim Carrey's performance is the centerpiece of this
thought-provoking social satire, which takes on everything from
media madness to theology.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
