</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMAN-LINNEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Linney's got the bases covered
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laura Linney is everywhere these days.
</P>
<P>
   She hits movie theaters today as Jim Carrey's faux wife in ``The
Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday on Showtime, she returns to TV as Mary Ann Singleton
in the miniseries ``More Tales of the City.''
</P>
<P>
   And every day except Monday, she's appearing onstage in the
Broadway drama ``Honour'' opposite Jane Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know what to think about it all, to be
perfectly honest,'' she says by phone from New York, where she
lives. Two weeks ago, she returned from a weekend in the country
with her husband and saw ``The Truman Show'' on the cover of Time
magazine. ``I've never been involved in anything that has this type
of momentum. It's been an adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, she plays ``Meryl,'' the wife of Carrey's Truman
Burbank _ the only man in the world who doesn't realize his life is
being broadcast live to the world as a 24-hour documentary. Or that
Meryl is actually an actress named Hannah Gill, who knows where all
the hidden cameras are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meryl Burbank is supposed to be the perfect woman, the creator
of the home, a woman with heart and warmth and love,'' Linney says.
``She's a throwback to those television shows from the 1950s.
Hannah Gill, on the other hand, is a profoundly ambitious, powerful
woman who knows that if she doesn't keep Truman happy, she'll be
written out of the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she was born and raised in New York City, ``My whole
family's from Georgia,'' Linney says. Her grandmother is from
Baxley, and her mother grew up in Douglas and on St. Simons Island.
Her father is playwright Romulus Linney, and she has cousins living
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Linney got to know Carrey on location in Seaside, Fla., by
reconstructing her entire married life with Truman. For the first
days of shooting, director Peter Weir had his actors pose for the
archival photos that speckle the film. ``We had to shoot these
stills like Truman's birthday, graduation, Thanksgiving, Christmas
and Halloween,'' she says. ``We even had this whole elaborate
creation of our wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrey isn't the first comedian turned dramatic actor with whom
Linney has worked. A few years ago, she spent several months in the
Atlanta area shooting ``A Simple Twist of Fate'' with Steve Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very similar in a lot ofways,'' she says of the two
leading men. ``They've both dealt with being in a tornado of fame.
They both cornered a market. They both hit a bull's-eye in a way
that had a global impact, as far as their talent is concerned, and
they monopolized a certain area of comedy. When you have that sort
of impact, the repercussions are enormous. But there's always more
to someone than just one thing, and when you're really, really
talented, you want to be able to explore that. Both are extremely
talented men who have the opportunity to show something
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her sunny, girl-next-door looks, Linney herself has been
able to do the same, moving from comedy to drama with ease.
``Because of `Primal Fear,' `Congo' and `Absolute Power,' some
people see me as this tough, smart woman who's wounded
underneath,'' she says. ``Then there's another group, the `Tales of
the City' crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   In the miniseries based on Armistead Maupin's books, Linney
plays Mary Ann Singleton, naive newcomer to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that character so much, and the people who created
it,'' she says. ``We have such a long history now, we really do
feel like family. Making (the sequel) after all this time was just
thrilling, a relief and sweet justice.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because it almost didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   When the first ``Tales of the City'' aired on Georgia Public
Television in January 1994, legislators condemned the show for its
use of nudity, sexual content and drug references. The legislators
had not actually seen the show but had read about it in an
interview with Linney in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. The
controversy in Georgia and other states resulted in PBS'
withdrawing support for the proposed sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved PBS so much, which is why I felt so
disappointed,'' Linney says now. ``Everyone has a right to air what
they want to, but they would never say why (they wouldn't back the
sequel). That's still my beef with them. If it's their political
belief, fine. But say so.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds, ``But I also know that it's never a simple situation.
There were many people and affiliates who supported the show. And
as much as I would love to slam PBS, that's not quite fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
