<HEADLINE>
A LEADING DEMOCRATIC STRATEGIST CALLS RECAPTURE OF HOUSE `50-50' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Martin Frost, chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, said Thursday that Democrats have
a 50-50 chance of retaking the House of Representatives this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to be as realistic as I can,'' the Texas Democrat told
reporters at a luncheon meeting. ``We have a very legitimate chance
of taking the House back. (Republicans) will be very, very
fortunate if they retain control.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost, the leading strategist for his party in the House races,
added, ``I think our chances are 50-50.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats need to win 11 seats to regain the 218-seat majority
needed to rule the 435-member House. After 40 years of nonstop
control of Capitol Hill, the Democrats lost both the House and
Senate after the 1994 election.
</P>
<P>
   Political oddsmakers give them little chance of retaking the
Senate, but increasingly the House is viewed as up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, meanwhile, expressed confidence that the House
would stay in GOP hands. ``We're on a roll!'' proclaimed a press
release from the National Republican Congressional Committee. ``The
Republican Party is enthused, strong at the grass roots and
motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost spoke in the wake of Tuesday's primaries in California,
Alabama, Iowa, Mississippi, Montana, New Jersey, New Mexico and
South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   He said Democrats are heartened by one Republican victory in
California _ that of former Rep. Bob Dornan, a strong conservative,
in the Orange County race against two moderate Republicans, lawyer
Lisa Hughes and California Superior Court Judge Jim Gray.. The
victory puts Dornan in a rematch against Rep. Loretta Sanchez in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez narrowly defeated him in a bitterly contested 1996 race.
Afterward he attributed her win to illegal immigrants casting
fraudulent ballots, a claim rejected earlier this year by a GOP-led
House task force.
</P>
<P>
   Frost said Dornan ``has national value'' as a symbol to rouse
support among Democratic voters. ``I think he'll continue to be a
problem for the Republican Party nationally, and among Hispanic
voters,'' the Texan said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Frost acknowledged that Democrats may face
problems elsewhere in California as GOP voters picked moderates who
favor abortion rights to run for seats being vacated by two
Democratic incumbents _ Rep. Jane Harman, who lost the California
gubernatorial primary to Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, and Rep. Vic Fazio,
who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Had voters picked hardline conservatives in those districts,
Democratic candidates would have been shoo-ins because the
districts are now under Democratic control, according to some party
strategists.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Frost would not concede the two districts. They are
``very tough'' and ``very competitive,'' he said. But he added,
``I'm not going to say they're uphill.''
</P>
<P>
   For Fazio's seat outside Sacramento, wealthy developer Doug Ose,
a Republican, faces attorney Sandie Dunn, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   For Harman's seat in and around Torrance, south of Los Angeles,
state Assemblyman Steven Kuykendall, a Republican, faces
businesswoman Janice Hahn, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Frost pointed to a number of Tuesday results elsewhere in the
nation that he said bode well for Democrats this November.
</P>
<P>
   One was in northern New Mexico, where the state's Democratic
attorney general, Tom Udall, is challenging Republican incumbent
Rep. Bill Redmond, a minister. More than half the district's voters
are Indian or Hispanic. Redmond won a special election last year
when the seat's former occupant, Democrat Bill Richardson, left to
be U.S. ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Another was in northeastern Alabama, where the Democratic
nominee is lawyer Don Bevil, son of popular former Rep. Tom Bevil,
who held the seat for 30 years before his retirement in 1997. Don
Bevil is challenging Rep. Robert Alderholt, R-Ala., who won in 1996
with 50 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Alabama, like other southern states, has grown increasingly
Republican in recent years. In 1990, two of Alabama's seven House
members were Republican. Now, five of eight are Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Frost also noted that in southern Mississippi, the elected
regional transportation commissioner, Ronnie Shows, a conservative,
is the Democratic nominee. Two Republicans, lawyer Delbert Hosemann
and banker Phil Davis, will compete in a runoff June 23 for the GOP
nomination. The seat is held by Republican Rep. Mike Parker, who is
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   The electoral math in Mississippi also favors Republicans.
Mississippi went from a 4-1 Democratic congressional delegation in
1990 to 3-2 Republican delegation this year.
</P>
<P>
   Frost said that blacks who traditionally vote Democratic may
prove crucial if the Alabama and Mississippi races turn out to be
close. The Alabama district is 25 percent black, and the
Mississippi district is 37 percent black, Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if President Clinton's travails over Whitewater, Monica
Lewinsky and satellite deals with the Chinese are undercutting
Democratic chances this fall, he said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues that resonate best for Democrats are health care,
education, and the future of Social Security and Medicare,'' Frost
said. ``To the extent that Democrats can talk about those issues,
they're going to penetrate whatever fog is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``My sense is the average person is befuddled by
what's going on in Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
