<HEADER>
A4558 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-TRUMAN05-COX     06-04 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TRUMAN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A boob inside the tube: Carrey gives ace performance in TV
satire
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Alrighty, then!
</P>
<P>
   The Mugger made the cover of Time, and a slew of other slick
publications. Depending on the hype, Jim Carrey's new movie is The
Film of the Summer, The Film Of The Year, or The Film Of The
Decade.
</P>
<P>
   Get real. It's just a film. Better than most, but not as deep as
the gong-bangers would have it.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``The Truman Show'' will appeal to the chattering
classes. Newspaper columnists and TV talking heads will leap at the
chance to deplore the world it depicts. And that is a good joke by
itself, since one of the movie's subjects is the omnipresence of
The Media and the virtual reality it creates for addicted
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   So give points to veteran director Peter Weir and screenwriter
Andrew Niccol (``Gattaca'') for manipulating the manipulators of
public discourse. But their movie is about much more than TV idiocy
_ sometimes too much for its own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' is a fantasy about a goofus who comes to
realize that his entire life has been a television show. Literally.
Truman Burbank (Carrey) was ``adopted'' at birth by a mastermind
with the rather suggestive name of Christof. Played by a spooky and
unsmiling Ed Harris, Christof is the all-powerful director of ``The
Truman Show,'' a mega-hit watched by zillions of fans.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 30 years, Truman has lived on a gigantic soundstage.
Everyone around him in the picture-perfect ``town'' of Seahaven is
an actor, including his impossibly sweet wife, Meryl (Laura
Linney), and oh-so-sincere best friend Marlon (Noah Emmerich).
</P>
<P>
   Meryl (Streep), Marlon (Brando), Burbank (the famous home of
Johnny Carson). Get it? Everyone's in on the joke but Truman. He
thinks he's an insurance salesman living happily in the best of all
possible worlds, a sitcom paradise of pleasant people and sanitized
surroundings. In fact, he's a stooge _ until the reality of the
unreality sinks in.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of stooges, Carrey turns in an ace performance. And we
don't mean Ace Ventura. In another stab at a ``serious'' role, he
has fine-tuned his shtick. The face is as expressive as ever, but
it has been de-watted. He used to wield his mugging like a weapon.
Now it's used in the service of a fetching innocence. His character
becomes vulnerable, somebody to root for, even as the movie points
out that we're being shamelessly manipulated to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey's Truman is something of a cross between nerdy Pee-wee
Herman and a gee-whiz Tom Hanks. His tag line is: ``Good morning,
and in case I don't see you, good afternoon, good evening and good
night.'' He delivers this pretty ordinary witticism with a cornball
cheeriness that forces it to be funny.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey also has room for physical comedy as he begins to
question the reality of things, especially when klieg lights drop
from the sky, rain falls only on him, and cryptic messages filter
through the radio.
</P>
<P>
   The film is sweet, slick and swift, but it has faults. Curiously
enough, its virtues tend to work against it. Its messages are
clever, but they're also so relentless we begin to feel bogged down
in a marshland of metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   The film is obviously a commentary on modern ``Live at Five''
television, or ``The Jerry Springer Show,'' where exhibitionism
amounts to the sole reason for existence _ and the audience is as
complicit as the guests.
</P>
<P>
   But other Big Questions keep coming, and coming, beginning with
the specter of Truman, as Everyman, forced to confront the
``whims'' of fate or The Big Guy in the Sky.
</P>
<P>
   The '50s sitcom quality of the film is perfect, from the
wonderfully warm yet artificial sheen of Seahaven (filmed in the
planned town of Seaside in northwest Florida) to Laura Linney's
portrayal of an ``Ozzie &AMP; Harriet'' wife. But this also serves to
make the satire seem retro, at times, more about '50s conformity
than the potential perils of cyberspace, or even the absurdity of
an entire nation mesmerized by a certain Bronco chase..
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s, there was much chatter about the manipulation of
the individual. The book ``The Organization Man'' kvetched about
corporate robots in gray suits and porkpie hats. John Kenneth
Galbraith and Vance Packard bleated that ad men and marketeers were
manipulating our lives _ that average Americans, poor idiots that
we are, were helplessly in their thrall.
</P>
<P>
   There's the feeling that this movie is another example of the
intellectual class identifying a social ``problem'' that only it
sees and dictating the corrective. Because there is a whiff of this
sort of arrogance, the flick is interesting without being
consistently entertaining, despite the suspenseful balancing act
between the sweet and the sinister.
</P>
<P>
   By the time a wised-up Truman makes his bid for freedom, we
don't care all that much, though we're supposed to. Shoot, we were
just beginning to really enjoy ``The Truman Show.'' The artificial
one. Guess that makes us part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
