<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4560 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER05-COX     06-04 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A menu, a movie and mischief
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--Annabelle Gurwitch and Paul Gilmartin, hosts of TBS'
popular Friday night film hash ``Dinner &AMP; a Movie,'' are eating a
leisurely lunch at Midtown's South City Kitchen and confessing.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what many viewers think, they're not married, she
admits.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling is rigged, he confides (and he should know _ he was
taught the ropes for a recent cross-promotional gig in Nashville
with Turner-owned World Championship Wrestling and, ultimately, got
pelted by wrestling fans who were shouting, ``Kill the cook!'').
</P>
<P>
   And neither one is a bona fide kitchen expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only cooking show where the people doing the cooking
aren't chefs,'' Gurwitch says. She's an actress with credits
ranging from ``Seinfeld'' to ``The Cable Guy.'' He's a stand-up
comic.
</P>
<P>
   Together they diss each other on camera while preparing dishes
that poke fun at the movies viewers see. At 10:30 EDT tonight, for
example, the flick is Richard Gere's Naval trainee-romance ``An
Officer and a Gentleman'' (1982). ``Dinner &AMP; a Movie's'' side dish:
Drop and Give Me 20 Bean Salad.
</P>
<P>
   All the recipes _ and their amazing titles _ come from the brain
of chef Claud Mann, a graduate of the California Culinary Academy
in San Francisco. ``It's never fake food,'' he says. Always the
real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, leads to one more confession. While Gurwitch
and Gilmartin do taste the food on the show, there was one complete
dish (a sandwich, actually) that he ate, but that she consumed
minus one key ingredient _ beef's tongue.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the upcoming new shows (All times aree Eastern
Daylight):
</P>
<P>
   -- June 12: ``Sleeping With the Enemy'' (1991) starring Julia
Roberts. 10:35 p.m. Recipe: Pecan Someone Your Own Size Pie.
</P>
<P>
   -- June 19: ``Tootsie'' (1982) starring Dustin Hoffman. 10 p.m.
Recipe: What's Under the Skirt Steak.
</P>
<P>
   -- July 10: ``Blue Steel'' (1990) starring Jamie Lee Curtis.
10:05 p.m. Recipe: High Caliber Shells 'n' Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   -- July 17: ``Encino Man'' (1992) starring Brendan Fraser. 10:30
p.m. Recipe: Missing Link Sausage With Ice Age Slushies.
</P>
<P>
   -- Aug. 7: ``Fire Birds'' (1990) starring Nicolas Cage. 8:05
p.m. Recipe: Fryers in the Hot Seat (If You Can't Stand the Heat,
Get Out of the Chicken).
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's 'Memoir' a sad reminder of RFK
</P>
<P>
   Take away the tabloid glare that now overwhelms the Kennedy
story and you're left with something as profound and sad as
anything in modern America.
</P>
<P>
   We forget. Fortunately, Discovery's three-hour rememberance,
``Robert Kennedy: A Memoir'' (8 p.m. EDT, Sunday) keeps its eye on
the prize and creates a profoundly sad documentary on the 30th
anniversary of Bobby Kennedy's murder.
</P>
<P>
   There's little new here, and no tabloid salaciousness. Yet it
gets at the heart of things in a way that's almost impossible to
turn from. It's a reminder that for many Americans Bobby Kennedy _
gunned down in 1968 after winning the Democratic primary in
California _ remains the nation's great ``what if?'' What if he'd
lived? What if he'd become president?
</P>
<P>
   ``People are drawn not only to his vision, but to the lost
potential,'' one observer says of the Kennedy's lingering hold.
``Not only in him, but in themselves and the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Through interviews and an endless reel of new and familiar tape,
Bobby Kennedy is portrayed first as tough and ruthless (he calls
mob boss Sam Giancana a ``little girl'' during one hearing), then
as a figure of hope shrouded in melancholy and doom (there's
heartbreaking video of him sitting on a rock by himself in West
Virginia, where he'd broken away from his campaign to be alone, and
later said he sat there thinking for half an hour of his late
brother John). His charisma was that of a kind of dreamy, fated
fifth Beatle, and that's just what these three hours capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memoir'' neither mythologizes nor denigrates Bobby Kennedy. It
simply, thoroughly, often eloquently presents the man so many still
miss.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Drew Jubera, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   War...what is it good for?
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that AMC continues its commitment to film
preservation this weekend with a three-day marathon of war movies,
including a restored version of the classic anti-war film``All
Quiet on the Western Front.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that AMC's Sixth Annual Film Preservation
Festival includes an original documentary, ``Cinema Combat:
Hollywood Goes to War'' (7:30 EDT, tonight).
</P>
<P>
   A chronological look at Hollywood and combat, the two-hour
program includes the usual intriguing mix of clips and archival
newsreels. But Martin Sheen, while a terrific actor, proves a
less-than-effective narrator (he can't help but suggest his
``Apocalypse Now'' persona, which is often at odds with some of the
more patriotic footage). Further, the collection of clips
emphasizes AMC's major weakness _ a limited cache of old movies
compared to its rival, Turner Classic Movies. For example,
``Casablanca,'' a Turner-owned film, is barely mentioned, while
something from the AMC library _ say, ``Pin Up Girl'' _ gets
seemingly unlimited screen time.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, this works in the documentary's favor _ a relatively
unknown Oscar-winning classic like ``Wings'' gets the respect (and
attention) it deserves. But overall, I'd skip the documentary and
stick to the 40 features being shown in the name of preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Grades: A+ for the Preservation Festival; and C- for ``Cinema
Combat.''
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   New HBO series short on reality
</P>
<P>
   They're attractive, they're successful and they're single. But
if the characters in HBO's new series ``Sex and the City'' (10:15
p.m. EDT, Saturday) bear any resemblance to reality, pray these
people never breed.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Jessica Parker stars as Carrie Bradshaw, a real-life
columnist for a New York tabloid whose assignment is
``investigating'' dating habits in the '90s. Call her Ally
McSqueal. Her pals (mostly women complaining about men), slither
from swanky lunch spots to chic nightclubs, spitting out slimy
pickup lines with their forked tongues.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who doubles as narrator and player in this theater of
the self-absorbed, reels off some zingers, including a scene in
which she describes a gold-digging friend: ``Miranda has the kind
of self-delusional confidence that causes men like Ross Perot to
run for president.''
</P>
<P>
   The debut episode deals with what Bradshaw calls ``the mid-30s
power flip'' or more bluntly, whether women can have sex like men
without any expectation of long term commitment. It's a good
question, but here it's wasted (and never answered) by grating
characters and limp writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City'' tries hard to be provocative, but it's
mostly just a big tease and the strongest case for mandatory
sterilization we've seen in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   _Lyle V. Harris, TV critic
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
