<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHT RECEIPTS, DARK HOUSES  
 THE LIFE OF JOLSON  
 `EVERYMAN' IN BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Broadway season, which came in like a Lion King's
roar, is going out with a whimper.
</P>
<P>
   The season appears on track to be the most lucrative in Broadway
history, earning more than $550 million in gross receipts,
according to estimates from the League of American Theaters and
Producers. But on the eve of the Tony Awards, which will be handed
out Sunday night at Radio City Music Hall, there are signs of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Two more Broadway shows have posted closing notices, and others
are hanging by a thread. Last week, ``Golden Child'' closed despite
its Tony nomination for best play. Ticket sales have slumped at
numerous shows since Memorial Day, even some that hoped to get a
boost from Tony nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Scarlet Pimpernel,'' up for best musical, earned only 31
percent of its potential at the Minskoff Theater in the week after
the holiday. ``High Society'' and ``The Sound of Music'' were also
hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   Now this week, ``The Life'' announced that it will close after
more than a year at the Barrymore Theater, and the revival of ``The
Sunshine Boys,'' starring Jack Klugman and Tony Randall, announced
that it will close June 28.
</P>
<P>
   The malaise is not limited to Broadway. Despite the recent
addition of Peri Gilpen, who plays Roz on the television series
``Frasier,'' the off-broadway comedy ``As Bees in Honey Drown''
will close Sunday at the Lucille Lortel Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling shows that come up empty-handed Sunday night may find
themselves making similar hard decisions next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're finding is that there was a little bit of a
flattening out of the attendance curve this season, helped by the
more mild than normal winter,'' said Jed Bernstein, the league's
executive director. ``A good week's attendance is north of 200,000
and a bad week is south of 150,000. This whole year, we dipped
below 150,000 only one or two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Return of Mr. `Swanee'
</P>
<P>
   Lest we get too bogged down in the waning season, it should be
noted that the first play of the 1998-1999 season is almost upon
us.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Leight's critically acclaimed ``Side Man,'' which had a
successful off-broadway run earlier this year, is set to open June
25 at the Roundabout Theater under Michael Mayer's direction.
</P>
<P>
   And another production rumored for the coming season is a
definite. Sam Harris, seen most recently on Broadway in ``The
Life,'' will play Al Jolson in a new musical based on the singer's
life called ``The Jazz Singer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jolson's hits like ``Toot Toot Tootsie'' and ``Swanee'' will be
intermingled with original music and lyrics by Will Holt and an
original book by Sherman Yellen. Gabriel Barre will direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be the toughest thing I've ever done,'' Harris
said. ``I'm hardly gone from the stage. At the moment, I sing 14
songs.''
</P>
<P>
   The world premiere will be at the Colonial Theater in Boston on
Nov. 3, where it will run through Nov. 29. From there, it will
transfer to a Broadway theater to be announced, with previews
beginning Dec. 17 and opening night scheduled for Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Harris describes the piece as a full-scale biography of the
famed showman, from his height in the mid-1920s through his work on
the first Hollywood talkie, his pursuit and marriage of Ruby Keeler
and gradual decline in the 1930s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a dark intensity, but it's also show biz,'' Harris
said. ``He's a megalomaniac, but he's also giving, in a very
manipulative way. He always needed an audience's approval. There
was a certain amount of desperation in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he has been studying Jolson's life and work and
thinks he has begun to come to understand him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved to perform and he loved to sing, as I do,'' Harris
said. ``I love being on stage. I get sick and throw up every time
before I go on, but I love it when I'm out there. It's my favorite
place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   `Everyman' in Brooklyn
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Shakespeare Company's three-week residency at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music comes to an end this weekend with the
last performances of ``Everyman,'' a 15th-century morality play
that has not been professionally performed in America since the
first decade of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Mydell, who was born in Georgia and studied acting in New
York before moving to London, where he has worked for two decades,
plays the central allegorical figure of a man preparing for death.
Mydell's mother and two sisters saw the first performance Tuesday
night, and it was a very emotional moment for the family, he said.
The play, about accepting death, has reverberations for the AIDS
crisis, and five of Mydell's siblings (there were 15 children in
all, including half-brothers and half-sisters) have died of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been sort of a grace thing, because it has allowed me
to expiate my response to my own family grief,'' Mydell said.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ Frances McDormand, who won an Oscar last year for ``Fargo,''
will return to the New York stage in the fall in a new version of
``Oedipus,'' written and directed by Dare Clubb for the Blue Light
Theater Company. Exact dates and a theater will be announced
shortly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Those who can't wait until Matthew Bourne's acclaimed
interpretation of ``Swan Lake,'' with all-male swans, opens at the
Neil Simon Theater in the fall can see a film of the production on
PBS's ``Great Performances'' at 9 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alec Baldwin will conclude the Manhattan Theater Club's
``Writers in Performance'' series with readings from Giacomo
Casanova's ``History of My Life'' at 7:30 p.m. Monday at City
Center.
</P>
<P>
   _ JoAnne Akalaitis' production of ``The Iphigenia Cycle'' of
Euripides, which drew wide acclaim at the Court Theater in Chicago
last year, will be presented in conjunction with the Theater for a
New Audience in January.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Pera Palas,'' a world premiere by the Turkish playwright
Sinan Unel, set in the famous Istanbul hotel of that name, begins
previews Monday at the McGinn/Cazale Theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
