<P>
   SOLAR-DONATIONS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida Power &AMP; Light
Co., a Fortune 500 company with $6.1 billion in revenue last year,
is asking its customers for a handout: donations for a solar energy
project. Customers have been skeptical. (Murawski, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUILDING _ ATLANTA _ Cozy but high-tech Tudor houses on
tree-lined streets could replace multi-gabled suburban
mini-mansions with two-story foyers and Palladian windows as
America's next dream homes. That's what some 5,000 architects and
designers will be told as they gather for the fifth annual Southern
Building Show, held in Atlanta June 4 - 6. A longing for simpler
days, a changing family and a computer in every home was among
themes discussed at the event. (Harte, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/3.
</P>
<P>
   HEAD-START _ Head Start graduates are no better prepared for
kindergarten than poor children who have had no pre-school, says a
legislative study that is raising new questions about the focus and
effectiveness of the $93-million program in Ohio. The study, based
on data from the Dayton City Schools, has already set off a heated
debate in a state that is among the nation's leaders in Head Start
spending. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PILOT-RETIRES _ The FAA's age limit has been a point of
contention since it was imposed in 1959. The agency says there is
no certain way to determine the age at which health and skills
deteriorate dangerously. So, the agency argues, it's safest to draw
an early line. Numerous pilots and pilot groups have challenged the
rule with studies showing that older pilots fly safely in other
parts of the world and can be tested as reliably as younger pilots.
(Kalajian, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
