<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4573 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAD-START05-COX     06-04 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAD-START05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Head start -- no head start?
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Head Start graduates are no better prepared for
kindergarten than poor children who have had no pre-school, says a
legislative study that is raising new questions about the focus and
effectiveness of the $93-million program in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The study, based on data from the Dayton City Schools, has
already set off a heated debate in a state that is among the
nation's leaders in Head Start spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Head Start classrooms are good places for kids to be _ they're
warm, they're nurturing, they have good things going on _ but we
say more attention should be given to promoting skills essential to
school success later on,'' said Nancy Zajano, director of the
Legislative Office of Education Oversight, a non-partisan research
arm of the state legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Head Start say the study is seriously flawed and
contradicts earlier reports showing the program benefits
disadvantaged youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very willing to cooperate in any studies with the
(legislative staff), but we take issue with this particular
study,'' said Barbara Haxton, executive director of the Ohio Head
Start Association, which sponsors much of the training for Head
Start teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not giving it a lot of credence,'' said Jaqui Sensky,
deputy chief of staff in Gov. Voinovich's office. The Ohio
Department of Education announced Wednesday it will begin
collecting data on pre-school students for a more comprehensive
analysis of Head Start's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative study comes after eight years of rapid expansion
of the program under Gov. Voinovich _ from $19 million during the
two years prior to his taking office to $146 million in the last
two-year state budget. Currently, Head Start serves 85 percent of
Ohio children living at or below the poverty level, more than any
other state. However, Ohio ranks 46th in per-pupil spending in the
program.
</P>
<P>
   The study recommends shifting more money into training Head
Start teachers, placing more emphasis on developing children's
learning skills and setting up model classrooms and annual progress
reports to meet that goal.
</P>
<P>
   The same study found that a more costly, federally funded Dayton
City School pre-school program does a significantly better job than
Head Start in preparing students for kindergarten. Among other
skills, the study looked at children's ability to understand what
they hear, to follow simple instructions and to identify shapes.
</P>
<P>
   SEE JUMPLINE/ 6A
</P>
<P>
   SAMPLE: Hed in Utopia Reg
</P>
<P>
   CONTINUED FROM 1A
</P>
<P>
   Head Start is operated by community agencies that receive $4,700
per pupil in state and federal money. Teachers generally have just
one year of training and no college degree. By comparison, the
Dayton schools pre-school program uses certified teachers with
college degrees and receives $7,200 per child. With less money,
Head Start also provides a wider array of services to families,
including parent education, job referrals and health and nutrition
guidance.
</P>
<P>
   James Williams, superintendent of Dayton schools, said he hasn't
had a chance to look at the study but agreed that Head Start could
benefit from having more certified teachers. ``I'm not saying that
the individuals that they have are not doing a good job, but we
need to find the funding... for a seamless approach to Head Start,
kindergarten and first grade.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislative office chose Dayton schools for the study
because it's the only district in the state that tests students at
the beginning and end of kindergarten on a wide range of school
readiness skills.
</P>
<P>
   Haxton and other critics say the sample of 1,230 Dayton students
was too small, that researchers didn't account carefully enough for
differences in poverty among students and that they didn't test the
students before entering Head Start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think that the true situation of these children was
taken into account,'' she said, adding that Head Start selects
students not just on their income level but factors such as a lack
of stimulation and attention at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get some kids who are four years old and have absolutely no
expressive language,'' she said. ``You would have no way of
understanding them.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the report especially object to researchers gauging
the poverty of students based on the percentage of poor families
living in their Zip Code. ``You know there's a variance in income
levels in virtually all the Zip Codes of Dayton,'' Haxton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Zajano said researchers tried their best to adjust for that
and noted that nearly all Dayton school students _ 83 percent _ are
at or below the poverty level anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Zajano said Head Start's biggest problem may be the lack of
consensus among its teachers, parents and administrators over what
children should be taught to prepare them for school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academics has an almost negative connotation in the Head Start
community,'' Zajano said. ``We're not talking about sitting kids in
rows and having them read flash cards, but we do think there needs
to be more emphasis on those (readiness) skills in a
developmentally appropriate way.''
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends that the Ohio Department of Education lead
the way in developing that new academic emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   But Haxton said, ``We can't expect all kids to develop at the
same rate when they come to pre-school. A curriculum that is
academically based is setting expectations that can't be reached by
some children, and maybe we're already programming them to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside
</P>
<P>
   Results of the Head Start study. 6A
</P>
<P>
   Head Start study
</P>
<P>
   E WHAT: The research arm of the state legislature compared the
school readiness of 1,230 Dayton kindergarten students during the
1996-97 school year. Students were divided into three groups: those
who had graduated from Head Start, those who had completed a Title
I pre-school program operated by Dayton schools and those who had
no known pre-school experience.
</P>
<P>
   E LIMITATIONS: Students were not tested before their entry into
pre-school to measure any direct gains from the programs. Income
levels of specific students' families were unknown. Instead,
researchers linked the poverty levels of students to the percentage
of poor families living in their Zip Code. Head Start students came
from Zip Codes where 30 percent of families lived in poverty. All
other students lived in Zip Codes where 26 percent of families
lived in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   E FINDINGS: Head Start students performed no better than
students who had no pre-school on seven different measures of
learning readiness. However, Title I students scored better on four
of the seven measures and on social competency skills than did the
Head Start students. The higher scores included skills in receptive
language (38.8 to 36.9), expressive language (44.7 to 43.5),
auditory memory (44.9 to 43.3), visual memory (44.4 to 43.5),
visual discrimination (33.6 to 31.8), fine motor (37.2 to 35.3) and
social competence (51.7 to 48.9).
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: The Legislative Office on Education Oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
