<HEADER>
A4574 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-DISCO05-COX     06-04 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-DISCO05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    They love the night life, they like to talk alot
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``I'm really not a disco type,''
declares an earnest character in ``The Last Days of Disco.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is?'' comes the reply.
</P>
<P>
   Great question. Exactly the sort favored by writer/director Whit
Stillman. In context, it's deadpan and almost innocently ironic.
The only difference from Stillman's typical dialogue is that it's
short.
</P>
<P>
   His bright but rather self-deluded characters tend to gush
rivers of high-faluting analysis, as though desperate to explain
themselves, often to themselves. They're not exactly Woody Allens,
but there is a touch of the same puzzled anxiety beneath the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   A Studio 54-like disco is at the center of this romantic comedy.
It's Stillman's third in his ``young, well-bred New Yorkers in
love'' series. In terms of time, the very early '80s, the movie
fits loosely between his ``Metropolitan'' and ``Barcelona.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of recent college grads spend their days at entry-level
jobs in publishing or the D.A.'s office. They rough-it in cheap
apartments. They've come down a tad from the upper middle-class
world in which they grew up.
</P>
<P>
   At night, though, they hang out at a glitzy dance club,
quibbling, flirting, schmoozing, playing at being hip, often acting
dumb. They include roommates Alice (Chloe Sevigny) and Charlotte
(Kate Beckinsale). The former is naive and uncertain; the latter is
a chatterbox and manipulator. A tad amoral without being truly
malicious, she doesn't mind giving her pal lousy advice about love
on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Among the crew are Des (Chris Eigeman), a Harvard dropout on the
make who is the under-boss of the club, where some hanky-panky is
going on at the till; Josh (Matt Keeslar), a sober-sided rookie
prosecutor in the D.A.'s office; and Jimmy (Mackenzie Astin), ``the
dancing ad man,'' who is barely holding on to his job by getting
clients past the ``jerk line'' of wannabes outside the club.
</P>
<P>
   The characters interact in varied, screwy ways. They form their
own little social group within the fickle disco scene. What they
have in common is that they are well-spoken schmoes whose superior
vocabularies don't give them any edge in the common sense
department. They're as puzzled by life and love as the next guy.
They just have a wonderful way of describing things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you notice that people who look alike never seem to know
each other?'' observes breezy Charlotte, who is also given to
nattering about the ``positive aspects of V.D.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The environmental movement was started by Bambi,'' argues
another member of the crew. Another person gives a funny exegesis
on the real meaning of the movie ``Lady and the Tramp.''
</P>
<P>
   So it goes, as this kooky band chatters the night away to the
sounds of what seems like every disco song ever recorded. The film
captures the period well, but the characters can also be as grating
as they are amusing. The acting is on target. Sevigny (``Kids'')
stands out as the insecure Alice. She's a fine actress with a
wonderfully expressive face. Although not strictly beautiful, it's
hard to take your eyes off her.
</P>
<P>
   At bottom, ``Disco'' may be one of those movies that clicks if
you're willing to admit to recognizing yourself and your era in
this motley crew. If not, you will probably find the movie bubbly
but slight. Sort of like disco itself.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
