<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4575 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLAR-DONATIONS05-COX     06-04 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLAR-DONATIONS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Customers sceptical at Florida Power &AMP; Light Co. environmental
donation campaign
 &HT;    By John Murawski
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida Power &AMP; Light Co., a Fortune 500
company with $6.1 billion in revenue last year, is asking its
customers for a handout: donations for a solar energy project.
</P>
<P>
   ``All contributions, large and small, help bring us one step
closer to making solar power a reality and preserving the
environment for future generations,'' says a bill stuffer that FPL
sent its 3.5 million customers at the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   It said the money would be used to install photovoltaic units at
its Martin County power plant near Lake Okeechobee. Photovoltaic
cells convert sunlight to electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Although the flier touts the FPL Solar Research Partnership as
``a joint effort between FPL and our customers,'' it doesn't say
how much the project will cost, how much FPL or its customers will
have to contribute or how much power it will make.
</P>
<P>
   Customers have been skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flier asks you to write a check for extra money _ it
doesn't look like it's going to a special fund. It looks like it's
going into a black hole,'' said Constantine HadjilambrinosCQ, a
professor in the Environmental Studies Department at Florida
International University in Miami. ``FPL has enough money to do
this on their own whereas other organizations don't. I would rather
give my money to some nonprofit that's doing the same kind of
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What FPL's flier doesn't say is that the company's goal is to
collect $70,000 to buy a 10 kilowatt facility, which will produce
enough electricity to power about five homes. The money is going to
a special fund, which FPL must report on to the state Public
Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the flier tell the customer that he, not solar energy,
is the real subject of this research project. According to FPL
officials and documents filed with the PSC, the purpose of the
project is to measure whether customers are willing to pay more for
energy that is environmentally clean. Photovoltaic energy costs up
to 10 times more to produce than does electricity made by fossil
fuels.
</P>
<P>
   After the money is collected, FPL will interview the donors and
submit a final report and conclusions to the PSC in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   All of FPL's customers are paying for the experiment: $250,000
for the company's promotion of the project and another $225,000 for
administrative and research costs. FPL shareholders won't pay a
cent.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators, who approved the project in 1996, say the
$475,000 cost to be shared by customers is minuscule and will add
less than a penny to the average annual bill.
</P>
<P>
   In the program's first six weeks of fund raising, 4,000
customers, all residential, have donated $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials are pleased with the results so far, said FPL
spokesman Bill Swank. The results also are not unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Before the fund raising began, FPL had concluded residential
customers alone would not contribute enough. After conducting focus
groups in Broward County and consulting with other utilities
working on similar projects around the country, FPL estimated only
about 1 percent of its customers would respond to the fund-raising
call and it would have to appeal to its commercial and industrial
customers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers were skeptical of FPL's intentions and wanted a
visible demonstration of FPL's commitment to the environment and to
solar power before considering contributing to the project,'' wrote
Dennis Brandt, FPL's marketing manager, to the Public Service
Commission in March.
</P>
<P>
   That commitment is still not evident, say some environmental
groups, including one that had worked closely with FPL on the
project but now refuses to help promote it.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Legal Environmental Assistance Foundation, or LEAF,
say FPL's bill stuffers and other marketing materials are a
turn-off. Tallahassee-based LEAF, based in Tallahassee, objects to
FPL's less than optimistic description of solar energy as
``currently very expensive to harness.'' LEAF also wants FPL to put
the photovoltaic modules in a prominent place _ a well-known
building, say _ to serve as a solar showcase.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put it out in the boonies where no one can see it,'' said
Gail Kamaras, director of LEAF's energy advocacy program. ``We
don't want to lend our credibility to this project until we see
some better effort on their part in terms of how they're marketing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamaras, however, does support financing it this and other such
programs through donations.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of customer subsidies, known as ``green pricing,''
was authorized by the PSC in 1994 as part of a statewide energy
conservation effort. The PSC has since found that most utilities in
Florida reject green pricing for lack of customer interest.
</P>
<P>
   But negative reactions are just as important to this experiment
as are contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a research project to find out whether customers are
truly interested in green pricing, and if so, to what extent,''
said FPL's Swank.
</P>
<P>
   FPL took up the project in 1996 after canceling a solar water
heater rebate program it deemed ineffective, prompting the PSC to
tell FPL to set up another program.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it will also provide FPL with $70,000 worth of
experimental equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a given that somewhere down the road this technology will
be viable for some applications, and they want to keep their hand
in it,'' said Jerry Venture, director of the photovoltaics and
advanced technologies division at the Florida Solar Energy Center,
which The center has worked with FPL on other photovoltaic
projects.solar experiments for more than a decade and will assist
the utility when it starts bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
