<P>
   KIDS-AZR _ Children are often the hidden victims of domestic
violence. And in many cases the cycle of intimate violence is
passed to yet one more generation. By Julie Amparano and Susie
Steckner.
</P>
<P>
   READING-WARS-BOS (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Harvard Education School
professor Catherine Snow is calling for an end to the ``reading
wars.'' By Michael Kenney.
</P>
<P>
   TENN-VALEDICTORIAN-NYT (Memphis) _ Three years ago, Daira Hodges
was a 14-year-old honor student. But on May 9, 1995, everything
changed when an ex-boyfriend, also 14, dragged her into a vacant
classroom, choked her, stabbed her 21 times, and then went to take
an algebra test, leaving her for dead. But she regained
consciousness, survived and on Tuesday graduation from East High
School as valedictorian of her class. This fall, she will begin
working toward a pre-med degree at Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   VALEDICTORIAN-NYT (Kerrville, Texas) _ Tivy High School
valedictorian Josh Walther saw humor in calling on the two
lowest-ranking members of his class to replace him at the podium at
commencement exercises. ``Why should I have to do more work and
give a speech?'' he planned on saying. ``I wasn't the one slacking
the last four years.'' School officials stopped him from giving the
speech. By Zeke MacCormack.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-YOUNG-ATHLETES-SPI (Undated) For many students, sports
physicals are a necessary nuisance to participate in sanctioned
school athletics. But too often the exams are cursory. They lack
the scope to detect a leading killer of young athletes: sudden
cardiac death, which takes 15 to 20 lives a year, according to the
American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-KID-WEATHER-SITE-NYT (Undated) _ In rain, snow, sleet and
hail, and even wind that will ruin a teen-ager's perfect hair,
students around the country are trudging outside daily to gather
precise weather data that will be used by teams of scientists
studying the environment. Photo. By Debra Nussbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-STUDENT-FEEDBACK-NYT (Undated) _ Teachers, of course, make
their living grading students. But with a device known as a
Perception Analyzer, students can now turn the tables (or the
lecterns) on their teachers and grade their performance. Photo. By
Adam Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-CARE-COX (Washington) _ While most parents expect college
to be their largest child-related expense, many will pay far more
for day care while their children are young, the Children's Defense
Fund (CDF) reports. By Samar Abulhassan.
</P>
<P>
   REMEDIAL-EDUC-REVIEW-NYT (Undated) _ All the brouhaha last week
over the dropping of remedial classes at the City University of New
York, one of the nation's largest systems, would make many people
think that remediation was a multicultural course invented by CUNY
professors. They would be wrong. By Karen &QL; 
Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-AZR (Undated) _ Children are often the hidden victims of
domestic violence. Some suffer cuts and bruises. Many others are
wounded deeply within by the horror they're forced to witness
between the adults they love the most. &QL; 
And in so many cases they visit the same horrors on their own
children, pushing the cycle of intimate violence through yet one
more generation. By Julie Samparano and Susie Steckner.
</P>
<P>
   DATING-RULES-SPI (Undated) _ Dating guides aimed at women are
springing up in bookstores all over. By Teresa Talerico.
</P>
