<HEADER>
A4587 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIANANMEN-ANNIVERSARY     06-04 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIANANMEN-ANNIVERSARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS MARK TIANANMEN ANNIVERSARY BY GIVING ADVICE TO CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Marking the ninth anniversary of the Tiananmen
Square crackdown, Democratic and Republican members of Congress
again urged President Clinton on Thursday to cancel his trip to
China, saying it ``sends the wrong message'' about the U.S.
commitment to human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The request by Sens. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., Tim Hutchinson,
R-Ark., Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., and
other lawmakers critical of human rights abuses in China, came one
day after Clinton called for the renewal of normal trade relations
with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends the wrong message at the wrong time,'' Ashcroft said,
saying the trip would not be in America's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   The critics told a news conference that they also objected to
Clinton's plan to be greeted in Beijing's Tiananmen Square, the
site where thousands of pro-democracy protesters were killed in a
bloody military crackdown on June 4, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``How sad it would be for the president of the United States to
tarnish the image of his office by being received in Tiananmen
Square,'' Pelosi said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi and Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., wrote Clinton Thursday that
his presence in Tiananmen Square would ``desecrate the memory of
the brave individuals who lost their lives fighting for democratic
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the first U.S. president to visit China since the
Tiananmen Square crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., told the news conference that he
feared Clinton's visit to China means ``that the United States will
be endorsing a government we should condemn and shirking a
responsibility we must embrace _ to give meaningful support to
democracy and human rights in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese dissident Wei Jingsheng, who was exiled to the United
States last year, also criticized Clinton for fostering relations
with Chinese officials, whom he called ``murderers and
executioners.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolves are always wolves in the world,'' Wei said through an
interpreter. ``Wolves never change.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Mike McCurry said Clinton will stick
to his plans to visit China despite the lawmakers' protests.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry also defended plans for Clinton's welcoming ceremony at
Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the world leaders including Israel's Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and French President Jacques Chirac have been
received at the Great Hall of the People, which is adjacent to
Tiananmen Square, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard to imagine there'd be any other way that the
Chinese would do it,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Clinton plans to address human rights concerns
during his visit, although the issue will not be the top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symbolic importance of the events in Tiananmen Square will
never be lost on this government,'' McCurry said. ``Indeed, we have
addressed them many, many times.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton promised to ``deal forthrightly'' with
human rights concerns in China during his visit, while pushing for
the renewal of China's ``most favored nation'' trade status.
Congress now has 90 days to decide whether to vote to cancel the
president's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made it clear that the human rights issue would be
second to strategic and economic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said China was key to U.S. strategic interests in Asia
that are being challenged by nuclear testing by India and Pakistan.
Good relations with Beijing are crucial amid possibilities of a
nuclear race in South Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
   China had helped Pakistan's nuclear program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
