A4588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-PRICES-NYT &LR;      06-04 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICES UP 2 PERCENT AFTER AGREEMENT TO CUT PRODUCTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Saudi Arabia, Venezuela, Mexico, Iraq)   (ja) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Oil prices rose by 2 percent in the futures markets
Thursday after Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico, three of the
world's largest producers, agreed to cut production by 450,000
barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   The three producers issued a statement from Riyadh, Saudi
Arabia, saying they had agreed on the cuts because ``the market
remains in a state of imbalance.''
</P>
<P>
   The three countries were the leaders in putting together a
coalition of major oil exporters last March who agreed to cuts that
eventually totaled 1.72 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual move in March prevented oil prices from collapsing
and sent them up by about 18 percent, into the range of $16 a
barrel, on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But continuing weak demand in Asia and rising exports from Iraq
have led to an oversupply, and prices have again fallen to the
range of $14 to $15.
</P>
<P>
   Early reports Thursday that more cuts were under way led crude
oil for July delivery to rise by as much 5 percent. But after the
announcement was actually made, showing that the cuts would be
lower than traders had expected, crude oil for July delivery closed
up 31 cents, to $15.12 a barrel, on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. In London, the benchmark Brent crude for July delivery
rose 44 cents, or 3.1 percent, to $14.48 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts predicted that when the cut is put into effect on
July 1 it would only help to keep the prices from falling and would
not lead to any significant increase.
</P>
<P>
   Vahan Zanoyan, the chief executive of the Petroleum Finance Co.,
a Washington-based consulting group, said that the
450,000-barrels-a-day cut was a ``a quick fix'' to help absorb the
increase in the exports from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be just in the nick of time to take care of Iraq,''
he said. Iraq has been exporting about 1.6 million barrels a day
and is expected to increase that this month by about 100,000
barrels a day under an easing of sanctions by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier move in late March by the three major world
producers was unusual since Mexico, which is not a member of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, helped bring
together two feuding members of OPEC, the Saudis and the
Venezuelans, to support cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News quoted Dolores Dobarro, the deputy minister for
energy and mines in Venezuela, as saying after the announcement
Thursday, ``We are expecting other OPEC and non-OPEC producers to
join in making additional cuts at the next OPEC meeting.'' That
meeting is scheduled for June 24 in Vienna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YORKTOWN-COX &UR;  &UR; PHOTOSS U.S.S.YORKTOWNUPRIGHTONT   06-04 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YORKTOWN-COX </SLUG>
     PHOTOS SHOW, U.S.S. YORKTOWN UPRIGHT ON THE
PACIFIC FLOOR
 &HT;     By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Exactly 56 years after the epic World War II sea
battle in which she sank, the aircraft carrier U.S.S. Yorktown
reappeared Thursday in eerie, blue-tinged photographs of her
resting place on the floor of the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just fine,'' said Robert Ballard, the undersea explorer
whose remotely controlled search vessels found the sunken carrier.
``She's safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yorktown rests upright and intact, in 16,650 feet of
unusually clear water about 1,200 miles northwest of Hawaii,
Ballard said.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier, which sank on June 7, 1942, three days after the
beginning of the Battle of Midway, was first photographed May 19.
</P>
<P>
   A sonar-equipped search vessel ``swept'' a 400-square-mile area
of ocean bottom and discovered a tiny spot, only one-sixteenth of
an inch long on the screens of monitors being scanned aboard a
surface vessel by Ballard and members of his crew.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more than 1,000 photographs taken of the ship from a
remotely operated camera vehicle revealed numerous signs of the
Battle of Midway, said Ballard, who presented video and slides from
the discovery at the National Geographic Society, one of the
sponsors of his expedition.
</P>
<P>
   The photos show a gaping hole left in the ship's port side by a
torpedo, places where bombs caused her flight deck to buckle, and a
bomb hole in the flight deck near midships, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is even evidence of the fires that raged on the ship
during a pair of assaults by dive bombers from Japanese Vice
Admiral Chuichi Nagumo's carriers 200 miles away, Ballard said.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard, whose previous undersea discoveries included the cruise
ship Titanic and the German battleship Bismarck, said the ship was
located by a sonar tracking vehicle that scanned the sea floor
while being towed behind a Navy ship.
</P>
<P>
   After the tiny blip appeared on sonar images, the
self-propelled, tethered camera device was lowered to the area.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard compared this to trying to lower a penny on a string
from the top of New York's World Trade Center in a wind and placing
it on a pencil.
</P>
<P>
   The process was complicated when extreme pressures caused the
camera device's glass ballast tanks to implode with the force of
six sticks of dynamite, necessitating several days of repairs,
Ballard said.
</P>
<P>
   The camera vehicle was slowly guided toward the object that
Ballard and members of his crew suspected was the Yorktown. The
first scene transmitted back to the surface was of the carrier's
still-intact bridge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Naval historians now see the Battle of Midway as the turning
point in the war in the Pacific. Although the Japanese sank the
Yorktown and a U.S. destroyer, the Hammann, they lost four of their
own carriers. More than 2,400 men were rescued from the Yorktown,
which lay in the water for three days after the battle, then rolled
over and sank.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, dive bombers from the Yorktown participated in a
devastating five-minute attack on three Japanese carriers, the
Akagi, the Kaga and the Soryu, at almost the precise moment
Japanese dive bombers, fighters and torpedo planes were attacking
the Yorktown in the first two assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors from the Japanese carriers joined Yorktown survivor
Bill Surgi, now of Rockville, Md., as consultants on Ballard's
research vessel. During repairs to the camera vehicle, sonar sweeps
were made of areas where the Japanese carriers were thought to have
sunk, but without success, Ballard said.
</P>
<P>
   Surgi presented small plastic foam cups to the Navy and Newport
News Shipbulding Co. to commemorate the finding of the carrier. The
cups, which normally hold eight fluid ounces, had been attached to
the outside of the tethered camera submersible, Surgi explained,
and sea pressure at nearly 17,000 feet had compressed them to about
the size of one-ounce shot glasses.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, three raw eggs attached to the
camera vehicle returned to the surface, uncracked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had them scrambled for breakfast the next day on an English
muffin,'' said Surgi, ``my last meal from the Yorktown.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Surgi and other members of the carrier's crew
recalled the bedlam of battle that ended the Yorktown's career in
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Wetherington of Dover, Fla., was a member of the ship's
fighter squadron, assigned to manually push fighters into position
to take off and pull them off the flight deck when they had landed.
</P>
<P>
   During battle, his job changed to loader for an anti-aircraft
gunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a dead-eye shot,'' Wetherington recalled, ``and
whenever he hit one of those Japanese planes, he's scream like a
banshee.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetherington, 79, said he heard only one order during the two
assaults on the ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was drilled in their jobs and they did them without
even thinking,'' he recalled. The order was ``abandon ship.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgi, 84, said his job during battle was to fight fires.
Holding his fire hose, he said, he saw a plane drop a bomb which
seemed to fall directly toward him.
</P>
<P>
   ~``I ducked and braced myself,'' he said. ``This metal helmet
I'm holding now saved my life, but my left arm was broken.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ship was abandoned, Surgi said he had trouble swimming
with only one arm, and when one of the Yorktown's destroyers
lowered cargo nets over the side for members of the carrier crew to
climb up, he was unable to climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just held on and they pulled me up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The last F-47 ``Wildcat'' fighter to leave the Yorktown deck was
piloted by John Adams, now of Perdido Key, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get it started to leave with my group,'' he said.
``I sat there on the deck with the attack under way and finally got
started and took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I was launched I saw two Japanese torpedo planes
approaching the ship. I couldn't turn sharply enough to fire on the
first, but I got the second one. The first one got its torpedo into
the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. fighters, torpedo planes and dive bombers could not
return to the Yorktown because of damage inflicted by Japanese
planes, and they landed on either the Hornet or the Enterprise, its
sister ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we abandoned ship, a lot of the guys were taking their
shoes off, but I just couldn't see getting in that water
barefooted,'' said Glenn Capps, now of Milton, Fla., ``so I kept
mine on.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem came when he tried to climb the cargo net onto a
nearby destroyer and had trouble getting footholds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I got near the top and suddenly a felt a grip like a
vise on my wrist. I'll never forget the feeling of that grip. I
didn't even see his face. He was reaching back for the next guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The bomb hole located by Ballard's camera could have been the
same one that exploded near a gun mount near midships and killed 12
of 21 crewmen.
</P>
<P>
   Among the survivors was Ray Scates of Spartanburg, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wounded pretty bad,'' he recalled. ``I had six teeth
knocked out and I've still got shrapnel in my head from it that
I'll take to my grave. That was in the first assault. They gave us
morphine and we fought again that afternoon. Later I had over a
hundred stitches in my belly.''
</P>
<P>
   Scates had lied about his age to get into the Navy. When the
Yorktown sank, he was 15 years old.
</P>
<P>
   William Leonard, who grew up in an Army family, attended the
U.S. Naval Academy and became a pilot.
</P>
<P>
   He retired from the Navy in 1971, a rear admiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a nice stainless steel sword down there somewhere, if
Dr. Ballard wants to retrieve it,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
