<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-DRUG-TESTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULE WOULD REQUIRE HOUSE MEMBERS TO TAKE RANDOM DRUG TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of the House of Representatives and their
staffers would be required to submit to random drug tests under a
proposal introduced Thursday by Reps. Gerald B.H. Solomon, R-N.Y.,
and Joe Barton, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal calls for the tests to be randomly administered
four to six times a year, using urine or hair analysis, according
to Solomon. The test results would be published every two years.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, who predicted the House would approve the rule next
week, said the program would not test for alcohol, which _ unlike
drugs _ is legal.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon added that he'd like to extend random drug testing to
state, county and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   The House had approved a similar drug test program last year but
it later fell victim to a parliamentary snarl.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo., has opposed
the drug-testing policy, arguing that there isn't any need for a
House-wide mandate and that members can test themselves and their
staffers if they want to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Civil liberties advocates have raised questins about the
practice, saying it violates the Fourth Amendment of the
Constitution which prohibits random searches and seizures. Courts
have held that a drug test is a search.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government isn't allowed to search your body or belongings
without good reason,'' said Arthur Spitzer, legal director of the
Washington chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union. ``Random
testing is the opposite of having a good reason. I would hope that
most members of Congress would care enough about the Bill of Rights
that they would not act so quickly to ignore it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Barton said he is convinced that the drug testing would
withstand legal scrutiny. He cited a recent Gallup poll showing 87
percent of Americans support drug testing for members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Courts have approved random drug testing for police officers who
carry guns, air traffic controllers and railroad engineers, but not
for ordinary government employees. Mandatory drug testing already
exists for the military and for White House personel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be one case where the House of Representatives is
catching up to the Clinton administration,'' Barton said. ``It's an
absolute proven winner if you want to have a drug-free work
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1852EDT &QL; 
