<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWMEDIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST NEW MEDIA INVESTS IN TWO FIRMS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Hearst Corporation announced Thursday that it has
made an investment in E Ink Corp., a developer of electronic
displays based on an ``electronic ink'' that can be printed onto
paper and other flexible surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic ink, developed at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology's Media Lab, could lead to the creation of electronic
books, newspapers and magazines, according to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic ink technology allows high-resolution text and images
to be displayed in color or black-and-white. A publication using
electronic ink essentially typesets itself, receiving the text and
images either over-the-air or through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Because the information is in electronic form, it can be
continuously updated and easily manipulated, according to the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, this novel technology could dramatically change
the way we publish and distribute our books, magazines and
newspapers,'' said Kenneth A. Bronfin, Hearst New Media &AMP;
Technology senior vice president and deputy group head. ``We look
forward to collaborating with E Ink as they develop this innovation
into products that consumers will want and need.''
</P>
<P>
   Other investors in E Ink include Motorola, Inc. and the
Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst also announced that it has invested in Exodus
Communications Inc., a leading provider of Internet services to
companies using the Internet as a critical part of their
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which hosts HomeArts (http://homearts.com) and
other Hearst Web sites, recently placed No. 12 in the Los Angeles
Times 100, a listing of California companies ranked by largest
increase in one-year sales revenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
