<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4612 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YORKTOWN-SURVIVORS-CO     06-04 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YORKTOWN-SURVIVORS-CO </SLUG>
   $ADV06  YORKTOWN SURVIVORS RECALL
BATTLE THAT SUNK CARRIER
 &HT;     Eds: For release Saturday, June 6. The spot story COX-YORKTOWN,
which moved Thursday, is remain usable as a sidebar.
 &HT;     By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While ocean explorers from the National Geographic
Society were presenting a remote-control video tour of the American
aircraft carrier U.S.S. Yorktown this week, survivors of the ship
toured their memories of the bedlam of a major sea battle.
</P>
<P>
   Although she was sunk by Japanese bombs and torpedoes, the
Yorktown's own planes participated in a fatal strike against three
Japanese carriers in the Battle of Midway in June 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's loss of those carriers and a fourth, which was sunk the
following day, marked the turning point in the war in the Pacific,
naval historians say.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. carriers Enterprise and Hornet, survived the sea
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Surgi, an airplane mechanic on the Yorktown, accompanied
Robert Ballard, the ocean explorer who previously located the
Titanic and the German battleship Bismarck, when he found the
Yorktown in 16,650 feet of water 1,200 miles northwest of Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Surgi, now 84, said his job during battle was to fight fires. He
was holding his fire hose, he said, when he saw a plane drop a bomb
which seemed to fall directly toward him.
</P>
<P>
   ~``I ducked and braced myself,'' he said. ``This metal helmet
I'm holding now saved my life, but my left arm was broken.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ship was abandoned, Surgi said he had trouble swimming
with only one arm, but managed.
</P>
<P>
   ``An officer told me to get rid of this helmet because it would
sink me,'' he said. ``I looked back at the Yorktown and realized
this was the only thing I had from that ship. I decided to keep
it.''
</P>
<P>
   When one of the Yorktown's destroyer escorts lowered cargo nets
over the side for members of the carrier crew, Surgi said, he was
unable to climb because of the broken arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just held on and they pulled me up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Wetherington of Dover, Fla., was a member of the ship's
fighter squadron, assigned to manually push fighter planes into
position to take off and pull them off the flight deck after they
had landed.
</P>
<P>
   During battle, his job changed to loader for an anti-aircraft
gunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a dead-eye shot,'' recalled Wetherington, 79, ``and
whenever he hit one of those Japanese planes, he's scream like a
banshee. All this time, our destroyers were circling us like
hornets, trying to protect that carrier.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetherington said he heard only one order during the two
assaults on the ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was drilled in their jobs and they did them without
even thinking,'' he recalled. The order he heard was ``abandon
ship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `Oh, (expression of consternation),' because
that was a big pond out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The last F-47 Wildcat fighter to leave the Yorktown deck was
piloted by John Adams, now of Perdido Key, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get it started to leave with my group,'' he said.
``I sat there on the deck with the attack under way and finally got
started and took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I was launched I saw two Japanese torpedo planes
approaching the ship. I couldn't turn sharply enough to fire on the
first, but I got the second one. The first one got its torpedo into
the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. fighters, torpedo planes and dive bombers could not
return to the Yorktown because of damage inflicted by Japanese
planes and landed on either the Hornet or the Enterprise, its
sister ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we abandoned ship, a lot of the guys were taking their
shoes off, but I just couldn't see getting in that water
barefooted,'' said Glenn Capps, now of Milton, Fla., ``so I kept
mine on.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem came when he tried to climb the cargo net onto a
nearby destroyer and had trouble getting footholds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I got near the top and suddenly a felt a grip like a
vise on my wrist. I'll never forget the feeling of that grip. I
didn't even see his face. He was reaching back for the next guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The bomb hole located by Ballard's camera could have been the
same one that exploded near a gun mount near midships and killed 12
crewmen.
</P>
<P>
   Among the survivors was Ray Scates of Spartanburg, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wounded pretty bad,'' he recalled. ``I had six teeth
knocked out and I've still got shrapnel in my head from it that
I'll take to my grave. That was in the first assault. They gave us
morphine and we fought again that afternoon. Later I had over a
hundred stitches in my belly.''
</P>
<P>
   Scates had lied about his age to get into the Navy. When the
Yorktown sank, he was 15 years old.
</P>
<P>
   William Leonard, who grew up in an Army family, attended the
U.S. Naval Academy and became a pilot.
</P>
<P>
   He retired from the Navy in 1971 as a rear admiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a nice stainless steel sword down there somewhere, if
Dr. Ballard wants to retrieve it,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Although its commander had feared the Yorktown would sink, she
was still afloat the following day.
</P>
<P>
   A salvage party was sent back, aboard the destroyer Hammann, to
recover the dead and try to right the ship. However, a Japanese
submarine got through the stricken carrier's defenses and fired
four torpedoes.
</P>
<P>
   One was a miss.
</P>
<P>
   Two hit the Yorktown and the third hit the Hammann, which was
tied alongside the carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherington, a member of the salvage party, heard the
abandon-ship order again.
</P>
<P>
   The Hammann sank rapidly. Loaded with depth charges that were
set to detonate at 50 feet, it exploded under water.
</P>
<P>
   The Yorktown continue to float, but she was now fatally hit.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, 1942, she rolled over and sank, never to be seen
again until Ballard's remote cameras found her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
