<SLUG> BC-FROG-DEFORMITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5-LEGGED TEXAS FROG MAILED TO CALIFORNIA FOR STUDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif. and Minn.) 
 
By CINDY HORSWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSS HILL, Texas _ Less than an inch in length, the brown frog
was so tiny that Matt Whitbeck ordinarily would have paid scant
attention.
</P>
<P>
   But something about the way the critter was maneuvering _ more
like a spider _ caused Whitbeck, a biological technician, to take a
second look.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the strange gait? The frog has five working legs.
</P>
<P>
   Whitbeck, a biological technician with the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service, found it last month as he was posting a sign to
mark the perimeter of a wildlife refuge along the Trinity River
near this Liberty County town in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Spring Peeper, whose scientific name is ``pseudacris
crucifer,'' had the traditional two hindlegs but three forelimbs.
</P>
<P>
   Known for its night crooning, such frogs are a common species in
Texas. But because of its extra limb, this particular frog may help
solve a biological mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists started tracking such malformed frogs about five
years ago. Research is starting to indicate that such deformities
may not be the result of genetic disorders, but rather birth
defects caused by exposures to something in the environment _
possibly agriculture chemicals, said Dr. David Gardiner, a
molecular biologist at the University of California in Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   The frog from the Trinity River Wildlife Refuge was shipped
Tuesday to his research center where it will be studied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It arrived by Fed-Ex in a jar and is still alive,'' Gardiner
said. ``Most specimens don't survive very long because of their
deformities _ not just the extra limbs but other disorders that
aren't as obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first live one I've had to study,'' he added.
``Everybody's coming in to look at it. It's like a pet. We're still
working on a name.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the first deformed frog found in the Houston area and
reported to the North American Reporting Center for Amphibian
Malformations.
</P>
<P>
   The center started keeping records a few years ago after
clusters of malformed frogs started appearing in northern states,
such as Minnesota, and several Canadian provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Marcus, manager of the Trinity River Wildlife Refuge, is
aware of only two other malformed frogs that have been found
recently in Texas. Only one of those is listed on the North
American reporting center's Internet site _ a bullfrog with an
extra limb found in a pond by some children in Burleson County in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the 1960s, another unexplained group of frog
deformities was recorded in several counties in Texas. The cause of
those deformities was never determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's odd to see this sort of thing,'' Marcus said. ``Some
think it might relate to pollution and the fact that frogs live
near water and can easily absorb chemicals through their skin.
These frogs may be like the canary that warns miners of gas leaks.
The frogs may be telling us that we're being endangered by
pollutants.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus so far hasn't found any more five-legged frogs on his
wildlife refuge, which consists of 4,600 forested acres along the
Trinity River about 45 minutes east of Houston. He will be keeping
a lookout, but since he manages the refuge by himself he doesn't
have time to make a search.
</P>
<P>
   In hot spots in Minnesota, the concentrations of malformed frogs
have run as high as 50 percent in some areas, Gardiner said.
</P>
<P>
   He said researchers want to know if whatever is causing
malformations in frogs may also be a threat to humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humans have the same signaling pathways that frogs do. While
humans might not grow an extra limb, our embryos may die before
birth. Frogs can survive easier because they have 3,000 embryos at
a time,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is trying to determine what kind of chemicals might
produce the deformities being found in frogs. The most common
deformity has been an extra limb, but other malformations are also
being noted, such as missing eyes, missing limbs and retained
tails.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a serious, persistent problem because of the possible
implications to human health,'' Gardiner said. ``In some areas, the
reports of malformed frogs have stopped but that's only because
there are no more frogs left there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
