   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Friday, June 5 and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, contact James Laurin at the Daily News, (818)
713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   TRUMAN-FILM-BUZZ (Los Angeles) _ A rapidly escalating crescendo
of ``buzz'' _ an indefinable sense that a movie is about to become
a blockbuster _ has overtaken Jim Carrey's ``The Truman Show,''
which opens today in 2,350 theaters nationwide. If America agrees,
it may be that once-in-a-while film that, against appearances,
somehow becomes a cultural event in tune with its time like ``Easy
Rider,'' ``Network'' and ``Forrest Gump.'' By Dave McNary.
</P>
<P>
   HEMACARE-BLOOD (Los Angeles) _ Tiny HemaCare Corp. is David to
the American Red Cross' Goliath. It has struggled over the past two
years to break the Red Cross monopoly on blood products, but to
little avail. To help turn things around, its board of directors
has hired a former Red Cross president, Bill Nicely. By Ben
Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   PANAVISION-PERELMAN (Los Angeles) _ Ronald Perelman, one of
America's richest men, completed his $600 million takeover of
Woodland Hills-based Panavision, the world leader in supplying
cameras to the motion-picture industry. By Dave McNary.
</P>
