<HEADLINE>
NOT MUCH HAS CHANGED IN `TALES OF THE CITY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome back to 28 Barbary Lane. It's been 4{ years since our
last visit, but only six weeks have passed in TV time. It is still
1977, and the stories unfolding in and around Anna Madrigal's
apartment house are as strange as ever. So are the people.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Singleton, the once naive transplant from Cleveland, is
looking for Mr. Right. So is her gay friend, Michael Tolliver. Mona
Ramsey is looking for her past. Newcomer Brian Hawkins is looking
through binoculars at the naked woman across the way. The wise and
wonderful Mrs. Madrigal is looking in her garden for some weed, if
you get my drift.
</P>
<P>
   So not too much has changed since the first ``Tales of the
City'' entertained PBS viewers in January 1994. Except that ``More
Tales of the City'' isn't airing on PBS. The juicy stuff that made
Armistead Maupin's serialized flights of fiction in the San
Francisco Chronicle a sensation in the '70s made some TV viewers
queasy in the '90s. Unappreciative of the pot smoking, the casual
cussing, the occasional nudity and the same-sex relationships in
the original ``Tales,'' a group of lawmakers-turned-critics
threatened to cut federal funding if PBS went ahead with a planned
sequel. PBS caved like the Mariners in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to Showtime, the premium-cable channel whose slogan is ``No
Limits.'' Maupin got a new home for his odd little ``family,'' and
the television audience _ at least the 15 million or so with
Showtime _ got five more hours of Maupin's enchanting stories.
</P>
<P>
   Though not entirely well acted, ``More Tales'' exerts a
maddeningly effective tug. Each of the six new installments has its
slow moments, but Maupin's stories, adapted by
</P>
<P>
   screenwriter Nicholas Wright, are just zany enough, in a David
E. Kelley sort of way, that woody performances and stony dialogue
are partly forgivable.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Linney, reprising the girl-next-door character of Mary
Ann, is the key figure _ literally and figuratively _ in ``More
Tales.'' She is somehow connected to every other player, including
the new man in her life, Burke Andrew (Colin Ferguson), who spent
three years in San Francisco but can't remember anything from the
period. The only clue to his past is a key found on him when police
discovered him unconscious in a park.
</P>
<P>
   Linney's strawberry-blonde likability transcends the low points,
providing vital links to Maupin's off-center tales of love,
treachery, friendship, murder, adultery, discovery, transsexuality,
voyeurism and disease.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Siemaszko is a treat in the role of the confused Mona
Ramsey (played by Chloe Webb in the original ``Tales''). Mona knows
she's from a strange family, but she has no idea how strange until
she meets up with Mother Mucca (Jackie Burroughs), a crusty crone
who runs a brothel in Winnemucca, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Gibson also returns as Beauchamp Day, Mary Lynn's
philandering philistine of a boss. If only he were so deliciously
despicable on ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, everything and everyone comes back to roost at
Barbary Lane under the watchful eye of Anna Madrigal (Olympia
Dukakis), whose solid-gold heart shines a warm light on Maupin's
well-imagined hope opera _ and on the likeliehood of a sequel to
the sequel: ``Further Tales of the City.''
</P>
<P>
   Armistead Maupin's More Tales of the City. Five-hour miniseries
continuing the stories of a diverse group of people living in San
Francisco in the late 1970s. Starring Laura Linney, Nina Siemaszko,
Olympia Dukakis, Thomas Gibson, William Campbell, Paul Hopkins,
Barbara Garrick, Colin Ferguson and Whip Hubley. Sunday and Monday
at 9 p.m., Showtime. Parental guideline rating: TV-MA (mature
audiences).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330, or send e-mail to:
tvguy &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
