<HEADER>
A4633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYMBELINE-THEATER-REV     06-04 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYMBELINE-THEATER-REVIEW-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CYMBELINE': MASTERFUL FAIRY TALE OF TROUBLED ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The wide world beyond the small one in which she has
always lived beckons through the fog, as tempting as it is unknown.
For Imogen, the sorely tried heroine of Shakespeare's
``Cymbeline,'' this shadowy future can't arrive quickly enough.
``O, for a horse with wings!'' she exclaims, and it's impossible
not to share her exhilaration and impatience. Yet her face suddenly
melts from ardent resolve into an expression that, for just a
second, betrays a terrified uncertainty. Anything could happen out
there, couldn't it? Anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   How can you not identify with such a scene? As portrayed with
life-clutching passion by Joanne Pearce in the Royal Shakespeare
Company's hot-and-cold interpretation of ``Cymbeline,'' at the
Opera House of the Brooklyn Academy of Music through Saturday,
Imogen embodies the ambivalence of everyone who has stood at the
crossroads of youth and adulthood. The moment when she decides to
break from her family and seek out the man she loves is what
concludes the first half of this production, and it's a glorious
testament to the questing, affirmative spirit of this strange,
crowded fairy tale of a romance.
</P>
<P>
   Imogen is right to be apprehensive, of course. Horrible things
will happen to her as, attired in men's clothing, she roams through
the wilds of Britain in the time of Caesar Augustus. She
unwittingly takes poison; dies (or seems to); is reborn; discovers
a headless corpse she believes belongs to her beloved, banished
husband, and joins the Roman troops that are warring against her
father, the British King of the play's title.
</P>
<P>
   A bit far-fetched, isn't it? Shakespeare's other resourceful,
cross-dressing heroines, like Viola and Rosalind, never had to
endure so much. Yet as long as Ms. Pearce is on stage, there's a
core of credibility to the extreme circumstances that surround her.
Never mind that her expansive gestures run to the melodramatic, or
that her throaty alto voice leans toward the declamatory. Ms.
Pearce's Imogen is perfectly in scale with the magnitude of
Shakespeare's play, exaggerated yet somehow wonderfully human.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything is on a level with Ms. Pearce's performance in
Adrian Noble's willfully mannered presentation of the second of
Shakespeare's late, troubled romances. As the artistic director of
the Royal Shakespeare Company, which concludes its five-work
repertory of performances at the academy with ``Cymbeline,'' Noble
has given himself the mandate of broadening the appeal of the
canon, of making it accessible to audiences unfamiliar with or
grown weary of their Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Cymbeline'' is mercifully without the desperate
attention-getting devices of the troupe's swanky, noisy ``Hamlet,''
directed by Matthew Warchus in the inaugural production of the
company's visit here. Noble provides a more successfully sustained
point of view, for sure. To make the work's unlikely, Brothers
Grimm-ish events more digestible, he places them in the context of
a severely stylized fable, both exotic and beguilingly simple.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant visual flavor, realized with flair and precision in
the set and costume designs of Anthony Ward, is Japanese. Seen
against the backdrop of an expansive cerulean sky with a hint of
menacing clouds, the emblem of a universe both benevolent and
endlessly unpredictable, the movements of the ensemble bring to
mind the iconographic postures of the Kabuki theater.
</P>
<P>
   When warriors face off in battle here, it is as Samurai
warriors. The servants in the court of Cymbeline (the busy Edward
Petherbridge, also the star of the company's ``Krapp's Last Tape'')
scurry about with the stooped stances and mincing postures of
extras in ``The Mikado.'' Cymbeline's ambitious wife (Joanna
McCallum), who unwisely goads her husband into war with Rome, plays
duplicity like a souped-up seesaw, alternating between honeyed
diplomacy and vicious eruptions of temper. And she looks like an
Asian variation on the evil queen in Disney's ``Snow White,'' a
foil to Petherbridge's subdued Cymbeline, who comes into his
majesty only in the final scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The production is winking at us a bit, it becomes clear, and
sometimes even nudging us in the ribs. Noble is deliberately
distancing his audience from the improbabilities of Shakespeare's
outlandish story (drawn in part from Boccaccio's ``Decameron''),
accenting the archetypal dimensions of many of its characters and
underscoring its mythological patterns. Yet he also asks us to be
moved by the work's deeply felt message of the redemptive powers of
forgiveness. He wants, in other words, to have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tricky balance, and sometimes the three-hour production,
which trims the folio text by roughly a thousand lines, indeed
succeeds in achieving it. Noble's reworking and streamlining of the
play's opening scene is splendid, condensing an awkward dialogue of
exposition between two courtiers into a single tale told by a
soothsayer (John Kane) around a fire, a story that elicits its
share of incredulous ``oohs'' from the listeners gathered onstage.
</P>
<P>
   As Kane mentions each of the characters who will figure in the
plot, the actors playing them stand up to cast off their identical
Zen monklike robes, assuming their roles with an infectiously eager
flourish. The implication here is irresistible: ``We're going to
tell you an incredible story,'' they seem to be saying. ``You have
to listen to it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a masterly setup, and throughout the evening Ward's
ingenious use of an immense, space-dividing white sheet proves
remarkably adroit in defining the work's many different settings,
from worldly Rome to rural Wales, while retaining the sense of an
abstract, universal myth. It's an atmosphere enhanced by Hugh
Vanstone's fluid, shifting lighting. The tone isn't always matched,
unfortunately, by that of the performances, which can veer toward
kitsch and cuteness.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYMBELINE-THEATER-REV     06-04 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYMBELINE-THEATER-REVIEW-980&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: and cuteness.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever there's a piece of coincidence-driven plot to be
explained, the actors tend to deliver it with a dizzy ``can you
believe this'' expression. And one of Shakespeare's most intriguing
villains, the Iago-like Italian nobleman Iachimo (Paul Freeman), is
portrayed as a vain, aging roue who seems incapable of causing the
damage he does. The disturbing scene in which Iachimo hovers over
the sleeping Imogen, whom he has vowed to seduce as part of a wager
with her banished husband, Posthumus (Damian Lewis), is stripped of
its sexual menace, played instead as something approaching a
vaudeville sketch.
</P>
<P>
   The trio of nobly born men living as children of nature in the
Welsh countryside (Ian Hogg, Jo Stone-Fewings and Richard Cant)
bring to mind the comically virile, gung-ho woodsmen of ``Seven
Brides for Seven Brothers.'' And the visitation of the imprisoned
Posthumus by the ghosts of his parents (David Glover and Jenifer
Armitage) and by the fate-ordering Jupiter (Ewart James Walters) is
oddly tentative, lacking clarity and power.
</P>
<P>
   There are other moments, however, when the evening's glib,
whimsical surface is torn by searing emotions. Most of these come
from Ms. Pearce, but the intense Lewis brings a haunting feeling of
irreparable injury to the scene where he is made to believe that
Imogen has betrayed him. And as Posthumus' devoted servant, Paul
Bentall brings a charmingly wry sense of wonder to the proceedings
that is the cornerstone of the play's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a godsend of a cartoon portrait of a lout from Guy
Henry, who plays Cloten, the Queen's dimwitted son and rejected
suitor to Imogen, with dazzling comic inventiveness. Deliciously
slow on the uptake and full of addled, injured pride, Henry's
Cloten brings to mind an idle, privilege-conscious aristocrat who
has spent too many nights in the company of cocaine and fawning
friends. He has some of the outrageous, daring spark of Jim Carrey
and pushes comic business to excess on more than one occasion. But
there's an oddly affecting emotional logic at the center of this
fool, and when Henry goes over the top, you happily accompany him.
</P>
<P>
   More than anyone, though, it's Ms. Pearce who gives this
``Cymbeline'' its requisite cosmic glow. No matter how absurd the
situations in which she finds herself, and that includes waking up
next to a headless corpse, her wandering Princess gives off a vital
sincerity that forestalls nervous laughter.
</P>
<P>
   You never doubt for a second that she is feeling, with every
nerve, whatever befalls her. Because she has remained wide open to
all experience, both painful and joyous, you also believe that she
has grown and learned by the evening's end. She takes us to the
play's peak of wondering acceptance of life's extravagant variety,
which the production itself never quite reaches.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CYMBELINE'
</P>
<P>
   By William Shakespeare; directed by Adrian Noble; set and
costumes by Anthony Ward; lighting by Hugh Vanstone; lighting
design re-creation by Geraint Pughe; music by Stephen Warbeck;
movement by Sue Lefton; fights by Terry King; sound by Paul
Slocombe; sound re-creation by Rebecca Watts. The Royal Shakespeare
Company presented by the Brooklyn Academy of Music, Bruce C.
Ratner, chairman of the board; Harvey Lichtenstein, president and
executive producer. At the Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   With: Edward Petherbridge (Cymbeline), Joanna McCallum (The
Queen), Joanne Pearce (Imogen), Damian Lewis (Posthumus), Paul
Freeman (Iachimo), Ian Hogg (Belarius), Jo Stone-Fewings
(Guiderius), Richard Cant (Arviragus), David Glover (Ghost),
Jenifer Armitage (Ghost), Ewart James Walters (Jupiter), Paul
Bentall (Pisanio), John Kane (Soothsayer) and Guy Henry (Cloten).
</P>
</TEXT>
