<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES FALL AFTER BRITISH INTEREST RATES RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices dropped sharply Thursday, hurt by new
signs of U.S. economic strength and a surprise increase in interest
rates by the Bank of England.
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety that Friday's May employment report from the Labor
Department might reveal further economic vitality also undermined
the bond market, where signs of a strong economy tend to elevate
fears of possible inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond fell 18/32 to a price of 104 11/32, while the
yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose to 5.82 percent,
from 5.78 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bond market has rallied quite noticeably recently because
of the exemplary inflation performance, the budget surplus, a
strong dollar, continued distress in Asia, a flight to quality from
overseas investors, and an expectation of slower economic growth in
the second quarter,'' said Donald Fine, chief market analyst at
Chase Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the market's improved tone hit a sour note today on signs
of continued buoyant consumer spending, strong factory orders and
inventories, and skittishness in front of tomorrow's labor-market
statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Factory orders rose 1.2 percent in April to near forecasts for a
1.6 percent gain, while first quarterly productivity numbers
increased dramatically to 1.1 percent from 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fine said the labor-market data due Friday will likely set the
tone for the financial markets until June 10, when Federal Reserve
Board chairman Alan Greenspan delivers his eagerly awaited
testimony to the Joint Economic Committee in Congress, which could
provide clues about the central bank's leanings on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England's unexpected decision to raise interest
rates by one-quarter point to 7.5 percent also hurt the Treasury
market by raising yields on British debt securities, making them
more competitive with Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Dennis Hynes, chief market strategist and managing
director of R.W. Pressprich &AMP; Co., a New York broker-dealer, said
he did not see the rate increase by the Bank of England having much
of an impact on the U.S. market. Hynes said the British bank tends
to be more forward-looking and pre-emptive than the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are making a statement and saying they are concerned
about inflation and asserting themselves, though it may be at the
expense of the economy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
