<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4642 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-BANKS-345&AMP;A     06-04 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-BANKS-345&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA AND FOREIGN BANKS REACH TENTATIVE AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Indonesia and a group of foreign bankers
agreed Thursday on a framework for rescheduling nearly $80 billion
in corporate and bank debt that has become one of the biggest
barriers to restarting the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
   As Indonesia plunges into a deep recession, the agreement offers
hope that its weakened currency could begin to recover, that cash
will start to flow again, that moribund companies will not be
crushed by their debts, and that Indonesia's crucial export
industries will flourish again.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent turmoil here, economic activity has come to a
virtual halt as the banking system reels from a mountain of bad
loans, interest rates have soared, lending has all but stopped and
cash has become scarce throughout the economy.
</P>
<P>
   As a framework for renegotiating debt, the unexpectedly quick
action by a group of 13 foreign banks meeting with Indonesian
officials in Frankfurt gives Indonesia the best economic news it
has received in months. It is also a boost to the new government of
President B.J. Habibie, who is struggling to assert his legitimacy
in the face of calls for an early election.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the intertwined political and economic crises _ which
seem still to be on a downward spiral _ present Indonesia with a
perilous outlook in the months ahead. On a visit to Jakarta on
Thursday, Stanley Roth, the top official for Asian affairs at the
State Department, said the most important factor in economic
recovery now would be the restoration of political stability.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's agreement focused on one of the country's most
intractable problems and offered hope that solutions are possible.
Bankers cautioned, however, that the framework is a prelude to
individual negotiations between lenders and borrowers who may
choose to use it as a guide for stretching out the repayment of
loans. ``It's not a magic pill,'' said an official at one bank
involved in the pact. Banks may opt out of certain parts and they
are free to decide which loans they will renegotiate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The pact was spearheaded by a steering committee involving the
Chase Manhattan Bank, the largest U.S. lender to Indonesian
companies, Deutsche Bank of Germany and Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi of
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   For hundreds of Indonesian companies, the framework provides a
three-year period during which they would only have to pay interest
on their loans. After that, there would be a five-year period
during which borrowers could make loan payments, presumably with
renegotiated interest rates and other terms.
</P>
<P>
   It gives banks up to four years to pay some $9 billion in debts
owed to other banks that now are generally being deferred by
informal understandings. As part of the agreement, Indonesia agreed
to pay more than $1 billion in bank debt and trade financing that
had been in arrears.
</P>
<P>
   And to jump-start trade, the pact provides for financing by
foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia also agreed to set up a new government office, the
Indonesian Debt Restructuring Agency, that will both provide
sufficient availability of dollars, German marks and Japanese yen
for repayment of foreign loans and protection against currency rate
fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   One of Indonesia's biggest problems is that its currency has
fallen to about 25 percent of the value against the dollar compared
to it value a year ago. With that weakness, borrowers have watched
their foreign loan payments skyrocket and many have found it
impossible to repay their borrowings.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia had formally halted debt repayments at the beginning
of this year, pending an agreement with international banks.
</P>
<P>
   But economists cautioned that the country's economic and
political problems are now so severe that there is little chance of
a quick turnaround. Inflation this year is expected to climb to 50
percent or more, and unemployment to as high as 20 percent. Overall
economic growth is projected to contract by at least 10 percent and
maybe as much as 20 percent. By contrast, the country's economic
growth averaged 8 percent a year for the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts said Thursday's agreement was far more
complex than previous debt rescheduling agreements reached in
Mexico in 1995 and South Korea earlier this year because of the
large number of Indonesian banks and corporations and weak
financial reporting requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Camdessus, the managing director of the International
Monetary Fund, which recently negotiated a $40 billion Indonesian
bailout, praised the bank pact for giving ``breathing space to
recover from the current crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the pact would ``have the immediate effect of relieving
the pressure on the foreign exchange market, and will help to
revive international trade and economic activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jakarta stock exchange jumped by 3.5 percent Thursday on
news of the banking agreement. But reflecting a broad
discouragement with the country's economic prospects, the
Indonesian currency, the rupiah, showed little response, remaining
at 11,550 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Strong, chief credit officer of the Chase Manhattan Bank,
which took a lead role in the talks with Indonesia, cautioned that
a recovery was still a long way off. ``It's going to be a long
process,'' he said. The banking framework is `` a very large step,
but just one step on a path that will require a lot of work on
everybody's part.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the agreement gives the banks considerable
flexibility in deciding which loans to renegotiate, which trade
financings would be extended and to which Indonesian companies.
</P>
<P>
   Under Thursday's agreement, the three-year grace period for
corporate borrowers could begin in December on interest payments.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian central bank will administer the new debt
restructuring agency that will operate like a state trust fund. In
providing risk protection and the availability of foreign exchange,
it will not subsidize exchange rates. Its role is to provide a
limited cushion against fluctuations of the rates.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials estimated Thursday that companies owing
about $60 billion would participate. The remaining $20 billion is
owed by companies that are either too damaged for rescue or are
strong enough to proceed with payments on their own.
</P>
<P>
   For Indonesian banks, the four years that may be used to repay
some $9 billion in loans, applies to borrowings due through next
March. The central bank will guarantee the repayments.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to revive the country's stagnant trade sector,
Indonesia will request international banks to make their ``best
efforts'' to maintain trade financing for one year at the levels
that existed at the end of last April. The government estimates
that such a deal could release financing for between $4 billion to
$6 billion in trade for Indonesian companies.
</P>
<P>
   Under Thursday's agreement, individual debtors and creditor
banks must proceed on their own to reach ``an amicable agreement''
on repayments, said an American banker in Jakarta. ``If the
Indonesian company still expresses its inability to repay debt, the
international bank can start bankruptcy proceedings,'' he said. But
given the eight-year window for repayments, he said he expected
such proceedings to be rare.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian government has insisted from the start that it
would not bail out bankrupt companies. Under the country's
agreement with the IMF, it has already formulated new bankruptcy
laws that are expected to be approved by Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Strong said the restructuring negotiations did not touch on any
provision for debt writeoffs. ``We hope there won't be any need for
writeoffs,'' he said. ``But that decision will be taken after banks
make an independent assessment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
