<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACT-UP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS ACTIVISTS MARCH WITH OPEN CASKET TO PROTEST CLINTON POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even in death, AIDS activist Steve Michael
protested in the same uncanny, confrontational manner he used when
he was alive.
</P>
<P>
   The former head of the Washington chapter of the AIDS Coalition
To Unleash Power (ACT UP), who died of the disease May 25 at age
42, lay in an open casket in front of the White House on Thursday
as more than 100 mourners gathered to protest President Clinton's
AIDS policies.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on Michael's final wishes, his mother Barbara Michael and
his companion Wayne Turner marched the body about half a mile down
Pennsylvania Avenue to the White House. The march, Turner said, was
to ``show the world that Bill Clinton has lied to and betrayed
people with AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame on you, Bill Clinton,'' Turner said, standing behind the
casket. ``Bill Clinton, you say feel my pain. Bill Clinton, you
have caused my pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of ACT UP accuse Clinton of backing down on promises
they say he made in the early days of his presidency to make AIDS a
top priority of the administration.
</P>
<P>
   They also attacked the president for his decision to not fund
needle-exchange programs that allow drug users to swap used needles
for clean ones.
</P>
<P>
   Although researchers concluded that the programs were effective
in curbing the spread of AIDS and did not encourage illegal drug
use, the Clinton administration banned federal funding for
needle-exchanges in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton is a murderer,'' said Ann Northrop of New York
City. ``He is a liar, and he is letting people with AIDS die on
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Northrop was Michael's running mate when he made a token bid for
the Democratic presidential nomination in 1996, campaigning in New
Hampshire against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the White House, demonstrators carried a 30-foot
effigy of Clinton dressed as the grim reaper and held up posters
showing the president with a long, Pinocchio-like nose and signs
that read, ``Clinton lies, we die.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Michael, a Los Angeles AIDS activist, said: ``Clinton
doesn't feel personally involved because no one he cares about has
died.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happened to his family, if it happened to Chelsea
(Clinton's daughter), he'd be keeping his promises,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Michael stroked and kissed her son's forehead and Turner,
35, leaned into the casket and whispered into Michael's ear. The
body was clothed in an ACT UP T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's body was returned to a funeral home after the
hour-long demonstration. The body will cremated Saturday and Turner
said he would keep the ashes at his Washington home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know. He might still have a few protests left in him
yet,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   During his lifetime, Michael chose not to lobby Congress, a
tactic used by other AIDS activists, and instead used
confrontational protests that got attention but angered those who
disagreed with his in-your-face style.
</P>
<P>
   He staged a demonstration during Clinton's last-minute Christmas
shopping spree in 1997 and yelled, ``Hey Bill! Your AIDS plan is a
sham!'' as the president left Washington's Union Station shopping
complex.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Mike McCurry called Thursday's
protest a ``dramatic action,'' but said the president ``takes very
seriously the fight against AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration has devoted considerable resources, has
called for increasing resources to be available for the fight
against this disease,'' McCurry said. ``I think the record shows
that (Clinton) has done more than any of his predecessors.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry noted that the president had called for an expedited
effort to develop an AIDS vaccine and called for Medicare and
health insurance programs to provide coverage for the disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
