<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the temperature in the town of Midland in west
Texas soared to a record 111 degrees. Meanwhile, just a few hundred
miles away at North Platte, Nebraska, the mercury could only climb
to 47 degrees, a record low maximum. The unseasonably large
contrast in temperatures revealed the footprint of a strong front
extending east to west across the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, showers and thunderstorms will erupt along and ahead of
this southward-sagging front from east Texas to Georgia and the
Carolinas. The most organized area of storms will occur in the
lower Mississippi Valley, as a low pressure zone ripples east along
the front. A few of the storms could reach severe levels, with
damaging winds and hail posing a threat. Tornadoes are possible,
though a major outbreak is unlikely. Teeming rains may produce
flash flooding in areas affected by recurrent eastward-moving
showers and thunderstorms. North of the front, pockets of rain will
dampen the lower Ohio River Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Cumulus clouds will build over northern New England after a
relatively clear morning, as air in contact with sun-warmed ground
rises into cold air aloft. Brief showers will dot the high ground
from upstate New York to northern Maine. Along the New England
coast, cool winds from the northwest will average 15 to 25 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, sunny, warm conditions will embrace the Southwest and
much of California. However, patches of fog and low clouds will
plague the coast early in the day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: STRONGEST TORNADO
</P>
<P>
   The tornado that roared through the town of Frostburg in western
Maryland Tuesday evening was the strongest to hit the state since
tornado records began to be recorded in 1950. The 15-mile long
tornado first struck near the Maryland border at Salisbury, Pa. For
most of its life, the tornado deserved a rating of F3 on the Fujita
scale, with damage consistent with wind speeds estimated between
150 and 200 mph. As the twister hit Frostburg, its rating briefly
jumped to F4, with winds of 210 mph. By convention, the overall
strength of the tornado will be listed as F4 in weather records. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
