<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-MIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE DOCKS WITH MIR FOR FINAL TIME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ American astronauts and Russian cosmonauts warmly
greeted one another aboard the Mir space station after a U.S.
shuttle crew docked Thursday for a ninth and final time.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the high-flying linkup over the Caspian Sea, the
crew of the shuttle Discovery reclaimed colleague Andy Thomas, the
last of seven Americans assigned to live and work aboard the
Russian orbital outpost since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The former Cold War rivals initiated the co-operative program to
prepare for the upcoming assembly of a new international space
station. It will be at least mid-1999 before that project is far
enough along for a reunion of the kind that unfolded Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, 46, was ecstatic over the prospect of returning to Earth
next week as his near five-month voyage draws to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot imagine how wonderful it was to look out the window
and see a bright point of light on the horizon that I knew to be
the shuttle and watch it slowly grow in size as it loomed up close
to us,'' Thomas said. ``It was really an absolutely magnificent
sight.''
</P>
<P>
   With commander Charles Precourt and pilot Dominic Gorie at the
controls, Discovery nestled into Mir's docking mechanism at 11:58
a.m., CDT, precisely as scheduled. Mir experienced none of the
steering problems that erupted prior to the shuttle's launch
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks beautiful from here, Houston, beautiful,'' Precourt
informed mission control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Masterful flying,'' acknowledged Marc Garneau, Discovery's
liaison in mission control.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, much of the drama would have been beamed to Earth by
the shuttle crew through live television. However, the video stream
was all but blacked out by a problem with the circuitry in
Discovery's high-speed communications system.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement was still evident, however, in the voices of the
astronauts and the cosmonauts as Discovery neared the outpost,
triggering an urgent exchange of greetings and range measurements
over a ship-to-ship radio frequency.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, who lack the shuttle's global satellite
communications network, managed a few brief live television views
as Discovery inched toward Mir's berthing port and of the
astronauts and cosmonauts embracing once the airtight hatches
separating the ships had swung open.
</P>
<P>
   The orbital encounter united Discovery's Precourt, Gorie, Wendy
Lawrence, Franklin Chang-Diaz, Janet Kavandi and their guest
Russian cosmonaut Valeri Ryumin with the Mir crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome, welcome,'' bellowed Mir commander Talgat Musabayev
and flight engineer Nikolai Budarin as Precourt and his crew
entered the station. ``We're glad to see you again in space. You
look good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are feeling great and glad to be here,'' Precourt assured
his hosts, offering fresh fruit, onions and large containers of
fresh water. Later, the crews celebrated with a meal together.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just my second day in space,'' gushed rookie astronaut
Kavandi. ``It's just overwhelming to be on a space station
already.''
</P>
<P>
   The two spacecraft are scheduled to stay joined until Monday,
allowing the crews to exchange several tons of food, clothing,
research equipment and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NASA's ground control teams are continuing their
efforts to re-establish the shuttle's satellite television link to
the ground. More than pictures are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The link is also needed by the ground-based research teams
working with the experimental physics observatory aboard Discovery
called the Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer.
</P>
<P>
   The observatory was developed to search for evidence of cosmic
anti-matter aboard the new space station. The Discovery flight was
an opportunity to test its operation.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers had planned to use the shuttle's frequency as a
two-way link to allow them to adjust the spectrometer's electronics
before making 100 hours of test observations.
</P>
<P>
   Repairs by the shuttle crew earlier in the flight had permitted
about one hour of ground transmissions through brief passes over
ground stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our real problem is that we are still baffled by what our real
problem is,'' said NASA flight director Paul Dye, who is attempting
to coordinate a repair plan.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery is scheduled to return to Earth on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
