<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4661 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTORNEY-CLIENT-PRIVI     06-04 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTORNEY-CLIENT-PRIVILEGE-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES DEATH END THE BOND OF SECRECY BETWEEN LAWYER AND CLIENT? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: RESENDING to note Sunday release date in slug.)  
 (For release Sunday, June 7)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Does the attorney-client privilege of
confidentiality die with the client?
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court will take up that question Monday as it hears
arguments from lawyers for Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and
attorneys representing the lawyer of the late Vincent Foster Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a boyhood friend of President Clinton and a Little Rock
law partner of First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, came to
Washington in 1993 to join the new administration as deputy White
House counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Within months of his arrival, Foster was embroiled in a
controversy surrounding the White House travel office.
</P>
<P>
   Republican critics charged that Mrs. Clinton had ordered the
firings of seven employees of the travel office in May 1993 in
order to make room for friends of the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said she had no role in the dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   In personal notes written at the time, Foster worried that
administration officials would face a congressional inquiry and
possibly a criminal probe of the firings. He expressed concern that
Mrs. Clinton's role would be misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   On July 11, Foster consulted his lawyer, James Hamilton, about
what he should do. During their two-hour meeting Hamilton took
three pages of notes.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days later, worried about the travel office controversy,
charges about Whitewater land deals and the hostile political
atmosphere in Washington, Foster drove to Fort Marcy Park in nearby
Virginia and shot himself to death.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Starr, investigating allegations that Mrs.
Clinton lied about her role in the travel office firings,
subpoenaed Hamilton's notes.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Washington rejected the subpoena, but in
August 1997 the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
ruled in a 2-to-1 decision that after a client's death, the
attorney-client privilege was no longer automatic in criminal
cases. The panel said that in some cases, such as Starr's, a
prosecutor's search for truth outweighed a dead client's interest
in confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court agreed to hear the case after Hamilton argued
that the attorney-client privilege lives on even though the client
is dead.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of this bitter legal dispute could affect how
thousands of Americans consult with lawyers in their final years.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief to the Supreme Court, Starr said Hamilton's notes
were ``highly relevant'' to his office's investigation of whether
Mrs. Clinton or presidential aides lied about the her role in the
travel office firings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no dispute that Mr. Foster would have been an
important witness in this office's investigation of whether
particular individuals made false statements or committed other
federal crimes during investigations of the travel office
firings,'' the brief said.
</P>
<P>
   Some constitutional law experts said that if Starr prevails, the
attorney-client privilege will be eroded, making people reluctant
to tell their lawyers the truth.
</P>
<P>
   David Luban, a law professor at Georgetown University here,
said, ``The whole reason we have an attorney-client privilege is to
encourage clients to be truthful, because they believe what they
say will be kept private.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the court says that privilege ends after death, there will
be many people, particularly the elderly and sick, who will not
feel safe being totally honest with their lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rice, an expert on attorney-client privilege at American
University in Washington, said the appeals court's decision assumes
that people no longer care about their reputation after they die.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the case, why do prominent people often request that
their personal papers and diaries not be released until 10n or 20
years after their death?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   In his Supreme Court appeal, Hamilton argued that the appeals
court's decision ``defeats the fundamental purpose of the
privilege, which is to encourage full and frank communication
between attorneys and clients.'' His brief added that without the
assurance that their conversations would remain private, Foster
``would not have confided in Mr. Hamilton and the notes at issue
would not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Q. Barrett, a former Iran-Contra prosecutor who now
teaches law at St. John's University in New York, said the
interests of law enforcement cannot be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are extraordinary circumstances where the interest of
law enforcement carries more weight and can override the
attorney-client privilege without destroying the reasons why we
have the privilege in the first place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The perjury allegations against the first lady were sparked in
1996 by the discovery of a memo suggesting that former White House
official David Watkins had lied about Mrs. Clinton's role in the
firing.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins originally told the General Accounting Office, a key
investigative arm of Congress, that Mrs. Clinton played no role in
the dismissals. But in a memo to then-White House Chief of Staff
Thomas F. McLarty, Watkins wrote that the travel staff had been
sacked after ``pressure for action from the First Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court was originally scheduled to hear the case this
fall, with a decision expected at the earliest in December. But in
April, Starr convinced the justices that waiting until the end of
the year would unduly delay his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The court is expected to rule on the case by early July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
