<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4664 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AWESOME-CRUISESHIPS-A     06-04 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AWESOME-CRUISESHIPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGER AND BETTER SHIPS ENERGIZING CRUISE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Italy _ The Grand Princess _ twice the size of the
Titanic _ sailed into port on Sunday night and seemed to eclipse
even the cupola of St. Mark's Cathedral. As passengers spilled out
to inspect the canals of Venice, most of Venice stared, awestruck,
at the world's largest cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the newest and the biggest,'' Marguerite Salomone of
Monterey, Calif., said, explaining why she and her husband,
Alfonso, had signed up a year ahead for a 12-day Mediterranean
cruise on an untested ship carrying 2,600 passengers. ``Anything
new is always better.'' She paused. Then, looking at the
quarter-mile walk to the elevator, she added, ``I'm not sure bigger
is better, though.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is exactly what Princess Cruises' parent company, the
Peninsular &AMP; Oriental Steam Navigation Co. of Britain, is betting
on.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;O has ordered two sister ships for the Grand Princess, which
will also be able to carry 109,000 gross tons, from the Italian
shipbuilding company Fincantieri. One of P&AMP;O's chief rivals, Royal
Caribbean, plans to launch two even larger ships next year that
will each carry 136,000 tons and accommodate 3,100 passengers.
Until the launching of the Grand Princess, the biggest cruise ship
ever built had a carrying capacity of 101,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has also ordered two huge cruise ships from Fincantieri,
whose shipyards are so busy that deliveries were delayed this
March, forcing Disney to cancel all its cruises for four months and
offer refunds to about 90,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise industry, boosted first by the hit television show
``The Love Boat'' and more recently by the movie ``Titanic,'' has
calculated that bigger ships provide economies of scale. And it
thinks it can draw in more passengers with ever more varied and
baroque forms of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Princess, which cost $450 million and is 50 feet
taller than the Statue of Liberty, has three grand dining rooms,
seven casual restaurants and cafes and 12 bars.
</P>
<P>
   It has three theaters offering a dizzying mix of cabaret and Las
Vegas-style variety shows and comedy acts (Alan King and Red
Buttons were the headliners for the maiden trip), a discotheque
with a glass skywalk, a casino, four swimming pools, miniature golf
and a game room with virtual-reality rides, including deep-sea
exploration.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a kind of virtual-reality medical unit, with
satellite hookups that allow ships' doctors to consult specialists
at Cedar Sinai Hospital in Los Angeles. There is also a wedding
chapel, which also offers a ``vows renewal'' service. There are no
provisions for burials at sea, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Princess is less a ship than a floating amusement
park; the strongest hint that it is a descendant of the old stately
ocean liners are the rarely used shuffleboard sets on a few of its
18 decks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the passengers are repeat customers lured by novel
amenities, not by Leonardo Di Caprio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients signed up long before the movie came out, and have
been on Princess cruises before,'' Stephanie Woods, 28, an
assistant cruise director, said. ``But you can tell they have seen
the movie: they pay more attention during the safety drills.'' (The
Grand Princess, unlike the Titanic, has enough lifeboats to
accommodate passengers and crew.)
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled maiden voyage of the Grand Princess, leaving from
Southampton, England, on May 14, was canceled at the last minute
when P&AMP;O decided some of the fixtures and fittings were not up to
standard, and offered refunds to passengers who paid between $4,000
to $10,000 each. Company directors were haunted by the public
relations disaster that afflicted Cunard when the QE2 began its
first cruise of the 1994 season before refitting work was
completed. QE2 passengers complained of exploding toilets and brown
water.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers who left Istanbul on May 26 on the Grand Princess,
and made stops in Turkey, Greece and Italy (the cruise ends in
Barcelona on June 6), reported some glitches, like dripping
air-conditioners and malfunctioning laundromats, but there were few
deep-felt complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, passengers acted like old hands lending their experience
to a virgin ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food isn't quite up to par yet,'' Bernice Mehrbrodt, 67,
of Santa Barbara, Calif., confided as she inspected the menu in the
500-seat Leonardo da Vinci restaurant, decorated with frescos of
Madonnas. ``But it's the first time out, and there are always a few
kinks. We're having a wonderful time.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband paid $8,500 for their cruise package,
including meals and shows. Passengers pay extra for their alcohol,
onshore excursions and such niceties as massages and spa
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Four cruise veterans who were admiring the roofs of Venice from
a glassed-in nook of the discotheque compared notes on past and
present voyages.
</P>
<P>
   John Clark of Toronto sailed on the German liner the Bremen in
1932 and shared a dining-room table with the King of Saudi Arabia
aboard the Spanish liner Queen Anna Maria in 1966. He expressed
some scorn for the more middle-class cruises prevalent today. ``I
am 92,'' he explained grumpily. ``The only trip that will take me
is a cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   His companions were more impressed by the world's biggest cruise
ship, but also expressed some wistfulness of scale. ``I'm glad we
came,'' said Jacqueline Smith, 74, of Fort Worth, Texas. ``I'm
having the best time I've ever had. But secretly, I think I like
the smaller ships better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
