<HEADER>
A4669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLDER-WOMEN-DRUGS-625     06-04 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDER-WOMEN-DRUGS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALCOHOL, DRUG ABUSE A PROBLEM FOR MILLIONS OF OLDER WOMEN, REPORT
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Fla., Minn.)  (th) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When her husband died, leaving her a widow at the age of 77, Dr.
Genevieve May started drinking to assuage her grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't get up in the morning,'' she said. ``I realized I
was using alcohol to raise my spirits. It raises your spirits for a
little while, and then you become depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   At 83, Dr. May, a California psychiatrist, checked into the
Betty Ford Center in Rancho Mirage, Calif., to be treated for
alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   Now 88 and sober for five years, Dr. May understands how a
vulnerable older woman can easily succumb to addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``With people dying around you, you feel more lonely and
isolated,'' she said. ``One tolerates alcohol less as one ages, and
then you have this extra stress of loss.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1.8 million American women 60 years and older abuse
alcohol, and 2.8 million women abuse psychoactive or mood-altering
prescription drugs, says a report released Thursday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by the National Center on Addiction and Substance
Abuse at Columbia University in New York City, calls the levels of
such abuse a hidden epidemic among the country's 25.6 million women
60 years and older.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the report, which draws on national surveys and interviews
with 400 doctors, said that of 1.8 million older women with alcohol
problems, barely 11,000 are currently in treatment programs.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not give comparable statistics for older men. But
other studies have found alcohol abuse somewhat more common among
men than women, whose heavy drinking is more likely to go unnoticed
because they tend to do it alone. Older women also have more access
to prescription drugs and are more likely than men to overuse them
or combine them with alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, titled ``Under The Rug: Substance Abuse
and the Mature Woman,'' research suggests that older women can
recover more successfully than younger ones who abuse drug or
alcohol. But most older women are also ashamed to seek treatment,
their children are hesitant to confront them and doctors sometimes
mistake their addiction for other ailments like Alzheimer's disease
or depression, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Ford, the former first lady who went public with her own
problems with alcohol and painkillers after leaving the White House
over two decades ago, said doctors tended to pass over such
conditions ``and move on to more medical stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they find it hard to spend the time on it,'' Mrs. Ford
said in a telephone interview from Washington. ``It can be rather
time-consuming with a patient unless they know how to detect it.''
</P>
<P>
   A report by the Center for Substance Abuse Treatment, part of
the Department of Health and Human Services, cited age
discrimination as another factor. The report said: ``There is an
unspoken but pervasive assumption that it's not worth treating
older adults for substance-use disorders. Behavior considered a
problem in younger adults does not inspire the same urgency for
care among older adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Egan, director of services for older adults at the
nonprofit Hanley Hazelden Center in West Palm Beach, Fla., put it
this way: ``We don't tend to serve our older adults in this country
_ we put them out to pasture. We say, `Mom's earned the right to
sit home and get zonked at 4 o'clock in the afternoon.'''
</P>
<P>
   The National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse found that
women who saw a doctor were 37 percent likelier than men to get a
prescription for a tranquilizer and 33 percent likelier to get a
prescription for an antidepressant.
</P>
<P>
   The center said that women 60 years or older took an average of
five prescription drugs at the same time and that 1 in 4 older
women, or 6.4 million Americans, used at least one psychoactive
prescription drug. The effects of such drugs are intensified by
alcohol.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The abuse embraces a pharmacopeia of tranquilizers, sedatives,
antidepressants and pain-relievers. Mrs. Egan, of the West Palm
Beach center, points out that so many drugs can leave older
patients lethargic, disoriented and addicted. But, she said,
``their most common statement is, `But the doctor prescribed it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Hassett, 57 and a trustee for the Hazelden Foundation, a
national nonprofit network of treatment and prevention centers,
said she saw women of her generation struggle with feelings of
shame about admitting their addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a different structure growing up than young people
today, so it's very difficult for older people,'' explained Mrs.
Hassett, a former public relations executive from New York who said
she had been sober for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Many older women also feel uncomfortable in programs that deal
with drugs like heroin or crack cocaine. The Columbia center's
report said that only 3.8 percent of the older women surveyed had
tried an illegal drug and that none used them now.
</P>
<P>
   Mary, a 74-year-old Minnesotan who did not want to be identified
by her full name, said she began drinking after her husband died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I saw the light, I didn't think it was a problem,'' she
said. ``After realizing what I'd done to myself and my family, I
realized it was a very big problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Her children persuaded her to enter treatment, where group
therapy sessions were dominated by younger drug abusers.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my stupidity, I would say, `What is crack?''' Mary said.
``I had difficulty relating to the younger people, not that they
didn't have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   She relapsed four times until finding the Hazelden program for
older adults, where, she said, ``We could relate to one another's
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary, who said she had been abstinent for 20 months, credited
her three children for their support: ``I said to them, `Thank
goodness you didn't give up on your mom.' They could have said, `To
heck with her.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
