<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DUAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WOMAN PART OF GROUP TO CLAIM DUAL CITIZENSHIP IN MEXICO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Maria Jimenez of Texas and 99 other people
reclaimed their Mexican birthright Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But for Jimenez and others, the ceremony in an inner courtyard
of the ornate National Palace marked a milestone rather than a
realization of their dreams of dual citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a voice but not a vote,'' said Jimenez, a native of
the border state of Coahuila who became a U.S. citizen and is the
Houston director of the American Friends Service Committee, a
Quaker civil rights organization. ``(But) for those of us who have
been struggling for dual citizenship, this is a step forward.``
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo presided over the ceremony, which put
the official seal on a newly enacted program bestowing
``nationality'' on Mexicans living abroad who have become citizens
of other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans, welcome to your homeland,'' Zedillo told the group,
which also included Mario Molina, a Mexico City-born U.S. citizen
who won the Nobel Prize in chemistry in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I congratulate all of you because these documents return, from
a legal point of view, something that each of you has kept intact
in your heart, at times for many years: the will to be Mexicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a law enacted in March, Mexicans who become citizens of
other countries can retain their Mexican nationality, holding on to
inheritance, property and other rights.
</P>
<P>
   The recovered nationality does not bestow the benefits of
citizenship. Those with dual nationality won't be able to vote in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Only 3,738 people, most of them in the United States, had filed
to reclaim their Mexican nationality from the time the program
started in March until the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   Some proponents have said that the recognition of their dual
nationality would allow Mexicans to become politically active
citizens in the United States and other countries without
permanently abandoning Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this, we free the consciences of millions of countrymen
who flatly refuse to obtain the citizenship of the United States in
order not to betray Mexico,'' Jose Chapa, a 78-year-old radio
journalist from Chicago who initiated the push for dual nationality
a decade ago, said in a speech at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can leave this political limbo and be actors in our own
destinies with the power to vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Mexican government had given us this constitutional
instrument before the anti-immigrant, xenophobic and racist wave in
California, I don't think the Pete Wilsons and Pat Buchanans would
have done us so much damage.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the issue that worries many in the United States
concerned about the huge influx of Mexican immigrants in recent
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Although scores of nations recognized dual nationality, critics
say the status for Mexicans living in the United States will
further slow their assimilation into U.S. society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worse possible time to introduce this question of
divided loyalties into the equation,'' said K.C. McAlpin, a
Houstonian working at The Federation for American Immigration
Reform, or FAIR, a Washington, D.C., group intent on limiting
immigration into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It raises unnecessary and dangerous questions that should not
exist in the minds of many Americans (about) the allegiance of
citizens of Mexican origin,'' he said. ``Citizenship in any
sovereign country should mean commitment to that country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jimenez, Chapa and others quickly point to the military
records of many Mexican Americans _ which include a
disproportionate number of Medals of Honor _ when challenged about
their loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   And they argue that, at a time when Mexico and the United States
are moving closer together economically, Mexicans who are U.S.
citizens can play an influential role south as well as north of the
Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Molina, who teaches chemistry at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, told Zedillo and other Mexican officials at Thursday's
ceremony that he intends to form an international commission to
seek solutions to Mexico City's deadly air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I express my faith in truth and science and my conviction that
my colleagues and I can make a useful contribution,'' Molina said.
``I reiterate that my personal efforts will only be guided by a
commitment to give Mexico my best effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government has traditionally been reluctant to
accept international advice or help in dealing with ecological
crises or natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Congress may consider granting voting rights to
Mexican citizens living in the United States. Absentee balloting
could dramatically influence the direction of Mexico's fledgling
democracy. Opposition candidates in recent years have campaigned in
Mexican communities throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience,'' Jimenez said, ``is that Mexicans (in the
United States), are very critical of their (Mexican) society and
their government because they know the reality of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
