<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-COX &UR;  &UR; SU     06-04 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-COX </SLUG>
     SUPREME COURT DENIES STARR'S REQUEST FOR
SPEEDY RULING ON PRIVILEGE
 &HT;     By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a victory for President Clinton, the Supreme
Court on Thursday denied independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
request for a speedy ruling on whether a White House attorney and
U.S. Secret Service agents can be forced to testify in Starr's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The order sends Starr's request back to the U.S. Court of
Appeals in Washington and into a legal process analysts said could
take up to a year to complete.
</P>
<P>
   However, the analysts said the order could also prompt Starr to
provide an impeachment report to Congress sooner than he might
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The White House quickly applauded the Supreme Court decision,
and used the occasion to intensify its public relations offensive
against Starr's probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is ... Day 1,400 of Ken Starr's tenure as an independent
counsel, at the rate of $30,000 a day of taxpayers' money,'' said
spokesman Michael McCurry. ``It's long past time for this thing to
be over and done with.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office responded with a terse prepared statement, saying
he would proceed with his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is seeking the testimony of Secret Service agents and
Clinton's closest legal counselor, Bruce Lindsey, in his
investigation of whether Clinton had an affair with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky and then urged her and others to lie
about it under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has denied the charges, which have dogged his presidency
since they surfaced in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's Supreme Court order presents Starr with a dilemma:
whether to wait for his request to work its way through the appeals
process and hope for a favorable ruling, or to simply proceed with
his case without the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The latter approach would focus Starr's spotlight once again on
Lewinsky, who has tried unsuccessfully to strike a deal under which
she would offer limited testimony in exchange for immunity from
prosecution for perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky has testified under oath that she had no affair with
Clinton, contradicting her widely reported taped conversations
about their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has always been the single most important witness in this
case, from day one, and what the Starr office has been trying to do
is to build a case without her, just in case they didn't get her
testimony,'' said former associate independent counsel Bruce E.
Yannett, a partner with the New York law firm Debevoise and
Plimpton.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Thursday's order on attorney and Secret Service
privilege, Yannett said, ``it is likely the Starr office will
proceed without this evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, Yannett said, Starr could turn over his evidence in
the weeks or months ahead to a congressional panel, which would
then evaluate the strength of the evidence to determine whether to
convene impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling capped a frenzied week of legal action in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the White House dropped its assertion that national
security interests entitled the administration to withhold certain
testimony behind the legal shield of ``executive privilege.''
Experts had said the Supreme Court might agree to take up this
question quickly.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers maintained, however, that Lindsey's
conversations with the president were protected from investigatory
scrutiny by attorney-client privilege, a long-established tenet
aimed at ensuring the confidentiality of communications between
lawyers and their clients.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey asserted such protection earlier this year before a
grand jury that was hearing testimony in the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has also appealed a U.S. District Court judge's
order requiring two uniformed Secret Service agents and one
attorney with the agency to testify before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   White House attorneys claim that forcing the agents to testify
could compromise presidential security in the future, an argument a
federal district court has said was outweighed by the need for
Starr to fully investigate his case.
</P>
<P>
   With both of those issues pending, Starr asked the Supreme Court
to leapfrog the federal appeals courts to rule on them
expeditiously.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that because ``a president is under serious criminal
investigation,'' potentially affecting the business of the White
House, a quick ruling was in order.
</P>
<P>
   The nine justices didn't make a formal ruling on the matter, but
simply denied Starr's request, in effect leaving both issues in the
hands of the lower court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is assumed that the Court of Appeals will proceed
expeditiously to decide this case,'' the Supreme Court order said.
</P>
<P>
   However the appeals court rules, however, the decisions are
likely to be appealed to the Supreme Court, meaning a final
resolution of the matter could take some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking many months, perhaps as much as a year,'' said
Yannett.
</P>
<P>
   That would put a resolution of the matter well beyond November's
congressional elections, an important point for Clinton. Only
Congress may impeach a sitting president, and if Democrats were to
gain the 11 seats they need to regain control of the House, they
presumably would be less inclined than Republicans to pursue an
aggressive impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is ultimately going to be decided in the political
arena,'' said Yannett. ``The White House has understood that from
the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
