<SLUG> BC-BAKER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PLEA-BARGAIN FOR MERCY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RUSSELL BAKER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's how to plea-bargain us all out of the whole ordeal:
</P>
<P>
   1. President Clinton concedes that he had consensual sexual
relations with Monica Lewinsky, as intimated by her former lawyer,
William Ginsburg, and resigns.
</P>
<P>
   2. Vice President Gore becomes president.
</P>
<P>
   3. Republicans agree that President Gore, in his first speech to
the country, does not have to say ``Our long national nightmare is
over,'' but only that ``Our incredibly complicated national bad
dream is now in abeyance.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Prosecutor Kenneth Starr agrees not to seek a 15-year prison
term for Clinton for lying about his activities with Ms. Lewinsky.
In a statement to the court, Starr will concede that a gentleman
must inevitably lie about such matters, but prove, by citing
appropriate precedents, that the president of the United States has
a constitutional duty not to be a gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   5. Starr will also be permitted to send a stern note home to
Mrs. Clinton about her husband's behavior, but only if he can
compose such a note at a cost of less than $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   6. This note may suggest, but may not require, that Mrs. Clinton
make Clinton write, 1,000 times on a yellow legal pad, ``I will
never again fib to a special prosecutor, or any lawyer earning more
than $300 per billable hour, about my sexual activities, whether
consensual or accidental.''
</P>
<P>
   7. Simultaneously with the president's resignation, Starr will
submit a written apology to the public for pretending that he was
not ``out to get Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   8. This apology will not include, as Clinton's lawyers demanded,
an admission that Starr's unctuous behavior grievously misled the
public about his personality since, when fooling around after
hours, Starr often abandoned his sanctimonious style and told
politically incorrect and raucous, if not bawdy, jokes.
</P>
<P>
   9. A distinguished group of 20 investigative reporters will
conduct a three-day seminar on C-Span to help the public understand
what Whitewater was about.
</P>
<P>
   10. The public will be asked to contribute to a so-called South
Seas Fund, the purpose of which will be to finance construction, on
an atoll south of Tahiti, of a $10 million house with sauna and
swimming pool. This will be presented to Paula Jones as a gift from
the nation, with the understanding that if she returns to America a
special prosecutor will be appointed with power to find legal
justification for putting her in jail.
</P>
<P>
   11. To show what can happen to people who vex special
prosecutors, Starr will be permitted to have Susan McDougal
televised wearing an orange jailbird suit while breaking stones in
a chain gang. Should Ms. McDougal, however, agree to say ''yes''
whenever asked if Clinton is a shady character, Starr will request
that the warden let her wear a less gaudy jailbird suit, possibly
something in teal blue.
</P>
<P>
   12. Linda Tripp will be restored to the White House job she held
before Clinton people transferred her to the Pentagon. Concurrently
with said transfer, she will be provided with a food-taster to
accompany her whenever she dines in the White House mess.
</P>
<P>
   13. Hillary Clinton will appear on NBC's ``Today'' show to say
she was completely wrong when she said her husband was the victim
of ``a vast right-wing conspiracy'' to destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   14. On the evening after Mrs. Clinton's breakfast-show
appearance, Starr will appear on David Letterman's show and, if
asked, will state his belief that the mysteriously missing Rose Law
Firm documents, which Mrs. Clinton couldn't find in Arkansas,
turned up _ amazingly enough _ in the White House parlor only
because they were transported there from Arkansas by an evil
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   15. Should Letterman roll on the floor laughing, or offer Starr
a good bargain on the Brooklyn Bridge, Starr agrees, nevertheless,
to maintain an expression of sober and sincere credulity until
Letterman's next commercial break.
</P>
<P>
   16. All parties agree to sign a declaration of repentance for
encumbering the public with squalor, vulgarity and eleventh-rate
politics and for insisting that their show was not totally
inconsequential to the destiny of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   17. Monica Lewinsky agrees never to be heard of again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
