<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALCATEL-DSC-555&AMP;ADD-N     06-04 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCATEL-DSC-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALCATEL TO BUY GEAR MAKER IN STOCK DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alcatel Alsthom of France, one of the world's largest makers of
telecommunications equipment, enhanced its position in the United
States Thursday with the announcement of its acquisition of DSC
Communications Corp. for $4.4 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   DSC is the second medium-sized telecommunications-equipment
company in two days to agree to a takeover. Ciena Corp. agreed on
Wednesday to be acquired by Tellabs Inc. for $7.1 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation has been one of the major themes for the last few
years among companies that sell telecommunications services. Now
the merger wave is spreading into companies that manufacture the
complex electronic gear that actually allows sophisticated
communications networks to function.
</P>
<P>
   Many big telecommunications carriers do not enjoy dealing with
dozens of suppliers and are looking to vendors that can provide a
broad range of equipment. The equipment makers are trying to
oblige.
</P>
<P>
   A big difference between the Ciena and DSC deals is that Ciena
is a young, fast-growing company that is looking for heft to
compete against industry giants like Northern Telecom of Canada and
Lucent Technologies Inc., while DSC is an older company that has
stumbled recently and whose chairman has already announced plans to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   But for Alcatel, acquiring DSC gives the company a larger
presence in the U.S. market. Alcatel sold $14.1 billion worth of
telecommunications gear last year but only $1.5 billion of those
sales were in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Alcatel's sales in the United States are of transmission
equipment that allows long-distance carriers to send information
down fiber-optic pipelines at high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   DSC had sales of $1.6 billion last year, largely of equipment
that switches phone calls from one circuit to another and of gear
that helps local phone companies deploy digital technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's world, if you want to be a worldwide player in
telecommunications, you have to have a presence in the United
States,'' Serge Tchuruk, Alcatel's chairman, said in a phone
interview. ``It is a country that in some respects leads the way in
the big revenue shift from so-called narrowband to broadband: data
and Internet and the like.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel's strong desire to increase its presence in the United
States was reflected in the large premium the company agreed to pay
for DSC's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, DSC's stockholders will receive
0.815 of an Alcatel American depository receipt for each share of
DSC stock.
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel's ADRs closed on Wednesday, before the deal was
announced, at $43.4375 on the New York Stock Exchange. That made
the deal worth about $35.40 for each share of DSC.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of DSC closed Wednesday at $19.6875 in Nasdaq trading,
meaning that Alcatel paid a premium of about 80 percent for control
of DSC.
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel will also assume DSC's net debt of $40 million. DSC will
be merged into Alcatel's U.S. telecommunications subsidiary. Krish
Prabhu, chief executive of that operation, will become president
and chief executive of the combined unit. In April, James Donald,
DSC's chairman, announced that he would retire soon.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, DSC's shares rose by nearly 40 percent, or $7.8125,
to $27.50, while Alcatel's ADRs fell by $4.3125, to $39.125, on
fears that Alcatel had paid too much for DSC.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was `My God, that's a lot of money they're
paying for it,''' said Sean Faughnan, who follows Alcatel for J.P.
Morgan Securities in London. ``Then when I did some of the number
crunching, it didn't look so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald declined to be interviewed. But in a statement he said,
``This transaction provides increased value to DSC's
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel paid a large premium for DSC, but DSC would have been
much more expensive just a few years ago _ when its stock briefly
traded above $60 in the fall of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But since then DSC has disappointed investors. According to
First Call, which tracks analysts' forecasts, DSC posted operating
earnings discounting one-time charges and credits of $1.63 a share
in 1995. That figure fell to 44 cents in 1996 before rebounding a
bit to 85 cents last year. Analysts polled by the firm forecast
that the company would record a loss of 7 cents this year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attribute much of the blame to DSC's management, saying
that the company failed to adequately develop new products to
remain competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``DSC was a franchise that had some assets that were fairly
valuable,'' said Steven Levy, an analyst for Salomon Smith Barney.
``It's going to require new management and a much more focused
management in terms of new product generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel is experienced in turnarounds. The company lost $5.4
billion in 1995 before cutting 10,000 jobs and returning to
profitability the following year.
</P>
<P>
   DSC was advised by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. Alcatel was advised by
Lehman Brothers. Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &AMP; Katz was counsel for
DSC. Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom was counsel for Alcatel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
