<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4756 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCHOPEN     06-04 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCHOPEN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REDEDICATED SELES SENDS HINGIS PACKING 
</HEADLINE>
 (ja) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ This was no screeching apparition in black scaring the
world's top player, Martina Hingis, half out of her wits on the
French Open's center court in what turned out to be a one-sided
semifinal that sent a clear message on a hazy afternoon at Roland
Garros.
</P>
<P>
   This was Monica Seles, her stakes raised and her mind at peace
following the devastating loss of her father-coach, Karolj, to
cancer 10 days before this Grand Slam began. This was a version of
Seles not seen since she was, like Hingis, a teen-ager on top of
the world, a teen-ager who had no inkling she would someday be
stabbed in the back by a deranged German fan of her chief rival,
Steffi Graf, and no inkling that her father would be stricken with
cancer just when she was ready to return to the game they both
loved.
</P>
<P>
   With a ferocity that proved her promise to recommit herself to
tennis was no idle threat, Seles dismantled Hingis, the precocious
performer who had beaten her in all five prior meetings, including
one right here in this round a year ago. The 24-year-old Seles
unveiled a pulverizing display of whiplash playmaking along with a
take-no-prisoners resolve in delivering the stunned Swiss teen-ager
a 6-3, 6-2 throttling that spoiled Hingis' hope of winning a fourth
consecutive slam in the only slam she hasn't yet conquered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess she surprised everybody,'' said Hingis, who buried her
stricken face in a towel on the last changeover, far from normal
behavior for her. ``She just played a great match today, just let
me run and didn't make any mistakes: I mean, she's been around for
a quite a while, and then all of a sudden she was gone for almost
four years, and here she is back, in better shape, probably better
than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, this slam final will be teen-ager-less for a change, a
battle of hardened veterans between Seles and Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario who share five French Open titles between them, including
the 6-2, 6-4 finale in 1991 when Seles defeated Sanchez Vicario to
win the second of three consecutive titles here.
</P>
<P>
   Guaranteeing this slam a Spanish finalist and possibly a Spanish
champion in both the men's and women's singles events, Sanchez
Vicario bobbed and weaved her way into a final-round duel with
Seles by thoroughly outhustling second-seeded Lindsay Davenport,
6-3, 7-6 (7-5).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ashamed of anything,'' said Davenport, an Olympic gold
medalist who has yet to reach a slam final and made 56 unforced
errors in this semifinal, ``but I didn't play great today. I guess
I beat myself, but she kind of forced it on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario, who won this title at 17 in 1989 and collected
it again in 1994, trails Seles by 14-2 in a rivalry that began
nearly 10 years ago and has favored Seles all three times they have
met on clay.
</P>
<P>
   Though Thursday's match-up between Seles and Hingis, who at 16
became the youngest No. 1 player in the sport's history just over a
year ago, seemed slanted toward the teen-ager, Seles revved up her
play to a level even Hingis, ever a quick study on-court, couldn't
match. Hingis later admitted it was a level she had not yet seen at
this tournament; Seles called it a level that only hints at the
heights she plans, in the next five years, to attain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to come out and be really aggressive today, and I
knew I had that in me,'' said Seles, whose rapier returns trapped
Hingis behind the baseline and led to the Swiss losing her serve
five times, notably the last games of both sets. ``I wasn't sure if
I could do that today, but I expected this of myself, and to do it
against the best-ranked player who has been really dominating is
good for me to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into this tournament I really wasn't that confident in
my game, but in a weird way, I had a peace of mind,'' Seles said.
</P>
<P>
   She had practiced briefly on May 15, the day after her father
died, just to remind herself that tennis, and this imminent slam,
might provide her best vehicle for getting on with her life exactly
the way her father had advised her to. On impulse, she hopped a
plane for Paris along with her mother, Ester, and toy terrier,
Ariel, a week after her father died.
</P>
<P>
   ``After deciding that I'm going to play,'' Seles said Thursday,
``I felt really content with the decision. That helped, because in
the last two years, I was never really content with any decision I
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles knew her father felt guilty when she skipped events, like
this year's Australian Open, in order to be with him. ``But when I
walked out the door to go and play tournaments, I felt guilty for
leaving him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Seles was precisely where she wanted to be, on center
stage, playing precisely the game she wanted to play: hardball. She
closed out the match with a wicked backhand passing shot at break
and match point.
</P>
<P>
   Seles, the owner of nine slam singles crowns, has left herself
just one victory short of making a consummate comeback, here at the
same slam where she won her first major in 1990. Seles is wearing
her father's wedding ring on a necklace because she felt it would
be a way to keep him close to her, but she denied that she's
playing this slam in memory of him or dedicating it to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss him tremendously, but win or lose, it doesn't make a
difference in me thinking about my dad or not thinking about him,''
Seles said. ``And it's not the same as it was before the stabbing,
but it never will be. And I don't want it to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
