<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4761 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECON-280&AMP;ADD-N     06-04 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-280&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA CUTS INTEREST RATES IN SIGN THAT STABILITY IS RETURNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION WARNING: also sent in `f' category code)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia slashed its sky-high interest rates Thursday in
a further sign that calm was returning to its financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Bank raised interest rates, to 150 from 50 percent,
last week in a drastic move to defend the ruble. But Thursday the
bank reduced the rate, to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the only sign that the government was making
progress. Yields on treasury bills continued to fall. And the new
head of Russia's tax service promised to raise badly needed revenue
by auditing the accounts of 1,000 prominent Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a pervasive sense among investors and Russian
officials that the nation's financial problems are deep-seated and
that restoring the confidence of foreign investors will be a
prolonged and difficult task.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is groaning under a mountain of debt, and its interest
rates are still very high compared to inflation, which is running
under 10 percent, according to new estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Many foreign investors are counting on the creation of a
multi-billion-dollar reserve to help prop by the ruble. Organized
by the International Monetary Fund, it would provide the Central
Bank with a line of credit if its reserves ran low.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the expectation that such a IMF reserve will be created
over the next several weeks is one reason Russia's financial
markets have become more stable.
</P>
<P>
   Western and Russian officials have continued to discuss such a
reserve, which could be $10 billion. At the same time, however,
some Russian officials have sought to demonstrate that the economic
situation is under control by declaring that emergency financial
assistance will not be needed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Putting on a brave face, Russian Finance Minister Mikhail
Zadornov suggested that Russia could get by cutting its budget
deficit and raising financing through Eurobonds.
</P>
<P>
   Russia sold a $1.25 Eurobond issue on Wednesday, though the
price was reduced compared with other debt. Zadornov said that the
government planned to sell two additional dollar-denominated
Europeans this year.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko has made similar comments,
though he has previously talked about the need for more IMF
assistance. He also dispatched a top-level Russian delegation to
Washington last week to seek U.S. support for expanded IMF aid.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian officials continued their public campaign to
highlight their reforms and mollify foreign investors. Kiriyenko
pressed his case in Paris during a previously scheduled visit.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin is expected to strike the same theme
when he visit Germany early next week, also on a previously
scheduled visit. Meanwhile, Yeltsin plans to use his weekly radio
address Friday to try to reassure the Russian public.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction in interest rates was announced by the Central
Bank this evening. Known as a refinancing rate, it represents the
rate at which the Central Bank provides rubles to commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the yields of treasury bills continued to fall. The
Russian government had raised the rates on treasury bill to more
than 80 percent last week to prevent investors from dumping their
securities and exchanging their rubles for dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday the yield on the treasury bills fell to about 45
percent, as some investors returned to the market. The yield was 30
percent before the latest financial crisis and hovered around 20
percent in November.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial markets are operating ``smoothly and
reliably,'' Kiriyenko said Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
