<HEADER>
A4766 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-LUKAS-LADN     06-04 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LUKAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUKAS GOES FOR ANOTHER JEWEL IN HIS CROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBBIE ARRINGTON  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. Just in case anyone forgot, trainer D. Wayne Lukas
wore a new baseball cap to his barn Thursday morning, inscribed
with ``10 Crowns.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how many Triple Crown races Lukas has won, including six
in a row starting with the 1994 Preakness. He's got three Kentucky
Derbies and three Belmonts in his string. And Saturday, he will be
looking for one more classic.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas entered two fresh horses Grand Slam and Yarrow Brae in the
Belmont Stakes in an attempt to block Real Quiet's quest for a
Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   While trainer Bob Baffert and Real Quiet have captured racing's
spotlight, Lukas has stood casually by, taking it all in. A Peb
cartoon in the Daily Racing Form this week portrayed Real Quiet,
Baffert and owner Mike Pegram in bed, hiding under the covers, as
Lukas howled. The caption read: ``Watch out - the spook is back!''
Said Lukas, ``I liked that a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand Slam has the best credentials in the race,'' Lukas said
of this Gone West colt. ``I may be a party of one, but I think he
was the best 2-year-old in the country last year. He's got the best
pedigree of his class. He's a track and stakes record holder, a
multiple Grade I winner and he's undefeated on this track.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got Jerry Bailey for a rider; he's King Kong in New
York,'' Lukas added. Bailey is winning here with 42 percent of his
mounts. ``And his trainer has won three Belmonts.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem: Grand Slam is coming back from a devastating
injury, suffered in last November's Breeders' Cup Juvenile at
Hollywood Park. In that race, the Baffert-trained Johnbill
repeatedly clipped Grand Slam's back leg, ripping the flesh from
hock to ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like someone had torn the skin all the way down
around his hoof like a sock,'' said Lukas. ``The tendons were
hanging out. I had never seen anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wayne Ilwraith, operating at the Cypress Equine Medical
Clinic, performed two hours of surgery to reconstruct Grand Slam's
leg. Some 290 stitches were needed to mend the wound.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Grand Slam had to stay standing for two months, tied
up by wires in his stall to keep him on his feet. But after 60 days
of healing, he managed to tear the wound completely open again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried when I saw it,'' said Lukas. ``I couldn't believe
it.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, a team of veterinarians decided to hack off the old
skin and muscle and try a different technique. ``They gave me
absolutely no hope of the horse ever racing again,'' added Lukas.
``But then, vets and doctors tend to be pessimists, so if the
surgery works, they look like heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a miracle making it to the post parade,'' he
continued. ``But now, I'm not worried about the injury at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Grand Slam failed in his first comeback attempt at Santa Anita
this spring, but has blossomed anew at Belmont, winning the Peter
Pan Stakes May 24. Coming back only 13 days later in the 1-{-mile
Belmont will prove a tough test, admitted Lukas. ``Win or lose, I
still think I have the best horse.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Yarrow Brae has raced in the shadow of another
Lukas 3-year-old, Cape Town, who broke a leg in the Preakness and
has been retired. Yarrow Brae comes off a win in the Illinois
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very nice horse, too,'' said Lukas. ``If you want some
coffee money, put a show bet on him. He'll surprise you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
