<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-US-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO ADMITS KNOWING ABOUT U.S. ANTI-DRUG OPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican authorities, who at first complained they
knew nothing about a U.S. money-laundering sting operation against
Mexican bankers, now concede they were told about it more than two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even though at least some people in the Mexican attorney
general's office knew, authorization for undercover activities by
U.S. agents in Mexico was never approved, the agency said in a
statement released late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The concession came as a team of U.S. Customs Service officials
met with Mexican officials to talk about the three-year sting,
which ended last month with the arrests of more than 100 people,
including at least 22 Mexican bankers.
</P>
<P>
   The furor over Operation Casablanca _ in which the banking
officials were lured to the United States and charged _ prompted
President Ernesto Zedillo to call for an investigation into the
activities of U.S. agents operating in Mexico without knowledge or
permission of the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Rosario Green presented American Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright on Monday with a list of Mexican laws the
Customs agents had violated.
</P>
<P>
   Green has said that Mexico would file charges and seek the
extradition of the Customs agents who operated across the border
without permission.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Thursday, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno said it
was premature to talk of extradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you are jumping ahead. The first thing that has to be
done before you extradite is to determine whether there is a basis
for filing charges, and whether charges will be filed,'' Reno told
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the U.S. Treasury Department confirmed that
Customs agents met here with representatives of the Mexican
attorney general's office, treasury department and foreign ministry
to talk about Operation Casablanca.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a law enforcement technical team informing them of
the specifics of the indictments,'' the spokeswoman said by
telephone. ``They agreed to further meetings and an exchange of
information on Casablanca.''
</P>
<P>
   During the operation, Customs agents masqueraded as drug sellers
with money to launder. The Mexican bankers who were charged
allegedly were willing to participate in money-laundering schemes.
</P>
<P>
   The bankers were lured to Nevada on the promise of attending the
opening of a gambling casino last month and were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican attorney general's office said in its statement that
a former assistant attorney general for international affairs had
admitted that three Customs officials visited him in January 1996
to tell him of the developing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rafael Estrada Sarnano (told) Attorney General Jorge Madrazo
Cuellar ... that he definitely remembers having met with (U.S.
Customs service officials in Mexico) who informed him of a money
laundering scheme in Mexican banks in the states of Sonora and Baja
California,'' the communique stated.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada worked under former Attorney General Antonio Lozano
Gracia, who was fired by Zedillo in December 1996. Estrada said he
told Lozano of the meeting with the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Lozano told a news conference Thursday that the visit was
informal and that the Customs agents spoke only in generalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't notify anything of concrete dates, nor locations
nor people,'' Lozano said. ``It was simply a conversation in
general.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the nature of substance of the conversation, the
attorney general's office said Mexico did not approve undercover
activities by foreign nationals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can in no way be considered as an authorization or
validation for informants or undercover witnesses in the service of
the United States government ... to have conducted activities on
(Mexican ) soil,'' the agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROADWAY-AD-COLUMN-52     06-04 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-AD-COLUMN-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BROADWAY THEATERS TRY UNIFIED APPROACH TO MASS
MARKETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although the current Broadway season formally ends
with the Tony Awards on Sunday evening, the theater industry's
efforts to market itself will actually be stepped up immediately
afterward, with the debut next week of a ``Live Broadway'' platinum
Visa credit card.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion is the latest installment of an effort by the
League of American Theaters and Producers to stimulate demand
nationwide for live theater and, essentially, establish
``Broadway'' as a highly visible brand. The card will be offered
jointly by the league, which is the trade group for Broadway
productions in New York and throughout North America, and First USA
Bank, a subsidiary of Banc One Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Continental Airlines signed up as the league's first
national corporate sponsor, paying a reported $750,000 annually in
cash and services over five years.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Schweppes became the league's second corporate
sponsor. Gerald Johnson, director of promotions for Dr Pepper/Seven
Up Inc., which is a division of Cadbury Schweppes PLC, said that
the company had struck a one-year deal for an unspecified sum, with
the possibility of an extension, to make Schweppes ``the exclusive
tonic and mixer of Live Broadway.'' Live Broadway is the league's
official logo, developed by Landor Associates, the corporate
identity firm, and introduced last year to heighten public
awareness of the Broadway stage.
</P>
<P>
   Schweppes will run a supermarket sweepstakes this summer
featuring a prize trip to New York that includes Broadway tickets.
It will also put the Live Broadway logo on its packaging.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of all these initiatives, said Jed Bernstein, the
league's executive director, ``is to return Broadway to its place
on the mainstream entertainment menu.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadway is one of the greatest untouched marketing platforms
for Corporate America,'' he said. ``If a sponsor tries to get
involved in any sport now, the price of entry is very high because
it's a crowded stage. But Broadway has done little in this area,
and we're creating a very efficient way for corporations to take
advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meg Meurer, the league's director of marketing and new business
development, said Broadway productions _ performed either on the
New York stage or in theaters around the country that are league
members _ faced stiff competition from all forms of entertainment,
including sports events, concerts, video games and even the
Internet. The league's goal, she said, is to make Broadway theater
``the most upscale form of mass entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey by Research International, a
division of WPP Group PLC, the average Broadway theatergoer in New
York is 41 years old, well educated and affluent, with an annual
household income of $91,000. Slightly more than half of these
theatergoers live in the New York area, while the rest are
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   First USA finds the league's audience attractive, said Stu
Upson, senior vice president for sports and entertainment
marketing, because ``it's loyal and the demographics are good.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Next week First USA will send out its first direct mail for the
Live Broadway credit card to more than a million people culled from
lists provided by the league's 500 members in 90 cities. The card,
which will give holders points toward Broadway tickets, backstage
tours and memorabilia, will also be promoted through telemarketing
and in places like the new Times Square Visitors Center, which will
open in August and contain a league box office.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Meurer and Bernstein, the league is seeking
additional sponsors in three categories _ automotive, financial
services and telecommunications. Bernstein said it had already
raised some $10 million in cash, merchandise and media donated by
sponsors and promotional partners, which also support its toll-free
information line.
</P>
<P>
   Theater industry executives and observers generally applauded
these initiatives. George Wachtel, a New York-based arts consultant
who previously was the league's director of research, deemed the
sponsorships ``helpful in a business where Broadway shows can't
afford to sell theatergoing as a life style.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Viertel, the producer of ``The Sound of Music,'' ``Smokey
Joe's Cafe'' and ``Forever Tango,'' and a member of the league's
executive committee, said he believed the league was successfully
addressing the problem of ``promoting Broadway as an idea when each
of us has a vastly different product.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Erlick, a consultant in New York who advised the league on
its First USA project, suggested that the theater industry
``traditionally has been fractionalized, with independent,
competitive producers doing their own branding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The league's programs create a hook for it to break through
the clutter more convincingly than individual producers can on
their own,'' he said. ``It gives them greater marquee value, more
of a pedigree.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
