<HEADER>
A4773 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-DRAW-LADN     06-04 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-DRAW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET DRAWS POST NO. 8
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBBIE ARRINGTON  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT,N.Y. _ Real Quiet will meet plenty of fresh-faced
opposition in Saturday's Belmont Stakes. On Thursday morning, the
Kentucky Derby and Preakness champion drew post No. 8 in a full
field of 13 for the last jewel in his Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Of the opposition, only two - Victory Gallop and Basic Trainee -
ran in both prior races. Derby runners-up Chilito, a last-minute
addition to the Belmont cast, Parade Ground and Hanuman Highway are
back after a breather. Preakness also-rans Classic Cat and Hot
Wells will try to silence Real Quiet's thunder again, too.
</P>
<P>
   But the five newcomers may have the best chance of upsetting
Real Quiet, a 6-5 favorite to become the first Triple Crown
champion in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from the opinion that if Real Quiet gets beat, it will
come from a new horse,'' said trainer D. Wayne Lukas, who will
saddle highly regarded Grand Slam and Yarrow Brae for the Belmont.
``But I'm a terrible handicapper.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jo and Raffie's Majesty both look like distance horses,
say their connections, and have been pointed to this 1-{-mile
marathon for months. Limit Out is a highly regarded sprinter who
will try to carry his speed past a mile.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 11 Triple Crown champions has ever had to beat more
than seven rivals for their place in racing history. Of the 13
Derby-Preakness winners who failed in the Belmont, only Canonero II
in 1971 had to run against 12 opponents; he finished fourth to 34-1
long shot Pass Catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Belmont Park officials stuck with tradition instead of following
ESPN's urging for a controversial NBA-style draw/draft used for the
Derby and Preakness. ``Suddenly, the draw has become brain
surgery,'' said Hank Greenberg of ESPN. ``So, we'll do it the
old-fahsioned way.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet's post was the last picked. If the Belmont had
followed the same draw format as the Derby and Preakness, he would
have been stuck with post No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet's trainer Bob Baffert, who is 0-for-7 at this track,
seemed pleased being behind the eight ball. ``My main concern right
now is leaving New York 1-for-8,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Five horses have won from post No. 8 before; post No. 1 with 22
winners has a distinctive edge in the Belmont history book.
</P>
<P>
   BELMONT NOTEBOOK
</P>
<P>
   ICE THOSE SILVER BULLETS: Mike Pegram, Real Quiet's
beer-and-burger-loving owner, has become as well known for his
eating habits as his horse. While out for dinner Wednesday night
with Baffert at a Manhattan steakhouse, their waiter immediately
recognized the pair and brought Pegram an ice bucket packed with
eight Coors Lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like having my own private cooler,'' said Pegram.
``People don't only know my name, but they give me what I want
before I even ask for it.''
</P>
<P>
   TRIPLE CROWN COOKIES: Back at the barn Thursday morning,
entrepreneur Tara Dalrymple gave Baffert several tins of special
Triple Crown Cookies, baked by her Ocala, Fla.-based Saratoga South
Cookie Company. The Derby mint cookie is laced with bourbon; the
Preakness chocolate-chip is topped with a sugar Black-Eyed Susan;
and the Belmont oatmeal cookie is crowned with a chocolate horse.
Dalrymple also sells cookies named after three Baffert-trained
horses: Silver Charm, Anet and Semoran.
</P>
<P>
   While finishing a TV interview, Baffert handed the bag of
goodies to a security guard with these instructions: ``If anyone
goes for that bag, shoot 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   BELMONT A BREEZE?: The Derby has its Mint Julep and Belmont
officials want an official drink for their classic race, too. For
Thursday's breakfast, they mixed up a big batch of Belmont Breeze:
Seagram's whiskey, Harvey's Bristol Cream sherry, a dash of sweet
and sour, cranberry and orange juices, club soda and 7-Up. Created
by Manhattan's famed Rainbow Room, the Belmont Breeze is served in
a tall glass over ice with mint and a twist of lemon. Few tasters
thought it would replace Long Island Iced Tea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
