<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
     TOBACCO BILL THREATENED BY PARTISAN WRANGLING
 &HT;     By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Sen. John McCain watched with mounting anxiety,
the Senate erupted into partisan posturing Thursday that could doom
passage of a comprehensive tobacco bill this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening now is what I feared would happen to this
bill. It is starting to get very partisan,'' said McCain, R-Ariz.,
chief sponsor of the $516 billion measure. ``A lot of things are
being said that are not necessarily helpful to the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate action has been delayed a week as both parties jockeyed
over a proposal by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, _ a tobacco bill
opponent _ to use roughly $50 billion to reduce the so-called
``marriage penalty'' in which couples with roughly equal incomes
pay higher taxes than they would if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the amendment lay the larger question of whether the
Senate was prepared to pass a bill that envisions a broad expansion
of federal regulatory powers over tobacco financed by a
$1.10-a-pack increase in cigarette prices.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties began playing their political cards Thursday,
trading accusations that could become campaign fodder this fall if
the tobacco bill fails.
</P>
<P>
   Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., set off the verbal volley
by offering a petition _ likely to be voted on Tuesday _ to force a
vote on whether to finish the bill next week. Daschle admitted
Democrats probably won't be able to get the 60 votes needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really comes down to this: do you want to pass a tobacco
bill or not? And we're getting a resounding `no' '' from the
Republicans. ``They don't want a tobacco bill,'' Daschle said,
arguing that the GOP strategy was to delay the bill until Congress
ran out of time this year.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., accused Democrats of trying
to load the bill with expensive government programs they knew
Congress would reject.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a bill, this (cloture petition) is a good step
toward having nothing happen because this sours the well,'' Lott
said. ``Do you want a bill or do you want an issue? Do you want to
do something about this problem, or do you want to play games?''
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the Senate rejected, 29-66, Lott's motion to kill
an amendment by Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., to impose stiffer
targets on reducing teen smoking and to penalize individual
manufacturers, rather than the industry in general, if the targets
were not met.
</P>
<P>
   After the motion was rejected, Lott _ who had earlier said the
Durbin amendment would kill the bill _ moved to accept it by voice
vote.
</P>
<P>
   McCain described action on the Durbin amendment as ``just
another vote,'' and predicted the major decisions about the bill
would be made in a future House-Senate conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
