<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-MIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE ARRIVES AT MIR TO RETRIEVE AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ The American astronaut Andrew Thomas
officially ended his 130-day mission aboard the Russian space
station Mir on Thursday when the shuttle Discovery arrived to pick
him up.
</P>
<P>
   The six-member crew of the shuttle will be the last from the
United States to dock at Mir.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a 46-year-old mechanical engineer born in Australia,
said he was thrilled to look out the Mir window and see ``a bright
point of light across on the horizon, which I knew to be the
shuttle.''
</P>
<P>
   Discovery will remain docked until Monday to deliver food,
water, personal items and technical equipment for two Russian
astronauts who will remain aboard the station until August. The
combined crews hauled the first of the supplies, including several
100-pound bags of water, into the space station Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The mission wraps up the first phase of NASA's international
space-station program. The National Aeronautics and Space
Administration paid Russia $400 million so that seven astronauts
could spend time learning how to live and work on Mir.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase of the program is the construction of a $40
billion orbiting outpost, and the first assembly flights for that
are scheduled for November and December.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle completed its ninth and final rendezvous with Mir at
12:58 p.m. EDT as the two spacecraft soared 239 miles above
Russia's border with Kazakhstan, northwest of the Caspian Sea.
Discovery is the third of NASA's four shuttles to visit Mir.
</P>
<P>
   A problem with Discovery's television antenna kept the shuttle
crew from beaming down crisp, colorful coverage of the historic
linkup, but the Mir crew stepped in with a hand-held camera to
relay views through Russia's little-used Altair
communications-satellite system. Later, they sent fuzzy,
sepia-toned images of the hatch opening and initial greetings
through ground stations in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in 1986, the station has long outlived its five-year
design life. It has also survived several crises including a flash
fire and a collision with a cargo vessel last year.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery is expected to return to Earth on June 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
