<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAYS IT MAY HAVE KNOWN ABOUT DRUG STING
</HEADLINE>
      AFTER WEEKS OF ANGRY WORDS, MEXICO NOW &HT;     By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After weeks of attacking the United States for
failing to notify it of a covert U.S. operation against drug-money
laundering, a top Mexican justice official now admits Mexico may
have had prior knowledge of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The admission comes on the heels of a threat Tuesday by Mexican
Foreign Minister Rosario Green to seek the extradition of U.S.
Customs agents so Mexico could prosecute them for participating in
undercover activities on Mexican soil.
</P>
<P>
   The agents' activities were part of ``Operation Casablanca,'' a
three-year investigation that was disclosed May 18 after U.S.
authorities arrested two dozen Mexican bankers and announced the
indictment of three top Mexican banks on money-laundering charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government, which at first welcomed the indictments,
has for weeks repeatedly accused the United States of breaking
Mexican law and binational agreements that require disclosure of
information about drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday evening, however, Mexico's Attorney General
issued a statement that includes a different version of events _ as
told by American officials who were in Mexico on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, according to the statement, United States
Treasury Department and Justice representatives were in Mexico City
to brief Mexican officials on the Casablanca indictments.
</P>
<P>
   During the briefing, the U.S. officials told their Mexican
counterparts that on Jan. 16, 1996, two U.S. Customs agents met in
Mexico City with a man who was then Mexico's Deputy Attorney
General of International Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans said that meeting's purpose with the deputy ``was
to inform him about the operation that later was named `Casablanca'
and ask for help,'' according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of their request for help to investigate a
money-laundering scheme, the Americans said that they never
received a response from Antonio Lozano Gracia (CQ), Mexico's
Attorney General at the time.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference on Thursday, Lozano Gracia said it was
``absolutely false'' that the Americans had asked for help or
disclosed that an investigation was underway in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He said the U.S. Customs agents in 1996 had an ``informal
conversation'' with one of his deputies about a laundering scheme
they had discovered that included hiding drug proceeds in trucks
and smuggling the money into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Treasury Department spokesperson in Washington had no
comment Thursday on the dispute over whether Mexico knew about an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only confirm there was a briefing in 1996,'' the
spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, United States authorities have said that Mexico had
not been informed of the Casablanca sting operation because of
concerns for the safety of U.S. agents.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a press conference in Washington on Thursday,
Attorney General Janet Reno said that it was ``premature'' to
discuss a threat to extradite U.S. Customs agents who had been sent
to Mexico as part of Operation Casablanca.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the Mexican government does not assume guilt until it
has thoroughly investigated a matter,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important that we learn from all of this the
need to communicate very clearly and very carefully, and we will
continue to try to do that in every way that we can,'' Reno added.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican displeasure with Operation Casablanca may be on the
agenda when President Clinton meets Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo June 10 and 11 after the United Nations World Drug Summit
next week in New York.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For use by clients of The New York Times News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
