A4784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      06-04 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS RALLY ON GOOD ECONOMIC NEWS; DOW UP 66.76 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market rebounded Thursday, as investors
were soothed by reports that the economy remains resilient and
merger activity is still vibrant.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Dow Jones industrial average fell 87.44 points,
heavy buying of blue-chip issues helped the Dow climb 66.76 points,
or about eight-tenths of a percent, to close at 8,870.56.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Broader measures were even stronger. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index gained 1.1 percent to close at 1,094.83 and the
Nasdaq composite soared 1.6 percent to 1,769.95. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's gain, though, still leaves most major stock indexes
far off their all-time highs. And Motorola's warning, after the
close of trading Thursday, that its second-quarter earnings would
probably not meet analysts' expectations may deal Wall Street a
still sharper blow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going through a correction phase,'' said Hugh Johnson, a
market strategist at First Albany Corp. ``We're having some big up
and down days in a largely direction-less market.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Motorola's warning may be another sign that profit growth
is weakening this year, and that Asia remains a concern, the U.S.
economy continues to expand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, for instance, the Commerce Department said that
factory orders were brisk in April and that retail sales in May
were the strongest in more than four years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the shares of retail outlets like Wal-Mart, The Gap
and Circuit City were in heavy demand Thursday, sending shares of
those companies sharply higher. But investors were also keen on oil
and technology issues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oil shares climbed along with oil prices on expectations that
Saudi Arabia and other oil producing states would agree to reduce
oil production and thereby lift oil prices. When an agreement to
cut oil production by 450,000 barrels a day came Thursday, the
price of a barrel of oil rose 2 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications stocks also soared after Alcatel, the
Paris-based maker of telephone equipment, said it would acquire DSC
Communications Corp. of Plano, Texas, for about $4.4 billion in
stock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, Tellabs Inc., another equipment maker, said it
would purchase Ciena Corp. for about $6.9 billion. That kind of
merger activity sent the shares of other telephone equipment and
networking stocks sharply higher Thursday on speculation that there
could be more telephone combinations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's gains come in the midst of a broader slump in the
stock market, one that had seen the Dow fall 4.4 percent from its
record high, posted May 13, and the technology-heavy Nasdaq drop
9.1 percent off its all-time high of 1,917.61, set April 22. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There has been a concern among investors that share prices got
ahead of corporate earnings prospects, that shares are vastly
over-priced and that inflation could increase this year because of
rising wage pressures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the counter-point, according to many analysts, has been a
near-perfect landscape of strong economic growth, low interest
rates a whirlwind of merger and acquisition activity, and an
apparently burning desire by people everywhere to buy and own
stocks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans are also witnessing the lowest unemployment rate in 25
years, and the prospect of the first federal budget surplus since
1969. And even if profit growth has slowed, many analysts and
investors are betting that profit growth will strengthen later this
year and into 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a seemingly perfect world, though, the debate is centering on
profits: will they or won't they climb ahead in the second part of
the year, after a sharp slowdown that saw just 2.5 percent growth
in the first quarter of 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``However you look at it, earnings growth has slowed sharply,''
said James Glassman, head of the U.S. research group at Chase
Securities. ``Equity analysts are expecting a strong second half of
the year with double-digit growth. But if that doesn't happen, I
don't know how the stock market's going to take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2009EDT &QL; 
