   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, June 5. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
WELFARE (Phoenix) - Thousands of Arizona's former welfare families
are walking away from free state health care benefits and no one is
sure why. While bureaucrats debate what to do, these former welfare
families are increasingly dependent on costly emergency room care
at taxpayers' expense _ even though most remain eligible for state
insurance coverage. Arizona is not alone. Arizona's welfare reform
began a year earlier than most states, but researchers already are
tracking this unexpected impact nationwide. By PAT KOSSAN. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PEYOTE (Phoenix) - A Kearny man, who claimed he possessed the
hallucinogen drug peyote for religious purposes, actually used it
for ``personal enjoyment'' and should not have a button of the
confiscated drug returned to him, a judge ruled this week. By JUDI
VILLA. Story would move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LOGCABINS (Phoenix) _ President Lincoln lived in one, and Gen.
Ulysses S. Grant directed the last campaigns of the Civil War from
another. Log cabins are part of the American consciousness. But now
they are crumbling. On Thursday, the National Park Service
announced a public-private partnership to save more than 400 log
structures, beginning with the Gatekeeper's Cabin on the North Rim
of the Grand Canyon. The cabin will be restored to its original
appearance using tools, material and techniques from a bygone era.
By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
