<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDE-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM MAY NOT SATISFY FANS OF WILDE'S CERE BRAL WIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - ``The only difference between a caprice and a lifelong
passion is that the caprice lasts a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A man cannot be too careful in the choice of his enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In this world, there are only two tragedies. One is not
getting what one wants, and the other is getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Wilde had a million of them: witty epigrams that set
British society abuzz at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilde,'' the biopic about the Irish writer who was the
cleverest man of his generation and the most scandalous, offers us
but a taste of Wilde's genius.
</P>
<P>
   It's like drinking from the fountain of wisdom but getting only
a sip.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the movie concentrates on Wilde's discovery of his
homosexuality and his destruction through the hypocrisy of English
society and the excesses of the man he loved.
</P>
<P>
   We first meet Wilde (Stephen Fry) when he comes off the lecture
tour of America and prepares to marry a proper Englishwoman
(Jennifer Ehle) so that he may always have a ready audience.
</P>
<P>
   Wilde fathers two sons, only to discover late in life that his
true nature is homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his confusion can be traced to the structure of
upper-class British society at that time: The proper intellectual
gentleman was expected to enjoy primarily the company of other men.
Women lived their quiet lives in back rooms, brought out and
dressed for formal occasions only.
</P>
<P>
   Wilde, who believes that pleasure is the best teacher, rushes
forward into London's underground homosexual society, while
maintaining the facade of his family life.
</P>
<P>
   Then he meets the young Lord Douglas (Jude Law), with whom he
falls in love, even though he knows it's an act of
self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas is a social rebel, at war with his tyrannical father.
The younger man's outrageous behavior threatens to disgrace Wilde
and entangle him with a legal system that abhors homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a man born ahead of his time, it's Wilde. His
actions now would cause no scandals, if they were even noticed.
Instead, his proclivities would ensure his stature within high
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilde'' features a first-rate performance by Fry, best known
for playing the imperturbable butler in the British TV series
``Jeeves and Wooster.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Brian Gilbert (``Tom &AMP; Viv``) creates a harsh, detailed
portrait of English society, the kind of rich production we have
come to expect from British films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilde'' will best satisfy audiences looking for social
history, particularly concerning the evolution of society's views
on homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   But it will least satisfy those who treasured Wilde's genius as
a writer, playwright and the wit of his times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilde'' is rated R for nudity, sex and profanity. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
