A4787 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUMAN-MOVIES-AZR &LR;      06-04 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMAN-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARREY'S GENIUS SHACKLED BY A TEDIOUS `TRUMAN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - First, it's not a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Jim Carrey is not Jim Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   Third, ``The Truman Show'' is a weird movie.
</P>
<P>
   But the weirdest thing about it: Ultimately, it's not weird
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey stars, in a primarily straight role, as Truman, a guy who
lives in a beautiful island town and has a perfectly normal life,
except for one thing: It's all phony.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, Truman's life has been the world's favorite TV
soap opera. And everyone in the world knows it except for Truman.
</P>
<P>
   His wife (Laura Linney) and every other person in the town are
really actors playing his wife and every other person in town.
</P>
<P>
   The town itself is fake; it's really a huge TV set.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the movie is devoted to setting up this
outlandish scenario, at which point Truman begins to suspect that
something is wrong with his neat little world and that a vast
conspiracy is keeping him on the island.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is rarely played for laughs, despite the immense
comic potential of the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, director Peter Weir (``Fearless``) uses the movie to
ask serious questions about the nature of reality and illusion,
which may work for people who have always felt that reality was an
iffy proposition.
</P>
<P>
   However, Weir's philosophy does not run deep.
</P>
<P>
   It devolves into questions that sink the film's concept:
</P>
<P>
   _If people spend all their lives pretending to live in a town,
aren't they actually living in a town?
</P>
<P>
   _What's the difference between a wife and a woman who spends 24
hours a day pretending to be a wife?
</P>
<P>
   As for the movie's profound message, it asks the riveting
question: Aren't we all watching too much television?
</P>
<P>
   What are they saving for the sequel: Aren't we all eating too
much junk food?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' is built on a fascinating concept. But the
director and writers don't do enough to develop that concept.
</P>
<P>
   While ignoring the potential for wild humor in the situation,
Weir spends so much time establishing the seeming normalcy of
Truman's life that the movie quickly gets boring.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other soap operas, nothing much happens to Truman.
</P>
<P>
   I can see why the producers wanted Carrey for the part. He's
bound to bring in some of his fans to see a movie that, starring
another actor, might have played the art houses.
</P>
<P>
   But to cast Carrey and then deprive him of a comic outlet is a
mistake. Carrey has a fount of wild comic talents, almost none of
which are called for in ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   About halfway through, Carrey makes one of his trademark loony
faces, and the audience howls hopefully. Everyone's thinking: At
last, Jim Carrey is going to be Jim Carrey. But it doesn't last.
</P>
<P>
   From Carrey's perspective, he's obviously trying to expand his
acting range into films more serious than ``Dumb and Dumber.''
</P>
<P>
   But does he really want to expand into the realm of the
ordinary?
</P>
<P>
   That nondescript territory is already crowded with scores of
actors, none of whom can do to a manic comedy what Carrey can.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' scores points for its clever idea. But they
should have brought this one back to the drawing board and
rewritten it.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG, ``The Truman Show'' contains nothing offensive. But
it's still not a good movie for kids younger than 12 because it's
too sad and confusing. 3 stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
