<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4789 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERFECT-MOVIES-AZR &LR;      06-04 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFECT-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK REDO FAR FROM PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Take two actors who have played the same roles too
many times before, put them in a movie that's been made too many
times before, and you have the multiple-deja-vu experience of ``A
Perfect Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Douglas is the arrogant millionaire, but when isn't he?
</P>
<P>
   Gwyneth Paltrow is the desired, aristocratic woman who can't be
possessed. Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Perfect Murder'' is a remake of ``Dial M For Murder,'' a
thriller made by Alfred Hitchcock in 1954, remade on TV in 1981 and
overproduced by every community theater group in the country .
</P>
<P>
   Why did director Andrew Davis (``The Fugitive``) think we needed
a new version of such an old chestnut? Probably because he's
playing a new Hollywood vanity game: showing off by remaking the
master, Hitchcock. With a remake of ``Psycho'' in the works, Davis
decided to tackle one ofHitchcock's lesser films.
</P>
<P>
   He handles the story with enough suspense. But if you've seen
the original in any of its many manifestations, I can't imagine why
you'd want to see it again.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Taylor (Douglas) is the wealthy bond trader, married to
the accomplished Emily (Paltrow).
</P>
<P>
   Painfully not in love with her older husband, Emily is having a
mad, passionate affair with a mad, passionate artist (Viggo
Mortensen).
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas knows something about the artist that Emily does
not, and it fits perfectly into his scheme to murder his wife.
</P>
<P>
   How does Steven plan to kill Emily? Why is his scheme perfect?
And how will everything go wrong?
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't seen ``Dial M For Murder,''``'' I'm not going to
give away your only hope for excitement.
</P>
<P>
   If you have seen the original, Davis and his screenwriters come
up with a few twists on the basic idea, but not enough. All the key
elements remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   Davis doesn't drag out the proceedings, for which we can be
thankful. But he doesn't create sympathetic characters, either.
Emily, with whose plight we should identify, is really just a
younger version of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the movie's one big mystery: Why would Emily, who
is independently wealthy and an adviser to a United Nations
ambassador, have married in the first place a cold fish who is old
enough to be her killer's father?
</P>
<P>
   Looks like more Hollywood vanity at work here.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Douglas, he could have mailed in his role from
outtakes of ``The Game,'' ``Disclosure'' and ``Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Paltrow, I like her as much as the next guy. But not in
every other movie.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't it occur to anyone in Hollywood that having Paltrow star
in four movies in less than six months is at least three movies too
many?
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow can concurrently be seen (doing much better) in
``Sliding Doors.'' If ``Great Expectations'' and ``Hush'' hadn't
been such bad pictures, she might be on four screens at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Mortensen (``G.I. Jane``) is most notable for winning the
cleft-chin award, outclefting both Douglas and Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   If you have somehow missed seeing ``Dial M for Murder,'' you
should find ``A Perfect Murder'' an imperfect but sufficient
suspense film.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have seen the original in any form, watching the copy
is like having to research a compare-and-contrast term paper for a
college class you really don't like.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Perfect Murder'' is rated R for violence, sex and profanity.
2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
