<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4790 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TALES-MOVIES-AZR &LR;      06-04 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALES-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TALES' SEQUEL CONTINUES ORIGINAL SAGA  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The 1994 PBS miniseries ``Tales of the City ''drew
firefrom conservative activists for its frank depiction of sex (gay
and straight) and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The hubbub clearly spooked PBS _ at the time under fire from
budget-axing congressional critics _ which passed on the sequel,
</P>
<P>
   ``Armistead Maupin's More Tales of the City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it personally, on a number of levels,'' said Maupin, to
a gathering of TV critics earlier this year. ``What maddened me
about PBS' betrayal of ``Tales of the City'' was the fact that they
weren't honest about it. Basically, they were put into a position
where they had a choice between pleasing their viewers or appeasing
their enemies, and they chose to appease their enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were caught in a sort of crossfire of the cultural wars,
and rather than saying, `We can't do this because we've been
officially censored by the legislatures of Georgia and Oklahoma,
and because we got bomb threats in Chattanooga, and because we're
afraid that PBS won't exist next year if we stick up for this
program,' they made excuses about funding and how they didn't do
sequels.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter the pay cable network Showtime, which could be the ideal
outlet for the follow-up. Maupin, for one, believes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this as a joyous occasion,'' he said. ``I look at
this as something that's going to excite a lot of people who are
going to want to hear this story keep being told. I really have not
thought of it in the political way for some time now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a great story to tell here, and I'm going to
get a chance to tell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're doing it in a way that I've always wanted to do it,
which is to show that this is about love, this is about affection,
this is about people connecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Maupin's first ``Tales'' _ originally told in the mid-1970s as a
serial in the ``San Francisco Chronicle,'' later published in a
series of books _ knitted together the lives of an odd but likable
collection of San Francisco-dwelling folks.
</P>
<P>
   The follow-up continues their stories (with a few minor cast
changes) in the same dreamy style as the original. Though ``More
Tales'' departs for a few remote locations, San Francisco and its
live-and-let-live mood remains an important element in the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lean a lot on the gay stuff because it's my own personal
thing, but what I'm really proud of is the fact that the story has,
from the beginning, attempted to create a very large canvas that
includes everyone,'' Maupin said. ``That is the point of it. That
you get to see the ways in which their lives are parallel, and the
way they interconnect and the way they form a family in spite of
their enormous differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, that's a model that broadcast television is just
beginning to understand. That you can do this. That this is
possible. This doesn't offend anybody. This is about the way the
world works. This is the way our own lives work. We all know each
other. We're out there, functioning together in the world, and
there's no reason that you shouldn't be able to see it on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Postscript: ``Armistead Maupin's More Tales of the City''
officially premieres Sunday, but was stealth-scheduled by Showtime
in late night last week, likely so it could qualify for this
season's Emmy Awards. The Emmy window closed May 31. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4791 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LILIES-MOVIES-AZR &LR;      06-04 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILIES-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATRICAL TWIST ENHANCES EFFECT OF `LILIES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - ``Lilies'' is about a gay love triangle in
turn-of-the-century Canada. Yet it is not the subject matter that
will put off most viewers. Its subject is handled fairly tamely by
the standards of most current movies.
</P>
<P>
   But this English-language Canadian film plays more like it has
subtitles than most foreign films.
</P>
<P>
   It is a highly stylized film, slow moving and full of high
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   It begins in 1952, when a hardened convict asks a noted bishop
to come to the prison for confession. It isn't the convict's
confession we are to receive, but the priest's.
</P>
<P>
   The main portion of the story, set in 1912, tells of an
adolescent homosexual love triangle among the bishop, the convict
and another boy, who is killed.
</P>
<P>
   These flashbacks are given to us as a theatrical presentation by
a cast of convicts. They dress up, build scenery and establish a
difficult, convoluted story that eventually breaks out of the
prison into live-action flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The shifting between ``realistic'' and theatrical flashbacks is
a surprisingly cinematic effect and, once you get used to it, quite
effective. Especially when you see the same convicts, all male,
playing both men and women in the ``real'' world.
</P>
<P>
   There is no outlandish drag act here. These are very fine actors
playing female parts, much like must have happened in Shakespeare's
day. Indeed, although every actor in the film is excellent, perhaps
the most outstanding work is turned in by Brent Carver as The
Countess, mother of the boy who is killed. He-she is a figure of
tremendous pathos. Carver won a Tony award for his work in ``Kiss
of the Spider Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   When she hears her son has taken a job, she recoils: ``Working?
That most vile and infamous of occupations.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is the closest to humor this movie offers. Mostly, it
is slow moving people in pain, beautifully photographed.
</P>
<P>
   It can be very hard to sit through ``Lilies'' _ especially the
slower first half _ but it will be hard to forget, sticking in your
imagination the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The film is unrated and contains brief nudity and adult subject
matter. 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-BANKING-700&AMP;AD     06-04 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-BANKING-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ADEPTLY, FINANCIAL SERVICES LEADERS LOBBY FOR BANKING BILL  js) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In all the cheerleading about legislation to rewrite the
nation's banking laws, one of the loudest voices belongs to Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co., which, each week, takes out a back-page ad in the
Washington political journal The Hill, a must read for the Capitol
Hill crowd.
</P>
<P>
   In banner type, Merrill proclaims: ``The American People Support
Financial Services Reform'' and ``Pass HR 10 Financial Services
Reform.'' A few days after the House did just that, Merrill
followed with: ``Congratulations to the House on HR 10.''
</P>
<P>
   If back-page ads are part of the tea leaves of Washington,
Merrill's ads show some of the muscle coming into play as the bill
moves from the House to the Senate, where it will soon come before
the Senate Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   By passing House Resolution 10, a far-reaching measure that
would update banking law, the House achieved a remarkable victory.
For two decades, this legislation, which passed by just a single
vote in late May, has been a political hot potato in both chambers
and has never gained enough votes to pass _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   But with House approval and with the financial services industry
experiencing a series of high-profile mergers that challenge
existing laws _ most notably the proposed $70 billion union of
Travelers Group Inc. and Citicorp _ the focus is now on the Senate,
where there are signs of a shift in attitude. Though many say the
bill's chances of passage are still slim, a number of events have
come together that are now increasing its odds of gaining approval.
The bill, at its most basic, removes the last remaining barriers to
allowing banks, securities firms and insurance companies to merge
into huge financial services companies.
</P>
<P>
   After being visited a few weeks ago by three of Wall Street's
top leaders, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, announced that he was scheduling committee hearings on
June 17, the first step toward floor consideration. Significantly,
D'Amato put the measure on the fast track and then followed it up
by having the group _ composed of Sanford Weill, chairman of
Travelers; David Komansky, Merrill's chief executive; and Philip
Purcell, chief executive of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter _ meet with
Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, who said he would set aside
time for floor debate.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of the three executives, dealing with the Senate
leaders was like pushing on an open door. According to those in the
meeting, the men did not even have to make their pitch. Before
opening their mouths, D'Amato told them what he would do: hold
hearings, issue a strong statement in support of the measure, and,
most important, try to broker a compromise between Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan,
over a regulatory battle that is the bill's main stumbling block.
The two are expected to testify at the D'Amato hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, D'Amato's announcement on the hearings was made
with Paul Sarbanes of Maryland, the ranking Democrat on the Senate
Banking Committee, who has switched his longstanding opposition and
now supports the bill. The three executives were also directed by
D'Amato to meet with Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, another key
Senate Democrat, who pledged to work for the measure, but predicted
it would be ``tough.''
</P>
<P>
   For D'Amato, who prides himself on being ``Senator Pothole,''
the gesture was a way to deliver an election-year package to Wall
Street and the banking community, which has poured millions into
his campaign coffers over the years and which employs more than
60,000 in New York with a payroll of $9 billion _ making it one of
his state's biggest industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working really hard on this bill,'' said Jack Morris, a
spokesman for Citicorp, which has one of Washington's biggest
lobbying operations, with a budget of $4.4 million as of mid-1997,
the most recent numbers available. The Citicorp-Travelers union
would not necessarily be halted if this legislation does not pass.
But the two companies might have to restructure the deal within
five years if the law is not changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're facing a real window of opportunity,'' Morris added.
``We've been around this issue for a long time and we do think
there seems to be a desire to move ahead. The fact that hearings
have been scheduled for early June is very positive.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So far, the feud between the Federal Reserve and Treasury
remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, as it left the House, would make the Federal
Reserve the main regulator by having the banking system set up in a
holding company structure with many new financial activities run
out of bank affiliates. Rubin prefers a structure in which the new
activities could also be run out of bank operating subsidiaries,
which have closer ties to the banking parent. Under this structure,
the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, a division of the
Treasury, would be the top regulator. Rubin said he would recommend
a presidential veto of the current measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are arguing that banking organizations ought to have an
option,'' Julie Williams, the acting comptroller, said. ``We are
not arguing they should be forced to do it one way or another, or
that they should be forced to do things so that only we have
jurisdiction. We think banking organizations ought to have the
choice of the most effective way to conduct their activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime observers say a compromise between the Federal
Reserve and Treasury is possible _ and necessary. ``I don't think
this is one of those issues that is like an on-off switch,'' said
Cory Strupp, a managing director and chief lobbyist at J.P. Morgan
&AMP; Co., which supports the bill. ``There certainly is room for
compromise. Any company in financial services likes to have as much
flexibility as possible. Regulatory diversity has served our
industry well. The key is having the Treasury and the Fed come to
some mutually agreeable solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Big banks like Banc One, BankAmerica , Nationsbank and U.S.
Bancorp support the bill, as do the insurance industry and Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in the financial services industry backs the bill.
Small bankers, represented by the Independent Bankers Association
of America, oppose it. But Kenneth Guenther, the group's chief
lobbyist, said his group's opposition had softened since many
amendments were added on the House floor, primarily one to outlaw
any combination of banking and industrial businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our opposition is becoming a closer call,'' Guenther said,
adding that ``everything is in a state of flux.''
</P>
<P>
   The strongest opposition comes from the American Bankers
Association. Edward Yingling, the group's chief lobbyist, said that
his group opposes having the Federal Reserve as the main regulator
and that the Senate calendar is too rushed to get a bill enacted
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this gets worked out this year,'' Yingling said.
``Trying to do so would be like threading the eye of the needle,
and there is just no time for it. I doubt you could pass one of the
most important bills in the business arena in decades with the
Senate calendar we're facing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
