<HEADLINE>
IS REAL QUIET READY FOR GALLOP?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ If you handicapped horses based on the analytical
bent of their trainers, you'd bet Elliott Walden's Victory Gallop
over Bob Baffert's Real Quiet in the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is widely known as quick with a quip, but the one-liners
burst from a sometimes scattered mind. Those of us who transcribe
his quotes notice that he speaks almost entirely in sentence
fragments and asides.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert also seems to be carried away with his newfound
celebrity, stepping over the bounds of good taste in the name of
comedy. He referred to rival trainer Sonny Hine's ``Elmer Fudd
voice'' and said Walden looks like the guy in high school who
couldn't get a date.
</P>
<P>
   So what if Walden is a pasty 6-foot-4 and wears thick glasses?
Talk with him, and you realize the recent Churchill Downs training
champion is a very sharp 35-year-old. He emits optimism but not
rhetoric. A product of a prominent Kentucky horse-breeding family,
he found fascination not in bloodlines but in trying to pick
winners at the track. Therefore his prerace comments are
levelheaded and rational. If his colt Victory Gallop doesn't win
Saturday, he'll know the reason why.
</P>
<P>
   While Real Quiet is trying to be the first Triple Crown winner
since Affirmed in 1978, Victory Gallop is trying to avoid being the
only horse other than Alydar in the same year to finish second in
all three races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things can (be reversed),'' Walden said here this
week. ``This might be pie in the sky, but I still think we ought to
have won the (Kentucky) Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Forced to rally on the far outside, Victory Gallop nearly caught
Real Quiet in the slow, :26 3/5 final quarter mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He beat us soundly in the Preakness, but I feel like we should
be split going into the Belmont,'' said Walden, the cast on his
right ankle, dislocated in a pickup basketball game, resting on a
trunk in D. Wayne Lukas' tack room.
</P>
<P>
   Walden doesn't think, as some analysts do, that jockey Gary
Stevens erred by challenging the Preakness pacesetters too early.
He notes that before the Derby, Victory Gallop raced close to the
lead with success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Real Quiet ran a monster race, that he moved forward
off the Derby, and we didn't,'' he said. ``I think (Victory Gallop)
had such a big effort at the Derby, he leveled off at Pimlico. Real
Quiet ran the kind of race in the Preakness that we ran in the
Derby. So I hope it's his turn to level off.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden thinks Lukas-trained Grand Slam, who is 4 for 4 at
Belmont and 0 for 4 elsewhere, must be respected because of that
statistic.
</P>
<P>
   He also has more respect for Real Quiet than some of his
colleagues, who question the colt's Triple Crown credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if he does win, Real Quiet, then he's a deserving
Triple Crown winner,'' Walden said. ``Or, if we beat him, then it
means we should have won the Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop came out of the Preakness a worn-out horse. He
developed a severe rash. But both conditions are behind him now,
Walden said.
</P>
<P>
   If that's so _ and with Walden's earnest delivery it's hard not
to believe him _ then Prestonwood Farm's horse certainly is the
leading threat to spoil the Triple Crown bid of the deserving
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop should like the extreme, 1{-mile course. His
sire, Cryptoclearance, was the runner-up to Bet Twice in the 1987
Belmont. Of course, that could also mean Victory Gallop is bred to
finish second.
</P>
<P>
   At Hollywood Park: The gates and betting windows will open at 11
a.m. Saturday, the first Hollywood Park race will be at 1:20 p.m.
Two stakes will be on the card, the Cinema Handicap and the Melair.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Grade I Gamely Breeders' Cup Handicap for fillies
and mares, whose recent winners include Eclipse Award winners
Hollywood Wildcat (1994) and Possibly Perfect ('95).
</P>
<P>
   The undercard: The three other stakes on the Belmont Stakes
program will include some top horses and names familiar to Southern
Californians.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-furlong Riva Ridge sprint features the return of
Coronado's Quest, who was injured on the eve of challenging Real
Quiet in the Preakness. Orville N Wilbur's wasn't entered in the
race after he made like Coronado's Quest, acting up so badly on the
track that he couldn't complete a scheduled workout.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan Handicap on turf has Chief Bearhart, winner of the
Breeders' Cup Turf last fall at Hollywood Park. Kent Desormeaux,
back in trainer Bobby Frankel's good graces, will ride Kirkwall.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-furlong True North has Kelly Kip and two California
veterans, Boundless Moment and Trafalger.
</P>
<P>
   The Just a Game, for fillies and mares on turf, finds Desormeaux
and Neil Drysdale teaming up with Dance Parade.
</P>
</TEXT>
