<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ The Supreme Court denies
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's request for expedited
consideration of Secret Service and attorney-client privileges in
his investigation of sex-and-perjury allegations at the White
House. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-BILL (Washington) _ The Senate is expected to consider
provisions of the tobacco bill that would raise billions of dollars
through a new fee on cigarettes, including efforts by Republicans
and Democrats to link tax cuts to the legislation. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTIONS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Looking at the ``Super
Tuesday'' primaries in eight states, Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas,
chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, tells
what he thinks the results mean for the Democrats' bid to retake
the House. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-DRUG-TESTS (Washington) _ Reps. Gerald B.H. Solomon,
R-N.Y., and Joe Barton, R-Texas, propose legislation that would
require members of Congress and their staff members to submit to
random drug tests, a practice that goes on in other branches of
government. Opponents question the constitutionality of such a
requirement. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-PRAYER (Washington) _ The House is scheduled to vote on a
constitutional amendment to allow voluntary prayer in schools. The
amendment is expected to fail. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   AGRICULTURE-HOUSE (Washington) _ The House is poised to approve
an agriculture bill that includes funding for the food stamp
program. The measure has already been approved by the Senate. By
GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   TIANANMEN-ANNIVERSARY (Washington) _ Rep. Nancy Pelosi,
D-Calif., and Sens. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark.,
and Russell Feingold, D-Wis., urge President Clinton not to go to
China later this month. But if he does, they say, he should not go
to Tiananmen Square, where hundreds of democracy demonstrators were
killed nine years ago by Beijing troops. By EUN LEE KOH. (Already
filed)
</P>
<P>
   ACT-UP (Washington) _ Act Up, a confrontational AIDS activist
group, marches to the White House, carrying a casket with the body
of its Washington, D.C., chapter founder, Steve Michael, who died
of AIDS last week. The group charges that President Clinton ``has
lied to and betrayed people with AIDS.'' By EUN LEE KOH. (Already
filed)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-MIR (Houston) _ The space shuttle Discovery docks with
the Russian space station Mir on the ninth and final trip by an
American space shuttle to the aging Russian outpost. By MARK
CARREAU. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   FAKE-ASTRONAUT (Houston) _ A Texas man explains the
circumstances of his arrest for falsely claiming to be an astronaut
and gaining access to some of the Johnson Space Center's secret
areas. NASA officials have downplayed the security breach but admit
that he could have created problems after gaining access to a
computer console. By JAKE DYER.
</P>
<P>
   FROG-DEFORMITY (Moss Hill, Texas) _ The brown frog was so tiny _
less than an inch in length _ that Matt Whitbeck wouldn't have paid
any attention except it was maneuvering more like a spider. The
reason: It had five limbs. Dr. David Gardiner, a molecular
biologist at the University of California at Irvine, says, ``This
is the first live one I've had to study. Everybody's coming in to
look at it.'' Scientists started tracking such malformed frogs
about five years ago. By CINDY HORSWELL. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   KID-TRIAL (Dallas) _ A jury verdict is expected in the trial of
an 11-year-old student charged with sexually assaulting a
3-year-old girl in Dallas. Two brothers, ages 7 and 8, testified
earlier that they helped the fourth-grader assault the little girl.
By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
