<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILOT-RETIRES05-BUS-C     06-04 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOT-RETIRES05-BUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veteran pilot fights FAA's retire at 60 rule
 &HT;    By Doug Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ LEARN TO FLY. The image of that
flight-school advertisement is forever fused with Frank Murphy's
childhood memory of roaring through the clouds in an old biplane
with his father at the controls.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy saw the sign each time he shuttled between New Jersey and
Alabama as a young engineer testing guidance systems at the NASA
design center in the 1960s. The sign, and the memory, tugged at him
until he finally walked into the Huntsville Flying Service and
signed up.
</P>
<P>
   A little less than three years later, on April Fool's Day 1969,
he quit his engineer's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided there was no point working if I could fly for a
living,'' he says. ``I don't think of flying as work. I think of
flying as art.''
</P>
<P>
   At 29, he got a late start at a lucky time. Six months after he
started ferrying cargo, his boss bought a fleet of surplus
piston-engine planes and started Span East Airlines. Murphy became
a commercial pilot.
</P>
<P>
   He's had a thrilling if occasionally bumpy ascent since.
Airlines have vanished around him, but Murphy's love of flying,
travel and adventure is stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like doing this,'' he says. ``I love doing this. There's
nothing else I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What hurts is the increasing sense that no one else really
cares.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 30, 1999
</P>
<P>
   This calendar page is the vision now fixed in Murphy's mind.
That day, his 60th birthday, he will become too feeble or addled or
simply incompetent to do what he loves.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Federal Aviation Administration rule book says,
regardless of what any doctor or inspector or Murphy himself
thinks. Murphy says he has no trouble passing his twice-yearly FAA
physicals and flight-simulator tests, and doesn't expect to.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes no sense,'' Murphy says. ``How can I be perfectly
capable of flying on Oct. 29 but not the next day?''
</P>
<P>
   The more he talks about it, the more agitated and disbelieving
he becomes. How can it come down to this? A mere 16 months. At the
least, he ought to get credit for the last three months he's spent
waiting to fly again.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who has lived in Miami since 1970, flew for Air Florida
and then for Carnival Air Lines. He stayed when the lettering on
the planes changed to Pan Am, but his job ended when the airline
filed for bankruptcy in February. He's been told he'll be flying
for Pan Am again sometime this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about flying again, but I know it won't be for
long,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's age limit has been a point of contention since it was
imposed in 1959. The agency says there is no certain way to
determine the age at which health and skills deteriorate
dangerously. So, the agency argues, it's safest to draw an early
line.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous pilots and pilot groups have challenged the rule with
studies showing that older pilots fly safely in other parts of the
world and can be tested as reliably as younger pilots.
</P>
<P>
   As for slowed reflexes, Murphy cautions against thinking in
terms of evasive maneuvers on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn to avoid those sort of quick motions in a cockpit,''
Murphy says. ``In 30 years, you learn to avoid problems as well as
deal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest and, to Murphy, most discouraging word came from the
U.S. Supreme Court last month. Two pilots, backed by a group called
the Professional Pilots Federation, sued to overturn the age limit
as illegal discrimination, but they lost and the Supreme Court
refused to consider their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurt,'' Murphy says. ``I guess I believed you could count
on the courts to protect the rights of the minority even when the
executive and legislative branches won't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Line Pilots Association, the union representing 49,000
pilots, opposed the rule for decades but now supports it. (Requests
for the union's comment on the Supreme Court decision went
unanswered.)
</P>
<P>
   To Murphy and other older pilots, the reason for the union's
turn-around is clear: Younger pilots, a majority of the union's
members, have a financial incentive to push the older pilots out.
</P>
<P>
   Because of flying's rigid seniority system, the only way to move
into the highest-paying jobs is for someone up ahead to retire.
</P>
<P>
   And getting to those jobs is important, because one of the major
influences on retirement pay is a pilot's final salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many younger pilots want to clear the path for
themselves,'' Murphy says. ``They don't think they'll ever turn
60.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did he.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who says he has a little bit of Indiana Jones in him,
talks enthusiastically about the days when he and a pal flew
plantains from Ecuador in an old DC-7.
</P>
<P>
   But he's just as enthusiastic about more recent adventures,
including summers based in Egypt and Turkey under Pan Am contracts
with airlines in those countries.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he's been talking more often and more forcefully, trying
to persuade as many people as he can that the age limit should be
repealed. He even showed up on CNN, but he also will make his case
one listener at a time.
</P>
<P>
   He carries a briefcase full of magazine articles, studies and
charts to support his position. One of them underscores the
difficulty he has finding sympathy. It shows that pilots for top
carriers can earn $3 million to $9 million over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asking you to cry for pilots,'' he says. ``But
remember: that figure is for 30 years. A lot of guys flying for
Eastern, Braniff and a lot of other airlines never got there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of pilots who have been bounced from job to job or who
always worked for smaller airlines really do need to work. The
FAA's age limit doesn't make them eligible for early Social
Security retirement or disability benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who is single, is ready to retire financially but not
emotionally. So he'll find a way to keep flying past Oct. 30, 1999
_ in Central America or Europe or some other place that will show
confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to leave my country, but I'm going to be flying
something, somewhere,'' he says. ``Why would I want to retire? I
never really worked.''
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-03-98 1017E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
