<SLUG> BC-SAPORTA05-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. envoy to Canada boosts Atlanta
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When Atlanta's own Gordon Giffin, now U.S. ambassador
to Canada, saw former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young Thursday at the
Commerce Club, the first thing he asked was, ``Are you still on the
board of Delta Air Lines?''
</P>
<P>
   After Young answered, ``yes,'' Giffin made an impassioned plea
for Delta to start flights from Atlanta to Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Not only would such a flight help him get back and forth, but
more importantly, it would further establish Atlanta as an
important base of exchange between the United States and Canada,
particularly in high technology.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just Delta that Giffin is targeting. In his mind,
the opportunities of business and academic exchanges between
Atlanta and Canada are endless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta can be the platform of hemispheric trade between
Canada and Latin America,'' Giffin said. ``While I'm in Canada,
there's no better opportunity to make this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the message Giffin sounded in a private talk to the
influential Commerce Club board.
</P>
<P>
   And it is a message he wants to broadcast while he is
ambassador, a post he expects to hold for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he is pleased his friend and fellow Democrat, Gov.
Zell Miller, will be spending two days in Ottawa on a mission this
month, when Giffin will introduce him to Canada's high-tech
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   He welcomes people from Atlanta to come to Canada to find
opportunities to strengthen their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not have joint ventures between Georgia and Canadian
companies pointed toward Latin America?'' he asked. ``I'm
soliciting business. There's never been the same sort of
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Canada and the United States enjoy the biggest trading
relationship in history _ $370 billion a year, more than all the
European Community countries combined.
</P>
<P>
   Giffin said he sees many U.S. business leaders in Canada but not
many from the Southeast _ something he intends to change. He also
is trying to get President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore (both
Southerners) to go on separate trips to Canada in the next couple
of years.
</P>
<P>
   Giffin has that pull because he has been a longtime insider in
state and national Democratic circles. He chaired the Clinton-Gore
campaign in Georgia in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Town talk
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the success of the Woodruff Arts Center corporate
campaign topping $6 million came from a new segment _ workplace
giving.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign pitches are being made to employees or managers at
several major companies in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For example, BellSouth's workplace giving totaled $133,000.
BellSouth also gave a corporate gift of $225,000. Other companies
doing workplace campaigns include Equifax, SunTrust, National Data,
Georgia Power and SunTrust.
</P>
<P>
   But the top corporate donors continue to be top companies in
Atlanta. Coca-Cola gave $300,000; Georgia Power, $250,000; Cox
Enterprises and related interests, $142,000; NationsBank, $140,000;
Wachovia, $140,000; SunTrust, $125,000; Home Depot, $105,000; and
United Parcel Service, $100,000. New to the top level is Deloitte &AMP;
Touche at $105,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Levy, managing partner of King &AMP; Spalding, announced Tim
Reis has joined the firm as counsel in the intellectual property
and technology area.
</P>
<P>
   Reis formerly held in-house counsel positions at United Parcel
Service and Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
</P>
<P>
   Reis will have responsibility for patent matters and electronic
commerce, Internet and computer security matters.
</P>
<P>
   NBA superstar Shaquille O'Neal has teamed with Atlanta-based
Boys &AMP; Girls Club of America, giving $1 million to launch
technology centers in 100 Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs nationwide over the
next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The centers will cost more than $15 million, and O'Neal, a Boys
&AMP; Girls Club alum, has pledged to help raise the remaining $14
million.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Office of University Partnerships has announced
the retirement of Thomas K. Hamall, its director. Andrea Ashmore,
formerly of Spelman College, will take on duties as special
assistant to the president and director of university partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   The program seeks to expand Georgia Tech's outreach in the
Atlanta community. Hamall headed the Atlanta Chamber of Commerce in
the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Chapter of the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation
International awarded the 1997-98 Volunteer of the Year honor to
David I. Roos Jr. Roos is president of Melvin S. Roos &AMP; Co. Inc.,
an Atlanta-based store fixture company. The Georgia Chapter raised
$1.5 million in special events this year to help find a cure for
diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: msaporta(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
