<SLUG> BC-LOGCABINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK SERVICE PUSHES TO SAVE LOG CABINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Lincoln lived in one, and Gen. Ulysses S.
Grant directed the last campaigns of the Civil War from another.
</P>
<P>
   Log cabins are part of the American tradition, but now many of
them are crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the National Park Service announced a
public-private partnership to save more than 400 log structures on
parkland, beginning with the Gatekeeper's Cabin on the North Rim of
the Grand Canyon in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The one-story, Depression-era cabin is deteriorating, its logs
rotting after insect infestation and 67 years of temperatures
ranging from 20 degrees below zero to 95 above. The cabin, which
boasts a central stone fireplace and front and side porches, is
used as housing for members of the park's seasonal staff.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin's restoration, scheduled for this summer, is part of a
$1 million project targeting log cabins in more than 300 U.S. parks
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The project, in partnership with the Ohio-based owner of Log
Cabin brand syrup, is more about history than housing.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of log cabins were built during the Revolutionary War
as schools, churches, mills and barns. Log construction allowed
Western boomtowns to pop up almost overnight. Supporters of 1840
presidential candidate William Henry Harrison successfully used the
log cabin as a campaign symbol. The Civilian Conservation Corps
used log construction extensively during the 1930s and 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these cabins date back to the late 19th century and
are related to our nation's historic leaders and events, as well as
the evolution of our national park system,'' said Grand Canyon
Superintendent Rob Arnberger, who traveled to Washington for the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rotted logs, crumbling stone foundations and leaking roofs are
threatening the structural integrity of many log structures,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The North Rim cabin will be rebuilt with an eye on historical
accuracy. For example, a concrete porch will be removed and
replaced with one of wood, similar to the original. Workers will
use tools, material and techniques from a bygone era.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial aspect of the project reflects a budget reality:
National parks can't make it on government money alone. Log Cabin
syrup labels and advertising will provide details on how the public
can contribute.
</P>
<P>
   The project will be overseen by the National Park Foundation, a
partner of the National Park Service that raises private-sector
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Log cabins, although they are regarded as quintessentially
American, did not originate in the United States, according to
historians. The style was introduced by Finnish and Swedish
settlers in the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   Public donations to the project may be made to the National Park
Foundation, P.O. Box 2735, Ridgely, MD, 21681. Information also is
available at www.nationalparks.org on the Internet. &QL; 
Jeff Barker can be reached at 202-662-7264 or at
jeff.barker(at)pni.com on the Internet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILOT-VIOLATIONS-COX     06-04 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOT-VIOLATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One pilot in crash over Cobb had FAA violations
 &HT;    By Doug Payne
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The pilot of the single-engine plane that collided in
mid-air with an executive jet over Cobb County had four citations
for violations of Federal Aviation Administration regulations on
his record, and his license had been suspended twice, according to
FAA records.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolf Hartwig Duncan, last surrendered his license for 60 days
in 1994, according to documents obtained by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution through a request under the Freedom of
Information Act.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, 44, was an experienced pilot with more than 10,000 hours
of flying time and may have been conducting an aerial inspection of
electrical lines for Georgia Power when the mid-air tragedy
occurred April 4. Duncan and four persons in the jet died.
</P>
<P>
   He first came to the attention of FAA enforcers in 1982, when he
was cited for failing to lower his landing gear before making a
landing at an unspecified airport in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   FAA spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen said her agency could not
comment on a specific pilot's record. But according to the FAA's
flight standards office, ``most pilots go through their entire
career without a violation,'' she said. But others in the general
aviation industry said the violations were no indicator of pilot
ability.
</P>
<P>
   The collision between Duncan's Cessna 172 Skyhawk and a Cessna
Citation jet killed Duncan and four attorneys with the Atlanta law
firm of Dow, Lohnes &AMP; Albertson. The jet was piloted by one of the
attorneys, Marion ``Chip'' Allen, 53.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys all represented Cox Enterprises, which owns The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The collision is still being investigated by the National
Transportation Safety Board, and will not be completed for at least
another three months, an agency spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Every aspect of the collision is being examined, including the
equipment on both planes. The engines have been examined and no
problems were found, saidPreston Hicks, the lead NTSB investigator
on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are also looking at the pilots' flight records.
Allen, the pilot of the private jet, had no violations over his
1,500 hours of logged flight time.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, a Cumming resident, was licensed for single- and
multi-engine aircraft and had a commercial pilot's license as well
as certification as an airframe and powerplant mechanic. He had
flown aerial surveys for a number of years, FAA records show. It
was while flying an aerial inspection of AT&AMP;T power lines that he
ran afoul of the FAA on July 12, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   That day he took off from Greenville, S.C., in the same airplane
that five years later would be involved in the crash above Cobb
County.
</P>
<P>
   He soon radioed the tower at Charlotte International Airport
that his engine was ``running rough'' and that he needed priority
routing to the airport. The tower cleared his route and as soon as
Duncan landed FAA inspectors went out to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   They questioned his failure to land at a closer airport, but
more seriously they found he was flying without a current medical
certificate or pilot's license. They also found that his Skyhawk,
which had undergone some modifications, had never been recertified
as airworthy.
</P>
<P>
   They determined that the plane's condition violated FAA
regulations on several counts:
</P>
<P>
   It didn't have an identification plate affixed to the fuselage;
</P>
<P>
   The plane carried no current list of equipment on board;
</P>
<P>
   Gas tank openings were not properly marked;
</P>
<P>
   On the instrument panel, the compass was not clearly marked;
</P>
<P>
   And the plane wasn't equipped with an emergency locator
transmitter, a device that helps rescuers find the airplane in case
of a crash.
</P>
<P>
   For those violations, Duncan surrendered his license for 60 days
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB investigators looking into the April 4 collision have
already said that another required electronic device was not
working on Duncan's plane that day: he was flying without a
functioning transponder, which helps air traffic controllers
identify individual airplanes on their radar screens. All aircraft
flying within about 30 miles of Atlanta must have a working
transponder under FAA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known whether the device was broken or simply never
turned on. Had the device been in operation, ``there would have
been a lot better chance of (crash) avoidance,'' NTSB board member
George Black said after the collision.
</P>
<P>
   The company that Duncan flew for when he incurred the 1993
violation, Brentco Inc. of Canton, Ohio, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power spokesman John Sell acknowledged that the utility
company did have a contractual relationship with Duncan. However,
he said, ``it has not been determined whether he was flying for
us'' on the day of the collision. Noting that the accident is still
under investigation, he declined further comment on the accident or
Duncan's flying record with Georgia Power.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA also suspended Duncan's license for 30 days in 1987 and
ordered it suspended it again for 45 days in 1990. However, the
1990 penalty was later waived. Records concerning those incidents
have been destroyed by the FAA, which routinely disposes of records
beyond a certain age, said Bergen, the FAA spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Also destroyed were records detailing a wheels-up landing Duncan
made in 1982. The violation is indicated in his certification file,
with the notation that he was ``counseled on use of a checklist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unusual to have that many violations, but it might be
tempered by his type of flying,'' said Dr. Vernon Grose, a former
member of the NTSB board and White House advisor on aviation
issues.
</P>
<P>
   In his line of work, Duncan was ``using an aerial position to
look down for problems in wiring. Flying the airplane may be a
secondary, rather than a primary consideration for him,'' Grose
said.
</P>
<P>
   In that type of flying, Grose noted, the pilot's attention is
focused on the ground and ``he isn't thinking particularly about
other air traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of an electronic beacon on board the aircraft showed he
was ``careless about certification of the airplane,'' Grose said.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's former father-in-law, Jack Steiner of Gainesville, said
Duncan was well-respected as a pilot. He said the violations on
Duncan's record were minor incidents that occurred early in his
career and never put other people nor Duncan's job at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a professional flier. There was nothing wrong with his
flying capabilities,'' Steiner said. ``Everybody loved that guy.
Everybody respected him. His life was flying. As long as he was
flying he was happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Private aviation industry authorities said number of FAA
citations against Duncan could be explained by the long hours he
logged in the air _ much like a professional truck driver who
spends more hours on the road is more likely to be stopped by
police. FAA regulations limit commercial airline pilots to no more
than 1,000 hours of flight time a year.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Morningstar, director of media relations for the Aircraft
Owners and Pilots Association, a general aviation advocacy
organization, said that ``any infraction of regulations is serious.
As a group, pilots are very concerned about flying according to
regulations and flying safely.''
</P>
<P>
   But based on what is known of Duncan's record, he said,
``there's nothing there that I would say pointed to careless
operation that would have affected the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
