A4809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     06-04 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT REBUFFS STARR'S EFFORTS FOR SPEEDY RULINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Thursday put the brakes on
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's effort to quickly settle two
legal disputes delaying his investigation of an alleged
presidential affair and cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   The nine justices decided to let the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the District of Columbia have a crack at resolving whether
President Clinton's most trusted adviser and three Secret Service
employees must testify before a federal grand jury in the Monica
Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is assumed that the Court of Appeals will proceed
expeditiously to decide this case,'' the justices said in a
two-paragraph statement rejecting Starr's request for fast-track
rulings on attorney-client privilege and creation of a so-called
``protective privilege'' for the Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   If the Supreme Court had agreed to take either case, it would
have been only the sixth time this century that an issue was
considered vital enough to abandon the normal appeals process. One
of those cases involved President Truman's seizure of steel mills
during the Korean War. Another led to the release of the Watergate
tapes, which prompted the 1974 resignation of President Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Although no schedule has been set for filing briefs or hearing
arguments, the Washington-based U.S. Court of Appeals could set
both privilege cases for next month. However, any rulings could
then be appealed to the Supreme Court, which means the issues of
testimony from presidential aide Bruce Lindsey and the Secret
Service would not be resolved before late autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigators believe Lindsey, a Clinton confidante for
30 years who serves as deputy White House counsel, can provide key
information about what the president knew and did after learning of
secretly tape recorded conversations in which Lewinsky reportedly
told a friend about an 18-month affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to shield Lindsey from having to answer Starr's questions
before the grand jury, Clinton first cited executive privilege,
then invoked lawyer-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Chief U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, after
reviewing sealed evidence, ruled last month that Starr's need for
Lindsey's testimony outweighs both executive and lawyer-client
privilege claims.
</P>
<P>
   The judge issued the same decision concerning Starr's efforts to
secure the cooperation of a Secret Service lawyer and two Secret
Service uniformed officers who were on duty at the times Lewinsky
allegedly met with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service director Lewis Merletti has said forcing Secret
Service personnel to testify will ``substantially undermine, if not
destroy,'' the trust presidents have in their protectors, making
presidents ``more vulnerable to assassination.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued after the Supreme Court decision Thursday,
Starr said his team of investigators and prosecutors ``will
continue to take every reasonable and practicable step to bring out
the relevant facts as promptly as possible, so this investigation
can be concluded in a thorough and expeditious manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision was cheered by the White House, which
had argued against Starr's attempt to shortcut the normal appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court acted appropriately today,'' said White
House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff, who has agreed to expedited
hearings at the Court of Appeals. ``Contrary to Mr. Starr's claims,
the governmental attorney-client privilege is not a `new'
privilege,'' Ruff said. ``It is well established that
confidentiality is the cornerstone of all attorney-client
communications.''
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Mike McCurry criticized Starr for
suddenly seeking to speed up this portion of his investigation of
the president. ``Today is day 1,400 of Ken Starr's tenure as
independent counsel at the rate of $30,000 a day of taxpayers'
money,'' McCurry said. ``If there's any delay, that's the delay
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr was appointed in 1994 to oversee an investigation of
Clinton's involvement in the failed Arkansas land deal called
Whitewater. The inquiry was expanded in January to include whether
the president lied under oath or urged others to cover-up his
relationship with Lewinsky, a former White House intern, or an
encounter with Democratic activist Kathleen Willey near the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Lewinsky have testified under oath that they never
had sex. Clinton also has said he never asked anyone to lie. Their
accounts allegedly are contradicted by the tapes in which Lewinsky
reportedly described engaging in oral sex with the president and
how he later encouraged her to lie when called to testify in a
sexual harassment lawsuit against him.
</P>
<P>
   At the federal courthouse, Democratic fund-raiser Nathan Landow
appeared before the grand jury to answer questions about his
contacts with Willey, who accused Clinton of fondling her breasts
and placing her hand on his crotch during a private meeting in
November 1993. Clinton denied any improper behavior during his
encounter with Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Landow, a wealthy Maryland developer, discussed with Willey what
she should say in Paula Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit, which was
dismissed two months ago. Landow has denied encouraging Willey to
lie about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   As he emerged from the courthouse, Landow declined comment
except to say: ``I'm done.''
</P>
<P>
   Also testifying Thursday was Sydney Blumenthal, a former
journalist and senior presidential adviser who was making his third
appearance before Starr's grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal appeared after the White House abandoned its claim
that executive privilege _ a president's right to receive
confidential advice from assistants _ should protect him from
having to answer prosecutor's questions.
</P>
<P>
   After Blumenthal's appearance, his attorneys announced that he
would have to return again and criticized the line of questioning
posed by Starr's deputies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was two hours of questions of `Up there at the White House,
do you talk about the Starr investigation?''' said William
McDaniel, one of Blumenthal's lawyers. The questioning turned to
Blumenthal's conversations with the president and first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton after about two hours of interrogation about
White House discussions of Starr and his deputies, McDaniel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation has become more about Starr than anything
else,'' McDaniel told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
