<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-MIDEAST-450&AMP;AD     06-04 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MIDEAST-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS OF U.S. PLAN TO RESTORE MIDEAST TALKS PUBLISHED IN ISRAEL  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SERGE SCHMEMANN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Two Israeli newspapers published details Thursday of
what they said was a U.S. plan that would finally restore
negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Neither U.S. nor Israeli officials would confirm the
authenticity of the reported plan, but they did say an agreement
could be reached in days.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, as reported by Haaretz and Maariv, retains the 13
percent withdrawal from the West Bank that the Palestinians and the
Clinton administration have insisted on as a minimum for a
resumption of talks.
</P>
<P>
   But it pairs the phased withdrawals with specific obligations on
the Palestinians to undertake security measures that Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has demanded, including confiscation of illegal
weapons in Palestinian territories and concrete procedures for
dealing with incitement, suspected terrorists and arms smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   The reported plan also includes separate ``understandings,'' one
of which is that Israel will build no new settlements and will not
allow ``significant'' expansion of existing settlements in the West
Bank. It is not clear whether such proposals have been presented by
the Americans in writing.
</P>
<P>
   The reports follow a flurry of diplomatic activities this week
by U.S., Palestinian and Israeli diplomats, including meetings in
London between Dennis Ross, the American Middle East mediator, and
two senior Palestinian negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   In Gaza, Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, made no specific
comment on the published plans, but said he hoped for movement by
mid-June. ``According to the American initiative, they promised
that the redeployment would be decided no later than the middle of
this month,'' he said. ``We hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Palestinians have agreed to a 13 percent withdrawal
by Israel, that encompasses only two of the three withdrawals
envisioned in the Oslo agreements. The scope of the third, which is
relegated in the proposal to ``a joint Palestinian-Israeli
committee,'' is reportedly still a matter of contention.
</P>
<P>
   Yet U.S. and Israeli officials seem optimistic that some break
is near in the 15-month deadlock, during which Washington has taken
an increasingly assertive role. In recent months the talks have
been essentially between the administration and Netanyahu, often
accompanied by ill-concealed irritation, threats and political
maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official said Thursday that a decision to resume
negotiations could be reached ``very shortly.'' And David
Bar-Illan, Netanyahu's communications director, said, ``I feel we
do think that if everything goes according to expectations, there
should be a package deal within a few days.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Netanyahu declared earlier this week that he would present a
withdrawal plan by the middle of the month, and was confident it
would receive the necessary support.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after so many setbacks over the past year, the possibility
of another one is strong. Netanyahu still has to contend with
Cabinet members who have vowed to block any deal that cedes more
than 9 percent of the West Bank, and Arafat could balk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a little bit more optimistic, but I've had so many
disappointments that I will wait before giving any
congratulations,'' President Ezer Weizman said after meeting with
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Though Netanyahu has strongly argued that a 13 percent pullback
would pose a serious threat to Israeli security, what evidently
made the latest proposal palatable was the extensive reciprocity _
a concept Netanyahu has repeatedly stressed _ between the Israeli
withdrawals and Palestinian actions against terror and anti-Israeli
incitement.
</P>
<P>
   As set out by David Makovsky, the diplomatic reporter for
Haaretz, the package proposes a three-stage plan over 12 weeks.
Talks on a final settlement, which under the Oslo accord are to be
completed by May 4, 1999, would begin immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Within the first five weeks, Israel would transfer 2 percent of
West Bank territory still under its control to full or partial
Palestinian control. At the same time, the executive committee of
the Palestine Liberation Organization would endorse a letter from
Arafat to President Clinton confirming changes in the Palestinian
Charter.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has insisted that changes voted by the Palestine
National Council two years ago did not satisfy the requirement to
rid the charter of its calls for Israel's destruction, and the U.S.
proposal appeared to fall short of his demand that the council be
convened again.
</P>
<P>
   During this period the Palestinians would also take specific
steps against incitement, while a U.S.-Palestinian committee would
determine the whereabouts of Palestinians who have committed
terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth week Israel would withdraw from a further 5
percent, while the Palestinians would confiscate illegal arms. In
the 12th week Israel would withdraw from another 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``understandings,'' in addition to constraints on
settlements, Israel would agree not to demolish Palestinian houses.
The Palestinians, for their part, would agree not to question
Israel's credentials at the United Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
