<HEADER>
A4815 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOXING-NOTEBOOK-COX     06-04 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXING-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Round by Round
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York -- Evander Holyfield is not quite fighting the battle
of the bulge. But as he gets older, he gets heavier.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield weighed in at 218 1/2 pounds Thursday for Saturday's
heavyweight title fight against Henry Akinwande, the heaviest of
his career. Holyfield weighed 218 for the second Mike Tyson fight
and 214 for his last bout against Michael Moorer. Akinwande, who at
6-foot-7 is four inches taller than Holyfield, weighed in at 240
1/4 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hallmark, Holyfield's fitness trainer, said the champion
weighed as high as 226 pounds 3 1/2 weeks ago. There was no
intention for Holyfield to add weight, Hallmark said, but ``Evander
is getting more rest now (between workouts). He's not doing as much
running around for interviews and such, so he's not quite as
drained.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark also said that ``athletes like Evander can fluctuate
five or 10 pounds and it's not that big of a deal. The weight can
change depending on whether he's eaten or how many fluids he's
taken in or whether he has been to the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Some women outside Madison Square Garden, where the weigh-in
took place, screamed when Holyfield took off his shirt for the
weigh-in. Akinwande drew scattered boos.
</P>
<P>
   Martin bout on hold
</P>
<P>
   Women's lightweight boxing champion Christy Martin (34-1-2),
scheduled to appear on the pay-per-view portion of the card,
currently has no opponent. Martin's scheduled opponent, Maria
Nieves-Garcia (2-1), was scratched because she is pregnant. She
rejected Nieves-Garcia's proposed replacement, Melissa Salamone
(9-0), who had knocked out her last three opponents in the first
round and is the sister of WBA light heavyweight champion Lou Del
Valle.
</P>
<P>
   Nieves-Garcia's pregnancy the pregnancy showed up on the
standard blood and urine tests given to female boxters, matchmaker
Bobby Goodman said, and it showed that Nieves-Garcia was 21 weeks
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``She kept saying, 'But I can't be pregnant,' `` Goodman said.
``So we retested her, and it came up positive again. Twenty-one
weeks. That's pretty pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been at least one other women's fight canceled because
of a pregnancy, last year in England, but this one is believed to
be the first in the U.S. Nieves-Garcia, already a single mother of
one, was to earn $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Brown hurt, Mercer out
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta heavyweight Marcellus Brown, who was to face Ray Mercer
on the undercard, suffered a broken right hand in training and is
out. Mike Sedillo was named as a replacement for Brown, but an
announcement was made later in the day that Mercer had failed a
physical and the bout was off. No further explanation was given.
</P>
<P>
   Quote/unquote
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield trainer Don Turner, when told that Akinwande said he
lost to Lennox Lewis because Turner, his former trainer, didn't pay
enough attention to him in training camp: ``And I'm not going to
pay any attention to him now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4816 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVANDER05-COX     06-04 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANDER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fighting on his terms
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are trying anything this week to draw attention
to the greatest heavyweight of this decade. Put him up on the
podium for a blur of satellite TV interviews. Fit him with a jockey
cap and pose him in front of photographers with Kent Desomeaux, who
rides Real Quiet here in the Belmont Stakes. Hold a weigh-in on
Seventh Avenue during a Manhattan traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters don't require these gimmicks to make money when Mike
Tyson is center stage. But things always have been different for
Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   His career is nearing closure, he owns two championship belts,
and he has earned money, power and respect _ without a prison
record. Yet as he prepares for Saturday's bout against Henry
Akinwande, Holyfield has heard criticism for being greedy in failed
negotiations for a showdown with Lennox Lewis and faces the
prospects of fighting Akinwande in a half-empty Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said he is not getting caught up in the apparent lack
of interest. While he would prefer to meet Lewis, he believes this
fight is underappreciated. Further, the WBA mandated this title
defense, and he refuses to get stripped of his crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who I fight,'' he said. ``I'm in this for the
titles.''
</P>
<P>
   What he can't grasp is why Tyson remains such a magnet for the
public and why cable operators who handle pay-per-view telecasts
are, in his words, ``trying to give me a pay cut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about hype now,'' Holyfield said. ``Like Tyson _ here's a
man who comes out of jail with the whole world watching. `Oh, he's
dangerous,' they say. People came to see if he would hurt the other
guy. People are into that. If you said, `We're gonna kill a chicken
and cut his head off,' people are gonna come out and watch them
kill the chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield wanted $20 million, the same as his previous paycheck
against Michael Moorer, to face Lewis, and he was widely blamed for
not accepting a reduced purse. Lewis received less criticism for
his demand of $10 million, even though the champion's standard
share is two-thirds against a challenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I proclaim to be the best,'' Holyfield said. ``When
Tyson was the man, even though I felt I was the man, he had the
titles, and I was willing to take less. Now I have a situation
where I have a bigger name and I have two belts. Why do people want
to cut their budget when it comes down to me? They payTyson a lot
of money. Why won't they pay me?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many people think Lennox Lewis is that great anyway,''
Holyfield said. ``It ain't gonna shock the world when I whip him.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield still believes a Lewis bout will happen, and he vows
he won't retire until he holds all three belts. That is the reason
he says he is not taking Akinwande for granted, despite the fact he
is in the rare position of a big favorite. If he loses, he is
beltless in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But Holyfield has struggled against lesser opponents _ Bert
Cooper, Bobby Czyz, Larry Holmes, Moorer in their first meeting.
Even Don Turner, Holyfield's trainer, was hesitant when asked if
the Akinwande fight would end quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on Evander's state of mind,'' he said. ``Evander,
sometimes, he overthinks. He can stop Henry or he can make it tough
on himself. I know the kinks in his armor.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield admitted he was reckless against Cooper and Czyz,
adding, ``I ignored the game plan because I thought I could just go
right at them. But I'm more mature now. I can focus better on what
I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That pertains to out-of-ring distractions, as well. Holyfield
has had his share of problems, and the most recent came six weeks
ago when his brother, James, 45, was sentenced to life in prison
for rape and child molestation, stemming from an incident in 1995.
Evander, the youngest of eight children, has visited James in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people my mother did all she could, raising us,''
Holyfield said. ``When my brother was growing up, my mother worked
from 10 to 10. She didn't have as much time with him, so he did
what he wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother was a roughhouser. We didn't have a daddy (around).
If something happened to one of us at school, he'd come with a
baseball bat and attack the whole school. He was our protector.
They called my brother wild man.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about Tyson being in and out of jail. Well, James'
whole life was like that. He got caught up in a lot of things. He
used to sell drugs, but he told me, `If I ever catch you on drugs,
I'm going to kill you,' and he really meant it. It's like he cared
more about me than himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said he did not go down the same path as his brother
because ``by'' the time I was growing up, my mom wasn't working,
and she had more time to spend with me. She raised me like I was a
piece of glass, like I was gonna break.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Holyfield is his own protector. Whether that is enough to
draw more than 8,000 people to the Garden on Saturday, he isn't
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't please everybody,'' Holyfield said. ``You live in a
fool's paradise if you think everybody cares about you. ... I would
love for the place to be packed. But if it was just him and myself
and a referee, I would be just as into it.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whatever drawing power he has, Holyfield said, ``I truly
believe people come out and say, `Well, Holy, he's a nice guy, but
I like to see him get whipped.' They like to see how I respond if I
get whipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be waiting a long time for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
