<SLUG> BC-NUKE-U.N.-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP U.N. MEMBERS URGE INDIA AND PAKISTAN TO END ARMS RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The United States, Russia, China, Britain and France
called on India and Pakistan on Thursday to freeze their nuclear
weapons development and agree not to test nuclear missiles or arm
them with warheads.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council, all nuclear powers themselves, offered to help India and
Pakistan reduce tensions over the disputed territory of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to isolate these countries or make them outcasts
or pariahs,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said after
meeting with the four other foreign ministers to discuss ways to
curb the region's nuclear arms race. ``We want to engage them in
constructive dialogue,'' she said, ``to show them that they have
earned nothing, zero, zilch by what they have done.''
</P>
<P>
   The five countries disagree about economic sanctions, and are
unwilling to offer anything that appears to be a payoff to India or
Pakistan, so they are left trying to get individual countries to
exert pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we are not big into inducements here is that we do
not want any other country to feel there is a benefit'' to testing,
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   What effect Thursday's appeal would have was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no illusions that we will succeed overnight,''
Albright said. Since the end of the Cold War, the United States and
Russia do not have as much leverage as they once had in the region,
and the three other countries do not have much either.
</P>
<P>
   They will evaluate how well Thursday's strategy works, and
foreign ministers of the seven leading industrial democracies plus
Russia _ a group that includes all the nations here Thursday except
China _ will meet again in London on June 12 to discuss further
steps, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   That will add to pressure already brought by Germany, Japan,
Canada and Italy to get India and Pakistan to sign the 1996 nuclear
test-ban treaty and an earlier agreement to keep nuclear weapons
from spreading. Germany and Japan both suspended aid to India after
it tested nuclear weapons last month.
</P>
<P>
   India has long opposed the test ban treaty, saying it will not
sign as long as the five nuclear powers keep their nuclear arms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thursday's meeting was headed by China, which India views as
almost as big an adversary as Pakistan, and Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan made little effort to disguise the Chinese view that India
bore the main responsibility for starting a new arms race in the
region, saying it had acted ``in defiance of world opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The five foreign ministers called on India and Pakistan to avoid
threatening moves by their conventional military forces, and said
they would encourage both to negotiate a solution on Kashmir. U.S.
officials said the United States would offer both countries
assistance in ``confidence-building'' technologies that would allow
them to monitor each other's activities in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which has imposed economic sanctions on both
countries as required under U.S. law, made no attempt here to get
other countries to follow suit. France and Russia were both
opposed, and French officials said their main aim here was a plan
to encourage both countries to sign and ratify the 1996
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isolating India and weakening Pakistan economically is not the
way,'' one French diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   France conducted underground nuclear tests in the South Pacific
in 1995. After a worldwide uproar, President Jacques Chirac ended
the testing and France signed the test ban treaty in 1996. China
also ended its own underground tests and signed at about the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Some people think France could be in a position to become the
Western country with the greatest leverage over India and Pakistan.
In the French view, India's motivation in developing operational
nuclear weapons was as much fear and resentment of China as it was
India's longstanding enmity with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   China and India fought a border war in the Himalayas in 1962,
and Pakistan is widely believed to have obtained what it needed to
build its bomb from China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are struck by the centrality of the Chinese problem for
India,'' said a French official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Though India does not yet have the long-range missile technology
for parity with China, Defense Minister George Fernandes said in
New Delhi on Wednesday that plans were going ahead to develop a
missile with a range beyond 1,500 miles, well into Chinese
territory.
</P>
<P>
   With President Clinton headed for China on June 25, some
officials feared that India would see the appeal by the charter
members of the nuclear club as a conspiracy against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``India is ready to stop testing and making fissionable
materials and sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, but only if
it is then treated by the other nuclear powers the same way as
China,'' a French official said. ``They say they have never
transferred any nuclear technology to anybody else, unlike China,
and yet they are being punished for developing nuclear weapons and
China isn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
