<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-CONGRESS-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OVER TOBACCO BILL ERUPTS IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A fierce partisan fight broke out in the Senate on
Thursday on tobacco and income tax legislation that could swamp the
anti-smoking bill, one of the biggest and most contentious measures
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But by bringing matters to a head, the bickering could just as
easily mean that the Senate will now find a way to pass soon not
only the tobacco bill but also a large tax reduction for married
couples that Republicans are trying to attach to it.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, after weeks of talking but taking no action, the
Senate on Thursday night took a preliminary vote on an amendment
that would make the legislation tougher on cigarette makers. More
definitive votes on the tobacco and tax issues seem more likely to
be cast next week.
</P>
<P>
   But every spat and every snag in the Senate makes it more
improbable that a companion measure can get through the House of
Representatives, that all the differences can be worked out and
that an anti-smoking bill acceptable to the White House can be
enacted.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. The outcome could be a steep increase in
the price of cigarettes, new regulation of tobacco products and a
tax cut worth hundreds of dollars a year to families of modest
means.
</P>
<P>
   But the fight, as it developed Thursday, was much more about
politics than substance.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by Republican efforts to shift the focus of the
debate from smoking, where Democrats are comfortable, to taxes,
where Republicans feel on solid ground, Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle moved to force an end to the debate and to bring the
measure to a vote early next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really comes down to this: Do we get a tobacco bill or
not?'' Daschle declared. ``And we're getting a resounding `no' on
the other side of the aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently taken by surprise, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
called the Daschle move counterproductive. ``The well has been
poisoned tremendously,'' he said. Accusing the Democrats of acting
in bad faith, he demanded: ``Do you want a bill or do you want an
issue?''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would urge all Republicans to vote against ending the
debate, a procedure called cloture that would require 60 votes for
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the chief sponsor of the legislation,
has been trying all year to tiptoe along a narrow bipartisan line.
Clearly shaken by Thursday's developments, McCain said that what he
feared worst had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have gotten very partisan,'' he said. ``A lot of things
are being said that aren't particularly helpful.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But buttonholed as he walked off the Senate floor, McCain said
that the Daschle move could have the positive effect of stopping
the talking and starting the voting. A few minutes later, he
returned to the floor to say that it made sense to resolve the
situation ``sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote on cloture is expected Tuesday. Both sides agreed that
it would not get 60 votes then.
</P>
<P>
   But on contentious measures like this, the Senate often takes
several cloture votes over a period of days or weeks, and the
prevailing view Thursday night was that cloture would eventually be
approved and a tobacco and tax bill would be voted up or down.
</P>
<P>
   Nine weeks ago, by a bipartisan vote of 19-1, the Senate
Commerce Committee approved a bill that would raise the price of
cigarettes by at least $1.10 a pack, give the Food and Drug
Administration added powers to regulate tobacco products and impose
penalties on the cigarette manufacturers if teen-age smoking did
not fall to specified levels.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, before leaving for a 10-day recess for Memorial
Day, the Senate took some preliminary, inconclusive votes. Then,
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, an opponent of the tobacco legislation,
proposed to use much of the revenue raised by the bill to offset
what is called the marriage tax penalty _ the higher tax bill owed
by some couples when they must file joint tax returns instead of
filing as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Senate, unable to reach an agreement to vote on
anything, has done nothing but talk.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans are unenthusiastic about an anti-smoking bill
that they see as a futile big-government response to a public
health problem. But they do not want Democrats to get the political
credit in an election year for a bill pictured as a way to stop
children from getting hooked on cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, Democrats by and large are opposed to cutting
taxes, but they do not want Republicans to get credit for a measure
portrayed as eliminating an unfair extra tax on married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle on Thursday offered a Democratic alternative to the
Gramm tax cut. He acknowledged that it stood little chance of
passing. But he wanted to give the Democrats a tax cut with their
name on it to vote for so that the Republicans would not get all
the political benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Lott tried to thwart that tactic by insisting that the Daschle
tax proposal could not be voted on immediately before or
immediately after the Gramm proposal, making it difficult for the
Democrats to pose them as alternative measures.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that if a tobacco bill is passed by the
Senate, a tax cut of some sort will be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   In its first vote in two weeks, the Senate on Thursday night
approved a Democratic amendment that would toughen the penalties on
tobacco companies if teen-age smoking did not fall enough to meet
the bill's annual goals.
</P>
<P>
   Approval came by a voice vote after the Senate voted, 66-29, not
to kill the amendment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
