<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. RE-OPENS DISCUSSIONS WITH IRAQ ON WEAPONS AND SANCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Four months after Secretary General Kofi Annan
stepped in and took charge of a crisis with Iraq, the initiative in
dealing with the government of President Saddam Hussein moved back
this week to the Security Council and the commission charged with
destroying Iraq's prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Two days of technical briefings on the information that Iraq has
been withholding from arms inspectors ended on Thursday with
Richard Butler, the Special Commission's executive chairman,
preparing to go to Baghdad with a list of steps Iraq must take if
sanctions are to be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Butler's visit next week will put the onus on Baghdad to meet
the requirements or explain in better detail why it cannot. He will
report back to the council.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday afternoon, Butler said that if
Iraq answers the outstanding questions and meets demands for
material and information, the Security Council could move a long
way toward lifting the eight-year embargo during the next major
review of Iraqi compliance, in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some items on this list that could be done in a day
if we were given the document or the piece of information we
need,'' Butler said. ``I did not say this will be over by October.
But I could foresee a report that was very different from any
previous report.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats who attended the marathon Security Council briefings,
which focused on missing documents and Iraqi concealment policies,
said that the opinions of the two most entrenched sides _ the
United States and Britain on one side and Russia, France and China
on the other _ had not changed.
</P>
<P>
   But these diplomats also said that ``neutral'' countries in the
15-member council were impressed by the depth of information they
were offered and the apparent flexibility the inspectors had shown
in meeting council questions and acknowledging that there might
never be 100 percent compliance in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not always a black or white picture, but a picture
that has all shades,'' said Danilo Turk, the representative of
Slovenia, which holds a rotating council seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presentation was very interesting to the members of the
Security Council who usually don't have access to technical
information,'' he said, speaking of smaller nations. ``We of course
receive reports, which are more summary in character, and it's not
the same thing. Now we are able to learn a bit more about the
technical aspects.''
</P>
<P>
   Celso L.N. Amorim, Brazil's representative, who had pressed for
a technical briefing and a ``road map'' to help Iraqis understand
what they must do, described Butler's list as ``a good starting
point.'' But he said that ``the details will have to be filled in
with the cooperation of Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   British and U.S. officials hope that the possession of fuller
information will steer some wavering countries away from a movement
to end sanctions soon and will persuade them to be wary of Iraqi
claims to have met all the demands of the council.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At his news conference on Thursday, Butler used the example of a
dispute over unaccounted for imported missile fuels that experts
say can be used only on Scud-type engines, which are prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Iraqi authorities have attempted to leave council members
with the idea that these fuels aren't unique, that they could be
useful in other Iraqi missile engines, those that they are allowed
to have because the missile would fly less that 150 kilometers,''
Butler said. ``That is not true, and I think the council now
understands that it is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   The document Butler will take to Baghdad next week for
discussion on June 13 and 14 with Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
lists in only general terms the areas of biological, chemical and
missile programs that need to be addressed. It contains no new
revelations, and is sketchiest on the biological weapons file,
which arms inspectors say is their most difficult and worrisome
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have called it a road map,'' Butler said of the list he
will discuss with Aziz, ``so I've said I would also need to discuss
with him the driving instructions for that road map; that is, how
long it would take, what the stops along the way would be, what
would be the best ways for us to fulfill this list.''
</P>
</TEXT>
