<HEADER>
A4838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MD-TROOPER-SUIT-ART-4     06-04 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MD-TROOPER-SUIT-ART-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND TROOPERS STOP DRIVERS BY RACE, SUIT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ A civil rights group and 11 black motorists filed a
class-action lawsuit in federal court here Thursday charging that
the Maryland state police used race as a factor in stopping and
searching drivers along Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   The suit contends that in their effort to seize illegal drugs
and weapons, troopers tend to stop blacks and members of other
minority groups more often than whites, applying a ``race-based
profile'' that suggests that minorities are more likely to be
engaged in criminal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is most disturbing,'' said Gary D. Rodwell of
Philadelphia, one of several plaintiffs who spoke at a news
conference to tell of experiences with Maryland troopers who had
stopped them along I-95, only to find nothing illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even now,'' Rodwell said, ``I continue to feel pretty
frightened on I-95, particularly after the sun goes down, and I
know I'm pretty much at the whim of people who are supposed to
protect and serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other plaintiffs, Rodwell, a 42-year-old executive, said he
had been detained for an unusually long time, in his case almost an
hour, while he was questioned and his car searched. One plaintiff,
James E. Alston Jr., 38, of Burtonsville, Md., said troopers with a
drug-sniffing dog had searched his luggage and left all his clothes
strewn on the side of the highway. Finding nothing illegal, he
said, they departed, and one told him to ``have a nice day.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland officials responded quickly to the accusation of racial
profiling, with a news conference of their own where they denied
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me make this crystal clear,'' said Col. David B. Mitchell,
chief of the agency. ``The Maryland state police has not ever, does
not ever and will not ever condone the use of race-based profiling.
It's against the law, and it will not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit and Mitchell's reply to it were reminiscent of the
furor created in New Jersey by state troopers' shooting of three
men _ two black, one Hispanic _ in a van that was stopped on the
New Jersey Turnpike on April 23. Like Mitchell, Col. Carl Williams,
the superintendent of the New Jersey state police, denied the
subsequent accusations of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   The section of the turnpike where the New Jersey shooting
occurred is Interstate 95, a Maine-to-Florida superhighway that
links large cities like New York, Philadelphia, Baltimore and
Jacksonville. I-95 is well known among law-enforcement agencies as
a major conduit for drug smugglers and gun runners, but plucking
the criminals from the huge volume of traffic can be a daunting
task. The police here said Thursday that 111 million drivers a year
travel along Maryland's stretch of the Interstate alone.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In recent years, the Maryland state police, among other
agencies, have intensified their enforcement efforts along the
highway. That led to litigation as early as 1993, when the American
Civil Liberties Union sued the state of Maryland on behalf of
Robert Wilkins, a lawyer who was stopped and searched the year
before because, he contended, he fit a racial profile.
</P>
<P>
   The state police denied the charge but agreed in a settlement to
maintain computer records on I-95 searches to track any patterns of
discrimination. Convinced by last year that little had changed, the
ACLU asked a federal court here to review the state police efforts.
Judge Catherine Blake found that discrimination against minority
motorists had not ended and ordered that the record-keeping
continue for another year.
</P>
<P>
   It was largely upon that determination that the civil liberties
union advertised for plaintiffs. Rodwell and 10 others agreed to
join the suit, along with the Maryland State Conference of branches
of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs, who seek unspecified damages and name Mitchell
and 22 other officers and troopers as defendants, maintain that
about 75 percent of speeders who were stopped along the state's
northern stretch of I-95 during a three-year period through last
December were white but that about 70 percent of all people stopped
by troopers there were black.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Keven L. Gray, commander of the barracks whose troopers
patrol the section of I-95 at issue, and himself a defendant in the
case, said he did not know where the civil liberties union's
lawyers got those numbers. The suit, however, says they came from
the computerized records that the state police were ordered to
maintain.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, at their own news conference the police produced
other statistics, which showed, they suggested, that justice had
been more evenly applied. Mitchell referred to charts showing that
over a 21-month period through March of this year, troopers under
Gray's command stopped more than twice as many white drivers
(32,727) as black (14,048).
</P>
<P>
   But more blacks than whites were searched, 187 to 166. As for
those arrested, 83 were black and 58 white.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said the facts ``speak for themselves, but they do not
support the accusations'' of the plaintiffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
