u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OKLA-BOMB-NICHOLS-350     06-04 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-BOMB-NICHOLS-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICHOLS SENTENCED TO LIFE WITHOUT PAROLE IN OKLAHOMA BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Ohio)  (th) 
 By JO THOMAS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Calling him ``an enemy of the Constitution,'' a federal
judge Thursday sentenced Terry Nichols to life in prison without
the possibility of parole for conspiring to bomb the Alfred P.
Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City, the deadliest terrorist
attack ever on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   In passing sentence after hearing from relatives of some of the
168 people who died in the blast, Judge Richard P. Matsch, who
presided over the trials of Nichols and his co-conspirator, Timothy
McVeigh, for the first time expressed his view of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a murder case,'' Matsch said. ``It is a crime and
the victims have spoken eloquently here. But it is not a crime as
to them so much as it is a crime against the Constitution of the
United States. That's the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols was convicted last December of conspiring with McVeigh
to use a weapon of mass destruction in the April 19, 1995 bombing
in Oklahoma City, but acquitted of federal murder charges in the
deaths of eight federal agents who died.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols was found guilty of involuntary manslaughter in those
deaths and Thursday was given the maximum sentence of six years in
prison for each, to run concurrently with his life sentence. He was
also acquitted of actually committing the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors presented evidence the Nichols and McVeigh saw the
bombing as retribution for the government raid on the Branch
Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, on April 19, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, his face pale and still, said nothing as the judge
spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, his lawyer, Michael Tigar, urged Matsch to ``stem the
cry for vengeance.'' But 12 relatives of bombing victims pleaded
tearfully that Nichols be given the maximum sentence for his role
in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence in this case shows that Terry Nichols
participated in a plot to undermine that government,'' Matsch said.
``He joined with those who think of the United States government as
some kind of occupying foreign power or some kind of oppressive
force that is taking away the freedom of the people of this
nation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Matsch read the preamble to the Constitution, setting out the
purposes of the nation's government, and asked, ``What was going on
in the Alfred Murrah building on April 19, 1995?''
</P>
<P>
   Then he named the agencies in the building, one by one, where
workers were trying, on the morning they were bombed, to do what
was called for in the Constitution _ establish justice, insure
domestic tranquility, provide for the common defense and promote
the general welfare. Meanwhile, some of their children played
nearby in the day care center in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was the purpose of this conspiracy?'' Matsch asked. ``The
evidence shows to my satisfaction that the intention was to
disrupt, to disorganize, to intimidate the operations of these
agencies and United States Government. Apparently, the intention
was that the response would be fear and terror and intimidation,
and that these people would not be able to perform their work and
that the response throughout the nation would be hysteria.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not suggesting that all the events of `The Turner Diaries'
were planned,'' he continued, referring to the anti-semitic novel
that was a favorite with both McVeigh and Nichols. ``The only
interference is that there was an intention to change the course of
government through fear and intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't work out that way,'' he added. ``There was no
anarchy. There was no reign of terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, as spectators and lawyers filed out of the
courthouse into a chilly spring rain, Larry Mackey, the lead
prosecutor, echoed the judge's words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim McVeigh and Terry Nichols were wrong about America. They
could launch a violent, ugly, horrifyingly horrible act against
innocent people,'' he said, but ``they have been defeated. The plot
failed. The success happened in this courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Tigar vowed to appeal, saying, ``There is a building across the
street. It is the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 10th Circuit. We
are prepared to be in this case all the way for the vindication of
Terry Nichols.''
</P>
<P>
   As Thursday's sentencing hearing began, bombing victims came to
the lectern, most of them weeping, to tell the judge of their
experiences and plead with him for a life sentence for Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Battreall told of her agony when her brother, Harley
Richard Cottingham, crushed under nine floors of concrete in the
offices of the Defense Investigative Services, was ``shipped as
freight to his home state in Nebraska and unloaded by a forklift''
from the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas trees were his hobby, she said. He planted 500
seedlings every year, and he hoped to raise them and play golf when
he retired. ``All these plans were blown up on April 19, 1995 by
selfish individuals who hated the government,'' she said. ``Even
hearing the name Oklahoma City sends chills down your spine.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharilee Lyons, who works for the Department of Housing and
Urban Development, told the judge her desk fell seven floors on the
day of the bombing, but she survived because she had not come to
work that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live with a tremendous amount of guilt,'' she said. She has
moved to Cleveland to work ``but the grief follows me everywhere I
go. The past three years have been one continuous nightmare. Inside
I feel just as dead as the 168 people who were murdered. It's a
type of life sentence to lose so much, so many, so precious to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Doris Jones, whose pregnant daughter Carrie Lenz died in the
offices of the Drug Enforcement Agency, said she doesn't know what
to say when people she meets ask if she has children. She has told
her granddaughter that Mrs. Lenz is in heaven, but ``one day she
told me she wished Carrie would stop being an angel so she could
see her.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Moser, who found her her husband Calvin Moser alive in
the wreckage, said she has not been able to sleep through the night
since the bombing. She was asked to help that day, she explained,
by taking blankets to the plaza at the foot of the shattered
building, and realized, to her shock, that they were to cover the
tiny bodies of dead infants.
</P>
<P>
   She touched one baby ``and whispered, `It's OK, baby. It's
OK,''' she said, but the baby was dead. Now, she continued, ``when
I see these mothers with empty arms, I wonder, was that your baby I
kissed on his way to heaven?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
