<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-INTERNET-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELF-REGULATION OF INTERNET COMPANIES IS POOR, SAYS FTC 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Civil liberties advocates and children's groups
urged the White House on Thursday to abandon its hands-off stance
to Internet privacy regulation after a Federal Trade Commission
report painted a dismal picture of the effectiveness of companies'
self-regulation, especially in regard to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that the Clinton administration policy has been an
abysmal failure,'' said Jeff Chester of the Center for Media
Education, an electronic media public-interest group based in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   After the FTC report was released Thursday morning, the agency's
chairman, Robert Pitofsky, called its conclusions ``disappointing''
but declined to call self-regulation a failure. ``I still believe
that the best way to deal with this is self-regulation rather than
heavy-handed government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC, which surveyed 1,400 Web sites in March, found that a
year after the agency had warned businesses of the need to adopt
strong privacy guidelines to avoid government regulation, 92
percent of all Web sites collected personal information from users
and only 14 percent of those sites disclosed how that information
was used.
</P>
<P>
   Most troubling to the FTC was the finding that 89 percent of the
children's sites surveyed collected personal information. Of those,
only 23 percent told children to seek parental permission, 7
percent said they would notify parents of their
information-gathering practices, and less than 10 percent provided
for parental control over the collection and use of the
information.
</P>
<P>
   At one Web site, the agency said, children were asked to give
their names, addresses, e-mail addresses, ages and whether they
ever received gifts of stocks, cash, savings bonds or certificates
of deposit.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites gave away candy for providing an e-mail address.
Others used games, surveys and popular animated characters to
persuade children to give their names, e-mail addresses and other
information.
</P>
<P>
   Also troubling, the report said, was the amount of data
collected by interactive public areas like chat rooms, which are
accessible to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``These activities enable children to communicate freely with
strangers, including adults,'' the report said. Investigation by
the FBI and Justice Department, it said, ``has revealed that online
services and bulletin boards are quickly becoming the most powerful
resources used by predators to identify and contact children.''
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends that Congress pass legislation to require
that Web sites collecting personal information from children
younger than 12 notify parents and obtain consent to collect the
information. The FTC, Pitofsky said, will continue to evaluate the
broader issues of Internet privacy and make recommendations later
this year on whether protections are needed for adults.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Berman, executive director of the Center for Democracy and
Technology, an online advocacy group, called on the FTC to ask
Congress for authority to immediately adopt rules to protect
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Punting this issue to Congress without taking this first step
may result in a political nightmare for the Internet community,
with controls on content and moves to a national identification
scheme for the Net,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Marc Rotenberg, director of the Electronic Privacy Information
Center, said the FTC report failed to address all of the critical
issues. ``We wanted to see them make a clear statement on the need
for protecting the anonymity of people on the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rotenberg, however, said he was not concerned about Congress
taking on the issue. ``Part of the problem is that the FTC has been
holding on to the ball and not letting people run with it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who really need to do something are the people in
the White House,'' Rotenberg said. He said Ira Magaziner, Clinton's
Internet adviser, had been ``traveling the world telling everyone
that self-regulation works. The message is clear: self-regulation
has not worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Magaziner was traveling on Thursday and could not immediately be
reached for comment. But Commerce Secretary William Daley was
critical of the progress made by industry to police itself.
</P>
<P>
   Daley said he and other officials had warned the industry that
it must move more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a critical mass of the companies to make
self-regulation work, and we haven't seen that yet,'' Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department is supposed to make a full report to the
White House in July on whether self-regulation is working. Business
groups insist it is and are pleading for more time to prove that.
</P>
<P>
   The Direct Marketing Association, for example, has endorsed
privacy policies similar to those recommended by the FTC and is
working to educate businesses of the need to follow the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The association said its own survey in May of the top 100
children's Web sites showed that 70 percent posted privacy polices,
compared with 38 percent in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
