<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE DEFEATS BID TO ALLOW PRAYER IN PUBLIC SCHOOLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House turned back an attempt Thursday by social
conservatives to amend the Constitution so that prayer services and
other religious expression could be organized on school grounds and
other public places.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the effort to establish organized prayer in the
nation's schools and give tax breaks to religious groups failed to
win the two-thirds majority needed to amend the Constitution. The
vote was 224-203.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure hailed its defeat as a victory for the
continued separation of church and state as established by the
nation's founding fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas, opponents dismissed the
proposal authored by Rep. Ernest Istook, R-Okla., as little more
than effort by the religious right to impose its views and beliefs
on the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional appeal to his colleagues, Edwards called the
amendment ``a horrible solution in search of a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure would have prohibited infringement of the right to
pray in public places or make other expressions of religious
beliefs and traditions. Opponents argued that its language could
have also allowed for public funding of religious schools or other
religious activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Istook amendment, in the name of protecting religion,
would harm religion by getting the federal government more involved
in religious matters,'' said Edwards, adding that the measure
``would open school doors to government-sanctioned prayer'' and
allow the government to endorse religious messages and give
religious groups tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, he said ``America's public schools would look like
a big-city airport with every religious group, cult and sect
pushing their practices and beliefs on our children.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That view was echoed by Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, who argued
that the amendment would allow the state to ``usurp'' his authority
as a parent to pass on his religious beliefs to his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is where this amendment is headed. And I am offended by
those who seek to impose their will on my children absent my
consent. Each of us is less free when government is given the power
to intrude on this right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supporters, however, argued that the Istook amendment would
simply correct a long history of Supreme Court decisions that
placed unfair restrictions on the public expression of religious
views. They cited a number of recent decisions limiting the rights
of individuals and groups to organize prayer services and Bible
clubs in schools, or, in one case, to construct a nativity scene on
government property.
</P>
<P>
   ``With increasing hostility and insensitivity, our courts have
systematically stripped us of our First Amendment right to basic
and fundamental rights of religious expression,'' said Rep. Bob
Riley, R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Other supporters, many of them Democrats, argued that the
Constitution provides more protection for pornographers and
politicians than it does for people who practice their religion.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in the House marked the first time since 1971 that
lawmakers had taken a stand on the issue, which was brought to the
floor after House Republican leaders promised religious
conservatives in a meeting several weeks ago that they would
continue to push for passage of a school prayer amendment and other
conservative legislative items.
</P>
<P>
   The Istook amendment was pushed hard by the Christian Coalition
and other conservative religious groups. They organized a
letter-writing and telephone campaign in an attempt to persuade
members. They also attacked Edwards as a religious bigot and
threatened to campaign against any lawmaker who voted against the
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   In a flier sent to the Texan's constituents in Waco, the
Christian Coalition said ``Edwards' bigotry directed at Christians
and other people of faith is outrageous and must be stopped.'' The
flyer said that his ``attitudes have no place in Texas or anywhere
in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Edwards prompted Rep. Bill Hefner, D-N.C., one of
153 co-sponsors of the amendment, to withdraw his support and
denounce Istook and the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not Christian,'' Hefner told Istook during the debate,
calling Edwards ``one of the finest ... most moral and most devoted
family men'' in the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Hefner, a gospel singer and devoutly religious man, also took on
another co-sponsor of the legislation who told members before the
vote that if they failed to support the Istook amendment God would
send them to hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was prepared to support this amendment ... but I'll take my
chances,'' Hefner said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
