u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-FLIGHT-BOS &LR;      06-04 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FLIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ALBANIANS FLEE KOSOVO, ALBANIA CALLS FOR FOREIGN INTERVENTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ As thousands of ethnic Albanians fled Thursday into
Albania from strife in Serbia's Kosovo province, Albania's foreign
minister, Paskal Milo, warned that the region is on the brink of
``open war'' and urged international intervention.
</P>
<P>
   In Tirana, a spokesman for Prime Minister Fatos Nano said
Albania is relying on help from NATO. ``We appeal to NATO,'' Ben
Blushi said. ``We will appeal to them to at least protect our
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany urged NATO to decide swiftly whether to dispatch troops.
``It's important that NATO reach its decision very quickly,'' said
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, who added that ``thousands, perhaps
tens of thousands'' of refugees were fleeing Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   According to the United Nations High Commission for Refugees,
nearly 7,000 have arrived in northern Albania and thousands more
are said to be crossing the mountains to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a NATO military reconnaissance team arrived in the
Macedonia Thursday to assess whether NATO troops should be
dispatched to the Albanian and Macedonian borders. Last week, NATO
ruled out sending forces immediately but said it would consider
deployment as an option.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-member team had not been expected to report their
findings until late June, according to NATO sources.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to a NATO diplomat in Brussels, ``This work may
be speeded up'' due to the rising tide of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   NATO defense ministers, including Defense Secretary William S.
Cohen of the United States, will meet next week in Brussels to
discuss the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Western powers fear that the conflict will spread into Albania
and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovan refugees began pouring into Albania over the weekend
after the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, intensified his
crackdown against the Kosovo Liberation Army, an armed separatist
movement based there.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's
population, have campaigned peacefully in the past for autonomy
from Serbia. But these efforts have yielded little, and the
popularity of the KLA has grown as a result.
</P>
<P>
   This year, after the KLA attacked Serb policemen, Milosevic
responded with force. Attacks on villages suspected of harboring
KLA fighters left scores of ethnic Albanians dead.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the two sides broke down in the wake of Serbia's
most recent attacks last week on three areas believed to be
strongholds for KLA soldiers. An estimated 250 Kosovo Albanians
have died since February.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian media reported that the military operation was to end
today. But Serbian paramilitary forces were reportedly still
shelling the Decani-Djakovica region of Kosovo Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Western reporters, who got within five miles of Djakovica, saw
Serbian army convoys carrying heavy artillery. An offensive near
the town of Glodjane was reportedly stalled, according to Serbian
independent radio.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of refugees into in Albania, the poorest country in
Europe, poses serious problems for it. They are largely women and
children who arrive exhausted and often injured, according to High
Commission spokesman Maki Shinohara, speaking by telephone from
Geneva. And the mountaineous border area into which they are
pouring is Albania's poorest. It has few jobs, poor housing, and
little food or drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   In Tirana, government spokesman Blushi said Albania will soon
stagger under the refugee burden. ``We can't take care of more than
20,000,'' Blushi said. The Albanian Interior Ministry estimates the
number of refugees at 11,000, nearly twice the High Commission
count.
</P>
<P>
   In a possible hardening of its position, the Albanian Socialist
Party, headed by Prime Minister Nano, said in a statement Thursday
that it supports the ``resistance and determination'' of the Kosovo
Albanians in the face of Milosevic's ``mad dream'' to ``drive away
from their lands two million Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   Albania had won international praise for its restraint in the
face of mounting violence in Kosovo, and it refused to intervene
over the future of the province.
</P>
<P>
   But Western diplomats Thursday dismissed the Socialist Party
statement, noting that Albania has neither the military firepower
nor the desire to become involved. Analysts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way the Albanians could take on the Yugoslav
forces,'' said Paul Beaver of Jane's Defense Weekly. ``The
Yugoslavs have better tanks, better communication, better
helicopters, better artillery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
