<HEADER>
A4851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILINGUAL-VOICES-ART-     06-04 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILINGUAL-VOICES-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATINO COMMUNITY REMAINS DIVIDED OVER FUTURE OF BILINGUAL
EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927 .) 
 (JT)  
 By DON TERRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ English can still be a riddle to 60-year-old
Rosario Gomez, even after three decades here in a house with red
and yellow roses in the front yard on Chicago Street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But her two adult children, both of whom were born in Los
Angeles and enrolled in bilingual education classes in grade
school, have good jobs, bright futures and are literate and fluent
in English and Spanish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That, Mrs. Gomez explained, is why her family voted no in
Tuesday's primary election here on Proposition 227, the nationally
watched initiative that will dismantle 30 years of bilingual
education in California. The measure easily passed with 61 percent
of the vote. But despite pre-election polls suggesting it would
also carry a majority of Latinos, fewer than 4-in-10 Latinos who
voted favored the proposition in the end, after an all-out blitz
against the measure by almost every elected Latino official in the
state. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, in more than two dozen interviews on the largely Latino
east side of Los Angeles, even some of the Latinos who voted no,
such as Mrs. Gomez's daughter, Elva Osorio, expressed deep concern
about the state of bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in school, bilingual education was much better than
it is now,'' Mrs. Osorio said. ``I voted no, but I knew it was
going to lose, because a lot of people are upset that their kids
don't know how to speak English and they're in the fifth grade.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting Latinos like the Gomez family to vote yes was a priority
for Ron Unz, a conservative Republican and the main sponsor and
financial backer of the measure, which will essentially eliminate
bilingual education in California if it survives court challenges.
His campaign spent a lot of time and energy wooing Latinos, hoping
to avoid the racially charged atmosphere that surrounded earlier
ballot initiative drives in California, on subjects like
affirmative action. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite those efforts, words like ``racism,'' ``prejudice''
and ``discrimination'' often came up in interviews after Tuesday's
primary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is racism towards us,'' said Rito Mateos, a
32-year-old gardener, who voted no. ``This is a threat to the
community. It's not going to stop here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gomez said she knew of no one on her block who voted yes.
``I think it passed because a lot of American people are tired of
us,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No matter how they voted, the Latino parents, telephone
operators, construction workers, flight instructors and others
interviewed all agreed on one issue: for immigrant children,
whether they are from Mexico or Vietnam, the key to unlocking the
treasures of America is to learn English as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted no, but it was hard for me to make up my mind,'' said
Gloria Luna, 65, whose great-grandmother was ``born in this state
when it was Mexico.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Luna said she decided to vote against 227 because so many
educators opposed it, saying its provision to provide non-English
speaking public school children with only one year of intensive
language training before sending them into mainstream classes would
do more harm than good. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so important for Hispanics to learn English,'' Mrs. Luna
said, ``but one year is much too fast.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Mrs. Gomez and Mateos, Mrs. Luna said she suspected that
prejudice and not pedagogy was at the root of the campaign to
eliminate bilingual education. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people who voted,'' Luna said, ``don't know
anything about education.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Feria, 44, agreed with Mrs. Luna, up to a point. Feria, a
flight instructor, was working in his family's wallet stand on
Olvera Street, the oldest street in Los Angeles, when he took time
out to talk about the initiative. He said anyone with the slightest
knowledge of education would have voted yes for 227 _ as he did. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe, the only way to learn English is to be
immersed in it,'' said Feria, who did not take part in bilingual
classes when he was in school. ``I wouldn't have a job as a flight
instructor if I didn't have the proper English skills.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Feria said the teachers and politicians who opposed 227 did so
because they were afraid they would lose their money and influence
if bilingual education is eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a money grab,'' Feria said. ``We do our kids a
disfavor by putting them in bilingual education.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As she walked through Olvera Street near downtown, past the
wallet stands, sandal stalls and booths selling Day of the Dead
figures, Mirian Luis, 22, a paralegal's assistant, said she voted
no on 227 because her nieces and nephews are doing well in
bilingual education programs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a joke,'' she said of the proposition. ``I mean, how are
the kids going to learn?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, on Cesar E. Chavez Avenue, George Ramos was
hanging orange and yellow flyers, balloons and a Mexican flag
advertising his travel business. He voted yes on Proposition 226,
because, he said, ``This is America.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is supposed to speak English,'' Ramos said. ``If you
go to France, you don't ask for bilingual education. If you go to
China, you cannot request bilingual education. They will kick you
out of there.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At El Mercado, a warehouse-like complex of shops and restaurants
not far from Chavez Avenue, Manuel Romero, a retired General Motors
worker, said he voted for 227 because there are not enough
qualified teachers to adequately staff bilingual education
programs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the state department of education said it is 20,000
bilingual education teachers short of what it needs. The state said
there are 1.4 million public school pupils with limited English
skills in California. Thirty percent of those students are in
bilingual classes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had quality teachers,'' Romero said, ``it would be
OK.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerry and Diana Ontiveros voted no. They grew up in a largely
white neighborhood in Whittier and attended Catholic schools before
going to college and getting married. They did not take part in
bilingual programs. They were surrounded by English speakers
everywhere they went, which is not the case for many immigrant
children who often live in segregated and isolated neighborhoods. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been assimilated into the mainstream culture all of my
life,'' Ontiveros said. ``Others haven't had the opportunities I've
had, and that's why I support bilingual education.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Moreno, a 30-year-old teacher's assistant, eating lunch at
El Mercado, said he voted for the proposition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like maybe bilingual education is like a handicap or
something,'' he said. ``It gives the kids too much leeway not to
learn.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maria Tovar said she voted for 227, but by mistake. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tovar said she supports bilingual education and thought a
yes vote meant saving the program. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When she came to the United States 25 years ago at the age of
14, Ms. Tovar said, she did not speak or understand English and
struggled in school to learn without a bilingual program. Several
of her classmates were not as determined, she said, and they
dropped out, never learning the language. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very, very tough,'' she said, ``trying to learn English
without bilingual education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
