<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4853 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWA-CRASH-DISPOSAL-NY     06-04 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-CRASH-DISPOSAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATALOGING MISERY: TWA CRASH VICTIMS' BELONGINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If it is possible to catalog heartbreak, then the
workers at the hangar in Calverton, N.Y., where the ruins of TWA
Flight 800 are stored, have done it. It takes the form of a blue
plastic three-ring binder, with 200 pages of color photos of
personal belongings, from cameras to underwear to hair dryers _
anything that 230 people could bring aboard a Boeing 747 for a long
trip abroad, and that a diver could then bring up from the bottom
of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly two years after the crash, cataloging misery is
evidently easier than reclaiming it. Copies of the catalog went out
to families of the victims months ago, but most of the items are
still, in the investigators' word, ``unaffiliated,'' stored in 200
cardboard barrels a few yards from the scaffolding that holds
together the shattered remains of the aircraft itself.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, in an experiment in sensitivity that is intended
to avoid the legal problems and ugly public disputes involving
families of previous crash victims, federal officials will begin a
new effort to identify the belongings and return what they can, and
to figure out what to do with the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all here,'' said Peter Goelz, the managing director of
the National Transportation Safety Board, holding a copy of the
catalog. ``But you have to have a strong constitution to go through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The belongings, about 2,000 items in all, encompass the detritus
of modern life _ the undistinguishable rows of men's underwear and
blue jeans _ as well as more individualized items that are more
personal. There is the family snapshot, two boys waving playfully,
one with his arm latched around the neck of the other. There is the
brown teddy bear, with beady yellow glass eyes, dressed in
blue-and-white striped t-shirt with matching cap, perhaps belonging
to a dead passenger, perhaps being carried as a gift to a child in
Paris, where the plane was bound from New York's Kennedy
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the items shown in the catalog have gone unclaimed,
with some relatives saying they did not want to reopen emotional
wounds and others saying it was difficult to make out the
belongings in the photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Like some other family members, Ron Yee _ whose sister Judith
Yee and cousin Patricia Loo were on board _ had already received
some personal effects after the crash. He put some ``little bits
and pieces of this and that'' in the crypt where his sister's ashes
are interred, he said Thursday, and has some others in a sealed box
at his home in Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   When the catalog reached him, he said, he realized there might
have been more of their belongings pictured inside, but ``it
crossed my mind that at this point, I really didn't want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB's new effort to deal with the items will begin Friday,
when, with the help of five volunteer relatives of the dead,
workers from the NTSB's family assistance team will begin the task
of sorting through the barrels to decide what is worth trying to
place _ a pair of plastic swim flippers, a ``Conair''-brand hair
dryer, with the anti-shock safety plug still attached, a T-shirt
that says ``Harley Davidson,'' and three small electronic devices
that look from the FBI's evidence photo to be tape players or
radios, each still in its original packaging, a clear plastic
bubble over a cardboard card.
</P>
<P>
   There are pairs of shoes, single shoes, floral print dresses and
toiletries kits. There are neckties that look, in the photos at
least, good enough to wear, and carry-on bags that look like they
have been through something horrible, like an explosion and fall
from 13,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Carven, whose sister Paula, and her 9-year-old son, Jay,
were on board, is one of the five relatives who will assist the
Safety Board. ``If you didn't get anything back, if you didn't get
any luggage but for a pair of pants or a torn T-shirt,'' Carven
said Thursday, ``I can see where it would be very important.''
</P>
<P>
   What the teams decide is not identifiable or not worth trying to
return to families will be set aside, with no decision yet on what
happens next. The material could be cremated and buried at a
memorial park, or could be boxed and stored indefinitely, like the
wreckage of planes themselves. ``It's very difficult to say `oh,
this is worthless and nobody'll want this and throw it away,' and
God forbid, it's somebody's last remnant that some family could
point to,'' said Carven, a lawyer in Bel Air, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Carven pointed to the importance for his family of the recovery
of jewelry that had belonged to his sister.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, he said, wears Paula's jewelry recovered from the
crash. ``My mother doesn't go a day without wearing most of it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A shorter list of items, maybe 200, will go into a new catalog
with clearer pictures, to be recirculated among the relatives.
</P>
<P>
   John Holst, of Smithtown, N.Y., whose son and daughter-in-law
were on the flight, said he was glad that the Safety Board was
making the effort. One part of that effort is taking better photos;
the ones in the first catalog were FBI evidence pictures, with some
items in plastic bags with the word, in block capitals,
``EVIDENCE.''
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB has learned that the fate of crash-related objects has
the capacity to inflict pain on the relatives. In Pittsburgh, for
example, in January 1995, four months after a USAir 727
mysteriously rolled over and crashed, relatives of the dead got in
a screaming match with airline representatives in the lobby of the
Hilton Hotel, where the NTSB was holding a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said it had about 70 pieces of jewelry and other
personal effects from the 132 passengers, and told the families
that these would be available for pick-up at the airport; some of
the relatives asked the airline to bring the items to the downtown
area so they could try to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   After the TWA Flight 800 crash, Congress passed the Aviation
Disaster Family Assistance Act, which gives the NTSB custody of
passengers' items and put it in charge of coordinating help to
their families.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of victims in other crashes say they suspect that
before the law changed, airlines tried to destroy personal effects
rather than return them, to prevent families from entering them as
evidence in court cases.
</P>
<P>
   Because Flight 800 crashed at sea, and TWA argued that it was
not required to pay for the recovery of the wreckage and did not
want to, the federal government paid and legally has custody of the
items.
</P>
<P>
   And the NTSB is determined to consult with relatives every step
of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Abe, deputy director for family affairs at the NTSB, said
that when families identified belongings, they would be asked if
they wanted the items back as is, or cleaned, or if they wanted the
NTSB to destroy them. It is important, he said, for families to
have the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the NTSB cannot identify the items, he said, ``in many
cases, it's the effort that makes the difference to the families.''
</P>
<P>
   For Holst and his family, the emotional process has been one
they have dealt with step by step, and will continue to do if some
of his son's belongings are identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happens, we'll deal with it,'' he said. ``It's not
something I'll be looking forward to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
