A4856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-CHAPLAIN-ART-     06-04 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-CHAPLAIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY HARVARD SENIORS TAKE COMFORT BEFORE COMMENCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ With all the pomp and pomposity at Harvard's
362nd commencement Thursday, there came one oasis-like moment of
reassurance, both divine and earthly, for young souls queasy with
fear at the thought of exiting the yard and entering the world.
</P>
<P>
   Known as Senior Class Chapel, it was a peculiarly Harvard rite _
like much on this day of arcane black-and-crimson procession _ but
a low-key one, not mentioned in the official program. It was
attended only by seniors themselves, herded in double file just
before the commencement, but in numbers so strong that some had to
sit on the aisle floors of the university's nondenominational
Memorial Church.
</P>
<P>
   The ritual included no Latin, no big words, no complex thoughts
and no denial of the psychological truth that even for those who
fancy themselves the best and the brightest, graduation can be
streaked by stark terror.
</P>
<P>
   It is to address that anxiety that the Rev. Peter Gomes, the
Plummer professor of Christian morals, minister of the Memorial
Church and author of popular books on the Bible, has for years
ushered seniors through a special commencement sermon meant to
soothe them with humor and, believers or not, with unabashedly
religious solace.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to be sent out of here for good, and most of you
aren't ready to go,'' Gomes, gowned in cherry red, told more than
1,000 seniors in genteelly ringing tones that called to mind a
cross between a Shakespearean actor and the sitcom character
Frasier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is about to bid you into the fellowship of
educated men and women, and you know,'' he paused and slowed,
``just _ how _ dumb _ you _ really _ are.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused again for the cheers of agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``And worse than that, the world _ and your parents in
particular _ are going to expect that you will now be among the
brightest and best,'' Gomes continued. ``But you know that you can
no longer fool all the people even some of the time. By noontime
today, you will be out of here. By tomorrow, you will be history.
By Saturday, you will be toast. That's a fact _ no exceptions, no
extensions.''
</P>
<P>
   Having stated the problem, the minister moved quickly to
alleviate it, promising students that their best years were yet to
come, and that God would be with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future is God's gift to you,'' Gomes said. ``God will not
let you stumble or fall. God has not brought you this far to this
place to abandon you or leave you here alone and afraid. The God of
Israel never stumbles, never sleeps, never goes on sabbatical.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Thus, my beloved and bewildered young friends, do
not be afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomes concluded with a benediction: ``God grant you life until
your work is done, and work until your life is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Hsiao-Yun Chu, a senior, said she appreciated the minister's
intent, but she did not relate to the Christian aspects of his
sermon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was reassuring our anxiety, but the means he chose were not
the ones I would have chosen,'' Ms. Chu said. Still, she added,
``It was the message I came away with that counts: `Go ahead! Don't
stop here!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
