u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-REPORT-     06-04 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-REPORT-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAY LEAVES STARR WITH DILEMMA IN CLINTON INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Ga., Mass.)   (See also CLINTON-STARR)  
(lb) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court's refusal Thursday to intervene
quickly in the legal fight between Kenneth Starr and President
Clinton in the independent-counsel investigation means that Starr
now faces an unpalatable set of choices.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Starr hinted for the first time that he is
considering making an impeachment referral to Congress, which would
then be forced to consider whether to exercise its authority to
remove the president.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr and his aides have said that they would follow Justice
Department guidelines that discourage seeking indictments as an
election nears. Now, with the Supreme Court's decision to put to an
appeals court the question of whether a top Clinton aide and
several Secret Service agents can be compelled to testify, Starr's
options for delivering an impeachment report may be dictated by the
looming political calendar.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Starr must decide whether to file a report in the next
few weeks that would be incomplete _ because it would not take
account of testimony he thinks could be crucial to his case _ or
wait until after Election Day, when his recommendation could have
far less political resonance for a new Congress and a president in
his final two years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, if he decided to file a report now, Starr could
jeopardize any criminal prosecutions that his office might seek, by
prompting Congress to begin its own inquiry, and taking such steps
as offering immunity to certain witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, the window for making an impeachment
referral, which Starr hinted he might do in his filing this week
seeking the Supreme Court's expedited review, will close by the end
of August.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have asked for a hearing in July by the appeals court
on the issue of whether Bruce Lindsey, a deputy White House
counsel, and three Secret Service employees, can assert privileges
that would prevent their testimony or must answer before a federal
grand jury questions posed by investigators about the president and
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the court honored their request, the final decision,
assuming it went to the Supreme Court again after the appeals court
ruled, would not come before Election Day, because the High Court
will recess this month and not return until October.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, where the year has been dominated by anxieties
over impeachment proceedings, the court's ruling did little to
resolve the key uncertainty that has hung over the session: how the
president's legal problems will affect the battle for control of
the House.
</P>
<P>
   Some deplored the decision and the impetus it gave for more
delay. ``I think it's unfortunate,'' said Rep. Robert Livingston,
R-La. ``I think we need to accelerate this thing. Let's get the
truth out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, many Republicans have been queasy about receiving
a report from Starr before the midterm election.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing how little Clinton's public standing had been harmed by
the allegations that he had a relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and
sought to cover it up, some have been fearful that an impeachment
inquiry could backfire on them at the polls, particularly if Starr
presented them with a weak case.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``If a report came to us that was ambiguous and it didn't have
enough substance for us to pursue, it would not be helpful,'' said
Rep. John Linder, the Georgian who heads the Republican House's
re-election committee. But he added that compelling evidence that
the president had committed a felony could sharply alter the mood
of the public.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Starr delays, the possibility of impeachment might still
sway some voters. But a delay could also leave Republicans on what
they view as more comfortable ground: a separate investigation into
whether Clinton's policy allowing U.S. commercial satellites to be
launched from Chinese rockets had compromised the United States'
national security.
</P>
<P>
   With this they believe the have found an issue that may resonate
with the public in a way that sexual allegations against the
president have not.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who have rallied around Clinton since the Lewinsky
case first broke, said they expected the court ruling to bolster
the current political mood of the country. Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass., said the ruling ``reduces the momentum'' Starr had
appeared to be building.
</P>
<P>
   But privately some Democrats expressed concerns about reports
that Clinton might refuse to testify, because that might suggest he
did have something to hide.
</P>
</TEXT>
