u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-480&AMP;ADD     06-04 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REJECTS ORGANIZED PRAYER IN PUBLIC SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ill., Okla., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time in more than a quarter of a
century, the House on Thursday debated _ and rejected _ an attempt
by religious conservatives to amend the Constitution to allow
organized prayer in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 224-203, falling 61 short of the two-thirds
necessary to pass a constitutional amendment. The vote doomed the
measure for now, but it had no future in the Senate anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Students may now pray, read the Bible and engage in religious
speech at school as long as they do so in a reasonable time, place
and manner, without disrupting other students.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to allowing organized prayer in school, the measure
would have allowed religious symbols on public property, such as a
creche at a courthouse. It also would have allowed use of tax money
for religious activities.
</P>
<P>
   The measure drew the active opposition of religious groups from
across the denominational spectrum, including Catholics, Jews,
Presbyterians, Seventh-Day Adventists and Muslims. They said the
measure was unnecessary, would coerce religious minorities into
conforming with the majority and would upend nearly 300 years of
religious freedom guaranteed by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amendment strips the individual of his or her rights to
pick his or her own prayer or to practice his or her own religion
without having to subject their beliefs to the manipulation and
interference of an arrogant majority,'' said Rep. Robert Scott,
D-Va.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the defeat was a blow to the religious right, which
had intensified lobbying on behalf of the measure in recent days.
Still, its leaders claimed success in just getting the matter onto
the House floor and in winning a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked very hard,'' Randy Tate, executive director of the
Christian Coalition, said. ``We want a seat at the table, and some
would love to keep us out. We've always believed our influence
should be commensurate with our numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives argued that the amendment was needed to protect
students from overly sensitive school administrators and misguided
judges who twisted the idea of separation of church and state into
a hostility toward religious expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basic liberties are being infringed because of judicial
wrongheadedness and, frankly, secularist bias,'' Rep. Henry Hyde,
R- Ill. and chairman of the Judiciary Committee, said on the floor.
``Neutrality towards religion, not hostility, is the ideal we
seek.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters also argued that the perceived hostility toward
religious expression coincided with an increase in violence, crime
and moral turpitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``As prayer has gone out of schools, guns, knives, drugs and
gangs have come in,'' said Rep. Ernest Istook Jr., the Oklahoma
Republican who sponsored the measure. ``It's time we put the
emphasis on what we believe, and almost every American believes in
God.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The amendment did not force anyone to pray, he said, but added,
those who did not want to should not have the power to censor those
who did.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have the right to shut people up and censor them
just because you choose to be thin-skinned and intolerant when
someone else is trying to express their faith,'' he said in the
daylong debate.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters and opponents argued that they were trying to protect
the guarantees of freedom of religion on which the nation was
founded.
</P>
<P>
   This only irked lawmakers like Rep. Amo Houghton of Corning,
N.Y., one of 28 Republicans who voted against the measure. A total
of 197 Republicans and 27 Democrats favored it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides claim to be on the side of the righteous,''
Houghton said on the House floor. But he suggested that the
sponsors seemed to have conflicting motives. ``People are screaming
about getting the government off our backs, but they turn around
and have the government tell our children how to pray,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Murphy, director of the Washington office of the American
Civil Liberties Union, dismissed the measure as ``something to
galvanize the far-right constituencies because they are
anticipating a close election in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said that this lobbying campaign had hurt Republicans.
It exposed the degree to which the religious right was involved in
congressional politics, which in turn spurred scores of other
religious leaders into active opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The national leadership has been involved on a level we've
never seen before,'' she said of the churches that joined a group
called the Coalition to Preserve Religious Liberty. ``More
denominations have been engaged in this battle, and they've decided
the Christian Coalition doesn't speak for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4863 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-KOSOVO-450&AMP;AD     06-04 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-KOSOVO-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS OF ETHNIC ALBANIANS FORCED TO FLEE YUGOSLAV FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PADESH, Albania _ President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia has
unleashed the largest military operation in the Balkans since the
end of the war in Bosnia, driving thousands of ethnic Albanians
from the border area with Albania and reducing their villages to
rubble.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10,000 refugees have streamed through the mountain
passes and thousands more are reported to be hiding in forests on
the other side of the border, according to U.N. officials, refugees
and refugee organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are trying to hang on, desperately hoping that the
world will intervene to save them,'' said Besim Aliaj, 36, as he
stood with some 30 people from his village who had been walking for
two days. ``We could not hold out any longer. There are thousands
more behind us. Once they realize there is no hope they will
follow. Everyone is being attacked from three sides. Only the
border area is safe. You flee or you die.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is trying to crush the separatist rebellion in the
Serbian province of Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs
nine to one and have long resisted Serbian rule.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian military attack is aimed at stopping the flow of
fighters and smuggled weapons from Albania by driving ethnic
Albanians sympathetic to the rebellion out of villages on the
Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic apparently wants to set up a kind of ``sanitary
cordon'' to cement his control over Kosovo. Diplomats and military
officials fear that the escalating conflict could draw the region
into a wider war.
</P>
<P>
   A line of disheveled and forlorn mothers, fathers and children
stumbled Thursday down jagged limestone rocks towards an alpine
valley carpeted with tiny flowers. Many tugged wearily at bulging
nylon bags. Others clutched silent, wide-eyed children. Leading
them were grim-faced young men clutching AK-47 assault rifles,
members of the Kosovo Liberation Army, a rebel group fighting Serb
forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the valley behind them lay their villages and hamlets, most
smoldering in ruins. Their silence was broken only by the distant
thud of heavy artillery and occasional retorts of automatic fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks as if the Serbs are pushing the refugees along,''
said Andrew Harper, the U.N. representative in Bajram Curri, 15
miles south of Padesh. ``They appear to be harassing them now to
move them to get out. We are preparing for a huge influx.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's decision to attack the rebels undermines the
American diplomatic effort to bring the two sides together. In May,
Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. envoy, persuaded Milosevic to begin
direct talks with the Albanian leadership. As a result, he called
for sanctions on Belgrade to be suspended.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The about-face angered many European allies, since Washington
had pushed Europeans to adopt them.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been unable to seal off the mountainous and
desolate border. During the last few weeks he has watched weapons,
supplies and mercenaries _ many of them veterans of the Bosnian
conflict _ flood in to build up the Kosovo Liberation Army, Western
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel force is fighting for a separate state. It already
controls as much as 40 percent of the province and for the past
three months has been engaged in daily hit-and-run clashes with the
police and the military.
</P>
<P>
   Now thousands of villages lie empty, shattered by heavy shells
and in flames, according to refugees that arrived in this mountain
pass Thursday. They said that Serb soldiers are slaughtering
cattle, sheep and horses, and attacking families hiding in the
hills with helicopter and mortar fire.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one route left open to the refugees, the route out
of the country over the razor-back peaks of the Repe Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   At nightfall hundreds of ethnic Albanians flee to the peaks,
wait for dawn amid the forbidding stone crevices, then make their
way down the precarious footholds to Albania, according to refugees
and refugee officials.
</P>
<P>
   At least a half dozen have died in the last stretches of the
trek, including two children, and dozens more are thought to have
died on the Kosovo side of the border, relief officials say. Many
of those who arrive have been been wounded by fragments of mortars
and artillery rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic closed off an area in central Kosovo in March. The
special police killed at least 80 people in villages where
guerrillas operated.
</P>
<P>
   Far from crippling the rebel movement the assault saw hundreds
or thousands of young men swell the rebel ranks and tons of weapons
and ammunition pour across the border on mule trains.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot make a distinction anymore between a member of the
Kosovo Liberation Army and those who struggle for independence in
Kosovo,'' said a young man in a black leather jacket, who plans to
return to Kosovo within a day to fight.
</P>
<P>
   All of the some two dozen men who crossed the border Thursday
and were interviewed said they intended to return to fight.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Bajram Curri, that has seen its population of 8,000
swollen by the arrival of 4,500 refugees in the past three days,
was awash in clusters of secretive young men, several bearded and
wearing Islamic skull caps, who said they have come to join the
battle across the border. The town appears to be a staging area for
many who plan to join the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Halil Dukaj, 55, stood on a rutted dirt road leading down from
the mountains with his wife. His face was crisscrossed with lines
and covered by a gray stubble. Dark circles hung below his eyes and
he said he has not slept much in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the last to leave my village,'' he said. ``The shelling
became unbearable. We tried to find shelter in another village, but
we were attacked from three sides and all food was cut off. As soon
as my wife and my family are safe I will return to my village to
fight. There is not a man among us who does not feel as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Serbs came into our village they captured nine young
men,'' said Zejnie Gaxheri, 60, who arrived Thursday with three
small grandchildren and 10 family members. ``They slit the throats
of these boys. They mutilated the corpses and left their bodies for
us to see.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am fed up,'' she said, flicking her fingers forward from
under her chin in a gesture of contempt. ``We are all fed up. The
world tells us to be patient. We were patient and look what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration's senior official
responsible for the Balkans expressed deep concern Thursday about
the violence in Kosovo. Robert Gelbard, the special representative
of the president to the region, used especially harsh language in
criticizing the government of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   He told a Senate panel that the United States would not shrink
from imposing increasingly harsh sanctions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, President Clinton met with ethnic Albanian leaders
from Kosovo who said they received assurances that Washington would
not allow their homeland to suffer the fate of Bosnia. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
