<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4878 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-stars-HNS &LR;      06-04 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-stars-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Stars see hope of win in Detroit
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT _ They are due, certainly. Some would even say overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mildew,'' Stars center Mike Modano suggests with a smile.
``It's been a long time. It's been tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it gets just a little tougher. To stay alive in these NHL
playoffs, Dallas must come up with a way to break through in its
own personal house of horrors _ Joe Louis Arena _ where a long run
of misery continued in Games 3 and 4 of these Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   An impossible task? Perhaps, but Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
insists he sees the light at the end of the tunnel as his team,
still down three games to two in the best-of-seven series,
approaches a 6:30 p.m. Game 6 faceoff at ``The Joe'' with nothing
less than a season on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think right now there's a confidence that we can play with
Detroit in their building,'' Hitchcock said. ``We need to take it
to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, ``I like the law of averages.''
</P>
<P>
   That much, at least, is in Dallas' favor. Since moving to Texas
in 1993, the Stars are just 2-16-2 at Joe Louis, including an 0-5
record in the playoffs. And while Dallas kept things interesting in
two games in Detroit last weekend, losses of 5-3 and 3-2 only added
to the inventory of negative images.
</P>
<P>
   The key to changing the ending, Hitchcock believes, is to tinker
with the beginning just a bit. Dallas fell behind 4-0 and 2-0 in
the games in Detroit, hardly an ideal approach for a
defense-oriented team that is at its best when getting ahead
quickly and grinding out low-scoring victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get down early,'' he said. ``If we get out of that
first period tied or better, that's a significant change in
strategy for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has to be our goal _ tied or better after the first _ and
build from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' best chance to do so may be in the Detroit nets _ and
between the ears of Red Wings goalie Chris Osgood. After stopping
Dallas for more than 58 minutes Wednesday night, Osgood was beaten
by a Guy Carbonneau wrist shot with just one minute, 25 seconds
remaining to force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Before the crowd could catch its breath, Osgood surrendered a
ridiculous 90-foot slap shot to Jamie Langenbrunner to settle the
issue just 46 seconds into OT.
</P>
<P>
   A fluke? Perhaps not. Langenbrunner's unlikely game-winner, in
fact, was the third long-distance goal Osgood has allowed in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Roenick beat him from just outside the blue line in the
opening series against Phoenix. St. Louis' Al MacInnis found the
net from just inside center ice in the conference semifinal. Toss
in Greg Adams' knuckler through the five-hole that accounted for
Dallas' winning goal in Game 2, and Osgood has endured some rocky
moments in the course of guiding the Wings within a game of their
third Stanley Cup finals appearance in four years.
</P>
<P>
   When Wednesday night's game was done, Osgood dressed hurriedly
and ducked out of the locker room, avoiding reporters. That left
teammates to express their support, some more enthusiastically than
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, they got a break,'' said Brent Gilchrist, the former
Star. ``But Chris played unbelievable just to keep us in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Larry Murphy echoed the theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it goes,'' he said. ``Now, it's just important
for us to get ready for Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be ready. So will Ozzie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars hope otherwise. With the series hanging in the balance
in the final period, they began to see something different from a
goalie who had denied them most of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players felt in the third period that all of a sudden
there were second-shot opportunities,'' Hitchcock said. ``We don't
know why. That's the first time in the series that has been
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As the game went on, you could see him second-guessing
himself,'' Modano said. ``But he's always come back and had strong
games, so I don't think we can count him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Red Wings aren't counting the Stars out after
watching the league's best regular-season team survive Wednesday
night's brush with playoff death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas obviously isn't giving up,'' Detroit captain Steve
Yzerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Not even at the thought of going back to ``The Joe,'' it seems.
Before heading to the airport Thursday afternoon, in fact,
Hitchcock actually seemed invigorated by the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In coaching, it's not the end result, it's the process,'' he
said. ``The process has been that we've gotten better and better as
this series has gone on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel confident that if we continue to improve we've got a
realistic chance of winning in that building.''
</P>
<P>
   With a bit more urgency in the air, the process resumes tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
