<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KID-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS JURY CONVICTS FOURTH-GRADER IN SEXUAL ASSAULT OF GIRL, 3 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ An 11-year-old boy was convicted Thursday in the sexual
assault and beating of a 3-year-old girl, and could be incarcerated
for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster, barely 4-foot-5 and weighing less than 70 pounds,
was convicted on two counts of aggravated sexual assault and one
count of injury to a child.
</P>
<P>
   A juvenile court jury deliberated for nearly seven hours before
returning the verdicts, which sent the boy's mother rushing from
the courtroom in tears and angered family friends who had attended
the trial for the past four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a threat to the world,'' said Freda Brown, who sat
beside the boy's mother in the hallway as the disposition stage of
the trial, known in adult court as the punishment phase, got under
way. ``He's still a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other boys, 8- and 7-year-old brothers, admitted taking part
in the April 9 attack on the West Dallas girl beside a creek in the
neighborhood where the children lived. The younger boys could not
be prosecuted because of their ages.
</P>
<P>
   When he was questioned by police the day after the assault, the
11-year-old, who is a fourth-grade special education student,
confessed to hitting the girl with a shoe and a brick and
participating in the sexual assault. On the witness stand
Wednesday, he recanted that story and said he only hit the girl and
that the two brothers engaged in the sexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   The toddler, left bruised and bloodied in a muddy pool of water,
was found wandering naked up the creek's embankment by an uncle who
had been searching for her. She was treated and released from a
local hospital. Tests for evidence of a sexual assault came up
negative, but a doctor testified during the trial that that is not
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who said the boy calls her ``aunt'' although she is only
a family friend, said the police ``bribed'' a confession from him
because they could not prosecute the other two boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to get somebody so they got the 11-year-old,'' she
said. She said he admitted his guilt last April because detectives
fed him hamburgers and told him he could go home if he cooperated
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes before the verdict was reached, the jurors came
back into court to request that a portion of Detective Greg
Dugger's testimony relating to the boy's oral confession be read to
them. Dugger, who testified Tuesday, said the boy told him he had
molested her.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found him the boy guilty of those two sexual assault
counts _ punishable by a maximum of 40 years each _ but acquitted
him of a third, which alleged that he made genital-to-genital
contact with the 3-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   He also was convicted of hitting the girl and pushing her down
an embankment and into the creek. That offense, injury to a child,
carries a maximum sentence of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is to return to court Friday to deliberate the boy's
sentence. It will have three sentencing options _ giving the boy
probation in his home, placing him in a treatment facility for six
months to a year, or sentencing him to serve time in a Texas Youth
Commission facility. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the disposition phase of the trial began Thursday afternoon,
the jury heard from a juvenile probation official, who has visited
with the boy every day since his arrest, and a psychologist who
examined him four times in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   Juliana Moore, the probation officer, said the investigation
conducted by her department revealed that the boy suffers from a
series of behavioral problems, including aggressiveness. He has
twice been suspended from school for threatening and yelling at
teachers and fighting with other students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not seen him exhibit any signs of remorse,'' Moore told
the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allison Krauth, testified that the boy told her candidly
that he was not sorry for what happened to the girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even feel sorry for her because she followed us,'' she
quoted him as saying in reference to how the three boys and the
girl came to be at the creek together. Previous testimony indicated
that the girl was left alone in a van at her house, got out and
followed the boys to the creek.
</P>
<P>
   There, according to testimony from the two brothers, they
undressed her, all three sexually molested her, beat her with shoes
and a brick, and the 11-year-old pushed her down a concrete
embankment to the creek.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said her department is recommending TYC confinement for
the boy so he can receive sex offender and anger control
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs a highly structured environment with close
supervision and intensive treatment _ all encompassing therapy,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
