<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ANNIVERSARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE GOVERNMENT WARNS DISSIDENT AGAINST MAKING PUBLIC
STATEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHINA-HONGKONG, CHINA-CONGRESS) 
(js) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Earlier this week, shortly after finishing years of
prison and probation, a former senior Chinese official openly
criticized the government, questioning its slow progress toward
democracy and condemning its decision in 1989 to send in soldiers
to quell student-led demonstrations in Tiananmen Square. He then
challenged the government _ which has professed its commitment to
the rule of law _ to respect his right to speak.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the ninth anniversary of the June 3-4 crackdown in
which hundreds of civilians were killed, the Chinese government
picked up that gauntlet and told Bao Tong, a former Central
Committee member who was imprisoned on charges of disclosing state
secrets _ revealing to student leaders in May 1989 that the
government planned to impose martial law in Beijing _ that such
freewheeling public statements would simply not be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Less that 24 hours after interviews with Bao appeared in foreign
publications, he said that the authorities had informed him that he
could only grant interviews with the advance approval of ``the
government organizations concerned'' and ominously warned of
penalties if any rules were violated.
</P>
<P>
   ``By China's Constitution and law I should enjoy the right to
freedom of expression and speech and I'm very willing to talk about
my views in a frank way,'' said Bao, 65, in a telephone interview
moments after he had been informed of the restrictions. ``So it is
with regret that I inform you it is impossible to interview me
now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bao's political views were no secret. In 1989, when he was
chief-of-staff to Zhao Ziyang, secretary general of the Communist
Party, both he and Zhao opposed the use of force against
demonstrators and indicated sympathy for their goals. Zhao, who was
ousted after the declaration of martial law, has been under a loose
form of house arrest ever since. Bao, the most senior Chinese
official jailed in 1989, spent seven years in prison, followed by
two years stripped of all political rights.
</P>
<P>
   On May 27, he said, officials from the Public Security Bureau
visited his house to tell him that his two-year probation was over
and his rights restored. And Bao started talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to chat with friends, that is my nature,'' said Bao .
``And since my political rights are now restored, the constitution
gives me the right to freedom of expression.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview Thursday morning, before officials warned
him, Bao said: ``The government has announced it will rule the
country according to law. So if I don't exercise my rights, it's
not good for the image of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Bao's challenge comes at an awkward time for the government, as
it is busily preparing for President Clinton's arrival in China on
June 25 and has taken great pains to emphasize the country's slow
but steady progress towards rule of law and greater personal
freedom. And it comes not from a longtime dissident, but from a
longtime Party stalwart and former associate of the late leader
Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with just five years ago, the government allows the
publication of a much wider range of books and magazines, and
newspapers and television are allowed to deal with some previously
taboo topics, including police brutality and rethinking Mao's
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   But the confrontation with Bao, as well as the Security Bureau's
handling of some prominent dissidents in recent weeks, serve as
reminders that much remains the same. Close to two dozen democracy
advocates around the country have been been detained in recent
weeks as part of an apparent campaign to prevent discussion of the
1989 Tiananmen Square crackdown, while others have received stern
warnings from security agents, according to a Hong Kong-based human
rights group, the Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic
Movement in China.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with The Washington Post, published on Wednesday,
and the Hong Kong-based South China Morning Post, published on
Thursday, Bao discussed a wide range of topics. He described how he
turned up for a meeting on May 28, 1989, a week before the
massacre, and was instead driven directly to jail. And he called
the decision to send troops into Tiananmen Square a big
``mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, immediately after he had been warned by security
agents against granting interviews to foreign reporters without
permission, _ a procedure that is in the regulations but often
ignored by private citizens and journalists here _ Bao gave a
cryptic answer to a question that had been posed earlier: Is China
becoming more free?
</P>
<P>
   ``What has just happened now is the best answer to that
question,'' he responded.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
