<HEADER>
A4886 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVACY-INTERNET-BOS &LR;      06-04 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 FTC WARNS THAT INTERNET OFTEN MAKES SURFERS GIVE UP PRIVACY
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission warned yesterday that getting onto
the Internet can often mean giving up your right to privacy and
urged Congress to establish protections for children, who the
agency said were especially vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting 1,400 of the most popular Web sites, the agency
found that the great majority requested personal information from
visitors _ names, addresses, phone numbers, and sometimes even
Social Security numbers and medical information. But there are no
legal restrictions on how companies can use this data, and the FTC
said most companies don't even bother to tell consumers how their
personal information will be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of on-line businesses have yet to adopt even
the most fundamental fair information practice,'' the agency said
in a report issued in Washington yesterday. And many of the sites
that offer no privacy protection solicit personal information from
children.
</P>
<P>
   The study's results have led the FTC to abandon its previous
policy that self-regulation by Internet-based businesses would be
sufficient to protect the privacy rights of citizens. Instead, the
agency is calling for a new federal law to strictly limit the
ability of Internet businesses to collect personal information from
children. And the agency held open the possibility that it might
request additional privacy protections for adults as well.
</P>
<P>
   The report dismayed business groups, which fear new federal
regulations that would make doing business on the Internet more
difficult and costly. The Direct Marketing Association, which
represents many businesses with Internet sites, said that
self-regulation efforts are finally beginning to work, and stated
its opposition to Internet privacy laws covering adults or
children.
</P>
<P>
   The association's senior vice president, Connie Heatley, cited a
study from the association that found that 70 percent of the most
popular children's Web sites have written privacy policies. ``We
think that there has been progress made, that organizations have
clearly responded to the FTC's challenge,'' Heatley said.
</P>
<P>
   But US Representative Ed Markey said the study proves the need
for an Internet privacy bill of rights. The Massachusetts Democrat
said Internet companies have shown little interest in regulating
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been addressing the Direct Marketing Association on this
issue for the past four years,'' he said. ``This survey makes it
quite clear that a very high percentage of direct marketers have
not heard the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Markey said he introduced legislation last summer to protect the
privacy of Internet users, but the House had taken no action on the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pitofsky, chairman of the FTC, said that despite the
report's disappointing findings, he would not call the industry's
efforts at self-regulation a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report is not meant to signal by us or perhaps by others
that there is no hope for industry self-regulation,
</P>
<P>
   he said. ``It's pretty clear that more incentives are necessary
to get industry to engage in what they thought they could
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC study was conducted in March. It found that:
</P>
<P>
   More than 85 percent of the sites surveyed requested personal
information from visitors. But only 14 percent told the visitors
how that information would be used.
</P>
<P>
   89 percent of the sites aimed at children asked for personal
information. Of these, only 54 percent provided any privacy
information to children and parents.
</P>
<P>
   More than three-quarters of the sites didn't ask children to get
a parent's permission before providing data.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 10 percent gave parents the right to restrict the use
of information about their children.
</P>
<P>
   The report calls for legislation that would require Internet
sites aimed at children to get the permission of a parent before
seeking information from children. Parents would also be guaranteed
the right to limit the use of such information.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC didn't recommend new laws to govern the use of personal
information collected from adults, but the agency left open the
possibility. It promised a set of recommendations on this issue
later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Rotenberg, director of the Electronic Privacy Information
Center in Washington, said the results of the survey call into
question the Clinton administration's hands-off approach to the
Internet. ``My view is that the White House, and the FTC to some
extent, backed themselves into a corner by saying that they wanted
to take a broad-based self-regulating approach to the Internet,''
Rotenberg said. ``Things like privacy protection do require
government action.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rotenberg said the FTC report doesn't go far enough. He
noted that many Internet sites force users to provide information
about themselves if they want to make use of the site. Rotenberg
favors a law that would require Web sites to grant access to
visitors who wish to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Steinhardt, president of the Electronic Frontier
Foundation, an Internet civil liberties group, also had a problem
with the FTC report. Steinhardt said the legislation might prevent
minors from communicating over the Internet with organizations
offering advice on gay rights, birth control, and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe that minors should be required to get their
parents' permission to visit Web sites that contain health or
reproductive information,'' said Steinhardt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2105EDT &QL; 
