A4897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCI-ANTITRUST-NYT &LR;      06-04 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCI-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCI PROPOSAL STILL RAISES INTERNET ANTITRUST WORRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The top European regulator reviewing Worldcom Inc.'s proposed
$37 billion acquisition of the MCI Communications Corp. said on
Thursday that MCI's proposed sale of part of its Internet business
may not be sufficient to allay his antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   MCI announced last week that it had agreed to sell its wholesale
Internet unit to Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC for $625 million in cash.
European regulators and the Justice Department had made clear to
MCI and Worldcom a concern that the combined company could unfairly
dominate the Internet and that the regulators would require the
companies to sell off some cyberspace assets.
</P>
<P>
   Foes of the deal, led by the GTE Corp., which lost in its
attempt to acquire MCI, have been pushing Worldcom to sell its
Uunet unit. Uunet is the leading Internet service company.
</P>
<P>
   But Worldcom has refused. Instead, MCI agreed to sell part of
its Internet unit to Cable &AMP; Wireless. MCI told Justice Department
officials about the Cable &AMP; Wireless deal more than a week before
it was publicly announced, in the hope of winning the department's
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   But the department refused to assure MCI that the Cable &AMP;
Wireless deal would be sufficient to remove its concerns.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Karel Van Miert, the European Union's competition
commissioner, also refused to give such an assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that what has been offered will be good enough,''
Van Miert said at a news conference in Washington. ``I even have
some doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Miert said he had notified each affected company of his
continued concerns and said the companies would each have a chance
to make additional suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   GTE hailed Van Miert's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Van Miert's comments today clearly indicate that MCI's recent
attempt to create the appearance of a divestiture through partial
sale of some minor Internet assets are not going to fool the EC,''
said Bob Bishop, a GTE spokesman, on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
