<HEADER>
A4905 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BOEHNER-LAWSUI     06-04 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BOEHNER-LAWSUIT-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  BOEHNER MAY SUE SECOND-RANKING DEMOCRAT
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald F. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 4 -- Congressman John A. Boehner's lawsuit
against another member of Congress may expand to include the second
most powerful Democrat in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The West Chester Republican filed a civil lawsuit against Rep.
Jim McDermott in January of 1997, alleging the Washington Democrat
distributed an illegally recorded cellular phone call between
Boehner -- who is chairman of the House Republican Conference --
and other top Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the U.S. Department of Justice (DOJ) also launched
its own criminal investigation to determine if McDermott broke any
laws.
</P>
<P>
   R. Ted Cruz, a lawyer for Boehner, said Thursday the DOJ
investigation may prove McDermott collaborated with House Minority
Whip David E. Bonior of Michigan before McDermott released a tape
of the call to three newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequently the fruits of a criminal investigation are very
helpful to a civil lawsuit,'' Cruz said. ``There is reason to
believe it will come out during the Justice Department's
investigation that there was communication between Congressman
McDermott and Congressman Bonior. If Bonior was involved, we would
be likely to add him as a defendant in our suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the Boehner camp agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could add other defendants to our lawsuit once more
information comes out during the criminal investigation,'' said
Marc S. Lampkin, general counsel to the House Republican
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But Boehner is unhappy with the speed at which DOJ is pursuing
its probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that continued delay in the criminal
investigation will impede my attempt to seek civil redress against
other parties, including other members of the House, who are
responsible for the disclosure of my private cellular phone
conversation,'' Boehner wrote in a letter to Attorney General Janet
Reno Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Boehner's lawyers also said DOJ's investigation is interfering
with their ability to conduct an aggressive civil investigation.
They argue that the statute of limitations will run out on their
case by January, and time is running short for them to conduct a
thorough investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want there to be competing investigations,'' Lampkin
said. ``Witnesses may hold off in their dealings with us because
they could be offered immunity (by the DOJ).''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to see the (the DOJ) carry out their duty to
prosecute federal crimes. It is disturbing that they have been
dragging their feet on it,'' Cruz said. ``The purpose of this
letter is to ask the attorney general to enforce her duties.''
</P>
<P>
   McDermott's lawyer, however, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that the criminal investigation has any bearing on
their case whatsoever. Nothing in the civil action has been delayed
by the Justice Department in any way,'' said Frank Cicero. ``They
are taking this as an opportunity to flog the attorney general and
Justice Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Cicero added that he believes Boehner's suit will be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filed a motion to dismiss on Monday which is based on
strong constitutional arguments,'' he said. ``The reason (the phone
call) was front-page newsworthy was because the speaker had made an
agreement to not try to spin the deal he got from the Ethics
committee.''
</P>
<P>
   During that fateful phone conversation, Boehner, House Speaker
Newt Gingrich, House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey and other
Republican leaders were discussing damage control strategy for the
House Ethics Committee's investigation into Gingrich's political
use of charity organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a matter of important public interest, that is why it
came out,'' Cicero said. ``This was not some private conversation
between Boehner and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz challenged the validity of Cicero's argument. He said
McDermott's team is just trying to ``distract attention from the
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if the cellular phone call is about the blue
prints for a nuclear submarine or your grandmother's recipe for
lemon meringue pie, the interception and distribution of the phone
call are against the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
