<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JUNE 5
</HEADLINE>
  Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-LIGHT-TRUCKS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, June 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 2,
about Government crash tests involving several types of vehicles
misstated the predicted result when a Ford Explorer, a mid-size
sport utility vehicle, hits a car from the side. The
two-wheel-drive version of the Explorer, which was part of the
test, is less likely to ride over the car _ not more likely _ than
the four-wheel-drive version is.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-GRALLA-NYT (moved on Saturday, May 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, May 30,
about an obituary of Vice Adm. Arthur R. Gralla on Sunday omitted
the names of two surviving sisters. They are Lynn Kritzer of North
Palm Beach, Fla., and Muriel Minkoff of Marlboro, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June 3,
about May automotive sales misstated some percentage changes. The
figures were correct in the table with the article: General Motors
truck sales rose 20.1 percent, not 19.2; Ford car sales fell 5.2
percent, not 5.5, and Ford truck sales rose 8.6 percent, not 6.2.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BOOK-EXPO-MEDIA-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 31)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 31,
about Tom Wolfe's appearance at the Book Expo America convention in
Chicago misstated the publication month for his new book, ``A Man
in Full'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux). It is November, not
September. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
