<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-ART-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAIL SALES UP 7 PERCENT IN MAY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ American retailers continued an impressive growth
spurt last month, one that bodes well for coming company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in retail stores open at least a year rose 7.1 percent in
May, according to the Goldman Sachs Retail Composite Index.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers, which have not benefited much from the robust U.S.
economy in the last few years, were finally enjoying the results of
strong consumer spending. May's 7.1 percent increase in retail
sales followed on the heels of a very strong April, when sales rose
10.2 percent and one of the largest monthly gains in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   And many retail analysts think that the buying might not end
soon. ``The beat goes on,'' said Richard Baum, a retail analyst at
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``The month was an extension of what has been
going on all year. We have still got the same story with the
leading indicators. Average hourly earnings are up a little over 3
percent. Housing turns are up 15 percent. The fact that you have
some paydown on consumer debt is producing personal expenditures.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers were able to sell a lot of their merchandise for full
price last month, which means that profit margins might be stronger
than expected when earnings are reported in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are raising our earnings estimates for a lot of
retailers,'' said Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst at Lehman Bros.
</P>
<P>
   From T-shirts to curtains to lawn mowers to patio furniture,
Americans continued their love affair with discount merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at Wal-Mart Stores Inc. rose 11 percent in May compared
with May 1997, and Kmart Corp. said its sales gained 6.9 percent
last month. Dollar General, which serves mostly lower-income
communities, said sales rose 14.4 percent, and Target, a discount
chain for middle-class shoppers, reported a 7.4 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength remains in discount and specialty apparel,'' Baum
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed a variety of clothing stores saw a healthy rise in sales
during May. The Gap said sales soared 24 percent, with huge gains
in all of its stores, including Old Navy and Banana Republic.
Talbots Inc. said sales jumped 13 percent. Even The Limited, which
has had several tough years, reported a sales gain of 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Department stores, which have trailed the rest of the industry
all year, came in behind other stores again. Sales at Federated
Department Stores Inc., for example, gained 1.8 percent and the
J.C. Penney Co. reported a mere four-tenths of a percent increase.
The Dayton Hudson Corp.'s same-store sales rose 6.1 percent,
largely because of its Target unit.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury department stores offered exceptions to the
lackluster department store sales. Sales at Neiman Marcus, a
Harcourt General unit, rose 9.6 percent, and Saks Holdings Inc.,
which operates Saks Fifth Avenue, said sales rose 3.7 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These stores may be benefiting from the first real hemline
change in several years as apparel makers have been churning out
skirts just below the knee and longer.
</P>
<P>
   Market prognosticators should take note: According to Wall
Street folklore, the market goes the way of hemlines. But perhaps
another hot seller this spring _ short pants like pedal pushers and
clam diggers _ will compensate.
</P>
<P>
   Sales among merchants of home furnishings and computers also
rose. Same-store sales at Pier 1 Imports Inc. rose 7.1 percent and
the Bombay Co. reported gains of 18 percent. Circuit City said
sales rose 12 percent and Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. reported sales
increases of 5.4 percent citing higher sales of consumer
electronics, appliance and home-improvement products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
