<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-NYT &LR;      06-04 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIA ACCEPTS PLAN TO END BATTLES WITH ERITREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea _ As Ethiopian and Eritrean troops continued to
exchange artillery fire along their border, the Ethiopian prime
minister on Thursday accepted a peace plan proposed by the United
States and Rwanda that would end the escalating border war.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from the Eritrean side.
</P>
<P>
   As a first step, the proposal calls for the unilateral
withdrawal of Eritrean forces from the disputed border town of
Badame, something the Ethiopian prime minister, Meles Zenawi, has
demanded since the beginning of the crisis three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But it remained unclear if the Eritrean president, Isaias
Afewerki, would accept the pullback. Earlier this week, he said his
troops would never withdraw from the town, which Eritrea considers
its territory.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Rice, the United States assistant secretary of State for
African affairs, met late Thursday night in this capital with
Afewerki in an effort to persuade him to sign onto the proposal
before more blood is shed. She called Ethiopia's acceptance of the
plan ``a necessary but not sufficient step'' towards peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half an agreement is less than 50 percent if you're talking
about war and peace,'' Ms. Rice said in an interview just before
meeting with the president. ``We hope that Eritrea will also accept
this package of recommendations in toto. Piecemeal acceptance of
one part or another is not the way forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The two countries have disagreed peacefully about the precise
demarcation of their borders ever since Eritrea became independent
in 1993. But on May 6, Eritrean troops clashed with Ethiopian
forces in Badame. Ethiopian officials had been administering the
town and Eritrean officers challenged their authority.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the conflict has intensified rapidly, with both
countries sending thousands of troops backed by tanks and heavy
artillery toward the border. The two armies have dug trenches less
than two miles apart in Badame, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several skirmishes in recent days, but on
Wednesday a full-scale artillery duel broke out near the border
town of Zala Ambessa.
</P>
<P>
   A team of diplomats and officials from the United States and
Rwanda released a proposal on Wednesday calling for the withdrawal
of Eritrean troops from Badame to the positions they held before
May 6. The two nations would begin talks to determine the border.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, both armies would pull back from the border regions to
create a demilitarized zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
