<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HARSCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH C. HARSCH, 93, JOURNALIST WHO WITNESSED HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: R.I., Mass., Vt., Ohio)  (ja) 
 By ERIC PACE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joseph C. Harsch, a dashing newspaper, radio and
television journalist and author who had a knack for being on hand
when history was made, died Wednesday at his home in Jamestown,
R.I. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Harsch, an Ohio-born Christian Scientist, logged much mileage
during his journalistic career. He worked for the Christian Science
Monitor from 1929 to 1988. For half those years, he worked
concurrently for network radio and television: for CBS from 1943-49
and later for NBC and then ABC.
</P>
<P>
   He was a correspondent in Washington in the Depression-racked
1930s and then covered World War II initially from bases in Fascist
Rome and then Hitler's Berlin from 1939 to 1941. After the war he
was a columnist for The Monitor and its chief editorial writer.
</P>
<P>
   His writing could be vivid. A month after the devastating
Japanese surprise attack on Pearl Harbor, he was on board the U.S.
carrier Enterprise as it departed from Hawaii, and he encountered a
promising naval officer, William F. Halsey Jr., who later became a
five-star admiral of the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were tears in his eyes _ whether from the wind whipping
in over the lip of the deck or from depth of feeling was the
unanswered question,'' Harsch wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Late in his life, he won praise for a volume of memoirs he
wrote, ``At the Hinge of History: A Reporter's Story'' (1993,
University of Georgia Press).
</P>
<P>
   As The Monitor said Thursday, ``He seemed to be everywhere, or
at least everywhere something important was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in Washington when the Depression confronted President
Herbert Hoover, and he was still there when President Franklin D.
Roosevelt's New Deal began grappling with it. He moved on to London
and was there in September, 1939, when Britain's Prime Minister
Neville Chamberlain declared war against Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   After that Harsch moved on to wartime Berlin, and later to
Hawaii, on his way to the Soviet Union. So he and his wife, Anne,
happened to be in Hawaii in December, 1941, when the Japanese
attacked Pearl Harbor, bringing the United States into World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   As he told the story, when he awoke in his hotel room to noise
of the attack, he woke his wife, saying, ``Listen to this, dear.
You have often asked me what an air raid sounds like. This is a
good imitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he was in Australia with Gen. Douglas MacArthur when the
general, having commanded the unsuccessful defense of the
Philippines against the Japanese, made his prophetic pledge, ``I
shall return.''
</P>
<P>
   Harsch went on to be with Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower in France,
and in ``At the Hinge of History'' he recalled the part he played
in the capture of Hitler's architect, Albert Speer, in a bathroom
in a German castle: Harsch did some translating for a British
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Harsch sent reports from Nazi concentration camps in 1945, after
they were overrun by the advancing Allied forces. And early in the
Cold War, in 1947 and 1948, he roved behind what Winston Churchill
had named the Iron Curtain. Presciently, Harsch concluded that it
would not be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   His many writings include the books ``Pattern of Conquest''
(1941), in which he analyzed the threat posed by Nazism before the
United States entered the war, and ``The Curtain Isn't Iron''
(1950), about the Cold War and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   He was made a Commander of the British Empire by Queen Elizabeth
II, and he won two Overseas Press Club Awards and other honors.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Toledo, Ohio, he received one bachelor's degree in 1927
from Williams College and another in 1929 from Cambridge
University.
</P>
<P>
   He married Anne Elizabeth Wood in 1932. She died last year.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the former Edna Raemer _ his
longtime editorial assistant _ whom he married late last month;
three sons, William of Saunderstown, R.I., Jonathan of Jamestown
and Paul of Pownal, Vt.; 12 grandchildren; one great-grandchild;
and a sister, Katherine Jamieson of Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
