<HEADLINE>
EXPECT CHILITO TO BE IN MOTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ The last horse entered in the Belmont Stakes,
Chilito, might be first out of the starting gate Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect he'll be on the lead,'' trainer Graham Motion said
from his barn at Laurel Race Course in Maryland, where the Flamingo
Stakes winner is based. ``That's what he likes to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Motion attributed Chilito's poor efforts in the Kentucky Derby
(11th, 27{ lengths behind Real Quiet) and the Jersey Derby (fifth)
to the fact ``he didn't get his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Chilito's four victories in 10 starts all came in front-running
style. He was a surprise entry Thursday morning and is 30-1 on the
Belmont morning line.
</P>
<P>
   Also likely to show early speed in the 1{-mile race are Grand
Slam, who's 6-1, and Basic Trainee, the 99-1 long shot.
</P>
<P>
   Chilito is scheduled to be vanned to New York today.
</P>
<P>
   Accuweather, or not: In the ever-changing forecast, clear skies,
a breeze and a high temperature of 72 are expected here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested development: When Real Quiet arrived from Kentucky on
Wednesday, owner Mike Pegram and Los Alamitos executive Brad
McKinzie rode in one of the cars escorting the colt's van from the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   McKinzie: ``I told him, `Mike, I always thought you and I might
wind up in the back seat of a police car in New York City, but not
with our hands in front of us.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
