<HEADER>
A4940 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS &LR;      06-04 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES REJECT STARR'S PLEA FOR QUICK RULING ON PRIVILEGE CLAIMS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court rejected independent counsel
Kenneth W. Starr's request Thursday to quickly resolve questions
over whether Secret Service agents and a senior White House aide
can be forced to testify before a grand jury _ leaving the legal
disputes between Starr and President Clinton dangling until the
autumn or early winter.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-paragraph notice, the justices effectively ordered a
White House appeal of two unfavorable lower court rulings to
proceed through a traditional appellate process that probably will
take months to complete. Though the decision was predicted, it was
immediately deemed a significant setback for Starr, who has been
trying to expedite his investigation of the Monica S. Lewinsky case
and was relying on the Supreme Court for help.
</P>
<P>
   After a string of legal defeats over the last month, White House
aides and lawyers hailed the decision as a victory for the
president and the legal rights they said he was trying to protect.
Those aides took strong exception to the notion that Clinton was
trying to stall Starr's investigation with lengthy appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is pleased,'' said White House press secretary
Michael McCurry. He added later: ``There is no delay. I mean, today
is what? Day 1,400 of Ken Starr's tenure as an independent counsel
at the rate of $30,000 a day of taxpayers' money? Now if there's
any delay, that's the delay right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr, citing a ``serious criminal investigation'' and raising
the image of former President Richard Nixon, had asked the court to
take the unusual step of circumventing the traditional appellate
process so he could gather the information he said he needed to
bring his investigation to a close. Analysts said the court had
taken such action only a few times in the nation's history and it
would have been extraordinary for the court to take it again.
</P>
<P>
   In its brief order, the court wrote, ``The petition for a writ
of certiorari before judgment is denied without prejudice. It is
assumed the Court of Appeals will proceed expeditiously to decide
this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office, which has tacitly accused the White House of
delaying the investigation with claims of executive privilege,
attorney-client privilege, and special privileges for Secret
Service agents, again called for cooperation and an expedited
conclusion to its case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the Supreme Court's determination today, we will
proceed to litigate these issues as quickly as the Court of
Appeals' schedule will permit,'' Starr said in a written statement.
``This office will continue to take every reasonable and
practicable step to bring out the relevant facts as promptly as
possible, so this investigation can be concluded in a thorough and
expeditious manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Starr spokesman Charles Bakaly: ``We believe that the
American people's need for facts in this criminal investigation
justifies extraordinary requests for relief.''
</P>
<P>
   In decisions spread over the last several weeks, US District
Judge Norma Holloway Johnson rejected White House claims that two
Clinton advisers, deputy counsel Bruce Lindsey and communications
aide Sidney Blumenthal, were protected from testifying before the
grand jury because of executive privilege and attorney-client
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also rejected the administration's argument that three
Secret Service agents assigned to the presidential detail should
not be forced to testify before the grand jury on any activity they
might have witnessed or conversations they might have overheard.
</P>
<P>
   The White House on Monday dropped its claim of executive
privilege and appealed the attorney-client privilege decision as it
affected Lindsey. The Justice Department also appealed the Secret
Service ruling. Because of Thursday's Supreme Court order, those
appeals will now be heard by a three-judge panel of the US Court of
Appeals in Washington, possibly by later this month. That panel is
not likely to issue a decision until late summer or early autumn,
and either side would then have the right to appeal the decision
before a larger panel of judges. Finally, the losing side could
appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the White House did this just to delay, but it
was not in their interest to have this go right to the Supreme
Court,'' said Fred Lawrence, an associate dean at the Boston
University Law School. ``Anything that deprives your adversary of
something he wants gives you some greater opportunity to negotiate
an arrangement, whether you are talking about making witnesses
available from the White House or paying back rent in a landlord
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Blumenthal appeared before the grand jury Thursday
since the White House decided not to appeal the judge's order that
his conversations with Clinton were not protected by executive
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal's lawyers, visibly angry, said from the courthouse
steps that prosecutors questioned their client for 2 1/2 hours
before the grand jury about White House conversations concerning
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus today was what do you discuss at the White House
when you discuss us,'' said William McDaniel, one of Blumenthal's
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal followed Democratic Party fund-raiser and activist
Nate Landow, who spent about an hour before the grand jury,
presumably answering questions about whether he tried to influence
the testimony of former White House volunteer Kathleen Willey.
Willey has accused Clinton of groping and kissing her in a study
adjacent to the Oval Office as she asked him for a job _ an
accusation Clinton has flatly denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done,'' Landow told reporters as he quickly left the
courthouse. Blumenthal's lawyers said he was expected back before
the grand jury at an undetermined date.
</P>
<P>
   For prosecutors, though, it is Lindsey, Clinton's closest
confidant in the White House, whom they regard as their potentially
most valuable witness as they investigate whether the president may
have lied under oath about his relationship with Lewinsky or tried
to obstruct justice and suborn perjury in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey has told prosecutors he has been privy to no wrongdoing
at the White House. But he has declined to answer prosecutors'
questions in 14 different areas of the Lewinsky case, citing
attorney-client privilege as the reason for his silence.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has also argued that if Secret Service agents
are allowed to testify, future presidents and others who receive
government protection may try to distance themselves from their
assigned details and put themselves inadvertently in harm's way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
