<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERENNIAL BATTLE IN FOURTH ESTATE  
 CHOOSING PAPER OVER CELLULOID  
 WHEN ALL IS DONE, MAKE A MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are some entertainment reporters out there who
won't sleep so well Friday night. In an essay in the July issue of
Premiere magazine, which will be hand-delivered to a select few
media movers and shakers Friday, the famously pugnacious Miramax
co-chairman HARVEY WEINSTEIN rails against the use of anonymous
quoted sources. Especially _ surprise _ in articles about him.
</P>
<P>
   But in his quest to admonish reporters like Dana Harris and Ross
Johnson of The Hollywood Reporter _ who wrote a piece last year
titled ``How Healthy Is the Patient?'' about allegations of
financial problems foisted on Miramax by ``The English Patient'' _
Weinstein uncovered the never-ending enmity between reporters and
editors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reporters would tell me, `Oh, this editor has that agenda,'
and editors would tell me, `Oh that reporter has this agenda,'''
said Weinstein, who interviewed several reporters and editors for
his story. ``You'd go in talking to editors and you'd commiserate
with them, and then you'd talk to reporters who would blame it on
the editors. The reporters would always say, `We'd rather be fair,
we'd rather be smart, but our editors tell us make it sexy, make it
hot.'''
</P>
<P>
   Choosing Paper Over Celluloid
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect any screenplays from DAVID FOSTER WALLACE, the
author of the 1,079-page best seller ``Infinite Jest.'' Although he
joined the writers Susan Minot, Dale Peck, David O. Russell and
Todd Solondz in a forum on ``The Seductions of Celluloid,''
convened by Harper's magazine Tuesday night, Foster said he did not
find the medium even remotely seductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard enough time writing fiction,'' Wallace said at a
postpanel party at the Coffee Shop. ``The idea of working on
something, and then having 12 or 14 other people who are answering
to other guys change it, just kind of makes me cringe. No amount of
money would make me be able to take it. I think my ego is too
fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   When All Is Done, Make a Movie
</P>
<P>
   What is left to do when your life has already been so cinematic:
Your grandfather was a renowned diplomat, your grandmother was one
of Washington's grand hostesses, your parents disappeared in a
plane over the Bermuda Triangle and you have wandered Africa
studying tigers with the Smithsonian Institution?
</P>
<P>
   LAVINIA CURRIER decided, of course, to make a movie _ about a
man's relationship with a wild leopard, filmed in the Jordanian
desert.
</P>
<P>
   Opening June 12 in Los Angeles and New York, the movie,
``Passion in the Desert'' (Fine Line Features), is the first
feature-length film to be directed by Ms. Currier, 41, whose social
pedigree is extravagant even by Hollywood standards.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandfather, DAVID BRUCE, was the U.S. envoy to France,
Germany, Britain, China and NATO before his death in 1977. Her
grandmother was known for her A-list Georgetown parties and,
shortly before her death in 1995, wrote a book about Napoleon and
Josephine. Her uncle is JOHN WARNER, the senator from Virginia, who
was once married to ELIZABETH TAYLOR.
</P>
<P>
   Her family connections came in handy: Ms. Currier often called
her grandmother for help with technical details in making the
movie, based on a Balzac story about a Napoleonic officer. ``I
said: `How did they salute? And would this guy have had any
education?'''
</P>
<P>
   But her grandmother did not prepare her for the reaction of her
Jordanian crew to a woman. ``They called me Lavinia,'' she said.
``They couldn't figure out what kind of creature would be wearing
trousers and bossing men around, I guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
