<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET DRAWS NO. 8 POST POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thirteen horses were entered Thursday in the 130th
running of the Belmont Stakes Saturday, with Real Quiet drawing the
No. 8 post position and favored at 6-5 to become the 12th winner of
the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   A fair, cool day with a dry, fast track was predicted for
Belmont Park when Real Quiet tries to accomplish something that his
stablemate Silver Charm failed to do last year: sweep the punishing
series of Triple Crown races that are contested over five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet won the Kentucky Derby at a mile and one-quarter on
May 2, beating Victory Gallop by a half-length, and the Preakness
at a mile and three-sixteenths on May 16, this time beating Victory
Gallop by two and a quarter lengths. Now he will try to outrun his
contemporaries in the Belmont at a mile and a half, a distance that
none of the horses has raced.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet's chief threats figure to be one old rival and one
new one. The old rival, Victory Gallop, ran second in both the
Kentucky Derby and the Preakness and was duly installed as second
choice in the field at 7-2. The new rival, Grand Slam, who won the
Peter Pan Stakes only 12 days ago, was made the third choice at
6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, the only trainer to win the Derby and Preakness in
consecutive years, smiled through all the tumult surrounding his
colt's rise to the top of the 3-year-old class, and said:
</P>
<P>
   ``People came here last year to see history, and it was a
letdown. If it's not meant to be this year, we'll come back next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this game a long time, through the ups and downs,
and you go through months where things aren't great, and I think
maybe I should've been a doctor or a lawyer. But when you're
rolling, you just enjoy it. This horse is much fresher at this
point than Silver Charm was last year. He's ready to run a big
race.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kent Desormeaux, the jockey on Real Quiet, who attended
Thursday's draw ceremony, echoed the party line, saying, ``If I can
get him comfortable, he'll run them into the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The field of challengers grew by one when Chilito, who ran 11th
in the Kentucky Derby, was named before the entry deadline Thursday
morning. The draw was conducted under traditional rules, with
starting positions chosen by lot, and unlike this year's Kentucky
Derby and Preakness, in which the trainers picked from the
available positions in the gate. Chilito drew the No. 4 post and
was expected to supply some early speed. But racing people tended
to mark him as ``cheap speed,'' and the Belmont Park oddsmaker
judged his chances at 30-1.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Also, as expected, D. Wayne Lukas decided to enter Grand Slam,
who won the Belmont Futurity and the Champagne Stakes last fall
before suffering a deep cut on his left hind leg in the Breeders'
Cup Juvenile in November. He has come back slowly this year, but
when he won the Peter Pan Stakes two weeks ago, the victory gave
him a winning streak of four races at Belmont Park. He is expected
to run close to the pacesetters in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Slam, with Jerry Bailey riding, will have to work to
challenge for the early lead. He drew the No. 13 slot on the
outside of the gate. Lukas has another horse in the race, Yarrow
Brae, winner of the Illinois Derby, who drew No. 12, was listed at
20-1. They will not run as an entry because they have different
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Grand Slam is 4-for-4 on this race track is
something you'd better put in your handicapping,'' Lukas said.
</P>
<P>
   David Cross, the trainer of Classic Cat, who ran third in the
Preakness, saw speed in the Belmont now as well as stamina, saying:
``Chilito and Grand Slam both put an emphasis on speed, and that
may help closers like mine. But you'd better be running at the
three-eighths pole, or you won't get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop won the Rebel and the Arkansas Derby before
finishing second to Real Quiet in both the Kentucky Derby and the
Preakness. The colt, who drew the No. 11 slot, spent a week or so
contending with a skin condition on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get caught up trying to change history,'' said his
trainer, Elliott Walden. ``He came out of the Preakness a little
banged up. He was tired, and he didn't eat very well for a couple
of nights. Then he developed the skin rash that was partly due to
stress. He's righted himself in the last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say we're better until we prove it. But I believe it's
a lot closer than a 2-0 match right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
