<SLUG> BC-NICHOLS-SENTENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICHOLS SENTENCED TO LIFE IN PRISON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ As his victims sobbed with relief and his son simply
sobbed, Terry L. Nichols was sentenced to life in prison Thursday
for his role in the Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, 43, showed no emotion when he heard the sentence,
adopting the same blank stare he wore throughout the trial. Only an
hour earlier, a man whose brother was killed in the blast reminded
US District Court Judge Richard P. Matsch that Nichols had not shed
a single tear in court, and urged the judge to give Nichols the
stiffest penalty allowed under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let him sit in prison for the rest of his life thinking about
what he did,'' said Rudy Guzman, who quit his job to attend the
trial nearly every day.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pleas of a dozen victims, sometimes choked out
through tears, other times offered in the sad detachment of
survival, Matsch said the sentence was not meant to slake any
thirst for vengeance. Instead, he said that the severity of the
terrorist attack, the deadliest ever committed on US soil,
warranted the forfeiture of Nichols's freedom forever. The federal
sentence carries no possibility of release.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, along with his friend and former Army buddy Timothy J.
McVeigh, intended to ``change the course of government ... through
fear and intimidation,'' Matsch said. ``But you know it didn't work
out that way. Quite to the contrary. ... A community became even
more united and perhaps a country as well.''
</P>
<P>
   McVeigh, 29, was convicted of all 11 federal counts and
sentenced to death by lethal injection last June. But uncertain of
Nichols's exact role in the bombing, a second jury acquitted
Nichols of the more serious charge of first-degree murder and found
him guilty of conspiring to manufacture the bomb, though not of the
bombing itself.
</P>
<P>
   That verdict was a clear rejection of the prosecution's
contention that Nichols and McVeigh were full partners despite
Nichols's absence from Oklahoma City on the day of the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that have been laid at Mr. Nichols's door don't
entirely belong to him,'' said lead defense attorney Michael E.
Tigar, who plans to file a motion for a new trial based on recent
news reports that some jurors felt pressured during deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Matsch had indicated he might take Nichols's
cooperation into account if he helped prosecutors answer
outstanding questions about the bombing. But Nichols still faces a
murder trial in Oklahoma City, and in a soft voice he declined to
address the court Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the defense team had already presented everything it knew
about the bombing, which killed 168 men, women and children and
injured hundreds more, Tigar went on to blame prosecutors and
federal agencies for a shoddy investigation that led to a largely
circumstantial case against his client. He added that Michael
Fortier, a friend of Nichols and McVeigh who also knew about the
deadly plot, was sentenced recently to just 12 years on unrelated
charges after his starring role as a witness at both men's trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that has been said here of Terry Nichols could be
said of'' Fortier, Tigar said, in arguing for a lighter sentence.
``His 12-year sentence ... stands as some kind of benchmark.''
</P>
<P>
   But Matsch rejected defense pleas for leniency and imposed the
maximum sentence at prosecutors' urging. Beyond the economic ruin,
estimated at hundreds of millions of dollars, beyond the emotional
and physical scars, the ``seriousness of the crime alone dictates a
sentence of life,'' said Larry A. Mackey , who led the prosecution
team.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols also received a concurrent sentence of 48 years, six
years for each of the eight federal law enforcement agents he
helped kill. During Nichols trial, prosecutors argued that he
helped bomb the building in retaliation for the siege at the Branch
Davidian complex near Waco, Texas, which claimed 75 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Stressing that he was not making a political statement, Martin
Cash, one of Nichols's victims, said regardless of motive, there
was no justification for the slaughter. Cash, his left eye
literally torn from its socket, his teeth lost to jaw trauma, asked
Matsch to impose a sentence ``59 seconds longer than the sentence''
Nichols ``imposed'' on the people of Oklahoma City: eternity.
</P>
<P>
   Cash was among a dozen victims and their relatives who poured
out their stories of broken bodies and busted hearts Thursday, each
one intent on ensuring that Nichols received life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Moser, a dental assistant whose husband lost much of
his hearing, recalled running toward the building and helping carry
out babies. They were not crying, they were not breathing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I still hear them crying in my nightmares,'' Moser said.
``It has been thre years since the bombing, but in my nightmare it
is now. ....Our grief is ever present. It is our life sentence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
