<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTITOBACCO MEASURE STALLED IN SENATE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A fragile coalition struggling to steer a massive
antitobacco bill through the Senate suffered a serious setback
Thursday as a storm of partisan rancor and election-year
brinksmanship stalled the measure's momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a showdown over using proceeds from the $516 billion
tobacco proposal to reduce taxes for married couples, the bill's
chief Democratic supporters accused Republican leaders of playing
parliamentary games to try to kill the antitobacco measure and
filed a motion to end debate on the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   As Republican leaders unleashed a counterattack, the antitobacco
bill's prime sponsor, Senator John McCain of Arizona, expressed
dismay and appeared close to conceding defeat. A vote on the motion
to end the debate is scheduled on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe in the wisdom of the Senate this is not a good piece of
legislation and we should drop it,'' said McCain, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate ended briefly last night, as the Senate voted
66-29 not to kill an amendment that would increase the maximum
annual penalties tobacco companies would pay for failing to meet
targets to reduce youth smoking. The amendment by Senator Richard
Durbin, an Illinois Democrat, would increase the maximum penalty
from about $4 billion to $7 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry, McCain's top Democratic ally in the
antitobacco coalition, reflected the growing acrimony in the debate
as he abandoned the spirit of compromise he has tried to foster
since the Senate began considering the measure two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry accused GOP leaders of hypocrisy for asserting they want
to curb youth smoking but permitting a small number of Republican
conservatives to tie up the bill for several days in what critics
described as a ``defacto filibuster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know a lot of them support the dealth penalty,'' Kerry said
of the bill's foes. ``In effect, this is a back-door death penalty
for children who will be sucked into smoking and ultimately will
die because of the disease they get as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate majority leader Trent Lott, whose parliamentary moves
were the prime target of Democratic scorn, issued a dismal
assessment of the antitobacco bill's prospects. ``The well has been
poisoned tremendously by what has been going on here,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy joined the verbal assault on the
Republican leaders, but he predicted the Senate will soon bow to
public pressure and pass the antitobacco bill.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying Thursday's skirmish was a move by Senator Phil Gramm,
a Texas Republican, to use about $52 billion in revenues from a
proposed $1.10-a-pack increase in cigarette prices to eliminate the
``penalty'' that many married couples pay in federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Congressional Budget Office, about 42 percent
of married couples filing jointly in 1996 paid an average of $1,400
more in taxes than they would have if they were not married.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders, wary of voting against the idea in an
election year, wrote an alternative to Gramm's bill that would use
about $28 billion of the proposed cigarette tax increase to reduce
the marriage tax penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan bickering intensified when Lott refused to schedule
consecutive votes on the competing measures. Democrats feared they
would face public disfavor for voting against Gramm's bill without
being able to vote on their alternative on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute nearly overshadowed anger among many public health
groups that cigarette money would not be used for antitobacco
programs. A public health coalition, Effective National Action on
Tobacco Control, issued a statement saying, ``If Congress wants to
reduce the marriage tax, it should do so in separate legislation,
not by gutting this effort to combat the use of tobacco by
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet former surgeon general C. Everett Koop said he would
reluctantly support the initiative. ``If it takes a tax cut to move
this bill forward, even though I don't like it, so be it,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
