<HEADER>
A4953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GUNS-NYT &LR;      06-04 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A TEST FOR CHARLTON HESTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, June 5:
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association opens its annual convention
Friday in Philadelphia in a nation where parents worry about
bullets in the schoolyard and about the easy access that disturbed
children have to loaded guns. But it is impossible to discern a
glimmer of civic or parental concern in the NRA's official program
for the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks after the latest deadly school rampage, in
Springfield, Ore., the NRA has an agenda planned that leaves plenty
of time for members to view the latest in weaponry and to hear
speakers spout familiar rhetoric about the right to bear arms.
Notably missing, however, is time set aside for a discussion of the
issue of gun violence and children, or to reconsider the
organization's reflexive opposition to common-sense measures that
would limit the access of criminals and children to bullets and
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   You would think that parents in the NRA would be concerned that
their dues finance a Washington lobby for greater danger in public
spaces. Confronted with the rash of deadly school massacres, and
statistics indicating an alarming number of youngsters toting guns
to school, the organization responds with its old rant that any
criminal misuse of weapons is inimical to its devotion to shooting
sports.
</P>
<P>
   What that conveniently ignores, of course, is the group's
influential role over the years at the state and national level in
blocking reasonable legislation that would restrict guns to hunters
and target-shooters and control the circumstances under which they
can be carried and used.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates in Congress want to strengthen the laws
limiting access to handguns for children, and put criminal
penalties on adults who do not lock away their firearms. The NRA's
Washington leadership refuses to recognize that such steps pose no
real threat to hunters and target-shooters. Instead the leaders
feed a kind of gun-owner paranoia that prevents the nation from
controlling a major public health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   James Brady, the former White House press secretary who was shot
and permanently injured in the assassination attempt on President
Ronald Reagan, and his organization, Handgun Control Inc., wrote to
Charlton Heston this week asking for his support for laws to
protect children. Heston has yet to respond. But the actor, who is
considered a shoo-in to be elected the next NRA president, has
disappointed those who hoped when he became an NRA vice president a
year ago that he would be a force for common sense in an
organization that uses propaganda to prevent its members from
thinking about the safety interests of their families.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Heston, whose long career has made him an icon of
respectability, needs to decide if he wants to end his career as
front man for a lobby whose civic irresponsibility is comparable
only to that of the cigarette companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980604.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WEISEL-600&AMP;ADD-NYT     06-04 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WEISEL-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIESEL GIVES STUDENTS A PERSONAL VIEW OF THE HOLOCAUST'S HORRORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SUSAN SACHS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Elie Wiesel has berated presidents, debated
philosophers, chided popes and harangued dictators. The
world-traveled Holocaust writer and Nobel laureate rarely falters.
But then, rarely has his audience been as direct as the
eighth-graders of Public School 111 in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't you ever regret being Jewish?'' Lorraine Lopez, 13,
asked Wiesel at the conclusion of his 45-minute talk in the
school's library Thursday that touched on the terrors of Auschwitz,
the fragility of memory and the evil of indifference in the face of
bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Wiesel flinched, and his eyebrows, winged in a permanent
expression of amazement, rose ever so slightly. ``Never,'' he
finally responded. Then he paid them a compliment that made several
of the assembled students, most of them black or Hispanic, exchange
shy smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned from you today more than you realize,'' Wiesel said
solemnly. He seemed a bit surprised himself. ``I feel good talking
to you,'' he told the teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   For the 65 students who perched on battered chairs or sprawled
on bright blue beanbags, Wiesel's appearance at their school at
56th Street and 10th Avenue capped a semester of special Holocaust
studies.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their social studies and language arts classes, they
read stories for the first time about the genocide of the Jews of
Europe. They saw films of concentration camps that shocked them.
</P>
<P>
   They wrestled with hatred in their midst when someone scrawled a
swastika on the wall of a boys' bathroom in April, shortly after
the visit of another Holocaust survivor who told of how she found
her family alive after the war.
</P>
<P>
   But they knew, from reading Wiesel's memoir, ``Night,'' that his
personal journey through hell did not have a happy ending and that
he was left orphaned and alone.
</P>
<P>
   So when their guest, significantly smaller and more frail than
many of the strapping teen-agers, began to speak in his soft,
accented voice, the room grew silent. One girl tiptoed to the
window and turned off the air-conditioner. The students stared
raptly.
</P>
<P>
   As he began, Wiesel confessed to some trepidation about even
coming to the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rarely speak to children your age,'' he told them. ``I speak
to university students, who are already mature. And I'm not sure I
like this, because the story you want to hear is a story filled
with pain, and something in me resists. Why should I give you pain?
You are entitled to joy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of education, he said, he came. But be warned,
he told them: ``When you enter the mind and the memory of a person
such as myself, there you will see nothing but darkness, with a few
sparks here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not spare them.
</P>
<P>
   Wiesel was 15 when he was taken to Auschwitz from his home in
Romania. In the camp, he saw his father die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever lose hope?'' asked Michael Thompson, 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question you ask me, I never ask it myself,'' Wiesel
responded. Now 69, with a busy schedule of lectures and political
activism, he is more accustomed to speaking about the Bible,
mysticism and literary philosophy than to making intimate
admissions in public. ``This is too personal,'' he said, ``but I
owe you that _ to answer your question.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened, Sita Kaba, a lanky 13-year-old, unfolded himself
from his chair, glanced around and asked, ``How did you feel when
your family died in the Holocaust?''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Wiesel said nothing. He cleared his throat. He
looked at his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was numb,'' he said. ``Remember, I was living in a place
where death was the norm and life was abnormal. The real pain came
later, when I was free.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This is the second year that the school has included the special
course on the Holocaust, which is based on materials developed by
the Simon Wiesenthal Center to promote tolerance. At P.S. 111, it
is one of several academic and cultural programs financed by The
New York Times Company Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers said they saw Holocaust studies as a particularly
useful tool, especially at a time of strained relations between
Jews and blacks in New York. Students learned not only history, but
also how easily bigotry can grow in the vacuum of apathy, said
Ellen Gallin Procida, the course's teacher.
</P>
<P>
   That lesson became all too real when some of the boys in the
class found the swastika in a bathroom. Enraged, upset and
energized by a youthful zeal for righting wrongs, they volunteered
to speak to other classes about the pain caused by intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took it very personally as a slap against humanity,'' Ms.
Procida said. ``They became sensitive to these issues through this
study.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Procida said black parents have been supportive, even though
many may consider the experience of slavery a holocaust of their
own and one little appreciated by whites.
</P>
<P>
   A student in Ms. Procida's class, Bobby Potts, 13, who is black,
said he really did not distinguish between the two tragedies.
``Each one is as bad as the other,'' he said. ``Maybe you can say
that more people were killed in the Holocaust, but they're pretty
much equal because lives were lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, another black student drew a slightly different
lesson. Ms. Procida said he told her that ``the Holocaust was worse
than slavery because it means we didn't learn anything from
slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiesel made a similar point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always dissatisfied,'' he told the students, when asked
whether he had achieved all that he had hoped to. ``I have the
strange feeling that I have not really begun and that I'm not doing
enough, because if my peers and I had really told the story as it
should have been told, many things would be different in the world
today.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
