<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     06-04 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SELES IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also TEN-FRENCHOPEN)  
 (JT)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The two of them first met nearly a decade before.
Nine-year-old Martina Hingis was escorted by her mother to a tennis
match in Zurich, Switzerland, where 16-year-old Monica Seles was
playing. Hingis was enough of a prodigy herself to have her
photograph taken with the older prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   Seles moved on quickly, winning the French Open the next year,
1990. Back home in Switzerland, Hingis watched on television as
Seles grunted and squinted, banged balls with two hands, forehand
and backhand.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was almost unbeatable,'' Hingis recalled Thursday. ``I saw
her win the French Open. She was becoming No. 1 in the world. I was
just a little kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Named for Martina Navratilova, the political symbol, not the
tennis player, Hingis does not have role models. It is hard to
think of her as ever being at an impressionable age, but maybe in
her own secure way she was a trifle awed by the two-handed marvel
she saw on the tube so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   That grunting, squinting apparition reappeared Thursday for
Martina Hingis on the clay courts of Roland Garros. Bellowing her
two-tone personal mantra like a samurai backhander _
``Aiiii-yeeee!'' _ Monica Seles materialized on the other side of
the net from Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis had beaten Seles all five times they had met, but
Thursday it was like Gordie Howe coming back to slap Wayne Gretzky
silly, like Bill Russell climbing back onto the court to stuff the
Chicago Bulls. This was the prototypical blast from the past, balls
rocketing into corners as if shot by smart bazookas, the way Seles
used to hit them. Hingis was the one person in the world who had to
cope with a mightily revitalized Monica Seles Thursday, and she
soon became undone.
</P>
<P>
   The score was 6-3, 6-2, and that included a concession by Seles
of a let call while Hingis was serving. Hingis promptly won the
sixth game of the second set, but the sporting gesture did not hurt
Seles _ and even if it had, Seles said, ``What's true is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of truth, it is a fact that Monica Seles lost part of
her youth to a cretin who stabbed her while she was on the court,
and who later got off with modest time served. Barely three weeks
ago, Monica Seles lost her father to cancer, after nursing him, and
making the medical and family decisions for her mother and father.
Seles has had two brutal interruptions in her career, but she said
she never stopped to think that this perpetually smiling young
woman had usurped a chunk of her potential career.
</P>
<P>
   Back when Hingis was watching on Swiss television, Seles had
become the youngest woman (or man, for that matter) to be ranked
first in world tennis, 17 years 3 months 9 days. Hingis now holds
that record, 16 years 6 months 1 day. Thursday, Hingis seemed like
a frustrated juvenile on the same court with this determined older
woman wearing a black outfit that was either a symbol of respect
for her father or a fashion concession to her mature figure, now
being pounded into shape by Grand Slam-level tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Venus Williams had graciously expressed respect for
Hingis after Tuesday's drubbing, Hingis had nothing but admiration
for Seles Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably getting a little bit tired,'' Hingis said.
``Then she just let me run, and she didn't make any mistakes. I
didn't get the chance to get back into the match. She was the
better player.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Hingis surprised that Seles could pull back a match like
this, seemingly a rerun of those matches Hingis had seen back in
1990? ``Well, I guess she surprised everybody. I mean she's been
around for a while and then all of a sudden she was gone for almost
four years, and here she is, back, in better shape, probably better
than ever, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Always a fair competitor, Seles did remember how to defuse an
opponent's protest. On Tuesday, Hingis had requested the chair
umpire to inspect four calls in the clay particles, and Hingis had
won three of those inspections. (``That's her conduct,'' Williams
had sniffed.) At least twice Thursday, Seles drew circles in the
clay, well in bounds, demonstrating where the ball had landed,
thereby kindly saving the umpire the trip down from the chair on a
warm afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis had no complaints, only respect. She said Seles was ``a
level better than the other ones I've played'' in this tournament.
It was more than that, much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Monica Seles was very nearly on the level of that
teen-age dominator who posed for a picture with a prodigy, nearly a
decade ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
