<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/04/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- June 4, 1998 -- HARVARD-CHAPLAIN,
6-04 -- The Rev. Peter Gomes, an author and the Plummer Professor
of Christian Morals, is applauded by Harvard seniors Thursday
before delivering a commencement sermon at the Senior Class Chapel.
``You are going to be sent out of here for good, and most of you
aren't ready to go,'' he tells the soon-to-be graduates. (Ed
Quinn/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BALTIMORE, Md. -- June 4, 1998 -- MD-TROOPER-SUIT, 6-04
-- At the plaintiffs' news conference Thursday in Baltimore, James
Alston Jr. mimicks the stance that he says a Maryland state trooper
took in ordering him out of his car after stopping him on
Interstate 95. A civil rights group and 11 black motorists filed a
class-action lawsuit in federal court here charging that the
Maryland state police used race as a factor in stopping and
searching drivers along the interstate. (Marty Katz/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LOS ANGELES -- June 4, 1998 -- BILINGUAL-VOICES-2, 6-04
-- Elva Osorio and her mother, Rosario Gomez, in front of their
East Los Angeles home. ``When I was in school bilingual education
was much better than it is now,'' says Mrs. Osorio, expressing deep
concern about the state of bilingual education. ``I voted no, but I
knew it was going to lose, because a lot of people are upset that
their kids don't know how to speak English and they're in the fifth
grade.'' (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOS ANGELES -- June 4, 1998 -- BILINGUAL-VOICES-1, 6-04
-- Jerry Ontiveros and his son, Jerome, 11, in East Los Angeles.
``I've been assimilated into the mainstream culture all of my
life,'' Ontiveros says. ``Others haven't had the opportunities I've
had and that's why I support bilingual education.'' (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SONOMA, Calif. -- June 4, 1998 -- WINE-WARRIOR-2, 6-01
-- A wild mushroom risotto served with Durell Vineyard's 1995 Pinot
Noir. The meal topped off an afternoon of wine tasting for Golden
State Warriors' general manager Garry St. Jean, right, and his wife
M.J. (John Burgess/Press Democrat Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SONOMA, Calif. -- June 4, 1998 -- WINE-WARRIOR-1, 6-01
-- Golden State Warriors' general manager Garry St. Jean listens to
the description of the Arrowood Voigner varietal wine during a
tasting of Sonoma County wines. ``Malolactic fermentation,'' St.
Jean says, impressed. ``Holy Moly!'' (John Burgess/Press Democrat
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- June 4, 1998 -- THEATER-NOTES, 6-04 -- Sam
Harris will play Al Jolson in a new musical titled ``The Jazz
Singer.'' Jolson hits like ``Toot Toot Tootsie'' and ``Swanee''
will be intermingled with original music and lyrics by Will Holt
and an original book by Sherman Yellen. Gabriel Barre will direct.
``It's going to be the toughest thing I've ever done,'' says
Harris. ``I'm hardly gone from the stage. At the moment, I sing 14
songs.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) POTTSVILLE, Pa. -- June 4, 1998 --
PA-SCHUYLKILL-OHARA-2, 6-04 -- Author John O'Hara lived for 12
years at 606 Mahantongo Street in Pottsville. The terrain is
Schuylkill County, the shovel-shaped anthracite coal region of
eastern Pennsylvania, which is barely disguised in the plentiful
short stories and novels of O'Hara. (Sal DiMarco Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BARNESVILLE, Pa. -- June 4, 1998 --
PA-SCHUYLKILL-OHARA-1, 6-04 -- Patrons dance to Joe Stanky and the
Cadets at the Lakeside Ballroom in Barnesville, a country club for
author John O'Hara's characters. The terrain is Schuylkill County,
the shovel-shaped anthracite coal region of eastern Pennsylvania,
which is barely disguised in the plentiful short stories and novels
of O'Hara. (Sal DiMarco Jr./New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 4, 1998 -- BROADWAY-TONYS-2, 6-04 --
Natasha Richardson, nominated for a Tony as best actress in a
musical, in ``Cabaret,'' a nominee for best musical revival. The
1997-1998 Broadway season comes to an official close on Sunday
night when the 52nd annual Tony Awards honoring artistic and
technical achievement on the Broadway stage are handed out during a
live television broadcast at Radio City Music Hall, Rosie O'Donnell
presiding. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 4, 1998 -- BROADWAY-TONYS-1, 6-04 --
``Ragtime,'' a Tony nominee for best musical. The 1997-1998
Broadway season comes to an official close Sunday night when the
52nd annual Tony Awards honoring artistic and technical achievement
on the Broadway stage are handed out during a live television
broadcast at Radio City Music Hall, Rosie O'Donnell presiding.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
SCHORER-DANCE, 6-4 -- Suki Schorer works with her students in
Studio 3 at the School of American Ballet at Lincoln Center. Ms.
Schorer is famous for staging Balanchine ballets for the workshop
every year. ``I've been doing it for 24 years,'' she says. ``Twelve
different ballets.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
BROADWAY-SEASON-PLAYS-2, 6-4 -- Alfred Molina, left, Alan Alda and
Victor Garber as quarreling friends in ``Art,'' which its author,
Yasmina Reza, describes as being as much a tragedy as a comedy. It
is just one of the plays which figures prominently in Sunday
night's broadcast of the 52nd annual Antoinette Perry Awards at
Radio City Music Hall.(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
BROADWAY-SEASON-PLAYS-1, 6-4 -- Matthew Ross, left, Clark Gregg and
Jordan Lage in Jez Butterworth's play ``Mojo'' at the Atlantic
Theater Company. It is just one of the plays which figures
prominently in Sunday night's broadcast of the 52nd annual
Antoinette Perry Awards at Radio City Music Hall. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 4, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 7 --
BALZAC-FILMS, 6-4 -- ``Balzac is a great source of stories for the
cinema,'' says Tony-winning theater director Des McAnuff from his
home. McAnuff's debut as a movie director will be in a new
adaptation of ``Cousin Bette,'' the sprawling 1847 drama of manners
that is one of Balzac's best-known novels. (Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LANDSORT, Sweden -- June 4, 1998 -- SWEDISH-SUMMER-HNS,
6-4 -- This dog watches over his master's house and boat in the
village of Landsort. Located in the outer reaches of the Stockholm
Archipelago, Landsort is home to one of Sweden's oldest
lighthouses. The reward for climbing the more than 100 steep steps
to the top is a magnificent view of scores of tiny islands and the
village, which, with a population of 31, has more buildings than
people. (Syd Kearney/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HOUSTON -- June 4, 1998 -- NURSING-SHORTAGE-HNS, 6-4 --
Registered nurse Tanie Whitby, 27, listens to a patient's heartbeat
at the Spring Branch Medical Center. Ms. Whitby, who moved to
Houston from Ottawa two years ago, is one of many nurses recruited
from Canada to relieve the city's shortage of nurses. Analysts and
other observers say the shortage reflects several factors the
declining enrollment in nursing school and a broader array of
career choices in the health care field. (Kirk Wagner/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PHOENIX -- June 4, 1998 -- MYSTERY-CASTLE-HNS, 6-4 --
Visitors to The Mystery Castle enjoy the grounds of the
8,000-square-foot native stone castle hand-built by Boyce Gulley
between 1929 and 1945. Mary Lou Gulley, the daughter of the
builder, lives here year-round, sharing her castle with public by
conducting tours nine months a year, four days a week. (Harry
Shatluck/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HOUSTON -- June 4, 1998 -- IMPOTENCE-DRUG-HNS, 6-4 --
Joseph Podolski, president and chief executive officer of Zonagen,
examines a triangular Vasomax pill. Podolski hopes that Vasomax, a
male impotency drug, will compete with Viagra, the hottest-selling
drug of all time. A company official estimates, if Zonagen is
successful with this drug, it could bring the company $200 million
to $300 million a year in additional revenues. (D. Fahleson/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) KRASNOYARSK, Russia -- June 4, 1998 -- SIBERIA-COLA-COX,
6-4 -- A local beverage company in the heart of Siberia has taken
on Coca-Cola with humorous ads like this one. ``Everyone knows it
is a joke to go against Coca-Cola,'' says Yevgenia Kuznetsova,
president of Pikra, a Siberian beer and soft-drinks manufacturer.
``So we called ours 'Crazy Cola' in order to laugh at ourselves.''
Even crazier, Crazy Cola is showing a profit a year after it was
introduced. (Cox Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
