<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JAZZ-BULLS-500&AMP;AD     06-04 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-BULLS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN NEEDS RELIEF IF BULLS ARE TO DEFEND TITLE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Michael Jordan came rising out of the paint
like a sputtering prop plane. There was a cough and a hiss and a
gurgle as Jordan flew in for a dunk that ended as he cracked the
ball against the rim like a new roll of pennies.
</P>
<P>
   There was not enough air in Jordan, not enough swoosh in his
swoop. He was spent as regulation spilled into overtime of Game 1
in the National Basketball Association finals Wednesday. You could
see it when his mind lapsed for a 24-second violation, and when his
concentration slipped on a clutch free throw.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, you could see it in the final score. The Jazz won,
88-85, in a game that would normally be tucked away by some great
Jordanesque moment. Instead, the Bulls trudged away from perhaps
their best chance at stealing the home-court advantage from the
Jazz by leaving a trail of evidence that points toward a decline.
</P>
<P>
   It's like noticing your parents are old for the first time.
There was something disconcerting in seeing how Jordan has finally
begun to show signs of mortality at 35. He is not immune to fatigue
anymore. It was true in his grueling seven-game conference final
against Indiana. And it was true on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bulls are to survive in this series, which continues with
Game 2 on Friday at the Delta Center, Jordan needs some relief,
whether he wants it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get Michael out of the game in the third quarter,
but he bargained his way back on the floor,'' Coach Phil Jackson
said Thursday before his team practiced. ``Against my better
judgment, I did not dissuade him. When I saw Jeff Hornacek reverse
him, I got him right out of the game. It's pretty obvious we're
going to have to provide a little more support. At least we carried
the action and the momentum, but defensively we couldn't make the
stops down the stretch because we were fatigued. Guys had their
hands on their knees.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, John Stockton was April fresh. The Jazz's
36-year-old, bowl-cut point guard was the one with the spring in
his high tops as he cut through the Bulls in overtime. But Stockton
was not acting on immortal energy, he was fresh because the Jazz
had the depth on their bench to rest him for 18 minutes in
regulation. All Coach Jerry Sloan had to do was insert Howard
Eisley, the kind of quick point guard that disrupts the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan did not have that luxury. The Bulls' bench scored just
eight points in Game 1, while Scottie Pippen and Jordan combined
for 54 of the Bulls' 85 points. After a while, it seemed the
burden, and the Jazz's double teams, left Jordan too ragged to come
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let him fool you,'' said Bryon Russell, who is often
assigned to guard Jordan. ``Maybe it's due to fatigue that he
missed some shots down the stretch. You can't look at the fact that
he's missed such and such a shot in the last three playoff games,
or whatever. He'll be there because this is when it counts.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This is not just about a missed dunk in Game 1 of the finals,
but about Jordan shooting a weary 37 percent in the fourth quarters
of his last six playoff games. This is about the fatigue-induced
spill he took as he drove on Derrick McKey for a winning shot in
Game 6 against the Pacers, and about the three fourth-quarter
turnovers he had in Game 4 in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has been easy for Jordan and the Bulls lately. This was
only magnified in Game 1 against the Jazz. There were
uncharacteristic turnovers from Pippen _ three in the first half _
and there was strained communication on the court. In one timeout,
Jordan yelled to get Pippen on the same page late in the fourth
quarter. It didn't matter that Pippen's 3-pointer went in to tie
the game, Jordan wanted him to make sure his partner saw the
mismatch he had on the gimpy Hornacek in the post.
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan is accustomed to berating a teammate for their
imperfections, he has displayed a few flaws as well. He is not the
same spry star who can carry his team no matter what; not without a
breather.
</P>
<P>
   That youthful glow is gone. You could see it in his tired eyes
Thursday. But there was also a sense that as frustrated as the
Bulls are to find themselves down by 1-0 in the four of seven games
series _ after a game they lost even though Karl Malone shot
9-of-25 _ they are not ready to walk off into the sunset and call
it a day on their dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an inner strength and confidence,'' Jordan said. ``One
game does not deteriorate that. Sure, it's a pressure situation.
But you don't fight that with frustration and anger. I think you
have to do it with a whole different frame of mind. Smiling, when
you really may be frustrated inside, can help relieve the tension.
I think it's that Zen Buddhism kind of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``One game does not dictate how this series is going to end. If
you want to write us off, go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Having to prove the opposite probably serves as needed fuel for
Jordan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
