<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-BADGES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL DISTRICT WANTS ID BADGES FOR STUDENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN MAESHIRO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- With schoolyard shootings nationwide raising
fears about campus safety, Antelope Valley Union High School
District officials are considering requiring students and staff
members to wear photo identification badges.
</P>
<P>
   The badges, which could have bar codes that would provide
information on students when scanned in school computer systems,
would make it easier to identify people who don't belong on campus,
said officials for the rural Los Angeles County school district.
</P>
<P>
   ``(With) what we see happening around the country, the
unfortunate situations with students being shot, security has
become a big issue,'' board member Brett Nelson said. ``We have to
do whatever we can do to protect students. We need to provide a
safe environment for our students, within reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The district board discussed the concept at a meeting Wednesday
and will revisit it at a future meeting along with the idea of
requiring school uniforms, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Trustee Kevin Carney said the board will probably vote on
whether to require name badges as a pilot program at one or more
schools at the next meeting. The policy, if approved, would take
effect next school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea,'' Carney said. ``Some people might
argue wearing one is an unnecessary burden on kids. You look at the
aerospace or airline industries or any form of employment where
there are security problems, it's almost standard that people wear
ID. We are all required to carry a driver's license.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the name-tag idea came up after he and fellow
trustees learned about it at a school boards conference in New
Orleans. Officials from one school district at the conference said
they paid for the badges through a corporate sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   The tags would make it easier to identify outsiders who don't
belong on campus, Nelson said. One teacher at the meeting said tags
would assist in identifying students involved in fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had fights that occurred that are mostly gang-related,
where people who weren't supposed to be on campus came on to get at
students from a rival gang,'' Nelson said. ``With the amount of
kids we have on campus, (with badges) it would be easy for a
teacher or a security person to identify a student by name.''
</P>
<P>
   At Littlerock High School, in the high-desert community of
Littlerock, east of Los Angeles, most staff members are already
wearing name badges, said Principal Marcia Crooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school gets bigger all the time, and we have turnover. It
helps getting to know each other, and it helps students get to know
new people on campus,'' she said. ``When a community member comes
to visit, they have to wear a visitor's pass. This way there's no
way of confusing existing staff members with anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said there may be some difficulties with name badges,
such as how to enforce wearing them or make sure students are
wearing the correct ones.
</P>
<P>
   Littlerock High students are supposed to carry identification
cards, and Crooks thinks it might be better to first work on
enforcing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me personally, we need to be able to adequately enforce
the student ID card first,'' she said. ``If we can't get them to
carry that, how are we going to get them to wear a name tag?''
</P>
<P>
   As far as enforcement, the district needs to weigh how much
effort it will take to enforce the wearing of ID badges vs. the
benefits from such a policy, Carney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that we need to work out with teachers,'' he
said. ``Teachers will be the ones who are going to enforce it.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
