<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELEVISION-MORETALES_     06-04 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEVISION-MORE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MORE TALES OF THE CITY' 
</HEADLINE>
 TALES _ 825 _ SFCHRON   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If PBS' ``Tales of the City'' caused a stir in
Georgia, Tennessee and Oklahoma, then ``More Tales of the City''
would bring Florida, Alabama, Utah and several counties in Indiana
into the ruckus, guaranteed. Sputtering and fuming, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Armistead Maupin's ``Tales of the City'' sequel, which
cheerfully revels in everything that gives so much of America the
screaming willies about San Francisco, is involuntarily bypassing
PBS and running instead on the Showtime pay-cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   PBS backed out of the sequel four years ago. So ``Armistead
Maupin's More Tales of the City'' will be televisied Sunday and
Monday (June 7 and 8) on Showtime in 21/2-hour chunks each night.
</P>
<P>
   Olympia Dukakis, Laura Linney, William Campbell, Barbara Garrick
and Thomas Gibson are back, perhaps miraculously, from the original
cast. And ``More Tales'' has the same magic mushroom effervescence
of the first miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``more'' applies strongly, though. ``More Tales''
carries a potent TVMA (mature audiences) rating. ``More Tales'' has
more bare buns _ practically all male _ than a corner Burger King,
and a dollop of male frontal nudity. There's an occasional bare
breast, female style. The language is rawer than in the original
``Tales,'' and the characters stoke a toke at practically every
opportunity. We are, after all, reliving the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the comic outrageousness of Maupin's story. Gender
bending? It's more like a pretzel, with the revelation that the
luminous landlord of 28 Barbary Lane, Anna Madrigal (Dukakis), is a
parent. A father.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mary Ann Singleton (Linney) and Michael Tolliver (now
played by Paul Hopkins) are posing as husband and wife on a Mexican
cruise, while each is in search of a stud muffin. Mona Ramsey (the
pouty Nina Siemaszko replaces Chloe Webb in the role) heads for
Nevada in an angel dust haze and soon finds herself answering
phones in a Winnemucca bordello.
</P>
<P>
   The viperous Beauchamp Day (Gibson, who's now the co-star of
``Dharma &AMP; Greg'') is back, scheming to end the pregnancy of his
wife DeDe (Garrick). What'll happen when word gets around that he's
not the father?
</P>
<P>
   And DeDe's socialite mother, Frannie Halcyon (Diana Leblanc) is
courted by a matrons' club that promises to reward her with a
``piece of the pleasure pie.'' Again, the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   It goes on. One of the main story lines involves Mary Ann's
shipboard lover, Burke Andrew (Colin Ferguson), who became an
amnesiac while investigating a bizarre mystery that leads
eventually to Grace Cathedral on Nob Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Swoozie Kurtz is cast in the sequel as Mona's worrywart mother,
Whip Hubley moves into the role of Barbary Lane tenant Brian
Hawkins, and there are cameo performances by Ed Asner, Paul Bartel
and, from ``Frasier,'' Dan Butler. Maupin himself puts in an
appearance in the final hour, in full regalia as an Episcopal
priest.
</P>
<P>
   But the surest scene stealer is a thin, elderly Canadian
actress, Jackie Burroughs, as Mother Mucca, the fidgety,
foul-mouthed bordello proprietor. She's all elbows and angles and
hissed profanities. It's a role that the late Ruth Gordon could
have inhabited happily, though no more entertainingly.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Pierre Gang and adapted from Maupin's book by
Nicholas Wright, ``More Tales'' breezes by with a sort of air of
benign perversity. But Maupin drops the fanciful tone a few times
to speak, through his characters, from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, that's the case when the sweet-natured Michael
Tolliver, hospitalized with the paralytic Guillain-Barre syndrome,
dictates a letter to his homophobic parents in Florida, telling
them he's gay and proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   His emergence from the closet coincides with Anita Bryant's
campaign against an anti-discrimination ordinance in Miami. Maupin
has said that he himself ``was brought roaring out of the closet''
by Bryant. Here, certainly, Maupin and ``More Tales'' are reaching
for the heart, &LR;  and not the funny bone.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly the miniseries percolates in exactly the same style
as ``Tales of the City.'' Together, the two _ Showtime televised
``Tales of the City'' earlier this week, in preparation for the
sequel _ comprise a viewing experience that feels apart from other
television.
</P>
<P>
   They're deliberately outrageous, in visual detail and story
overlay, and yet Maupin never seems to be trying to poke a sharp
stick in anyone's eye. If anything, he's planed and sanded the
edges. Neither ``Tales'' production seeks to offend, really; on the
contrary, their merrier purpose is to broaden the viewer's sense of
inclusiveness. Fast and far.
</P>
<P>
   The Barbary Lane exteriors are in fact interior shots, and of
course it shows. The lighting is iffy throughout ``More Tales of
the City, &LR; '' and not the production's strong suit. But even here,
the sometimes eerie lighting inadvertently contributes to the
mystique of the Russian Hill address created by Maupin. Barbary
Lane is in and of the city, but also a safe enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's what Maupin and the ``More Tales'' creative crew
are telling us about San Francisco, too. The city can certainly be
eerie in its own right. And while it's in and of America, San
Francisco is a safe enclosure where each day the ridiculous bumps
into the miraculous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
