<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S IN A STADIUM NAME? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED PENHALE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It doesn't rhyme or sound very snazzy, but Seattle
Mariners officials said Thursday that calling their new ballpark
Safeco Field feels right.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based Safeco insurance company will pay the Mariners
$1.8 million a year for 20 years, adjusted annually for inflation,
to hang its corporate name on the $417 million baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question it's a good fit,'' Mariners President
Chuck Armstrong said Thursday. ``Safeco has a very positive
image.''
</P>
<P>
   An insurance-industry fixture in the Northwest for 75 years,
Safeco has a growing national presence. Signing with the Mariners
for the stadium naming rights will enhance the company's
recognition coast to coast, Safeco Corp. Chairman Roger Eigsti
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it will be great exposure for us,'' Eigsti said.
</P>
<P>
   With superstars like Ken Griffey Jr., the Mariners are a team
that's popular nationwide _ a team that can draw national TV
audiences who will see and hear the Safeco name, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said the Mariners talked to more than two dozen
companies which either expressed an interest in buying the naming
rights or were approached by the ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco was favored because the Mariners wanted a company that
was home-grown but with a national reputation, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just think this is a great combination of two companies who
believe in community,'' Eigsti said at a news conference Thursday
near the ballpark construction site south of the Kingdome. ``It's a
real natural.''
</P>
<P>
   As word spread that the baseball stadium will be named Safeco
Field, radio disc jockeys were wondering out loud if umpires at
Safeco Field will have to call base runners ``Safeco'' instead of
``safe,'' or whether the team might become one of the insurance
company's liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong mused that there probably is no end to the baseball
metaphors Safeco could employ in its advertising and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Mariners, said Tom Gibbs, chairman of the state
agency overseeing construction of the new, mostly publicly funded
ballpark, there is an association with a solid company that values
communities and families.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco is a fast-growing Fortune 500 company with 1997 revenues
of more than $4.7 billion. The company's assets exceed $30 billion.
It has 11,300 employees and 8,000 independent agencies representing
a diversified mix of insurance and financial products.
</P>
<P>
   ``This quite a day for me and for (Mariners) ownership,'' said
Mariners CEO John Ellis, as a big banner that said Safeco Field was
unfurled by a construction worker high atop a support structure for
the 45,600-seat stadium's retractable roof.
</P>
<P>
   Counting the impact of inflation, Eigsti said the cost of the
naming-rights contract will be ``in excess of $40 million'' over 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's competitive with most of the (stadium)
naming-rights deals around the country,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners would not identify other finalists in the running
for the naming rights, but the ballclub approached its top
advertising sponsors such as The Boeing Co., Microsoft Corp., Eagle
Hardware &AMP; Garden, Starbucks Coffee Co., Airborne Express, Texaco
and Seafirst Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing was approached but passed on the opportunity, company
spokeswoman Sherry Nebel said. Starbucks, widely regarded as a hot
contender, also was approached, but spokesman Chris Gimbl would not
say if the coffee company actively sought the naming rights.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Isaki, Mariners vice president for development, said that
when team officials settled on Safeco's offer, the corporate name
that connotes safety and security ``had a good feel to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners won the right to sell the naming rights in
negotiations over terms of its ballpark lease. The money the
Mariners will make over two decades from selling the naming rights
is roughly equivalent to the Mariners' $45 million obligation
toward stadium construction costs.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the sale of naming rights has been viewed as the
money the team would use to pay its share of stadium construction,
but Isaki noted that the team must put up its full $45 million
contribution by the end of construction.
</P>
<P>
   The money for naming rights will be part of the ballclub's
long-term revenue stream, along with funds from the sale of luxury
suites, tickets, concessions and stadium advertising, Isaki said.
</P>
<P>
   Under state legislation that created the financing package for
the new ballpark, scheduled to open in July 1999, the state Public
Facilities District must consult with the Legislature on the
stadium name before the PFD may approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs, the PFD chairman, said top leaders of the state House and
Senate have no qualms about the naming rights going to Safeco. The
PFD will vote to formalize the deal June 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
