<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SALUTING THE DINGELL-MALONEY SWITCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., N.Y., Mich.)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, June 5:
</P>
<P>
   One of the most frustrating roadblocks to campaign finance
reform has been the inability of congressional supporters to unite
behind a single coherent strategy. Thursday, Democratic legislators
eliminated a roadblock to reform by announcing that they would not
vote for a toothless commission that could have displaced serious
reform.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal establishing a commission to study campaign finance
reform had been offered by Reps. Carolyn Maloney of New York and
John Dingell of Michigan, who said they were looking for a backup
in case more substantial reform bills failed.
</P>
<P>
   Their intentions may have been good. But the sponsors
inadvertently played into a devious strategy of House Speaker Newt
Gingrich. To protect his special-interest money, he decreed that
the House would vote on a dozen competing campaign finance
proposals this month, and that only the one with the most votes
would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   That meant the impotent commission could kill the real reform
package _ the Shays-Meehan bill, which would ban unlimited ``soft
money'' donations to parties and curb fund-raising for candidate
ads placed by independent groups. Shays-Meehan has survived
numerous attempts to inter it, and Republican leaders, under the
lash of public opinion, had promised to bring it up for a vote. But
they have not stopped plotting to kill it by using the commission
to attract a greater number of votes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maloney and Dingell were way too slow and stubborn about
recognizing that they were being used by Gingrich. But they finally
announced Thursday that they and other Democrats would simply vote
``present'' when the commission bill comes up on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Martin Meehan,
D-Mass., said they would support an amendment to their measure that
would provide for a commission to study further changes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dingell and Ms. Maloney started off in the wrong
direction tactically, we wholeheartedly salute them for reaching
the correct decision in time to make a difference. Giving up one's
own legislative handiwork to further a larger cause is a big
sacrifice for any member of Congress. But in doing so, both
legislators showed they could emerge as champions of reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
