<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: TRAUTWIG GIVES LESSON IN HOW TO INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Conducting a decent post-game interview isn't that
difficult, if you watch the game, show the curiosity to prepare
questions that can produce illuminating answers and think
reasonably well on your feet.
</P>
<P>
   As a model of a top-notch interview, consider Al Trautwig's talk
on the MSG Network with Orlando Hernandez on Wednesday night after
El Duque's seven-inning stint in place of the dog-bit David Cone
led the New York Yankees to a 7-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Directing his questions through the catcher-interpreter Jorge
Posada, Trautwig asked about El Duque's emotions. Then, after
Posada discussed Hernandez's stuff from the bullpen onward,
Trautwig asked: ``In the seventh inning, it looked like he reached
back and put something extra on it. Does he remember that?''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's reply was one of a mature pitcher, as he discussed
using his fastball to keep hitters off balance and throwing curves
for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   With the next question _ ``Can he talk about the experience of
being accepted by the team, because it seemed like an easy
process?'' _ Hernandez's stony demeanor cracked slightly. Through
Posada, Hernandez said he realized ``the kind of quality people''
who are on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Trautwig then tossed in a question seemingly designed to elicit
animation from Hernandez: ``How old were you when you first dreamed
of coming and playing with the Yankees?'' His reply _ that his
Yankee dreams began at age 8, his family loved the Yankees and he
played in a Yankee T-shirt _ was accompanied by a broadening smile
and hand gestures. He began to make eye contact with Trautwig.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he wasn't nervous?'' was Trautwig's final question, which
drew out more emotion. Hernandez described how he felt
``responsible for the Hispanic community,'' how he felt an
obligation to fill Cone's shoes, and how thankful he was to the
Yankees, the Cuban people and his agent, Joe Cubas.
</P>
<P>
   He rubbed his moistened eyes several times. Now, as Trautwig
tried to sign off, Hernandez interrupted to dedicate the game to
the two daughters he left behind when he fled Cuba on a makeshift
sailboat. If Trautwig felt an urge to ask Hernandez about his
wrenching decision to leave his daughters in Cuba, or about the
guilt he feels, he left it for another, less celebratory, time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to Rolando Arrojo,'' Trautwig said Thursday in an
interview, referring to the Tampa Bay pitcher who also defected
from Cuba, ``and he put his kids on a boat like the one El Duque
took from Cuba. I asked Joe Cubas how El Duque felt about that, and
he said his life is not complete without his kids. Cubas said he
speaks to his kids every day.''
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, Trautwig said he wished he had an hour Wednesday
night to ask Hernandez everything possible about his harrowing
flight from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a huge fan of when the human element enters the story,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, NBC's Ahmad Rashad isn't so curious. He proved
later Wednesday that he is the anti-Trautwig. With Utah's John
Stockton after the Jazz's 88-85 victory over Chicago in Game 1 of
the NBA finals, Rashad's interview consisted of presenting three
banal generalities _ like ``Visiting teams try to steal one but you
wouldn't let it happen'' _ but no questions.
</P>
<P>
   He never asked Stockton about the seven points he scored in
overtime, the floater he sank with 9.3 seconds left or whether he
was surprised that Steve Kerr was guarding him. You would think
Rashad's producers would feed him pertinent questions to avoid this
continuing embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   MIND READER? One peril of being an analyst whose self-described
role is to try to articulate players' thoughts is that your mind
reading will fail.
</P>
<P>
   Before Scottie Pippen's 3-pointer tied Game 1, NBC's Isiah
Thomas noted that Michael Jordan was screaming for the ball. But
once the ball went in, Thomas presumed that Jordan forgave Pippen,
and mind-read thusly: ``He says, `Scottie, it's your turn.'
Scottie's saying, `I'm with you, Michael.'''
</P>
<P>
   But as Jordan and Pippen gathered at a subsequent timeout,
Jordan openly castigated Pippen, wrecking Thomas' cameo as Kreskin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-oh, time for an interpretive U-turn!'' Thomas must have
thought. (See, it's easy to mind read!)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas now presumed what they were saying: ``He's hollering at
Scottie Pippen, `Get it to me, get it to me.' He said, `Look,
Scottie, I'm feeling it. Get it to me.' But Scottie's saying, `I
feel it, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is what was being said. But it's best to stick to the
facts.
</P>
<P>
   A NOSY CAMERA: For Saturday's Evander Holyfield-Henry Akinwande
pay-per-view bout, Showtime Event Television will use a camera that
will move along a track mounted 25 to 35 feet above the Madison
Square Garden ring. It will be used to follow the fighters in their
ring walks, to peer at them in their corners between rounds, and
for replays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can pan, tilt or zoom to any part of the arena,'' said Jay
Larkin, SET's executive producer, about the German technology.
``We're only limited by the amount of track we have.''
</P>
<P>
   AIRWAVES: Game 1 of the National Basketball Association
championship series produced an 18.0 rating, the highest for an
opener of the finals. ... Terrific report by CNN/SI's Bill Nack on
Wednesday on horse racing's Triple Crown, which could be won by
Real Quiet on Saturday afternoon at the Belmont Stakes. Few write
as elegantly as Nack about horse racing, whose storytelling skills
translate well to television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
