<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CONGRESS-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIA HEAD REFUSES TO TESTIFY BEFORE SENATE ON SOME ASPECTS OF CHINA
INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the Justice Department's request, the director
of central intelligence refused on Thursday to share information
that is ``central'' to a Senate investigation into whether American
security was hurt by allowing China to launch satellites for a
company that contributed heavily to Democrats, the inquiry's
chairman said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., who heads the intelligence
committee, said the refusal by the nation's top intelligence
official, George Tenet, to testify about certain technical
information was ``disturbing.'' Shelby said he would confront
Attorney General Janet Reno on Friday when she and Louis Freeh,
director of the FBI, are scheduled to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Justice Department officials said that Tenet was told not
to talk to senators about certain information because the
disclosure could hamper a federal criminal inquiry into whether
Loral Space and Communications of New Yorkand another satellite
maker, Hughes Electronics, a Los Angeles-based division of the
General Motors Corp., illegally gave China space expertise that
allowed Beijing to more accurately aim its nuclear missiles.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Shelby warned the Clinton administration to honor its
promise to cooperate with his committee's investigation and not
hide behind the Justice Department inquiry. ``I don't know if
they're stonewalling,'' Shelby told reporters. ``This is central to
our investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate officials said the information Tenet refused to discuss
relates to a Pentagon report, and possibly a similar report by
another intelligence arm of the government, that concluded that
American national security was harmed by the information passed on
to China.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby said that the information Tenet refused to discuss ``was
known to intelligence agencies before the criminal inquiry began,''
and therefore should be provided to the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby said Tenet was obligated by law to disclose the
information to the panel. Indeed, Tenet told senators he had bee
prepared to answer all questions until the Justice Department's
warned him against it, and that the director felt he was ``in a
box,'' Shelby said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the panel played down the wrangling. ``There's a
lot of partisan energy behind this,'' Sen. Robert Kerrey of
Nebraska, the ranking Democrat on the committee, said in an
interview. ``The Justice Department has legitimate reasons based on
previous leaks to ask for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's three-hour closed hearing with Tenet marked the
opening round of months of hearings by several House and Senate
committees into whether China learned secret information from
American satellites that Beijing then used to aim its nuclear
missiles more accurately.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are also delving into accusations that the Chinese
government illegally funneled money to the Democrats during
President Clinton's re-election campaign.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senators and their aides said Tenet discussed both of these
broad topics, but they declined to give details.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shelby's committee is leading the investigation in the Senate.
The House plans to create a select committee to handle its separate
inquiry.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Loral's chairman and chief executive, Bernard Schwartz, was the
largest personal contributor to the Democratic National Committee
last year. Schwartz has denied he sought any favors in exchange for
his contributions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While there are many strands to the various congressional
inquiries, federal and congressional investigators are focusing on
the events following the explosion on Feb. 15, 1996, of a Chinese
rocket carrying a $200 million Loral satellites seconds after
liftoff.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the explosion, China asked the two American companies to
conduct an independent review of the accident. The team was led by
Loral, but included experts from Hughes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say the American experts overstepped
the boundaries of what they could tell the Chinese during the
review. The State Department asked the Pentagon's Defense
Technology Security Administration to investigate.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In mid-May 1997, the Pentagon agency report, based on
intelligence and rocket experts, found that American security had
been harmed. Two weeks later, the United States Customs Service
began an investigation that became the basis for the government's
criminal inquiry.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Thursday, on the ninth anniversary of the massacre in
Tiananmen Square, Capitol Hill was awash in hearings, floor
speeches and rallies that condemned the Chinese government's human
rights record and Clinton's visit to China later this month.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The House approved a resolution, 305-116, urging Clinton to
avoid visiting Tiananmen Square during his upcoming visit. A group
of lawmakers met with Chinese dissidents, including Wei Jengsheng.
Protesters held a candlelight vigil outside the Chinese embassy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the president really need to stand in blood-stained
Tiananmen Square?'' Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., who heads the
House International Committee, said on the House floor.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two House committees, International Relations and Government
Reform and Oversight, heard testimony on accusations about the sale
of human organs from executed prisoners in China to foreigners.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
