r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-USC-LADN     06-04 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHERTON SETTLES DOWN AND TROJANS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
OMAHA, Neb. _ On Thursday, Seth Etherton, USC's All-American
right-hander, encountered only a brief relapse of the whiplash
malady that beset him the first time he faced homer-happy Louisiana
State in the College World Series.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This time, LSU hit just two home runs, tantamount to a slump
after bashing a record eight off the Trojans in the first round,
six of them off of Etherton.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Trojans were able to hold off LSU for a 5-4 victory at
Rosenblatt Stadium and earn a third shot at the two-time defending
champion Tigers this afternoon. The winner today qualifies for
Saturday's championship game against unbeaten Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Bertman, the veteran LSU skipper coaching his 1,000th game,
had an inkling early on that Thursday's game would be different
from the 12-10, 10-homer slugfest with the Trojans in the opening
round last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up and looked out at the window at the hotel flags
blowing opposite from the other day,'' Bertman said, ``We're very
dependent on the home run, and Mother Nature didn't treat us as
well as we'd have liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Etherton, who this time around had considerably more
snap to his breaking pitches and was able to handcuff the powerful
Tigers on a half dozen hits over eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   It got a little dicey in the ninth, when LSU scored once off of
ace reliever Jack Krawczyk and had the tying run on base. But
Krawczyk got Danny Higgins to fly to center for the final out and
record his 22nd save of the season and 48th of his career, both
NCAA records.
</P>
<P>
   ``What record?'' deadpanned Krawczyk, who's allowed four runs on
eight hits over 5 2/3 innings in three CWS appearances, relying
mostly on his deceptive changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``But today I struck out a guy on a fastball,'' he said,
sounding surprised. ``That was good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' win snapped LSU's 10-game win streak in the CWS, a
mark the Tigers now share with USC.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers still had their homers. Jack Dalton hit one in the
first inning, giving every batter in the lineup at least one in
just three CWS games, and Cedrick Harris, who bats ninth, hit one
in the top of the seventh to break a 2-2 tie, the 16th overall in
the CWS by LSU.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans regained the lead with two runs in the bottom of the
seventh on successive singles by Seth Davidson, Wes Rachels and
Greg Hanoian, a sacrifice bunt by Robb Gorr and a botched
double-play ball by first baseman Eddy Furniss.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Davidson's one-out run-scoring triple in the eighth
that produced what developed as the decisive run.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Lane opened the inning with a single off left-handed
reliever Chris Demouy, and Rod Perry Jr. bunted him to second.
Davidson sent a liner into the gap in right-center, scoring Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, it had been a frustrating day for the Trojans
(47-17), who are seeking their-record 12th College World Series
crown. Twice they had runners thrown out at the plate to end
innings, the first time in the third inning, when Higgins, the left
fielder, cut down Hanoian trying to score from second on a single
by Eric Munson, and then in the fourth, when right fielder Wes
Davis threw out Brad Ticehurst trying to score a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Morgan Ensberg and Munson hit homers for the Trojans,
who aren't exactly powerless; they've hit a USC-record 106 homers
this season, nine at the CWS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any rules against hitting three-run homers,''
USC coach Mike Gillespie said. ``We'd like to hit some, too, like
they do. But, in our case, we still have to do the little things if
we're going to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
