<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE FLIES TO OHIO, BUT `EL DUQUE' STAYS IN BRON 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez was supposed to be a one-day
wonder. Promote him for one night on a big stage, then send him
back to Class AAA for more seasoning. But he pitched beautifully
Wednesday and impressed George Steinbrenner, the team's principal
owner, and now Hernandez may be here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez struck out seven in seven innings and beat Tampa Bay,
7-1, and rather than hop the shuttle to Columbus on Thursday, he
remained with the team, as Steinbrenner met with other officials in
Manager Joe Torre's office.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, who flew in from Tampa, Fla., Thursday, would not
immediately speak with reporters, other than to briefly compliment
Hernandez. But he apparently rendered a vote to keep El Duque, as
Hernandez is known; Torre _ who said unequivocally Wednesday that
Hernandez would return to Class AAA immediately after his start _
acknowledged that plans have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza, who has pitched well as a starter for the
Yankees, will probably be shifted to the bullpen, with Hernandez
taking his spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the shift in the club's intentions, Torre said:
``The fact is, I don't have the ultimate decision to make. When you
have an organization and an owner who knows what he wants to do,
that's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Hernandez could be easily justified on the grounds that
he has demonstrated he is one of the organization's 11 best
pitchers. A scout who watched Hernandez pitch Wednesday said that
if Sandy Koufax, the Hall of Fame pitcher, had a fastball that
deserved an 8 on a scale of 1 to 8, then Hernandez deserved an 8
for his control.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez seemed to be able to throw his breaking pitches for
strikes just about any time he wanted, Tim Raines said, ``and you
just don't see that very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza's presence in the bullpen would strengthen the team's
middle relief. Willie Banks struggled before being dropped from the
team last week _ Thursday, he was traded to Arizona _ and Jeff
Nelson and Darren Holmes have been erratic.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza has pitched effectively out of the bullpen in the past,
and, being a sinker-ball pitcher, he has the ability to get ground
balls and double plays.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Keeping Hernandez would provide financial benefits as well.
Steinbrenner has complained about the lack of attendance at Yankee
Stadium, and Hernandez would draw attention and fans to the Yankees
on the nights that he pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a poor team on Wednesday, the Yankees drew 27,291 _
about 8,000 more than they drew Monday, 5,000 more than Tuesday's
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But others in the organization who preferred to send Hernandez
back to Class AAA and keep Mendoza in the rotation _ judging by
Torre's pronouncement Wednesday, this was the course of action
favored by most _ could offer compelling logic, too.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza has arguably been one of the Yankees' three most
effective starters in the last six weeks, along with David Wells
and Hideki Irabu, compiling a 3-1 record and a 4.18 earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza has pitched five or more innings in seven of his last
eight starts, with a 3.48 ERA as a starter since April 20.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza is in his third year with the team, which, for many,
would give him extra consideration.
</P>
<P>
   With Hernandez in Class AAA, the Yankees would be better suited
to address an injury to one of their starting pitchers; if Mendoza
shifts to the bullpen now, and another pitcher is hurt in a month,
then Mendoza would have to go through the sometimes lengthy process
of re-adapting to the physical regimen required for a starting
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the question of Mendoza's confidence: would he be
hurt by losing his job when he has pitched well? Torre said:
``We're not dealing with pieces of paper. There are people who
would have to be talked to.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza said: ``I'd rather be a starter, but the bullpen is OK.
The important thing is to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If others in the organization want to change Steinbrenner's
mind, they'll have a few days to do so. Mendoza pitches Saturday,
against Florida, and the earliest Hernandez might be needed to
start again would be Tuesday, in Montreal, if the cut on David
Cone's right hand hasn't healed sufficiently.
</P>
<P>
   If Cone can pitch, then Hernandez may not be scheduled to start
for another week to 10 days. ``We'll keep him around here,'' Torre
said, ``and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez longed to pitch in the United States since his
childhood. He was out of organized baseball for a year and a half,
after being banned by officials in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   He spent half a day on a leaky boat, fleeing Cuba, and three
more days hoping and praying for someone to pluck him and his wife
and six others from an island. Nearly three months passed before he
was able to sign his first contract.
</P>
<P>
   He's waiting again for his fate to be decided _ but in this
case, it seems that good things are in store for him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
