<HEADLINE>
ORAN K. HENDERSON, COURT MARTIALED IN MY LAI CIVILIAN KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ga., Ind.)  (js) 
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Col. Oran K. Henderson, the highest-ranking officer to be tried
as a consequence of the killings of Vietnamese civilians in My Lai
in 1968, died Tuesday at the Lebanon Veterans hospital in Lebanon,
Pa. He was 77 and had pancreatic cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, a career officer, was acquitted in a court martial in
1971, leaving Lt. William Calley Jr., a platoon leader, as the only
soldier to be found guilty and punished for the massacre in My Lai.
The belated disclosure of apparent war crimes in the hamlet and the
subsequent accusations of a cover-up tarnished the Army's
reputation and broadened criticisms of U.S. involvement in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's death came less than a month after that of Ronald
Ridenhour, a 52-year-old New Orleans journalist who as a young
helicopter gunner serving in Vietnam had heard what had happened at
My Lai and brought the atrocity to public attention through letters
to politicians, which he felt safe enough to send only after
leaving the military.
</P>
<P>
   Those letters eventually led to newspaper exposes and official
inquiries that confirmed the killings at My Lai, which took place
as the 105 men of Company C attacked the hamlet of 700 people,
believing it was a Viet Cong base. According to Seymour Hersh,
whose reporting on My Lai was awarded a 1970 Pulitzer Prize, no
Viet Cong were encountered. At least 350 civilians were killed,
among them women and children, at My Lai alone, and there were
other killings by B company at nearby hamlets.
</P>
<P>
   That day, March 16, was Henderson's first as the commanding
officer of the newly formed 11th Infantry Brigade, which included
Company C. When the assault was mounted, he was watching from a
command helicopter circling over My Lai.
</P>
<P>
   Only after the news accounts made My Lai as recognizable a name
as Saigon did the Army conduct an official investigation. After
three-and-a-half months of taking evidence, Lt. Gen. William Peers,
who headed the panel, declared on March 18, 1970, ``Our inquiry
clearly established that a tragedy of major proportions occurred
there on that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the Army was to charge 25 officers and enlisted men
with having taken part in the massacre in some way or of having
covered it up. Of this total, 19 men had charges against them
dropped without facing trials. Of the six who came before courts
martial, only Calley was convicted. He received a life sentence at
hard labor, which was soon reduced to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But as Calley was increasingly perceived _ even by his critics _
as the single scapegoat for My Lai, he was paroled by Howard
Callaway, secretary of the Army in the Nixon administration, after
serving less than four years. He is now a jeweler in Columbus, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson was the highest ranking officer of those who went
before court martial, and his case at the end of 1971 was the last
one to be heard. He had been charged with willful dereliction of
duty for not having carried out an adequate investigation. His
trial at Fort Meade, Md., lasted 62 days, thus tying the Calley
case as the longest court martial in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution argued that with the information available to
him and with complaints that were made at the time by helicopter
pilots, it was inconceivable that Henderson could report as he did
to his division commander that ``only 20 civilians'' had been
inadvertently killed by artillery fire. The prosecution contended
that Henderson had covered up the killings because he feared that
he would lose his new position as brigade commander and thought
that any report of a mass killing would end his chances for
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The defense argued that Henderson had tried to find out what had
happened at My Lai, but was prevented by officers who kept lying to
him, insisting that only 20 civilians had been killed. Until his
first day commanding the 11th Brigade, the colonel had compiled an
enviable military record.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Indianapolis on Aug. 25, 1920, he spent much of his
adulthood in combat. He served and was wounded in three wars _
World War II, Korea and Vietnam. He was awarded four Purple Hearts
for combat wounds, and five Silver Stars and five Bronze Stars for
valor.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 18, 1971, after 106 witnesses had been heard, Henderson
stood at attention and heard the president of the jury declare that
he had been found not guilty. He saluted and said the verdict
``reaffirms the confidence any Army man can have in the military
system.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to active duty, becoming commandant of the
Indiantown Gap Military Reservation in Pennsylvania. When he
retired in 1974, he told The Associated Press that his departure
was mandatory since he had been colonel for five years without
promotion. He said that while his retirement was not necessarily
related to My Lai, he did feel responsible for the incident because
the troops involved were under his command.
</P>
<P>
   As a civilian, he became Pennsylvania's director of civil
defense, organizing relocation and recovery efforts in the wake of
devastating floods in 1977. At that time, as he once again found
himself in the news, he observed: ``Occasionally people will come
up to me and say, `I remember your first name, Oran, from
someplace.' We usually get around to the fact that I had had a
little bit of publicity a few years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, who made his home in Carlisle, Pa., is survived by
three children: Kenneth R. of Guilford, Ind., Ann H. Kline of
Lebanon, Pa., and Nancy V. Schultz of Monroe, N.Y.; five
grandchildren; a brother, Wayne of Indianapolis; and two sisters,
Glenita Bastin of Noblesville, Ind., and Virginia Betts of
Indianapolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
