<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH OUT FOR LIMIT OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ As the search intensifies for a Belmont Stakes
horse that might derail Real Quiet's bid for the Triple Crown, eyes
are increasingly cast toward lightly raced Limit Out.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason. The speedy Limit Out is trained by
69-year-old legend H. Allen Jerkens, who wears the scalps of many
famous horses on his belt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962 and 1963, Jerkens sent out Beau Purple to upset Kelso
three times in less than a year. The only races Secretariat lost
after his Triple Crown sweep in 1973 were to Onion and Prove Out,
both trained by Jerkens. His list of victims is so long, in fact,
he was inducted into the Racing Hall of Fame in 1975 at age 45, the
youngest trainer at that time to be so honored.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the painfully shy but temperamental Jerkens is known around
the Belmont Park backstretch as ``The Giant Killer,'' a nickname he
deserves but didn't seek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing I can do about it,'' he said. ``I'm stuck with it. But
I didn't come up with it, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   A contrast to today's BMW-driving and cellular phone-toting
horsemen, Jerkens is a throwback to a time when trainers dedicated
their lives to their horses. He is still at the barn religiously at
5 a.m. seven days a week, rides a pony to accompany all his horses
to the track for gallops and obsesses about every detail of daily
care and race preparation.
</P>
<P>
   As Jerkens prepares Limit Out for Saturday's race, he is relying
on all his experience.
</P>
<P>
   Limit Out has won four of five lifetime starts and has run seven
furlongs in 1 minute, 20 2/5 seconds. However, he has never raced
beyond a mile, and the Belmont distance is a 1 1/2 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if it were his horse, the conservative Jerkens would
be seeking a more logical spot than the Belmont. But Limit Out is
owned by Jerry Shields, a New York Racing Association trustee who
has asked Jerkens to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you get roped into these things,'' Jerkens said with
a chuckle. ``I'm changing the way I've been training him, trying to
teach him to run longer distances, to breathe differently.
Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn't. Who knows?'' &QL; 
REAL QUIET DRAWS NO. 8 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday morning, Real Quiet drew post position No. 8 in a
13-horse Belmont field. The lineup was swelled by the surprise
entry of front-runner Chilito, owned by banking and media magnate
Joseph Albritton, who has homes in Washington, D.C., and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Bob Baffert seemed unconcerned about Real Quiet's
slightly disadvantageous draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have a horse training great than have a great post
position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet got his first feel of the Belmont Park surface
yesterday in a casual jog around the track. &QL; 
WEATHER FACTOR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All week, rain has been in the forecast for tomorrow's race. But
yesterday the weather handicappers did an about-face and are
calling for partly sunny skies, temperatures around 70 and only a
slight chance of showers.
</P>
<P>
   That could be important to Real Quiet's chances: The only time
he raced over a wet track, he was beaten badly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
