</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--BLINEBURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Likely swan song &QL; 
sounding off-key
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ As the ugly events in Game 1 of these NBA Finals
continue to be as digestible for the Bulls as the soles on a pair
of worn-out Nikes, we receive this unpleasant news flash for
parents all across the land:
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan has taken to playing the piano.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that in addition to shelling out money that was
intended for the mortgage payment and the light bill to keep Junior
shod in the latest, stylin' pair of overpriced high-tops, now any
self-respecting mom and dad also will feel pressured into adding a
baby grand to the living-room furniture. Maybe a Steinway with a
Swoosh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played the piano last night,'' Jordan said. ``I played at
it. Don't confuse the issue. I'm just pushing the keys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a piano here in my hotel room. I'm taking lessons
from Ahmad.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, would be the ubiquitous Ahmad Rashad, NBC's
news hound and barnacle who has hitched a ride on the hull of the
S.S. Jordan. For a guy whose annual NBA salary is $33 million and
whose impact on the global economy has been estimated by Fortune
magazine at $10 billion, you would think Jordan would fly in
somebody such as Van Cliburn if he wanted to take piano lessons.
Instead, he's learning The Battle Hymn of the Republic from a
microphone-toter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike and I sit there and bang the keys together,'' Rashad
says.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls remain confident
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of keeping down breakfast, let's not explore
this subject further, except to wonder if any future musical jaunt
will have Jordan interested in Jazz. Namely, how to play it tonight
in Game 2 of the NBA Finals at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the opener found the Bulls wearing smiles so
broad, you would have thought they had accompanied Dennis Rodman on
one of his side trips to Las Vegas and hit the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really talked to my team yet to measure anything
about their level of emotion,'' said coach Phil Jackson. ``But I've
looked at the game tapes and discussed it with my staff, and I feel
fine. It's a beautiful day here in Salt Lake City.''
</P>
<P>
   In one breath Scottie Pippen said the Bulls were frustrated
after their 88-85 overtime loss, and in the next the smile was back
in place and he said the pressure was still on the Jazz to defend
its home court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still feel that we're in control of the series,'' Pippen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said the Bulls have an inner strength that allows them to
get through the tough times, of which this situation would seem to
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   That frustration seemed evident. After Pippen hit a big 3-point
shot in the fourth quarter, Jordan shouted in Pippen's face on the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that I was screaming at Scottie Pippen,'' Jordan said.
``I don't have a reason to scream at Scottie Pippen. He and I are
on the same wavelength. I think, due to the loudness of the arena,
I'm pretty sure I was yelling to get a point across.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of barking and frustration from the Bulls in
Game 1. Perhaps with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Champs in strange situation
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since losing the Finals opener to the Lakers
in 1991 _ a series they won in five games to start their dynasty _
the Bulls trail in the Finals. What's more, there were many signs
there are cracks in their championship foundation, on the floor and
in the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   His Airness scored 33 points but had to put up 29 shots to do
it. Jordan played 46 minutes of the overtime game. He seemed weary
and spent at the end. On one play, he could not seem to dunk the
ball. With just more than a minute left in the overtime, he had a
mental lapse, which resulted in a 24-second violation.
</P>
<P>
   His Weirdness, Rodman, played the game with tape wrapped around
his right thumb because of torn ligaments. His hair dyed with a
green camouflage pattern, Rodman looks like the product of mating
between a Martian and a Hereford.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson snapped at Rodman for a couple of ill-timed shots and a
defensive lapse that allowed Karl Malone to roar down the lane for
an uncontested dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan sniped at Luc Longley for trying to dribble through
traffic to the hoop in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game Utah tried to give away, kicking back a 75-68
lead in the last four minutes of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The champion Bulls won that kind of game. The old Bulls seized
the day.
</P>
<P>
   This time they played a different tune, one that maybe Jordan
will have to learn from Ahmad in the next piano lesson. It's an old
Neil Sedaka number: Breaking Up Is Hard To Do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
