<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Real Quiet 5 Million Buckx
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ A Chicago Tribune editor turned up his nose this
week when he wrote about Real Quiet's Triple Crown bid at
Saturday's Belmont Stakes. He claimed Real Quiet joining the ranks
of Secretariat, Seattle Slew and Citation was ``akin to the
Clampetts moving in across the street at your Beverly Hills digs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just doesn't fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer John Veitch _ who, in 1978, guided Alydar to three
straight runner-up finishes to Affirmed, the last Triple Crown
champ _ noted the other day that Real Quiet won this year's
Kentucky Derby and Preakness against fields depleted of injured
contenders Grand Slam, Lil's Lad, Event of the Year, Halory Hunter
and Coronado's Quest. The way Veitch sees it, if Real Quiet wins
Saturday, the question remains:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whom did he beat?''
</P>
<P>
   And D. Wayne Lukas _ thoroughbred racing's preeminent trainer in
recent times until being eclipsed the past two years by Bob
Baffert, the affable trainer of Real Quiet _ could only look in the
direction of his rival last month and sniff:
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people need to be more professional.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does Baffert answer the snipers and snobs? Actually, he
let his 4-year-old daughter Savannah handle it on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Real Quiet had drawn the eighth post position for
Saturday's 130th running of the Belmont Stakes, the shy little girl
dressed in a yellow tam and smock crawled into her daddy's arms.
Baffert grinned: ``What are we gonna say to the folks from Visa on
Saturday?''
</P>
<P>
   Savannah looked down a moment, then whispered ``I know . . .
We're gonna say, `Five million dollars!' ''
</P>
<P>
   If Real Quiet wins the mile-and-a-half Belmont and becomes our
new Pegasus, he will have won one of the most elusive titles in all
of sports. And that will mean the richest payday in thoroughbred
racing history. Along with the $600,000 winner's share from the
Belmont comes a $5 million bonus from Visa.
</P>
<P>
   Getting one of their credit cards might be easy, but they know
that winning the three Triple Crown races in just five weeks is an
almost impossible task. Thirteen horses have run to the lip of
history _ winning the Derby and Preakness _ only to lose the
Belmont, a grueling, 12-furlong race that all but blocks the
passage to immortality. Most American bred and trained horses are
not built for this throwback test of stamina over speed.
</P>
<P>
   In racing history, only 11 horses have won the Triple Crown.
They make up a fabled fraternity to which Real Quiet, critics say,
doesn't rate admission. They see him _ this colt whose deformed
knees were once held together by screws and pins, this ugly
duckling who Baffert bought for a flea market price tag of $17,000,
this also-ran who had won just twice before the Derby _ as a knock
kneed, narrow-chested castoff standing at a back-door entrance to
fame
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason the Belmont field grew to 13 horses Thursday.
A couple of trainers see Real Quiet as a pretender, ready to be
silenced for good.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this dismissal may be aimed at Baffert. Never mind he's
the only trainer ever to contend for the Triple Crown two years in
a row. Last year, his big gray colt, Silver Charm, was headed for
Triple Crown triumph when he was caught deep in the Belmont stretch
by Touch Gold.
</P>
<P>
   Some backsiders remember that a little over six years ago,
Baffert was still part of the minor-league quarter horse circuit.
With such limited seasoning, he's taken thoroughbred racing by
storm. He doesn't just produce, he does it with style. He's fun _
the guy who two years in a row put the silver Preakness bowl on his
head, the guy who once wore a pumpkin on his head in the Winners
Circle after a Halloween victory, the guy who Thursday told the
post-draw crowd, ``Now I just got to keep him alive two more
days.''
</P>
<P>
   That brought more laughter and embrace, but in some quarters,
that also brings petty backlash. Baffert knows:
</P>
<P>
   ``Look how they're knocking President Clinton. He's like us, a
regular guy. But the high echelon knocks him because he's not like
them. They think they set the standard and if you do well, they
want to tear you down. The thing is, we (owner Mike Pegram and
Baffert) grew up at the same time as him. We grew up in the hippie
generation and it's coming out now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is Clinton's doing a great job. Look at the way our
economy is. To me he's one of the greatest presidents since I've
been alive. And Real Quiet? I've had great horses and he is a great
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said his bay colt has grown into greatness: ``He's
changed mentally. He never used to stop and stand, he was always
wiggling. Then he got to Kentucky and turned tough. He learned to
stop and stare. We had him in the stable next to Silver Charm and
he must have told him how to act. He's just a big awkward kid whose
finally getting it down. He's finally learned to dunk the
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Preakness he was tired and then he dug down and won on
blood and guts. We can't help that other horses fell by the
wayside. That's what the Triple Crown is all about. It's survival
of the fittest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been able to do this because he has character. And today
again he looked good in his workout. He's full of himself right now
and I see him coming up big Saturday. I can't see him losing unless
we get some bad luck. And I believe in karma. I think the Triple
Crown gods will look down on us. If not, well, we've had fun. But
if he does win, it will be awesome. And then there'd be just one
more thing . . .''
</P>
<P>
   He looked at his daughter, who this time did not flinch when she
whispered:
</P>
<P>
   ``Five million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Archdeacon at 225-2156 or e-mail tom_archdeaconcoxohio.cox
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
