<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAWLEY LAWYER SAID TO HAVE NOT QUESTIONED DEFENDANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Though Alton Maddox Jr. publicly accused a
young prosecutor of raping and kidnapping Tawana Brawley late in
1987, when Maddox had his suspect, Steven Pagones, in court 10
years ago ready to testify under oath, he never asked a single
question.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Hayes, the lawyer who was representing Pagones at the
time, testified Thursday in the Tawana Brawley defamation case that
his client had been subpoenaed by Maddox _ Ms. Brawley's adviser _
for a hearing in June 1988, only to wait in the courthouse hallway
while Maddox told the presiding judge to cut proceedings short
because reporters had to meet deadlines and he had to return to New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   But Maddox said that the judge presiding over that hearing _ a
contempt-of-court charge for Ms. Brawley's mother _ had barred
several people whom he wanted to call, including Gov. Mario Cuomo
and Attorney General Robert Abrams, and had also prevented him from
putting Pagones on the stand. ``I would have loved to ask Pagones a
question.'' Maddox said. ``I thought that he should have his day in
court, but other forces did not.''
</P>
<P>
   Pagones is now suing Maddox and two other advisers to Ms.
Brawley _ C. Vernon Mason and the Rev. Al Sharpton _ for naming him
as one of a group of men who they said attacked the teen-ager over
four days in 1987. A grand jury found no evidence that Ms. Brawley
had been assaulted, and it specifically exonerated Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox's failure to confront Pagones at that time goes to the
crux of the defamation case, said Pagones' current lawyer, William
Stanton. He is trying to prove that the Brawley advisers made
reckless, malicious accusations and purposefully avoided learning
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve was in court, ready to testify, and Maddox didn't call
him,'' Stanton said Thursday. ``That, to me, is reckless at least
and probably malicious. They totally ignored that, and wanted to go
ahead with their lies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
