<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-world </SLUG>
 cup-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only tough to survive `Group of Death'
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
``D'' stands for death.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner were powerhouse teams Paraguay, Spain, Nigeria and
Bulgaria drawn together into Group D for the upcoming World Cup
than all the world began talking about the luscious possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   This should be a brutal first-round World Cup show.
Entertaining, but brutal.
</P>
<P>
   Put it this way: If the World Cup is the Super Bowl times 10, as
some say, then this is the Black and Blue Division unchained.
</P>
<P>
   It has been called the ``Group of Death'' for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   All four Group D teams have legitimate World Cup hopes. All four
are playing well going into the tournament. All four have more
World Cup credentials than the majority of nations in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But two teams will go home early. ``D'' stands for
disappointment, too.
</P>
<P>
   Spain was a Cup quarterfinalist just four years ago and boasts
one of the greatest players in the world in Raul Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay had one of the strongest World Cup qualifying runs of
any nation and is a super-talented team formed in the mold of
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is the defending Olympic champion with two more years of
experience under its belt, and the Super Eagles have victories over
such powers as Argentina and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria is returning virtually intact a team that made an
inspiring World Cup semifinals run four years ago and features the
creative goal-scoring of Hristo Stoichkov, whose six goals in 1994
were more than any other player in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It promises to be perhaps the most dramatic and entertaining
soccer of the entire first stage, with every match potentially
pivotal and every point huge.
</P>
<P>
   Luck _ a shot bounced off the crossbar or a seeing-eye
deflection into the net _ might be as important as anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to make predictions,'' said Bora Milutinovic,
the former United States and Mexican national team coach now
leading Nigeria. ``Every match will be the same, very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most pivotal match figures to be the opener in the
group between Spain and Nigeria on June 13 in Nantes. The winner of
the match could go a long way, if not all the way.
</P>
<P>
   If it is Nigeria, look out. In fact, it was nearly 20 years ago
when the great Brazilian superstar, Pel, predicted that an African
nation would win the World Cup championship by the end of the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Well, this is the final Cup of the century and a victory over
the talented Spaniards could be just the jolt that carries the deep
and talented Nigerians all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic admits that this is by far the best team he has
coached.
</P>
<P>
   It is a team extremely deep at every position, athletic and for
years now has been honing its skills in the tough European
professional leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Victor Ikpeda has twice been named African Footballer
of the Year, while no less than seven other Nigerian players are
regulars for their professional teams.
</P>
<P>
   Spain, on the other hand, has much more Cup experience than any
nation in the group, although it hasn't always been good
experience. It is a team that traditionally has fallen short of
expectations and broken a lot of hearts.
</P>
<P>
   But now there is a dominant player on the roster _ Raul _ like
few in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Already, his professional team, Real Madrid, or ``Raul'' Madrid
as the Spanish press calls it, has turned down a nearly $46 million
offer for Raul's contract.
</P>
<P>
   This could be Spain's year. And Raul, 21, seems capable of
putting on a one-man show similar to those of Argentina's Diego
Maradona or Pel in past World Cup tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   The only questions for the other deadly dangerous teams in this
group are minor ones.
</P>
<P>
   Can Bulgaria ride Stoichkov's greatness to another memorable Cup
run?
</P>
<P>
   And can Paraguay keep up the great streak of play that it has
been on?
</P>
<P>
   Stoichkov, 34, is coming off a marvelous season in Europe. He
doesn't seem to be slowing a bit. The Bulgarians also should
benefit from a counterattacking style contrary to every other
team's in the group.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay, which loves to attack, has faltered against teams such
as Bulgaria in the past. Its style tends to leave gaping holes in
the defense.
</P>
<P>
   But for nearly two years now, during which the Paraguayans have
lost only two full international matches, few teams have managed to
keep up with this up-and-coming team.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which team survives this group, it should be a thrill
to watch. And after surviving the Group of Death, ``D'' also could
stand for World Cup destiny for the eventual winner here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
