<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' BACK OPTIMISTIC IN CANCER FIGHT  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Giants running back LeShon Johnson
smiled when he referred to his wife of six weeks as ``a computer
geek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She can get on the Internet and find out anything,'' Johnson
said Thursday of Nalani, whom he married April 27. ``She can fly in
and out of all those web sites.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last 10 days, Nalani has been doing research on a
totally unexpected subject. It is non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, the type
of cancer that has stricken her husband. It will be treated with
six months of chemotherapy beginning next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been finding out all she can and then filling me in,''
LeShon said Thursday at Giants Stadium. ``I get little reports on
what she's learned all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   This, too, brought a smile to Johnson's face. ``I'm very lucky
to have her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Staring down between the cowboy boots on his feet, he added:
``We're going to beat this thing and get on with life.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the day Johnson met with reporters and teammates,
preparing for the next, unexpected stage in his life: the one after
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He has been examined and tested. ``I've been poked so much I
feel like a human pin cushion,'' he said. He has had long,
emotional telephone conversations with his mother, father and
brothers back home in Oklahoma. And he has come to face a new
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought you had to be old to get cancer,'' said Johnson,
signed by the Giants just three months ago as a free agent.``I
thought I was a healthy, 27-year-old football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, standing on a makeshift podium next to the Giants
practice field, Johnson listened as the Giants' trainer, Ronnie
Barnes, read off a new set of statistics for this football player.
</P>
<P>
   ``LeShon has non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, B cell,'' Barnes said.
``CAT scans have isolated the tumor above his waist. It is 8
millimeters in size. The doctors tell me they are very encouraged
and optimistic that the lymphoma is localized and treatable. He
will start his chemotherapy treatments next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will be treated by Dr. David J. Wolf, an oncologist at
New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center who also treated former
Giants lineman Karl Nelson in the late 1980s. Nelson, like hockey
star Mario Lemieux, had Hodgkin's lymphoma, which is generally
considered easier to treat than non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   But as Dr. Marc Lippman, the director of the Vince Lombardi
Cancer Research Center of Georgetown University, said in a
telephone interview from Washington, there are about 15 different
types of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 10-year survival rates for these lymphomas can range from
10 percent to 90 percent,'' Lippman said. ``It all depends exactly
what subtype of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma he has.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, although questioned on the subject, were not
specific about Johnson's lymphoma type.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is some lymphomas are completely curable and most can
be put into remission,'' Lippman said. ``If he goes into remission,
he can play again, and most likely he will.''
</P>
<P>
   Lippman added that it was a good sign that Johnson had no
symptoms before the tumor was detected by a routine chest X-ray
last month. It was also a good sign that Johnson's doctors are
saying the lymphoma was detected at an early stage. Asked if
Johnson could play while undergoing chemotherapy, Lippman said:
``Some people go through chemo with only a few setbacks, and some
people get kind of beat up. Let's just say he certainly wouldn't be
on top of his game.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the podium Thursday, beneath a brilliant sun, Johnson nodded
at the Giants' practice field. ``It's my goal to be back out there
before my six months of treatments are over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He then encouraged ``young people'' to get checkups. And he
thanked the Giants for making him feel so at home and welcomed in
just three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was speechless when they told me,'' Johnson said. ``I was
scared and nervous. But I know I have a lot of people praying for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, he plans to go home to Haskell, Okla., where his
father runs a horse ranch and where LeShon learned to ride rodeo
bulls at the age 8. ``I need a little time at home,'' he said
Thursday, standing by the door of the Giants' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   LeShon and Nalani Johnson and their 5-month-old son will return
Tuesday. They are looking for an apartment in New Jersey, not too
far from Giants Stadium so LeShon can attend practices. The
chemotherapy will be administered in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I wanted it,'' he said. ``I'm staying here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
