<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDONESIA IN DEBT PACT WITH FOREIGN BANKERS
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia and a group of foreign bankers agreed on a framework
for rescheduling nearly $80 billion in corporate and bank debt that
has become one of the biggest barriers to restarting the nation's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement offers hope that Indonesia's weakened currency can
begin to recover, that cash will start to flow again, that moribund
companies will not be crushed by debts and that crucial export
industries will flourish again.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS OFFER ON HOLOCAUST CLAIMS
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland's three major commercial banks have reportedly
offered a settlement of more than $1 billion to end suits brought
by Holocaust victims and their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS CLIMB ON ECONOMIC NEWS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rebounded as investors were soothed by reports that the
economy remains resilient. The Dow Jones industrial average rose
66.76 points, to 8,870.56; the Nasdaq composite, 1.59 percent, to
1,769.95, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, 1.1 percent,
to 1,094.83.
</P>
<P>
   BOND PRICES ARE JOLTED
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, Treasury prices dropped sharply, with the
yield on the 30-year bond rising to 5.82 percent from 5.78. The
market weakened on signs of a strong economy and the Bank of
England's surprise move to raise its benchmark lending rate by
one-quarter point, to 7.5 percent. That raised yields on British
debt securities, making them more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   NEW OIL AGREEMENT RAISES PRICES
</P>
<P>
   An agreement by Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico to reduce oil
production sent oil prices up 2 percent in the futures markets.
</P>
<P>
   WARNING ON WORLDCOM-MCI MERGER
</P>
<P>
   The top European regulator reviewing the proposed $37 billion
Worldcom-MCI merger said MCI's proposed sale of part of its
Internet business might not be enough to allay his antitrust
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR PRODUCTIVITY GROWTH DECLINES
</P>
<P>
   Growth in the productivity of U.S. workers lapsed to an annual
rate of 1.1 percent in the first three months of the year, the
government said. Factory orders rose 1.2 percent in April, the
biggest increase in five months. And the number of Americans filing
for unemployment benefits surged 30,000 last week.
</P>
<P>
   BIG, BIG BOAT TAKES TO SEA
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Princess _ twice the size of the Titanic _ is on its
maiden voyage. It is the world's largest cruise ship _ 50 feet
taller than the Statue of Liberty _ and cost $450 million. The
cruise industry has several more vessels, just as large or larger,
on order from the Italian shipbuilder Fincantieri.
</P>
<P>
   CALL FOR ACTION ON INTERNET PRIVACY
</P>
<P>
   Civil-liberties advocates and children's groups urged the White
House to abandon its hands-off stance on Internet privacy
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   PANEL BACKS EUROPE ON TARIFFS
</P>
<P>
   A World Trade Organization panel, reversing a ruling that
favored the United States, said European Union nations can continue
to impose tariffs on computer-networking equipment exports ahead of
a July 1, 2000, deadline for eliminating all such tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   A CREDIT CARD IS BORN
</P>
<P>
   The theater industry is stepping up efforts to market itself,
with the debut of a ``Live Broadway'' credit card.
</P>
</TEXT>
