<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-UNREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STERN TALKS LOCKOUT, QUESTIONS PATRIOTISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ David Stern stopped short of calling them
unpatriotic, but he did question the wisdom of players who are
considering boycotting this summer's World Championships in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the individual players decide to trash their country,
that's going to be their decision,'' Stern said Thursday during his
annual address.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by the league's deputy commissioner, Russ Granik, Stern
spent much of the news conference at the Delta Center detailing the
growing labor strife between the players and the owners. The league
is expected to lock out the players July 1 if the two sides cannot
agree on a revised collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, the union's president, has been advising members
of the U.S. team not play. And Michael Jordan supported that stance
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a heartbeat,'' Jordan said. ``I would be in favor of not
playing in the World Championship games. If you're going to try to
handcuff one side, we have to retaliate.''
</P>
<P>
   Granik warned that such a boycott could influence U.S. chances
for automatically qualifying for the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney,
Australia. Granik, who is also the president of USA Basketball,
said if the United States did not win the gold medal in Athens it
would have to qualify by playing in a qualifying tournament
possibly during the 1999-2000 NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wearing the USA Basketball hat, I have concern,'' Granik said.
``We have not gotten any notice or anything from players that
they're not going to play, but people obviously have read the
reports that it's being discussed. It will certainly damage USA
Basketball in its international relations and its standing in the
international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, the players association executive director, said
the union was investigating whether the United States could receive
a bye because it won the gold medal at the Atlanta Games in 1996
and has never failed to qualify for an Olympics. He said he was
mindful of the players possibly being portrayed as unpatriotic if
they boycotted the games.
</P>
<P>
   Among the league's stars, the team includes Grant Hill and Gary
Payton. The possibility of sending college players has been
discussed, but no formal decision has been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always worried about our public image,'' Hunter said.
``I am definitely worried about that. Depending upon what the
circumstances are, though, David Stern is in the catbird's seat. We
hope we can reach an agreement with the NBA to head off the
action.''
</P>
<P>
   Because players signed contracts with USA Basketball, Stern is
mostly wringing his hands when it comes to the league's
involvement. But Hunter added, ``We could argue we think USA
Basketball is the alter ego of the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   The boycott talk is merely the latest salvo fired in the labor
battle between the two sides. The players canceled a meeting with
the owners in New York on Monday, claiming their proposals were
unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   The key issue over which both sides will haggle this summer
involves the league's desire to implement a hard salary cap that
would put a ceiling on how much teams can spend each season. Such a
proposal would most likely do away with the Larry Bird exception, a
rule by which teams can pay their own free agents any amount of
money to retain their rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want a hard cap,'' Dikembe Mutombo, an executive
committee member, told The Atlanta Journal-Constitution over the
weekend. ``They want to get rid of the Bird exception. They want to
tax teams who spend more. We can't live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners exercised their right to re-open the existing deal in
April after a revenue split amounted to the players receiving more
than 57 percent of basketball-related income. Once the threshold
topped 51.8 percent, the owners were allowed to exercise their
option.
</P>
<P>
   While the union does not want a ceiling on player salaries, the
league is afraid the enormous contracts of a few have severely
hampered its economic system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really very simple,'' Granik said. ``Under our current
system too much money is being paid out in salaries. And we need a
new system that will bring salary growth in line with revenue
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked where the two sides are in negotiations with only 27 days
left to make a deal before business is interrupted, Hunter said:
``I think it'll come to a head when it's apparent there is going to
be a lockout. It's incumbent on the NBA to come up with a process
or a system that we feel is beneficial to us. We're farther apart
now than when we started.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
