<HEADLINE>
NYC ASKS COURT FOR IMMEDIATE ENFORCEMENT OF PORN RESTRICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Acting with a speed uncharacteristic of a
governmental body, lawyers for the city filed papers with a federal
appeals court Thursday asking that New York be allowed to
immediately enforce three-year-old zoning laws intended to weed out
and isolate sex businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The 2nd Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals ruled Wednesday that free
speech issues raised by sex shop owners fighting the zoning laws
had been fully reviewed since the laws were passed in 1995. The
court said no further review was necessary and that the zoning laws
``may be enforced forthwith.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, lawyers for the sex shop owners said that
they would invoke federal rules allowing them to delay enforcement
for 21 days, while they searched for mistakes or technicalities
overlooked by the court.
</P>
<P>
   Just minutes before the appeals court closed Thursday lawyers
for the city filed papers asking that the court disallow the 21-day
window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the utter lack of merit of plaintiffs' case and the
public interest in enforcement of this important regulatory zoning
scheme,'' wrote Chief Assistant Corporation Counsel Leonard
Koerner, ``the city urgently requests that this court vacate the
stay of enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Koerner did not return telephone calls to his office Thursday
night, but City Councilman Walter McCaffrey, who sponsored the
zoning law, said the motion was a move to end any further
foot-dragging by sex shop owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone on too long,'' McCaffrey said. ``Sixteen different
judges have ruled in favor of the zoning change. Every day they are
open is another day they can pay for their high-priced lawyers to
stall the inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Herald Price Fahringer, an lawyer representing 105 sex-shop
owners, called the move dictatorial and said that Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani had no regard for due process of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think that to allow these establishments to continue to
operate for another 21 days will bring about the collapse of the
city is preposterous,'' Fahringer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
