<SLUG> BC-PREGNANT-BOXER-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTER SCRATCHED FROM BOUT: SHE'S PREGNANT  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maria Nieves-Garcia got a surprise during her
pre-fight medical examination for her bout at Madison Square Garden
Saturday: She found out she was pregnant. Thursday, when a third
test confirmed what Nieves-Garcia could not believe, she was
scratched from the bout.
</P>
<P>
   A 21-year-old from Mexico City who has a son, Nieves-Garcia was
scheduled to fight Christy Martin on the undercard of the Evander
Holyfield-Henry Akinwande heavyweight championship bout.
</P>
<P>
   A standard prefight medical examination conducted by the New
York State Athletic Commission on Tuesday showed that the fighter
was pregnant. Nieves-Garcia was given the results on Wednesday,
told boxing officials that she did not believe she could be
pregnant and was given a second test. It also came back positive.
</P>
<P>
   Nieves-Garcia again swore to boxing officials that she was not
pregnant, so she was given a third, more sophisticated blood test
on Thursday morning. The test was positive again and determined
that she was 21 weeks along in her pregnancy, so she was removed
from the card.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time that I've come across that, to have a
fighter who was pregnant,'' said Bobby Goodman, the matchmaker for
Don King Productions, the promoter of Saturday night's card.
``That's pretty pregnant,'' Goodman said. ``I can't believe she
didn't know. I called her manager, and he said he wouldn't have
sent her up here if he had known she was pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieves-Garcia is the Women's International Boxing Federation
lightweight champion and has a record of 2-1. She was going to be
paid $15,000 for the match against Martin (34-1-2), which was to be
among those on the Showtime Event Television pay-per-view
broadcast. Nieves-Garcia could not be reached by telephone at her
hotel in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   There were negotiations to sign Melissa Salamone (9-0), a
two-time women's lightweight Golden Gloves from Queens, N.Y., as a
replacement for Nieves-Garcia. But Martin turned down Salamone as
an opponent because she was unfamiliar with Salamone's style and
did not want to fight a hometown boxer.
</P>
<P>
   Salamone is the sister of Louis Del Valle, the World Boxing
Association light heavyweight champion who will meet Dario Matteoni
on the undercard. Goodman was still looking for another opponent
for Martin as of Thursday evening.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A crowd of about 250 showed up for the Holyfield and Akinwande
weigh-in in the lobby outside Madison Square Garden Thursday. After
Holyfield weighed in at 218{ pounds, a cheer went up. After
Akinwande weighed in at 240\ pounds, there was a smattering of
boos.
</P>
<P>
   This is the most that Holyfield has weighed for a bout. He
weighed 218 pounds for his last fight against Tyson. Three and a
half weeks ago, Holyfield weighed 226 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight Ray Mercer was scratched from the card for medical
reasons, said Tony Russo, the executive director of the athletic
commission. Russo would not reveal why Mercer failed the physical.
Marc Roberts, Mercer's manager, said he did not know what the
medical problem was, but was told by the commission's doctors that
it was not life threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Marcellus Brown was Mercer's original opponent, but he broke his
hand in training and was replaced by Mike Sedillo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
