<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISING-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLICIS ACQUIRES EVANS, DMB&AMP;B SUES GATEWAY  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Texas, Calif., Idaho, Ind., Wash., S.D., N.Y.)  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Publicis Acquires Evans Group
</P>
<P>
   Publicis SA in Paris continued its U.S. acquisition streak on
Thursday by buying Evans Group, an agency with billings estimated
at $350 million, and merging Evans with Publicis/Bloom, one of two
Publicis American shops. Financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our acquisitions in the U.S. will continue,'' Maurice Levy,
chairman and chief executive at Publicis, said. The deal comes a
month after Publicis acquired Hal Riney &AMP; Partners in San
Francisco, which is being renamed Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney while
remaining a separate agency.
</P>
<P>
   The agency formed by merging Evans and Publicis/Bloom, to be
called Publicis, will have more than 600 employees and billings
estimated at $700 million from clients like BMW, Hewlett-Packard
and Nestle. Robert Bloom, 64, chairman and chief executive at
Publicis/Bloom in New York, will head the combined Publicis with
those titles.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Johnson, 57, chairman and chief executive of Evans, who is
based in Salt Lake City, will become chairman and chief executive
of Publicis-Dialog, a new unit of Publicis that will offer
integrated marketing communications services.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas offices of Evans and Publicis/Bloom will be combined,
with Steve Price, 46, and Seth Werner, 43, co-chairmen and chief
executives there, in those same titles at Publicis. The
Publicis/Bloom New York office becomes the New York office of
Publicis. The Evans offices in Boise, Idaho; Indianapolis; Salt
Lake City and Seattle become offices of Publicis. The Evans office
in San Francisco becomes an office of Publicis-Dialog.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DMB&AMP; B Sues For Its Expenses  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications unit of
MacManus Group in New York filed suit on Thursday against the
computer company Gateway Inc., contending that Gateway still owes
the agency at least $9 million for expenses related to work
performed before DMB&AMP; B was dismissed. In the suit, filed in
Federal District Court in New York, DMB&AMP; B contended that Gateway
breached its contract with the agency ``by not paying us,'' said
Bill Haney, a spokesman for MacManus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret it has come to this,'' he added. ``It's their right
to terminate us, but it's also our right to receive the
compensation they owe us.''
</P>
<P>
   Angela Peacock, a spokeswoman for Gateway in North Sioux City,
S.D., said that the company did not comment on pending legal
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway dismissed DMB&AMP; B in late March after the agency had
handled its worldwide account for only a year, with billings
estimated at $50 million to $70 million. The account, which had
been one of the 10 largest at DMB&AMP; B, was shifted last month to
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising in New York, part of the
McCann-Erickson World Group unit of Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Accounts  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mattel Inc., El Segundo, Calif., to Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding, Los
Angeles, part of True North Communications, as the first agency to
handle advertising for two new assignments from its Disney
Entertainment division. One is for Winnie the Pooh and Disney
activity toys, and the other is for action figures. Billings were
not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
