A5022 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      06-04 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   IPO by Cleveland Indians Not Exactly a Hit With Investors  
   
 By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The Cleveland Indians Baseball Co. went public yesterday, and the
team's initial offering wasn't exactly a home run for shareholders.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In fact, it wasn't even a broken-bat single. After the first day
of trading on Nasdaq, shares of the Tribe's common stock closed at
$14.75, down 25 cents from the initial offering price of $15.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's American League champions sold about four million
shares of common stock, but gave up virtually no control. Another
600,000 shares were set aside for the deal's lead investment
banker, McDonald &AMP; Co. of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The shares popped up above the $15 mark at one point but spent
most of the day bouncing between $14 and $15 like a bobbled
pop-fly.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if you're an investor thinking that a winning baseball
franchise can fetch the Ruthian returns of a Silicon Valley IPO,
you may want to stay in the stands on this one.
</P>
<P>
   The real winner in this deal is Indians owner Richard Jacobs
and &UR;  &LR; his original investors &UR; . &LR;  By offering a slice of the team to
loyal fans, Jacobs raised $60 million without having to do as much
as lift a bat.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet for the owner, he has ceded hardly any voting control
to the public shareholders. The shares sold yesterday carry only
one vote per share.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Jacobs and his investment group retain all of the 2.3
million Class B shares, which carry 10,000 votes each. That gives
insiders almost 99 percent control, according to Securities and
Exchange Commission filings.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder why the Indians opted to tap the public market
for some extra cash, says Jeffrey Logsdon, research director of
Cruttenden Roth, an Irvine securities firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economics of the (baseball) business have changed so
dramatically that the need to access capital has become critical,''
says Logsdon, who tracks entertainment companies.
</P>
<P>
   In order to cover skyrocketing player salaries, teams
increasingly need bigger stadiums with tonier luxury boxes.
Certainly, with about $60 million in public money, Jacobs ought to
be able to score a couple of free-agent hurlers.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians' offering has captured the attention of other sports
teams. Although the San Francisco Giants have no plans to go
public, the team's owners are keeping an eye on the Tribe IPO, says
Larry Baer, the team's executive vice president and chief operating
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As teams are looking to raise capital, this is certainly one
form of doing it,'' Baer says.
</P>
<P>
   And with the stock market in the late innings of an
extraordinary bull run, it's only logical that sports businesses
would want a piece of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is very high and sports franchises, like everybody
else, want to capitalize on it,'' says Andrew Zimbalist, an
economics professor at Smith College in Northampton, Mass., and
author of ``Baseball and Billions.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs ``can take millions out of the team without giving the
shareholders much of anything,'' Zimbalist says.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians managed to double their profits to about $22 million
in 1997 _ but $9.3 million came from one-time league expansion
fees. Most of the time, baseball teams don't see much growth in
earnings. You can only fill so many seats and sell so many hot
dogs, and broadcasting revenues also have ceilings based on
media-market size.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Indians near the top of their game, there seems to
be little room for improvement on the field or in the stock market.
But that doesn't seem to dissuade loyal fans from buying stock.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, several other sports franchises have issued stock to
the public over the years, including the Boston Celtics basketball
team and the Green Bay Packers football team.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers' stock is essentially worthless because it can't be
traded on an open market. But fans all over the country, and
especially in Dairyland, will plunk down hard cash for the
certificates to assure that their team can raise money when it
needs to.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' stock, which rolled out in 1986 on the Big Board at
$18.50 a share, has been about as successful as the team's record
during the post-Larry Bird era. It now trades around $20.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a November 1996 offering by the Florida
Panthers National Hockey League team has produced more positive
results. It's trading at $19 a share, almost double the $10
offering price. But it was engineered by empire-builder Wayne
Huizenga, the team's owner, who is no stranger to public stock
offerings. Also, unlike the Indians' deal, which is a pure baseball
play, Florida Panthers Holdings is loaded with other businesses and
assets, including real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with the exception of the Panthers, it is unconditional
devotion to a favorite team that drives the sale of its common
stock, says Jeff Borden, a Chicago journalist and life-long Tribe
fan.
</P>
<P>
   Borden says he bought two shares of Indians stock yesterday,
expecting to frame the certificate and hang it on his wall. ``It's
clearly not a real investment for me,'' Borden explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not particularly bullish on how the stock will perform,
but I'm bullish on the team's prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   His analysis on the team's performance could be right down the
pipe. The Indians sit atop the American League Central Division and
have gone to the World Series two out of the last three years.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at San Francisco Chronicle, 901
Mission St., San Francisco 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by
e-mail at mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
