<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--NBA-HNS &LR;      06-04 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--NBA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBA strife threatening World Championship squad
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich's role as coach of
the U.S. entry into next month's World Championship of Basketball
could be jeopardized if NBA players elect not to participate in the
biennial tournament because of the league's labor strife.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 players chosen to compete have signed contracts with USA
Basketball, but NBA commissioner David Stern on Thursday said if
those players decide not to honor those deals, USA Basketball would
be left with no choice but to field a team of college or
Continental Basketball Association players.
</P>
<P>
   A change in the makeup of the team could mean a change in the
coaching staff, too, although USA Basketball president and NBA
deputy commissioner Russ Granik said it's possible Tomjanovich
would remain as coach regardless of possible roster shakeups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy Tomjanovich and Del Harris (the Los Angeles Lakers'
coach, who will assist Tomjanovich) have contracts to coach the
team,'' Granik said. ``But USA Basketball is not going to have a
problem with them (perhaps not coaching).
</P>
<P>
   ``They both profess they'll do whatever makes the most sense for
USA Basketball. If it makes sense for Rudy to remain a coach no
matter what, I'm sure he would. If it makes sense to replace him
because we had different players, I know Rudy would understand
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. roster includes Detroit's Grant Hill, Seattle's Gary
Payton and Vin Baker, Minnesota's Kevin Garnett and Tom Gugliotta,
San Antonio's Tim Duncan, Miami's Tim Hardaway, New York's Allan
Houston, Charlotte's Glen Rice, Sacramento's Chris Webber,
Milwaukee's Terrell Brandon and Atlanta's Christian Laettner.
</P>
<P>
   But they are being pressured by key members of the NBA Players
Association to boycott the World Championship in Athens, Greece,
from July 26 through Aug. 9. Training camp for the U.S. team opens
July 8 in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   NBA owners voted 27-2 on March 23 to exercise an option to
reopen the collective-bargaining agreement and are expected to lock
out the players before July 1. NBA insiders expect a long
negotiating process this summer before labor peace is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Some players view the World Championship as one of the few
leverage chips players possess.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a heartbeat, I support it (a boycott),'' Michael Jordan
said. ``I would be in favor of not playing in the World
Championship games. If you're going to try to handcuff one side, we
have to retaliate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' Charles Barkley agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm caught between a rock and a hard spot because I think Rudy
deserves to coach that team,'' Barkley said. ``But that's about the
only leverage we as players have. It would be embarrassing for the
NBA (if the players revolted).''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich is in Chicago for the NBA's pre-draft camp and
preferred not to comment about the situation regarding the World
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   But an NBA source said the matter involves more than just the
U.S. team changing for the tournament. The source said USA
Basketball is weighing its options and will send letters to the
players in about 10 days to ask them of their intentions. If the
NBA players do not participate, USA Basketball will scramble to
find an alternate team.
</P>
<P>
   ``USA Basketball has a commitment to FIBA (Federation
Internationale de Basketball Association) to field a team,'' Granik
said. ``At some point, USA Basketball will have to make a decision.
Now, there's a team USA Basketball is putting together this summer
to play in the Goodwill Games. That's a possibility. There are CBA
players. So there are other options. But I think those options are
not likely to be competitive in the modern world of international
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing people don't realize is that if we don't win the
gold medal in Greece, then we don't qualify automatically for the
2000 Olympics. This event very much is directly related to the
Olympics. And if we don't qualify, we will have to qualify in the
Americas zone, which could take place in the 1999-2000 NBA season.
So there's a real possibility that we won't qualify to play in the
Olympics in 2000 if we don't send the right team to Greece.''
</P>
<P>
   One insider said the qualifying tournament for the 2000 Olympics
probably will be in March of that year, meaning NBA players would
be unable to participate because the season would be going on.
Without NBA players, the U.S. likely would not qualify for the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, meanwhile, issued a strong declaration to the members of
the U.S. team that, should they decide not to honor their contracts
with USA Basketball, it would hurt them more than it would hurt the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the NBA's perspective, the players will do whatever they
want to do,'' Stern said. ``What we have is a system between the
NBA and FIBA where we agree that we will require our teams to give
permission to let players participate in global events. In
particular, it was also a request from USA Basketball that we
release our players to go represent the United States of America.
And we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step, as far as we're concerned, is a contract
between our players and USA Basketball, which is a separate
organization from the NBA. We've tried very hard to work with FIBA
and USA Basketball. And if the individual players, having made that
commitment, decide to trash their country, that's going to be their
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. roster for the World Championship must be submitted
this month to FIBA, Granik said. And so far, there are no changes,
in spite of pleas from NBA players union chief Patrick Ewing that
the players boycott the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not gotten any notice from players that they are not
going to play, but people obviously have read the reports that this
is being discussed,'' Granik said. ``It certainly will damage USA
Basketball and its international relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That said, there's not a lot that USA Basketball can do,
except that hope the players will understand that this has all
these different ramifications that have nothing to do with the
NBA.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
