<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES SMILE IN A BOOK BY THE MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cabbies, street vendors and jaywalkers. These may not
sound like a few of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's favorite things, but
they all wear big grins in a new picture book written and published
for the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The cover of ``What Will You Be?'' says it is ``A story by:
Mayor Rudy Giuliani'' but he is also the star, appearing in nine
photographs and drawings in the book. The book follows his
real-life yellow Labrador, Goalie, as he romps through a buffet of
career choices, encouraging youngsters to aim high and study hard,
even if the curriculum is ``The Joy of Napping.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was driven a dozen blocks from City Hall to Public
School 1 in Chinatown on Thursday for a ``publishing party'' that
consisted of him reading the book to 40 schoolchildren and eight
television cameras. When Giuliani asked what the dog was dreaming
about in one picture, several pupils blurted out, ``Being mayor!''
Giuliani joshed, ``Some people believe that would be an
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knew the mayor could rap? But here is how he starts his
tale:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a boy I liked to dream big,
</P>
<P>
   But who would have thought being mayor would be my gig.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, which the mayor dedicates to his mother, Helen
Giuliani, was written and illustrated by Kristin Doney, 31, a
children's-book illustrator who lives in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   Devotees of picture books will find the mayor's collaboration
with Ms. Downey _ packed with busy, sprawling images in ink and
watercolor _ to be a case of ``Where's Waldo?'' meets Richard
Scarry. While a rainbow of children frolics at a blackboard that
lists job choices from astronaut to yoga instructor, Goalie is
shown thinking, ``I need a snack ... and a nap.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor asked the children about their own aspirations and
shook Tiffany Wong's hand when she said she wanted to be ``a DA.''
Giuliani, a former federal prosecutor, then quizzed her about what
a district attorney does, eliciting silence.
</P>
<P>
   The back of the book features a biography of the mayor. ``At
first,'' it reads, ``he wanted to play baseball for the New York
Yankees. Later he wanted to become a doctor, a priest or a
helicopter pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   The book was published by New York City Public/Private
Initiatives Inc., a private group headed by Tamra Roberts Lhota,
the wife of the mayor's budget director, Joseph Lhota. The book was
made possible in part by a $25,000 grant from Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
The mayor's office said copies would be donated to all elementary
school libraries and all branches of the New York Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said 10,000 copies were in print, but he expected at
least twice as many to be distributed ultimately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
