<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5150 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-04 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--FINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Bulls' confidence belies dilemma
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ The way the Chicago Bulls continue to talk the big
talk, they surely must be the most dominant team ever to fall
behind 1-0 in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they have lost their last four road games and,
apparently, the snap and mystique that have made them one of the
NBA's dynasties, the Bulls say their will to win is stronger than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   But the facts do nothing to support their case that this is the
same Bulls team that confidently and routinely wins tight games and
resists those muscle-tightening situations because they are who
they are.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Utah Jazz, who will go for a 2-0 lead tonight at the
Delta Center, notices the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the Bulls I remember seeing,'' Bryon Russell said
Thursday. ``That's a different team than it was last year. We have
to take advantage of mismatches we see out there just like they're
used to taking advantage of the mismatches that are usually
presented to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell ended up being one of those mismatches whenever he lined
up against Toni Kukoc. Russell had 15 points and eight rebounds in
Game 1; Kukoc had nine points and three rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the Bulls exude a ``What, us worry?'' confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have an inner strength and inner confidence for
ourselves and what we can accomplish,'' Michael Jordan said. ``And
one game does not deteriorate that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it's a pressure situation, the ultimate, the apex of a
season. I believe even if we lose (tonight), which I'm not thinking
that way, we still have a great opportunity to go home and win in
our building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave a good effort in Game 1. Now, we have to give a better
effort. It's a whole different frame of mind. I think that's that
Zen Buddhism kind of stuff. We're practicing that.''
</P>
<P>
   That no doubt makes Phil Jackson happy. What would make the
Zen-spouting coach happier is if the Bulls would prove again
tonight in Game 2 they haven't slipped a notch or two when it comes
to being clutch performers.
</P>
<P>
   After one game of the Finals, it's far too early to write off
the Bulls. But Jackson said Thursday that his team was showing its
age, mainly because the Bulls were tired at the end of Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   He cited two plays _ Jordan's inability to elevate and
subsequent shot-clock violation with 1:19 left in overtime and
Steve Kerr's hack of John Stockton when a still-fresh-looking
Stockton drove for a layup. The three-point play put Utah ahead by
five points in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were very fatigued,'' Jackson said. ``It's
pretty obvious we're going to have to provide a little more support
(from the bench). I thought two days of rest might get them back up
to speed. Then, we played a good offensive second half and carried
the action and the momentum, but defensively we couldn't make the
stops down the stretch simply because we were fatigued.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job of resting guys who mean something to them
down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz was vastly superior to the Bulls in the overtime.
Whether or not it was the fatigue taking its toll on Chicago, which
was playing its sixth game in 12 days and facing the Jazz, which
was coming off 10 days of rest, the Bulls did not look like
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And still, they feel good about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our confidence is still there,'' Scottie Pippen said. ``We
still feel like we're in control of this series and they still have
to defend their home court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we still have an opportunity to get a game here.
As poorly as we played, that was anybody's game (Wednesday). Karl
(Malone) didn't have a great game, and we felt that if we were ever
going to steal a game out here, last night should have been that
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we still feel very good. Our confidence is very high.''
</P>
<P>
   What might help the Bulls is diversity. Jordan and Pippen
combined for 48 of the Bulls' 82 shots and for 54 of their 85
points.
</P>
<P>
   Shandon Anderson, a member of Utah's productive bench, which
outscored Chicago's reserves 22-8, said he believes such numbers
don't work in the Bulls' favor. Anderson said he believes the Bulls
might be too reliant on Jordan. When the Bulls give the basketball
to Jordan, it's almost as if they rest and watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that just leaves the other guys standing out on the
perimeter, just watching,'' Anderson said. ``You have those guys
out there, guys who can score, just watching, so it's going to be
hard for them. If he (Jordan) goes for 40 or 50 points and the
other guys just stand out there and do nothing, then that's good
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the end, Jordan and Pippen were fatigued and had
trouble making plays. They were a combined 1-for-4 from the field
in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concern when you can't execute down the stretch,''
Jordan said. ``And I think that is an area of improvement we need
to focus on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
