A5226 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-CASUAL-WEAR-$ADV     06-04 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-CASUAL-WEAR-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO WHAT COLOR T-SHIRT BEFITS A BOARD MEETING?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Va., N.J.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics) Because everybody seems to know what Friday means, the
problem with Casual Friday is clearly the word ``casual.'' Some
people interpret the dictionary definition _ informal _ to mean
going without a necktie or jacket. To others, it means torn jeans,
tiny tennis skirts, flip-flops or T-shirts that say ``I'm Low on
Estrogen'' or ``Got a Gun.'' Maybe things will get better when the
lexicographers roll up their sleeves and provide a better
definition. (end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the fire alarm went off during a lunchtime workout last
month at the YMCA at Lexington Avenue and 53rd Street, it was
everybody out of the basement pool.
</P>
<P>
   Dripping, barefoot swimmers congregated in the lobby, where they
found a minimal supply of small towels. Fifteen minutes later, with
the firefighters still checking each floor, a young executive
dressed only in his swimsuit said: ``I must call the office and
explain my delay. I can't go back like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfa P. Goldberg of Manhattan remembers the voice that replied:
``Why not? Isn't it called Casual Friday?'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a programmer for Prodigy in the early 1990s, Paul R. Loring
of Pleasantville, N.Y., was accustomed to wearing casual clothing
in the office while the rest of the staff was wearing suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeans and T-shirts were the norm in our department,'' he
writes. ``However, some of us were down to T-shirts, shorts and
sandals on the nicer days. So we were all surprised when the
companywide e-mail went out declaring Casual Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   `` `How much more casual can we get?' we asked ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the next day, a group of us arrived at work in our
bathrobes.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holly M. Horning, the president of Image Design Group of
Alexandria, Va., which teaches individuals and companies how to use
image as a tool, works daily with the problem of office dress. In
the course of her work, she has come across:
</P>
<P>
   _ A senior executive who runs several miles to work in his
two-piece jogging suit and then strips to his T-shirt and running
shorts and begins work without bothering to shower.
</P>
<P>
   _ A senior partner in a law firm who wore a polo shirt and jeans
while greeting prospective clients in a major case. Judging him by
his clothing, they assumed he was an associate and went elsewhere,
offended because they thought the firm had assigned their case to
an inexperienced lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   _ A woman who sent productivity plummeting by arriving for her
job in the shortest of Lycra miniskirts and a strapless, stretchy
bandeau top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' writes Ms. Horning, companies wait until they
have serious problems before calling an image consultant. ``In a
poll we do with all our corporate participants, over 90 percent of
employees are baffled by what to wear,'' she said. ``They are
confused by the term `casual.''' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to interpretations of casual, George A. Dietrick,
a Garden City, N.Y., physician-executive, stands at the
conservative end of the spectrum. He recalls that a few years ago,
when Dress-Down Friday was instituted in the corporate office where
he worked, ``the policy change generated intense discussions at the
water coolers and copy machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CFO and I, the medical director, had multiple discussions
on just what we would wear, since both our personal styles were the
preferred and, in fact, expected collars and ties (not jackets)
around the office at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did it mean anyway? Who would wear what? How would the
senior executives influence and enforce the new dress code?''
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, the doctor and his associate believed that
Casual Friday would spin out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, most of the men responded by wearing khakis and polo
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of us realized that the speculation around the office
was that our interpretation of Casual Friday would be `Light
Starch.''' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forget Casual Friday. Some people are casual all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Arlene B. Isaacs, a New York City business consultant and
executive coach, remembers a 26-year-old client who took the
interpretation to extremes.
</P>
<P>
   At their first meeting, Ms. Isaacs recalled, the client wore
high-heeled sandals and was encased in a floral polyester jumpsuit,
worn without a bra; her fingernails and toenails were painted
black, which matched the roots of her dyed blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost 30 percent of our business in the last four months,
and I don't know why,'' said the client, who was being groomed to
take over her family's auto parts business.
</P>
<P>
   Her work consisted of making calls on garage managers. ``It
wasn't her catalogue they were assessing,'' Ms. Isaacs recalls.
``She became infuriated with their blatant passes, lost her cool
and alienated the men, who couldn't understand why she was taking
umbrage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Isaacs recommended a modest investment: a blazer, a tailored
straight skirt, closed-toe pumps and consultation with a colorist.
``The mechanics no longer viewed her as the item of the day,'' Ms.
Isaacs writes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter Giuliano, the chairman and founder of Executive
Communications Group, a consulting firm in Englewood, N.J., recalls
an instructor who led a program in media training for a client in
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the program dealt with how to dress for a tough
on-camera interview, and how to handle the questions. Because the
participants were field technicians at a chemical plant, the
instructor disregarded their casual attire at the session _ work
boots, overalls and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the workers, however, had soot on his face and wore a red
bandanna around his neck, so the instructor gently told him to wash
for his final on-camera interview the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The client did as told, turning up clean and shiny. He would
have made a perfect spokesman for the company, except for one
detail.
</P>
<P>
   Because this was the company's official casual day, he left his
dentures at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-98 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
