<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Padres-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Hampton, 
Astros get 
a lesson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ashby dominant &QL; 
in Padres' 5-1 win
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN DIEGO _ Mike Hampton's command abandoned him on day when Andy
Ashby happened to be conducting a seminar on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, that summed up the Astros' 5-1 loss to the San
Diego Padres on Thursday at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby lectured the Astros' bats with an assortment of pitches
that ranked among the best they had seen all season. The
righthander sprinkled eight hits over nine innings to notch his
third consecutive complete game and his fourth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou's homer leading off the ninth inning spoiled Ashby's
shutout bid, but that was about the only mistake the hot-handed
pitcher made all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashby had everything working,'' said Dave Clark, who started
in right field and was 0-for-4 with three strikeouts. ``It seemed
like everything he threw was a strike. He just messed everyone up.
He was on top of it, and he pitched a hell of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   For one of the few times this season, Hampton was at the other
end of the spectrum _ although he still managed to keep the Astros
close. Hampton held the Padres to five hits in 6 innings, but he
walked five batters.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the walks led to runs, but they proved to be meaningless.
Ashby got all the run support he needed in the first inning when
Greg Vaughn hit a two-run homer to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give Asbhy credit,'' Hampton said. ``That home run
in the first was plenty for him. I just didn't have anything. I
didn't have a fastball, a curveball, a changeup or a cutter. I went
six-plus innings with absolutely nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some good movement on some of my pitches, but it was a
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating. Good pitchers have to be able to win even
when they don't have their best stuff. I didn't have much, and I
just wasn't able to get the job done. I walked a lot of guys, but
some of the walks were situational. I had good enough control to
throw strikes; I just didn't want to give in to the hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss cut the Astros' National League Central Division lead
over the idle Chicago Cubs to one game and left them with a 3-3
record on the six-game road trip to Colorado and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros open a three-game homestand against Kansas City
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have liked to have won today, but 3-3 is all right,''
manager Larry Dierker said. ``After losing those last two at
Colorado, it was good to see us come here and get a couple of wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sweep would have been nice, but it just wasn't meant to be.
Ashby was tough. He's not a guy you want to face right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros missed Padres ace Kevin Brown, but they couldn't
dodge the hottest pitcher in San Diego's rotation. Ashby, who had
eight strikeouts Thursday, is 2-1 with a 1.73 ERA in his last three
starts.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Alou's 12th homer, the Astros didn't get a
runner into scoring position after the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We caught him when he's hot,'' Tim Bogar, who started at
second base for the Astros, said of Ashby. ``I don't think I saw
any pitches that were straight all day. He was really moving the
ball around on us. He's one of the overlooked guys in the league,
but when he's on, he's hard to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamp battled and kept us in the game, but Ashby just had the
better hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros got off to an inauspicious start when Quilvio Veras
led off first with what appeared to be a bloop single. Center
fielder Carl Everett charged the ball and nearly made the play, but
it got past him and Veras was credited with a double.
</P>
<P>
   That all but assured Hampton (7-3) would have to face Vaughn,
one of the hottest hitters in the majors, with a runner in scoring
position. Vaughn's homer was his third in the series and his fifth
against the Astros in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vaughn hit a pretty decent pitch,'' Hampton said. ``It was a
changeup down and away, and he just went and got it. When you're
hot like he is right now, you hit everything. I didn't think he'd
be looking for an off-speed pitch, but I guess he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton retired eight batters in a row after Vaughn's homer and
faced 13 batters before he allowed another hit. Veras broke through
with a single in the fifth to score Andy Sheets, who had drawn a
leadoff walk. The Padres added two runs in the seventh on a squeeze
bunt by Ashby (7-4) and a sacrifice fly by Veras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamp didn't have his good stuff, and every pitcher is going to
have games like that,'' said catcher Brad Ausmus, who caught Ashby
when he played for the Padres. ``Andy was on his game. He's added a
split-finger pitch, which he hasn't thrown before, and it's just
made him that much more effective. He pretty much shut us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres pitching coach Dave Stewart said of Ashby: ``His sinker
is so devastating that from time to time I don't know the sinker
from the forkball, to be honest. He was nasty today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
